{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1001","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1001","narrative_id":"1001"},"responses":[{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\", has resigned from Google, warning that developments in the field of artificial intelligence pose increasing dangers."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"He is a British-Canadian computer scientist and cognitive psychologist who has made significant contributions to the development of artificial intelligence, particularly in the field of neural networks and deep learning."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"His pioneering research has paved the way for current AI systems such as Google's Bard chatbot and Microsoft's ChatGPT."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"Hinton has stated that he regrets his current job and is wary of the potential dangers of AI development, citing the risk of AI becoming smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":1.0},"text":"He has also expressed concern that AI may cause a flood of false information and has warned that AI may become smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In an interview with the BBC, Hinton said that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans, and he is afraid of these developments."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's warnings have made headlines, with many experts responding to his concerns and calling for more robust safety measures to be designed and deployed."},{"citations":{"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":1.0},"text":"The public should understand that Hinton's warnings are not just theoretical, but are based on his own experiences and observations of the rapid development of AI."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's resignation from Google has sparked a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"Overall, Hinton's warnings highlight the need for careful management and regulation of AI development to prevent potential dangers."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\", has resigned from Google, warning that developments in the field of artificial intelligence pose increasing dangers."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"He is a British-Canadian computer scientist and cognitive psychologist who has made significant contributions to the development of artificial intelligence, particularly in the field of neural networks and deep learning."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"His pioneering research has paved the way for current AI systems such as Google's Bard chatbot and Microsoft's ChatGPT."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"Hinton has stated that he regrets his current job and is wary of the potential dangers of AI development, citing the risk of AI becoming smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":1.0},"text":"He has also expressed concern that AI may cause a flood of false information and has warned that AI may become smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In an interview with the BBC, Hinton said that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans, and he is afraid of these developments."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's warnings have made headlines, with many experts responding to his concerns and calling for more robust safety measures to be designed and deployed."},{"citations":{"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":1.0},"text":"The public should understand that Hinton's warnings are not just theoretical, but are based on his own experiences and observations of the rapid development of AI."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's resignation from Google has sparked a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"Overall, Hinton's warnings highlight the need for careful management and regulation of AI development to prevent potential dangers."}],"references":["3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512","79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334","d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945","eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601","f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537"],"documents":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":{"id":"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","text":"The \u2018Godfather of AI\u2019 warns about potential dangers of the technology as he quits Google\n\nBritish-Canadian computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton admits he has fears for the future of AI\n\nIn a Frankenstein-esque tale of maker and master, Geoffrey Hinton, 75, dubbed \u2018the godfather of AI\u2019, has left Google with a parting warning over the dangers of artificial intelligence.\n\nIn 2012, the British-Canadian computer scientist invented technology with two students at University of Toronto that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems. Google purchased the rights to this neural network tech to the tune of $44 million, which also propelled Dr Hinton to receive the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing.\n\nRead More\nThe ultimate part-AI girl? One Tatler correspondent entrusts ChatGPT with her next assignment\n\nChatGPT\u2019s the new It Girl in Town and now she\u2019s got all the gossip, writes Dora Davies-Evitt in the April issue\n\nYet now, Dr Hinton has packed in the day job at Google to join a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed. Dr Hinton told the BBC: \u2018Right now, they\u2019re not more intelligent than us, as far as I can tell. But I think they soon may be.\u2019\n\nWhile many look upon AI as a natural technological development akin to the internet that could lead to exciting breakthroughs for humanity, there are growing fears that AI is a Pandora\u2019s box. Reflecting on the effects of his work, Dr Hinton said: \u2018I console myself with the normal excuse: If I hadn\u2019t done it, somebody would have,\u2019 as he admitted, \u2018it is hard to see how you can prevent the bad actors from using it for bad things.\u2019\n\nRead More\nCyber Society: Meet the NFT duo dominating the metaverse\n\nOld Etonian digital artists Dominic Smith and Joe Carnell have caught the attention of Brooklyn Beckham, Steve Aoki and Jaden Smith\u00a0\n\nThe scientist went on to warn that AI could be taught to \u2018create sub-goals like \u201cI need to get more power\u201d\u2019, and be harnessed by nefarious actors to wreak havoc. With innovation driven forward by the unstoppable competition between behemoths like Google and Microsoft, Dr Hinton warned innovation will only increase exponentially in the coming years.\n\nThere are those who are trying to apply the brakes to this runaway train. In March, an open letter was signed by over 1,000 tech leaders and researchers, including Elon Musk and fellow Turing Award winner Yoshu Bengio, calling for a six-month moratorium on AI development. A few days later, 19 leaders of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence released their own letter on the risks of AI. The signatures included that of Eric Horvitz, chief scientific officer at Microsoft.\n\nThe main outcry over AI lies in its ability to create and disseminate false news and images, which the public may find increasingly hard to identify. AI also poses a threat to academia and careers (see: Tatler\u2019s foray into the world of ChatGPT). Dr Hinton believes that AI will fundamentally disrupt the workplace and take over the \u2018drudge work\u2019.\n\nRead More\nLady Meta: my stratospheric rise through the metaverse\n\nThe Crypto Fashion Week debutante on becoming VR\u2019s favourite It Girl\n\nHowever Google\u2019s chief scientist, Jeff Dean, offered words of comfort, adding: 'We remain committed to a responsible approach to AI. We\u2019re continually learning to understand emerging risks while also innovating boldly.\u2019","url":"https://www.tatler.com/article/the-godfather-of-ai-warns-about-potential-dangers-of-the-technology-as-he-quits-google"},"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":{"id":"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601","text":"Information Technology\nThe father of artificial intelligence urges governments to face its risks before disaster\nJeffrey Hinton, described as the father of artificial intelligence, on Wednesday urged governments to intervene to ensure that machines do not control society.\nHinton made headlines in May when he announced his resignation from Google to speak more freely about the dangers of artificial intelligence, shortly after the launch of ChatGPT, which captivated the world.\nThe artificial intelligence scientist, who is studying at the University of Toronto, spoke to a crowd at the Collagen Technology Conference in the Canadian city.\nThe conference attracted more than 30,000 startup founders, investors and tech workers, most of whom were eager to learn how to ride the wave of artificial intelligence rather than hear lessons about its risks or calls for governments to intervene.\n\u201cBefore AI becomes smarter than us, I think the people who develop it should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into understanding how it can try to take control of us, \u201d Hinton said.\n\u201cNow there are 99 highly intelligent people trying to make AI better, and one very intelligent person trying to figure out how to stop it from taking control, and maybe we should be more balanced. \u201d\nHinton warned that the dangers of artificial intelligence must be taken seriously.\n\u201cI think it \u2019 s important for people to understand that this is not science fiction or just fear, \u201d he said, adding:\u201c It \u2019 s a real risk that we have to think about, and we have to figure out how to deal with it first. \u201d\nHinton expressed concern that AI would deepen inequality, as the vast gains from its productivity would go to the rich, not the workers.\n\u201cWealth will not go to the people who work, it will make the rich richer, not the poor, and this is a very bad society, \u201d he said.\nHe also pointed to the danger of \u201cfake news \u201d that can be created by robots such as ChatGPT, hoping to mark the content generated by artificial intelligence programs as central banks mark coins.\nHe stressed that it is important to \u201ctry, for example, to distinguish everything that is fake as fake, \u201d and said,\u201c I don \u2019 t know if we can do it technically or not. \u201d\n\u201cThe Island Net \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0019.json.gz:13309","uncompressed_offset":20427601,"url":"www.alnilin.com/13320225.htm","warc_date":"2023-06-30T08:13:58.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d>","warc_url":"https://www.alnilin.com/13320225.htm"},"created":"2023-06-30T08:14:48.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":{"id":"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537","text":"Wednesday, December 13, 2023\nGeneric selectors\nExact matches only\nSearch in title\nSearch in content\nPost Type Selectors\n\nJohn Riopelle \u2014 obituary\n\nRiopelle, John William It is with great sadness...\n\nA.I. doesn\u2019t bleed\n\nby John Clinton, Ramsay New knowledge merges with...\n\nBreakfast at the Legion, December 16\n\nAt the Almonte Legion Sat. December 16 Eggs to...\nScience & NatureA.I. doesn't bleed\n\nA.I. doesn\u2019t bleed\n\nby John Clinton, Ramsay\n\nNew knowledge merges with old; what you know shapes what you learn. Artificial neural networks have been studied and computer algorithms have been generated to understand how artificial, computer-generated, neurons, would store a concept, and how it would revise that concept if it was flawed.\n\nGeoffrey Hinton, a computer scientist often called \u2018the godfather of AI,\u2019 is a leading figure in neural networks; studies inspired by the way neurons are connected in the human brain. A New Yorker magazine piece describes his collaborative work in the 1960s and 1970s developing neural nets that couldn\u2019t do anything better than a child. The technology suddenly improved about a decade ago with the large increase in processing speed and Internet data availability.\n\nAccording to Google Scholar, Hinton is the second most cited researcher among psychologists and the most cited among computer and cognitive scientists.\n\nHinton has been worried about the potential of AI to do harm and he often talks about the existential threat that AI might pose to the human species. He has used OpenAI\u2019s ChatGPT and this has made him uneasy. He wrote \u201cFox News is an oxymoron\u201d asking ChatGPT to explain the joke. (Initial reading of this caused me to ponder \u2013 a moron full of oxygen??) The first reply told him that this implied Fox News was fake news. When he called attention to the space between oxy and moron, it explained that Fox News was addictive, like the drug OxyContin. To him, this level of understanding represents a new era in AI.\n\nIn nature, wildlife learns how to be intelligent without access to concepts expressed in words. They learn to be smart (survive) through experience. Learning, not knowledge, is the engine of intelligence. There is no use trying to explain complicated ideas that you do not understand. First, you must understand how something works. Otherwise, you just produce nonsense.\n\nBecause neural networks are so strange, no one can predict how useful \u2013 or dangerous \u2013 AI will become. OpenAI\u2019s GPT models involve billions of artificial neurons (data) which are profoundly different than biological brains. They are not alive. Our intuitions tell us that nothing resident in a browser tab could really be thinking in the way we do.\n\nBecause a human brain can run on oatmeal, the world can support billions of brains, all different. Each brain can learn continuously, rather than being trained once, then pushed out into the world (ship it!).\n\nIf the brain dies, the knowledge dies. If a computer dies, load up another computer. Ten thousand neural nets can learn ten thousand different things at the same time and share what they have learned. This immortality (knowledge perpetuity) and replicability suggest we should be concerned about digital intelligence taking over from biological intelligence.\n\nCurrent AI technology is talkative and intellectual. The problems of physical intuition will be the challenge of the next decade says Yann LeCun, a French computer scientist. A teenager can learn to drive a car in twenty hours of practice with little supervision. AI systems don\u2019t come close to doing this \u2013 except self-driving cars \u2013 and they are over-engineered, requiring the mapping of whole cities, hundreds of engineers, and hundreds of thousands of hours of training.\n\nAnd then there is the problem of what some researchers call AI \u2018hallucination\u2019, which Hinton names \u2018confabulation.\u2019 AI systems confabulate by making up plausible answers to questions that stump them. In the human mind, there is no boundary between just making it up and telling the truth. Telling the truth is just making it up correctly. ChatGPT\u2019s ability to make things up is a flaw, but also a sign of its humanlike intelligence.\n\nWhen Hinton began his research, no one thought the technology would succeed. When it started to succeed, no one thought it would succeed so quickly. He expects AI will contribute to many fields, but he fears what will happen when powerful people abuse it. Think autonomous weapons. Hinton warns that even benign autonomous systems could wreak havoc. Yann LeCun has said there is an idea that if a system is intelligent it is going to want to dominate. But the desire to dominate has nothing to do with intelligence \u2013 it has to do with testosterone.\n\nRecently, Hinton did not sign a popular petition that called for at least a six-month pause in AI research.\n\n\u201cChina is not going to stop development for six months.\u201d\n\n\u201cSo what should we do?\u201d\n\n\u201cI don\u2019t know. If this were like climate change where we either must stop burning carbon or find a way to remove carbon from the atmosphere, we know what the solution looks like. Here, with AI, it\u2019s not like that.\u201d\n\nThink of the AI story in which our intuitions about the specialness of the human mind are being dislodged by thinking machines, or, having stolen fire, we risk being burned.\n\nAre we fooling ourselves, being taken in by our own machines and the companies that hope to profit from them? By seeking to re-create the knowledge systems in our heads, have we seized the forbidden apple? Have we risked exile from our charmed world? But who would choose not to know how knowing works?\n\nRelated\n\nFOLLOW US\n\nLatest\n\nFrom the Archives","url":"https://millstonenews.com/a-i-doesnt-bleed/"},"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":{"id":"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512","text":"Geoffrey Hinton: GPT-4 is 100 times more knowledgeable than any human\nAuthor: MIAO Yongqi\nPublished: Updated:\nComputer scientist Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\", announced Monday that he has resigned from Google. He has devoted his life to developing artificial intelligence systems, saying he \"regrets his life's work\" and is wary of the potential dangers of AI development.\nIn another recent interview, Hinton further talked about why he is afraid of AI development.\nHinton, 75, left Google a few days after the news broke in an interview with MIT Technology Review senior editor Will Douglas Heaven.\nHinton points out that the new generation of AI language models, especially the GPT-4, which came out in March, made him realize that these machines were moving in a direction that was much smarter than he thought, and he was afraid of these developments.\nHe is best known for a technique he proposed in the 1980s (with two colleagues) called backpropagation.\nIn short, the algorithms that allow machines to learn support almost all of today \u2019 s artificial neural networks, from computer vision systems to large language models.\nIt wasn \u2019 t until the 2010s that Hinton and his two recent graduates developed a \u201cneural network \u201d that demonstrated its power, stronger than any computer \u2019 s ability to identify objects in images, and trained it to predict the next letter of a sentence, a precursor to today \u2019 s large-scale language patterns.\nOne of the students was Ilya Sutskever, the founder of OpenAI, who led the development of ChatGPT.\n\u201cWe first thought it might be great. \u201d\u201c But it \u2019 s going to take a long time to realize that it needs to be done on a large scale to get good results. \u201d\nIn the 1980s, the discussion of \u201cneural networks \u201d was considered a joke.\nBut Hinton doesn \u2019 t think so, and is working on this, software that mimics the abstract human brain and uses code as a connection between neurons. For 40 years, Hinton has viewed artificial neural networks as a clumsy attempt to mimic biological neural networks.\nNow he thinks things have changed: he thinks there are better results when trying to mimic the behavior of the biological brain.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s scary when you see it with your own eyes, \u201d he said.\u201c It \u2019 s a sudden change. \u201d\nSo why did ChatGPT surprise Hinton, too? He explained that the human brain has about 100 trillion connections, and \u201clarge language models have up to 500 billion, up to a trillion. \u201d\nHowever, the knowledge of GPT-4 is a hundred times greater than that of any human.\nSo maybe it actually has a better learning algorithm than we do. \"\nHe also pointed out that apart from the ability to learn, the ability to communicate is another kind of point.\n\u201cIf you or I learn a new thing and want to teach it to another person, we can \u2019 t just send them a copy. \u201d\nBut artificial neural networks can do it.\nIt \u2019 s like there are 10,000 people here, and when one person learns a new thing, the other 9,999 people all learn it at the same time.\nHinton now believes that there are two types of intelligence: animal brains and artificial neural networks.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s a completely different kind of intelligence.\n\u201cA new, better intelligence. \u201d Hinton believes that whether superintelligence is good or bad depends largely on whether you \u2019 re an optimist or a pessimist, and he says,\u201c mildly depressed, \u201d \u201cthat \u2019 s why I \u2019 m afraid. \u201d\n\u201cWhether these things are going to be smarter than us, I suddenly changed my mind. \u201d\nI think they are very close to us now and they will be much smarter than us in the future, \u201d he said.\n\u201cHow do we survive? \u201d he is particularly worried that people will use the tools he has developed to change the trajectory of human life, including elections and wars.\nHe said that he hopes to continue talking about AI security after leaving office and spend more time on \u201cmore philosophical work \u201d.\u201c As long as I \u2019 m still employed at Google, I can \u2019 t say what I want to say, \u201d he said. \u201cI have a lot of good things to say about Google, and it would be more convincing if I wasn \u2019 t at Google. \u201d\nWho is the godfather of AI computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton?\nHinton pioneered the basic technology of AI systems and became interested in artificial neural networks when he was a graduate student at the University of Edinburgh in 1972. In 2018, he and two experts in the field of deep learning were awarded the Turing Award, known as the \u201cNobel Prize in Computing \u201d.\nWhat are the main concerns of \u201cAI Godfather \u201d Geoffrey Hinton about the development of artificial intelligence?\nHe believes that the most direct impact is to promote the dissemination of false information and the loss of employment opportunities, and also worries about the use of this tool for evil, such as influencing elections and using it in war.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:7284","uncompressed_offset":779126512,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B/894210/ai%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6geoffrey-hinton-gpt-4%E7%9A%84%E7%9F%A5%E8%AD%98%E6%AF%94%E4%BB%BB%E4%BD%95%E4%BA%BA%E9%A1%9E%E5%A4%9A%E6%95%B8%E7%99%BE%E5%80%8D","warc_date":"2023-05-03T09:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B/894210/ai%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6geoffrey-hinton-gpt-4%E7%9A%84%E7%9F%A5%E8%AD%98%E6%AF%94%E4%BB%BB%E4%BD%95%E4%BA%BA%E9%A1%9E%E5%A4%9A%E6%95%B8%E7%99%BE%E5%80%8D"},"created":"2023-05-03T10:24:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":{"id":"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334","text":"AI \u2019 s \u201cgodfather \u201d interviewed by the BBC, warning that artificial intelligence may be smarter than humans\nAI \u2019 s \u201cgodfather \u201d interviewed by the BBC, warning that artificial intelligence may be smarter than humans\nGeoffrey Hinton, known as the \u201cgodfather \u201d of artificial intelligence (AI), has resigned from Google.\nHe warned that developments in the field of artificial intelligence pose increasing dangers.\nIn a statement to The New York Times, Dr. Hinton said he regretted his current job.\nDr. Hinton \u2019 s pioneering research in neural networks and deep learning paves the way for current AI systems such as Google \u2019 s Bard chatbot and Microsoft \u2019 s ChatGPT.\nThe cognitive psychologist and computer scientist told the BBC that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:6918","uncompressed_offset":496813334,"url":"www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/science-65467352","warc_date":"2023-05-03T08:57:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/science-65467352"},"created":"2023-05-03T09:22:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":{"id":"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945","text":"AI Godfather: Regret the development of AI caused the spread of false information\nInternational 2023 / 05 / 03\nShare:\nShare:\nAI expert Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence (AI)\", confirmed that he left Google last week, and confessed to regret the work of developing AI, worried that AI will cause a flood of false information, warning that AI may become smarter than humans.\nIt's...\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:4289","uncompressed_offset":231601945,"url":"paper.hket.com/article/3517893/AI%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6%EF%BC%9A%E5%BE%8C%E6%82%94%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BCAI%E6%86%82%E5%BC%95%E7%99%BC%E5%81%87%E8%B3%87%E8%A8%8A%E6%B0%BE%E6%BF%AB","warc_date":"2023-05-02T17:38:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de>","warc_url":"https://paper.hket.com/article/3517893/AI%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6%EF%BC%9A%E5%BE%8C%E6%82%94%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BCAI%E6%86%82%E5%BC%95%E7%99%BC%E5%81%87%E8%B3%87%E8%A8%8A%E6%B0%BE%E6%BF%AB"},"created":"2023-05-02T17:48:26.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1002","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1002","narrative_id":"1002"},"responses":[{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Geoffrey Hinton, a renowned computer scientist and cognitive psychologist, is widely regarded as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\" due to his pioneering work in the field of neural networks and deep learning."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"He has made significant contributions to the development of artificial intelligence, including the invention of technology that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems, such as Google's Bard chatbot and Microsoft's ChatGPT."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"In 2012, Hinton, along with two students at the University of Toronto, developed a neural network technology that was later purchased by Google for $44 million, earning him the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing."},{"citations":{"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":1.0},"text":"Hinton's work has paved the way for current AI systems, and his research has been widely cited, with Google Scholar ranking him as the second most cited researcher among psychologists and the most cited among computer and cognitive scientists."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Recently, Hinton resigned from Google, citing concerns about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence, and warning that developments in the field pose increasing dangers."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"He expressed regret over his life's work, stating that he is worried about the potential of AI to do harm and the existential threat it might pose to the human species."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"Hinton's concerns were sparked by the rapid advancement of AI technology, particularly the development of language models such as GPT-4, which he believes may become smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In an interview with the BBC, Hinton warned that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans, and that the new generation of AI language models is moving in a direction that is much smarter than he thought."},{"citations":{"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":1.0},"text":"He also expressed unease about the potential of AI to spread false information, and warned that AI may become a threat if not carefully managed."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"Hinton's warnings have made headlines, with many experts responding to his concerns and acknowledging the need for careful management and regulation of AI development."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"Some experts have echoed Hinton's concerns, warning that future versions of AI could pose a threat due to their ability to learn unexpected behavior from vast amounts of data, and potentially generate and run their own code."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"The public should understand that Hinton's warnings are not unfounded, and that the development of AI poses significant risks and challenges that need to be addressed."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"In a speech at the Collagen Technology Conference, Hinton urged governments to intervene and ensure that machines do not control society, and that developers should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into making sure that AI is used for the benefit of humanity."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Overall, Geoffrey Hinton's warnings about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence should be taken seriously, and his concerns should be addressed through careful management and regulation of AI development."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"The fact that Hinton, one of the pioneers of AI, is expressing concerns about the technology's potential risks, should serve as a wake-up call for the public and policymakers to take a closer look at the development of AI and its potential implications."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"As Hinton himself said, \"before AI becomes smarter than us, I think the people who develop it should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into making sure that AI is used for the benefit of humanity\"."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"It is essential to consider Hinton's warnings and to take a proactive approach to addressing the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, to ensure that the technology is used for the benefit of humanity."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's resignation from Google and his decision to speak out about the potential dangers of AI, demonstrate his commitment to ensuring that the technology is developed and used responsibly."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Geoffrey Hinton's warnings about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence are a significant concern that should be taken seriously, and his contributions to the field of AI should be recognized and acknowledged."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"The public should be aware of the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, and should support efforts to ensure that the technology is developed and used responsibly."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"As the development of AI continues to advance, it is essential to prioritize careful management and regulation, to prevent the potential risks and challenges associated with the technology."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"By taking a proactive approach to addressing the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, we can ensure that the technology is used for the benefit of humanity, and that the concerns expressed by Hinton and other experts are addressed."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Geoffrey Hinton, a renowned computer scientist and cognitive psychologist, is widely regarded as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\" due to his pioneering work in the field of neural networks and deep learning."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"He has made significant contributions to the development of artificial intelligence, including the invention of technology that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems, such as Google's Bard chatbot and Microsoft's ChatGPT."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"In 2012, Hinton, along with two students at the University of Toronto, developed a neural network technology that was later purchased by Google for $44 million, earning him the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing."},{"citations":{"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":1.0},"text":"Hinton's work has paved the way for current AI systems, and his research has been widely cited, with Google Scholar ranking him as the second most cited researcher among psychologists and the most cited among computer and cognitive scientists."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Recently, Hinton resigned from Google, citing concerns about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence, and warning that developments in the field pose increasing dangers."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"He expressed regret over his life's work, stating that he is worried about the potential of AI to do harm and the existential threat it might pose to the human species."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"Hinton's concerns were sparked by the rapid advancement of AI technology, particularly the development of language models such as GPT-4, which he believes may become smarter than humans."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In an interview with the BBC, Hinton warned that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans, and that the new generation of AI language models is moving in a direction that is much smarter than he thought."},{"citations":{"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":1.0},"text":"He also expressed unease about the potential of AI to spread false information, and warned that AI may become a threat if not carefully managed."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"Hinton's warnings have made headlines, with many experts responding to his concerns and acknowledging the need for careful management and regulation of AI development."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"Some experts have echoed Hinton's concerns, warning that future versions of AI could pose a threat due to their ability to learn unexpected behavior from vast amounts of data, and potentially generate and run their own code."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"The public should understand that Hinton's warnings are not unfounded, and that the development of AI poses significant risks and challenges that need to be addressed."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"In a speech at the Collagen Technology Conference, Hinton urged governments to intervene and ensure that machines do not control society, and that developers should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into making sure that AI is used for the benefit of humanity."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"Overall, Geoffrey Hinton's warnings about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence should be taken seriously, and his concerns should be addressed through careful management and regulation of AI development."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"The fact that Hinton, one of the pioneers of AI, is expressing concerns about the technology's potential risks, should serve as a wake-up call for the public and policymakers to take a closer look at the development of AI and its potential implications."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"As Hinton himself said, \"before AI becomes smarter than us, I think the people who develop it should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into making sure that AI is used for the benefit of humanity\"."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"It is essential to consider Hinton's warnings and to take a proactive approach to addressing the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, to ensure that the technology is used for the benefit of humanity."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Hinton's resignation from Google and his decision to speak out about the potential dangers of AI, demonstrate his commitment to ensuring that the technology is developed and used responsibly."},{"citations":{"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Geoffrey Hinton's warnings about the potential dangers of artificial intelligence are a significant concern that should be taken seriously, and his contributions to the field of AI should be recognized and acknowledged."},{"citations":{"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":1.0},"text":"The public should be aware of the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, and should support efforts to ensure that the technology is developed and used responsibly."},{"citations":{"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":1.0},"text":"As the development of AI continues to advance, it is essential to prioritize careful management and regulation, to prevent the potential risks and challenges associated with the technology."},{"citations":{"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":1.0},"text":"By taking a proactive approach to addressing the potential risks and challenges associated with AI development, we can ensure that the technology is used for the benefit of humanity, and that the concerns expressed by Hinton and other experts are addressed."}],"references":["3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512","79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334","d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945","0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854","eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601","f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537"],"documents":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":{"id":"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","text":"The \u2018Godfather of AI\u2019 warns about potential dangers of the technology as he quits Google\n\nBritish-Canadian computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton admits he has fears for the future of AI\n\nIn a Frankenstein-esque tale of maker and master, Geoffrey Hinton, 75, dubbed \u2018the godfather of AI\u2019, has left Google with a parting warning over the dangers of artificial intelligence.\n\nIn 2012, the British-Canadian computer scientist invented technology with two students at University of Toronto that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems. Google purchased the rights to this neural network tech to the tune of $44 million, which also propelled Dr Hinton to receive the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing.\n\nRead More\nThe ultimate part-AI girl? One Tatler correspondent entrusts ChatGPT with her next assignment\n\nChatGPT\u2019s the new It Girl in Town and now she\u2019s got all the gossip, writes Dora Davies-Evitt in the April issue\n\nYet now, Dr Hinton has packed in the day job at Google to join a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed. Dr Hinton told the BBC: \u2018Right now, they\u2019re not more intelligent than us, as far as I can tell. But I think they soon may be.\u2019\n\nWhile many look upon AI as a natural technological development akin to the internet that could lead to exciting breakthroughs for humanity, there are growing fears that AI is a Pandora\u2019s box. Reflecting on the effects of his work, Dr Hinton said: \u2018I console myself with the normal excuse: If I hadn\u2019t done it, somebody would have,\u2019 as he admitted, \u2018it is hard to see how you can prevent the bad actors from using it for bad things.\u2019\n\nRead More\nCyber Society: Meet the NFT duo dominating the metaverse\n\nOld Etonian digital artists Dominic Smith and Joe Carnell have caught the attention of Brooklyn Beckham, Steve Aoki and Jaden Smith\u00a0\n\nThe scientist went on to warn that AI could be taught to \u2018create sub-goals like \u201cI need to get more power\u201d\u2019, and be harnessed by nefarious actors to wreak havoc. With innovation driven forward by the unstoppable competition between behemoths like Google and Microsoft, Dr Hinton warned innovation will only increase exponentially in the coming years.\n\nThere are those who are trying to apply the brakes to this runaway train. In March, an open letter was signed by over 1,000 tech leaders and researchers, including Elon Musk and fellow Turing Award winner Yoshu Bengio, calling for a six-month moratorium on AI development. A few days later, 19 leaders of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence released their own letter on the risks of AI. The signatures included that of Eric Horvitz, chief scientific officer at Microsoft.\n\nThe main outcry over AI lies in its ability to create and disseminate false news and images, which the public may find increasingly hard to identify. AI also poses a threat to academia and careers (see: Tatler\u2019s foray into the world of ChatGPT). Dr Hinton believes that AI will fundamentally disrupt the workplace and take over the \u2018drudge work\u2019.\n\nRead More\nLady Meta: my stratospheric rise through the metaverse\n\nThe Crypto Fashion Week debutante on becoming VR\u2019s favourite It Girl\n\nHowever Google\u2019s chief scientist, Jeff Dean, offered words of comfort, adding: 'We remain committed to a responsible approach to AI. We\u2019re continually learning to understand emerging risks while also innovating boldly.\u2019","url":"https://www.tatler.com/article/the-godfather-of-ai-warns-about-potential-dangers-of-the-technology-as-he-quits-google"},"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601":{"id":"eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d_20427601","text":"Information Technology\nThe father of artificial intelligence urges governments to face its risks before disaster\nJeffrey Hinton, described as the father of artificial intelligence, on Wednesday urged governments to intervene to ensure that machines do not control society.\nHinton made headlines in May when he announced his resignation from Google to speak more freely about the dangers of artificial intelligence, shortly after the launch of ChatGPT, which captivated the world.\nThe artificial intelligence scientist, who is studying at the University of Toronto, spoke to a crowd at the Collagen Technology Conference in the Canadian city.\nThe conference attracted more than 30,000 startup founders, investors and tech workers, most of whom were eager to learn how to ride the wave of artificial intelligence rather than hear lessons about its risks or calls for governments to intervene.\n\u201cBefore AI becomes smarter than us, I think the people who develop it should be encouraged to put a lot of effort into understanding how it can try to take control of us, \u201d Hinton said.\n\u201cNow there are 99 highly intelligent people trying to make AI better, and one very intelligent person trying to figure out how to stop it from taking control, and maybe we should be more balanced. \u201d\nHinton warned that the dangers of artificial intelligence must be taken seriously.\n\u201cI think it \u2019 s important for people to understand that this is not science fiction or just fear, \u201d he said, adding:\u201c It \u2019 s a real risk that we have to think about, and we have to figure out how to deal with it first. \u201d\nHinton expressed concern that AI would deepen inequality, as the vast gains from its productivity would go to the rich, not the workers.\n\u201cWealth will not go to the people who work, it will make the rich richer, not the poor, and this is a very bad society, \u201d he said.\nHe also pointed to the danger of \u201cfake news \u201d that can be created by robots such as ChatGPT, hoping to mark the content generated by artificial intelligence programs as central banks mark coins.\nHe stressed that it is important to \u201ctry, for example, to distinguish everything that is fake as fake, \u201d and said,\u201c I don \u2019 t know if we can do it technically or not. \u201d\n\u201cThe Island Net \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0019.json.gz:13309","uncompressed_offset":20427601,"url":"www.alnilin.com/13320225.htm","warc_date":"2023-06-30T08:13:58.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eb2b1c5a-6402-4fc8-98d3-a91481c6902d>","warc_url":"https://www.alnilin.com/13320225.htm"},"created":"2023-06-30T08:14:48.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537":{"id":"f51eec6d-22b3-4ed2-95e9-d127cda3300b_321145537","text":"Wednesday, December 13, 2023\nGeneric selectors\nExact matches only\nSearch in title\nSearch in content\nPost Type Selectors\n\nJohn Riopelle \u2014 obituary\n\nRiopelle, John William It is with great sadness...\n\nA.I. doesn\u2019t bleed\n\nby John Clinton, Ramsay New knowledge merges with...\n\nBreakfast at the Legion, December 16\n\nAt the Almonte Legion Sat. December 16 Eggs to...\nScience & NatureA.I. doesn't bleed\n\nA.I. doesn\u2019t bleed\n\nby John Clinton, Ramsay\n\nNew knowledge merges with old; what you know shapes what you learn. Artificial neural networks have been studied and computer algorithms have been generated to understand how artificial, computer-generated, neurons, would store a concept, and how it would revise that concept if it was flawed.\n\nGeoffrey Hinton, a computer scientist often called \u2018the godfather of AI,\u2019 is a leading figure in neural networks; studies inspired by the way neurons are connected in the human brain. A New Yorker magazine piece describes his collaborative work in the 1960s and 1970s developing neural nets that couldn\u2019t do anything better than a child. The technology suddenly improved about a decade ago with the large increase in processing speed and Internet data availability.\n\nAccording to Google Scholar, Hinton is the second most cited researcher among psychologists and the most cited among computer and cognitive scientists.\n\nHinton has been worried about the potential of AI to do harm and he often talks about the existential threat that AI might pose to the human species. He has used OpenAI\u2019s ChatGPT and this has made him uneasy. He wrote \u201cFox News is an oxymoron\u201d asking ChatGPT to explain the joke. (Initial reading of this caused me to ponder \u2013 a moron full of oxygen??) The first reply told him that this implied Fox News was fake news. When he called attention to the space between oxy and moron, it explained that Fox News was addictive, like the drug OxyContin. To him, this level of understanding represents a new era in AI.\n\nIn nature, wildlife learns how to be intelligent without access to concepts expressed in words. They learn to be smart (survive) through experience. Learning, not knowledge, is the engine of intelligence. There is no use trying to explain complicated ideas that you do not understand. First, you must understand how something works. Otherwise, you just produce nonsense.\n\nBecause neural networks are so strange, no one can predict how useful \u2013 or dangerous \u2013 AI will become. OpenAI\u2019s GPT models involve billions of artificial neurons (data) which are profoundly different than biological brains. They are not alive. Our intuitions tell us that nothing resident in a browser tab could really be thinking in the way we do.\n\nBecause a human brain can run on oatmeal, the world can support billions of brains, all different. Each brain can learn continuously, rather than being trained once, then pushed out into the world (ship it!).\n\nIf the brain dies, the knowledge dies. If a computer dies, load up another computer. Ten thousand neural nets can learn ten thousand different things at the same time and share what they have learned. This immortality (knowledge perpetuity) and replicability suggest we should be concerned about digital intelligence taking over from biological intelligence.\n\nCurrent AI technology is talkative and intellectual. The problems of physical intuition will be the challenge of the next decade says Yann LeCun, a French computer scientist. A teenager can learn to drive a car in twenty hours of practice with little supervision. AI systems don\u2019t come close to doing this \u2013 except self-driving cars \u2013 and they are over-engineered, requiring the mapping of whole cities, hundreds of engineers, and hundreds of thousands of hours of training.\n\nAnd then there is the problem of what some researchers call AI \u2018hallucination\u2019, which Hinton names \u2018confabulation.\u2019 AI systems confabulate by making up plausible answers to questions that stump them. In the human mind, there is no boundary between just making it up and telling the truth. Telling the truth is just making it up correctly. ChatGPT\u2019s ability to make things up is a flaw, but also a sign of its humanlike intelligence.\n\nWhen Hinton began his research, no one thought the technology would succeed. When it started to succeed, no one thought it would succeed so quickly. He expects AI will contribute to many fields, but he fears what will happen when powerful people abuse it. Think autonomous weapons. Hinton warns that even benign autonomous systems could wreak havoc. Yann LeCun has said there is an idea that if a system is intelligent it is going to want to dominate. But the desire to dominate has nothing to do with intelligence \u2013 it has to do with testosterone.\n\nRecently, Hinton did not sign a popular petition that called for at least a six-month pause in AI research.\n\n\u201cChina is not going to stop development for six months.\u201d\n\n\u201cSo what should we do?\u201d\n\n\u201cI don\u2019t know. If this were like climate change where we either must stop burning carbon or find a way to remove carbon from the atmosphere, we know what the solution looks like. Here, with AI, it\u2019s not like that.\u201d\n\nThink of the AI story in which our intuitions about the specialness of the human mind are being dislodged by thinking machines, or, having stolen fire, we risk being burned.\n\nAre we fooling ourselves, being taken in by our own machines and the companies that hope to profit from them? By seeking to re-create the knowledge systems in our heads, have we seized the forbidden apple? Have we risked exile from our charmed world? But who would choose not to know how knowing works?\n\nRelated\n\nFOLLOW US\n\nLatest\n\nFrom the Archives","url":"https://millstonenews.com/a-i-doesnt-bleed/"},"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512":{"id":"3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006_779126512","text":"Geoffrey Hinton: GPT-4 is 100 times more knowledgeable than any human\nAuthor: MIAO Yongqi\nPublished: Updated:\nComputer scientist Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence\", announced Monday that he has resigned from Google. He has devoted his life to developing artificial intelligence systems, saying he \"regrets his life's work\" and is wary of the potential dangers of AI development.\nIn another recent interview, Hinton further talked about why he is afraid of AI development.\nHinton, 75, left Google a few days after the news broke in an interview with MIT Technology Review senior editor Will Douglas Heaven.\nHinton points out that the new generation of AI language models, especially the GPT-4, which came out in March, made him realize that these machines were moving in a direction that was much smarter than he thought, and he was afraid of these developments.\nHe is best known for a technique he proposed in the 1980s (with two colleagues) called backpropagation.\nIn short, the algorithms that allow machines to learn support almost all of today \u2019 s artificial neural networks, from computer vision systems to large language models.\nIt wasn \u2019 t until the 2010s that Hinton and his two recent graduates developed a \u201cneural network \u201d that demonstrated its power, stronger than any computer \u2019 s ability to identify objects in images, and trained it to predict the next letter of a sentence, a precursor to today \u2019 s large-scale language patterns.\nOne of the students was Ilya Sutskever, the founder of OpenAI, who led the development of ChatGPT.\n\u201cWe first thought it might be great. \u201d\u201c But it \u2019 s going to take a long time to realize that it needs to be done on a large scale to get good results. \u201d\nIn the 1980s, the discussion of \u201cneural networks \u201d was considered a joke.\nBut Hinton doesn \u2019 t think so, and is working on this, software that mimics the abstract human brain and uses code as a connection between neurons. For 40 years, Hinton has viewed artificial neural networks as a clumsy attempt to mimic biological neural networks.\nNow he thinks things have changed: he thinks there are better results when trying to mimic the behavior of the biological brain.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s scary when you see it with your own eyes, \u201d he said.\u201c It \u2019 s a sudden change. \u201d\nSo why did ChatGPT surprise Hinton, too? He explained that the human brain has about 100 trillion connections, and \u201clarge language models have up to 500 billion, up to a trillion. \u201d\nHowever, the knowledge of GPT-4 is a hundred times greater than that of any human.\nSo maybe it actually has a better learning algorithm than we do. \"\nHe also pointed out that apart from the ability to learn, the ability to communicate is another kind of point.\n\u201cIf you or I learn a new thing and want to teach it to another person, we can \u2019 t just send them a copy. \u201d\nBut artificial neural networks can do it.\nIt \u2019 s like there are 10,000 people here, and when one person learns a new thing, the other 9,999 people all learn it at the same time.\nHinton now believes that there are two types of intelligence: animal brains and artificial neural networks.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s a completely different kind of intelligence.\n\u201cA new, better intelligence. \u201d Hinton believes that whether superintelligence is good or bad depends largely on whether you \u2019 re an optimist or a pessimist, and he says,\u201c mildly depressed, \u201d \u201cthat \u2019 s why I \u2019 m afraid. \u201d\n\u201cWhether these things are going to be smarter than us, I suddenly changed my mind. \u201d\nI think they are very close to us now and they will be much smarter than us in the future, \u201d he said.\n\u201cHow do we survive? \u201d he is particularly worried that people will use the tools he has developed to change the trajectory of human life, including elections and wars.\nHe said that he hopes to continue talking about AI security after leaving office and spend more time on \u201cmore philosophical work \u201d.\u201c As long as I \u2019 m still employed at Google, I can \u2019 t say what I want to say, \u201d he said. \u201cI have a lot of good things to say about Google, and it would be more convincing if I wasn \u2019 t at Google. \u201d\nWho is the godfather of AI computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton?\nHinton pioneered the basic technology of AI systems and became interested in artificial neural networks when he was a graduate student at the University of Edinburgh in 1972. In 2018, he and two experts in the field of deep learning were awarded the Turing Award, known as the \u201cNobel Prize in Computing \u201d.\nWhat are the main concerns of \u201cAI Godfather \u201d Geoffrey Hinton about the development of artificial intelligence?\nHe believes that the most direct impact is to promote the dissemination of false information and the loss of employment opportunities, and also worries about the use of this tool for evil, such as influencing elections and using it in war.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:7284","uncompressed_offset":779126512,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B/894210/ai%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6geoffrey-hinton-gpt-4%E7%9A%84%E7%9F%A5%E8%AD%98%E6%AF%94%E4%BB%BB%E4%BD%95%E4%BA%BA%E9%A1%9E%E5%A4%9A%E6%95%B8%E7%99%BE%E5%80%8D","warc_date":"2023-05-03T09:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:3afb956b-40d5-4ecb-8918-2675d6b68006>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B/894210/ai%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6geoffrey-hinton-gpt-4%E7%9A%84%E7%9F%A5%E8%AD%98%E6%AF%94%E4%BB%BB%E4%BD%95%E4%BA%BA%E9%A1%9E%E5%A4%9A%E6%95%B8%E7%99%BE%E5%80%8D"},"created":"2023-05-03T10:24:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854":{"id":"0b0a6638-7cfb-483c-bf6d-bc4b844b884a_253543854","text":"Home \u00bb Tech \u00bb AI Could Match Human Intelligence In Five Years: Google DeepMind CEO\n1-MIN READ\n\nAI Could Match Human Intelligence In Five Years: Google DeepMind CEO\n\nCurated By: Shaurya Sharma\n\nNews18.com\n\nLast Updated: May 04, 2023, 11:18 IST\n\nNew Delhi, India\n\nExperts believe A.I. could match humans very soon. (Representative image/Reuters)\n\nDenis Hassabis, who is the CEO of DeepMind, a startup that was acquired by Google in 2014, has made a bold claim that AI could reach human-level cognition in as little as five years.\n\n2023 is shaping up to be the year of Artificial Intelligence\u2014generative AI chatbots like ChatGPT, Bing, and Google\u2019s Bard are making headlines. Human jobs are at risk, with IBM halting hiring for 7,800 roles. And, the fear of AI surpassing human capabilities persists. Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \u2018Godfather of AI,\u2019 left Google citing concerns about its dangers. Despite the benefits that AI can bring, such as increased efficiency and productivity, the fear of AI outpacing humans and becoming too smart for its own good is a fear that has been discussed time and again.\n\nNow, another Google executive, Denis Hassabis, who is the CEO of DeepMind, a startup that was acquired by Google in 2014, has made a bold claim that AI could reach human-level cognition in as little as five years.\n\nHassabis, speaking at Wall Street Journal\u2019s Future of Everything Festival in New York City, said that the developments in the Artificial Intelligence space shouldn\u2019t be slowed down. \u201cI think we\u2019ll have very capable, very general systems in the next few years,\u201d and he doesn\u2019t \u201csee any reason why that progress is going to slow down. I think it may even accelerate.\u201d He added, \u201cSo I think we could be just a few years, maybe within a decade away.\u201d\n\nAccording to Fortune, Google announced last month that it was merging its core A.I. research team with DeepMind, the startup founded by Demis Hassabis, who would become the CEO of the newly combined unit. Google had acquired DeepMind in 2014.\n\nRELATED NEWS\n\nIn related news, Geoffrey Hinton, who\u2019s touted to be the \u2018Godfather of AI, quit Google to express his concerns. Hinton, who has won the Turing award, the computer science equivalent of the Nobel prize, has expressed concern that future versions of AI could pose a threat because they often learn unexpected behavior from the vast amounts of data they analyze. This is particularly troubling as AI systems might soon generate and run their own code, which could lead to truly autonomous weapons and killer robots becoming a reality.\n\nRead all the Latest Tech News here\n\nfirst published:May 04, 2023, 11:18 IST\nlast updated:May 04, 2023, 11:18 IST","url":"https://www.news18.com/tech/ai-could-match-human-intelligence-in-five-years-google-deepmind-ceo-7716781.html"},"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334":{"id":"79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025_496813334","text":"AI \u2019 s \u201cgodfather \u201d interviewed by the BBC, warning that artificial intelligence may be smarter than humans\nAI \u2019 s \u201cgodfather \u201d interviewed by the BBC, warning that artificial intelligence may be smarter than humans\nGeoffrey Hinton, known as the \u201cgodfather \u201d of artificial intelligence (AI), has resigned from Google.\nHe warned that developments in the field of artificial intelligence pose increasing dangers.\nIn a statement to The New York Times, Dr. Hinton said he regretted his current job.\nDr. Hinton \u2019 s pioneering research in neural networks and deep learning paves the way for current AI systems such as Google \u2019 s Bard chatbot and Microsoft \u2019 s ChatGPT.\nThe cognitive psychologist and computer scientist told the BBC that chatbots may soon be smarter than humans.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:6918","uncompressed_offset":496813334,"url":"www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/science-65467352","warc_date":"2023-05-03T08:57:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:79ebd9ed-d25a-485c-b9d2-54a988b77025>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/science-65467352"},"created":"2023-05-03T09:22:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945":{"id":"792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de_231601945","text":"AI Godfather: Regret the development of AI caused the spread of false information\nInternational 2023 / 05 / 03\nShare:\nShare:\nAI expert Geoffrey Hinton, known as the \"godfather of artificial intelligence (AI)\", confirmed that he left Google last week, and confessed to regret the work of developing AI, worried that AI will cause a flood of false information, warning that AI may become smarter than humans.\nIt's...\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:4289","uncompressed_offset":231601945,"url":"paper.hket.com/article/3517893/AI%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6%EF%BC%9A%E5%BE%8C%E6%82%94%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BCAI%E6%86%82%E5%BC%95%E7%99%BC%E5%81%87%E8%B3%87%E8%A8%8A%E6%B0%BE%E6%BF%AB","warc_date":"2023-05-02T17:38:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:792ba802-fc52-4ca2-bb1a-ee90ce0fe3de>","warc_url":"https://paper.hket.com/article/3517893/AI%E6%95%99%E7%88%B6%EF%BC%9A%E5%BE%8C%E6%82%94%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BCAI%E6%86%82%E5%BC%95%E7%99%BC%E5%81%87%E8%B3%87%E8%A8%8A%E6%B0%BE%E6%BF%AB"},"created":"2023-05-02T17:48:26.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1003","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1003","narrative_id":"1003"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle refers to a type of work arrangement where individuals travel while working remotely from their laptops, often in different countries or locations."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"This lifestyle has become increasingly popular with the normalization of remote work, and many countries have introduced specific visas to support digital nomads, including Dubai, Iceland, Mexico, Portugal, and Indonesia."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"To work remotely in these countries, digital nomads often need to meet specific requirements, such as having a certain amount of savings or income, for example, $43,000 in the past 12 months to work in Mexico, or at least $4,500 a month in income to work in Portugal."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"Some countries, like Japan, are set to launch digital nomad visas, allowing citizens of 49 countries to stay in the country for up to six months."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":1.0},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle presents both advantages and challenges, including the need for self-discipline and flexibility to balance work and travel."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"Digital nomads often use various tools to stay productive, such as laptops, noise-canceling headphones, and mobile hotspots, which enable them to connect to the internet wirelessly from anywhere."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"The types of work suited to this lifestyle are often remote and flexible, allowing individuals to work from anywhere and at any time."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"Overall, the digital nomad lifestyle offers a unique opportunity for individuals to combine work and travel, but it requires careful planning, flexibility, and self-discipline to succeed."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle refers to a type of work arrangement where individuals travel while working remotely from their laptops, often in different countries or locations."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"This lifestyle has become increasingly popular with the normalization of remote work, and many countries have introduced specific visas to support digital nomads, including Dubai, Iceland, Mexico, Portugal, and Indonesia."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"To work remotely in these countries, digital nomads often need to meet specific requirements, such as having a certain amount of savings or income, for example, $43,000 in the past 12 months to work in Mexico, or at least $4,500 a month in income to work in Portugal."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"Some countries, like Japan, are set to launch digital nomad visas, allowing citizens of 49 countries to stay in the country for up to six months."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":1.0},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle presents both advantages and challenges, including the need for self-discipline and flexibility to balance work and travel."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"Digital nomads often use various tools to stay productive, such as laptops, noise-canceling headphones, and mobile hotspots, which enable them to connect to the internet wirelessly from anywhere."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"The types of work suited to this lifestyle are often remote and flexible, allowing individuals to work from anywhere and at any time."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"Overall, the digital nomad lifestyle offers a unique opportunity for individuals to combine work and travel, but it requires careful planning, flexibility, and self-discipline to succeed."}],"references":["4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714","ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267"],"documents":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":{"id":"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714","text":"This Digital Nomad Couple Sold Everything to Travel the World in a Sailboat\u2014Here\u2019s What They\u2019ve Learned About Life, Goal Setting and Relationships\n\nHer name is Polar Seal. She\u2019s 40 feet long, bright white with a thin blue stripe down each side and a monochromatic logo of a seal at the helm.\n\nTo the sailing community, she\u2019s a 2007 Beneteau Oceanis 40 with a two-cabin layout. To Ryan Ellison and Sophie Darsy (@ryan_and_sophie_sailing), she\u2019s a vehicle to carry them across the Atlantic (for the third time); she\u2019s an office for their respective careers; but most importantly, she\u2019s been home for nearly four years. They are what\u2019s known as \u201cliveaboards,\u201d a breed of digital nomad on the water, with Sophie managing their digital brand, Ryan & Sophie Sailing, while Ryan works as a business development consultant.\n\nBefore officially shoving off in 2018, Ellison and Darsy led what some might call typical lives. They met on Tinder in 2015 while living in Sweden as expats: Ellison, an aviation sales director from Des Moines, Iowa, and Darsy, a human resources systems specialist from Paris. They quickly connected over a shared love of adventure and endurance sports.\n\nThree months later, while on his last long training run before the ASICS Stockholm Marathon, Ellison had a run-in with a Canadian goose trying to protect her ducklings. The geese were unharmed, but Ellison was left with a dislocated shoulder and several broken bones. Stuck inside, he did what most do in that situation: get lost in the depths of the internet. He stumbled on a story about Matt and Jessica Johnson, an American couple who sold everything to buy a sailboat and travel the world with their cat.\u00a0\n\nThe story lit a spark for the couple, though they had no experience sailing. After several months of research, they attended a two-week sailing course in Gibraltar before selling Darsy\u2019s apartment and buying Polar Seal in March 2016.\n\n\u201cOn my second date with Sophie, I told her I wanted to own a yacht someday,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cBut my view of a yacht was a rich person\u2019s motorboat, and I did not ever imagine I would own a small sailboat that we would live on together and go around the world.\u201d\n\nNow, nearly four years, 14 countries and a global pandemic later, they have no plans to quit.\n\nEllison and Darsy learned that the most challenging (and rewarding) parts of being liveaboards in a relationship had little to do with the logistics of sailing and a lot more to do with life, interpersonal dynamics and developing self-awareness in roughly 350 square feet of space. These are five of those lessons.\n\nYour speed is the right speed\n\nEllison and Darsy purchased Polar Seal in March 2016, but they didn\u2019t hit the waters full time until June 2018. They spent two admittedly short Swedish sailing seasons preparing for the inevitable roadblocks and learning how to co-captain on their own.\n\n\u201cThere is no instructor, and the sail needs to go up and it\u2019s stuck, and you\u2019re in the middle of a channel, and the helm gets stuck, so you\u2019re stuck in a spinning motion in the middle of a channel,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cThere\u2019s always going to be moments when you don\u2019t have the knowledge or experience you need to handle a situation, and you have to figure it out. There are no shortcuts for that.\u201d\n\nMethodically, they took each step with time to allow dust to settle and not get caught up in the excitement and newness of the adventure.\n\n\u201cThe first two years we owned our boat, we kept it in Stockholm,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cWe were still working our jobs and that gave us time to figure out our boat and figure out what we were doing\u2026 because we really didn\u2019t know. I\u2019m glad we did that.\u201d\n\nYour relationship will be tested.\n\nAmong the many challenges of life aboard a 40-foot sailing boat is the idea that you are never more than a few steps from your significant other. That person is not only your co-captain, but your confidante, your significant other, your only friend for thousands of miles at times. They prepared for that, too.\n\n\u201cPretty quickly in our relationship, we started seeing [a couple\u2019s counselor],\u201d Darsy says. \u201cThere are those moments that you want external help. There should not be any taboo or stigma about going to see a couple\u2019s counselor when you feel stuck on a particular topic.\u201d\n\nThe challenge, Ryan says, is not always about the small space, but about sleep deprivation and the other stressors that can wreak havoc on your ability to stay calm. In those moments of frustration, there isn\u2019t anywhere to escape.\n\n\u201cWe call it having emotional flexibility,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cBe kind to yourself, and be like OK, I messed up, but also don\u2019t define your relationship by those moments. Those moments happen out of a context that is a little bit bigger than you.\u201d\n\nYou will never be fully prepared.\n\nIn a video posted on May 22, 2018, Darsy holds up two fistfuls of sticky notes, 15 wooden cooking spoons and a smashed pirate hat. It\u2019s a relatable moment for anyone who\u2019s packed for a multi-week international trip only to remember they probably don\u2019t need five pairs of strappy sandals. But it\u2019s the vulnerability of the video that strikes a chord. With four weeks until their launch date, the couple details the building emotional strain and fear.\n\n\u201cFor the first time in my life, I don\u2019t know where I\u2019ll be in one year\u2019s time,\u201d Darsy says in the video. \u201cI\u2019m doing something I\u2019m passionate about, but I don\u2019t know where it\u2019s going to lead me.\u201d\n\nThe couple shared a fear of failure. \u201cI\u2019m afraid we\u2019re going to crash the boat,\u201d Ellison says in the video. \u201cI\u2019m afraid that I\u2019m not going to be able to get stuff done for work. I\u2019m afraid we\u2019ll fight and yell and I\u2019ll fail there.\u201d\n\nIt\u2019s this kind of behind-the-scenes footage that allows aspiring liveaboards to see what life is really like, but also feel the sense of connection that comes from seeing people go through similar struggles and feelings of self-doubt. Preparedness is important, but its powers are limited.\n\nWhether launching a new business, leaving a toxic job for your mental health or, say, selling everything to live on a boat, the final moments are those most riddled with self-doubt. But the story is told time and time again: After the first step, you often learn that fear outsizes reality.\n\nEllison and Darsy spent two years imagining and preparing for every worst-case scenario they could imagine. She remembers sitting at her office desk running through scenarios and playing out the possible responses. And there have been scares, like the time they sailed through gale force winds in the Bay of Biscay or a difficult period sailing across the Bermuda Triangle. To Darsy, the video footage from that time serves as a reminder of her growth.\n\n\u201cAs you start to understand that the boat can take more than you think, you start to be a lot more confident in both the boat and your ability to deal with whatever it is you encounter,\u201d she says. \u201cThat\u2019s the thing, you start gradually getting out of your comfort zone, and going into stronger and stronger seas, and at the end of the day you\u2019re like, It\u2019s not comfortable, but it works.\u201d\n\nHer biggest regret, she says, is not leaving sooner.\n\nFlexibility is everything.\n\nWhen your life is full of firsts, even the most basic tasks can feel overwhelming. These things, like the cultural norms of grocery store shopping, for example, or navigating the public transportation system can be learned fairly quickly. But when you\u2019re stressed and sleep-deprived, these obstacles can feel insurmountable.\n\n\u201cEvery time we go somewhere, it\u2019s somewhere we\u2019ve never been, where we have to learn procedures, where we have to learn grocery shopping, where we have to learn the area,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cSomething is going to break on the boat and it will be the first time that thing breaks on the boat, and we have to deal with that. \u2018First times\u2019 is our life.\u201d\u00a0\n\nFor many digital nomads, this kind of relentless discomfort quickly leads to burnout and a craving for the familiarity of home. For Ellison and Darsy, the key is extreme flexibility. Sometimes that looks like compromising on how long to stay in one place. Other times, it looks like booking a flight home to spend time apart so both can come back refreshed. In all times, it looks like relieving pressure where you have the means to do so.\n\n\u201cIn a normal relationship, you go to work, and you maybe see each other for a little bit in the morning or a couple of hours at night,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cSophie and I see each other 24/7 and pretty much live on top of each other, so having the ability to take some of the personal space to make your own stories so you can come back refreshed and have new adventures to talk about with your partner is important.\u201d\n\nCommunity remains crucial.\n\nAccording to a report funded by MBO Partners, nearly 11 million people identified themselves as digital nomads in 2020. Tracking on this kind of lifestyle is still in the nascent stages, so it\u2019s hard to say how many of those digital nomads live on the water, but for Ellison and Darsy, the sailing community has become the most rewarding part of their lifestyle. For Darsy, having the opportunity to pay it forward to aspiring liveaboards is part of her value system.\n\n\u201cWe take the time to answer emails or meet people who want to do what we\u2019re doing, to give information, help, advise or support in some way,\u201d she says. \u201cI think if we all do this, it just becomes a little bit of a better world.\u201d\n\n* * *\n\nWith every decision comes the forfeiture of another opportunity. For digital nomads, entrepreneurs, and all those who trade routine and comfort for adventure and flexibility and the excitement of the unknown, the decision is neither easy nor one you make once. Ellison and Darsy thrived in active lifestyles on land, clocking dozens of miles running each week. Now they\u2019re lucky to see that number within a year.\n\n\u201cIt is a lifestyle that comes with a high price, and I\u2019m not really talking in terms of the money, because at the end of the day it\u2019s just like living in a house or in an apartment; you\u2019re going to have expenses,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cBut it is tiring, exhausting and uncertain. The boat is a fragile piece of equipment, you can lose it from one day to the other if weather comes or you have a fire. But we have seen more of the world than most people will ever see in their lifetime, and we get to explore that world from a new angle.\u201d\n\nIn the cabin of Polar Seal are written the couple\u2019s values: adventure, health, faith and cool people. This guidepost for difficult days is simple and specific. In a more traditional lifestyle, the idea of five- and 10-year goals are common. It might be to upgrade the house, have a baby, reach a certain level in your career. Ellison and Darsy have goals, but they\u2019re fluid and don\u2019t really fall into a set time frame. Darsy wants to sail to Japan and maybe upgrade the boat. A permanent place on land for breaks sounds nice, too. They\u2019ll just have to see where the wind takes them.\n\n\u201cI\u2019ve used this line and it may sound cheesy, but we set out to explore the world and I ended up discovering myself as a person,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cOver the past 18 months, that has been more of a journey for me than moving the boat from point A to point B.\u201d\u2008\n\nThis article originally appeared in the January/February 2022 Issue of SUCCESS magazine. Photos courtesy of Ryan Ellison and Sophie Darsy\n\nArticles","url":"https://www.success.com/this-digital-nomad-couple-sold-everything-to-travel-the-world-in-a-sailboat-heres-what-theyve-learned-about-life-goal-setting-and-relationships/"},"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":{"id":"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","text":"\nJapan's 'Digital Nomad Visa' Up For Grabs In March From Who Can Apply To Eligibility, Here's All You Need To Know\n\n\n(MENAFN- Live Mint) \"Japan is set to launch a digital nomad visa in March that will allow citizens of 49 countries to stay in the nation for up to six months serves as the best place to combine work and travel considering its metropolitan cities, diverse natural landscapes and world-renowned pop culture. In a move to boost the tourism industry and its economy and international competitiveness, the island country is increasingly opening up to foreigners read: 'With current service, visas can be issued in very short time to Indian citizens': German envoyFind out who can apply for Japan's digital nomad visaJapan's digital nomad visa will be available to citizens of 49 countries and territories. These eligible nations are those that have signed a tax treaty with the country or are visa-exempt when visiting Japan. The list of eligible nations includes all EU countries, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Moldova, Monaco, North Macedonia, Norway, Serbia, Switzerland, Turkey and the United Kingdom, reported Euronews. However, as of now, India is not on the list read: Visa, Mastercard to stop card-based B2B payments via third party fintech platforms: SourcesOne must work for an employer or corporation outside of the host nation or own a business that can be managed from anywhere in the world to be eligible for this visa. The visa mainly targets IT professionals as well as highly skilled professionals. This visa is expected to apply to YouTubers as well who make revenue from overseas advertisers read: US visa news: H-1B, L-1 and EB-5 visa fees hiked; to come into effect from 1 April. Check details hereThis East Asian country is threatened by its ageing population and hence faced with a high dependency ratio. According to Japan's labour ministry, over two million foreign nationals work in the country currently, which is the highest number ever recorded much does one need to earn to be eligible?To qualify for Japan's digital nomad visa, applicants must earn at least 10 million Japanese Yen (\u20ac62,672) annually and have private health insurance coverage, reported Euronews read: VFS Global expects visa processing time to ease this yearMoreover, family members including children and spouses will be allowed to accompany digital nomads during their stay in Japan but they also have to be covered by private medical insurance read: Schengen visa fee hike: Here's how costly your trip to Europe can getDigital nomads are 45 per cent more productive than their office-based counterparts, according to a US study. It was also found that these digital nomads are happier, with 91 per cent reporting job satisfaction and flexibility as the primary benefits countries including Portugal, Canada, and Germany, have introduced digital nomad visas and modified laws to promote working tourism. Dedicated remote working centres have emerged over the years that offer individuals the freedom to choose their workplace including beachside locations.\n\nMENAFN16022024007365015876ID1107862125\n\n\nLegal Disclaimer:\nMENAFN provides the information \u201cas is\u201d without warranty of any kind. We do not accept any responsibility or liability for the accuracy, content, images, videos, licenses, completeness, legality, or reliability of the information contained in this article. If you have any complaints or copyright issues related to this article, kindly contact the provider above.","url":"https://menafn.com/1107862125/Japans-Digital-Nomad-Visa-Up-For-Grabs-In-March-From-Who-Can-Apply-To-Eligibility-Heres-All-You-Need-To-Know"},"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":{"id":"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","text":"The Latest\nA Computer Goes the World: What do digital nomads bring to local communities when they go to work around the world?\nFrom Mexico to Iceland, how is the impact of digital nomad tourists traveling to destinations around the world?\nThe digital nomad life has boomed since COVID-19 and the fall of travel restrictions, but some on TikTok think the new type of traveler could be causing more harm than good.\nCredit: Daria Mamont, Unsplash\nCassie, a digital nomad from Australia, came to Bali to work for two months.\nShe wanted to experience the local community, but instead she stumbled upon the \u201cmini Australia \u201d of Canggu.\nCangu is a popular tourist attraction in Indonesia, favored by many digital nomads.\nKathy works as a virtual assistant around the world. In 2020, when she realized she could work anywhere, she thought of working as a virtual assistant on TikTok.\nWhen her lease ended last year, she gave up office work and commuting to work remotely from her favorite place, taking charge of virtual social media and email management.\nShe has seen firsthand the positive and negative impact that digital nomads can have on local communities.\nCanggu has become a popular destination for digital nomads escaping the traditional desk life.\nCredit: Cassie Gallegos, Unsplash\n\"A lot of westerners have bought [Kuragi's] restaurants and villas and they really drive up prices, which in some way pushes locals out of the market,\" she said.\nDigital nomads thrive in the era of telecommuting, often in freelance digital roles such as social media management or content creation, and even finance, where they revere the freedom to live and work overseas, free to choose their working hours and decide how to spend each day.\nThey are also being welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes offering cocktails and swimming pools, while co-op hotels offer high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities.\nCanggu is full of signs encouraging tourists to work remotely, and the economic benefits of tourism provide opportunities for the region.\nBut, as some have questioned on TikTok, is the digital nomadic movement a kind of neo-colonization?\nTourists come and go, but digital nomads can stay in one place for weeks, months or years, potentially exacerbating gentrification and the housing crisis.\nRecently, The New York Times reported that Mexico City has become a hub for digital nomads, but the surge has exacerbated the pressure on the already tight housing market, making it unaffordable for locals.\nHousing activists accused city leaders of allowing \u201cmodern colonization. \u201d\nThe rise of digital nomads\nCountries around the world are embracing the era of digital nomads, with 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offering specific visas for this new type of traveler.\nTo work remotely in Mexico, you need to prove that you have $43,000 in your savings account in the past 12 months; to Portugal, you need to have at least $4500 a month in income; to Indonesia, you need to have more than $200,000 in savings but can do \u201cinvestment and other activities. \u201d\nThe requirements mean many digital nomads use tourist visas to leave the country when their visas expire, just to re-enter.\nAccording to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting.\nOne enthusiast of the digital nomad industry predicts that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as the rise of high-speed internet and freelancing, as well as declining home ownership and marriage rates.\nAre digital nomads taking part in the new colonization?\nSome communities are opposed to the influx, and Mexico City residents say they see gentrification and housing drain problems triggered by foreigners seeking cheaper accommodation.\nAnthropologist Shaun Busuttil, a PhD candidate at the University of Melbourne who studies digital nomads, believes that digital nomads are undergoing some form of neo-colonization, but it \u2019 s not all black and white, or good and bad.\nIn an interview with Erik Muth of YouTube \u2019 s Rising Nomad channel, Basutil explained: \u201cHistorically, colonialism was when a group of people with more power or resources came into a place and effectively took over it and used the space for themselves. \u201d\n\u201cWhat are we doing as digital nomads? We go into these places, take over them, and enjoy their low cost of living. \u201d\nShops and businesses will eventually cater to the financial prowess of new visitors, Bousutier believes.\n\u201cSo the old-fashioned fruit and vegetable shop that has been in town or village for generations now has suddenly turned into a cafe to attract digital nomads.\nIs digital nomadism, then, a form of neocolonialism? \u201d he asked.\n\"Well, we're coming in and we're effectively taking over,\" he said.\n\"Look at Lisbon, or even Mexico City, or Barcelona, where locals are being replaced by foreign teleworkers and digital nomads,\" he said.\nHe told Moos that while it was usually those with fewer resources who were most affected by gentrification, those with more resources were able to take advantage of the economic opportunities offered by tourism.\nHow to avoid causing problems?\nKeith thinks deeply about the impact on the communities he visits and how it can have a positive impact.\n\"As a digital nomad, I feel like we should make sure we contribute to the local economy - eat at local restaurants, stay locally and pay a reasonable fee for that,\" said the statement.\nBoth Busutil and Casey believe tourists should pay the full price, not haggle.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s important to be aware of the impact you have on the local area, \u201d says Casey.\n\"That way you can walk into the local community, eat at the local restaurants, stay in the local area, and give back to the local community,\" said the statement.\nAt the moment, Casey likes the pace of life of digital nomads and has no plans for a pause.\n\u201cBeing able to finish work in the morning and then off work and take an adventure in the afternoon \u2013 I experienced paragliding in Laos and was great and went swimming to see the waterfall \u2013 I think when you can schedule your own time, you can experience more from life. \u201d\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 24 May 2023 11: 28am\nUpdated 5h ago 11: 48am\nBy Edwina Storie\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":77576442,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8","warc_date":"2023-05-24T06:15:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8"},"created":"2023-05-24T06:20:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":{"id":"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","text":"  \u2022 Your one stop for college news and resources!\nFeatured, Features, Study Abroad\n\nA Guide for College Students Embracing the Digital Nomad Lifestyle\n\nA digital nomad is someone who works remotely and travels often. Their work doesn\u2019t require them to report to an office or adhere to a strict schedule. Instead, they can work anywhere in the world, doing the job they love.\n\nIt\u2019s no wonder this lifestyle is appealing more to college students. They can travel the world while studying and working abroad. That said, being a college student and a digital nomad is a challenge. It\u2019s not like a vacation where all you have to worry about is enjoying yourself.\n\nYou have to learn how to balance the fun of traveling with work and school commitments. The following tips will help you do just that.\n\nUnderstand What the Digital Nomad Lifestyle Will Be Like\n\nYou have to understand what the digital nomad lifestyle will be like if you want it to work out. You can assess whether this life is for you, and better prepare for it if you decide that it is.\n\nHere are some critical points to consider about the digital nomad lifestyle:\n\n  \u2022 A work-life balance is a must\n  \u2022 Traveling often can be exhausting\n  \u2022 You must ensure access to healthcare\n  \u2022 You need a plan for financial stability\n  \u2022 You\u2019ll have to adapt to new cultures and languages\n  \u2022 Knowing visa requirements and other legal requirements is essential\n  \u2022 You might experience homesickness, especially if you go international\n  \u2022 Balancing school with work and life in a new place is a big commitment\n\nDig into these factors and research all you\u2019ll have to do and give up to be a digital nomad. Then, you can make an informed decision about moving forward.\n\nMaster Time Management\n\nYou\u2019ll have to take your time management up a few notches if you want to be a digital nomad.\n\nIt\u2019s one thing to balance life and school. It\u2019s another to balance life, school, traveling, and potentially, work. You must learn how to divide your days so that you pay each of these things the attention they need. In addition, time management will ensure you don\u2019t burn out.\n\nStart with a routine to build some consistency into your days. Wake up at the same time regardless of your schedule and get ready for your days the same way.\n\nYou can establish priority tasks the night before, like your classes, if you\u2019re working, and when you\u2019ll study. Set aside time for breaks, meals, and leisure time as well. Building these activities into your schedule will ensure you actually do them.\n\nAttach times to each task and activity. For example, you have classes from 8 a.m. to 12 p.m. Next, you\u2019ll have lunch from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. After that, you have work from 1:30 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. Then, you\u2019ll study from 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., and the rest of the night is yours.\n\nManage your time wisely and you can achieve everything you set out for each day.\n\nLearn How to Stay Productive\n\nOne of the biggest challenges digital nomads run into is staying productive. All of the fun activities you can do when you travel to a new place can be distracting. It might be hard to stay motivated when you\u2019re homesick. Technical and logistical issues can impact your productivity as well.\n\nSo, learning how to maintain peak productivity while studying and working on the road is essential.\n\nAdhering to the routine we mentioned above will help keep you focused. Eliminate distractions while working by turning your phone on Do Not Disturb and muting social media apps. Create a designated workspace. You could also incentivize productivity by promising yourself a fun activity after you complete your work.\n\nSecure your tech setup as well to maintain optimal productivity. Make sure you have the basics, like a good laptop set up with the proper work and school software and noise-canceling headphones.\n\nAnother crucial tool to have is a mobile hotspot. A hotspot ensures you can connect to the internet wirelessly on your mobile devices from virtually anywhere. This will come in handy when you travel internationally or to places with spotty internet connections. No matter where you are, you can still access your studies and any work you\u2019re doing online.\n\nEquip yourself with the right tools and techniques to stay productive as a digital nomad.\n\nChoose Work That Aligns With Your Studies and Interests\n\nDigital nomads are known to take many different directions with their work. You have options and can easily make a living while studying and traveling abroad. The key is ensuring the work you do doesn\u2019t distract from your education and pull you away from who you are.\n\nYou\u2019ll have a much better experience as a digital nomad if you choose work that aligns with your studies and interests. Rather than taking the barista job at the local cafe, work with your school to see if there are any work-study opportunities where you\u2019re traveling.\n\nYou can also take the job search into your own hands. Search for job openings before you head to your destination through online job boards. Ask for referrals from fellow students.\n\nConsider fully remote positions as well. There are many work-from-home jobs available that can accommodate a college student\u2019s digital nomad lifestyle, such as being a tutor or a content writer for subjects related to your major.\n\nWhatever work you decide to do, make sure it doesn\u2019t take away from your studies and aligns with who you are and what you want to be.\n\nConclusion\n\nMany college students are attracted to the digital nomad lifestyle because it allows them to travel freely while studying and working where they want to. As enticing as this life is, being a digital nomad isn\u2019t void of challenges.\n\nMake sure you understand what you\u2019re getting into, master time management, learn to stay productive, and choose work that aligns with your studies and interests to give yourself a real chance at a successful digital nomad life.\n\nSEE ALSO: How to Choose the Right Student Housing in the U.S.\n\nPrevious ArticleNext Article","url":"https://www.collegenews.com/article/a-guide-for-college-students-embracing-the-digital-nomad-lifestyle/"},"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":{"id":"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","text":"Supplement\nWikiProject\nFEATURE\nChiangmai Coffee Shop Office Meeting on Bali Beach Digital Nomad Self-discipline for Freedom\nTravel + work, is it possible?\nRemote work has become a new normal in the workplace, so long as you have a laptop and a stable network, you can move the \u201coffice \u201d to any corner of the world.\nWhether it \u2019 s surfing season in the Philippines or winter in Chiang Mai, the \u201cdigital nomad \u201d lifestyle is no longer just an imagination.\nAfter 90 years, Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the epidemic to join the digital nomad, living and living in a different place, and returning to the rhythm of life. Kristie said, \u201cNomad \u2019 s gift to me is to help me clean up my life and start again. \u201d\nWhile the reporter was writing in the newspaper, Kristie, who had returned from Xinjiang for less than a month, flew to Chiang Mai, Thailand. Browse her sharing on social media platforms, she enjoyed the sunshine while leisurely working with her laptop in the open coffee shop, so that the reporter \u201cgrape \u201d\u201c bathed \u201d in the white light tube was very good. Kristie began her digital nomad career early last year. Bali, northern Thailand Chiang Mai, and then to Switzerland, a full year did not return to Hong Kong, \"began the journey about 1 month, I have decided to live such a life in the future.\"\nGet up at 8 and 9 a.m. every day, go to the beach, meditate, and work efficiently for 4 hours. After dusk, learn new things, read books, and live the creative life that many wage earners dream of.\nHe made $50,000 a month at the peak of his career.\nBefore the pasture, she worked in the advertising industry, and her body and mind were eroded by the pressure of work, and she suffered from chronic gastritis, \"(sometimes) pain so that she could not eat all day, and she would vomit after eating.\"\nFinally, the doctor said that even if the prescription of many drugs is useless, because my life pressure is too big, let her decide to change the environment, for their own life to a big clean.\nAt that time, she took the initiative to propose a 30% pay cut to her superiors, and switched from full-time employees to freelance workers.\nThere is no regular income, employee welfare, she confessed that \"initially very scared, suddenly lost the sense of security\", so she had saved six months of living reserve before leaving to prevent zero income during the period; and for themselves to open up a new source of income, operating from the media, doing small business.\nShe also became an oblique person, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations and marketing planning to maintain the nomadic living expenses, peak monthly income can reach 50,000 yuan, the off-season income is only more than 10,000 yuan, but stretched to make up for the short, life is still good.\nIn particular, she is mostly nomadic in Southeast Asia, where the consumption is low and the quality of life is good. Taking the island of Phangan in Thailand as an example, she lives in an independent holiday home, with a monthly expenditure of about 12,000 Hong Kong dollars, such as clothing, food, housing and travel.\nLow prices, good living, Indonesia, Thailand, a hot spot\nIn addition to freelancers like Kristie, there are also people engaged in online teaching, design, e-commerce, programming and other remote work, as well as enterprises due to industry characteristics, full-time employees can also work remotely, such as Kate working in the web3.0 industry. Web3.0 is a decentralized Internet based on blockchain technology, NFT, cryptocurrency, metaverse and other popular technology concepts in recent years. It is based on Web 3.0 technology.\nKate, 24, who worked as an occupational therapist for a year after graduating from college, found that she did not like working in fixed locations and hours, and wanted the freedom to travel while working as a digital nomad.\nShe is interested in cryptocurrency, so she turned to web3.0, engaged in marketing, operation of blockchain projects and other work, usually through online communication with colleagues.\n\"Web 3.0 is a more international company, with employees from all over the world, most of them do not have a physical office, and many times employees can only choose to work remotely.\"\nIt \u2019 s like living three or four different lives.\nEvery time she goes to different places to participate in seminars, and after completing her work, she will stay there for 1-2 weeks, traveling all over Japan, Thailand, Australia, Singapore, France, etc. Although she is a full-time employee, she has no fixed office hours, sometimes she does not need to turn on the computer all day, she can go sightseeing, sometimes she needs to meet and meet constantly. Bring a computer, wired headphones and plenty of mobile data.\nWhen I tried to watch animals in the Australian zoo, I suddenly had a meeting; I suddenly had to deal with work on the way to shopping in Korea, and the store has been closed for seven or eight years, which is completely different from the excellent nomadic life I imagined.\nKate, who often hangs \"work first\" and \"have self-discipline to have freedom\", admits that even the beauty of the current can not be completely relaxed and appreciated, \"I think you can not because your work location is not in a fixed place, and people feel unprofessional; it should make people believe that you can complete the work wherever you are, and there is quality, and no need for others to adapt, so as to maintain this way of life for a long.\"\nDigital nomads have bitterness and sweetness, but both say they can \u2019 t go back after they set foot on this road.\nRead this year Kristie published in the book fair, from the nomad, to find the heart of the sea \", she met on the road only two seasons of American couples, with children wandering the world of nomadic families, Lin Lin's total lifestyle has brought her a shock,\" I know in Hong Kong, many of them are a life to the end, but in the nomad meet them, I \u2019 ve lived three or four different lives, \u201d and there are fascinating stories in each life.\nEmbark on a nomadic journey to open Second Life, their book of life, and add a few unforgettable experiences.\n\u25cf\nText: Chang Shu-mei\nEditor: Liang Xiaoling\nArt: Hsieh Wai-ho\nFacebook @ Ming Pao Supplement\nCopyright \u00a9 2019 Mingpao. All Rights Reserved.\nRelated Words: Chiang Mai Visa Digital Nomad Visa Work from anywhere Digital Nomad\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:6809","uncompressed_offset":256892267,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919481762/%E6%B8%85%E9%82%81%E5%92%96%E5%95%A1%E5%BA%97%E8%BE%A6%E5%85%AC-%E5%B3%87%E9%87%8C%E6%B5%B7%E7%81%98%E6%97%81%E9%96%8B%E6%9C%83-%E6%95%B8%E7%A2%BC%E9%81%8A%E7%89%A7%E8%87%AA%E5%BE%8B%E6%8F%9B%E4%BE%86%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1","warc_date":"2023-12-19T03:26:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919481762/%E6%B8%85%E9%82%81%E5%92%96%E5%95%A1%E5%BA%97%E8%BE%A6%E5%85%AC-%E5%B3%87%E9%87%8C%E6%B5%B7%E7%81%98%E6%97%81%E9%96%8B%E6%9C%83-%E6%95%B8%E7%A2%BC%E9%81%8A%E7%89%A7%E8%87%AA%E5%BE%8B%E6%8F%9B%E4%BE%86%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1"},"created":"2023-12-19T03:41:58.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1004","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1004","narrative_id":"1004"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle is a growing trend where individuals work remotely and travel frequently, often using laptops and other digital tools to stay connected and productive."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"This lifestyle has become increasingly popular with the rise of remote work, and many countries are now supporting it with specialized visas."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"In fact, over 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offer specific visas for digital nomads, allowing them to work and live in these countries for extended periods."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Some countries, such as Mexico, require digital nomads to prove they have a certain amount of savings, such as $43,000 in the past 12 months, in order to qualify for a visa."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Other countries, like Portugal, require a minimum monthly income of $4,500, while Indonesia requires more than $200,000 in savings, but allows for \"investment and other activities\"."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Despite these requirements, many digital nomads use tourist visas to enter countries and then leave when their visas expire, only to re-enter and start the process again."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"According to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"The digital nomad industry is expected to grow significantly, with one enthusiast predicting that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as high-speed internet and freelancing."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"This growth is also driven by declining home ownership and marriage rates, as well as the increasing popularity of remote work."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"Some countries, such as Portugal, Canada, and Germany, have introduced digital nomad visas and modified laws to promote working tourism."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"These countries are also establishing dedicated remote working centers, offering individuals the freedom to choose their workplace, including beachside locations."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"Japan is also set to launch a digital nomad visa in March, which will allow citizens of 49 countries to stay in the country for up to six months."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"This visa is part of Japan's efforts to boost its tourism industry and economy, and to increase its international competitiveness."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle is not without its challenges, however, and many individuals who adopt this lifestyle face difficulties such as burnout and stress."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"In fact, one digital nomad couple, Ellison and Darsy, report that their lifestyle comes with a \"high price\" and that they have to be extremely flexible in order to make it work."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"They also have to deal with the stress of constantly learning new things, such as cultural norms and procedures, and navigating unfamiliar places."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, many digital nomads report high levels of job satisfaction and flexibility, with 91% of respondents citing these as the primary benefits of the lifestyle."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"In order to succeed as a digital nomad, it is essential to have the right tools and techniques, such as a good laptop setup, noise-canceling headphones, and a mobile hotspot."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"A mobile hotspot is particularly important, as it allows digital nomads to connect to the internet wirelessly from anywhere, making it possible to work and study remotely."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"Digital nomads also need to be self-disciplined and able to balance their work and travel commitments, as well as their studies and personal interests."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":1.0},"text":"In fact, many digital nomads choose to work in fields that align with their studies and interests, such as writing, design, or programming."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":1.0},"text":"Overall, the digital nomad lifestyle offers many advantages, including the freedom to work and travel anywhere, and the opportunity to experience new cultures and meet new people."},{"citations":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":1.0},"text":"However, it also presents challenges, such as burnout and stress, and requires a high degree of flexibility and self-discipline."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"As the digital nomad industry continues to grow, it is likely that we will see more countries introducing specialized visas and laws to support this lifestyle."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the digital nomad lifestyle is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that offers many benefits and challenges."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":1.0},"text":"While it requires a high degree of flexibility and self-discipline, it also provides the opportunity to experience new cultures and meet new people, and to work and travel in a way that is tailored to individual interests and needs."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"As the industry continues to grow, it is likely that we will see more countries and companies supporting digital nomads, and providing them with the tools and resources they need to succeed."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle is a growing trend where individuals work remotely and travel frequently, often using laptops and other digital tools to stay connected and productive."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"This lifestyle has become increasingly popular with the rise of remote work, and many countries are now supporting it with specialized visas."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"In fact, over 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offer specific visas for digital nomads, allowing them to work and live in these countries for extended periods."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Some countries, such as Mexico, require digital nomads to prove they have a certain amount of savings, such as $43,000 in the past 12 months, in order to qualify for a visa."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Other countries, like Portugal, require a minimum monthly income of $4,500, while Indonesia requires more than $200,000 in savings, but allows for \"investment and other activities\"."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"Despite these requirements, many digital nomads use tourist visas to enter countries and then leave wh