as burnout and stress, and requires a high degree of flexibility and self-discipline."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"As the digital nomad industry continues to grow, it is likely that we will see more countries introducing specialized visas and laws to support this lifestyle."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the digital nomad lifestyle is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that offers many benefits and challenges."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":1.0},"text":"While it requires a high degree of flexibility and self-discipline, it also provides the opportunity to experience new cultures and meet new people, and to work and travel in a way that is tailored to individual interests and needs."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":1.0},"text":"As the industry continues to grow, it is likely that we will see more countries and companies supporting digital nomads, and providing them with the tools and resources they need to succeed."}],"references":["4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714","ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267"],"documents":{"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714":{"id":"66a58391-3a62-480f-be64-9b2280bbe834_951964714","text":"This Digital Nomad Couple Sold Everything to Travel the World in a Sailboat\u2014Here\u2019s What They\u2019ve Learned About Life, Goal Setting and Relationships\n\nHer name is Polar Seal. She\u2019s 40 feet long, bright white with a thin blue stripe down each side and a monochromatic logo of a seal at the helm.\n\nTo the sailing community, she\u2019s a 2007 Beneteau Oceanis 40 with a two-cabin layout. To Ryan Ellison and Sophie Darsy (@ryan_and_sophie_sailing), she\u2019s a vehicle to carry them across the Atlantic (for the third time); she\u2019s an office for their respective careers; but most importantly, she\u2019s been home for nearly four years. They are what\u2019s known as \u201cliveaboards,\u201d a breed of digital nomad on the water, with Sophie managing their digital brand, Ryan & Sophie Sailing, while Ryan works as a business development consultant.\n\nBefore officially shoving off in 2018, Ellison and Darsy led what some might call typical lives. They met on Tinder in 2015 while living in Sweden as expats: Ellison, an aviation sales director from Des Moines, Iowa, and Darsy, a human resources systems specialist from Paris. They quickly connected over a shared love of adventure and endurance sports.\n\nThree months later, while on his last long training run before the ASICS Stockholm Marathon, Ellison had a run-in with a Canadian goose trying to protect her ducklings. The geese were unharmed, but Ellison was left with a dislocated shoulder and several broken bones. Stuck inside, he did what most do in that situation: get lost in the depths of the internet. He stumbled on a story about Matt and Jessica Johnson, an American couple who sold everything to buy a sailboat and travel the world with their cat.\u00a0\n\nThe story lit a spark for the couple, though they had no experience sailing. After several months of research, they attended a two-week sailing course in Gibraltar before selling Darsy\u2019s apartment and buying Polar Seal in March 2016.\n\n\u201cOn my second date with Sophie, I told her I wanted to own a yacht someday,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cBut my view of a yacht was a rich person\u2019s motorboat, and I did not ever imagine I would own a small sailboat that we would live on together and go around the world.\u201d\n\nNow, nearly four years, 14 countries and a global pandemic later, they have no plans to quit.\n\nEllison and Darsy learned that the most challenging (and rewarding) parts of being liveaboards in a relationship had little to do with the logistics of sailing and a lot more to do with life, interpersonal dynamics and developing self-awareness in roughly 350 square feet of space. These are five of those lessons.\n\nYour speed is the right speed\n\nEllison and Darsy purchased Polar Seal in March 2016, but they didn\u2019t hit the waters full time until June 2018. They spent two admittedly short Swedish sailing seasons preparing for the inevitable roadblocks and learning how to co-captain on their own.\n\n\u201cThere is no instructor, and the sail needs to go up and it\u2019s stuck, and you\u2019re in the middle of a channel, and the helm gets stuck, so you\u2019re stuck in a spinning motion in the middle of a channel,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cThere\u2019s always going to be moments when you don\u2019t have the knowledge or experience you need to handle a situation, and you have to figure it out. There are no shortcuts for that.\u201d\n\nMethodically, they took each step with time to allow dust to settle and not get caught up in the excitement and newness of the adventure.\n\n\u201cThe first two years we owned our boat, we kept it in Stockholm,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cWe were still working our jobs and that gave us time to figure out our boat and figure out what we were doing\u2026 because we really didn\u2019t know. I\u2019m glad we did that.\u201d\n\nYour relationship will be tested.\n\nAmong the many challenges of life aboard a 40-foot sailing boat is the idea that you are never more than a few steps from your significant other. That person is not only your co-captain, but your confidante, your significant other, your only friend for thousands of miles at times. They prepared for that, too.\n\n\u201cPretty quickly in our relationship, we started seeing [a couple\u2019s counselor],\u201d Darsy says. \u201cThere are those moments that you want external help. There should not be any taboo or stigma about going to see a couple\u2019s counselor when you feel stuck on a particular topic.\u201d\n\nThe challenge, Ryan says, is not always about the small space, but about sleep deprivation and the other stressors that can wreak havoc on your ability to stay calm. In those moments of frustration, there isn\u2019t anywhere to escape.\n\n\u201cWe call it having emotional flexibility,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cBe kind to yourself, and be like OK, I messed up, but also don\u2019t define your relationship by those moments. Those moments happen out of a context that is a little bit bigger than you.\u201d\n\nYou will never be fully prepared.\n\nIn a video posted on May 22, 2018, Darsy holds up two fistfuls of sticky notes, 15 wooden cooking spoons and a smashed pirate hat. It\u2019s a relatable moment for anyone who\u2019s packed for a multi-week international trip only to remember they probably don\u2019t need five pairs of strappy sandals. But it\u2019s the vulnerability of the video that strikes a chord. With four weeks until their launch date, the couple details the building emotional strain and fear.\n\n\u201cFor the first time in my life, I don\u2019t know where I\u2019ll be in one year\u2019s time,\u201d Darsy says in the video. \u201cI\u2019m doing something I\u2019m passionate about, but I don\u2019t know where it\u2019s going to lead me.\u201d\n\nThe couple shared a fear of failure. \u201cI\u2019m afraid we\u2019re going to crash the boat,\u201d Ellison says in the video. \u201cI\u2019m afraid that I\u2019m not going to be able to get stuff done for work. I\u2019m afraid we\u2019ll fight and yell and I\u2019ll fail there.\u201d\n\nIt\u2019s this kind of behind-the-scenes footage that allows aspiring liveaboards to see what life is really like, but also feel the sense of connection that comes from seeing people go through similar struggles and feelings of self-doubt. Preparedness is important, but its powers are limited.\n\nWhether launching a new business, leaving a toxic job for your mental health or, say, selling everything to live on a boat, the final moments are those most riddled with self-doubt. But the story is told time and time again: After the first step, you often learn that fear outsizes reality.\n\nEllison and Darsy spent two years imagining and preparing for every worst-case scenario they could imagine. She remembers sitting at her office desk running through scenarios and playing out the possible responses. And there have been scares, like the time they sailed through gale force winds in the Bay of Biscay or a difficult period sailing across the Bermuda Triangle. To Darsy, the video footage from that time serves as a reminder of her growth.\n\n\u201cAs you start to understand that the boat can take more than you think, you start to be a lot more confident in both the boat and your ability to deal with whatever it is you encounter,\u201d she says. \u201cThat\u2019s the thing, you start gradually getting out of your comfort zone, and going into stronger and stronger seas, and at the end of the day you\u2019re like, It\u2019s not comfortable, but it works.\u201d\n\nHer biggest regret, she says, is not leaving sooner.\n\nFlexibility is everything.\n\nWhen your life is full of firsts, even the most basic tasks can feel overwhelming. These things, like the cultural norms of grocery store shopping, for example, or navigating the public transportation system can be learned fairly quickly. But when you\u2019re stressed and sleep-deprived, these obstacles can feel insurmountable.\n\n\u201cEvery time we go somewhere, it\u2019s somewhere we\u2019ve never been, where we have to learn procedures, where we have to learn grocery shopping, where we have to learn the area,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cSomething is going to break on the boat and it will be the first time that thing breaks on the boat, and we have to deal with that. \u2018First times\u2019 is our life.\u201d\u00a0\n\nFor many digital nomads, this kind of relentless discomfort quickly leads to burnout and a craving for the familiarity of home. For Ellison and Darsy, the key is extreme flexibility. Sometimes that looks like compromising on how long to stay in one place. Other times, it looks like booking a flight home to spend time apart so both can come back refreshed. In all times, it looks like relieving pressure where you have the means to do so.\n\n\u201cIn a normal relationship, you go to work, and you maybe see each other for a little bit in the morning or a couple of hours at night,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cSophie and I see each other 24/7 and pretty much live on top of each other, so having the ability to take some of the personal space to make your own stories so you can come back refreshed and have new adventures to talk about with your partner is important.\u201d\n\nCommunity remains crucial.\n\nAccording to a report funded by MBO Partners, nearly 11 million people identified themselves as digital nomads in 2020. Tracking on this kind of lifestyle is still in the nascent stages, so it\u2019s hard to say how many of those digital nomads live on the water, but for Ellison and Darsy, the sailing community has become the most rewarding part of their lifestyle. For Darsy, having the opportunity to pay it forward to aspiring liveaboards is part of her value system.\n\n\u201cWe take the time to answer emails or meet people who want to do what we\u2019re doing, to give information, help, advise or support in some way,\u201d she says. \u201cI think if we all do this, it just becomes a little bit of a better world.\u201d\n\n* * *\n\nWith every decision comes the forfeiture of another opportunity. For digital nomads, entrepreneurs, and all those who trade routine and comfort for adventure and flexibility and the excitement of the unknown, the decision is neither easy nor one you make once. Ellison and Darsy thrived in active lifestyles on land, clocking dozens of miles running each week. Now they\u2019re lucky to see that number within a year.\n\n\u201cIt is a lifestyle that comes with a high price, and I\u2019m not really talking in terms of the money, because at the end of the day it\u2019s just like living in a house or in an apartment; you\u2019re going to have expenses,\u201d Darsy says. \u201cBut it is tiring, exhausting and uncertain. The boat is a fragile piece of equipment, you can lose it from one day to the other if weather comes or you have a fire. But we have seen more of the world than most people will ever see in their lifetime, and we get to explore that world from a new angle.\u201d\n\nIn the cabin of Polar Seal are written the couple\u2019s values: adventure, health, faith and cool people. This guidepost for difficult days is simple and specific. In a more traditional lifestyle, the idea of five- and 10-year goals are common. It might be to upgrade the house, have a baby, reach a certain level in your career. Ellison and Darsy have goals, but they\u2019re fluid and don\u2019t really fall into a set time frame. Darsy wants to sail to Japan and maybe upgrade the boat. A permanent place on land for breaks sounds nice, too. They\u2019ll just have to see where the wind takes them.\n\n\u201cI\u2019ve used this line and it may sound cheesy, but we set out to explore the world and I ended up discovering myself as a person,\u201d Ellison says. \u201cOver the past 18 months, that has been more of a journey for me than moving the boat from point A to point B.\u201d\u2008\n\nThis article originally appeared in the January/February 2022 Issue of SUCCESS magazine. Photos courtesy of Ryan Ellison and Sophie Darsy\n\nArticles","url":"https://www.success.com/this-digital-nomad-couple-sold-everything-to-travel-the-world-in-a-sailboat-heres-what-theyve-learned-about-life-goal-setting-and-relationships/"},"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":{"id":"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","text":"\nJapan's 'Digital Nomad Visa' Up For Grabs In March From Who Can Apply To Eligibility, Here's All You Need To Know\n\n\n(MENAFN- Live Mint) \"Japan is set to launch a digital nomad visa in March that will allow citizens of 49 countries to stay in the nation for up to six months serves as the best place to combine work and travel considering its metropolitan cities, diverse natural landscapes and world-renowned pop culture. In a move to boost the tourism industry and its economy and international competitiveness, the island country is increasingly opening up to foreigners read: 'With current service, visas can be issued in very short time to Indian citizens': German envoyFind out who can apply for Japan's digital nomad visaJapan's digital nomad visa will be available to citizens of 49 countries and territories. These eligible nations are those that have signed a tax treaty with the country or are visa-exempt when visiting Japan. The list of eligible nations includes all EU countries, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Moldova, Monaco, North Macedonia, Norway, Serbia, Switzerland, Turkey and the United Kingdom, reported Euronews. However, as of now, India is not on the list read: Visa, Mastercard to stop card-based B2B payments via third party fintech platforms: SourcesOne must work for an employer or corporation outside of the host nation or own a business that can be managed from anywhere in the world to be eligible for this visa. The visa mainly targets IT professionals as well as highly skilled professionals. This visa is expected to apply to YouTubers as well who make revenue from overseas advertisers read: US visa news: H-1B, L-1 and EB-5 visa fees hiked; to come into effect from 1 April. Check details hereThis East Asian country is threatened by its ageing population and hence faced with a high dependency ratio. According to Japan's labour ministry, over two million foreign nationals work in the country currently, which is the highest number ever recorded much does one need to earn to be eligible?To qualify for Japan's digital nomad visa, applicants must earn at least 10 million Japanese Yen (\u20ac62,672) annually and have private health insurance coverage, reported Euronews read: VFS Global expects visa processing time to ease this yearMoreover, family members including children and spouses will be allowed to accompany digital nomads during their stay in Japan but they also have to be covered by private medical insurance read: Schengen visa fee hike: Here's how costly your trip to Europe can getDigital nomads are 45 per cent more productive than their office-based counterparts, according to a US study. It was also found that these digital nomads are happier, with 91 per cent reporting job satisfaction and flexibility as the primary benefits countries including Portugal, Canada, and Germany, have introduced digital nomad visas and modified laws to promote working tourism. Dedicated remote working centres have emerged over the years that offer individuals the freedom to choose their workplace including beachside locations.\n\nMENAFN16022024007365015876ID1107862125\n\n\nLegal Disclaimer:\nMENAFN provides the information \u201cas is\u201d without warranty of any kind. We do not accept any responsibility or liability for the accuracy, content, images, videos, licenses, completeness, legality, or reliability of the information contained in this article. If you have any complaints or copyright issues related to this article, kindly contact the provider above.","url":"https://menafn.com/1107862125/Japans-Digital-Nomad-Visa-Up-For-Grabs-In-March-From-Who-Can-Apply-To-Eligibility-Heres-All-You-Need-To-Know"},"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":{"id":"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","text":"The Latest\nA Computer Goes the World: What do digital nomads bring to local communities when they go to work around the world?\nFrom Mexico to Iceland, how is the impact of digital nomad tourists traveling to destinations around the world?\nThe digital nomad life has boomed since COVID-19 and the fall of travel restrictions, but some on TikTok think the new type of traveler could be causing more harm than good.\nCredit: Daria Mamont, Unsplash\nCassie, a digital nomad from Australia, came to Bali to work for two months.\nShe wanted to experience the local community, but instead she stumbled upon the \u201cmini Australia \u201d of Canggu.\nCangu is a popular tourist attraction in Indonesia, favored by many digital nomads.\nKathy works as a virtual assistant around the world. In 2020, when she realized she could work anywhere, she thought of working as a virtual assistant on TikTok.\nWhen her lease ended last year, she gave up office work and commuting to work remotely from her favorite place, taking charge of virtual social media and email management.\nShe has seen firsthand the positive and negative impact that digital nomads can have on local communities.\nCanggu has become a popular destination for digital nomads escaping the traditional desk life.\nCredit: Cassie Gallegos, Unsplash\n\"A lot of westerners have bought [Kuragi's] restaurants and villas and they really drive up prices, which in some way pushes locals out of the market,\" she said.\nDigital nomads thrive in the era of telecommuting, often in freelance digital roles such as social media management or content creation, and even finance, where they revere the freedom to live and work overseas, free to choose their working hours and decide how to spend each day.\nThey are also being welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes offering cocktails and swimming pools, while co-op hotels offer high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities.\nCanggu is full of signs encouraging tourists to work remotely, and the economic benefits of tourism provide opportunities for the region.\nBut, as some have questioned on TikTok, is the digital nomadic movement a kind of neo-colonization?\nTourists come and go, but digital nomads can stay in one place for weeks, months or years, potentially exacerbating gentrification and the housing crisis.\nRecently, The New York Times reported that Mexico City has become a hub for digital nomads, but the surge has exacerbated the pressure on the already tight housing market, making it unaffordable for locals.\nHousing activists accused city leaders of allowing \u201cmodern colonization. \u201d\nThe rise of digital nomads\nCountries around the world are embracing the era of digital nomads, with 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offering specific visas for this new type of traveler.\nTo work remotely in Mexico, you need to prove that you have $43,000 in your savings account in the past 12 months; to Portugal, you need to have at least $4500 a month in income; to Indonesia, you need to have more than $200,000 in savings but can do \u201cinvestment and other activities. \u201d\nThe requirements mean many digital nomads use tourist visas to leave the country when their visas expire, just to re-enter.\nAccording to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting.\nOne enthusiast of the digital nomad industry predicts that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as the rise of high-speed internet and freelancing, as well as declining home ownership and marriage rates.\nAre digital nomads taking part in the new colonization?\nSome communities are opposed to the influx, and Mexico City residents say they see gentrification and housing drain problems triggered by foreigners seeking cheaper accommodation.\nAnthropologist Shaun Busuttil, a PhD candidate at the University of Melbourne who studies digital nomads, believes that digital nomads are undergoing some form of neo-colonization, but it \u2019 s not all black and white, or good and bad.\nIn an interview with Erik Muth of YouTube \u2019 s Rising Nomad channel, Basutil explained: \u201cHistorically, colonialism was when a group of people with more power or resources came into a place and effectively took over it and used the space for themselves. \u201d\n\u201cWhat are we doing as digital nomads? We go into these places, take over them, and enjoy their low cost of living. \u201d\nShops and businesses will eventually cater to the financial prowess of new visitors, Bousutier believes.\n\u201cSo the old-fashioned fruit and vegetable shop that has been in town or village for generations now has suddenly turned into a cafe to attract digital nomads.\nIs digital nomadism, then, a form of neocolonialism? \u201d he asked.\n\"Well, we're coming in and we're effectively taking over,\" he said.\n\"Look at Lisbon, or even Mexico City, or Barcelona, where locals are being replaced by foreign teleworkers and digital nomads,\" he said.\nHe told Moos that while it was usually those with fewer resources who were most affected by gentrification, those with more resources were able to take advantage of the economic opportunities offered by tourism.\nHow to avoid causing problems?\nKeith thinks deeply about the impact on the communities he visits and how it can have a positive impact.\n\"As a digital nomad, I feel like we should make sure we contribute to the local economy - eat at local restaurants, stay locally and pay a reasonable fee for that,\" said the statement.\nBoth Busutil and Casey believe tourists should pay the full price, not haggle.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s important to be aware of the impact you have on the local area, \u201d says Casey.\n\"That way you can walk into the local community, eat at the local restaurants, stay in the local area, and give back to the local community,\" said the statement.\nAt the moment, Casey likes the pace of life of digital nomads and has no plans for a pause.\n\u201cBeing able to finish work in the morning and then off work and take an adventure in the afternoon \u2013 I experienced paragliding in Laos and was great and went swimming to see the waterfall \u2013 I think when you can schedule your own time, you can experience more from life. \u201d\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 24 May 2023 11: 28am\nUpdated 5h ago 11: 48am\nBy Edwina Storie\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":77576442,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8","warc_date":"2023-05-24T06:15:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8"},"created":"2023-05-24T06:20:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":{"id":"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","text":"  \u2022 Your one stop for college news and resources!\nFeatured, Features, Study Abroad\n\nA Guide for College Students Embracing the Digital Nomad Lifestyle\n\nA digital nomad is someone who works remotely and travels often. Their work doesn\u2019t require them to report to an office or adhere to a strict schedule. Instead, they can work anywhere in the world, doing the job they love.\n\nIt\u2019s no wonder this lifestyle is appealing more to college students. They can travel the world while studying and working abroad. That said, being a college student and a digital nomad is a challenge. It\u2019s not like a vacation where all you have to worry about is enjoying yourself.\n\nYou have to learn how to balance the fun of traveling with work and school commitments. The following tips will help you do just that.\n\nUnderstand What the Digital Nomad Lifestyle Will Be Like\n\nYou have to understand what the digital nomad lifestyle will be like if you want it to work out. You can assess whether this life is for you, and better prepare for it if you decide that it is.\n\nHere are some critical points to consider about the digital nomad lifestyle:\n\n  \u2022 A work-life balance is a must\n  \u2022 Traveling often can be exhausting\n  \u2022 You must ensure access to healthcare\n  \u2022 You need a plan for financial stability\n  \u2022 You\u2019ll have to adapt to new cultures and languages\n  \u2022 Knowing visa requirements and other legal requirements is essential\n  \u2022 You might experience homesickness, especially if you go international\n  \u2022 Balancing school with work and life in a new place is a big commitment\n\nDig into these factors and research all you\u2019ll have to do and give up to be a digital nomad. Then, you can make an informed decision about moving forward.\n\nMaster Time Management\n\nYou\u2019ll have to take your time management up a few notches if you want to be a digital nomad.\n\nIt\u2019s one thing to balance life and school. It\u2019s another to balance life, school, traveling, and potentially, work. You must learn how to divide your days so that you pay each of these things the attention they need. In addition, time management will ensure you don\u2019t burn out.\n\nStart with a routine to build some consistency into your days. Wake up at the same time regardless of your schedule and get ready for your days the same way.\n\nYou can establish priority tasks the night before, like your classes, if you\u2019re working, and when you\u2019ll study. Set aside time for breaks, meals, and leisure time as well. Building these activities into your schedule will ensure you actually do them.\n\nAttach times to each task and activity. For example, you have classes from 8 a.m. to 12 p.m. Next, you\u2019ll have lunch from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. After that, you have work from 1:30 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. Then, you\u2019ll study from 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., and the rest of the night is yours.\n\nManage your time wisely and you can achieve everything you set out for each day.\n\nLearn How to Stay Productive\n\nOne of the biggest challenges digital nomads run into is staying productive. All of the fun activities you can do when you travel to a new place can be distracting. It might be hard to stay motivated when you\u2019re homesick. Technical and logistical issues can impact your productivity as well.\n\nSo, learning how to maintain peak productivity while studying and working on the road is essential.\n\nAdhering to the routine we mentioned above will help keep you focused. Eliminate distractions while working by turning your phone on Do Not Disturb and muting social media apps. Create a designated workspace. You could also incentivize productivity by promising yourself a fun activity after you complete your work.\n\nSecure your tech setup as well to maintain optimal productivity. Make sure you have the basics, like a good laptop set up with the proper work and school software and noise-canceling headphones.\n\nAnother crucial tool to have is a mobile hotspot. A hotspot ensures you can connect to the internet wirelessly on your mobile devices from virtually anywhere. This will come in handy when you travel internationally or to places with spotty internet connections. No matter where you are, you can still access your studies and any work you\u2019re doing online.\n\nEquip yourself with the right tools and techniques to stay productive as a digital nomad.\n\nChoose Work That Aligns With Your Studies and Interests\n\nDigital nomads are known to take many different directions with their work. You have options and can easily make a living while studying and traveling abroad. The key is ensuring the work you do doesn\u2019t distract from your education and pull you away from who you are.\n\nYou\u2019ll have a much better experience as a digital nomad if you choose work that aligns with your studies and interests. Rather than taking the barista job at the local cafe, work with your school to see if there are any work-study opportunities where you\u2019re traveling.\n\nYou can also take the job search into your own hands. Search for job openings before you head to your destination through online job boards. Ask for referrals from fellow students.\n\nConsider fully remote positions as well. There are many work-from-home jobs available that can accommodate a college student\u2019s digital nomad lifestyle, such as being a tutor or a content writer for subjects related to your major.\n\nWhatever work you decide to do, make sure it doesn\u2019t take away from your studies and aligns with who you are and what you want to be.\n\nConclusion\n\nMany college students are attracted to the digital nomad lifestyle because it allows them to travel freely while studying and working where they want to. As enticing as this life is, being a digital nomad isn\u2019t void of challenges.\n\nMake sure you understand what you\u2019re getting into, master time management, learn to stay productive, and choose work that aligns with your studies and interests to give yourself a real chance at a successful digital nomad life.\n\nSEE ALSO: How to Choose the Right Student Housing in the U.S.\n\nPrevious ArticleNext Article","url":"https://www.collegenews.com/article/a-guide-for-college-students-embracing-the-digital-nomad-lifestyle/"},"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":{"id":"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","text":"Supplement\nWikiProject\nFEATURE\nChiangmai Coffee Shop Office Meeting on Bali Beach Digital Nomad Self-discipline for Freedom\nTravel + work, is it possible?\nRemote work has become a new normal in the workplace, so long as you have a laptop and a stable network, you can move the \u201coffice \u201d to any corner of the world.\nWhether it \u2019 s surfing season in the Philippines or winter in Chiang Mai, the \u201cdigital nomad \u201d lifestyle is no longer just an imagination.\nAfter 90 years, Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the epidemic to join the digital nomad, living and living in a different place, and returning to the rhythm of life. Kristie said, \u201cNomad \u2019 s gift to me is to help me clean up my life and start again. \u201d\nWhile the reporter was writing in the newspaper, Kristie, who had returned from Xinjiang for less than a month, flew to Chiang Mai, Thailand. Browse her sharing on social media platforms, she enjoyed the sunshine while leisurely working with her laptop in the open coffee shop, so that the reporter \u201cgrape \u201d\u201c bathed \u201d in the white light tube was very good. Kristie began her digital nomad career early last year. Bali, northern Thailand Chiang Mai, and then to Switzerland, a full year did not return to Hong Kong, \"began the journey about 1 month, I have decided to live such a life in the future.\"\nGet up at 8 and 9 a.m. every day, go to the beach, meditate, and work efficiently for 4 hours. After dusk, learn new things, read books, and live the creative life that many wage earners dream of.\nHe made $50,000 a month at the peak of his career.\nBefore the pasture, she worked in the advertising industry, and her body and mind were eroded by the pressure of work, and she suffered from chronic gastritis, \"(sometimes) pain so that she could not eat all day, and she would vomit after eating.\"\nFinally, the doctor said that even if the prescription of many drugs is useless, because my life pressure is too big, let her decide to change the environment, for their own life to a big clean.\nAt that time, she took the initiative to propose a 30% pay cut to her superiors, and switched from full-time employees to freelance workers.\nThere is no regular income, employee welfare, she confessed that \"initially very scared, suddenly lost the sense of security\", so she had saved six months of living reserve before leaving to prevent zero income during the period; and for themselves to open up a new source of income, operating from the media, doing small business.\nShe also became an oblique person, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations and marketing planning to maintain the nomadic living expenses, peak monthly income can reach 50,000 yuan, the off-season income is only more than 10,000 yuan, but stretched to make up for the short, life is still good.\nIn particular, she is mostly nomadic in Southeast Asia, where the consumption is low and the quality of life is good. Taking the island of Phangan in Thailand as an example, she lives in an independent holiday home, with a monthly expenditure of about 12,000 Hong Kong dollars, such as clothing, food, housing and travel.\nLow prices, good living, Indonesia, Thailand, a hot spot\nIn addition to freelancers like Kristie, there are also people engaged in online teaching, design, e-commerce, programming and other remote work, as well as enterprises due to industry characteristics, full-time employees can also work remotely, such as Kate working in the web3.0 industry. Web3.0 is a decentralized Internet based on blockchain technology, NFT, cryptocurrency, metaverse and other popular technology concepts in recent years. It is based on Web 3.0 technology.\nKate, 24, who worked as an occupational therapist for a year after graduating from college, found that she did not like working in fixed locations and hours, and wanted the freedom to travel while working as a digital nomad.\nShe is interested in cryptocurrency, so she turned to web3.0, engaged in marketing, operation of blockchain projects and other work, usually through online communication with colleagues.\n\"Web 3.0 is a more international company, with employees from all over the world, most of them do not have a physical office, and many times employees can only choose to work remotely.\"\nIt \u2019 s like living three or four different lives.\nEvery time she goes to different places to participate in seminars, and after completing her work, she will stay there for 1-2 weeks, traveling all over Japan, Thailand, Australia, Singapore, France, etc. Although she is a full-time employee, she has no fixed office hours, sometimes she does not need to turn on the computer all day, she can go sightseeing, sometimes she needs to meet and meet constantly. Bring a computer, wired headphones and plenty of mobile data.\nWhen I tried to watch animals in the Australian zoo, I suddenly had a meeting; I suddenly had to deal with work on the way to shopping in Korea, and the store has been closed for seven or eight years, which is completely different from the excellent nomadic life I imagined.\nKate, who often hangs \"work first\" and \"have self-discipline to have freedom\", admits that even the beauty of the current can not be completely relaxed and appreciated, \"I think you can not because your work location is not in a fixed place, and people feel unprofessional; it should make people believe that you can complete the work wherever you are, and there is quality, and no need for others to adapt, so as to maintain this way of life for a long.\"\nDigital nomads have bitterness and sweetness, but both say they can \u2019 t go back after they set foot on this road.\nRead this year Kristie published in the book fair, from the nomad, to find the heart of the sea \", she met on the road only two seasons of American couples, with children wandering the world of nomadic families, Lin Lin's total lifestyle has brought her a shock,\" I know in Hong Kong, many of them are a life to the end, but in the nomad meet them, I \u2019 ve lived three or four different lives, \u201d and there are fascinating stories in each life.\nEmbark on a nomadic journey to open Second Life, their book of life, and add a few unforgettable experiences.\n\u25cf\nText: Chang Shu-mei\nEditor: Liang Xiaoling\nArt: Hsieh Wai-ho\nFacebook @ Ming Pao Supplement\nCopyright \u00a9 2019 Mingpao. All Rights Reserved.\nRelated Words: Chiang Mai Visa Digital Nomad Visa Wor