but this part may have little impact on the price.\nAt the beginning of this year, Pakistan officially released the news of the purchase of J-10C, there are unconfirmed rumors that J-10C may appear in Africa a second customer, which is more likely to be Sudan, and the purchase of the model will not be J-10C, the cooperation between China and Pakistan JF-17 Dragon is also one of the options, after all, JF-17 uses more customers.\nWith an area of nearly 2 million square kilometers, the Islamic state of Sudan in North Africa is the third largest country in Africa. Its name Sudan means \"black land\" in official Arabic.\nSudan, ruled by a military government, has long been plagued by the Darfur conflict and South Sudan's independence, and has been named the \"most unstable country in the world\".\nEconomically based on agricultural and animal husbandry processing products, the military has long been supported by the former Soviet Union and Russia, and the existing weapons are mostly Russian-Chinese systems, and there are a small number of US-French weapons.\nThe aircraft purchased from China and Russia are mostly old models, such as China's Keang-5, J-7, FTC-2000, etc. The Russian-made MiG-23, MiG-29, Su-24, Su-25, etc., a total of about 40 ~ 50 aircraft.\nThe FTC-2000, also known as the Jian-9, is considered to be the third generation trainer, so there has been a need to update the fighter fleet for many years.\nFrom the perspective of the composition of the Sudanese Air Force, it is still the largest number of Russian-made fighters, so it is the most likely to buy Russian-made fighters again.\nAlthough the French surge is also actively in contact, the price of each aircraft is as high as 100 to 200 million US dollars to deter the sultan.\nSince this year, the Russian Air Force and fighter aircraft have shown everyone \u2019 s surprise, which has seriously hit the outside world \u2019 s perception of Russian-made military fire, so the J-10C seized the opportunity as early as the contact, although it has not yet achieved actual combat results, but also Pakistan began to use on the tense India-Pakistan border, there are not many buyers in the international search, in the current atmosphere, the J-10C deal is finally Get a breakthrough.\nThe size of Sudan's air force is small, if the first batch of J-10C is purchased, the number should only be more than 10, about enough to form a squadron.\nIn recent years, China has pushed J-10C internationally, and many countries have expressed interest. In addition to Thailand in Southeast Asia and Argentina in South America, some countries in the Middle East and Africa have also been considered.\nEspecially after Russia \u2019 s performance in Ukraine has become an international laughingstock, many customers who used Russian-made aircraft in the past should turn to China.\nIn addition to fighter aircraft, other ground weapons or various types of frigates, unmanned ships and now the most popular drones, will also be due to the performance of the Russian army and China get a large number of orders.\nSince fighter trading has always been the largest trading item in the international arms market, if China \u2019 s J-10C can have a big win in this wave of Russian orders, it will significantly boost China \u2019 s ranking in the global arms market share.\nAccording to the 2021 ranking of the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, the United States ranked first in arms transactions for the year with 39%, Russia ranked second with 19%, France ranked third with 11%, and China ranked fourth with 4.9%.\nAnd France \u2019 s share of the increase mainly comes from India and the Middle East countries to buy surge fighters, China J-10C this year has Pakistan \u2019 s deal, if coupled with Sudan \u2019 s order, it may surpass France to become the world \u2019 s fourth largest arms exporter in 2022, if the J-10C can thus open the market, and even in a few years may surpass Russia, to become only the United States defense industrial power.\nSource: Headlines Revealed on Facebook.com\n# J-10C # SUDAN # JET # ARMY # RUSSIA","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0032.json.gz:1865","uncompressed_offset":453477269,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20221027000680-260407","warc_date":"2022-10-26T21:22:26.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9e893a13-a5bb-4822-8f87-187cba831d3d>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20221027000680-260407"},"created":"2022-10-26T21:41:50.000Z","lang":"eng"},"558e844a-b52a-4f3a-8553-1ab6b696cb94_230889465":{"id":"558e844a-b52a-4f3a-8553-1ab6b696cb94_230889465","text":"China\nChina wants to smell.\nChina 's main fighter jet J-10C first export to Pakistan to fight India' s \"gusty wind\" procurement engine improved long-range missile deal key\n(Ming Pao News) Pakistan's military confirmed on Wednesday (5) that it is buying multi-purpose J-10C fighters from China in response to the introduction of French Rafale fighters by the Indian Air Force. The J-10C is the main equipment of the People's Liberation Army Air Force, and once a deal is reached, it will be the most advanced fighter aircraft exported by China in history and will also be the Pakistan Air Force's strongest fighter.\nIt has been rumored that the number of J-10Cs exported to Pakistan is 35 to 40, and the price is about 1.5 billion US dollars (about 11.7 billion Hong Kong dollars).\nSpeaking at a press conference, Maj. Gen. Babar Iftikhar, a spokesman for Pakistan \u2019 s army, said: \u201cThis is a step to upgrade our air force and get the best possible technology because we know what the other side (India) is getting. \u201d\n\"Our opponents are using one excuse after another to keep buying the latest equipment,\" Iftihal warned.\nAny conventional imbalance in the region is dangerous, \"and\" it will lead us into a race to buy more equipment. \"\nIt is expected to purchase more than 30 aircraft, each about $390 million.\nThis is the first time the Pakistani military has made it clear that it is buying Chinese J-10s, but Iftihar did not say how many will be purchased.\nChina has not commented on this.\nAccording to the military self-media \"white wolf view of the world\" on December 23 last year, since the service in 2006, the Chinese Air Force has been equipped with nearly 500 J-10C, becoming the Chinese Air Force's largest number of fighter aircraft.\nIts foreign trade version of the J-10CE is also of interest to many countries, including Ukraine and \"Pakistan Railway\" (the nickname of the mainland people for Pakistan), Pakistan is ready to sign with China 35 to 40 aircraft, worth about 1.5 billion US dollars, each less than 50 million US dollars (about 390 million Hong Kong dollars).\n\"China Times\" reported that this arms case is China's long-awaited defense deal, from the beginning of the J-10A until the J-10C deal, in addition to the Indian purchase of wind, J-10C successfully replaced the turbofan -10 vector thrust engine and decided to match the PL-15 long-range air-to-air missile, is Pakistan willing to finalize the deal two key factors.\nLow-price export of Huamou real war inspection J-10C\nAnother eye-catching item is the price, which was first reported at the 2018 Zhuhai Airshow at $70 million per aircraft, and is now about $50 million.\nChina is willing to sell to Pakistan at such a low price, in addition to friendly relations, but also considering that the India-Pakistan border may be the only battlefield that can allow the J-10C to have a combat test.\nThe report also said that last year, China and Pakistan agreed to the export of the Perila-15 (PL-15) long-range air-to-air missile, in addition to the use of the Pakistan Dragon Block 3, can also be equipped with the newly purchased J-10C.\nIt is believed that after importing the J-10C, its active phased array radar plus the long-range air-to-air missile, as long as it grasps the opportunity and uses it properly, it has the opportunity to defeat the fighter jet.\nIn 2015, India announced the purchase of 36 French fighter aircraft, worth US $8 billion (about HK $62.4 billion), with a unit price of nearly US $300 million (about HK $2.3 billion).\nPakistan: March National Day parade will see J-10 formation\nPakistan \u2019 s interior minister, Sheikh Rasheed Ahmad, also revealed plans to buy Chinese fighters at a public event last week, saying that a squadron of 25 J-10s will participate in Pakistan \u2019 s Independence Day parade on March 23 and that the flyby ceremony \u201cwill be conducted by the Pakistan Air Force in response to the (Indian) gusty fighters. \u201d\nThe 25 J-10Cs are believed to be the first aircraft to be delivered to Pakistan.\n\u25a0 Ming Pao reporting hotline: inews @ mingpao.com / 9181 4676\nRelated words: Gust fighter J-10C Pakistan\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0000.json.gz:24775","uncompressed_offset":230889465,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B/article/20220107/s00013/1641494284442/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B%E4%B8%BB%E5%8A%9B%E6%88%B0%E6%A9%9F%E6%AE%B2-10c%E9%A6%96%E5%87%BA%E5%8F%A3-%E5%B7%B4%E5%9F%BA%E6%96%AF%E5%9D%A6%E7%82%BA%E6%8A%97%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E3%80%8C%E9%99%A3%E9%A2%A8%E3%80%8D%E6%8E%A1%E8%B3%BC-%E5%BC%95%E6%93%8E%E6%94%B9%E8%89%AF%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%B0%8E%E5%BD%88%E6%88%90%E4%BA%A4%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5","warc_date":"2022-01-07T20:58:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:558e844a-b52a-4f3a-8553-1ab6b696cb94>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B/article/20220107/s00013/1641494284442/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B%E4%B8%BB%E5%8A%9B%E6%88%B0%E6%A9%9F%E6%AE%B2-10c%E9%A6%96%E5%87%BA%E5%8F%A3-%E5%B7%B4%E5%9F%BA%E6%96%AF%E5%9D%A6%E7%82%BA%E6%8A%97%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E3%80%8C%E9%99%A3%E9%A2%A8%E3%80%8D%E6%8E%A1%E8%B3%BC-%E5%BC%95%E6%93%8E%E6%94%B9%E8%89%AF%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%B0%8E%E5%BD%88%E6%88%90%E4%BA%A4%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5"},"created":"2022-01-07T21:09:40.000Z","lang":"eng"},"cd6f7c06-5e22-4103-9de2-9817a9a60efa_121885815":{"id":"cd6f7c06-5e22-4103-9de2-9817a9a60efa_121885815","text":"Adsence Ads 300X250\nAdsense Ads 900\u00d7250\n\nPAF formally inducts Rafale rival China-made J-10C fighter jets\n\nWeb Desk BOL News\n\n11th Mar, 2022. 02:25 pm\nAdsense Ads 300 x 100\nAdsence Ads 300X250\n\nKAMRA: The Pakistan Air Force (PAF) formally inducted a modern Chinese-made J-10C multi-role combat aircraft also known as \u201cvigorous dragon\u201d during a ceremony held at Kamra Airbase on Friday.\n\nPrime Minister Imran Khan attended the induction ceremony of the single-engine fighter jet at the invitation of Chief of the Air Staff (CAS) Air Chief Marshal Zaheer Ahmad Babar, along with other federal ministers and the Chinese ambassador.\n\nDuring the ceremony, The Prime Minister has witnessed a thrilling flypast of various aircraft formations, including the newly inducted J10C, F-16s, JF-17s, and Mirages, which displayed a sophisticated array of avionics and weaponry.\n\nRead more:\u00a0PAF\u2019s acquisition of J10-C\n\nFollowing the flypast, the Prime Minister witnessed the landing of five J-10C aircraft, which have been inducted into the 15 Squadron.\n\nThe J-10C is larger and can be outfitted with a bigger active electronically scanned array (AESA) radar than the JF-17 Block 3 uses.\n\nThe aircraft can carry fourth-generation air-to-air missiles such as the short-range PL-10 and the beyond-visual-range PL-15.\n\nAccording to a foreign media report, China will deliver a total of 25 J-10C fighter jets to Pakistan, significantly increasing the country\u2019s military capability to defend airspace.\n\nRead more:\u00a0J-10C induction ceremony: Pakistan knows how to protect its boundaries, says Imran\n\nAfter being tested in Chengdu, the first batch of combat aircraft arrived in Pakistan a few days ago.\n\nImages of a Pakistan Air Force (PAF) J-10C fighter jet with the Pakistan Air Force (PAF) markings recently surfaced on social media and were widely circulated by media outlets.\n\nChinese analysts have praised the latest defence cooperation between China and Pakistan, saying that the move is significant for both countries because it strengthens the Pakistani military\u2019s combat capabilities, promotes China\u2019s aviation equipment, and serves regional security interests.\n\n\u201cThe J-10C will significantly improve the Pakistan Air Force\u2019s combat capabilities,\u201d Chinese analysts predicted.\n\n\u201cThe J-10C is a 4.5-generation medium-sized fighter jet that is more powerful than the China-Pakistan jointly developed lightweight fighter jet, the JF-17, which is currently in service with the Pakistan Air Force,\u201d Shi Hong, Executive Chief Editor of Shipborne Weapons, told the Global Times.\n\n\nDownload BOL News App for latest news","url":"https://www.bolnews.com/pakistan/2022/03/paf-formally-inducts-rafale-rival-china-made-j-10c-fighter-jets/"},"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755":{"id":"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755","text":"Turkey replaces F-16 with Chinese fighter jet\nWednesday 08 March 2023 - 12: 09 GMT\nKagri Erhan, a member of the Security Council and Foreign Policy of the Turkish Presidency, announced that Ankara is expected to abandon its requests for American-made fourth-generation F-16C / D fighter jets due to the availability of a better alternative.\nWorld - Turkey\nThe Turkish official noted that the \u201c$20 billion cost package \u201d and the availability of more cost-effective options, notably the Chinese J-10C, could make such a rollout a reality.\n\"Now we have other options such as the Chinese plane that was sold to Pakistan, the Russian planes and also the Eurofighter,\" he said.\nAccording to Miltary Watch, Pakistan began receiving Chinese J-10C fighters in February 2022.\nThe Chinese fighter is of the same weight as its American counterpart, the F-16, but it is several decades newer with multiple features and performance advantages, especially in terms of armament, flight and flight performance.\nIt is a lightweight single-engine fighter with low operating cost and improved fifth-generation avionics.\nChinese aircraft also have similar capabilities and in most respects are superior to their American counterparts, in addition to requiring less maintenance needs and much faster delivery time.\nAlthough Turkey is the largest foreign operator of the US F-16, with about 250 in service, which means the new aircraft can be easily integrated with existing training and logistics systems and weapons, China has in the past modified its fighters to be able to operate US weapons at the request of foreign customers.\nOne of the main advantages of the Chinese fighter is its very low cost compared to its American counterpart, due to the fact that China manufactures large quantities of them, unlike the American.\nTurkey \u2019 s preference for lightweight fighters makes the Chinese single-engine aircraft an effective and pioneering option.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0007.json.gz:10313","uncompressed_offset":115461755,"url":"www.alalam.ir/news/6559603/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A8%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-03-08T12:32:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72>","warc_url":"https://www.alalam.ir/news/6559603/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A8%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-03-08T12:37:13.000Z","lang":"eng"},"82c7d54c-fbec-441a-91f2-7aca1b82742c_1008363996":{"id":"82c7d54c-fbec-441a-91f2-7aca1b82742c_1008363996","text":"US newspaper lists Su-35 and MiG-31 on list of five most dangerous fighter jets\nScience and Technology\nThe Su-35 fighter.\nCopy Link https: / / www.rt.com / t1a7\nMilitary Watch lists Su-35 and MiG-31 as the five most dangerous fighters for the U.S. Air Force.\nJ-20\nThe list included the Chinese J-20, which became the second fifth-generation aircraft after the American F-35, and was designed to enable the fighter to fly at supersonic speed without operating the Forsage.\nMiG-31.\nMiG-31.\nSecond on the list is the MiG-31 fighter, which remains a promising aircraft despite its age, an air battle plane, the great power of weapons and the ability to launch hypersonic missiles, including into space.\nJ-16\nThe J-16 is a Chinese ghost-developed model of the Su-35, as a legend of the Soviet aircraft industry.\nSu-35\nSu-35\nIt is also a Russian upgraded version of the Su-35 equipped with modern radars and a target detection station.\nIts projected introduction of the powerful R-37 and Ka-77 missiles will expand the aircraft \u2019 s capabilities and increase its export capability.\nJ-10\nThe J-10 is a Chinese 4 + + generation light fighter equipped with modern electronic warfare equipment and a wide range of missiles.\nIn addition, it is less expensive to produce and maintain than the J-16.\nSource: Rossiyskaya Gazeta\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0014.json.gz:44901","uncompressed_offset":1008363996,"url":"arabic.rt.com/technology/1354687-%D8%B5%D8%AD%D9%8A%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%AC-%D8%B3%D9%88-35-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%BA-31-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%B7%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%85%D8%B3/","warc_date":"2022-05-17T15:09:20.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:82c7d54c-fbec-441a-91f2-7aca1b82742c>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/technology/1354687-%D8%B5%D8%AD%D9%8A%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%AC-%D8%B3%D9%88-35-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%BA-31-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%B7%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%85%D8%B3/"},"created":"2022-05-17T15:52:11.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1009","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1009","narrative_id":"1009"},"responses":[{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"The Saharan dust storms have been known to impact weather and air conditions in the Americas, particularly in the Caribbean and the Gulf of Mexico."},{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"These storms can cause a decrease in rainfall and maintain high temperatures, leading to heat-related issues."},{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"The dust clouds contain various elements, including iron, silica, fungi, bacteria, and viruses, which can cause acute respiratory diseases, allergies, and skin problems."},{"citations":{"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012":1.0},"text":"The Saharan Air Layer (SAL) has been detected in the Atlantic, with significant plumes of dust reaching as far as Florida and the Gulf Coast."},{"citations":{"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012":1.0},"text":"This can lead to enhanced sunrises and sunsets, but also poses health risks, especially for people with allergies and respiratory issues."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":1.0},"text":"In 2020, the United States experienced the most massive Saharan dust storm ever recorded, dubbed \"Godzilla,\" which highlighted the potential for increasing occurrences of such dust invasions."},{"citations":{"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":1.0},"text":"To mitigate the effects of contemporary Saharan dust storms, preparations such as safeguarding health, especially for individuals with allergies and respiratory issues, are necessary."},{"citations":{"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":1.0},"text":"Residents in affected areas, such as the Bahamas, are urged to take precautions as the dust can be problematic for people with allergies and respiratory issues."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":1.0},"text":"Climate change is altering weather patterns globally, affecting dust storm behavior and leading to variations in their frequency and intensity."},{"citations":{"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373":1.0},"text":"Understanding the biological components of dust storms, such as the microbes that migrate with dust, is crucial in assessing their potential impact on human health."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"The Saharan dust storms have been known to impact weather and air conditions in the Americas, particularly in the Caribbean and the Gulf of Mexico."},{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"These storms can cause a decrease in rainfall and maintain high temperatures, leading to heat-related issues."},{"citations":{"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":1.0},"text":"The dust clouds contain various elements, including iron, silica, fungi, bacteria, and viruses, which can cause acute respiratory diseases, allergies, and skin problems."},{"citations":{"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012":1.0},"text":"The Saharan Air Layer (SAL) has been detected in the Atlantic, with significant plumes of dust reaching as far as Florida and the Gulf Coast."},{"citations":{"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012":1.0},"text":"This can lead to enhanced sunrises and sunsets, but also poses health risks, especially for people with allergies and respiratory issues."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":1.0},"text":"In 2020, the United States experienced the most massive Saharan dust storm ever recorded, dubbed \"Godzilla,\" which highlighted the potential for increasing occurrences of such dust invasions."},{"citations":{"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":1.0},"text":"To mitigate the effects of contemporary Saharan dust storms, preparations such as safeguarding health, especially for individuals with allergies and respiratory issues, are necessary."},{"citations":{"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":1.0},"text":"Residents in affected areas, such as the Bahamas, are urged to take precautions as the dust can be problematic for people with allergies and respiratory issues."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":1.0},"text":"Climate change is altering weather patterns globally, affecting dust storm behavior and leading to variations in their frequency and intensity."},{"citations":{"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373":1.0},"text":"Understanding the biological components of dust storms, such as the microbes that migrate with dust, is crucial in assessing their potential impact on human health."}],"references":["958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541","97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373","135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352","976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012","bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316"],"documents":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":{"id":"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541","text":"03-27-2024\n\nSahara desert dust storms carry harmful bacteria and fungi around the globe\n\nWe often dismiss springtime allergies as reactions to local pollen. Yet, something else might cause our sniffles and sneezes: a massive dust storms that originate thousands of miles away in Africa\u2019s Sahara region.\n\nThese gargantuan dust plumes travel the globe every summer, carrying a cocktail of pollutants and potential pathogens across continents.\n\nDr. Shankar Chellam, a Texas A&M University professor is leading the charge to understand the biological hitchhikers within dust storms.\n\nHe and his team are working to determine what microbes, specifically bacteria and fungi, migrate with the dust and explore their potential impact on human health.\n\nHidden passengers in Sahara dust\n\n\u201cWe all get allergies and potentially other more severe health effects when we breathe in dust, and it\u2019s not fully known as to what causes those allergies,\u201d said Dr. Chellam.\n\n\u201cSome people may think it is just the sand or clay minerals in the dust. Others think it is the metals or organics in the dust, and then some think it\u2019s the bacteria and fungi.\u201d\n\nThe Saharan dust cloud carries vast amounts of sand particles that transport bacteria and fungi.\n\nDr. Chellam\u2019s research uniquely addresses how Saharan dust storms introduce these microbes into North America.\n\nWhat the dust storm from Sahara tells us\n\nDr. Chellam and his team analyzed samples from a Saharan dust event that reached Houston in 2018. They measured metals, bacteria, and fungi to investigate any connections.\n\nFascinatingly, their findings revealed strong links between the biodiversity of the microbes and specific elements, especially calcium.\n\nWhile these elements occur naturally in the Sahara, they also exist in our local environments. Pinpointing the exact origin of the dust and its cargo remains a challenge that scientists continue to tackle.\n\nOur air \u2013 Not as empty as we think\n\nPerhaps the most startling discovery is that even seemingly lifeless clouds of dust brim with biological activity.\n\n\u201cA key takeaway from this study is that a lot of biodiversity is not scientifically described. It doesn\u2019t have a name, it can\u2019t be cultured, and because it can\u2019t be cultured, it\u2019s difficult to study,\u201d explained Dr. Daniel Spalink, assistant professor at Texas A&M.\n\nThe team\u2019s high-tech DNA analysis allowed them to create an inventory of bacteria and fungi, even if the microbes themselves weren\u2019t active.\n\nSurprisingly, they found traces of several pathogens known to cause disease in humans, as listed by the World Health Organization (WHO).\n\n\u201cIt doesn\u2019t tell us if they are going to be able to infect us and make us sick,\u201d Spalink cautions, \u201cBut at least the DNA of several pathogenic bacteria and fungi were identified in the African dust.\u201d\n\nImpact of climate change on Sahara dust\n\nClimate change is altering weather patterns globally. This transformation affects dust storm behavior, leading to variations in their frequency and intensity.\n\nIn 2020, the United States experienced the most massive Saharan dust storm ever recorded, which experts named \u201cGodzilla.\u201d\n\nThis event highlighted the potential for increasing occurrences of such dust invasions. \u201cThe whole dynamics of the Saharan dust coming to Houston is primarily driven by atmospheric processes,\u201d said Dr. Sourav Das, a former student of Dr. Chellam.\n\nGlobal connection of Sahara dust\n\nSahara dust storm travels far beyond the borders of North America, affecting global environmental systems in profound ways.\n\nThis dust, originating from the vast Sahara Desert, embarks on transcontinental journeys that influence climate, ocean biology, and ecosystems far removed from its source.\n\nThe Saharan dust plays a critical role in climate regulation. As it travels across oceans and continents, it reflects sunlight back into space, cooling the Earth\u2019s surface.\n\nThis natural phenomenon acts as a counterbalance to the warming effects of greenhouse gases, showcasing how desert dust can influence global temperatures.\n\nHowever, the dust also carries microorganisms and nutrients, such as phosphorus, that fertilize remote ecosystems, from the Amazon rainforest to the Caribbean Sea, demonstrating nature\u2019s complex nutrient cycles.\n\nBenefits to oceans\n\nOcean biology benefits from the nutrient-rich dust as well. When Saharan dust settles on ocean waters, it delivers essential minerals that stimulate the growth of phytoplankton.\n\nThese microscopic plants form the foundation of the oceanic food chain, supporting a diverse array of marine life.\n\nThe influx of nutrients from the Sahara can thus boost marine productivity, affecting fish populations and the global fishing industry.\n\nDisadvantages\n\nThe impact of Saharan dust is not universally beneficial. In ecosystems unaccustomed to the influx of foreign particles and nutrients, the dust can disrupt local environments.\n\nFor example, excessive dust deposition can smother coral reefs, blocking sunlight and hindering photosynthesis. This can stress coral ecosystems, leading to bleaching events and loss of biodiversity.\n\nMoreover, the health implications of Saharan dust extend across continents. The dust carries not only nutrients but also pollutants and pathogens that can affect air quality and public health.\n\nCommunities in the path of these dust plumes may experience increased respiratory issues, allergies, and diseases, highlighting the need for global health monitoring and preparedness.\n\nStudy insights\n\nIt\u2019s crucial to gather data across multiple dust events, spanning many years, to get a clearer picture of these airborne microbial communities and how they might transform over time.\n\nWhile a lot remains unknown, research like this shines a spotlight on the hidden travelers swirling in the air we breathe \u2014 travelers who might be affecting our health in surprising ways.\n\nThe next time you catch a glimpse of a dust storm rolling in, remember the globe-trotting microbes it carries!\n\nThe findings of the study are published in Environmental Science & Technology.\n\n\u2014\u2013\n\nLike what you read? Subscribe to our newsletter for engaging articles, exclusive content, and the latest updates.\u00a0\n\nCheck us out on EarthSnap, a free app brought to you by Eric Ralls and Earth.com.\n\n\u2014\u2013\n\nNews coming your way\nThe biggest news about our planet delivered to you each day","url":"https://www.earth.com/news/sahara-desert-dust-storms-carry-harmful-bacteria-and-fungi-around-the-globe/"},"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":{"id":"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316","text":"0\n\nLayer of Saharan dust will affect the Bahamas by the weekend\n\nBy EARYEL BOWLEG\n\nTribune Staff Reporter\n\nebowleg@tribunemedia.net\n\nRESIDENTS are urged to \u201csafeguard their health\u201d as a plume of Sahara dust moves over the south-east Bahamas.\n\nThe Department of Meteorology said the dust will gradually move across the country this weekend.\n\nIt warned the dust could be problematic for people with allergies and respiratory issues.\n\n\u201cSahara dust is made of sand, dirt, and other dust particles that are lifted into the atmosphere from the vast Sahara Desert in Africa,\u201d the advisory said.\n\nActing director of meteorology Jeffrey Simmons told The Tribune the dust tends to appear around this time every year.\n\nHe said the dust has lingered around southeastern islands for the past week, prompting some to complain about allergies.\n\n\u201cThat\u2019s the reason, you know, why we put out this warning alerting people about it, people who have these allergy issues or any respiratory issues so that they could, you know, be aware of the impact this could have on them for this weekend and possibly going into another week or two,\u201d he said.","url":"http://www.tribune242.com/news/2023/jul/20/layer-saharan-dust-will-affect-bahamas-weekend/"},"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012":{"id":"976e5a88-b9d0-4613-be71-b666fa22d6f3_776351012","text":"Saharan dust reaches stunning levels in Atlantic. Here's what that means for hurricane season\n\nSignificant Saharan dust plumes are common in the Atlantic during the start of hurricane season. If levels of SAL maintain a steadiness after about Aug. 20, then there would be significant ramifications to both the amount of cyclones and their overall strength.\n\nFirst, Europe that was socked in by record levels of dust from the Sahara Desert in Africa. The Atlantic appears to have now taken the lead, with dust levels not seen in years across parts of the basin.\n\nSatellite measurements indicate intensive plumes of dust, called the Saharan Air Layer, across much of the eastern Atlantic. Traces of dust have even made the more than 4,000-mile journey to Florida and the Gulf Coast.\u00a0\n\nSunrises and sunsets have been enhanced across the Sunshine State as the particles scatter typical colors, allowing hues of orange, yellow and red to dominate the sky.\n\nAside from the vibrant colors, something not falling from the sky is precipitation.\n\nAccording to NOAA, the air surrounding the SAL has about 50% less moisture than the typical atmosphere. This means the presence of the SAL can be detrimental to cloud formation and thunderstorm activity.\u00a0\n\nSignificant plumes of dust and dry air are common during the first months of the hurricane season and usually persist through mid-August.\n\nA LOOK AT A PHENOMENON THAT COULD DERAIL AN ACTIVE HURRICANE SEASON\n\n\n\n\u00a0\n\nHow Saharan dust impacts hurricane season\n\nNOAA estimates that more than 180 million tons of dust leave the African continent every year, reducing thunderstorm activity and tropical cyclone formation.\u00a0\n\nDry air and Saharan dust are perennial wild cards in tropical weather outlooks, as meteorology has yet to develop sufficient methods to forecast plumes weeks and months in advance.\n\nYears with significant dust often experience reduced cyclone activity. Seasons with minimal dust typically rank at the top echelons of activity, thanks to increased moisture availability for tropical systems and warmer water temperatures.\n\n\n\n\u00a0\n\nThe current season is a bit unusual as water temperatures started on the warm side across much of the basin, negating any minor effects from a dust storm.\n\nWarm waters and limited exposure to dry air helped with the formations of\u00a0AlbertoBeryl and\u00a0Chris during late June and early July.\n\nSince Beryl\u2019s historic trek through the Caribbean and into the Gulf of Mexico, the basin has been relatively quiet, a likely product of the increase in dry air.\n\nThe trend for limited activity in the Atlantic basin is expected to continue for the foreseeable future, meaning that the next cyclone formation may be weeks away.\n\n5 THINGS TO KNOW ABOUT THE SAHARAN DUST PLUME\n\nDuring an average year, the fourth-named storm usually doesn\u2019t form until about Aug. 15, meaning any formation during the next month will keep the season ahead of a typical schedule.\n\nDespite the hostile conditions in the Atlantic, hurricane forecasters at Colorado State University maintain that 2024 will be a busy season in the Atlantic.\n\nCSU released its updated outlook Tuesday, which calls for an additional 22 named storms, 11 hurricanes and five major hurricanes.\n\n\"This forecast is of above-normal confidence. We anticipate a well above-average probability for major hurricane landfalls along the continental United States coastline and in the Caribbean,\" CSU forecasters stated during their most recent tropical update. \"As with all hurricane seasons, coastal residents are reminded that it only takes one hurricane making landfall to make it an active season.\"\n\nThe season runs through Nov. 30, but nearly 60% of cyclone formation occurs in August and September.\n\nLoading...","url":"https://www.foxweather.com/weather-news/saharan-dust-levels-atlantic-hurricane-season-july-2024"},"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352":{"id":"135649f4-82c4-4bc9-903a-9d935421ea27_1026921352","text":"Havana, Cuba.- Cubans are entering the final days of July with a forecast of high temperatures, accompanied by little rain throughout the national territory.\n\nIn recent days, the heat punished the inhabitants of the Caribbean island, where through the Institute of Meteorology it was learned that in 38 of the 68 stations subordinate to the scientific entity, temperatures above 34 Celsius degrees were reported.\n\nMeanwhile, the nightly broadcast of the National Television Newscast specified that in the eastern territory of Granma 39\u00b0C were registered on Saturday.\n\nBehind it, the most overwhelmed towns were Col\u00f3n in the western province of Matanzas with 37.2 \u00b0C; and Bainoa, in the also western province of Mayabeque, with 36.5 \u00b0C; while in the capital the thermometers marked 36 \u00b0C.\n\nDays prior to the establishment of these temperature records for the current month, the Institute of Meteorology warned about the arrival of a cloud of dust from the Sahara on the island.\n\nThe experts explained that this phenomenon would cause a new decrease in rainfall and would maintain the feeling of great heat.\n\nThese clouds contain iron, silica, fungi, bacteria, viruses, various pathogenic mites, among other elements. They can cause acute respiratory diseases, allergies and skin problems.\n\nDust from the Sahara affects coral reefs, and fruit, rice, sugar cane, bean and other crops. It is caused by storms that occurred in the Sahara desert, coming out of the African continent.\n\nIt moves over the freshest and most humid marine air, and joining the flow of the trade winds, it quickly reaches the Atlantic Ocean, the Caribbean Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.","url":"https://www.radioreloj.cu/news/science/more-heat-and-little-rain-in-cuba/"},"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373":{"id":"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373","text":"Dust storms from the Sahara desert spread invisible allergens around the world\nScience and Technology\nCopy Link https: / / en.rt.com / x903\nMany blame pollen when the allergy season begins, but there are \u201cinvisible travelers \u201d coming from the Sahara and Sahel region, who may be the cause of this allergy.\nThe huge dust plumes, which originate thousands of miles away in sub-Saharan Africa, travel by dust storms around the world every summer, carrying a mix of pollutants and potential pathogens across continents.\nDr. Shankar Chilam, a professor at Texas A & M University, led the task of understanding the biological movers within dust storms.\nHe and his team are working to identify microbes, specifically bacteria and fungi, that migrate with dust and explore their potential impact on human health.\nDr. Chillam \u2019 s research uniquely addresses how desert dust storms introduced these microbes into North America.\nDr Chillam and his team analysed samples of desert dust that arrived in Houston in 2018, measuring minerals, bacteria and fungi to check for any links.\nSurprisingly, their findings revealed strong links between microbial biodiversity and specific elements, especially calcium.\nWhile these elements occur naturally in the Sahara Desert, they are also found in local North American environments.\nIdentifying the exact source and payload of the dust remains a challenge that scientists continue to face.\nPerhaps the most surprising discovery is that even seemingly lifeless dust clouds are full of biological activity.\nHigh-tech DNA analysis allowed the team to create a reservoir of bacteria and fungi, even if the microbes themselves were not active.\nSurprisingly, they found traces of several pathogens known to cause disease in humans, according to the World Health Organization.\nDr Daniel Spalink, an assistant professor at Texas A & M University, warns: \u201cThis doesn \u2019 t tell us whether they will be able to infect us and make us sick, but at least the DNA of many pathogenic bacteria and fungi has been identified in African dust. \u201d\nClimate change is changing weather patterns globally.\nThis shift affects the behavior of dust storms, leading to differences in their frequency and severity.\nThe dust storm in the Sahara travels far beyond the borders of North America, affecting global ecosystems in profound ways.\nThe dust, which originates from the vast Sahara desert, is released on transcontinental journeys that affect climate, ocean biology and ecosystems far from its source.\nAs it travels across oceans and continents, desert dust reflects sunlight back into space, cooling the Earth \u2019 s surface.\nThis natural phenomenon acts as a counterbalance to the greenhouse effects of greenhouse gases, illustrating how desert dust can affect global temperatures.\nDust also carries microorganisms and nutrients, such as phosphorus, which fertilises remote ecosystems, from the Amazon rainforest to the Caribbean Sea, demonstrating complex nutrient cycles in nature.\nOcean biology also benefits from nutrient-rich dust.\nWhen desert dust settles on ocean waters, it provides essential minerals that stimulate the growth of phytoplankton that form the basis of the oceanic food chain and support a variety of marine life.\nThus, the flow of food from the Sahara could boost marine productivity, affecting fish populations and the global fishing industry.\nBut the effect of desert dust is not always beneficial, and in ecosystems unusual for the flow of foreign particles and nutrients, the dust can disrupt local environments.For example, excessive dust deposition can strangle corals, block sunlight and hinder photosynthesis.\nMoreover, the health effects of desert dust extend across continents, where dust not only carries nutrients but also contaminants and pathogens that can affect air quality and public health.\nCommunities in the path of these dust plumes may face increased respiratory problems, allergies and diseases, highlighting the need for surveillance and global health preparedness.\nSource: earth.com\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here\nMoment by moment...\nDevelopments in the terrorist attack on the Krokos shopping center on the outskirts of Moscow and the fate of the perpetrators and victims","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0008.json.gz:38258","uncompressed_offset":663017373,"url":"arabic.rt.com/technology/1551315-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%8