ng of any Saudi citizen\nWe have called this vision (Saudi Arabia Vision 2030), but we will not wait until then, but we will immediately start implementing all that we have committed ourselves to, and with you and how much Saudi Arabia will be a great country we are all proud of, God willing.\nSpeech of His Royal Highness Prince Mohammed bin Salman bin Abdulaziz\nCrown Prince, Prime Minister\nPresident of the Council for Economic and Development Affairs","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0014.json.gz:41301","uncompressed_offset":821927739,"url":"www.alweeam.com.sa/940817/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%8A%D8%AC%D9%8A/","warc_date":"2023-05-16T12:44:38.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d5cfca4d-1f22-4ed7-9692-1b12bc638a57>","warc_url":"https://www.alweeam.com.sa/940817/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%8A%D8%AC%D9%8A/"},"created":"2023-05-16T13:19:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"acfb0cea-fea6-41de-8259-b55498d43f7d_493804949":{"id":"acfb0cea-fea6-41de-8259-b55498d43f7d_493804949","text":"Paris Fashion Week: Mohammed Ashi brings CHANGE in Saudi Arabia's culture to the ramp\n\nThe Saudi fashion industry is just one facet of a broader strategy pursued by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman to diversify the country's economy and foster social changes.\n\nFirst Published Jul 6, 2023, 2:10 PM IST\n\nIn a remarkable milestone for Saudi Arabia's cultural evolution, Mohammed Ashi, a Saudi designer, made his debut at Paris Fashion Week, marking a significant moment in the kingdom's push into the global fashion scene. Ashi, known for dressing top celebrities, described this achievement as the pinnacle of his career. The event coincided with Saudi Arabia's announcement of its own fashion week scheduled for October, as the country aims to tap into new retail opportunities valued at $32 billion annually.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Saudi documenting Hadith to stop misuse by Islamic radicals, terrorists\n\nThe Saudi fashion industry is just one facet of a broader strategy pursued by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman to diversify the country's economy and foster social changes. This approach involves redirecting the nation's oil wealth towards investments in movies, sports, video games, tourism, and other cultural endeavors. While skeptics initially viewed these initiatives as mere smokescreens to deflect attention from human rights concerns, the reforms have surpassed expectations by introducing substantial and transformative changes.\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by Ashi Studio (@ashistudio)\n\nYousef Akbar, a fashion designer who established his brand in Australia and has dressed renowned celebrities like Nicole Kidman and Rita Ora, expressed his astonishment at the magnitude of the transformation. He never anticipated such progress while growing up, and starting his fashion label in Australia seemed to determine the course of his career. However, he now operates his business from Jeddah, highlighting the growing opportunities within Saudi Arabia's burgeoning fashion scene.\n\n\"For the first two years, I almost didn't believe it was real, but then I realised, wow, it IS real,\" said 37-year-old Yousef Akbar, who began his eponymous fashion label in Australia in 2017.\n\n\"I really never thought when I was growing up that this would happen. When I started my brand in Australia, I thought my whole life would be there since I'm a fashion designer,\" Akbar added.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Why Saudi Arabia's oil production cuts are a risky gamble\n\nThe Saudi Fashion Commission aims to capitalize on newfound freedoms regarding public dress and the flourishing private sector, projecting a remarkable 48 percent surge in retail sales to $32 billion between 2021 and 2025. In line with this vision, the commission has launched the Saudi 100 brands program, fostering local designers and nurturing a homegrown industry.\n\nBurak Cakmak, the CEO of the Saudi Fashion Commission, believes that the country's rich heritage and existing brand presence lay the groundwork for a thriving fashion industry, dispelling the notion that Saudi Arabia is starting from scratch.\n\n\"Just because the country wasn't exposed to the rest of the world doesn't mean they are starting now,\" he told AFP in Paris. \"I had an event for a brand this week that's been running since the 70s.\"\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by Ashi Studio (@ashistudio)\n\nIt is important to acknowledge that LGBTQ individuals face severe repression in Saudi Arabia, as the country criminalizes same-sex relations. Despite this, the authorities are apparently turning a blind eye to the influence of queer designers and couturiers within the fashion industry.\n\nSusanne Koelbl, author of \"Behind the Kingdom's Veil,\" suggests that as long as individuals maintain loyalty to the ruler and their families approve, the authorities are choosing to overlook these aspects.\n\n\"Maybe you can't dance naked on the table, but almost anything else is possible now, as long as your family is OK with it and you are loyal to the ruler,\" Koelbl told AFP.\n\nWith opposition largely repressed and religious leaders stripped of power, Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman faces few obstacles in implementing his well-planned and long-scheduled reform agenda, which is dramatically reshaping Saudi society. This process of change brings new and significant opportunities, particularly for women, who are experiencing a shift in societal roles and expectations.\n\n\"It's a well-planned, long-scheduled reform process which is about to change the society completely,\" said Koelbl.\u00a0\"The Saudi people don't tend to be revolutionary and for the vast majority there are indeed new and big opportunities now, especially for women.\"\n\nFor those benefiting from these reforms, the excitement is palpable and inspiring. Witnessing the realization of what was once deemed impossible serves as a powerful motivation for individuals like Yousef Akbar, who see tremendous potential for their own businesses.\n\n\"It sounds cliched, but seeing something happen that we all thought was impossible is very inspiring for my own business,\" said Akbar.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Arab youth sees India as stronger ally than the US: New survey\n\nSaudi Arabia's presence at Paris Fashion Week and its broader efforts to embrace cultural transformation are indicative of a nation striving to redefine itself on the global stage. As the kingdom continues to invest in various aspects of global culture, it signals a desire to not only diversify its economy but also to foster social progress and create opportunities for its people.\n\nFollow Us:\nDownload App:","url":"https://newsable.asianetnews.com/lifestyle/paris-fashion-week-mohammed-ashi-brings-change-in-saudi-arabia-s-culture-to-the-ramp-snt-rxd9ev"},"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":{"id":"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813","text":"Study: The Crown Prince \u2019 s philosophy of management is a compass for the Kingdom \u2019 s renaissance and achievements within the framework of \u201cVision 2030 \u201d\nShe said he takes a strategic approach based on inclusivity, a duality of modernization, originality, boldness and realism.\nCrown Prince Mohammed bin Salman\nAl-Qarar Center for Media Studies has issued a new study that provides an analytical reading of the philosophy of His Highness Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman in the administration, which represents a compass for the Kingdom \u2019 s renaissance and its successes and achievements within the framework of the pioneering development vision \u201cSaudi Vision 2030 \u201d.\nThis came in conjunction with the celebration of the fifth anniversary of the pledge of His Highness as Crown Prince.\nThe study was based on the monitoring and analysis of a series of speeches, speeches, meetings, statements and statements of His Highness the Crown Prince (may God protect him), the number of which reached (16) articles during the period from 2018 to the current year 2022.\nThe study concluded with a set of results, including the Crown Prince \u2019 s adoption of a strategic approach to management based on several pillars, most notably comprehensiveness in approach, dual modernization and originality, boldness and realism, in addition to uniqueness and excellence, universality of presentation, as well as openness to all, and always looking forward.\nThe study pointed to the adoption of His Highness the Crown Prince in his speeches and statements primarily on logical probabilities in the process of influence and persuasion, through addressing the mind with evidence and proofs, using the language of numbers, logical reasoning, and comparisons between the past, present and the future, in addition to proving what has been achieved on the ground effectively, and citing the reports of international institutions.\nThe study pointed out that Prince Mohammed bin Salman, may Allah support him, is betting in achieving the comprehensive development process on the Kingdom's own capabilities, especially the great Saudi people.\nShe pointed out that the language of his speech includes many central actors, which he always mentions clearly, most notably the Saudis, especially the young men and women of the Kingdom, as well as the economic, social, cultural and civilizational potential of the Kingdom, as well as the regional and international status of the Saudi state, whether at the economic, political or Islamic level.\nThe decision center study concluded that HRH Prince Mohammed bin Salman, may God protect him, follows a philosophy based on inclusiveness and renewal in all aspects of life, noting that HRH was able to convey the conviction of his comprehensive development project \"Vision 2030\" to every Saudi citizen, which made the people united in order to achieve the desired progress.\nNews you might like.\nNo stories found.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0012.json.gz:36953","uncompressed_offset":1045813813,"url":"sabq.org/saudia/%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%87%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A5%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030","warc_date":"2022-04-27T20:28:48.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59>","warc_url":"https://sabq.org/saudia/%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%87%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A5%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030"},"created":"2022-04-27T21:25:08.000Z","lang":"eng"},"c2ea8378-284e-41e4-83c2-5e65e89c6096_470502412":{"id":"c2ea8378-284e-41e4-83c2-5e65e89c6096_470502412","text":"Arab News\nKing Salman: We are determined to achieve Saudi Vision 2030\nSaudi Arabia \u2019 s King Salman bin Abdulaziz announced his intention to continue implementing initiatives and reforms to achieve the goals of Saudi Vision 2030.\nKing Salman, in a speech on Sunday during a cabinet session chaired by him to approve the Saudi budget, said: \"We announce the budget for the next fiscal year...\nAfter the Kingdom has overcome the economic effects and exceptional stages of the COVID-19 pandemic, and the Kingdom \u2019 s continued economic launch as a result of economic and financial reforms, in accordance with the Kingdom \u2019 s Vision 2030, we aim to pay attention to the security and health of citizens and residents, human development, continued economic growth, diversification and financial sustainability. \u201d\nThe king pointed out that spending in this budget amounted to 955 billion riyals, and revenues are estimated at 1045 billion riyals, with a surplus of 90 billion riyals.\n\u201cWith the help of God, we are determined to continue to implement economic initiatives and reforms to achieve the objectives of the Kingdom \u2019 s Vision 2030, continuously improve the quality of life, optimize the use of available resources, raise the level of transparency, efficiency and quality of government spending to promote growth and development, develop basic facilities and services for citizens and residents, develop the educational environment and support housing plans. \u201d\nHe added: \"The budget confirms our keenness to protect and enhance our gains, and I have directed ministers and officials, each in his regard, to actively commit to implementing the programs and projects included in the budget of development and social programs and projects, follow up the health situation in light of the continuation of the epidemic and its repercussions on the health and economic conditions locally and internationally.\"\nWe have presented to you our visitors the most important details about the news of King Salman: We are determined to achieve \"Saudi Vision 2030\" on the dot of the Gulf in this article and we hope to provide you with all the details clearly and more credibility and transparency and if you want to follow more news you can subscribe with us for free through our alerts system on your browser or by joining the mailing list and we will provide you with all that is new.\nWe also have to remind you that this content is already published on the site of the Arab morning and may have been the editorial team in Dot AlKhaleej confirmed or modified or quoted or may have been transferred in full and you can read and follow the updates of this news from the main source.\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0036.json.gz:17503","uncompressed_offset":470502412,"url":"dotalkhaleej.co/arab/29051986/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83-%D8%B3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%8A%D9%82-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030.html","warc_date":"2021-12-12T21:12:06.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:c2ea8378-284e-41e4-83c2-5e65e89c6096>","warc_url":"https://dotalkhaleej.co/arab/29051986/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83-%D8%B3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%8A%D9%82-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030.html"},"created":"2021-12-12T21:42:15.000Z","lang":"eng"},"de7bafe3-0613-4f8d-a925-cd3f5a571d98_897868556":{"id":"de7bafe3-0613-4f8d-a925-cd3f5a571d98_897868556","text":"RIYADH \u2014 Saudi Crown Prince and Prime Minister Mohammed bin Salman highlighted the remarkable achievements made by Saudi Arabia ever since the launch of its Vision 2030 and the government\u2019s relentless efforts to implement structural reforms in the financial and economic sectors. The Crown Prince, who is also chairman of the Council of Economic and Development Affairs, said this in a statement issued on the occasion of the approval of the state\u2019s general budget for the fiscal year 2024 by the Council of Ministers on Wednesday.\n\nPrince Mohammed bin Salman underscored that the Kingdom is witnessing sustainable economic growth in light of the great development capabilities and opportunities that the Kingdom enjoys within the framework of the Vision 2030 to enable it to move forward towards a better future worthy of its status in accordance with the directives of Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Salman. \u201cThis produced a clear and prominent impact on the growth of the gross domestic product (GDP) of non-oil sectors.\u201d\n\nThe Crown Prince affirmed the commitment made by the government in the budget for the fiscal year 2024 so as to enhance economic growth through the expansion of government spending. \u201cThe budget figures announced by King Salman come supportive and enabling many programs and initiatives. These include investments to strengthen infrastructure, raise the quality of services provided to citizens, expatriates and visitors, in addition to developing promising economic sectors, enhancing investment attraction, stimulating industries, and raising the proportion of local content and non-oil Saudi exports,\u201d he said while praising the effective and important role of the Public Investment Fund (PIF) and the National Development Fund.\n\nThe Crown Prince emphasized that work would continue to develop the Kingdom\u2019s public financial performance, by increasing financial capacity and building government reserves, in a way that enhances the capacity of the Kingdom\u2019s economy, maintains sustainable levels of public debt, and enables it to confront any developments or crises that may arise in the future. \u201cThe increase in spending is mainly due to the government\u2019s keenness to continue developing the level of public services provided to citizens, expatriates and visitors, as well as to implement many projects and expand spending on sectoral and regional development strategies that would achieve positive structural changes, leading to expanding and diversifying the economic base,\u201d he said.\n\nThe Crown Prince stressed the government\u2019s keenness on developing and strengthening partnership with the private sector so as to enable and motivate it to play its major role in achieving economic diversification, as far as to enable the labor market to absorb more of the Saudi workforce, create job opportunities in the labor market and reduce unemployment rates among Saudis. \u201cThe total number of Saudis in the labor market this year jumped to 2.3 million, in addition to improving the investment environment to be an attractive environment that contributes to raising the proportion of domestic and foreign investment, developing non-oil exports and improving the non-oil trade balance of payments,\u201d he said.\n\nThe Crown Prince emphasized that the journey of economic diversification continues through supporting promising sectors, as the Kingdom works to raise tourism targets to 150 million visitors internally and externally by 2030 in addition to building an effective sports sector through the \u201cInvestment and Privatization Project for Sports Clubs,\u201d in order to achieve the goals of the Vision 2030 in the sports sector, as these sectors are witnessing rapid growth and providing diverse opportunities.\n\nPrince Mohammed bin Salman reiterated the Kingdom\u2019s determination to develop its industrial sector, as it is one of the most important vital sectors in the Saudi economy, by diversifying the industrial base and value chains through the \u201cNational Strategy for Industry'', which focuses on 12 sub-sectors to diversify the industrial economy and raise the industrial domestic product by around three times compared to the year 2020, reaching SR895 billion in 2030 to be a major contributor to the development of non-oil exports. This is in integration with the important role of the PIF as it is the investment arm that contributes and complements the efforts undertaken by the government in diversifying the economy, and the pivotal role of the National Development Fund and its affiliated funds in providing concessional financing to the private sector, he pointed out.\n\nSpeaking about the pivotal and leadership role of the Kingdom, the Crown Prince stressed the Kingdom\u2019s role regionally and internationally, and its endeavor to ensure that the countries of the world enjoy security and stability, as they are the main factors for development and prosperity, and its keenness to develop and stabilize supply and value chains in a way that serves the development and economic prosperity of all countries of the world.\n\nThe Crown Prince stressed the Kingdom\u2019s determination to continue the development momentum during the coming year and in the medium and long term with boosting the attractiveness of the Kingdom\u2019s economy as a base for local and foreign investments besides diversifying the economy through the development of all economic sectors.\n\n\u00a9 Copyright 2022 The Saudi Gazette. All Rights Reserved. Provided by SyndiGate Media Inc. (Syndigate.info).","url":"https://www.zawya.com/en/economy/gcc/crown-prince-saudi-arabia-is-moving-towards-a-better-future-worthy-of-its-lofty-status-gnmpdxfl"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1012","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1012","narrative_id":"1012"},"responses":[{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"Mohammed bin Salman Al Saud, commonly referred to as MBS, has been the driving force behind Saudi Arabia's ambitious 2030 vision, a comprehensive development plan aimed at reducing the country's dependence on oil and diversifying its economy."},{"citations":{"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152":1.0},"text":"Since his appointment as Crown Prince in 2017, MBS has introduced a series of social and economic reforms, which have been instrumental in transforming the country's landscape."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"One of the key aspects of MBS's vision is the curtailing of the influence of the Wahhabi religious establishment, which has been achieved by restricting the powers of the religious police."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"This move has been seen as a significant step towards modernizing the country and promoting a more moderate form of Islam."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"MBS has also been a strong advocate for women's rights, and his government has implemented several reforms aimed at improving the status of women in Saudi society."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"For instance, women are now allowed to apply for a passport without the consent of a male guardian and can visit cinemas with their boyfriends."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"Additionally, the government has changed the legislation to allow women to drive, and according to research firm Statista, over 175,000 women applied for a driving license in Riyadh within a year and a half of the law being passed."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"These reforms have been widely welcomed, and Saudi Arabia has been ranked by the World Bank among the top 20 reformers in the world, and second among the top high-income countries and G20 countries in terms of implementing business climate improvement reforms."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"MBS's vision for Saudi Arabia is built around three key themes: a vibrant society, a thriving economy, and an ambitious development plan."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"The government has made significant progress in achieving these goals, with non-oil revenues increasing by 15% and the budget deficit being reduced."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"The Crown Prince's philosophy of management has been praised for its inclusivity, modernization, originality, boldness, and realism, and has been instrumental in guiding the country's renaissance and achievements."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"A study by the Al-Qarar Center for Media Studies has provided an analytical reading of MBS's philosophy of management, which represents a compass for the Kingdom's renaissance and its successes and achievements within the framework of the pioneering development vision \"Saudi Vision 2030\"."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"The study was based on the monitoring and analysis of a series of speeches, meetings, statements, and statements of MBS, and provides valuable insights into his vision and leadership style."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"Overall, MBS's 2030 vision for Saudi Arabia has been a game-changer for the country, and his social and economic reforms have been instrumental in transforming the country's landscape and promoting a more modern and moderate form of Islam."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"While there are still challenges to be addressed, particularly with regards to women's rights and the influence of the Wahhabi religious establishment, MBS's vision and leadership have been widely praised, and Saudi Arabia is poised to become a major player on the global stage."},{"citations":{"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152":1.0},"text":"The country's celebration of the sixth anniversary of MBS's pledge to draw the joy of the people and write a new history of stability at the political level and achievements at the national level is a testament to the progress that has been made."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"As the country continues to move forward, it is clear that MBS's 2030 vision will play a critical role in shaping Saudi Arabia's future and promoting a more modern, moderate, and prosperous society."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"Mohammed bin Salman Al Saud, commonly referred to as MBS, has been the driving force behind Saudi Arabia's ambitious 2030 vision, a comprehensive development plan aimed at reducing the country's dependence on oil and diversifying its economy."},{"citations":{"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152":1.0},"text":"Since his appointment as Crown Prince in 2017, MBS has introduced a series of social and economic reforms, which have been instrumental in transforming the country's landscape."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"One of the key aspects of MBS's vision is the curtailing of the influence of the Wahhabi religious establishment, which has been achieved by restricting the powers of the religious police."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"This move has been seen as a significant step towards modernizing the country and promoting a more moderate form of Islam."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"MBS has also been a strong advocate for women's rights, and his government has implemented several reforms aimed at improving the status of women in Saudi society."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"For instance, women are now allowed to apply for a passport without the consent of a male guardian and can visit cinemas with their boyfriends."},{"citations":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":1.0},"text":"Additionally, the government has changed the legislation to allow women to drive, and according to research firm Statista, over 175,000 women applied for a driving license in Riyadh within a year and a half of the law being passed."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"These reforms have been widely welcomed, and Saudi Arabia has been ranked by the World Bank among the top 20 reformers in the world, and second among the top high-income countries and G20 countries in terms of implementing business climate improvement reforms."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"MBS's vision for Saudi Arabia is built around three key themes: a vibrant society, a thriving economy, and an ambitious development plan."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"The government has made significant progress in achieving these goals, with non-oil revenues increasing by 15% and the budget deficit being reduced."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"The Crown Prince's philosophy of management has been praised for its inclusivity, modernization, originality, boldness, and realism, and has been instrumental in guiding the country's renaissance and achievements."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"A study by the Al-Qarar Center for Media Studies has provided an analytical reading of MBS's philosophy of management, which represents a compass for the Kingdom's renaissance and its successes and achievements within the framework of the pioneering development vision \"Saudi Vision 2030\"."},{"citations":{"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":1.0},"text":"The study was based on the monitoring and analysis of a series of speeches, meetings, statements, and statements of MBS, and provides valuable insights into his vision and leadership style."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"Overall, MBS's 2030 vision for Saudi Arabia has been a game-changer for the country, and his social and economic reforms have been instrumental in transforming the country's landscape and promoting a more modern and moderate form of Islam."},{"citations":{"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":1.0},"text":"While there are still challenges to be addressed, particularly with regards to women's rights and the influence of the Wahhabi religious establishment, MBS's vision and leadership have been widely praised, and Saudi Arabia is poised to become a major player on the global stage."},{"citations":{"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152":1.0},"text":"The country's celebration of the sixth anniversary of MBS's pledge to draw the joy of the people and write a new history of stability at the political level and achievements at the national level is a testament to the progress that has been made."},{"citations":{"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":1.0},"text":"As the country continues to move forward, it is clear that MBS's 2030 vision will play a critical role in shaping Saudi Arabia's future and promoting a more modern, moderate, and prosperous society."}],"references":["16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152","cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703","a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813","1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850","eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758"],"documents":{"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758":{"id":"eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82_892176758","text":"Despite the government \u2019 s alleged reforms,\nWidespread violations of women \u2019 s rights in Saudi Arabia\nSunday 01 January 2023 - 05: 52 GMT\nThe widespread German network Deutsche Welle has highlighted the persistence of widespread violations of women \u2019 s rights in Saudi Arabia despite alleged government reforms.\nWorld - Saudi Arabia\nSaudi authorities continue to discriminate against women as second-class citizens with an unchanging authoritarian guardianship system and strict disobedience laws and rules that restrict the rights of unmarried women.\nSince Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman launched the so-called \u201csocial and economic reform \u201d dubbed Vision 2030 in April 2016, the status of women has changed dramatically, with the network seeing that some laws were in favor of women and others headed for the worse.\nWhile women activists like Loujain al-Hathloul were jailed for three years following a drive for women to drive, the relevant legislation was changed in 2018 \u2014 and according to research firm Statista \u2014 within a year and a half, more than 175,000 women applied.\nDriving license in Riyadh.\nOther laws have been amended since 2018, meaning women are now allowed to apply for a passport without the consent of a male guardian and go to cinemas with their boyfriends.\nLina al-Hathloul, the sister of women \u2019 s activist Loujain al-Hathloul, who is the head of communications and surveillance at the London-based ALQST Human Rights Organisation, said: \u201cThe regime of repression is still in place \u201d in Saudi Arabia.\nBecause of the male guardianship system, girls and women still rely on male guardian consent for most decisions.\nIn case of disobedience, these guardians, who could be fathers, husbands, brothers or sons, are entitled to be sent to so-called \u201ccare homes \u201d \u2014 forever, al-Hathloul said.\nMoreover, this year, three court rulings starkly emphasized the Saudi ambivalence between men and women.\nIn January, a court in the city convicted Yasser M.\nVerbal sexual harassment of a woman.\nHe was sentenced to eight months in prison and a fine of 5,000 rials (1,265 euros / $1,330).\nYasir M was one of the first cases to be convicted following the tightening of Saudi legislation to combat sexual harassment in 2019.\nBut in August, PhD student Salma al-Shehab, 34, was sentenced to 34 years in prison, and a month later Noura bint Saeed al-Qahtani was sentenced to 45 years in prison.\nBoth were convicted of retweeting human rights calls.\n\u201cThe result is fear \u2014 people no longer know what the red lines are, \u201d said al-Hathloul. For her, the liberation of women \u2019 s rights over the past four years is nowhere near what Saudi women really want.\n\u201cWe want to live in Saudi Arabia without fear and be able to claim our rights. \u201d\nAccording to the 2019 Women, Peace and Security Index (WPS), Saudi Arabia ranks lowest globally.\nAccording to the index, female labor force participation remains low across the region despite a rapid rise in female education rates and improved access to health care.\nWomen hold only 16 per cent of legislative seats in MENA countries compared to 25 per cent globally.\nCertain States actively suppress women's rights by persecuting women's rights activists.\nNowhere is this more evident than in Saudi Arabia, where authorities arbitrarily arrest and detain women \u2019 s rights leaders with impunity.\nThe authorities of the House of Saud, a legitimate permanent resident of the United States, arrested Aziza al-Yousef in May 2018 on charges related to her peaceful human rights activism.\nDespite her provisional release in March 2019, Ms. Al-Yousef cannot leave the Kingdom due to pending charges in court.\nSource: Saudi Leaks","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0000.json.gz:506","uncompressed_offset":892176758,"url":"www.alalam.ir/news/6493578/%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-01-01T04:18:00.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eac6eeef-f0fb-427b-b9b3-a05209fb6f82>","warc_url":"https://www.alalam.ir/news/6493578/%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-01-01T06:11:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850":{"id":"1ec84a30-fdcd-4f1f-a0a0-4429222362aa_712309850","text":"Moderate ideology: The silent Saudi revolution\n\nSports events, movie screenings, art exhibitions and music concerts are becoming increasingly common in the kingdom, and Saudi citizens are lapping them all up.\n\nPublished: 25th July 2023 12:34 AM\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0 Last Updated: 25th July 2023 12:45 AM \u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0A+A-\n\nIt has been \u2018work in progress\u2019 for some time now. Saudi Arabia is changing the tone and texture of its ideology from what has always been considered obscurantist to something that keeps with the times. Sports events, movie screenings, art exhibitions and music concerts are becoming increasingly common in the kingdom, and Saudi citizens are lapping them all up.\n\nThe kingdom has rapidly secured its position as a centre for cultural events, art exhibitions and film screenings. The nation\u2019s Vision 2030 envisages and fully supports the expansion of the entertainment market to SR30 billion. Almost every domain of entertainment for which Saudi citizens earlier travelled far and wide is now available at home. This is thanks to a break from the past that the de facto ruler, Mohammad bin Salman (MbS), the Crown Prince, has initiated. It makes eminent sense in a nation seeking to develop itself beyond the energy sector with three visionary themes: a vibrant society, a thriving economy and continuity in terms of ambition in comprehensive development.\n\nAll this translates into a modern civilisational outlook with technology, intellectualism, private investment, trade, tourism, academics and more, all becoming the prime domains of functioning. The traditional worldwide perception of Saudi Arabia as the centre of the obscurantist ideology of Islam and a nation with an anti-reformist outlook has persisted, and not without reason. A brief understanding of this is important to appreciate the degree of change that Prince MbS has been able to generate.\n\nAs the custodian of the Holy Shrines of Mecca and Medina and the land where Islam\u2019s first message was delivered, the Saudi rulers and clergy have always been all-powerful, even more so after adopting the core ideology expounded by Saudi thinker Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab. There is a long history behind this.\n\nA virtual pact between the powerful clergy and the Royal Family has existed to promote the Wahhabi ideology in return for the powers that the Royals enjoyed. The pact saw enhanced clergy power after 1979 when the Shia Revolution occurred in Iran, the Saudi Ikhwan attempted a takeover of the Holy Shrine at Mecca, and the Soviets invaded Afghanistan. Wahhabi ideology was about going back to the basics and making the faith much less tolerant by supporting \u2018Takfir\u2019, or the power of declaration of a believer as an apostate if Wahhabi tenets are not adhered to. The militant part of the ideology started to come to the fore after 1979. From segments of the Arab world to Afghanistan, Pakistan, parts of India, Indonesia, Philippines and other Southeast Asian nations, militancy promoting the Saudi brand flourished, giving rise to the notion of a clash of civilisations.\n\nSaudi Arabia\u2019s energy resources always dictated US policy. A grey zone existed here with simultaneous US support to Israel and Saudi Arabia, stacked primarily against Iran and the collective Arab will against Israel. A couple of factors brought the trigger for change. Among them were the discovery of shale gas in the US and the progressive decline in US dependency on Saudi energy resources. Second was the dwindling Saudi economy and the realisation that in an energy-based economy, without expansion into other domains of economic development, such as trade, technology, tourism, investments, entertainment and intellectual research, Saudi Arabia would waste its opportunities and resources. The tremendous advantage of being the centre of the Islamic world could give it enduring leadership status if it could neutralise the rising militancy within Islam. Nations all around, such as the UAE, had fully utilised their possessions and drawn major economic attraction due to pragmatism followed in all domains, including faith issues. The position of women in Saudi society, in particular, had a damning effect on the nation.\n\nNothing changes without a leader and a vision. Saudi Arabia was fortunate to get MbS, although his personal equation with the US has remained strained for various reasons, not the least being the Khashoggi factor. However, none of that has affected his intent of modernising the nation and for that, a more moderate form of Islam within the kingdom is necessary. To his credit, he has convinced the clergy of the need to follow his vision, which will also project Islam differently to many others who follow the Saudi guidelines on faith.\n\nSheikh Mohammed bin Abdul Karim Al-Issa, from Saudi Arabia, who recently visited New Delhi for six days, is the Secretary General of the Muslim World League. The organisation was once at the forefront of promoting obscurantist ideology but is now transformed, as is evident from Sheikh al Issa\u2019s message in New Delhi. The Sheikh\u2019s belief which he transparently shared is that a whole generation of Muslims has grown up with an ideology that has given them a negative view of other faiths and an intolerantly sectarian understanding of their own.\n\nIn his several meetings with intellectuals, leaders and clergy from diverse faiths in India, he emphasised the role of the clergy in any faith. He admitted that Islam had earned a bad name for itself due to the acts of a few and the refusal of the followers to condemn those acts. He spoke of the role of family and education and decried religious teachers\u2019 unsupervised education of young Muslim children. He mentioned that when intolerance and militancy were rising, people feared confronting them. His most poignant argument was that such obscurantism and militancy cannot be eliminated in the typical military way; they have to be removed from the roots by narratives stronger than the ones expounded.\n\nSheikh Al-Issa\u2019s visit to India was symbolic of what appears to be the fading of the intolerant and militant element of Islam, but we cannot read too much into this. That change is taking place at the ideological centre is positive, but there is no guarantee of permanency. It is also not necessary that the message from Saudi Arabia is gelling with the vast Muslim populations worldwide. These populations are enmeshed with their local cultures and unlikely to follow examples. What is true is that a message supporting reformation has emanated from the nation considered the custodian of the shrines and, by many, of the faith. Nurturing this and taking it beyond is now the challenge.\n\nLt Gen Syed Ata Hasnain (Retd)\n\nFormer Commander, Srinagar-based 15 Corps. Now Chancellor, Central University of Kashmir\n\n(atahasnain@gmail.com)\n\n\n\nflipboard facebook twitter whatsapp","url":"https://www.newindianexpress.com/opinions/2023/jul/25/moderate-ideology-the-silent-saudi-revolution-2598162.html"},"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813":{"id":"a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59_1045813813","text":"Study: The Crown Prince \u2019 s philosophy of management is a compass for the Kingdom \u2019 s renaissance and achievements within the framework of \u201cVision 2030 \u201d\nShe said he takes a strategic approach based on inclusivity, a duality of modernization, originality, boldness and realism.\nCrown Prince Mohammed bin Salman\nAl-Qarar Center for Media Studies has issued a new study that provides an analytical reading of the philosophy of His Highness Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman in the administration, which represents a compass for the Kingdom \u2019 s renaissance and its successes and achievements within the framework of the pioneering development vision \u201cSaudi Vision 2030 \u201d.\nThis came in conjunction with the celebration of the fifth anniversary of the pledge of His Highness as Crown Prince.\nThe study was based on the monitoring and analysis of a series of speeches, speeches, meetings, statements and statements of His Highness the Crown Prince (may God protect him), the number of which reached (16) articles during the period from 2018 to the current year 2022.\nThe study concluded with a set of results, including the Crown Prince \u2019 s adoption of a strategic approach to management based on several pillars, most notably comprehensiveness in approach, dual modernization and originality, boldness and realism, in addition to uniqueness and excellence, universality of presentation, as well as openness to all, and always looking forward.\nThe study pointed to the adoption of His Highness the Crown Prince in his speeches and statements primarily on logical probabilities in the process of influence and persuasion, through addressing the mind with evidence and proofs, using the language of numbers, logical reasoning, and comparisons between the past, present and the future, in addition to proving what has been achieved on the ground effectively, and citing the reports of international institutions.\nThe study pointed out that Prince Mohammed bin Salman, may Allah support him, is betting in achieving the comprehensive development process on the Kingdom's own capabilities, especially the great Saudi people.\nShe pointed out that the language of his speech includes many central actors, which he always mentions clearly, most notably the Saudis, especially the young men and women of the Kingdom, as well as the economic, social, cultural and civilizational potential of the Kingdom, as well as the regional and international status of the Saudi state, whether at the economic, political or Islamic level.\nThe decision center study concluded that HRH Prince Mohammed bin Salman, may God protect him, follows a philosophy based on inclusiveness and renewal in all aspects of life, noting that HRH was able to convey the conviction of his comprehensive development project \"Vision 2030\" to every Saudi citizen, which made the people united in order to achieve the desired progress.\nNews you might like.\nNo stories found.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0012.json.gz:36953","uncompressed_offset":1045813813,"url":"sabq.org/saudia/%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%87%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A5%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030","warc_date":"2022-04-27T20:28:48.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a333ae7f-0373-44b2-a266-ed7304052c59>","warc_url":"https://sabq.org/saudia/%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%87%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A5%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-2030"},"created":"2022-04-27T21:25:08.000Z","lang":"eng"},"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703":{"id":"cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141_45867703","text":"Friday 23rd September 2022 Abu Dhabi UAE\nPrayer times\nNews Highlights\nToday 's Issue\nToday 's Issue\nArabic & International\nKing Salman.\nA journey of reform and development\nKing Salman.\nA journey of reform and development\nSeptember 23, 2022 02: 33\nAhmed Murad (Cairo)\nSaudi Arabia \u2019 s 92nd National Day celebrations coincide with the eighth anniversary of the pledge of allegiance to the Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, King of Saudi Arabia, as King of Saudi Arabia on January 23, 2015.\nOver the past eight years, he has achieved a long series of unprecedented achievements and reforms, making him one of the most prominent and important historical leaders of Saudi Arabia.\nKing Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud was sworn in as King of Saudi Arabia on January 23, 2015, succeeding the late King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz. King Salman began his reign by affirming his determination to continue the achievements witnessed by Saudi Arabia in the last three decades, implement an integrated reform and development program, promote the Kingdom \u2019 s domestic and foreign policy, and take positive positions on various local, regional and international issues.\nAlmost 70 years ago, King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud began his career in public work, after being appointed Acting Prince of Riyadh Region on March 16, 1954, at the age of 19, and the following year he was appointed Governor and Prince of Riyadh Region with the rank of Minister. It has grown and flourished, making it a regional hub for travel and trade, and is home to millions of Saudi nationals and expatriates from all over the world to work within the Kingdom.\nDuring his tenure in the Emirate of Riyadh, King Salman paid great attention to improving the level of infrastructure, where he oversaw the implementation of dozens and hundreds of infrastructure projects that made Riyadh a \u201cglobal city \u201d with standard specifications and standards through the establishment of a network of highways and modern, as well as the establishment of many vital facilities, such as schools, hospitals, universities, museums, sports stadiums and recreational cities.\nMandate of the Covenant\nIn a new phase of King Salman bin Abdulaziz \u2019 s career, he was appointed Minister of Defense in November 2011, and the following year, on June 18, 2012, he was appointed Crown Prince and Deputy Prime Minister, retained his position as Minister of Defense, and worked to modernize and develop the Saudi Armed Forces, which witnessed a remarkable leap in training and armament, as well as implementing a comprehensive plan to develop the entire sectors of the Ministry of Defense.\nDevelopment Programs\nOver the past eight years, King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud has been keen to implement comprehensive and integrated development programs to advance Saudi Arabia politically, economically and socially, and has achieved many achievements and reforms at various levels, which made Saudi Arabia ranked by the World Bank among the top 20 reformers in the world, and ranked second among the top high-income countries and G20 countries in terms of implementing business climate improvement reforms.\nIn the second year of his leadership, King Salman launched the Kingdom \u2019 s Vision 2030 on April 25, 2016, to be at the forefront of the development programs he adopted in order to achieve comprehensive national development, reduce the Kingdom \u2019 s dependence on oil, diversify sources of income through a package of economic reforms unprecedented in the Kingdom \u2019 s history, achieve financial stability, and other development programs that contributed to the increase in non-oil revenues by 15%, reduce the budget deficit by 48% foreign investment by 130%.\nUnder the patronage of King Salman, the Kingdom \u2019 s Vision 2030 has succeeded in achieving many achievements in the first five years, specifically during the period between 2015 and 2020, and with the beginning of 2021, a new phase in the process of achieving Vision 2030 began.\nIn the framework of this new phase, the National Investment Strategy was issued on October 11, 2021, which is expected to contribute to the growth of the national economy and diversify its sources, thus achieving many of the objectives of Vision 2030, including raising the contribution of the private sector to GDP to 65%, boosting foreign direct investment to 5.7% of GDP, increasing the proportion of non-oil exports from 16% to 50% of GDP, and reducing the unemployment rate to 7%.\nUnder the umbrella of the National Investment Strategy, investments of more than 12 trillion riyals will be injected into the local economy until 2030.\nThe biggest budget\nFor the first time in the history of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, the trend began under King Salman towards approving the general budget of the Kingdom by supporting and developing the national economy without relying mainly on oil as the sole source of national income, which was ranked by observers among the most important achievements in the history of the Kingdom.\nIn 2019, King Salman announced the largest budget in the history of the Kingdom, spending more than 1.1 trillion riyals, and revenues amounted to 975 billion riyals.\nSaudi Arabia, led by King Salman, has transformed the Saudi Public Investment Fund (PIF) into a sovereign fund with assets estimated at $2 trillion to $2.5 trillion, making it the largest sovereign fund in the world.\nIn the petroleum sector, Saudi Aramco announced in 2021 plans to produce 2 billion cubic feet per day of natural gas from the giant Jafoura field by 2030, making the kingdom the third largest natural gas producer in the world.\nHealth and Education\nKing Salman has paid great attention to the health and education sectors, and the two sectors witnessed an unprecedented boom during the reign of King Salman through the implementation of many projects. In the health sector, several health centers were launched in the last eight years, including 4 for cardiac catheterization, 7 for tumors, 3 for obesity and its diseases, 5 for behavioral and developmental disorders, as well as the launch of 4 surgical robots specialized in general surgeries, urology and artificial intelligence laboratory. For health technical research, and to raise the level of health services provided by 600 health centers by applying the Wasfti system.\nWork has also begun on the first robotic-mediated smart pharmacy at King Fahd Specialist Hospital in Tabuk.\nIn the education sector, King Salman has adopted several programs and plans to develop education and make a real renaissance in this vital sector. In this context, his decision came to merge the Ministries of Education and Higher Education into one ministry under the name of the Ministry of Education, allocate special programs for talented students, open special centers for the development of technical and engineering sciences in 32 schools across the Kingdom, and launch the \u201cYour Job and Mission \u201d program. You come back after they come back.\nOn November 14, 2021, the Kingdom announced the launch of Prince Mohammed bin Salman City, the first non-profit city in the world, which aims to support young Saudi talents, and work to encourage learning and develop leadership skills among young people.\nBlue oil.\nThe desalination industry has seen an unprecedented boom, as the kingdom has set records in the industry making it the world \u2019 s largest desalinated water producer and is expected to become a major hub for desalination technologies in the world, the Middle East and beyond, leading observers to call the industry a \u201cnew Saudi blue oil. \u201d\nSaudi Arabia \u2019 s production of desalinated water currently stands at more than 9 million cubic meters per day, with production expected to reach more than 14 million cubic meters per day in 2025.\nThe Saudi Saline Water Conversion Corporation manages 33 desalination plants, including 8 on the Arabian Gulf coast and 25 on the Red Sea coast, and in 2018 won the award of the largest desalination system in the world from the Guinness World Book.\nNational Projects\nOver the past eight years, King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud has adopted an expanded work map that included a package of giant national projects, most notably the establishment of Neom Industrial City (Oxagon), the largest floating structure in the world. The city is based on the same concepts as The Line communities launched in January 2021. 13% of world trade.\nThis is in addition to a giant project to redevelop the waterfront in the center of Jeddah \u2019 s Corniche with the aim of transforming it into a vital area, the King Salman Energy City project known as \u201cSpark \u201d, with investments estimated at $1.6 billion, and the Prince Mohammed bin Abdulaziz International Airport project with a capacity of more than 8 million passengers annually in its first phase, and 40 million passengers annually in the third phase.\nIn addition to the development of the petrochemical sector in Ras Al Khair Industrial City, the establishment of some other industrial cities, such as Jubail and Yanbu, and the development of a city for the automotive industry in order to attract investments, increase exports and provide jobs, and the repair of more than 4 million square meters of road networks.\nIn the housing sector, many housing projects have been implemented during the past eight years, including the provision of more than 282 residential products including housing units, land and subsidized financing to promote and develop the real estate sector in various regions of the Kingdom, as well as regulating the rental market and preserving the rights of parties during the rental process through the adoption of the \u201cEjar \u201d program.\nDar Al-Hijra is one of the most important residential projects launched during the reign of King Salman, and is one of the largest residential, hotel and commercial projects in Saudi Arabia, including 20 administrative towers, 80 residential towers, 80 hotels providing 40,000 rooms for pilgrims, as well as government, administrative and commercial offices accommodating 31,000 employees, a 400-bed hospital and a huge transit station.\nKing Salman is keen to develop the various regions of the Kingdom and achieve comprehensive development in them, and in this context, strategic offices were established in October 2021 to develop the areas of Al-Baha, Al-Jawf and Jazan, as well as the launch of a strategy to develop the Asir region by pumping 50 billion riyals in various investments.\nAll rights reserved to Al Ittihad Newspaper 2022 \u00a9","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0028.json.gz:21514","uncompressed_offset":45867703,"url":"www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A/4317613/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83-%D8%B3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86---%D9%85%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%85%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2022-09-23T01:21:17.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cbda1669-f39c-4ab8-9dac-c23403569141>","warc_url":"https://www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A/4317613/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%83-%D8%B3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86---%D9%85%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%85%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2022-09-23T01:24:26.000Z","lang":"eng"},"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152":{"id":"16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8_725045152","text":"On the anniversary of the sale of the Crown...\nAl-Ajmi: The Kingdom has witnessed 6 years of achievements at all levels\nHe said that this was the result of a lot of clear and strategic planning, looking forward to a bright future for the country.\nThe expert and professor of digital media, Dr. Fahed bin Salem Al-Ajmi, said that the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia has witnessed during the past six years a great development at all levels and trends, culminating in many achievements on the ground, which was the result of a lot of clear and strategic planning, looking forward to a bright future for the country.\nIn detail, Al-Ajmi explained that the past six years have made great achievements that confirmed that the decision of the Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Salman bin Abdulaziz, may God protect him, to choose His Royal Highness Prince Mohammed bin Salman as Crown Prince was a historic decision in the interest of the nation and its future, with the support of an overwhelming majority of 31 votes out of 34. The young man who illuminated the Kingdom \u2019 s skies with many of the plans and strategies that culminated in the Kingdom \u2019 s Vision 2030, for which His Highness served as an architect and a cornerstone of its strong and solid foundation.\nHe added that what His Highness has done in the past six years confirms the great and continuous volume of work in a busy journey to achieve the achievements that put the Kingdom in the ranks of the developed countries of the world, and those great and diverse achievements, which are not enough to mention the importance of their abundance and diversity and the strength of their impact on our tangible reality.\nAl-Ajmi said: Citizens and residents of the Kingdom believe that the changes made by His Highness the Crown Prince, which were sponsored by the father leader King Salman bin Abdul Aziz - may God protect them - is a turning point at the level of the state.\nDespite the existence of many global challenges and difficulties, and despite the Kingdom \u2019 s passing through difficult situations that served as a crossroads, His Highness went on to give young people a long-term perspective, making his country \u2019 s history and heritage a starting line to address the present and make his work towards the future in all fields. Internationally, according to an insight into the young leader, who soon became the talk of the world.\nThe Kingdom of Saudi Arabia celebrates the sixth anniversary of the pledge of His Highness Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman to draw the joy of the people and write a new history of stability at the political level and achievements at the national level. The political, economic, developmental and social files, and this project continues to prove its success and the strength of the foundation on which it was built and confirm that whoever comes with such a vision is a successful leader with a great personality, which can be described as an \"exceptional\" personality, making his main concern the upliftment of the homeland and the citizen.\nAl-Ajmi concluded by saying: \u201cOn the occasion of this precious and dear anniversary, we recall the great meanings of the youth inspirer, the leader of reforms and the change-maker to achieve the promising future in the march of prosperity of the homeland and the citizen under the generous care and guidance of the Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Salman bin Abdulaziz. \u201d\nNews you might like.\nNo stories found.\nSabq Electronic Newspaper\nsabq.org","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:17245","uncompressed_offset":725045152,"url":"sabq.org/saudia/regions/to0q5ckv3k","warc_date":"2023-04-05T20:39:17.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:16ca398b-f1ff-42c5-95ed-8e37d09b70f8>","warc_url":"https://sabq.org/saudia/regions/to0q5ckv3k"},"created":"2023-04-05T21:16:17.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1013","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1013","narrative_id":"1013"},"responses":[{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement originated in Italy, where it was founded by Carlo Petrini and a group of activists in the 1980s."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement was formed in response to the opening of McDonald's restaurants in the heart of Rome, which led to a decline in regional food traditions."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement is based on the tenets of \"Good quality, clean and fair\"."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, and its goal is to encourage the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption that respects seasonality and minimizes the negative impact on the environment."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and it has been promoted in Taitung, Taiwan for over 10 years."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Some current proponents of the slow food movement worldwide include Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, Aruna Tirkey from India, and Nazlina Spice Station from Malaysia."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"To sample the best slow food cuisine, one can attend the Taitung Slow Food Festival, which is held every spring and autumn in Taitung Forest Park."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"The festival features traditional ingredients and promotes environmental protection and plastic reduction."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"Additionally, one can visit the Causeway Coast, where slow food events and businesses are supported by the Slow Food movement."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement originated in Italy, where it was founded by Carlo Petrini and a group of activists in the 1980s."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement was formed in response to the opening of McDonald's restaurants in the heart of Rome, which led to a decline in regional food traditions."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement is based on the tenets of \"Good quality, clean and fair\"."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, and its goal is to encourage the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption that respects seasonality and minimizes the negative impact on the environment."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and it has been promoted in Taitung, Taiwan for over 10 years."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Some current proponents of the slow food movement worldwide include Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, Aruna Tirkey from India, and Nazlina Spice Station from Malaysia."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"To sample the best slow food cuisine, one can attend the Taitung Slow Food Festival, which is held every spring and autumn in Taitung Forest Park."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"The festival features traditional ingredients and promotes environmental protection and plastic reduction."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"Additionally, one can visit the Causeway Coast, where slow food events and businesses are supported by the Slow Food movement."}],"references":["96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237","347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398","3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363"],"documents":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":{"id":"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237","text":"Praise the slow pace of life.\nExplore the fun of the world calmly\nThe idea of slow living negates the belief that a successful person should be busy or fast, and encourages the person to be present consciously at every moment.\nOnce the society is saturated with the new, it returns to the past, and this is what happens in art, decoration, fashion, and social trends.\nFrom here, too, the slow pace of life can be seen as a return to the old calm in some way, after the rhythm of life has become too fast to keep up with.\nThe idea of a slow life can be a convenient orientation for those who are looking for a calm state of mind, trying to take a long-term view of life and the world away from constant stress, anxiety and gasping.\nSlow living helps us live more consciously and clearly with what we value and need in life, where we do everything at the right speed, rather than constantly striving for speed.\nThe idea of slow living negates the belief that a successful person must be busy or fast, and encourages the person to be present consciously at every moment.\nLife is better, not faster.\nThe idea of slow living is part of the broader slow movement that began in the 1980s in Italy.\nAfter opening McDonald \u2019 s restaurants in the heart of Rome, Carlo Petrini and a group of activists formed a movement defending regional food traditions called Slow Food.\nOver time, the movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, trying to encourage the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption that encourages respect for seasonality, and to minimize the negative impact on the environment of food production.\nCarlo Petrini \u2019 s idea began to take shape when he noticed the disconnect between farmer and consumer, due to the huge boutiques and fast food restaurants that fed central Rome and dramatically eroded local food traditions.\nCarl Honor\u00e9, one of the most famous theorists of the idea of slow living, helped bring the idea to areas other than food when he published a book in Praise of Slow in 2004.\nAwareness is growing about slow travel, slow thinking and slow action, all of which are examples of the different branches of the slow living movement.\nNot all slowness is negative.\nAs more people were forced to slow down their lifestyle, interest in slow living increased during the epidemic period.\nThe search for the term slow life has increased by 4 times in Google and YouTube.\nAlthough some of these images and videos depict a romantic rural life far from reality, for most people, the increase in research related to this content shows the desire to return to nature and seek hobbies closer to it, especially as a large number of people turned to remote work, which gave the opportunity to connect more with the self and search for what is truly pleasing, which is forgotten in the midst of a fast and breathless life.\nThe slow life movement gets rid of the negative connotations of the word \"slow\", which some may associate with laziness and non-productivity.\nCarl Honor\u00e9 explains the difference between good slowness and negative slowness, as good slowness is the deliberate slowness to do things at the right speed to achieve the best result.\nOn the other side, there is also good speed and bad speed.\nSpeed can be exciting and exhilarating in the right circumstances while the rush to finish things from just above the surface without going deep is just the opposite, because it causes distraction and is difficult to prioritize.\nEssential elements of slow living\nSlow living doesn \u2019 t mean we give up technology and fall back into old times, but it does help us give up distracting activities, make us reclaim our own time to become more present and aware of every moment in life, and help build stronger relationships and spend quality time with friends and children.\nIt also helps us build our own values, design the lifestyle that suits us, and dedicate time to what we \u2019 re really looking for, not what the fast-paced lifestyle of the planet forces us to do.\nA slow life entails taking a break and redefining our relationship with things like a phone, tablet, or other gadgets like them, and then making room for screen-free time.\nHonor\u00e9 says, \u201cThe cornerstone of slow living is to form balanced and more humane relationships with modern technologies.\n\u201cWe have to somehow learn when to go ahead with technology and when to slow down and stop moving between social media, the Netflix screen or even aimlessly surfing the internet. \u201d\nHonor\u00e9 also emphasizes the need to let go of the fear of rejection or being lost, and instead of trying to do everything, we should choose only what matters to us and touches us, without the worry of saying the word \u201cno \u201d.\nWe must say no to everything that does not concern us and not increase the burden we place on ourselves.\nWe have to prioritize carefully and let everything else go, having grown tired of the speed with which we feel we are racing rather than actually living our lives.\nWe always wait for a moment other than the moment we live, which makes us feel that our lives are vanishing in vain.\nSlow life solidifies deep pleasures and strong emotions, away from entertainment and shallow pleasures that fade away shortly and leave us burdened with feelings of frustration and loneliness.\nSource: Websites","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:13092","uncompressed_offset":78339237,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/news/lifestyle/2022/3/17/%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%85%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AD-%D8%A5%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%A6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81","warc_date":"2022-03-18T06:23:13.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/news/lifestyle/2022/3/17/%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%85%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AD-%D8%A5%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%A6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81"},"created":"2022-03-18T06:29:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":{"id":"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363","text":"Breaking The Industrial Cycle With Slow Food\n\nWhere do you go to get your groceries? If your first thought was your local supermarket, you are not alone. Shopping in large grocery stores became the norm for many of us, and we rely on these outlets more than we realise. They are convenient, filled to the brim with seemingly every product you could imagine and have a price point that fits most pockets.\n\nFrom afar it seems like the perfect solution, but we all witnessed what happened in 2020, when the COVID-19 pandemic turned life on its head and among many others, highlighted the fragility of our food economy and the part supermarkets play in it.\u00a0\n\nThe University of Oxford describes our food system as \u201ca complex set of interconnected practices and relationships that ultimately deliver food from farms, processing facilities, factories, warehouses, and retailers, to the dinner table.\u201d\u00a0\n\nSlow Food\n\nThe industrial food system is built for scale and efficiency with an aim to maximise production, reduce cost, and function much like factories.\n\nAlthough many supermarkets and producers are taking steps to include the origins of their products on their labels, there is still not enough transparency around where our food actually comes from. This industrialised structure offers customers accessibility to a wider range of products at more affordable prices but has economic and environmental impacts that many are not aware of.\n\nIndustrial agriculture is notorious for using a range of fertilisers, pesticides, herbicides in their processes to maximise output, some of which stays present in the soil long after the crops are harvested. The products are then processed in factories, stabilised with preservatives and packaged in plastic, all occurring before they are loaded onto long haul freights, planes, lorries to arrive in distribution centres and eventually to supermarket shelves.\u00a0\n\nBBC Good Food reported that \u201cDEFRA estimates that moving food is responsible for 25 per cent of all miles covered by heavy goods traffic in the UK. Transporting food within, to and around the UK produces 19 million tonnes of CO2 annually \u2013 equivalent to around 5.5 million typical cars.\u201d\n\nThe length of the supply chains involved in industrial food systems result in a fragile structure as any slight disruption throughout the intricate process can halt the supply chain at any time.\u00a0\n\nHowever, this industrial food system is not the only one available to our economy. While our modern supermarkets heavily rely on large-scale agriculture, large scale production and precise, uninterrupted international food trade and fast turnaround times, the alternative slow food system focuses on a more resilient structure.\n\nAs the resilient alternative to this industrial cycle that many in the industry are championing, Slow Food is focused on returning to the traditional methods and celebrating all things local.\n\nThe not for profit grassroots organisation, Slow Food was set up in Italy in the late 1980s in a bid to promote traditional food preparation methods and locally sourced ingredients, going against the arrival of the American fast-food chain McDonald\u2019s in Rome. The eco-gastronomic organisation now has around 100,000 members in over 150 countries.\u00a0\n\nRecognising and raising awareness of the negative impact the industrial food system had on society, the economy and the environment, the organisation ignited a Slow Food movement: a new way of conscious consumerism that takes seasonality, locality and tradition into account.\n\nA slow, or resilient food system can take on many forms, starting with us as individuals making a conscious effort to engage with producers, venues and outlets that are aligned with the slow food values, to foraging, growing our own produce and going to local farmers\u2019 markets.\n\nAny involvement in the movement can make a significant difference in local communities and build a more sustainable, resilient and eco-friendly food system.\n\nAs the first accredited Slow Food destination in Northern Ireland, the Causeway Coast and Glens have been spearheading the move toward this resilient system and together with Taste Causeway, the collaborative network of local food and drink businesses.\n\nFrom exciting slow food events to highlighting producers and awarding them with Slow Food accreditation, Taste Causeway and Slow Food NI are putting local suppliers and venues at the forefront of consumers\u2019 minds, one business at a time.\u00a0\n\nTo find out more about how you can support the Slow Food movement, the businesses involved and the upcoming events on the Causeway Coast, go to https://slowfood.tastecauseway.com/\u00a0\n\nShare This:\n\nShare on facebook\nShare on twitter\nShare on linkedin","url":"https://www.businessfirstonline.co.uk/other-articles/breaking-the-industrial-cycle-with-slow-food/"},"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":{"id":"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","text":"Taitung \u2019 s first ever International Slow Food Forum will be held on April 28!\nInternational slow food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia gathered at the Taitung County Government Hall to share the experience of slow food promotion around the world, and exchange and learn with local slow food practitioners in Taitung, making Taitung a new base for dialogue with the international slow food movement and linking up the southern island culture.\nThe slow food movement originated in Italy, has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and has been promoted in Taitung for 10 years.\nThe slow food spirit of \u201cGood quality, clean and fair \u201d comes from Italy, but it has grown up in Taitung with a rich variety of local features.\nThe Taitung County government specially invited seven international slow food activists and local slow food practitioners from Taitung County to exchange ideas on the eve of the first slow food festival this year, \u201cfrom the festival to the day, from the traditional to the contemporary. \u201d The theme is to explore how traditional food culture can be practiced in contemporary society through the Slow Food Movement, and how the international Slow Food Movement can blossom in all corners of the world through the diverse participation of citizens and community power.\nOn the agenda, Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, first introduced the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and shared the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food Presidia projects of the Slow Food movement.\nIn response to the International Year of Xiaomi 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey will introduce the Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nNazlina Spice Station in Malaysia is an introduction to the local cuisine, starting from Laksa, to the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nCommunity power is also an important theme of this forum. The Gonnay couple from the Philippines and Ramon Uy Jr will discuss how the Slow Food movement can achieve the function of cultural inheritance and food farming education through community connection from family, community, organization, market, and tourism.\nThe local representative of Taitung, ibu istanda takiscibanan of the Bunun tribe, shared the history of restoring millet in the Kandeng tribe of Haiduan Township; Guo Lijin, CEO of Jinhetang, will talk about the experience and future vision of slow food in Taitung for ten years; and many Taitung slow food chefs and shop owners will join hands to show the strength of the cohesion in the local community.\nSimultaneous real-time interpretation service is available, and people who are interested in promoting slow food are welcome to join us.\nFor details and registration, please go to\nhttps: / / www.accupass.com / go / TTSlowFoodForum\n2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum\nFrom Festivals to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary\nDate: 4 / 28 (Fri) 09: 00-16: 30\nVenue: Taitung County Government Hall\nTaitung County Government Advertisements\n# Slow Food # Taitung # International # Slow Food Movement # Italy","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:11979","uncompressed_offset":611052333,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-07T00:28:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405"},"created":"2023-04-07T01:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":{"id":"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398","text":"The first International Slow Food Forum was held today at the Taitung County Government Auditorium. International Slow Food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia brought experience from all over the world to promote slow food.\nWang Zhihui, deputy mayor of Taitung County, said that this year's Slow Food Festival \"Morning Table\" will be held in Taitung Forest Park on April 29 and 30.\nThe slow food movement, which has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, originated in Italy and has been promoted in Taitung for more than 10 years.\nIn the \"Taitung Slow Food Festival\" held every spring and autumn, the public and tourists pay more attention to the source of ingredients in their lives, practice environmental protection and plastic reduction, and tell new stories in the contemporary era with traditional ingredients.\nOn the eve of the first Slow Food Festival this year, the Taitung County government invited seven international Slow Food Movement advocates to exchange with local Slow Food practitioners. The theme of the forum was \u201cFrom Festival to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary \u201d.\" Flowers? \"and other issues, hoping to continue to move internationally and link the Austronesian culture.\nThe 2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum begins at 9: 00 am on the 28th. Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, introduce the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and share the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food. The Food Presidia Project.\nIn response to the International Year of Millet 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey shared the experience of the local Slow Food Festival in India with Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nIn addition, Malaysia representative Nazlina Spice Station is a local cuisine, from Laksa to talk about the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nThe ibu istanda takiscibanan, who represents the Bunun in Taitung, shares with the international community the journey of restoring millet to the Kandeng tribe in Haiduan Township, while Kuo Li-chin, CEO of Tinhetang, fully describes the experience and future vision of Slow Food in Taitung for ten years.\nInternational speakers will participate in the Taitung Slow Food Festival \u201cMorning Table \u201d held in Taitung Forest Park on the 29th and 30th, and demonstrate the traditional breakfast of Indian and Filipino aborigines on the 30th. The event is free of charge. Please refer to the full text of the forum download website (https: / / reurl.cc / pL0XvZ), and Taitung Slow Food Food Festival information (https: / / www.facebook.com / SlowFoodTaitung /).\n# International Slow Food Forum # Taitung Slow Food Festival # Taitung County Government # Slow Food Festival","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0012.json.gz:28713","uncompressed_offset":97571398,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230428003952-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-28T10:18:14.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230428003952-260405"},"created":"2023-04-28T10:23:35.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1014","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1014","narrative_id":"1014"},"responses":[{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement has a rich history and background that spans over three decades, originating in Italy in the 1980s."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement was founded by Carlo Petrini and a group of activists who sought to defend regional food traditions and promote the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The idea of slow living, which negates the belief that a successful person must be busy or fast, is a key component of the slow food movement, encouraging individuals to be present consciously at every moment."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, with the goal of encouraging respect for seasonality and minimizing the negative impact on the environment of food production."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's tenets are centered around the concept of \"Good quality, clean and fair\" food, which emphasizes the importance of high-quality ingredients, sustainable production methods, and fair prices for farmers and producers."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"One of the main drivers of the slow food movement was the opening of McDonald's restaurants in the heart of Rome, which led to the erosion of local food traditions and prompted Carlo Petrini to form a movement to defend regional cuisine."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Today, the slow food movement has a global presence, with international representatives from countries such as Italy, the Philippines, India, and Malaysia working to promote slow food and preserve local culinary traditions."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Some current proponents of the slow food movement worldwide include Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, who are working to expand the movement globally."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Aruna Tirkey from India is another prominent proponent of the slow food movement, sharing her experience of promoting local cuisine and preserving traditional food practices."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Nazlina Spice Station from Malaysia is also a key figure in the movement, working to preserve Penang's food heritage and promote local cuisine."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"To sample the best slow food cuisine, one can attend events such as the Taitung Slow Food Festival, which is held every spring and autumn in Taitung, Taiwan."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The festival features a range of local ingredients and traditional dishes, and provides an opportunity for visitors to learn about the slow food movement and its principles."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"In addition to attending festivals, individuals can also support the slow food movement by visiting local farmers' markets and restaurants that prioritize sustainable and locally sourced ingredients."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"The Causeway Coast in Northern Ireland is one region that is home to a number of slow food businesses and events, and visitors can find out more about the movement and its activities in the area by visiting the Slow Food website."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"Overall, the slow food movement is a global phenomenon that is working to promote sustainable food systems, preserve local culinary traditions, and encourage individuals to adopt a slower and more mindful approach to food and eating."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's emphasis on quality, sustainability, and fairness has resonated with people around the world, and its impact can be seen in the growing number of slow food festivals, markets, and restaurants that are popping up in cities and towns everywhere."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"As the movement continues to grow and evolve, it is likely that we will see even more innovative and creative approaches to slow food, from farm-to-table restaurants to community-supported agriculture programs."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"By supporting the slow food movement and its principles, individuals can help to create a more sustainable and equitable food system that prioritizes the well-being of people, animals, and the environment."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement has a rich history and background that spans over three decades, originating in Italy in the 1980s."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The movement was founded by Carlo Petrini and a group of activists who sought to defend regional food traditions and promote the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The idea of slow living, which negates the belief that a successful person must be busy or fast, is a key component of the slow food movement, encouraging individuals to be present consciously at every moment."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, with the goal of encouraging respect for seasonality and minimizing the negative impact on the environment of food production."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's tenets are centered around the concept of \"Good quality, clean and fair\" food, which emphasizes the importance of high-quality ingredients, sustainable production methods, and fair prices for farmers and producers."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"One of the main drivers of the slow food movement was the opening of McDonald's restaurants in the heart of Rome, which led to the erosion of local food traditions and prompted Carlo Petrini to form a movement to defend regional cuisine."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Today, the slow food movement has a global presence, with international representatives from countries such as Italy, the Philippines, India, and Malaysia working to promote slow food and preserve local culinary traditions."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Some current proponents of the slow food movement worldwide include Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, who are working to expand the movement globally."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Aruna Tirkey from India is another prominent proponent of the slow food movement, sharing her experience of promoting local cuisine and preserving traditional food practices."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"Nazlina Spice Station from Malaysia is also a key figure in the movement, working to preserve Penang's food heritage and promote local cuisine."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"To sample the best slow food cuisine, one can attend events such as the Taitung Slow Food Festival, which is held every spring and autumn in Taitung, Taiwan."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The festival features a range of local ingredients and traditional dishes, and provides an opportunity for visitors to learn about the slow food movement and its principles."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"In addition to attending festivals, individuals can also support the slow food movement by visiting local farmers' markets and restaurants that prioritize sustainable and locally sourced ingredients."},{"citations":{"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":1.0},"text":"The Causeway Coast in Northern Ireland is one region that is home to a number of slow food businesses and events, and visitors can find out more about the movement and its activities in the area by visiting the Slow Food website."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"Overall, the slow food movement is a global phenomenon that is working to promote sustainable food systems, preserve local culinary traditions, and encourage individuals to adopt a slower and more mindful approach to food and eating."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's emphasis on quality, sustainability, and fairness has resonated with people around the world, and its impact can be seen in the growing number of slow food festivals, markets, and restaurants that are popping up in cities and towns everywhere."},{"citations":{"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":1.0},"text":"As the movement continues to grow and evolve, it is likely that we will see even more innovative and creative approaches to slow food, from farm-to-table restaurants to community-supported agriculture programs."},{"citations":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":1.0},"text":"By supporting the slow food movement and its principles, individuals can help to create a more sustainable and equitable food system that prioritizes the well-being of people, animals, and the environment."}],"references":["96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237","347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398","3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363"],"documents":{"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237":{"id":"96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9_78339237","text":"Praise the slow pace of life.\nExplore the fun of the world calmly\nThe idea of slow living negates the belief that a successful person should be busy or fast, and encourages the person to be present consciously at every moment.\nOnce the society is saturated with the new, it returns to the past, and this is what happens in art, decoration, fashion, and social trends.\nFrom here, too, the slow pace of life can be seen as a return to the old calm in some way, after the rhythm of life has become too fast to keep up with.\nThe idea of a slow life can be a convenient orientation for those who are looking for a calm state of mind, trying to take a long-term view of life and the world away from constant stress, anxiety and gasping.\nSlow living helps us live more consciously and clearly with what we value and need in life, where we do everything at the right speed, rather than constantly striving for speed.\nThe idea of slow living negates the belief that a successful person must be busy or fast, and encourages the person to be present consciously at every moment.\nLife is better, not faster.\nThe idea of slow living is part of the broader slow movement that began in the 1980s in Italy.\nAfter opening McDonald \u2019 s restaurants in the heart of Rome, Carlo Petrini and a group of activists formed a movement defending regional food traditions called Slow Food.\nOver time, the movement has gained supporters in more than 150 countries, trying to encourage the enjoyment of good food and conscious consumption that encourages respect for seasonality, and to minimize the negative impact on the environment of food production.\nCarlo Petrini \u2019 s idea began to take shape when he noticed the disconnect between farmer and consumer, due to the huge boutiques and fast food restaurants that fed central Rome and dramatically eroded local food traditions.\nCarl Honor\u00e9, one of the most famous theorists of the idea of slow living, helped bring the idea to areas other than food when he published a book in Praise of Slow in 2004.\nAwareness is growing about slow travel, slow thinking and slow action, all of which are examples of the different branches of the slow living movement.\nNot all slowness is negative.\nAs more people were forced to slow down their lifestyle, interest in slow living increased during the epidemic period.\nThe search for the term slow life has increased by 4 times in Google and YouTube.\nAlthough some of these images and videos depict a romantic rural life far from reality, for most people, the increase in research related to this content shows the desire to return to nature and seek hobbies closer to it, especially as a large number of people turned to remote work, which gave the opportunity to connect more with the self and search for what is truly pleasing, which is forgotten in the midst of a fast and breathless life.\nThe slow life movement gets rid of the negative connotations of the word \"slow\", which some may associate with laziness and non-productivity.\nCarl Honor\u00e9 explains the difference between good slowness and negative slowness, as good slowness is the deliberate slowness to do things at the right speed to achieve the best result.\nOn the other side, there is also good speed and bad speed.\nSpeed can be exciting and exhilarating in the right circumstances while the rush to finish things from just above the surface without going deep is just the opposite, because it causes distraction and is difficult to prioritize.\nEssential elements of slow living\nSlow living doesn \u2019 t mean we give up technology and fall back into old times, but it does help us give up distracting activities, make us reclaim our own time to become more present and aware of every moment in life, and help build stronger relationships and spend quality time with friends and children.\nIt also helps us build our own values, design the lifestyle that suits us, and dedicate time to what we \u2019 re really looking for, not what the fast-paced lifestyle of the planet forces us to do.\nA slow life entails taking a break and redefining our relationship with things like a phone, tablet, or other gadgets like them, and then making room for screen-free time.\nHonor\u00e9 says, \u201cThe cornerstone of slow living is to form balanced and more humane relationships with modern technologies.\n\u201cWe have to somehow learn when to go ahead with technology and when to slow down and stop moving between social media, the Netflix screen or even aimlessly surfing the internet. \u201d\nHonor\u00e9 also emphasizes the need to let go of the fear of rejection or being lost, and instead of trying to do everything, we should choose only what matters to us and touches us, without the worry of saying the word \u201cno \u201d.\nWe must say no to everything that does not concern us and not increase the burden we place on ourselves.\nWe have to prioritize carefully and let everything else go, having grown tired of the speed with which we feel we are racing rather than actually living our lives.\nWe always wait for a moment other than the moment we live, which makes us feel that our lives are vanishing in vain.\nSlow life solidifies deep pleasures and strong emotions, away from entertainment and shallow pleasures that fade away shortly and leave us burdened with feelings of frustration and loneliness.\nSource: Websites","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:13092","uncompressed_offset":78339237,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/news/lifestyle/2022/3/17/%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%85%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AD-%D8%A5%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%A6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81","warc_date":"2022-03-18T06:23:13.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:96da40f6-f654-43da-a3f7-d19d9c31ede9>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/news/lifestyle/2022/3/17/%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%85%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AD-%D8%A5%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%A6%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81"},"created":"2022-03-18T06:29:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363":{"id":"3fc1cd45-38d0-4612-8e8e-21d9a4fd7376_751985363","text":"Breaking The Industrial Cycle With Slow Food\n\nWhere do you go to get your groceries? If your first thought was your local supermarket, you are not alone. Shopping in large grocery stores became the norm for many of us, and we rely on these outlets more than we realise. They are convenient, filled to the brim with seemingly every product you could imagine and have a price point that fits most pockets.\n\nFrom afar it seems like the perfect solution, but we all witnessed what happened in 2020, when the COVID-19 pandemic turned life on its head and among many others, highlighted the fragility of our food economy and the part supermarkets play in it.\u00a0\n\nThe University of Oxford describes our food system as \u201ca complex set of interconnected practices and relationships that ultimately deliver food from farms, processing facilities, factories, warehouses, and retailers, to the dinner table.\u201d\u00a0\n\nSlow Food\n\nThe industrial food system is built for scale and efficiency with an aim to maximise production, reduce cost, and function much like factories.\n\nAlthough many supermarkets and producers are taking steps to include the origins of their products on their labels, there is still not enough transparency around where our food actually comes from. This industrialised structure offers customers accessibility to a wider range of products at more affordable prices but has economic and environmental impacts that many are not aware of.\n\nIndustrial agriculture is notorious for using a range of fertilisers, pesticides, herbicides in their processes to maximise output, some of which stays present in the soil long after the crops are harvested. The products are then processed in factories, stabilised with preservatives and packaged in plastic, all occurring before they are loaded onto long haul freights, planes, lorries to arrive in distribution centres and eventually to supermarket shelves.\u00a0\n\nBBC Good Food reported that \u201cDEFRA estimates that moving food is responsible for 25 per cent of all miles covered by heavy goods traffic in the UK. Transporting food within, to and around the UK produces 19 million tonnes of CO2 annually \u2013 equivalent to around 5.5 million typical cars.\u201d\n\nThe length of the supply chains involved in industrial food systems result in a fragile structure as any slight disruption throughout the intricate process can halt the supply chain at any time.\u00a0\n\nHowever, this industrial food system is not the only one available to our economy. While our modern supermarkets heavily rely on large-scale agriculture, large scale production and precise, uninterrupted international food trade and fast turnaround times, the alternative slow food system focuses on a more resilient structure.\n\nAs the resilient alternative to this industrial cycle that many in the industry are championing, Slow Food is focused on returning to the traditional methods and celebrating all things local.\n\nThe not for profit grassroots organisation, Slow Food was set up in Italy in the late 1980s in a bid to promote traditional food preparation methods and locally sourced ingredients, going against the arrival of the American fast-food chain McDonald\u2019s in Rome. The eco-gastronomic organisation now has around 100,000 members in over 150 countries.\u00a0\n\nRecognising and raising awareness of the negative impact the industrial food system had on society, the economy and the environment, the organisation ignited a Slow Food movement: a new way of conscious consumerism that takes seasonality, locality and tradition into account.\n\nA slow, or resilient food system can take on many forms, starting with us as individuals making a conscious effort to engage with producers, venues and outlets that are aligned with the slow food values, to foraging, growing our own produce and going to local farmers\u2019 markets.\n\nAny involvement in the movement can make a significant difference in local communities and build a more sustainable, resilient and eco-friendly food system.\n\nAs the first accredited Slow Food destination in Northern Ireland, the Causeway Coast and Glens have been spearheading the move toward this resilient system and together with Taste Causeway, the collaborative network of local food and drink businesses.\n\nFrom exciting slow food events to highlighting producers and awarding them with Slow Food accreditation, Taste Causeway and Slow Food NI are putting local suppliers and venues at the forefront of consumers\u2019 minds, one business at a time.\u00a0\n\nTo find out more about how you can support the Slow Food movement, the businesses involved and the upcoming events on the Causeway Coast, go to https://slowfood.tastecauseway.com/\u00a0\n\nShare This:\n\nShare on facebook\nShare on twitter\nShare on linkedin","url":"https://www.businessfirstonline.co.uk/other-articles/breaking-the-industrial-cycle-with-slow-food/"},"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":{"id":"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","text":"Taitung \u2019 s first ever International Slow Food Forum will be held on April 28!\nInternational slow food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia gathered at the Taitung County Government Hall to share the experience of slow food promotion around the world, and exchange and learn with local slow food practitioners in Taitung, making Taitung a new base for dialogue with the international slow food movement and linking up the southern island culture.\nThe slow food movement originated in Italy, has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and has been promoted in Taitung for 10 years.\nThe slow food spirit of \u201cGood quality, clean and fair \u201d comes from Italy, but it has grown up in Taitung with a rich variety of local features.\nThe Taitung County government specially invited seven international slow food activists and local slow food practitioners from Taitung County to exchange ideas on the eve of the first slow food festival this year, \u201cfrom the festival to the day, from the traditional to the contemporary. \u201d The theme is to explore how traditional food culture can be practiced in contemporary society through the Slow Food Movement, and how the international Slow Food Movement can blossom in all corners of the world through the diverse participation of citizens and community power.\nOn the agenda, Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, first introduced the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and shared the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food Presidia projects of the Slow Food movement.\nIn response to the International Year of Xiaomi 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey will introduce the Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nNazlina Spice Station in Malaysia is an introduction to the local cuisine, starting from Laksa, to the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nCommunity power is also an important theme of this forum. The Gonnay couple from the Philippines and Ramon Uy Jr will discuss how the Slow Food movement can achieve the function of cultural inheritance and food farming education through community connection from family, community, organization, market, and tourism.\nThe local representative of Taitung, ibu istanda takiscibanan of the Bunun tribe, shared the history of restoring millet in the Kandeng tribe of Haiduan Township; Guo Lijin, CEO of Jinhetang, will talk about the experience and future vision of slow food in Taitung for ten years; and many Taitung slow food chefs and shop owners will join hands to show the strength of the cohesion in the local community.\nSimultaneous real-time interpretation service is available, and people who are interested in promoting slow food are welcome to join us.\nFor details and registration, please go to\nhttps: / / www.accupass.com / go / TTSlowFoodForum\n2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum\nFrom Festivals to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary\nDate: 4 / 28 (Fri) 09: 00-16: 30\nVenue: Taitung County Government Hall\nTaitung County Government Advertisements\n# Slow Food # Taitung # International # Slow Food Movement # Italy","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:11979","uncompressed_offset":611052333,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-07T00:28:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405"},"created":"2023-04-07T01:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398":{"id":"573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c_97571398","text":"The first International Slow Food Forum was held today at the Taitung County Government Auditorium. International Slow Food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia brought experience from all over the world to promote slow food.\nWang Zhihui, deputy mayor of Taitung County, said that this year's Slow Food Festival \"Morning Table\" will be held in Taitung Forest Park on April 29 and 30.\nThe slow food movement, which has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, originated in Italy and has been promoted in Taitung for more than 10 years.\nIn the \"Taitung Slow Food Festival\" held every spring and autumn, the public and tourists pay more attention to the source of ingredients in their lives, practice environmental protection and plastic reduction, and tell new stories in the contemporary era with traditional ingredients.\nOn the eve of the first Slow Food Festival this year, the Taitung County government invited seven international Slow Food Movement advocates to exchange with local Slow Food practitioners. The theme of the forum was \u201cFrom Festival to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary \u201d.\" Flowers? \"and other issues, hoping to continue to move internationally and link the Austronesian culture.\nThe 2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum begins at 9: 00 am on the 28th. Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, introduce the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and share the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food. The Food Presidia Project.\nIn response to the International Year of Millet 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey shared the experience of the local Slow Food Festival in India with Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nIn addition, Malaysia representative Nazlina Spice Station is a local cuisine, from Laksa to talk about the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nThe ibu istanda takiscibanan, who represents the Bunun in Taitung, shares with the international community the journey of restoring millet to the Kandeng tribe in Haiduan Township, while Kuo Li-chin, CEO of Tinhetang, fully describes the experience and future vision of Slow Food in Taitung for ten years.\nInternational speakers will participate in the Taitung Slow Food Festival \u201cMorning Table \u201d held in Taitung Forest Park on the 29th and 30th, and demonstrate the traditional breakfast of Indian and Filipino aborigines on the 30th. The event is free of charge. Please refer to the full text of the forum download website (https: / / reurl.cc / pL0XvZ), and Taitung Slow Food Food Festival information (https: / / www.facebook.com / SlowFoodTaitung /).\n# International Slow Food Forum # Taitung Slow Food Festival # Taitung County Government # Slow Food Festival","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0012.json.gz:28713","uncompressed_offset":97571398,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230428003952-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-28T10:18:14.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:573bbdbd-ccb5-417f-82b3-117a2073ed1c>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230428003952-260405"},"created":"2023-04-28T10:23:35.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
