{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1018","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1018","narrative_id":"1018"},"responses":[{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"The live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films have been a prominent feature of the company's production schedule in recent years, with a slew of releases in the last 5-10 years, including Cinderella (2015), The Jungle Book (2016), Beauty and the Beast (2017), Dumbo (2019), Aladdin (2019), The Lion King (2019), Mulan (2020), Pinocchio (2022), and Little Mermaid (2023)."},{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"These remakes have been driven in part by the success of earlier live-action adaptations, such as Maleficent (2014), which demonstrated the potential for financial gain from reimagining beloved animated classics."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"The role of nostalgia in driving Disney's decisions to produce live-action remakes is significant, as the company seeks to tap into the fond memories of audiences who grew up with the original animated films."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"By reworking these classic stories with modern production values and well-known actors, Disney aims to create a sense of familiarity and nostalgia in audiences, while also introducing the stories to a new generation of viewers."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"However, the process of adapting these classic stories for contemporary audiences is not without its challenges, and changes have been made to the original stories and characters in the remakes."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"For example, the live-action remake of Aladdin (2019) featured a number of changes to the story and characters, including the addition of new characters and plotlines."},{"citations":{"e26a2d38-6a10-47fe-b438-aa9c187eabd8_852949505":1.0},"text":"The public reaction to these adaptations has been mixed, with some viewers praising the updates and others criticizing the changes to the original stories and characters."},{"citations":{"8138d416-ceaa-43d3-a92d-7ad903317f2b_769285838":1.0},"text":"The son of the original Snow White director, David Hand, has been particularly vocal in his criticism of the live-action remakes, calling the upcoming remake of Snow White a \"disgrace\" and stating that the film's portrayal of the seven dwarves is \"insulting\"."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"Despite these criticisms, Disney continues to produce live-action remakes of its classic animated films, with a number of projects currently in development, including remakes of Moana and Lilo and Stitch."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"The company's commitment to these remakes is likely driven by the financial success of earlier adaptations, such as The Lion King (2019), which grossed over $1 billion worldwide."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"However, some critics have argued that the live-action remakes are overly reliant on nostalgia, and that the company is prioritizing financial gain over artistic merit."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"John Musk, a film critic, has stated that the live-action remakes are often lacking in terms of storytelling and character development, and that the company is more focused on selling a familiar product than on creating a compelling narrative."},{"citations":{"9bf4d61e-80c6-417e-8c40-6d987236d4fb_1002818262":1.0},"text":"Despite these criticisms, the live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films continue to be a major part of the company's production schedule, and are likely to remain a prominent feature of the film landscape for years to come."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"The use of nostalgia as a driving force behind these remakes is a key factor in their success, and the company's ability to balance nostalgia with modern production values and storytelling will be crucial in determining the success of future adaptations."},{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"Overall, the live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films are a complex and multifaceted phenomenon, driven by a combination of financial, artistic, and cultural factors."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"As the company continues to produce these remakes, it will be important for them to balance the need to appeal to nostalgic audiences with the need to create compelling and engaging stories that resonate with modern viewers."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"The live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films have been a prominent feature of the company's production schedule in recent years, with a slew of releases in the last 5-10 years, including Cinderella (2015), The Jungle Book (2016), Beauty and the Beast (2017), Dumbo (2019), Aladdin (2019), The Lion King (2019), Mulan (2020), Pinocchio (2022), and Little Mermaid (2023)."},{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"These remakes have been driven in part by the success of earlier live-action adaptations, such as Maleficent (2014), which demonstrated the potential for financial gain from reimagining beloved animated classics."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"The role of nostalgia in driving Disney's decisions to produce live-action remakes is significant, as the company seeks to tap into the fond memories of audiences who grew up with the original animated films."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"By reworking these classic stories with modern production values and well-known actors, Disney aims to create a sense of familiarity and nostalgia in audiences, while also introducing the stories to a new generation of viewers."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"However, the process of adapting these classic stories for contemporary audiences is not without its challenges, and changes have been made to the original stories and characters in the remakes."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"For example, the live-action remake of Aladdin (2019) featured a number of changes to the story and characters, including the addition of new characters and plotlines."},{"citations":{"e26a2d38-6a10-47fe-b438-aa9c187eabd8_852949505":1.0},"text":"The public reaction to these adaptations has been mixed, with some viewers praising the updates and others criticizing the changes to the original stories and characters."},{"citations":{"8138d416-ceaa-43d3-a92d-7ad903317f2b_769285838":1.0},"text":"The son of the original Snow White director, David Hand, has been particularly vocal in his criticism of the live-action remakes, calling the upcoming remake of Snow White a \"disgrace\" and stating that the film's portrayal of the seven dwarves is \"insulting\"."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"Despite these criticisms, Disney continues to produce live-action remakes of its classic animated films, with a number of projects currently in development, including remakes of Moana and Lilo and Stitch."},{"citations":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":1.0},"text":"The company's commitment to these remakes is likely driven by the financial success of earlier adaptations, such as The Lion King (2019), which grossed over $1 billion worldwide."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"However, some critics have argued that the live-action remakes are overly reliant on nostalgia, and that the company is prioritizing financial gain over artistic merit."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"John Musk, a film critic, has stated that the live-action remakes are often lacking in terms of storytelling and character development, and that the company is more focused on selling a familiar product than on creating a compelling narrative."},{"citations":{"9bf4d61e-80c6-417e-8c40-6d987236d4fb_1002818262":1.0},"text":"Despite these criticisms, the live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films continue to be a major part of the company's production schedule, and are likely to remain a prominent feature of the film landscape for years to come."},{"citations":{"04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266":1.0},"text":"The use of nostalgia as a driving force behind these remakes is a key factor in their success, and the company's ability to balance nostalgia with modern production values and storytelling will be crucial in determining the success of future adaptations."},{"citations":{"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":1.0},"text":"Overall, the live-action remakes of classic animated Disney films are a complex and multifaceted phenomenon, driven by a combination of financial, artistic, and cultural factors."},{"citations":{"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":1.0},"text":"As the company continues to produce these remakes, it will be important for them to balance the need to appeal to nostalgic audiences with the need to create compelling and engaging stories that resonate with modern viewers."}],"references":["affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494","e26a2d38-6a10-47fe-b438-aa9c187eabd8_852949505","2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838","8138d416-ceaa-43d3-a92d-7ad903317f2b_769285838","9bf4d61e-80c6-417e-8c40-6d987236d4fb_1002818262","b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962","04be02f4-bf63-4cf4-a520-2859d5be0752_801436266"],"documents":{"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494":{"id":"affa62b6-3681-4651-bd81-70d2425e5fae_433916494","text":"Is Disney's Aladdin 2 Still Happening? Star Mena Massoud Remains Hopeful\n\nDisney loves a live-action remake.\u00a0The House of Mouse has discovered that instead of coming up with new ideas they can simply remake their classic animated flicks into live action.\u00a0The results have been pretty darn profitable, and the studio shows no signs of stopping \u2014 there are currently live-action remakes of \"Moana\" and \"Lilo and Stitch\" on the way. One of their successful live-action remakes was the 2019 take on \"Aladdin,\" helmed by \u2014 believe it or not \u2014\u00a0Guy Ritchie. The film was a smash, hauling in over $1 billion worldwide and going on to become the\u00a0ninth highest-grossing film of 2019.\u00a0\n\nWhen you make numbers like that, a sequel can't be far behind. Sure enough, in 2019 the film's producer,\u00a0Dan\u00a0Lin, revealed that Disney was in the early stages of developing a sequel.\u00a0But that's the last we've really heard of the potential follow-up.\u00a0The live-action \"Aladdin\" starred Will Smith as the Genie first made popular by the late Robin\u00a0Williams, while the titular role of Aladdin was played by\u00a0Mena Massoud. Massoud has seemed to cast doubt about the sequel ever happening at this point.\u00a0He most recently gave an update on the potential project late last year.\u00a0\n\nNo idea where it's at\n\nBack in March of 2023, Mena Massoud Tweeted that \"Aladdin 2\" was \"Very unlikely at this point.\" (The Tweet has since been deleted, but the folks at Collider caught it at the time). Then, in December of 2023, Massoud was promoting his horror movie \"The\u00a0Sacrifice\u00a0Game\" when ScreenRant asked him about \"Aladdin 2.\" He replied: \"I don't have any updates ... the strike kind of just put everything on hold. I know they were trying to get it off the ground for a long time but I have no idea where it's at.\" He added:\n\n\"Listen, we shot in 2017. It's been six years now since we shot and wrapped the project. So to me, at a certain point, life just goes on. So not really, I'm sure they have their reasons. I know they were trying for a long time. So I don't know what the obstacles exactly were. But maybe now after the strike is over, they'll continue to try to get it off the ground ...\u00a0But I hope, I hope definitely that it happens in some way.\"\n\nIn other words, it really doesn't sound like this sequel is happening \u2014 but you never know.\u00a0\n\nOther films\n\nA sequel wasn't the only potential \"Aladdin\" project Disney was said to be working on. In 2019, it was revealed the studio was planning a spin-off film based around\u00a0Prince Anders, a character played by Billy\u00a0Magnussen.\u00a0Disney quickly faced backlash for planning a movie around one of the only white guys in a film filled with people of color, but the studio continued to push forward.\u00a0In 2022, Magnussen said the project was still in development \u2014 but we haven't heard anything about it since.\n\nIn 2015, before the live-action \"Aladdin\" was even made, the studio also announced they were making a prequel movie called \"Genies,\" with the plan being that the film would lead into the live-action \"Aladdin.\" That never happened, and \"Genies\" was scrapped. At this point,\u00a0I wouldn't be surprised if the\u00a0\"Aladdin\" sequel or the Prince Anders spin-off were both scrapped as well. Despite the smashing success of the 2019 \"Aladdin,\" it feels like too much time has gone by to strike while the iron is hot.","url":"https://www.slashfilm.com/1517459/is-disney-aladdin-2-happening-live-action-sequel-mena-massoud-hopeful/"},"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838":{"id":"2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139_226946838","text":"Watch movies for $1\nAlerts from Kinoafisha\nSoon at the box office of Claustrophobes.\nValley of the Devil 1\nWe remind you about the release of your favorite premieres and main news directly in the browser!\nMenus\nYour tickets in your personal account\nBack to the old: 9 Disney game remakes that are in development right now\nAs practice shows, nostalgia sells well.\nAt the moment, Disney is developing a lot of animated remakes, including with live actors.\nThis is not surprising given the success of the recent rework of their classic animated films.\nIt seems that Disney will continue to explore the genre and offer unique interpretations of favorite projects.\nPeter Pan and Wendy\nRelease date: 2022\nThe remake of the new \u201cPeter Pan \u201d was directed by David Lowry, who previously worked on the film adaptation of\u201c Pete and his dragon \u201d in 2016.\nIt is reported that the shooting of the project has already been completed, but the exact date has not yet been announced.\nIt is known that the basis of the film \u201cPeter Pan and Wendy \u201d is the original story about a boy who did not want to become an adult, and the magical country of Neverland.\nThe exact date of the premiere of the project has not yet been announced, but is expected in the second half of 2022.\nPinocchio\nRelease date: September 8, 2022\nThe animated film \u201cPinocchio \u201d with live action was shot by Robert Zemeckis according to his own script in collaboration with Chris Weitz.\nThe Wooden Boy was originally voiced by Benjamin Evan Ainsworth.\nIts creator, Gepetto, was played by Tom Hanks.\nAlso in the remake took part Cynthia Erivo, Luke Evans and others.\nThe premiere of the fantasy musical is scheduled for September 8, 2022.\nNot only Disney: 8 amazing cartoons that are worthy of a game remake\nLittle Mermaid\nRelease date: May 26, 2023\nAbout the rethinking of the \u201cLittle Mermaid \u201d rumors have been around for a long time, and after the announcement of the actress for the main role, dark-skinned Holly Bailey, fierce disputes began.\nNevertheless, the film adaptation decided to finish and announced the premiere date - May 26, 2023.\nThe plot will tell the original story of a mermaid who fell in love with an earthly prince and asked the witch for legs to please him.\nThe beloved underwater princess in the film adaptation was played by actor John Hauer-King.\nSnow White and the Seven Dwarfs\nRelease date: 2023\nThe exact date of the premiere of the remake of \"Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs\" has not yet been announced.\nThe story is taken from the fairy tale of the Brothers Grimm, and adapted by screenwriter Greta Gerwig.\nThe project is directed by Mark Webb.\nThe role of the beauty of Snow White will be played by Rachel Zegler, and the evil witch will be embodied on the screen by the vander woman Gal Gadot.\nThe premiere is expected presumably in 2023.\nHercules\nRelease date: not announced\nThe director of the film adaptation of \u201cHercules \u201d will be the author of\u201c Gentlemen \u201d Guy Ritchie.\nHe will direct a full-length film with live actors based on the 1997 cartoon.\nThe script was adapted by the author of \u201cShan-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings \u201d Dave Callham.\nThe cast of the film about the adventures of Hercules on Olympus has not yet been officially announced.\nIt is reported that the musical accompaniment of the picture will work Alan Mencken, the author of the compositions \u201cThe Little Mermaid \u201d,\u201c Aladdin \u201d and other cartoons.\nBambi\nRelease date: not announced\nThe film \"Bambi\" about a deer who is forced to learn to live independently in the forest after the death of his mother, will be created using computer technology.\nThe story is taken from the eponymous film adaptation of 1942.\nPreviously, similar technologies were used in the remake of The Lion King by John Favreau.\nGen\u00e8ve Robertson-Dworet and Lindsay Beer will be scripted, and the director will be announced later.\nThe date of the premiere is not yet known.\nHunchback\nRelease date: not announced\nWork began on a reimagining of the cartoon \"Hunchback of Notre Dame\" in 1996.\nThe story, taken as the basis of the original and remake, was written by Victor Hugo in the novel \u201cNotre Dame de Paris \u201d.\nThe remake will be playable, but the cast has not yet been announced.\nAlso, the director \u2019 s chair is not yet occupied, and David Henry Hwang is already working on the script.\nThe date of the premiere has not yet been announced.\nThe Sword in the Stone\nRelease date: December 13, 2024\nThe 1963 film adaptation based on the legends of King Arthur will also receive a new adaptation.\nDirected by Juan Carlos Fresnadillo.\nThe start of production of the new \u201cSword in the Stone \u201d started back in 2018, but due to financial problems it had to be suspended.\nIt is reported that due to the small budget of the picture, the project will be released exclusively for the Disney + streaming service.\nThere is no information yet about the actors who will take part in the film adaptation.\nThe project will be released on December 13, 2024.\nRobin Hood\nRelease date: not announced\n\"Robin Hood\" will get a hybrid version with live actors for the Disney + platform.\nIn development is a remake of the animated classic of 1976 with director Carlos Lopez Estrada at the head.\nCGI technologies will be used in the project.\nAbout the casting, the potential release date and other details are not yet known.\nThe script will be written by Kari Granlund, who previously worked on the remake of Lady and the Tramps.\nQuality binge watching: the best HBO series Read more 20 July 2022\nLife after Hogwarts: 14 roles, thanks to which Radcliffe ceased to be Harry Potter Read more 23 July 2022\nNot only Disney: 8 stunning cartoons that are worthy of a game remake Read more 24 July 2022\nEyes on the forehead climb: 9 strange fan theories about \"Twilight\" Read more 23 July 2022\nMore than any psychotraining: 7 new inspiring films about finding yourself Read more 25 July 2022\nTest: only a real superhero will guess 11 of the 11 Marvel movies in just one frame Read more 23 July 2022\nAlexander Gorbatov shares a personal list of his favorite films and TV series specifically for the Movie poster Read more 25 July 2022\n\u201cWhy did you bring me this freak \u201d: find out why these 12 popular actors were refused Read more 26 July 2022\nIvan Makarevich talks about the best series about love and about the Russian show, which is worth showing to the whole world Read more 25 July 2022\n7 new films shot in mysterious St. Petersburg, which are worth watching Read more 24 July 2022\n17 most viewed TV series of the first half of the year, which can already be found on the network Read more 25 July 2022\nRelated video","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0022.json.gz:137803","uncompressed_offset":226946838,"url":"www.kinoafisha.info/news/snova-za-staroe-9-igrovyh-remeykov-disney-kotorye-nahodyatsya-v-razrabotke-pryamo-seychas/","warc_date":"2022-07-27T00:04:08.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2b7b6721-9b08-432c-b318-1f57bf8a8139>","warc_url":"https://www.kinoafisha.info/news/snova-za-staroe-9-igrovyh-remeykov-disney-kotorye-nahodyatsya-v-razrabotke-pryamo-seychas/"},"created":"2022-07-27T00:20:05.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e26a2d38-6a10-47fe-b438-aa9c187eabd8_852949505":{"id":"e26a2d38-6a10-47fe-b438-aa9c187eabd8_852949505","text":"The upcoming live-action remake of Disney\u2019s Moana will have a few new parts, including a director as the film has tapped Thomas Kail \u2014 a Tony Award-winning director for his work on Hamilton \u2014 to direct the film.\n\nThe Hollywood Reporter broke the story that Kail will helm the live-action Moana film. The project was announced earlier this spring and we know that Dwayne Johnson \u2014 who voiced Maui in the animated film \u2014 will return as the demigod in the film. He will also be producing via Seven Bucks Productions along with Dany Garcia, Hiram Garcia, and Beau Flynn (via Flynn Picture Co.). Jared Bush \u2014 the animated film\u2019s screenwriter \u2014 wrote the remake\u2019s script with Dana Ledoux Miller.\n\nWhile Johnson is returning, Kail won\u2019t be the only newcomer. It was also recently announced that Auli\u2019i Cravalho would not be returning as Moana via a post from the actor\u2019s Instagram (though she remains a producer).\n\nLive and breathe sports?\n\n\ud83d\udea8 Get viral graphics, memes, rumors and trending sports news delivered right to your inbox with the Clutch Newsletter.\n\nThomas Kail is an accomplished theatre director in his own right and should have no issue translating Moana from animated to live-action form. He won a Tony Award for Best Direction of a Musical in 2016 for Hamilton. However, his roots with Lin-Manuel Miranda go back even further, as Kail\u2019s first director credit in theater is for In the Heights. He has also directed Hamilton for its filmed recording for Disney+ and has a couple of feature films in the works including Silver Wings and another Fiddler on the Roof adaptation.\n\nMoana was a huge hit for Disney in 2016. It currently stands as the fourth highest-grossing film from Walt Disney Animation Studios ($248,757,044) and the film grossed a whopping $643,331,111 worldwide during its theatrical run. While the live-action remakes have varied in quality, Disney\u2019s likely just hoping for the financial success that even The Little Mermaid brought.","url":"https://clutchpoints.com/moana-news-hamilton-in-the-heights-director-to-direct-live-action-remake"},"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962":{"id":"b0cdad92-634f-4d6e-b764-f694603e164e_943700962","text":"Skip to Content\n\nA Definitive List of All the Disney Live-Action Films\n\nFrom Halle Bailey\u2019s Little Mermaid to the live-action Moana to sequels galore.\n\nBy Delia Paunescu and Amy Mackelden\n\nMost of us grew up watching Disney movies, and for better or worse, we wondered what it might be like to be a Disney princess. In recent years, Disney has cleverly played into that nostalgia by transforming its classic animations into live-action movies filled with some of Hollywood\u2019s biggest stars. Following the success of big-budget adaptations like Beauty and the Beast and The Lion King, Disney has committed to turning the majority of its animated catalog into cinematic treats. From Angelina Jolie\u2019s star turn in Maleficent to the upcoming live-action version of Moana, fans will be spoiled for choice. Here, we round up all of Disney\u2019s live-action movie adaptations to date, as well as some of the rumors about what\u2019s to come.\n\n1\n\nMaleficent (2014)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDisney's Maleficent - Official Trailer 3\nWatch on\n\nLoosely based on Sleeping Beauty, Angelina Jolie\u2019s wicked witch arrived when lots of evil queens were getting their own feature films (Remember Charlize Theron in Snow White and the Huntsman?). Elle Fanning\u2019s turn as Princess Aurora put her on the map as an A-lister to watch. The film even launched a Maleficent makeup collaboration with M.A.C., which we adored.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO\n\n2\n\nCinderella (2015)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDisney's Cinderella Official US Trailer\nWatch on\n\nDisney\u2019s dreamy live action remake of Cinderella cast Cate Blanchett as the evil stepmother, with Bodyguard star Richard Madden playing the Prince. When she landed the title role, Lily James\u2019 most significant part had been as a rebellious cousin on Downton Abbey. Naturally, the fairytale brought James worldwide recognition (and she went on to play young Meryl Streep in Mamma Mia 2).\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO\n\n3\n\nThe Jungle Book (2016)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nThe Jungle Book Official Big Game Trailer\nWatch on\n\nThe original Jungle Book features some of the best music in Disney\u2019s catalog, so director Jon Favreau\u2019s 2016 live-action remake had a lot to live up to. Newcomer Neel Sethi masterfully took on the part of the boy trying to stay alive with a vengeful Shere Khan hunting him down.\n\nA sequel has reportedly been in the works since Jungle Book was released, with Favreau rumored to be returning as director, according to The Hollywood Reporter.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+ WATCH ON PRIME VIDEO\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n4\n\nBeauty and the Beast (2017)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nBeauty and the Beast \u2013 US Official Final Trailer\nWatch on\n\nFew Disney remakes were more anticipated than Beauty and the Beast. It was lavish in its production, starring Emma Watson as Belle and Dan Stevens as an all-too-human Beast. Supporting cast members like Stanley Tucci, Emma Thompson, Audra McDonald, and Ewan McGregor were exceptional as the castle staff.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO WATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n5\n\nChristopher Robin (2018)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nChristopher Robin Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nHonestly, it feels like this movie came and went without anyone, besides die-hard Winnie the Pooh fans, paying much attention. It\u2019s a shame, really, because Ewan McGregor is endearing in the grown-up title role and the Hundred Acre Woods\u2019 animal pals are as warmly fuzzy as you\u2019d hope.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO WATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n6\n\nMary Poppins Returns (2018)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nMary Poppins Returns | Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nEmily Blunt steps into Julie Andrews\u2019 cape and brings the magical nanny to life once more. The Devil Wears Prada darling did a terrific job, and was nominated for a Golden Globe as a result. Anyone who grew up loving the cheerily psychedelic musical numbers is bound to appreciate Hamilton star Lin-Manuel Miranda as lamplighter Jack. As if Mary Poppins Returns couldn't get any better, Meryl Streep, Dick Van Dyke, Julie Walters, and Angela Lansbury are also all in the film.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+ WATCH ON AMAZON PRIME\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n7\n\nDumbo (2019)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDumbo Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nDumbo remains one of the most upsetting stories in Disney\u2019s roster, and 2019\u2019s live-action remake will give you all of the feels. Directed by Tim Burton and starring Colin Farrell, Michael Keaton, and Danny DeVito, Dumbo re-tells the emotional story of a young elephant with the gift of flight, who finds himself embroiled in some circus drama.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO WATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n8\n\nAladdin (2019)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDisney's Aladdin - \"Connection\" TV Spot\nWatch on\n\nFans were desperate to find out who had been cast in the live-action Aladdin, no doubt because the original movie is so beloved. While Mena Massoud took on the title role, Power Rangers star Naomi Scott transformed into Princess Jasmine. And of course, Will freaking Smith did his very best to fill Robin Williams\u2019 iconic lamp as the Genie.\n\nIn 2020, it was revealed that a sequel is in the works, via Deadline. Plus, a spin-off featuring Prince Anders is also in development.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO WATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n9\n\nThe Lion King (2019)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nThe Lion King Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nThe all-star remake of The Lion King might be the most important thing the house of the mouse has done since they released the original Lion King in 1994. This live-action version cast none other than Beyonc\u00e9 herself as Nala. She stars alongside Donald Glover as Simba, and Billy Eichner and Seth Rogen as Timon and Pumbaa, with James Earl Jones reprising his original role as Mufasa. A sequel (or prequel) is on the way.\n\nWATCH ON PRIME VIDEO WATCH ON DISNEY+\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n10\n\nMaleficent: Mistress of Evil (2019)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nMALEFICENT 2: MISTRESS OF EVIL Official Trailer #2 (2019) Angelina Jolie, Disney Movie HD\nWatch on\n\nAngela Jolie and Elle Fanning returned for the follow-up to 2014\u2019s Maleficent. Jolie\u2019s character continues to wrestle with people\u2019s perception of her as a villain, while Princess Aurora receives a marriage proposal, much to Maleficent\u2019s chagrin. Meanwhile, an endangered species known as the Dark Fae start to rise up.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n11\n\nLady and the Tramp (2019)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nLady and the Tramp | Official Trailer | Disney+ | Streaming November 12\nWatch on\n\n1955\u2019s canine couple du jour were given a live-action/animation hybrid update, which debuted on Disney+ in 2019. Justin Theroux voiced the scampy Tramp and Tessa Thompson played the elegant Lady in this animal romance. Thompson\u2019s BFF Janelle Mon\u00e1e, and Kiersey Clemons round out the cast of this cute remake.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n12\n\nMulan (2020)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDisney's Mulan | Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nDisney casting directors had their job cut out for them with Mulan, reportedly spending a year auditioning nearly 1,000 actresses for the lead. The part ultimately went to Chinese superstar Liu Yifei. Fans finally saw the 31-year-old in full character thanks to this arresting first image. Director Niki Caro told the Hollywood Reporter: \u201cIt\u2019s a big, girly martial arts epic. It will be extremely muscular and thrilling and entertaining and moving.\u201d What more do you need to know?\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+ WATCH ON PRIME VIDEO\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n13\n\nCruella (2021)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nDisney's Cruella | Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nAnyone else think Cruella was woefully misunderstood? Enter 2021\u2019s Cruella, which tells the story of 101 Dalmatians\u2019 villainous diva before she became, well, fully evil. The inimitable Emma Stone won the lead role, infusing the tale with \u201980s punk chic. From the eye-catching costumes to the super cute puppies, Disney\u2019s origin story has everything. A sequel is reportedly in the works.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+ WATCH ON PRIME VIDEO\n\n14\n\nPinocchio (2022)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nPinocchio Trailer #2 (2022)\nWatch on\n\nTom Hanks as Geppetto? Say no more. It may be 80 years later, but this live-action remake is just as relevant today as the original was upon its release. Joseph Gordon-Levitt gives a heartfelt performance as Jiminy Cricket, and Pinnochio\u2019s journey to becoming a real boy is brought to life in stunning visuals.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+\n\n15\n\nPeter Pan & Wendy (2023)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nPeter Pan & Wendy | Official Trailer | Disney+\nWatch on\n\nThere have been numerous adaptations of J. M. Barrie\u2019s iconic story, but Disney promises to delight fans of its 1953 animated classic with the live-action Peter Pan & Wendy. After meeting Peter Pan, Wendy (Ever Anderson) embarks on an adventure to Neverland, where she faces up to Captain Hook. A story that truly never gets old.\n\nWATCH ON DISNEY+\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n16\n\nThe Little Mermaid (2023)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nThe Little Mermaid | Official Trailer\nWatch on\n\nAriel\u2019s story of thirst-trapping Prince Eric, after selling her voice to that glorious diva Ursula in exchange for human legs, is ripe for a remake, especially given the 1998 original\u2019s fishy gender dynamics. Halle Bailey wows in the lead role, with Melissa McCarthy embodying sea witch Ursula. Lin-Manuel Miranda wrote new songs for the flick, alongside Disney musical genius Alan Menken.\n\nThe Little Mermaid hits theaters on May 26, 2023.\n\nWATCH THE ORIGINAL ON DISNEY+\n\n17\n\nSnow White (2024)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nRachel Zegler and Gal Gadot on 'Snow White' | D23 2022 | Entertainment Weekly\nWatch on\n\nDisney is bringing its live-action magic to 1937 animation Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs. While Rachel Zegler will take the lead as Snow White, Gal Gadot has been cast as the Evil Queen. With Greta Gerwig tapped to write the screenplay, we can expect Snow White to be all kinds of wonderful.\n\nSnow White is set to hit theaters on March 22, 2024, per Deadline.\n\nWATCH THE ORIGINAL ON DISNEY+\n\n18\n\nMoana (TBD)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nLive-Action Moana Announcement\nWatch on\n\nIn April 2023, it was announced that Moana (which was just released in 2016) would be getting the live-action treatment, with Dwayne Johnson reprising his role as demigod Maui. The original voice of Moana, Auli\u2018i Cravalho, has signed on as an executive producer. Johnson said in a statement, \u201cThis story is my culture, and this story is emblematic of our people\u2019s grace and warrior strength.\u201d The release date is currently unknown.\n\nWATCH THE ORIGINAL ON DISNEY+\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n19\n\nLilo & Stitch (TBD)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\nLilo & Stitch (2002) Trailer #1 | Movieclips Classic Trailers\nWatch on\n\nA live-action/CG hybrid remake of the supremely adorable 2002 film about a Hawaiian girl and the alien who befriends her was first announced in October 2018. It is being produced by Dan Lin and Jonathan Eirich, who were also tasked with the Aladdin remake. A release date is up in the air but it\u2019s possible this will debut on Disney\u2019s upcoming streaming service. The cast includes Zach Galifianakis, Courtney B. Vance, and newcomer Maia Kealoha as Lilo, per The Hollywood Reporter.\n\nWATCH THE ORIGINAL ON DISNEY+\n\n20\n\nHercules (TBD)\n\nThis content is imported from youTube. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.\n1997 Hercules Official Trailer 1 Walt Disney Pictures\nWatch on\n\nIn June 2022, Deadline reported that Aladdin director Guy Ritchie had signed on to direct the live-action remake of Hercules. The 1997 animate feature retold the legend of demigod Hercules, who was voiced by Tate Donovan. While details on the remake remain scarce, Hercules is certainly one to watch for Disney fans.\n\nWATCH THE ORIGINAL ON DISNEY+\n\nDelia Paunescu\n\nDelia Paunescu is a writer, producer, and social media consultant based in New York City. She's written for Vulture, Racked, Brooklyn Magazine, New York Post, and amNewYork, among others. Delia also spent two years leading NowThis Entertainment. She'd very much like to shout at you about why Jane the Virgin is the greatest show of all time\u00a0over on Twitter.\u00a0\n\nAmy Mackelden is a freelance writer, editor, and disability activist. Her bylines include Harper's BAZAAR, Nicki Swift, Cosmopolitan, Marie Claire, ELLE, The Independent, Bustle, Healthline, and HelloGiggles. She co-edited The Emma Press Anthology of Illness, and previously spent all of her money on Kylie Cosmetics.\n\nWatch Next\n\u00a0\n\nMovies & TV 2023\n\nPriya Kansara Went From Health Care to Hollywood\n\nWhat We Know About 'Red, White & Royal Blue'\n\nCara Delevingne Joins Kim Kardashian in 'AHS'\n\nMelissa Barrera Knows What She Wants\n\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\nAdvertisement - Continue Reading Below\n\nA Part of Hearst Digital Media\n\nWe may earn commission from links on this page, but we only recommend products we back.\n\n\u00a9Hearst Magazine Media, Inc. All Rights Reserved.\n\nPrivacy NoticeCA Notice at CollectionYour CA Privacy Rights/Shine the LightDAA Industry Opt OutTerms of UseSite Map","url":"https://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/g25474442/all-disney-live-action-movies/"},"8138d416-ceaa-43d3-a92d-7ad903317f2b_769285838":{"id":"8138d416-ceaa-43d3-a92d-7ad903317f2b_769285838","text":"Snow White director\u2019s son calls Disney remake a \u201cdisgrace\u201d\n\nDisney\n\nThe original Snow White director\u2019s son has slammed the upcoming Disney remake as \u201cinsulting\u201d and a \u201cdisgrace.\u201d\n\nDisney has recently recreated several of its classic films into live-action adaptations. Past examples include The Little Mermaid, Dumbo, and Pinocchio. However, these recreations have generated backlash for various reasons.\n\nFor example, Halle Bailey\u2019s role as Ariel wasn\u2019t universally agreed upon. This is due to haters complaining that the princess should have been white like in the 1989 animated movie.\n\nArticle continues after ad\n\nNow, the upcoming remake of Disney\u2019s Snow White starring Rachel Zegler has been under fire for its controversial portrayal of the seven dwarves among other reasons. Here\u2019s what the son of the original Snow White director had to say about the film.\n\nSon of Snow White director criticizes upcoming Disney remake\n\nIn an interview with The Telegraph, David Hand, who worked as a Disney designer in the 1990s, admitted his negative feelings toward the Snow White remake. Hand\u2019s father, also named David, served as one of the directors of the 1937 film.\n\nArticle continues after ad\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s a whole different concept and I just totally disagree with it, and I know my dad and Walt would also very much disagree with it,\u201d 91-year-old Hand said. He continued by calling the movie a \u201cdisgrace\u201d and discussed Disney\u2019s \u201cradical thoughts.\u201d\n\n\u201cThey\u2019re making up new woke things and I\u2019m just not into any of that. I find it quite frankly a bit insulting [what] they may have done with some of these classic films,\u201d Hand remarked. \u201cThere\u2019s no respect for what Disney did and what my dad did. \u2026 I think Walt and he would be turning in their graves.\u201d\n\nArticle co