8921":1.0},"text":"To observe benefits, it is recommended to practice balance workouts, such as Tai Chi, one to two times a week."},{"citations":{"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":1.0},"text":"Tai Chi has been found to improve motor coordination, reduce muscle strain, and enhance overall physical stability."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"The sport also has a positive effect on the nervous system and can help relieve pressure on the intervertebral discs."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Overall, the scientific evidence suggests that Tai Chi is a effective method for reducing falls and improving physical stability in older adults."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"A physical therapist can also design a specialized treatment program to help individuals reduce their risk of falls, which may include exercises such as Tai Chi or yoga."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"By staying active and practicing exercises like Tai Chi, older adults can minimize the effects of aging on their balance and reduce their risk of falls."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"More than 4,000 participants were involved in 17 studies that looked at the effectiveness of fall-prevention exercises, including Tai Chi."}],"references":["184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782","80c8da15-5fa3-4f38-8fa6-3c8ddc7d04f2_904596165","2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624","08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184","eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921"],"documents":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":{"id":"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782","text":"Exercise programs meant to prevent falls in seniors may also help prevent injuries caused by falls, according to a new review.\n\nFall-related injuries are common among seniors and a major cause of long-term pain and disability. They also increase the risk of having to go to a nursing home and have a high economic cost.\n\nThe new findings, published online Oct. 29 in the journal bmj.com, suggest that \"reducing the risk of falling and improving protective responses during a fall may be an important and feasible means of preventing fractures and other serious injuries in the elderly,\" the study authors wrote in a journal news release.\n\nWell-designed exercise programs can prevent falls in seniors living at home, but there is a lack of evidence on whether such programs can help prevent fall-related injuries, said French researchers Fabienne El-Khoury and colleagues.\n\nIn this review, they analyzed 17 studies that looked at whether fall-prevention exercises lowered seniors' risk of fractures and other injuries caused by falls. More than 4,000 participants were involved in all.\n\nTai Chi was the exercise in two of the studies, but most of them used gait, balance, strength and functional training, which involves workouts that help people do normal daily activities.\n\nMost of the programs reduced fall-related injuries and appeared to significantly curb falls that lead to fractures, serious injuries and medical care.\n\nBalance training was emphasized in all of the exercises that were effective in preventing falls, the researchers noted.\n\nMore information\n\nThe U.S. National Institute on Aging has more about older adults and falls.\n\nLatest videos","url":"https://www.newsday.com/news/health/balance-training-seems-to-prevent-falls-by-elderly-w61786"},"80c8da15-5fa3-4f38-8fa6-3c8ddc7d04f2_904596165":{"id":"80c8da15-5fa3-4f38-8fa6-3c8ddc7d04f2_904596165","text":"Health \u00b7 Life\nHow to prevent falls in the winter? Scientific exercise helps reduce risk\nDecember 10, 2021 16: 06 Source: People 's Daily Online\nFor older people, falling is no small thing.\nAccording to the official micro-news of the China CDC, the low temperature in winter affects the physical activity of the elderly.\nRain and snow are common, and the ground is slippery and slippery to increase the risk of falls in the elderly\nThe China CDC reminds every elderly person and caregiver of the elderly to take the initiative to prevent elderly people from falling.\nThe Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention pointed out that scientific exercise can help reduce the risk of falls and fractures in the elderly, and the elderly do not break their exercise habits in winter and holidays, and can be replaced by indoor exercise when the weather is bad.\nWhen the elderly exercise, under the premise of ensuring safety, attention should be paid to strengthening functional exercise such as balance ability, muscle strength and endurance.\nFor example, Taijiquan, Baduanjin and other sports can be carried out, and there are some small moves to strengthen exercise for preventing elderly people from falling.\nFamilies are a common place for falls among the elderly.\nThe Chinese CDC suggests that the home environment can be adapted for aging.\nFor example, the ground anti-skid treatment, in the toilet, toilet, stairs and other positions to install handrails, remove the indoor floor height difference, improve indoor lighting and lighting, night can use night lights, replace the height and soft and hard uncomfortable sofa, etc., remove the indoor will hinder the elderly moving items.\nIn addition, the rain and snow weather elderly should be minimized to go out.\nWhen the elderly go out, it is necessary to slow down the pace of walking, wear anti-skid shoes, don't put your hands in your pockets, and use a walking stick when necessary.\nTo choose a flat ground, few obstacles, handrails, good light road to walk.\nWhen going up and down stairs, rolling stairs and steps, it is necessary to walk slowly and stand firmly.\n(Editor: Sun Hongli, Lu Qian)\nRelated News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0036.json.gz:3135","uncompressed_offset":904596165,"url":"health.people.com.cn/n1/2021/1210/c14739-32305014.html","warc_date":"2021-12-10T09:25:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:80c8da15-5fa3-4f38-8fa6-3c8ddc7d04f2>","warc_url":"http://health.people.com.cn/n1/2021/1210/c14739-32305014.html"},"created":"2021-12-10T10:25:08.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":{"id":"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624","text":"Learn about the sport of Tai Chi\nThe German health centre says Tai Chi is a centuries-old Chinese martial art, also known as shadow boxing.\nIt combines physical training, self-defense and meditation.\nThe focus of Tai Chi is on body tightening, mental alertness and breathing, the center explained, noting that motor training consists of a series of traditional Chinese physical exercises that flow smoothly with each other in order to achieve harmony between body and soul.\nMuscle and Joint Stimulation\nIn this way all the muscles, tendons, joints and bones are stimulated and stretched in a gentle way.\nThe upright position of the back during exercise creates a stretching effect in the spine, relieving pressure on the intervertebral discs.\nThe nervous system is also positively affected by the gentle posture of the back.\nStudies have suggested that tai chi reduces the risk of falls in older adults thanks to its ability to improve their balance.\nThe sport also has a positive effect on degenerative arthritis, the symptoms of which are knee stiffness, pain and swelling.\nImprove lung function\nTai chi is also beneficial for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) as it improves lung function.\nIt is also useful for patients with Parkinson \u2019 s, which affects the nervous system and its symptoms are disorders of movement, tremor of the hands, stiffness and instability of the body position, where sports contribute to improving balance and mobility.\nIn addition, tai chi improves the cognitive functioning of the brain, making it also useful for dementia patients.\nOn the other hand, slow flowing movements have a relaxing and meditative effect, helping to feel relaxed, calm and psychologically comfortable.\nSource: German","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:18937","uncompressed_offset":437053624,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/health/2024/4/16/%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A7%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%8A","warc_date":"2024-04-16T18:28:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/health/2024/4/16/%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A7%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%8A?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-04-16T18:55:44.000Z","lang":"eng"},"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":{"id":"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921","text":"7 Exercises Necessary for Perfect Balance\nBalance is your ability to coordinate and control your body \u2019 s center of gravity \u2013 in everyday life you have to deal with this all the time!\nFor example, your balance ensures that you can walk without falling.\n(Illustrated - Gettyimages)\nAlthough it may not occur to you, you need a good balance to do almost everything, including walking, getting up from a chair and bending over to tie your shoes.\nBalance training involves doing muscle-strengthening exercises that help keep you upright, including your legs and torso as these types of exercises can improve stability and help prevent falls.\nAnd while there are intense balancing exercises like some very challenging yoga poses, others are as simple as standing on one leg for a few seconds.\nIf you have a problem with this, you can use equipment that forces your body to stabilize, such as a semi-circular stability ball.\nMeaning of Balance\nBalance is your ability to coordinate and control your body \u2019 s center of gravity \u2013 in everyday life you have to deal with this all the time!\nFor example, your balance ensures that you can walk without falling, that you can sit up straight, and that you can jump over a hole without falling.\nYour body uses different systems: your eyes (the visual system) help you see the space around you, your inner ear (the vestibular system) records rotating movements and accelerations, and the receptors in your joints and muscles and the pressure receptors in your skin (together the stimulus receptor system) transmit changes in your posture.\nAll the stimuli your body receives through these systems come together in your central nervous system, and your brain in turn sends the message to your muscles that adapt immediately to prevent you from falling; all this has to happen at lightning speed and that \u2019 s what it should be, as our bodies have to adapt constantly as we move.\nWith the help of balanced training, you can teach your muscles to respond more quickly to brain messages as this allows you to improve fine motor and coordination skills.\nAreas targeted by balance\n\u2022 Middle: Yes, balance exercises target this area, you need strong core muscles to achieve good balance, many stability exercises work to exercise the abdominal muscles and other core muscles.\n\u2022 Forearms: No, balance exercises do not target these ends, most balance exercises revolve around balance on your feet.\nLegs: Yes, the legs are definitely areas where balance is targeted, and exercises in which you balance on one leg and then squat or lean forward also work to exercise the leg muscles.\nButtock: Yes, the same balance exercises that work on the legs also work to strengthen the buttocks.\nBack: Another area targeted by balance exercises, where your core muscles include some of your back muscles.\nGood balance depends on:\nSensory information from your eyes (visual system), muscles, tendons, joints (stimulation inputs), and balance organs in the inner ear (vestibular system).\nThe brain stem understands all of this sensory information combined with other parts of the brain.\nMovement of your eyes to keep things stable in your vision and maintain your balance.\nWhat are the benefits of balance training?\nThe benefits of balance training are great, for example:\n\u2022 You can improve your posture and you can stand or sit better.\n\u2022 Train your deep muscles, especially the muscles in the torso and around the spine.\n\u2022 Reduce back wear and less muscle pain due to poor posture.\nPrevent injuries during exercise and in daily life because your body is not constantly out of balance, causing muscle strain.\n\u2022 Ability to perform movements more efficiently and smoothly.\nA positive effect on how your body feels and your performance improves as you make faster progress.\n\u2022 Improve the motor coordination of the body.\nHow often do you have to do this type of training?\nYou have to aim to do balance workouts one to two times a week, this applies to beginners all the way to advanced athletes, and it is very important that professionals improve their stability as well.\nSimple exercises to get the perfect balance:\nTai Chi (Tai Chi)\nStudies show that tai chi, a gentle exercise often called \u201cmovement meditation, \u201d can help you reduce falls if you \u2019 re older and have balance problems, a skilled teacher can show you slow and precise movements that help you not only achieve more stability but also boost your overall health and mood as well.\nStanding on one leg (one-legged stand)\nStart by installing yourself on the back of the chair or any other sturdy handle.\nRaise one foot to approximately calf level and hold for 10 seconds.\n\u2022 Repeat this 10-15 times and then move on to the other leg.\nAs time goes on and your balance improves you may be able to continue in this situation without fixating yourself on any purpose.\nWeight Shifts (Weight Shifts)\nStand with your feet spaced by the width of your hip.\nSlowly lean forward horizontally on one leg to bear all your weight while lifting the other leg off the ground.\n\u2022 Wait for up to 30 seconds, then move to the other side.\nYou can do the same exercise while standing straight and raising one leg forward or left / right.\n\u2022 Yoga and Pilates\nTo maintain your balance, you need muscles that can hold you while standing, walking, or doing other movements. These muscles are known as your \u201ccore muscles. \u201d Yoga and Pilates involve movements that help you stretch and strengthen these muscles, but first consult your doctor before starting and to learn the movements correctly it is a good idea to join a nearby class taught by a certified instructor.\nHeel-to-Toe Walk\nWalk slowly in a straight line.\n\u2022 Touch your heel to the opposite toe as you progress.\nWalk about 20 steps using the wall for support if you feel unsteady.\nBack Leg Raises (Back Leg Raises)\nTo build up the lower back and buttocks, try raising your back leg while standing upright.\nHold a chair and lift one of your legs back without bending your knee or pointing your toe.\n\u2022 Keep the leg on the floor slightly bent.\n\u2022 Hold position for 5 seconds.\nDo this 10-15 times with the first leg before moving on to the other leg.\n\u2022 Squats (squats)\nTo strengthen the muscles of your legs and pelvis, do a squat exercise.\nStand up straight, make your feet slightly wider than your hips while pointing your toes forward.\nBend your knees and send your ass back, and slowly descend as if you were sitting.\nPlace your weight on your heels and arms in front of you or on your thighs.\nRaise yourself once and repeat 10 times.\nTo get a better idea of how strong your balance is while standing, lift one foot and see how long you can keep it there, or test your balance as you move and try to walk as if you were on a tightrope for 10 steps and see how it goes, you \u2019 ve probably noticed that one side is much stronger and more coordinated than the other.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0026.json.gz:63859","uncompressed_offset":331358921,"url":"www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/09/09/7-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B6%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A","warc_date":"2023-09-13T10:18:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923>","warc_url":"https://www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/09/09/7-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B6%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A"},"created":"2023-09-13T10:34:05.000Z","lang":"eng"},"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":{"id":"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184","text":"Healthy aging comes with challenges. For a variety of reasons, as each year passes, the likelihood of falling increases.\n\nAccording to Dr. Boris Goralnik, a geriatric specialist at UPMC in North Central Pa, a fall is defined as an unexpected event in which a person comes to rest on the ground, floor, or a lower level.\n\n\u201cFalls result in fall-related injuries, progression of gait impairments, loss of independence, depression,\u201d Goralnik said. \u201cIt is a leading cause of injury-related morbidity and mortality among older adults.\u201d\n\nBy preventing falls, providers try to prevent related injuries such as fractures, hematomas, and skin lacerations. From practice and literature, said Goralnik, the most important risk factor of falls is a previous history of falls.\n\nAccording to Janine Fee, MS, MPT, a physical therapist who is certified in vestibular rehabilitation at Evangelical Community Hospital, physical balance, which is important to avoid falling, can be complicated.\n\n\u201cI like to use the analogy of a baseball field,\u2019\u2019 Fee said. \u201cEvery player on the field is important and if a player is not working, then your team \u2014 your balance \u2014 is going to be impacted.\u201d\n\nFee said many systems have a direct impact on balance. Eyes, ears, sense of touch \u2014 especially with our feet, muscle strength, flexibility, and posture are a few. And, the brain can have a major impact on our ability to avoid falling.\n\nFee said any weakening of one or more of these areas will significantly increase the risk of falling.\n\nAccording to the Centers for Disease Control website, one out of four seniors over the age of 65 will fall each year. One out of five of those falls will cause serious injuries such as broken bones or head injuries.\n\n\u201cThis can then lead to serious consequences that may significantly impact a person\u2019s overall quality of life,\u201d said Fee. \u201cEven if the fall didn\u2019t cause harm, it is likely that the person now develops a fear of falling.\u201d\n\nMany factorsIn many cases, Goralnik said, falls and fall-related injuries lead to substantial deficiency in activities of daily living and the need for supportive care for older adults. He agreed with Fee that a fear of falling leads to things like not participating in activities that require balance, causing weaknesses and furthering the risk of repeated falls. Paying attention to the body and being more aware of areas contributing to balance is a big step in preventing falls.\n\nAge alone should not be blamed as a factor regarding balance, said Fee.\n\n\u201cI strongly believe that if you stay active, you can minimize the effects that aging has on all of these players,\u201d Fee said.\n\nDiseases and underlying medical conditions like Parkinson\u2019s disease, Multiple Sclerosis, neuropathy, strokes, vision problems, and pain can impact a person\u2019s balance. Other factors such as medications, fear of falling, and environmental factors.\n\nIt is very important for older patients to discuss with their providers any changes in the gait, possible new onset gait unsteadiness, or if they start to experience new musculoskeletal pain, Goralnik advised.\n\n\u201cSome of the medications may increase the risk of falls,\u201d said Goralnik. \u201cIt is very important for people to have a complete list of all current medications when they visit their medical providers.\u201d\n\nHaving detailed information, he said, about existing and potential risk factors may help reduce the risk of future falls.\n\nFee added that testing can be completed to assess balance and what kind of treatment or therapy might be available to assist with balance. Fee said a fall risk assessment is a good first step to preventing falls.\n\n\u201cYou can talk to your doctor or health care provider to refer you to a physical therapist to evaluate your risk for falling,\u201d said Fee.\n\nShe said a physical therapist will measure/evaluate strength, flexibility, analyzation of posture and feet, how you walk and perform specific balance measures to determine your areas of weakness. The therapist may also ask about fall history and possible home hazards like uneven pavement, rugs, steps, clutter or pets.\n\n\u201cThen a physical therapist can design a specialized treatment program to help you reduce your risk of falls,\u201d Fee said. \u201cOther recommendations to improve overall balance is getting involved in a local gym where you can perform strength and balance exercises like Tai Chi or yoga.\u201d\n\nTemporary conditionsIn addition to medical conditions such as strokes, brain injuries, etc., other temporary conditions also have effects on an individual\u2019s balance.\n\nFee, a physical therapist who specializes in inner ear disorders, said the most common inner ear problem is a condition known as Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV). Classic symptoms include brief episodes of spinning or imbalance that occur when lying down, rolling over in bed, or looking up.\n\n\u201cBPPV can significantly increase a person\u2019s risk for falling especially if they have other balance risk factors. This problem is easily identified by the physical therapist that is trained in detecting inner ear problems,\u201d she added.\n\nFee said a physical therapist with specialized training can provide the most appropriate intervention to reduce or resolve these symptoms in as little as one to three sessions.\n\nFee said physical therapists can often identify risk factors and provide specific recommendations to improve balance.\n\n\u201cPhysical therapists are like coaches, but you have to do the work. In order for your balance to improve, you have to challenge the team!\u201d\n\nGoralnik added, that in many cases, falls and fall-related injuries lead to substantial deficiency with activities of daily living and the need for supportive care for older adults.\n\nThe economic burdens from falls are substantial and likely to increase with the growth of the older population, according to Goralnik.\n\nFall-related health care costs include hospital bills, fees for professional service, and costs of prescription medications, home health services, long-term care facilities, and durable medical equipment.\n\n\u201cAlways inform your doctor about recent falls and fall-related injuries,\u201d concluded Gorainik.\n\nIt is very important for seniors to discuss any changes of the gait, possible new onset gait unsteadiness, or if they started to experience new musculoskeletal pain with their doctor.\n\nTrending Video","url":"https://www.dailyitem.com/news/doc-fall-prevention-key-to-preventing-injuries-in-seniors/article_6b96f7cc-2b8d-11ed-b79c-1f9704d203dc.html"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1022","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1022","narrative_id":"1022"},"responses":[{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Falls are a major health risk, especially among older adults, often leading to serious injuries and loss of independence, and it is essential to explore the effectiveness of Tai Chi as a method to reduce falls and improve physical stability."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"The risk of falls and fall-related injuries is a significant concern for older adults, and exercise programs, including Tai Chi, have been recommended to prevent falls and improve balance."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"According to a review of 17 studies, fall-prevention exercises, including Tai Chi, can reduce the risk of falls and fall-related injuries in older adults."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"The studies analyzed involved over 4,000 participants and found that most of the programs reduced fall-related injuries and appeared to significantly curb falls that lead to fractures, serious injuries, and medical care."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Balance training was emphasized in all of the exercises that were effective in preventing falls, and Tai Chi was found to be a beneficial exercise for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"Tai Chi is a centuries-old Chinese martial art that combines physical training, self-defense, and meditation, and it has been shown to improve balance and reduce the risk of falls in older adults."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"The exercise consists of a series of traditional Chinese physical exercises that flow smoothly with each other, stimulating and stretching all the muscles, tendons, joints, and bones in a gentle way."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"The upright position of the back during Tai Chi exercise creates a stretching effect in the spine, relieving pressure on the intervertebral discs, and the nervous system is also positively affected by the gentle posture of the back."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"Studies have suggested that Tai Chi reduces the risk of falls in older adults thanks to its ability to improve their balance, and it has also been shown to have a positive effect on overall health and mood."},{"citations":{"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":1.0},"text":"To achieve the benefits of Tai Chi, it is recommended to practice the exercise one to two times a week, which applies to beginners and advanced athletes alike."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"A physical therapist can design a specialized treatment program to help individuals reduce their risk of falls, and recommendations to improve overall balance include getting involved in a local gym where you can perform strength and balance exercises like Tai Chi or yoga."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"In addition to medical conditions, temporary conditions such as strokes, brain injuries, and vision problems can also impact an individual's balance, and it is essential to address these conditions to prevent falls."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"Age alone should not be blamed as a factor regarding balance, and staying active can minimize the effects of aging on balance and overall health."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"Falls can have a significant impact on a person's overall quality of life, leading to a fear of falling, weakness, and furthering the risk of repeated falls."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Therefore, based on the scientific evidence, Tai Chi can be an effective method for reducing falls and improving physical stability in older adults, and it is recommended to practice the exercise regularly to achieve the benefits."},{"citations":{"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":1.0},"text":"The frequency and duration of Tai Chi practice required to observe benefits can vary, but practicing one to two times a week can be beneficial for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Overall, the evidence suggests that Tai Chi is a valuable exercise for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls in older adults, and it can be a useful addition to a fall prevention program."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Falls are a major health risk, especially among older adults, often leading to serious injuries and loss of independence, and it is essential to explore the effectiveness of Tai Chi as a method to reduce falls and improve physical stability."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"The risk of falls and fall-related injuries is a significant concern for older adults, and exercise programs, including Tai Chi, have been recommended to prevent falls and improve balance."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"According to a review of 17 studies, fall-prevention exercises, including Tai Chi, can reduce the risk of falls and fall-related injuries in older adults."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"The studies analyzed involved over 4,000 participants and found that most of the programs reduced fall-related injuries and appeared to significantly curb falls that lead to fractures, serious injuries, and medical care."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Balance training was emphasized in all of the exercises that were effective in preventing falls, and Tai Chi was found to be a beneficial exercise for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"Tai Chi is a centuries-old Chinese martial art that combines physical training, self-defense, and meditation, and it has been shown to improve balance and reduce the risk of falls in older adults."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"The exercise consists of a series of traditional Chinese physical exercises that flow smoothly with each other, stimulating and stretching all the muscles, tendons, joints, and bones in a gentle way."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"The upright position of the back during Tai Chi exercise creates a stretching effect in the spine, relieving pressure on the intervertebral discs, and the nervous system is also positively affected by the gentle posture of the back."},{"citations":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":1.0},"text":"Studies have suggested that Tai Chi reduces the risk of falls in older adults thanks to its ability to improve their balance, and it has also been shown to have a positive effect on overall health and mood."},{"citations":{"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":1.0},"text":"To achieve the benefits of Tai Chi, it is recommended to practice the exercise one to two times a week, which applies to beginners and advanced athletes alike."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"A physical therapist can design a specialized treatment program to help individuals reduce their risk of falls, and recommendations to improve overall balance include getting involved in a local gym where you can perform strength and balance exercises like Tai Chi or yoga."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"In addition to medical conditions, temporary conditions such as strokes, brain injuries, and vision problems can also impact an individual's balance, and it is essential to address these conditions to prevent falls."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"Age alone should not be blamed as a factor regarding balance, and staying active can minimize the effects of aging on balance and overall health."},{"citations":{"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":1.0},"text":"Falls can have a significant impact on a person's overall quality of life, leading to a fear of falling, weakness, and furthering the risk of repeated falls."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Therefore, based on the scientific evidence, Tai Chi can be an effective method for reducing falls and improving physical stability in older adults, and it is recommended to practice the exercise regularly to achieve the benefits."},{"citations":{"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":1.0},"text":"The frequency and duration of Tai Chi practice required to observe benefits can vary, but practicing one to two times a week can be beneficial for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls."},{"citations":{"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":1.0},"text":"Overall, the evidence suggests that Tai Chi is a valuable exercise for improving balance and reducing the risk of falls in older adults, and it can be a useful addition to a fall prevention program."}],"references":["eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921","184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782","08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184","2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624"],"documents":{"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624":{"id":"2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237_437053624","text":"Learn about the sport of Tai Chi\nThe German health centre says Tai Chi is a centuries-old Chinese martial art, also known as shadow boxing.\nIt combines physical training, self-defense and meditation.\nThe focus of Tai Chi is on body tightening, mental alertness and breathing, the center explained, noting that motor training consists of a series of traditional Chinese physical exercises that flow smoothly with each other in order to achieve harmony between body and soul.\nMuscle and Joint Stimulation\nIn this way all the muscles, tendons, joints and bones are stimulated and stretched in a gentle way.\nThe upright position of the back during exercise creates a stretching effect in the spine, relieving pressure on the intervertebral discs.\nThe nervous system is also positively affected by the gentle posture of the back.\nStudies have suggested that tai chi reduces the risk of falls in older adults thanks to its ability to improve their balance.\nThe sport also has a positive effect on degenerative arthritis, the symptoms of which are knee stiffness, pain and swelling.\nImprove lung function\nTai chi is also beneficial for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) as it improves lung function.\nIt is also useful for patients with Parkinson \u2019 s, which affects the nervous system and its symptoms are disorders of movement, tremor of the hands, stiffness and instability of the body position, where sports contribute to improving balance and mobility.\nIn addition, tai chi improves the cognitive functioning of the brain, making it also useful for dementia patients.\nOn the other hand, slow flowing movements have a relaxing and meditative effect, helping to feel relaxed, calm and psychologically comfortable.\nSource: German","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:18937","uncompressed_offset":437053624,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/health/2024/4/16/%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A7%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%8A","warc_date":"2024-04-16T18:28:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2e864b6f-2e85-4876-845a-6831478b1237>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/health/2024/4/16/%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A7%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%8A?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-04-16T18:55:44.000Z","lang":"eng"},"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782":{"id":"184485a7-25df-4efa-b2f3-f28ae72d25e3_199781782","text":"Exercise programs meant to prevent falls in seniors may also help prevent injuries caused by falls, according to a new review.\n\nFall-related injuries are common among seniors and a major cause of long-term pain and disability. They also increase the risk of having to go to a nursing home and have a high economic cost.\n\nThe new findings, published online Oct. 29 in the journal bmj.com, suggest that \"reducing the risk of falling and improving protective responses during a fall may be an important and feasible means of preventing fractures and other serious injuries in the elderly,\" the study authors wrote in a journal news release.\n\nWell-designed exercise programs can prevent falls in seniors living at home, but there is a lack of evidence on whether such programs can help prevent fall-related injuries, said French researchers Fabienne El-Khoury and colleagues.\n\nIn this review, they analyzed 17 studies that looked at whether fall-prevention exercises lowered seniors' risk of fractures and other injuries caused by falls. More than 4,000 participants were involved in all.\n\nTai Chi was the exercise in two of the studies, but most of them used gait, balance, strength and functional training, which involves workouts that help people do normal daily activities.\n\nMost of the programs reduced fall-related injuries and appeared to significantly curb falls that lead to fractures, serious injuries and medical care.\n\nBalance training was emphasized in all of the exercises that were effective in preventing falls, the researchers noted.\n\nMore information\n\nThe U.S. National Institute on Aging has more about older adults and falls.\n\nLatest videos","url":"https://www.newsday.com/news/health/balance-training-seems-to-prevent-falls-by-elderly-w61786"},"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921":{"id":"eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923_331358921","text":"7 Exercises Necessary for Perfect Balance\nBalance is your ability to coordinate and control your body \u2019 s center of gravity \u2013 in everyday life you have to deal with this all the time!\nFor example, your balance ensures that you can walk without falling.\n(Illustrated - Gettyimages)\nAlthough it may not occur to you, you need a good balance to do almost everything, including walking, getting up from a chair and bending over to tie your shoes.\nBalance training involves doing muscle-strengthening exercises that help keep you upright, including your legs and torso as these types of exercises can improve stability and help prevent falls.\nAnd while there are intense balancing exercises like some very challenging yoga poses, others are as simple as standing on one leg for a few seconds.\nIf you have a problem with this, you can use equipment that forces your body to stabilize, such as a semi-circular stability ball.\nMeaning of Balance\nBalance is your ability to coordinate and control your body \u2019 s center of gravity \u2013 in everyday life you have to deal with this all the time!\nFor example, your balance ensures that you can walk without falling, that you can sit up straight, and that you can jump over a hole without falling.\nYour body uses different systems: your eyes (the visual system) help you see the space around you, your inner ear (the vestibular system) records rotating movements and accelerations, and the receptors in your joints and muscles and the pressure receptors in your skin (together the stimulus receptor system) transmit changes in your posture.\nAll the stimuli your body receives through these systems come together in your central nervous system, and your brain in turn sends the message to your muscles that adapt immediately to prevent you from falling; all this has to happen at lightning speed and that \u2019 s what it should be, as our bodies have to adapt constantly as we move.\nWith the help of balanced training, you can teach your muscles to respond more quickly to brain messages as this allows you to improve fine motor and coordination skills.\nAreas targeted by balance\n\u2022 Middle: Yes, balance exercises target this area, you need strong core muscles to achieve good balance, many stability exercises work to exercise the abdominal muscles and other core muscles.\n\u2022 Forearms: No, balance exercises do not target these ends, most balance exercises revolve around balance on your feet.\nLegs: Yes, the legs are definitely areas where balance is targeted, and exercises in which you balance on one leg and then squat or lean forward also work to exercise the leg muscles.\nButtock: Yes, the same balance exercises that work on the legs also work to strengthen the buttocks.\nBack: Another area targeted by balance exercises, where your core muscles include some of your back muscles.\nGood balance depends on:\nSensory information from your eyes (visual system), muscles, tendons, joints (stimulation inputs), and balance organs in the inner ear (vestibular system).\nThe brain stem understands all of this sensory information combined with other parts of the brain.\nMovement of your eyes to keep things stable in your vision and maintain your balance.\nWhat are the benefits of balance training?\nThe benefits of balance training are great, for example:\n\u2022 You can improve your posture and you can stand or sit better.\n\u2022 Train your deep muscles, especially the muscles in the torso and around the spine.\n\u2022 Reduce back wear and less muscle pain due to poor posture.\nPrevent injuries during exercise and in daily life because your body is not constantly out of balance, causing muscle strain.\n\u2022 Ability to perform movements more efficiently and smoothly.\nA positive effect on how your body feels and your performance improves as you make faster progress.\n\u2022 Improve the motor coordination of the body.\nHow often do you have to do this type of training?\nYou have to aim to do balance workouts one to two times a week, this applies to beginners all the way to advanced athletes, and it is very important that professionals improve their stability as well.\nSimple exercises to get the perfect balance:\nTai Chi (Tai Chi)\nStudies show that tai chi, a gentle exercise often called \u201cmovement meditation, \u201d can help you reduce falls if you \u2019 re older and have balance problems, a skilled teacher can show you slow and precise movements that help you not only achieve more stability but also boost your overall health and mood as well.\nStanding on one leg (one-legged stand)\nStart by installing yourself on the back of the chair or any other sturdy handle.\nRaise one foot to approximately calf level and hold for 10 seconds.\n\u2022 Repeat this 10-15 times and then move on to the other leg.\nAs time goes on and your balance improves you may be able to continue in this situation without fixating yourself on any purpose.\nWeight Shifts (Weight Shifts)\nStand with your feet spaced by the width of your hip.\nSlowly lean forward horizontally on one leg to bear all your weight while lifting the other leg off the ground.\n\u2022 Wait for up to 30 seconds, then move to the other side.\nYou can do the same exercise while standing straight and raising one leg forward or left / right.\n\u2022 Yoga and Pilates\nTo maintain your balance, you need muscles that can hold you while standing, walking, or doing other movements. These muscles are known as your \u201ccore muscles. \u201d Yoga and Pilates involve movements that help you stretch and strengthen these muscles, but first consult your doctor before starting and to learn the movements correctly it is a good idea to join a nearby class taught by a certified instructor.\nHeel-to-Toe Walk\nWalk slowly in a straight line.\n\u2022 Touch your heel to the opposite toe as you progress.\nWalk about 20 steps using the wall for support if you feel unsteady.\nBack Leg Raises (Back Leg Raises)\nTo build up the lower back and buttocks, try raising your back leg while standing upright.\nHold a chair and lift one of your legs back without bending your knee or pointing your toe.\n\u2022 Keep the leg on the floor slightly bent.\n\u2022 Hold position for 5 seconds.\nDo this 10-15 times with the first leg before moving on to the other leg.\n\u2022 Squats (squats)\nTo strengthen the muscles of your legs and pelvis, do a squat exercise.\nStand up straight, make your feet slightly wider than your hips while pointing your toes forward.\nBend your knees and send your ass back, and slowly descend as if you were sitting.\nPlace your weight on your heels and arms in front of you or on your thighs.\nRaise yourself once and repeat 10 times.\nTo get a better idea of how strong your balance is while standing, lift one foot and see how long you can keep it there, or test your balance as you move and try to walk as if you were on a tightrope for 10 steps and see how it goes, you \u2019 ve probably noticed that one side is much stronger and more coordinated than the other.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0026.json.gz:63859","uncompressed_offset":331358921,"url":"www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/09/09/7-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B6%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A","warc_date":"2023-09-13T10:18:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eac7354a-8d3a-4125-a99c-ff8769c17923>","warc_url":"https://www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/09/09/7-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B6%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A"},"created":"2023-09-13T10:34:05.000Z","lang":"eng"},"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184":{"id":"08b29f61-ad72-46e6-859d-df2e6233ec1b_349742184","text":"Healthy aging comes with challenges. For a variety of reasons, as each year passes, the likelihood of falling increases.\n\nAccording to Dr. Boris Goralnik, a geriatric specialist at UPMC in North Central Pa, a fall is defined as an unexpected event in which a person comes to rest on the ground, floor, or a lower level.\n\n\u201cFalls result in fall-related injuries, progression of gait impairments, loss of independence, depression,\u201d Goralnik said. \u201cIt is a leading cause of injury-related morbidity and mortality among older adults.\u201d\n\nBy preventing falls, providers try to prevent related injuries such as fractures, hematomas, and skin lacerations. From practice and literature, said Goralnik, the most important risk factor of falls is a previous history of falls.\n\nAccording to Janine Fee, MS, MPT, a physical therapist who is certified in vestibular rehabilitation at Evangelical Community Hospital, physical balance, which is important to avoid falling, can be complicated.\n\n\u201cI like to use the analogy of a baseball field,\u2019\u2019 Fee said. \u201cEvery player on the field is important and if a player is not working, then your team \u2014 your balance \u2014 is going to be impacted.\u201d\n\nFee said many systems have a direct impact on balance. Eyes, ears, sense of touch \u2014 especially with our feet, muscle strength, flexibility, and posture are a few. And, the brain can have a major impact on our ability to avoid falling.\n\nFee said any weakening of one or more of these areas will significantly increase the risk of falling.\n\nAccording to the Centers for Disease Control website, one out of four seniors over the age of 65 will fall each year. One out of five of those falls will cause serious injuries such as broken bones or head injuries.\n\n\u201cThis can then lead to serious consequences that may significantly impact a person\u2019s overall quality of life,\u201d said Fee. \u201cEven if the fall didn\u2019t cause harm, it is likely that the person now develops a fear of falling.\u201d\n\nMany factorsIn many cases, Goralnik said, falls and fall-related injuries lead to substantial deficiency in activities of daily living and the need for supportive care for older adults. He agreed with Fee that a fear of falling leads to things like not participating in activities that require balance, causing weaknesses and furthering the risk of repeated falls. Paying attention to the body and being more aware of areas contributing to balance is a big step in preventing falls.\n\nAge alone should not be blamed as a factor regarding balance, said Fee.\n\n\u201cI strongly believe that if you stay active, you can minimize the effects that aging has on all of these players,\u201d Fee said.\n\nDiseases and underlying medical conditions like Parkinson\u2019s disease, Multiple Sclerosis, neuropathy, strokes, vision problems, and pain can impact a person\u2019s balance. Other factors such as medications, fear of falling, and environmental factors.\n\nIt is very important for older patients to discuss with their providers any changes in the gait, possible new onset gait unsteadiness, or if they start to experience new musculoskeletal pain, Goralnik advised.\n\n\u201cSome of the medications may increase the risk of falls,\u201d said Goralnik. \u201cIt is very important for people to have a complete list of all current medications when they visit their medical providers.\u201d\n\nHaving detailed information, he said, about existing and potential risk factors may help reduce the risk of future falls.\n\nFee added that testing can be completed to assess balance and what kind of treatment or therapy might be available to assist with balance. Fee said a fall risk assessment is a good first step to preventing falls.\n\n\u201cYou can talk to your doctor or health care provider to refer you to a physical therapist to evaluate your risk for falling,\u201d said Fee.\n\nShe said a physical therapist will measure/evaluate strength, flexibility, analyzation of posture and feet, how you walk and perform specific balance measures to determine your areas of weakness. The therapist may also ask about fall history and possible home hazards like uneven pavement, rugs, steps, clutter or pets.\n\n\u201cThen a physical therapist can design a specialized treatment program to help you reduce your risk of falls,\u201d Fee said. \u201cOther recommendations to improve overall balance is getting involved in a local gym where you can perform strength and balance exercises like Tai Chi or yoga.\u201d\n\nTemporary conditionsIn addition to medical conditions such as strokes, brain injuries, etc., other temporary conditions also have effects on an individual\u2019s balance.\n\nFee, a physical therapist who specializes in inner ear disorders, said the most common inner ear problem is a condition known as Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV). Classic symptoms include brief episodes of spinning or imbalance that occur when lying down, rolling over in bed, or looking up.\n\n\u201cBPPV can significantly increase a person\u2019s risk for falling especially if they have other balance risk factors. This problem is easily identified by the physical therapist that is trained in detecting inner ear problems,\u201d she added.\n\nFee said a physical therapist with specialized training can provide the most appropriate intervention to reduce or resolve these symptoms in as little as one to three sessions.\n\nFee said physical therapists can often identify risk factors and provide specific recommendations to improve balance.\n\n\u201cPhysical therapists are like coaches, but you have to do the work. In order for your balance to improve, you have to challenge the team!\u201d\n\nGoralnik added, that in many cases, falls and fall-related injuries lead to substantial deficiency with activities of daily living and the need for supportive care for older adults.\n\nThe economic burdens from falls are substantial and likely to increase with the growth of the older population, according to Goralnik.\n\nFall-related health care costs include hospital bills, fees for professional service, and costs of prescription medications, home health services, long-term care facilities, and durable medical equipment.\n\n\u201cAlways inform your doctor about recent falls and fall-related injuries,\u201d concluded Gorainik.\n\nIt is very important for seniors to discuss any changes of the gait, possible new onset gait unsteadiness, or if they started to experience new musculoskeletal pain with their doctor.\n\nTrending Video","url":"https://www.dailyitem.com/news/doc-fall-prevention-key-to-preventing-injuries-in-seniors/article_6b96f7cc-2b8d-11ed-b79c-1f9704d203dc.html"}}}
