binary authors in the genre."},{"citations":{"313a3381-4790-45a2-8734-d595fd2ee46a_38674691":1.0},"text":"Overall, the genre of science fiction has undergone a significant transformation over the years, influenced by a wide range of authors and factors."}],"references":["313a3381-4790-45a2-8734-d595fd2ee46a_38674691","40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979"],"documents":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":{"id":"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979","text":"Science Fiction: Chinese Female Writers | Culture | DW | 21.10.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nCultural warp and weft\nScience fiction: the rise of Chinese women writers\nWhile the space for feminist expression in China has shrunk further over the past decade, there \u2019 s good news from this week \u2019 s World Science Fiction Conference in Chengdu: Chinese female writers are thriving in the science fiction world, making them one of the most striking trends in the genre.\nThe rise of Chinese female writers in science fiction has become one of the most striking trends in the genre, according to participants at this week's World Science Fiction Conference in Chengdu.\nThe World Science Fiction Conference, the world \u2019 s oldest and most influential science fiction event, was held in China for the first time this year and attracted a large number of local fans, both male and female.\nChina remains a relatively socially conservative country, and under President Xi Jinping, the space for feminist expression has narrowed further over the past decade.\nBut author and editor Regina Kanyu Wang, who was nominated for two prestigious Hugo Awards at the World Science Fiction Conference this year, said the number of women writers in science fiction has soared in recent years.\nShe said more and more women are now realizing that \"it's not just nerdy, nerdy science-fiction novels like Liu Cixin [author of the three-body series] that can be published, or can be considered science fiction.\" Liu Cixin is great, and we all like him.\nBut there's a lot more to it than Liu Cixin's style. \"\nThe good news, says Wang, is that once women start to become writers, they don \u2019 t feel they \u2019 re being treated unequally.\nThe market and readers need a new perspective, she said.\nThe 81st World Science Fiction Conference will be held in Chengdu from October 18 to 22.\n\"Now, many Chinese female science fiction writers focus on issues that women face that men may not feel,\" Zhou Danxue, a literary scholar at XJCC Liverpool University, told AFP. \"These writers can reflect unique female experiences in their own way.\"\nWang said that in the past two years, four anthologies of Chinese fantasy novels written only by female or non-binary authors have been published, which is a major breakthrough.\nThere wasn \u2019 t even an all-female science fiction writer \u2019 s portfolio before that.\nBefore the 1990s, there were very few female science fiction writers.\nAn article in the collection \"The Way Spring Comes\", which Wang Kanyu participated in compiling, pointed out that the Internet is a training base for women and queer talents.\nAuthor Ni Xueting explained that the widespread use of the Internet \u201cnot only brought a new sense of community to people, but also \u2026 removed many barriers to writing based on industry and social stereotypes, especially for non-male writers. \u201d\nChen Qiufan, one of China \u2019 s leading science fiction writers, told AFP that the genre had traditionally not received special attention and was seen as \u201cwritten and read by boys. \u201d\nHe said there was now a \"wider and more diverse audience\", estimating that his readers were split equally between men and women.\nChinese women writers begin to make their mark in science fiction\nMonet, a 21-year-old woman who visited the science fiction convention on Friday, said she sometimes felt isolated among her own fan base.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s hard to share my interests with people who don \u2019 t understand me.\nThey ask, \"Why does a girl like science fiction?\"\nShe is optimistic about these changes in attitude, pointing out that there are a lot of interested primary and secondary school students at the conference site.\n\u201cI think interest in Chinese science fiction has to be nurtured from an early age, \u201d she says.\u201c We didn \u2019 t have that opportunity when we were young \u2026 I really envy them, to be honest. \u201d\n(AFP)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0030.json.gz:29419","uncompressed_offset":387896979,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E7%A7%91%E5%B9%BB%E5%B0%8F%E8%AF%B4%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%A5%B3%E6%80%A7%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%A3%8E%E7%94%9F%E6%B0%B4%E8%B5%B7/a-67173649","warc_date":"2023-10-21T19:06:29.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E7%A7%91%E5%B9%BB%E5%B0%8F%E8%AF%B4%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%A5%B3%E6%80%A7%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%A3%8E%E7%94%9F%E6%B0%B4%E8%B5%B7/a-67173649"},"created":"2023-10-21T19:35:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"313a3381-4790-45a2-8734-d595fd2ee46a_38674691":{"id":"313a3381-4790-45a2-8734-d595fd2ee46a_38674691","text":"Supplement\nSunday literature.\nCulture\nSunday Literature: Tu Chien's Years, Huang Hua and Long Memories: A Review of Books by Tu Chien\nHe died, and there was a great book about him, and a great book about him.\nBorn in Hong Kong on February 19, 1935 (also known as February 19, 1934), Du Chin studied at Lingnan Primary School and St. Stephen's College in Hong Kong. He graduated from the Chinese Department of Sun Yat-sen University.\nDu has been engaged in the editorial and translation work of newspapers and periodicals for 30 years. He has edited the monthly book \u201cOpen Volume \u201d and\u201c Readers \u2019 Friends \u201d. He is the author of \u201cNew Trends in Asian, African and Latin Literature \u201d (1976),\u201c Contemporary Foreign Writers and Works \u201d (1980), \u201cThe Night Voyage of the Book Sea \u201d (2 volumes, 1980, 1984),\u201c World Science Fiction \u201d (1992). He also translated several science fiction novels, including The Story of a Detective (1994), The Story of a Detective (2019), The Story of Three Generations (2014), Long Memories: The Eyes of a Teacher and Friends (2015), and translated several science fiction novels.\nDu moved to Canada in his later years and died on July 23, 2022.\nFrom Afro-Asian to Contemporary Foreign Literature\nI have \"Asian, African and Latin Literature New Trend\", published by Hong Kong Wanyuan Book Company, this book from the left side, introduced the Asian, African and Latin literature, and it is rare to write a relatively mild, not too much ideological discourse.\nFrom the illustrations in the book, Du Chen should have seen a number of foreign books before writing this book, including book reviews such as \"Achebe's Novel Creation\" and \"Du Bois's Will\", which discuss the more famous black writers, and scroll down a \"text prison of a novel - this novel exposes the corruption of the police\", from 1974 Nelson Marra The award-winning novel \u201cThe Bodyguard, \u201d and its associated spate of arrests, describes the repression of freedom of speech and the press by the Uruguayan police, as well as the repression of the literary and artistic world.\nThe incident has faded from the memory of ordinary literary readers, but Du Jian recorded it with a book review and became a page of literary history.\nTowards the end of the 1970s, the tendency of the dogmatic left gradually faded, and Du Jian \u2019 s reading range became wider. Contemporary Foreign Writers and Works was published by the Hong Kong Ocean Arts and Culture Society, and its chapters were published in the magazine Ocean Arts and Culture.\nDu introduced Graham Greene, John Cheever, Colette, Bertolt Brecht, Isak Dinesen, Nadine Gordimer, Ryuichiro Tanizaki and Ryuosuke Okawa, eight 20th-century writers who not only came out of the confines of Afro-Asian literature. As soon as the book is in hand, readers can enjoy the work from the two texts of the commentary and the translation. In \u201cContemporary Foreign Writers and Works, \u201d Du Jian chose to translate Ryuichiro Tanizaki \u2019 s\u201c tattoo \u201d and Ryuosuke Okawa \u2019 s \u201cbamboo forest \u201d, both of which are popular and popular.\nThe South African female writer Gaudimet, introduced by Du Jian in the late 1970s, won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1991.\nBook Sea Night Flight\n\"Book Sea Night Voyage\" two episodes published by Beijing Sanlian, when there were many prints in mainland China, naturally has a certain influence, these two books seem to have opened a window for long-closed mainland readers.\nSome of the book \u2019 s reviews have been found in The New Trend of Asian, African and Latin Literature and Contemporary Foreign Writers and Works. The book is mainly a collection of book reviews written by Du Jian in his spare time between 1974 and 1978.\nAs for \"Book Sea Night Voyage II\", the content is equally extensive, there is no less than, the second set of the epilogue, Du gradually explained his own ten years as a day of three paragraphs on the reading method:\n\"I read there is no shortcut, and will not\" speed reading \", using a stupid way, the old man actually read the book, there is no other way.\nI divide the time into three sections every day, to work a section, do work concentrate on other, the other section is translation and writing, people engaged in writing in Hong Kong, every day have to be a \"reptile\", write thousands of words, earn some manuscript money to