{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1030","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1030","narrative_id":"1030"},"responses":[{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"The genre of science fiction in literature has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by various factors such as technological advancements, social and cultural developments, and the emergence of new authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Science fiction, which was once dominated by Western authors, has now become a global phenomenon, with authors from diverse backgrounds and cultures contributing to the genre."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"In the early 20th century, science fiction was largely influenced by ideologies such as capitalism and communism, as well as threats associated with civilian and military technologies."},{"citations":{"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305":1.0},"text":"However, as the genre evolved, it began to incorporate more diverse perspectives, including those of women authors and people of color, who have made significant contributions to the field."},{"citations":{"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305":1.0},"text":"The Syrian writer and critic Ahmed Ali Mohammed, for example, has explored the features of science fiction in Arabic literature, highlighting the genre's presence in Arab creative writings despite its emergence and prosperity in the Western world."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"In recent years, authors from countries such as China have also made a significant impact on the genre, with writers like Wang Jinkang contributing to the development of philosophical science fiction."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"Wang Jinkang's work, which combines elements of science fiction and philosophy, has been influenced by the latest technological advances and has explored the influence of technology on alienation, civilization, and other themes."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The genre has also become more cosmopolitan, with authors incorporating elements of their own cultures and styles into their work, adding a unique flavor to the genre."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"According to Wang Jinkang, the success of science fiction is reliant on a country's economic, scientific, and technological development, which can be seen in the movement of the genre's center from Britain and France to the United States over the last century."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"In China, for example, the overall economic development has been good, and the creative environment of Chinese science fiction has continued to improve over the past 40 years."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"As a result, science fiction has become a global phenomenon, with authors from diverse backgrounds and cultures contributing to the genre and pushing its boundaries."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The shift from short-form to long-form writing has also been a significant development in the genre, with authors facing new challenges and opportunities in terms of storytelling and world-building."},{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"Overall, the genre of science fiction has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by a range of factors and contributions from diverse authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The genre's ability to incorporate new ideas, technologies, and perspectives has allowed it to remain relevant and fresh, and its continued evolution is likely to be shaped by the contributions of authors from around the world."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"As Wang Jinkang notes, science fiction is unlike any other form of literature, and its success is reliant on a country's economic, scientific, and technological development."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The genre's future is likely to be shaped by the continued convergence of technology and literature, as well as the emergence of new authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the genre of science fiction has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by a range of factors and contributions from diverse authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The genre's continued evolution is likely to be shaped by the contributions of authors from around the world, and its ability to incorporate new ideas, technologies, and perspectives will allow it to remain relevant and fresh."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"The genre of science fiction in literature has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by various factors such as technological advancements, social and cultural developments, and the emergence of new authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Science fiction, which was once dominated by Western authors, has now become a global phenomenon, with authors from diverse backgrounds and cultures contributing to the genre."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"In the early 20th century, science fiction was largely influenced by ideologies such as capitalism and communism, as well as threats associated with civilian and military technologies."},{"citations":{"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305":1.0},"text":"However, as the genre evolved, it began to incorporate more diverse perspectives, including those of women authors and people of color, who have made significant contributions to the field."},{"citations":{"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305":1.0},"text":"The Syrian writer and critic Ahmed Ali Mohammed, for example, has explored the features of science fiction in Arabic literature, highlighting the genre's presence in Arab creative writings despite its emergence and prosperity in the Western world."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"In recent years, authors from countries such as China have also made a significant impact on the genre, with writers like Wang Jinkang contributing to the development of philosophical science fiction."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"Wang Jinkang's work, which combines elements of science fiction and philosophy, has been influenced by the latest technological advances and has explored the influence of technology on alienation, civilization, and other themes."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The genre has also become more cosmopolitan, with authors incorporating elements of their own cultures and styles into their work, adding a unique flavor to the genre."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"According to Wang Jinkang, the success of science fiction is reliant on a country's economic, scientific, and technological development, which can be seen in the movement of the genre's center from Britain and France to the United States over the last century."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"In China, for example, the overall economic development has been good, and the creative environment of Chinese science fiction has continued to improve over the past 40 years."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"As a result, science fiction has become a global phenomenon, with authors from diverse backgrounds and cultures contributing to the genre and pushing its boundaries."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The shift from short-form to long-form writing has also been a significant development in the genre, with authors facing new challenges and opportunities in terms of storytelling and world-building."},{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"Overall, the genre of science fiction has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by a range of factors and contributions from diverse authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The genre's ability to incorporate new ideas, technologies, and perspectives has allowed it to remain relevant and fresh, and its continued evolution is likely to be shaped by the contributions of authors from around the world."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"As Wang Jinkang notes, science fiction is unlike any other form of literature, and its success is reliant on a country's economic, scientific, and technological development."},{"citations":{"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":1.0},"text":"The genre's future is likely to be shaped by the continued convergence of technology and literature, as well as the emergence of new authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the genre of science fiction has undergone significant changes and evolution over time, influenced by a range of factors and contributions from diverse authors and demographics."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The genre's continued evolution is likely to be shaped by the contributions of authors from around the world, and its ability to incorporate new ideas, technologies, and perspectives will allow it to remain relevant and fresh."}],"references":["764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305","fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711","ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341","01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677"],"documents":{"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711":{"id":"fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17_94673711","text":"Turkish Drama from History to Science Fiction\nResidents of Istanbul rush to wear headphones after the country has been hit by a pandemic that is transmitted only through language communication and speech.\nThese headphones protect them from the gossip of patients who have been hit by the pandemic.\nOnly a handful of residents have survived the disease, including Murat, a former Turkish linguist who is trying to help a young boy and is clashing with the ruthless CDC while venturing to discover his immune head in the Turkish series \"Overheating Head\", due to air next month on Netflix on December 2, 2022, directed by Mert Baikal.\nThe series is a sci-fi series and is a work of dystopia or miserable worlds in which all human beings suffer from a major collective crisis that does not belong to any individual, and is the opposite of the model of \"utopia\", which means \"utopia\" in which everything goes perfectly.\nIt consists of 8 parts and is taken from the novel of the Turkish writer Afshin Kom, and bears the name of the film itself.\nThe idea of \u200b \u200b the series is not new in the world of art, which presented similar ideas but new in terms of television series, especially digital platforms such as Netflix and others.\nIn addition, the series presents the idea of \u200b \u200b science fiction revolving in the city of Istanbul with all its oriental and Islamic culture.\nIt is also in the orbit of a new wave of Turkish series that adopt science fiction as the main theme, such as the series \"submarine Yakamuz S-245\" by the directors Tolga Karagelik and Umut Aral, which began a few months ago on Netflix, and deals with the discovery of the Turkish military base \"Incirlik\" of a strange phenomenon that causes a disruption in the magnetic field of the sun, resulting in the explosion and the death of all humans.\nIn the film \"Wheat\" clear metaphors and how the human first resort to the cave in search of survival in isolation represented in the experience of the story of the owners of \"Surat al-Kahf\" and then resort to money as in the story of the owners of the two gardens before reaching the basic station, which is the search for self from the inside and not the outside in the story of our Lord Musa peace.\nScience fiction is not just a matter of entertainment, but a kind of prediction of the future of technological and scientific development in the world.\nCinema has proven its ability to predict many events, including political, social and scientific ones.\nPerhaps the most striking example of this is several works of art that predicted the COVID-19 pandemic in close detail and away from what we have seen in real life, such as Steven Soderberg \u2019 s 2011 American film \u201cOutbreak \u201d, which tells the story of a woman returning to the United States from a trip to Hong Kong carrying an infectious disease.\nThere is also the 2016 film \u201cPandemic \u201d by American director John Suts, about the journey of a New York City doctor who travels to Los Angeles to search for survivors after a deadly virus has claimed the lives of many people around the world.\nScience Fiction with Modern Turkish Drama\nThe Turkish drama went through several stages before it reached the stage of science fiction.\nIt was the beginning of social and romantic series.\nThese series promoted the idea of the beauty of the place, the costumes and the feelings within a framework of tragedy.\nThen I turned to historical issues, which carried all the broad political hopes that many had placed on Turkey in the context of a miserable Arab political and development reality.\nHistory has been a common denominator with tens of millions of Turkish and Arab peoples, a universal bond that reinforces identity, rediscovers the past, builds bridges and nurtures a sense of nostalgia.\nScience fiction, by contrast, leaps into the future, stimulates thinking about new science and technology, enhances self-ability, realizes the impossible, and thinks the absurd.\nIt is a natural progression of any ambitious production process that begins with the exhumation of memory and the past, and after most of the symbols and events of its modern history are consumed in historical series moving towards a new dramatic genre.\nAnd the Turkish drama did well to carve this trend, because on the one hand it offers an oriental cinematic vision of science, and on the other hand it combats the spirit of frustration and despair experienced by young people by presenting a cinematic scientific narrative from an oriental Muslim country with a record of inventions and industrialization in the current era.\nIt is no secret that imagination as an idea is the magic word of the current generation of Turkish government, opposition and people.\nThe significance of this word is illustrated by a famous position between the late Prime Ministers Necmettin Erbakan and Bulent Ecevit when the latter accused the projects of the Welfare Party (Erbakan Party) as fictional, and replies that he (Ecevit) as a poet knows well the role of imagination in life and that the Welfare Party already has a wide imagination but seeks to achieve it on the ground.\nThe 2017 film \"Wheat\", directed by Semih Kaplanoglu, is one of the important attempts in the framework of science fiction stemming from Turkish culture, albeit in a cinematic rather than television setting.\nHe presented Arab and Islamic culture in the context of an interesting and unique science fiction.\nIt is an English-language film about the philosophy of the relationship between man and the modern technical nature, produced jointly by Turkish-German, French-Swedish and Qatari.\nIt is about the journey of Professor Errol Erin, an agronomist who lives in a futuristic city protected from the entry of multi-ethnic immigrants.\nAfter the city is hit by a genetic engineering problem whose causes are unknown, the professor decides to look for another scientist who has written a study of the crises of genetically modified crops.\nThis journey of research leads him to discover what he knew about himself and life.\nIn the film, there are clear metaphors for the cave, and how man first resorts to the cave in search of survival in isolation represented in the experience of the story of the owners of the cave, and then resorts to money as in the story of the owners of the two gardens, before reaching the basic station, which is the search for self from the inside and not the outside in the story of Moses, as a gift to the same Koranic Sura (cave).\nThis last stop leads to the model of civilized urbanism based on rational construction of urbanism based on the building of the soul with the story of Dhul-Qarnain.\nThe film here is an application of the theory of \"Quranic cinema\", which we mentioned in another article last Ramadan, about the inspiration of the Quranic stories cinematically in terms of meaning and symbolism other than the direct and known stories.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0034.json.gz:19881","uncompressed_offset":94673711,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/opinions/2022/11/16/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%84","warc_date":"2022-11-17T07:14:39.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fd5a6809-317e-49a3-8641-9fb080214c17>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/opinions/2022/11/16/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%84"},"created":"2022-11-17T07:20:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341":{"id":"ac3a1030-35ca-4592-9ac0-7de59165a212_979870341","text":"Interview with Wang Jinkang, 2024 Hugo Finalist\n\nINTRODUCTION: Eight Light Minutes(8LM) Culture of Chengdu has given permission for File 770 to reprint the series of interviews with Chinese science fiction writers which they have been running this week on Facebook. The first one is a question and answer session with Wang Jinkang, whose novella Seeds of Mercury is a 2024 Hugo Award finalist.\n\nSUPPORTING CHINESE WRITERS SERIES (1): 2024 HUGO AWARD NOMINATION INTERVIEW WITH WANG JINKANG\n\nTranslated by Joseph Brant.\n\nWang Jinkang(\u738b\u664b\u5eb7) was born in Nanyang, Henan Province in 1948. He is a senior engineer, and a member of the Chinese Writer\u2019s Association (CWA), The China Popular Science Writing Association (CPSWA), The Committee of Scientific Literature and Art, and the Henan Writers\u2019 Association. Since the publication of his first story, The Return of Adam, in 1993, he has published over 90 short works, and 20 full novels, including Cross, We Together, Escape from The Mother Universe, Parents of Heaven and Earth, and Cosmic Crystal Eggs, totaling over six million words. He has won China\u2019s Galaxy Award 16 times, as well as The Chinese Science Fiction Nebula\u2019s Lifetime Achievement Award. He is considered one of Chinese science fiction\u2019s \u2018Four Heavenly Kings\u2019, and his emblematic work Seeds of Mercury was shortlisted for the 2024 Hugo Award for Best Novella.\n\nHello Mr. Wang! Before we start, I would like to congratulate you on Seeds of Mercury\u2019s shortlisting for 2024\u2019s \u201cBest Novella\u201d Hugo Award. This is news that has excited countless Chinese science fiction fans. Ever since the publication of Chinese Science Fiction: An Oral History, readers have commented that your contributions have particularly appealed to them and would like to know more about your life and work. Hopefully, this long-awaited interview will provide some of the insights the sci-fi community has longed for.\n\nQ1Mr. Wang, despite having produced many great works, this is the first time you\u2019ve been shortlisted for the Hugo. How did you feel when you learned that you\u2019d been shortlisted?\n\nWang Jinkang: Of course I was elated. Although I\u2019ve won many awards in China, in fact the most Galaxy Awards in history, this is the first time I\u2019ve been shortlisted for a Hugo. It felt like 31 years ago, when I first saw The Return of Adam in print, and when I won my First Galaxy Award. I think every author experiences these moments of excitement. It\u2019s excellent that Chinese science fiction has reached a certain level, after years of growth, it\u2019s now more and more visible internationally, which is fantastic. Of course, what we value even more, is these works transcending their era, and surviving the tides of time to reach future generations.\n\nReligion and Science are enemies who love each other.\n\nQ2Mr. Wang, as one of the \u2018Four Heavenly Kings\u2019 of Chinese science fiction, you\u2019re already very well known in China, with a creative career spanning over thirty years, with works such as Leopard Man, Ant Life and Survival Experiment and so on. This shortlisted work is such a quintessential piece. However, this interview is not just intended for the Chinese sci-fi fans, but for readers around the world, who may not be familiar with Seeds of Mercury. Could I ask you to introduce it for the benefit of the overseas sci-fi fans?\n\nWang Jinkang: Seeds of Mercury is a two-threaded story. The first one follows a female scientist named Shawu, who discovers a new formula for life, and creates a fluid metal nano life form. When she dies, she entrusts that formula to Chen Yizhe, a businessman with a pure heart, along with the message \u201creal life cannot be bred in pens. In the Solar System, there happens to be a suitable place for it to breed freely \u2013 Mercury\u201d. Chen Yizhe accepts this monumental legacy enthusiastically, using his personal wealth to maintain the laboratory. In order take the next step, of \u201cseeding Mercury\u201d, he must turn to the society around him. Mr Hong, a multi-billionaire with a disagreeable personality but a benevolent soul, decides to liquidate his empire to facilitate the spaceship\u2019s construction. Furthermore, Hong makes another astonishing decision: to relocate to Mercury, have his body frozen in the millennia-old ice caves of the planet\u2019s north pole, to be awakened every 10 million years, to assist the evolution of these micro-lifeforms. In just 15 years, Chen Yizhe sends Hong to Mercury to seed the nano-life into the liquid metal lakes of Mercury, after which Hong settles down in its polar caves. Meanwhile, Hong\u2019s lawyer, and soulmate named Yin, bids her painful farewells from the distant Earth.\n\nThe second storyline is set 100 million years later, when the Suola race have evolved on Mercury, their metal bodies adapted to the hundred-degree temperatures of the planet. They are sustained by light (drawing energy directly by photosynthesis). With no sense of hearing, they rely on the flashing of light through two orifices in their abdomen to communicate in binary. The entire Suola race are devout followers of Shawu, venerate the Star Father, the great god Shawu and her earthly incarnation. They have been initiated in science, and after studying their Holy Book, scientist Tu Lala discovers that much scientific knowledge has been disguised and hidden within. From this he deduces that life on Mercury originates from The Blue Planet. He implores the high priest to send an expedition to search for the Holy Site in the depths of the ice, with the excuse of reviving the incarnation of Shawu, as the Book prophesied. The high priest consents, sending a chaplain to supervise the mission. Tu Lala actually locates the Holy Site, and discovers the incarnation of Shawu (Mr Hong), frozen in the ice, along the sacred rites of \u201chow to revive the incarnation of Shawu\u201d.\n\nHowever, unexpected occurrences, mainly due to the ignorance and blind devotion of the believers, result in Tulala\u2019s unfortunate violent death (as metallic organisms, the Suola can easily resurrect after a sudden death, but those who do are considered an untouchable caste). In order to protect Mr Hong\u2019s body, Tu lala risks the humiliation, but tragically, his student Qi Qiaqia denounces him, exposing his untouchable status, and inciting the crowd to him, During which time, Mr Hong\u2019s body is destroyed in the scorching sunlight. To avoid blame, Qi Qiaqia suddenly declares that the incarnation of Shawu was a false god, which is why the Father Star could destroy it. This narrative is accepted by the devotees, who hail him as their new high priest. In the thousands of years that follow, Suola society descends into darkness, religious cruelly suppressing science, but from among the population comes a new \u201cSect of Repentance\u201d, apparently founded by an untouchable. Silently they preserve everything related to science, awaiting the next rebirth of Shawu in future millennia.\n\nQ3Seeds of Mercury was first published in 2002, and its appeal still endures, even after all this time. What inspired you to write this story?\n\nWang Jinkang: The initial inspiration probably came from a sad epiphany I had as a teenager. The human body is too fragile. Our proteins start to coagulate above 80\u00b0C, our brain suffers irreversible damage if we don\u2019t breathe for five minutes, our body can\u2019t withstand radiation, and we can die from disease, hunger, dehydration, drowning and freezing\u2026 It\u2019s admirable that such a fragile life form has been propagated on for billions of years, but it also makes me apprehensive that humanity would not survive a disaster. Human civilisation is a great achievement, which is why we are proud of it; but it also makes me anxious, worrying that humanity may not survive the next cataclysm. I couldn\u2019t help but imagine, what if a creator, or god of evolution, created a metallic life, invulnerable to fire and flood? Many years later, I combined these youthful imaginings with my subsequent concept of \u201cTemplates for Life\u201d and turned it into this novella.\n\nQ4Seeds of Mercury is a piece about the sublime act of Creation, and a reflection on the transitory nature of life. Did you write it with the intention of exploring the contradiction between Science and Religion? Or did that grow naturally out of the creative process? Also, do the sentient beings you write about reflect your own views and positions?\n\nWang Jinkang: I didn\u2019t intend to construct that dichotomy between Science and Religion, but it\u2019s exactly what happened on Earth, so when I created a history for Mercury\u2019s civilisation, those episodes just appeared naturally. Religion and Science are enemies who love each other. European Papacy cruelly persecuted Galileo, Bruno, and other \u2018heretics\u2019, and strictly forbade the theory of evolution, but medieval Europe became the birthplace of modern science. When we look back at the history of Civilisation over millennia, you can\u2019t help but sigh that history is full of paradoxes, and that The Creator is always full of mischief, making fun of the theories of Cause and Effect. As to whether this new life carries some of my own views or positions? Of course. Tu Lala is the heir to the human spirit, with his scientific rationality, adventurous spirit, sense of responsibility, fortitude, and self-sacrifice. In the story, when Tu Lala meets the holy body of Shawu Incarnate, and he figures out that the great god was a scientist. Thus, demonstrating that the intellectual spirits of all scientists are inter-relatable, even if they are alien. That is what I believe in my heart.\n\nToday\u2019s AI isn\u2019t quite up to the standard of \u201cReturn of Adam\u201d\n\nQ5Mr. Wang, the world has moved on 22 years since the first publication of Seeds of Mercury. What changes do you think have occurred in science fiction writing in the present day, compared to the early years both in terms of the environment, and the core themes?\n\nWang Jinkang: These 22 years have brought great changes, and it could be said that civilisation has reached a critical point, that we\u2019re on the cusp of drastic changes. However, for the science fiction writer, who is used to seeing the world from a god-like point of view (through the eyes of science) we think in millennia, so 22 years is too short a period to affect the themes of my work. For example, my debut story Return of Adam showed a society where AI had overcome natural humanity, though it had taken on a parasitic approach, augmenting the processing power (IQ) of the human mind to far outstrip the basic brain, and in fact, became the core of human consciousness. The rapid development of AI today, especially the LLM systems, is amazing, even frightening, but in general, today\u2019s AI isn\u2019t quite up to the standards of Return of Adam. Still, I\u2019m saddened that some things I wrote about, which I assumed would be far in the future have come to pass in my lifetime. For example, in 1997, when many Chinese people asserted that AI could never triumph in the field of Weiqi (Go), I was convinced it eventually would, and wrote a scene of an \u2018AI beating a human chess master\u2019 in one of my stories, before it actually happened. I just never expected to see it in my lifetime.\n\nQ6Before Liu Cixin appeared, you \u201cheld up half the sky\u201d in Chinese Sci-fi. When you first appeared in China\u2019s science fiction circles, you were relatively older, and more experienced. Do you think that maturity allowed your work to appear more rounded?\n\nWang Jinkang: My life and experiences have been quite unique. I\u2019ve lived through a very special time in China\u2019s history, worked as a rusticated youth, a miner and model maker. I went to university at 30, became a mechanical engineer, wrote literary novels, and only broke into the science fiction world by chance at 45, publishing my first sci-fi story. If anything, my near-fanatical reading of literature at university paved the way for my future writing. At that time, the reforms were already happening in China, and it was opening up to the world. A huge amount of foreign literature was pouring into the country, dazzling readers like me. There may be another special factor, which is, because I was studying engineering, I was standing atop this wall of science and watching this river of literature racing by, I had a sense of detachment. Add to that I only started writing SF decades after experiencing the rise, fall and distilling of the wave of literature. I suppose that\u2019s why my writing style has a poised, bleak, and sombre character.\n\nQ7What sort of stories do you think are expected from the current literary ecosystem? Which sci-fi genres do you expect to take off in the future?\n\nWang Jinkang: I have always felt that science fiction is unlike any other form of literature. The richness of mainstream literature does not necessarily coincide with the strength of a country. As the aphorisms go, \u201cclassics are born from chaos\u201d, and \u201cpoets are fortunate when the country is not\u201d. However, the success of science fiction is reliant on enough readers and authors being educated to a certain threshold, and so depends on the country\u2019s economic, scientific, and technological development, which can be proven by the movement of science fiction\u2019s centre from Britain and France to the United States over the last century. Over the past 40 years, China\u2019s overall economic development has been good, and as one of the oldest sci-fi writers in the country, I\u2019ve experienced this first-hand. I feel that as China continues to modernise and converge with the rest of the world, the creative environment of Chinese sci-fi will continue to improve. As for which themes, I feel will start to emerge? It\u2019s expected that artificial intelligence and space themes, with more emphasis on exploring the human condition, are going to be the stories of importance, but other themes will also develop immensely.\n\nScience fiction writers are used to seeing the world from a god-like viewpoint.\n\nQ8 Mr. Wang, science fiction has taken root in China now for around a century, and you have played a pivotal role in the history of science fiction in the country. Irrespective of whether or not you win this Hugo Award, you have influenced a generation of sci-fi fans and creators. How do you view your own Creative Achievements?\n\nWang Jinkang: I\u2019m flattered, but I only really played a leading and inductive role in the early stages of the so-called \u201cNew Generation\u201d of Chinese sci-fi back in the 1990s. I\u2019m content with the two aspects of my writing career, firstly, in forming the genre of Philosophical Science Fiction, which is based on the latest technological advances, and digs deep into the influence it has on alienation, civilisation, and so forth, to discover this genre\u2019s philosophical uniqueness. This genre did not originate in my work, foreign writers including Mr. Arthur C. Clarke have long created excellent works of philosophical sci-fi, but these elements in my work are more concentrated. Furthermore, with regards science fiction as \u201cthe most cosmopolitan form of literature\u201d, I consider my work, whilst still cosmopolitan, to be imbued heavily with Chinese styles and themes, which adds a certain flavour to the genre.\n\nQ9Do you feel that science fiction writing is shifting from short-form to long form, and what difficulties do you feel are associated with that?\n\nWang Jinkang: In my experience there are three main issues faced when moving into the long-form. Firstly, there must be enough knowledge, from the accumulation of experience and information. Secondly, there must be a more mature view of Nature and human society, in their entirety. These are not necessarily the dominant trait of the novel but will play important roles in the story\u2019s development. Thirdly, the ability to comprehend the entirety of the larger story. This ability to grasp the complete story is equally important to mainstream literary writers, but in science fiction, concepts always play a driving role in the whole work and should be logically consistent in themselves.\n\nQ10In your eyes, what is the role of Morality and Ethics in Science Fiction?\n\nWang Jinkang: Science fiction authors often look at the world from a godlike point of view, and in the eyes of a creator, survival comes first, and morality and ethics are just auxiliary codes established by humans once they reached a certain level of civilisation. They are also conducive to the overall survival of the human race. As Humanity develops, and \u201cco-operation\u201d becomes more central to society, the role of morality and ethics becomes more and more important, but they certainly won\u2019t stay the same, and the rules will certainly have additions and deletions. For example, once technology becomes suitably advance, the ethics of \u201cstrict prohibition regarding editing the genes of a human being\u201d are very likely to change.\n\nQ11Throughout your career, which of your stories are you most satisfied with?\n\nWang Jinkang: Of my short and medium length works, I like Seeds of Mercury\u2019, Bee Keepers and The Song of Life, and of my longer works, I\u2019m most satisfied with Ant\u2019s Life and the Alive Trilogy (Escape From The Mother Universe, Parents of Heaven And Earth, and Cosmic Crystal Eggs).\n\nThank you, reader, for giving meaning to my life.\n\nQ12Mr. Wang, some sci-fi fans have pointed out you are \u2018the oldest non-American writer shortlisted for the Hugo Award\u2019, which is an impressive feat. What are your hopes for the Hugo Awards?\n\nWang Jinkang: There\u2019s a bit of a special circumstance here, where a story I wrote 22 years ago, was only translated into English last year, and shortlisted according to the translation\u2019s publication date, even though, I\u2019m very happy to hold this \u201cWorld Record\u201d. I hope it will go further than just being a finalist, but even if it doesn\u2019t, I still consider it a great honour to be shortlisted.\n\nQ13What would you like to say to the readers regarding the inclusion of Seeds of Mercury in the Hugo Awards shortlist, which was voted for by individual sci-fi fans one after another?\n\nWang Jinkang: I\u2019ve always had a reverence for my readers. The two most common inscriptions I write to fans at signings are \u201cThe reader is the god of authors\u201d, and \u201cThank you reader, for giving meaning to my life\u201d. Out of the millions of publications each year, in a sea of stories, to have any number of people read your work, enjoy it, and keep it in their memory after that relentless tide of time, is a rare blessing. One might even call it a great gift from the readers to the author.\n\n\nDiscover more from File 770\n\nSubscribe to get the latest posts sent to your email.","url":"https://file770.com/interview-with-wang-jinkang-2024-hugo-finalist/"},"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305":{"id":"764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b_389925305","text":"Monday 27 December 2021\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\n\u201cStudies in Scientific Literature. \u201d\nA book that explores the features of science fiction in Arabic works\nScience fiction literature has witnessed a wide presence in Arab creative writings despite its emergence and prosperity in the Western world, and despite its creative popularity, it has not received sufficient critical attention. Based on this idea, the Syrian writer and critic Ahmed Ali Mohammed observes the features and features of science fiction in Arabic literature, both ancient and modern, in his book \"Studies in Science Literature\", recently published in the series of studies by the Arab Writers Union.\nThe Syrian researcher believes that the Arab criticism has overlooked the literature of science fiction, citing a number of arguments such as the immaturity of this type of writing in the Arab world, and the disregard of his writers for the features of literary writing, as well as the lack of scientific knowledge, which the writer considers weak, especially with the presence of remarkable writings in this field succeeded in setting a firm foot and overcome many shortcomings.\nLeadership in scientific literature\nAli points out that the philosophical messages of Avicenna and Ibn Tufayl can be considered as the beginning of the link in ancient Arabic literature between literature and science, as the Arab heritage includes philosophical messages written in successive times that represented the basis of literary thinking based on science fiction, the most prominent of these messages: \"The message of Hayy bin Yaqzan\" by Avicenna.\nShahabuddeen al-Sahrawardi \u2019 s \u201cStrange Alienation \u201d message is inspired by the story of the neighborhood of Ben Yaqzan, and Ibn al-Nafees \u2019 s\u201c Perfect Letter \u201d in which he followed the example of his predecessors.\nThe author says of the relevance of these letters to science fiction: \"These letters draw a narrative basis based on the facts of science, elaborate on the imagination based on thought and knowledge, and depict part of the knowledge of their owners.\nThe most prominent aspect of these letters is the narrative imager related to the facts of science and the perceptions of philosophy, which confirms the existence of seeds of scientific literature in the Arabs. \u201d\nScience Fiction Poetry\nThe writer points out that science fiction literature has been associated with narrative forms, was raised with the French writer Jules Verne, who published the first story in science fiction literature in 1863 entitled \"Five Weeks in a Balloon\" and then wrote another story entitled \"Journey to the Hollow of the Earth\" and then continued productions, including the novel \"Time Machine\" by George Wells and others.\nScience fiction poetry is rare, including the poem \"The Asteroid\" by Russian poet Nikolai Glazkov, translated by Al-Azhar University professor Ahmed Shafiq al-Khatib, a poem based on the achievements of science fiction literature in terms of prediction, foresight and time travel.\nCriticism of scientific literature\nSome of the works of Tawfiq al-Hakim include The Year of One Million (1953), which is dominated by philosophical consideration of life, nature and the universe, and his play Journey to Tomorrow (1958), which involves a forward-looking view of the future related to man \u2019 s struggle with time, as well as his play \u201cFood for Every Mouth \u201d.\" In which he talks about the problem of food that people will suffer from in the future, and his play \"The Prayer of Angels\", which deals with the impact of science on the happiness of humanity and the provision of its needs.\nPolitical fiction literature\nThe writer monitors the branches of science fiction literature that not only addressed the problems of the environment, pollution, space and planets, but touched the problems of politics, society and economy through the literature of political fiction, which includes under its banner the literature of utopia and dystopia.\nThere are a number of writings concerned with depicting Utopia, which means a utopia without trace of corruption, evil or injustice, the most prominent of these writings is Thomas Moore \u2019 s \u201cUtopia \u201d, which depicts an ideal world critical of the political, religious and social conditions of his time.\nThe literature of dystopia comes in contrast to utopia, but they belong under the name of political fiction, which is a branch of science fiction literature, as each deals with political life by storytelling accompanied by fiction, and dystopia means the literature of the corrupt city or the world of bitter reality that depicts a society full of corruption and highlights the phenomena of destruction, murder and destruction and transformation of human beings. A feuding.\nThe author mentions a number of Western and Arabic writings that have emerged in the field of dystopia, including George Orwell \u2019 s 1984, Aldous Huxley \u2019 s Brave New World, and Ray Bradbury \u2019 s Fahrenheit 451.\nAt the level of Arabic writings, a number of works can be observed such as the novel \"The Front\" by Izz al-Din Issa, the novel \"The Tale of the Last Arab\" by Wassini al-Araj, \"Frankenstein in Baghdad\" by Ahmed Saadawi, \"The Second War of the Dog\" by Ibrahim Nasrallah, \"Mercury\" by Mohammed Rabie, \"The Line\" by Basma Abdul Aziz, and \"Novelist of the First City\" by Omar Hazek. And \"Orwell in the Southern Suburbs\" by Fawzi Thebian.\nLiterary Studies\nIn his book, the Syrian critic offers critical readings in a number of works under the banner of science fiction literature, including the novel \"Hala al-Nour\" by Mohammed al-Ashri, seeking to stand on the aesthetic trend, especially with the departure of literary criticism from the study of the aesthetic aspects of science fiction literature, observing the methods of the novelist mixing the facts of science with the world mythical heritage.\nThe book provides another analysis of the collection \u201cBehind the Dark Walls \u201d by the Syrian writer Taleb Omran, which falls within the literature of dystopia, because the stories depict worlds in which savagery, destruction, murder and destruction prevail, and on the other hand it monitors the Syrian storyteller \u2019 s interest in the method of scientific storytelling and its reliance on astronomical knowledge and geographical information.\nThe writer also analyzes the elements and features of fantasy in some of the works of Ahmed Khaled Tawfik as one of the most prominent writers in this field, explaining that science fiction is different from fantasy or wonder in the contemporary novel in that it starts from the modern scientific output, and depends on scientific knowledge specialized, while fantasy completely degenerates from logic and depends on the imagination and does not find a trace of laws we know in reality and depends on mythological and form It is in harmony not with the outside world but with its own world according to which it takes place.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0037.json.gz:52003","uncompressed_offset":389925305,"url":"www.dostor.org/3667088","warc_date":"2021-12-27T10:20:53.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:764901a5-ae9e-4bb0-be99-00e9fcaa1a8b>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/3667088"},"created":"2021-12-27T10:53:56.000Z","lang":"eng"},"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":{"id":"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677","text":"Science Fiction and Politics in Literature and the Arts (Symposium, Toulouse)\n\nScience Fiction and Politics in Literature and the Arts\n\nThe aim of this symposium run by the LLA-Cr\u00e9atis laboratory at the University of Toulouse Jean-Jaur\u00e8s is to develop open thinking about \u201cpolitical\u201d questions, in the broad sense of the term, that science fiction narratives allow. Different types of stories can be considered, in different literary genres or in cinema, video series and comics. It can be studied and interrogated from a historical, political and social perspective by involving, where appropriate, the possible contributions of different analyzes (anthropology, semiotics, feminist studies, postcolonial studies, etc.) Diversity of perspectives and questions raised by gender.\n\nThe entire twentieth-century period produced works in San Francisco that were marked by ideologies such as capitalism and its \u201ccommunist\u201d counterpart, but also by threats associated with civilian and/or military nuclear power, religious-related abuses, racism, minority liberation struggles, and pollution. , etc. These perceptions persisted, but in the period from the last 20 years of the 20th century to the first 20 years of the 21st century, other concerns were voiced: ecological pesticides, the climate crisis, demographic crises, resource depletion, or the danger. The scientific and technical potential (transhumanism, \u201cartificial intelligence\u201d, etc.) is being carried away.\n\nThe link to the realities of the times (as in the collection \u201cLe Passager Clandestin / Dyschroniques\u201d) can of course depend on one or more authors, take into account a work or compare several (especially in the case of short stories and short films). The broader perspective will consist in considering the basic ideologies, either in relation to the literary prizes awarded, or in relation to the works themselves, the semantics of these presenting themselves from the outset sometimes as criticism, sometimes as propaganda, the two being able to be combined according to modalities that tend to be ironic, Satirical, disruptive, etc.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The number of dengue fever cases is on the rise\n\nIn any case, it would be a matter of highlighting the \u201cexploratory potential\u201d in these works, of identifying the \u201cproblematic tools\u201d and of making the ideas put forward in fictional form productive from the point of view of political theory. (Y Rambhala).\n\nOf course, it is advisable to include works belonging to different geographical and linguistic fields so that the panorama of this search is sufficiently realistic.\n\nProvisional schedule of courses (date adjustments possible)\n\nOct 20, 2-4 PM / Nov 17, 2-4 PM / Dec 15, 2-4 PM / Jan 19, 2-4 PM / Feb 9, 2-4 PM / Mar 15, 2-4 PM / May 31 , 2-4 p.m\n\nContribution proposals must be sent Before October 1, 2023 To the following addresses: frederics[email\u00a0protected], [email\u00a0protected], [email\u00a0protected]","url":"https://www.vaughantoday.ca/science-fiction-and-politics-in-literature-and-the-arts-symposium-toulouse/"}}}
