uch as Ethiopia, Kenya, Nigeria, and Egypt."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"In 2022, six of the 15 largest new investment mega projects announced were in Africa, with Egypt witnessing an increase in foreign direct investment of more than double to $11 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The number of new projects in Africa has more than doubled to 161, and the value of international project financing transactions has increased by two-thirds to $24 billion."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"European countries remain the most important investors in Africa, led by investors from the United Kingdom and France, with increased investments in renewable energy."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"The number of international projects in the field of renewable energies in Africa increased to an estimated 71 projects, almost double the 36 projects recorded in 2020."}],"references":["da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125","b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898","a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782","e3d3bec1-19f0-4d60-a67f-c8cb4d639ade_764369635","df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718"],"documents":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":{"id":"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nIt has reached $11 billion.\nUN highlights doubling of foreign direct investment in Egypt\nThe United Nations Trade and Development Board (UNCTAD) said in its annual report on foreign direct investment flows for the year 2022, on Wednesday in Geneva, that Egypt witnessed an increase in foreign direct investment more than doubled to $11 billion as a result of increased cross-border M & A sales.\nInvestment flows to Africa fell to $45 billion in 2022 from a record $80 billion in 2021 and accounted for 3.5 percent of global foreign direct investment, the report said, adding that international project financing deals targeting Africa showed a 47 percent drop in value.\nThe report pointed out that the number of announcements of new projects increased by 39% to 766, and that six of the 15 largest new investment mega projects (those worth more than $10 billion) announced in 2022 were in Africa, stressing that Egypt witnessed an increase in foreign direct investment more than doubled to $11 billion as a result of increased cross-border M & A sales.\nThe number of new projects has more than doubled to 161, and the value of international project financing transactions has increased by two-thirds to $24 billion.\nFDI inflows have risen over the past five years in four of the continent \u2019 s regional economic groupings, with FDI in the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) growing by 14% to $22 billion, and inflows also rising in the Southern African Development Community (SADC) (quadrupled to $10 billion) and the West African Economic and Monetary Union (WEMU) (doubled to $5.2 billion). East African Community (up 9% to $3.8 billion).\nAccording to the report, the largest increase in 2022 was in new field projects announced in energy and gas supply (to $120 billion from $24 billion in 2021), and the value of projects in construction and extractive industries rose to $24 billion and $21 billion, respectively, while the information and communication sector recorded the largest number of projects.\nEuropean investors remain by far the largest owners of FDI in Africa, led by the United Kingdom ($60 billion), France ($54 billion) and the Netherlands ($54 billion).","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0019.json.gz:45070","uncompressed_offset":660205898,"url":"www.dostor.org/4441108","warc_date":"2023-07-05T12:52:23.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4441108"},"created":"2023-07-05T13:20:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":{"id":"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","text":"Japan, Korea and India experience to expand Africa, Taiwan and Africa entrepreneurs association\nThe \u201cTaiwan-Africa Entrepreneurs Association \u201d, commissioned by the International Trade Bureau of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, attracted more than 130 enterprises interested in exploring the African market. The exhibition and consultation desk at the representative office showed that our company's desire to expand the African market is very hot.\nThe theme of the event was \u201cThe Key to Success for Foreign Investors (Japan, Korea and India) in Expanding Africa \u201d. The event was addressed by Wang Ximeng, Secretary General of the Foreign Trade Association, Liu William, Deputy Director of the Bureau of International Trade of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, Msibi, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Swaziland, and Chen Shu-fang, President of the Association of Taiwan Commerce. In addition, Hung Sheng Packaging General Manager Tang Jung-hung, Yi Ho Industrial General Manager Fu Yang-li, and Nam Wei Industrial Strategy Director Yang Wei-han analyze the development opportunities in Africa from their practical experience in the packaging, building materials, and textile industries.\nWang Ximeng, secretary general of the Foreign Trade Association, pointed out that in addition to the competition between Europe, America and China over the layout of the African continent, Japan, South Korea, India and other countries in Asia are committed to increasing investment and economic cooperation in Africa.\nThere are more than 1.3 million people of Indian descent in Africa, such as in East Africa, where more than 60% of the economic lifeline is controlled by Indians.\nIn addition, 18 of India's 25 newly established embassies and consulates are located in Africa, and India has become the fifth largest investor in Africa, while Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba have already planted flags in Africa; South Korea's Hyundai, Samsung, LG and other large enterprises have also been stationed in Africa.\nThrough this event, we hope to help our business people to learn from foreign companies such as Japan, Korea and India, as well as African market leaders, and shorten the path to enter the African market.\nLiu, deputy director of the International Trade Bureau, said that in recent years, the global economy has continued to be volatile due to changes in the international situation such as Sino-US trade frictions, global inflation, and the Russian-Ukrainian war, but Africa has shown great resilience during this period.\nIn addition, foreign direct investment in Africa reached US $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered. In 2022, the total import and export value of Africa reached a new high in recent years, with imports reaching US $694.5 billion, up 14%, and exports reaching US $661.4 billion, up 19%. It is hoped that through the activities of the association, upstream and downstream companies in various industries can learn from each other and share their experiences, and work together to promote Taiwan-Africa economic and trade relations.\nThe event will be held in conjunction with AGOA, a major textile manufacturer in South China, and the representative offices of African embassies in Taiwan, Africa-related associations, and import and export banks providing trade and financial services. For more information, please visit africa.taiwantrade.com for more information.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0024.json.gz:5975","uncompressed_offset":494470718,"url":"ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html","warc_date":"2023-08-17T03:05:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e>","warc_url":"https://ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html"},"created":"2023-08-17T03:43:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e3d3bec1-19f0-4d60-a67f-c8cb4d639ade_764369635":{"id":"e3d3bec1-19f0-4d60-a67f-c8cb4d639ade_764369635","text":"British International Investment Plc (BII) aims to invest $60 billion in Africa over the coming five years, Bloomberg reported on July 27th.\n\nThe investments will be made in several fields including renewable power and digital infrastructure, along with supporting women-owned businesses.\n\nBII will pay attention to the powerhouse markets in Ethiopia, Kenya, Nigeria, and Egypt, with the investments being focused on the private sector.\n\nThe support plan, which is a part of a global program worth $10 billion, covers a $76 million contribution to a $500 million fund being arranged by Old Mutual Ltd\u2019s African Infrastructure Investment Managers.\n\nFor his part, BII\u2019s CEO Nick O\u2019Donohoe said in an interview that his fully-owned company by the UK has been a major investor in power, particularly renewable energy, in Africa over the past three or four years.\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2022 Arab Finance Brokerage Company All rights reserved. Provided by SyndiGate Media Inc. (Syndigate.info).","url":"https://www.zawya.com/en/economy/africa/uks-bii-plans-60bln-investments-in-africa-within-5-years-tb2xfckg"},"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782":{"id":"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782","text":"Global investors waiting to pour in money in Africa to firewall China\n\nBy IANS | Published: August 2, 2021 02:09 PM2021-08-02T14:09:05+5:302021-08-02T14:25:34+5:30\n\nNew Delhi, Aug 2: After a tepid inflow of foreign direct investments (FDI) into Africa in 2020 amid the ...\n\nNext\n\nNew Delhi, Aug 2: After a tepid inflow of foreign direct investments (FDI) into Africa in 2020 amid the Covid-19, investors are once again warming up to the continent. According to the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), FDI flows into Africa declined by 16 per cent in 2020 to $40 billion, from $47 billion in 2019.\n\nChina, the primary investor in the continent, has also slowed down its investments into the continent leaving an opportunity for other investors.\n\nWhile the UNCTAD projected FDI inflow into Africa to grow this year, it said that the slow vaccine roll-out programme is a cause for concern. According to UNCTAD, FDI to the continent is projected to grow by only 5 per cent in 2021. But analysts said Africa as an investment destination has led to \"an unprecedented curiosity\" among other countries, which are now aggressively looking to mute China's dominance in the continent.\n\n\"Africa is critical in the new geopolitical and geo-economic contours. The continent, with its vast natural resources, offers a ready growth platform,\" an analyst told India Narrative.\n\nAccording to a study published by Brookings Institution last week, Africa is home to 17 per cent of the world population. However, by 2050, it will have 26 per cent of the global population 2.53 billion people. \"If Africa is not successfully integrated into the global economy, there could be a major threat to global prosperity and stability,\" the study said, adding that by 2050, the continent will be home to an estimated $16.12 trillion of combined consumer and business spending.\n\nThe African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA) \u2013 the mega trade could give a push to intra-continental investment.\n\nTouted as one of the biggest trade deals in the world, the AfCTA aims to create a single market comprising 1.3 billion people with a combined GDP of about $3.4 trillion.\n\nMeanwhile, the US may have woken up late in recognising the potential of Africa but is making all attempts to make up for the lost time.\n\nThe Group of Seven or G7 has already decided to support US President Joe Biden's proposal of carving out a mega infrastructure plan under the \"Build Back Better World\" (B3W) initiative, expected to bring in transparency and sustainability. Besides, the initiative will be carried out only in consultation with local communities.\n\nThe G7 in its meeting in June also announced that it will increase its support to the Indo Pacific and Africa. \"We resolve to collaborate with partners around the world, including in the Indo-Pacific and Africa, to actively promote these shared values for the good of all,\" said the statement.\n\nIndia too has pressed the pedal on investments in the region. Sources said that the still-born Asia Africa Growth Corridor\u2014the mega infrastructure project that was launched in 2017 to connect Asia and Africa must be revived.\n\nCarnegie Endowment for International Peace noted that Chinese financiers committed $153 billion to African public sector borrowers between 2000 and 2019. \"After rapid growth in the 2000s, annual lending commitments to Africa peaked in 2013, the year the BRI was launched. By 2019, though, new Chinese loan commitments amounted to only $7 billion to the continent, down 30 percent from $9.9 billion in 2018,\" it said.\n\nDisclaimer: This post has been auto-published from an agency feed without any modifications to the text and has not been reviewed by an editor\n\nOpen in app","url":"https://english.lokmat.com/international/global-investors-waiting-to-pour-in-money-in-africa-to-firewall-china/"},"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":{"id":"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125","text":"FDI flows to North Africa down 5% in 2021\nForeign direct investment to North Africa fell 5 percent to $9.3 billion for the whole of 2021, according to a report on \u201cInvesting in the World \u201d released by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) on June 9, 2022.\nThese investments, towards Tunisia, improved slightly from $652 million in 2020 to $660 million in 2021.\nThe same investment to Morocco increased by 52 percent to 2.2 billion dollars in 2021, compared with a 12 percent drop to 1.5 billion dollars in Egypt.\nDespite the decline in these investments in Egypt, it remains the second country to benefit from the inflow of foreign direct investment in Africa.\nAccording to the same report, the flow of foreign direct investment in Africa reached a record level of $83 billion for the whole of 2021, more than double the investment achieved for the whole of 2020.\nDespite this significant growth, the flow of investment to Africa in 2021 represented only 5.2 percent of the global total, compared to 4.1 percent in 2020.\nMost African countries saw a slight increase in foreign direct investment (FDI) in 2021.\nThese investments developed in South, East and West Africa, while they maintained their previous levels in Central Africa, while declining in North Africa.\nEuropeans remain the most important investors in Africa, led by investors from the United Kingdom ($65 billion) and France ($60 billion).\nIncreased investments in renewable energy\nDespite the overall positive trend of foreign direct investment towards Africa, the announcement of new projects remained weak at $39 billion and shows only a weak recovery compared to $32 billion recorded in 2020 and less than $77 billion recorded in 2019.\nIn parallel, the number of international projects in the field of renewable energies in Africa increased to an estimated 71 projects, almost double the 36 projects completed in 2011.\nAmong these projects is a $20 billion project that aims to export wind energy to the UK from Morocco.\nBy laying 3,800 km of submarine cables.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0018.json.gz:4737","uncompressed_offset":927341125,"url":"ar.webmanagercenter.com/2022/06/15/337032/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D9%81%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AB%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%86%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8/","warc_date":"2022-06-15T13:37:53.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d>","warc_url":"https://ar.webmanagercenter.com/2022/06/15/337032/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D9%81%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AB%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%86%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8/"},"created":"2022-06-15T14:14:26.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1032","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1032","narrative_id":"1032"},"responses":[{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Foreign investment in Africa has been on the rise in recent years, with the continent attracting significant amounts of foreign direct investment (FDI)."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"According to the African Development Bank (AfDB), Egypt ranked second in terms of foreign direct investment flows in the continent in 2021, attracting nearly $5.1 billion."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"South Africa was the largest recipient of foreign direct investment in 2021, with investments of more than $40.9 billion, nearly half of the total inflows to the continent in that year."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Mozambique also attracted significant investments, with foreign direct investment increasing by 68% in 2021, largely directed to green projects in the energy sector."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"The report by the AfDB expected Egypt's GDP growth rate to decline to 4.4% this year from 6.6% estimated last year, and to rise to 5.1% next year."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"In terms of geographical areas, foreign investment has been concentrated in South, East, and West Africa, while maintaining previous levels in Central Africa and declining in North Africa."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The largest increase in foreign direct investment was in new field projects, with the number of new projects more than doubling to 161, and the value of international project financing transactions increasing by two-thirds to $24 billion."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"The bulk of foreign direct investment in African countries is increasingly going to clean energy resource projects, with the number of international projects in the field of renewable energies in Africa increasing to an estimated 71 projects."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Major foreign companies that have made significant investments in Africa include Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba, as well as South Korean companies such as Hyundai, Samsung, and LG."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The UAE real estate company Reportage has also announced a real estate project worth $1.5 billion in Egypt."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"African entities that have formed partnerships with foreign companies in recent years include the Egyptian government, which has partnered with foreign companies to develop green projects in the energy sector."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The total foreign direct investment in Africa reached $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"The flow of investment to Africa in 2021 represented only 5.2 percent of the global total, compared to 4.1 percent in 2020."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"Europeans remain the most important investors in Africa, led by investors from the United Kingdom ($65 billion) and France ($60 billion)."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The volume of foreign direct investment flows to North Africa declined by 5% to $9.3 billion last year."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The number of new green projects in Egypt has more than tripled to $5.6 billion, according to the UNCTAD report."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The acquisition of one company by another has been a significant type of foreign direct investment in Africa, with the UAE Holding \"ADQ\" acquiring several Egyptian companies."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The decline in stock prices on the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar has encouraged this type of rapid investment."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The FDI inflows have risen over the past five years in four of the continent's regional economic groupings, with FDI in the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) growing by 14% to $22 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The Southern African Development Community (SADC) has also seen a significant increase in FDI, quadrupling to $10 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The West African Economic and Monetary Union (WEMU) has seen FDI inflows double to $5.2 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The East African Community has seen FDI inflows increase by 9% to $3.8 billion."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Overall, foreign investment in Africa is expected to continue growing, with significant opportunities for investment in clean energy, green projects, and other sectors."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The continent's resilience in the face of global economic volatility has made it an attractive destination for foreign investors."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"As the African economy continues to grow, it is likely that foreign investment will play a significant role in shaping the continent's future."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Foreign investment in Africa has been on the rise in recent years, with the continent attracting significant amounts of foreign direct investment (FDI)."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"According to the African Development Bank (AfDB), Egypt ranked second in terms of foreign direct investment flows in the continent in 2021, attracting nearly $5.1 billion."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"South Africa was the largest recipient of foreign direct investment in 2021, with investments of more than $40.9 billion, nearly half of the total inflows to the continent in that year."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Mozambique also attracted significant investments, with foreign direct investment increasing by 68% in 2021, largely directed to green projects in the energy sector."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"The report by the AfDB expected Egypt's GDP growth rate to decline to 4.4% this year from 6.6% estimated last year, and to rise to 5.1% next year."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"In terms of geographical areas, foreign investment has been concentrated in South, East, and West Africa, while maintaining previous levels in Central Africa and declining in North Africa."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The largest increase in foreign direct investment was in new field projects, with the number of new projects more than doubling to 161, and the value of international project financing transactions increasing by two-thirds to $24 billion."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"The bulk of foreign direct investment in African countries is increasingly going to clean energy resource projects, with the number of international projects in the field of renewable energies in Africa increasing to an estimated 71 projects."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Major foreign companies that have made significant investments in Africa include Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba, as well as South Korean companies such as Hyundai, Samsung, and LG."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The UAE real estate company Reportage has also announced a real estate project worth $1.5 billion in Egypt."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"African entities that have formed partnerships with foreign companies in recent years include the Egyptian government, which has partnered with foreign companies to develop green projects in the energy sector."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The total foreign direct investment in Africa reached $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"The flow of investment to Africa in 2021 represented only 5.2 percent of the global total, compared to 4.1 percent in 2020."},{"citations":{"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":1.0},"text":"Europeans remain the most important investors in Africa, led by investors from the United Kingdom ($65 billion) and France ($60 billion)."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The volume of foreign direct investment flows to North Africa declined by 5% to $9.3 billion last year."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The number of new green projects in Egypt has more than tripled to $5.6 billion, according to the UNCTAD report."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The acquisition of one company by another has been a significant type of foreign direct investment in Africa, with the UAE Holding \"ADQ\" acquiring several Egyptian companies."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The decline in stock prices on the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar has encouraged this type of rapid investment."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The FDI inflows have risen over the past five years in four of the continent's regional economic groupings, with FDI in the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) growing by 14% to $22 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The Southern African Development Community (SADC) has also seen a significant increase in FDI, quadrupling to $10 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The West African Economic and Monetary Union (WEMU) has seen FDI inflows double to $5.2 billion."},{"citations":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":1.0},"text":"The East African Community has seen FDI inflows increase by 9% to $3.8 billion."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"Overall, foreign investment in Africa is expected to continue growing, with significant opportunities for investment in clean energy, green projects, and other sectors."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The continent's resilience in the face of global economic volatility has made it an attractive destination for foreign investors."},{"citations":{"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":1.0},"text":"As the African economy continues to grow, it is likely that foreign investment will play a significant role in shaping the continent's future."}],"references":["a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754","da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125","b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898","df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495"],"documents":{"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898":{"id":"b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e_660205898","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nIt has reached $11 billion.\nUN highlights doubling of foreign direct investment in Egypt\nThe United Nations Trade and Development Board (UNCTAD) said in its annual report on foreign direct investment flows for the year 2022, on Wednesday in Geneva, that Egypt witnessed an increase in foreign direct investment more than doubled to $11 billion as a result of increased cross-border M & A sales.\nInvestment flows to Africa fell to $45 billion in 2022 from a record $80 billion in 2021 and accounted for 3.5 percent of global foreign direct investment, the report said, adding that international project financing deals targeting Africa showed a 47 percent drop in value.\nThe report pointed out that the number of announcements of new projects increased by 39% to 766, and that six of the 15 largest new investment mega projects (those worth more than $10 billion) announced in 2022 were in Africa, stressing that Egypt witnessed an increase in foreign direct investment more than doubled to $11 billion as a result of increased cross-border M & A sales.\nThe number of new projects has more than doubled to 161, and the value of international project financing transactions has increased by two-thirds to $24 billion.\nFDI inflows have risen over the past five years in four of the continent \u2019 s regional economic groupings, with FDI in the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) growing by 14% to $22 billion, and inflows also rising in the Southern African Development Community (SADC) (quadrupled to $10 billion) and the West African Economic and Monetary Union (WEMU) (doubled to $5.2 billion). East African Community (up 9% to $3.8 billion).\nAccording to the report, the largest increase in 2022 was in new field projects announced in energy and gas supply (to $120 billion from $24 billion in 2021), and the value of projects in construction and extractive industries rose to $24 billion and $21 billion, respectively, while the information and communication sector recorded the largest number of projects.\nEuropean investors remain by far the largest owners of FDI in Africa, led by the United Kingdom ($60 billion), France ($54 billion) and the Netherlands ($54 billion).","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0019.json.gz:45070","uncompressed_offset":660205898,"url":"www.dostor.org/4441108","warc_date":"2023-07-05T12:52:23.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b40e3169-b0e3-4e79-9135-979f85ff557e>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4441108"},"created":"2023-07-05T13:20:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":{"id":"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","text":"Japan, Korea and India experience to expand Africa, Taiwan and Africa entrepreneurs association\nThe \u201cTaiwan-Africa Entrepreneurs Association \u201d, commissioned by the International Trade Bureau of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, attracted more than 130 enterprises interested in exploring the African market. The exhibition and consultation desk at the representative office showed that our company's desire to expand the African market is very hot.\nThe theme of the event was \u201cThe Key to Success for Foreign Investors (Japan, Korea and India) in Expanding Africa \u201d. The event was addressed by Wang Ximeng, Secretary General of the Foreign Trade Association, Liu William, Deputy Director of the Bureau of International Trade of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, Msibi, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Swaziland, and Chen Shu-fang, President of the Association of Taiwan Commerce. In addition, Hung Sheng Packaging General Manager Tang Jung-hung, Yi Ho Industrial General Manager Fu Yang-li, and Nam Wei Industrial Strategy Director Yang Wei-han analyze the development opportunities in Africa from their practical experience in the packaging, building materials, and textile industries.\nWang Ximeng, secretary general of the Foreign Trade Association, pointed out that in addition to the competition between Europe, America and China over the layout of the African continent, Japan, South Korea, India and other countries in Asia are committed to increasing investment and economic cooperation in Africa.\nThere are more than 1.3 million people of Indian descent in Africa, such as in East Africa, where more than 60% of the economic lifeline is controlled by Indians.\nIn addition, 18 of India's 25 newly established embassies and consulates are located in Africa, and India has become the fifth largest investor in Africa, while Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba have already planted flags in Africa; South Korea's Hyundai, Samsung, LG and other large enterprises have also been stationed in Africa.\nThrough this event, we hope to help our business people to learn from foreign companies such as Japan, Korea and India, as well as African market leaders, and shorten the path to enter the African market.\nLiu, deputy director of the International Trade Bureau, said that in recent years, the global economy has continued to be volatile due to changes in the international situation such as Sino-US trade frictions, global inflation, and the Russian-Ukrainian war, but Africa has shown great resilience during this period.\nIn addition, foreign direct investment in Africa reached US $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered. In 2022, the total import and export value of Africa reached a new high in recent years, with imports reaching US $694.5 billion, up 14%, and exports reaching US $661.4 billion, up 19%. It is hoped that through the activities of the association, upstream and downstream companies in various industries can learn from each other and share their experiences, and work together to promote Taiwan-Africa economic and trade relations.\nThe event will be held in conjunction with AGOA, a major textile manufacturer in South China, and the representative offices of African embassies in Taiwan, Africa-related associations, and import and export banks providing trade and financial services. For more information, please visit africa.taiwantrade.com for more information.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0024.json.gz:5975","uncompressed_offset":494470718,"url":"ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html","warc_date":"2023-08-17T03:05:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e>","warc_url":"https://ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html"},"created":"2023-08-17T03:43:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495":{"id":"ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775_845790495","text":"AFED: EGYPT RECEIVED $5.1 BILLION INVESTMENTS IN 2021\nGDP growth is expected to rise to 4.4% this year\nAbdulrahman Abu Al-Enein\n6: 52 AM, Wednesday, 31 May 23\nRecent data issued by the African Development Bank (AfDB) revealed that Egypt ranked second in terms of foreign direct investment flows in the continent in 2021 and attracted nearly $5.1 billion.\nAccording to the Africa Economies Outlook 2023, South Africa was the largest recipient of foreign direct investment in 2021 with investments of more than $40.9 billion, nearly half of the total inflows to the continent in that year, followed by Egypt and Mozambique, which each attracted nearly $5.1 billion, representing about 6.2% of the total volume.\nIn the same context, the report expected Egypt \u2019 s GDP growth rate to decline to 4.4% this year from 6.6% estimated last year, and to rise to 5.1% next year.\nThe report pointed out that the inflation rate rose from 4.5% in the fiscal year 2020 / 2021 to 8.5% in the fiscal year 2021 / 2022 due to the rise in food and energy prices globally and the devaluation of the pound against the dollar.\nHe said that the current account deficit shrank to 3.5% of GDP in the fiscal year 2021 / 2022 compared to 4.4% in the previous fiscal year 2020 / 2021 due to the rise of tourism revenues to 10.7 billion dollars against 4.9 billion dollars, respectively.\nThe African Development Bank pointed out that the banking sector remains profitable and well capitalized, noting that the rate of non-performing loans reached 3.2% in June 2022, explaining that subsidies and social protection programs have reduced the impact of high food and energy prices on vulnerable families.\nThe Minister of Planning Hala Al-Said said in previous statements that despite the current effects of the Russian-Ukrainian crisis, which is likely to spread over the next year, the Egyptian economy is expected to grow by 4.2% by the end of the current fiscal year 2023-2022.\nAl-Saeed said that with the development of inflationary trends in the Egyptian economy and despite the success of the state in curbing it and reducing it from very high levels (25% in 2017-2016) to less than 5% in 2021-2020, the rate increased to about 15% in 2022, and continued to rise, especially after the Russian-Ukrainian crisis.\nForeign direct investment in Mozambique increased by 68% in 2021, the report said, noting that these investments were largely directed to green projects in the energy sector.\nNigeria accounted for 5.8% of FDI inflows to Africa and Ethiopia 5.1% despite economic challenges.\nThe bulk of foreign direct investment in these countries is increasingly going to clean energy resource projects.\nMauritius and South Africa recorded the largest outflows in 2021, but a few countries recorded net inflows, including Egypt ($18 billion) and Nigeria ($5.9 billion).\nThe Bank estimates that capital flight through net investment outflows continued in 2022 at around $28 billion, which is close to the 2021 level due to higher interest rates linked to deflationary monetary policies in developed countries.\nOfficial development assistance (ODA) to Africa stabilized at $65 billion in 2021 after the previous 28 percent jump in 2020.\nThe significant increase in such assistance since 2020 reflected the support provided by the international community to help African governments address the humanitarian, social and economic impacts of the coronavirus epidemic and the difficult global economic conditions.\nThe African countries that saw the largest increase in ODA in 2021 included Egypt (428%), Equatorial Guinea (115%), Angola (109%), Gabon (82%) and Sudan (60%).\nThe report pointed out that official development assistance to Egypt during 2021 amounted to about 8.2 billion dollars, Ethiopia 4 billion dollars, Sudan 3.8 billion dollars, the Democratic Republic of the Congo 3.5 billion dollars, Nigeria 3.4 billion dollars, and Kenya 3.1 billion dollars.\nAfrican countries need to leverage this external support to address existing vulnerabilities and build more resilient economies, given the risks that advanced economies are reallocating resources for reconstruction and humanitarian assistance in Ukraine at the expense of meeting the continent \u2019 s official development assistance commitments.\nUkraine received $16.1 billion in net official development assistance (ODA), equivalent to 7.8 percent of the total aid resources provided last year.\nIt is noteworthy that the report was launched in light of the annual meetings of the African Development Bank Group held under the auspices of President Abdel Fattah El Sisi in Sharm El Sheikh from 22 to 26 May.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0016.json.gz:14677","uncompressed_offset":845790495,"url":"almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B5%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%AA-5-1-%D9%85%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%AF/","warc_date":"2023-05-31T03:29:46.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ae292450-64e9-4526-be1f-0c7555974775>","warc_url":"https://almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B5%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%AA-5-1-%D9%85%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%AF/"},"created":"2023-05-31T04:39:19.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":{"id":"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754","text":"\u00ab Money \u00bb monitors the forecasts of economic analysts for foreign investment flows in the current year\nA number of them predicted it would reach $10 billion.\nSamar Al-Sayed\nPraying for Mahmood\n6: 59 AM, Wednesday, 27 Jul 22\nWael Ziadeh: The Russian-Ukrainian war is an opportunity for the Egyptian stock exchange to attract more capital\nEsraa Ahmed: Clean energy, infrastructure and digital financial services are the most attractive sectors\nHani Geneina: Companies should be encouraged to reinvest their profits instead of transferring them to parent entities abroad\nNaaman Khaled: Most of the money will come from Gulf markets\nThe Egyptian government aims to increase foreign direct investment flows, especially the Gulf, in the local market in the coming period, in light of the repercussions of the Russian-Ukrainian war on the global and local economies, and a number of analysts and macroeconomic experts estimated the value of these investments to reach $10 billion, driven by various factors, including the decline in the stock prices of companies on the stock exchange, and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar.\nThe latest report issued by UNCTAD in June on the volume of foreign investment flows in 15 African countries last year showed that Egypt ranked second in the list, recording the volume of flows about 5.122 billion dollars compared to 5.852 billion in 2020 compared to 9.010 billion in 2019.\nSouth Africa came first last year with a 1,235% jump in investment inflows of $40.889 billion compared to $3.062 billion in 2020 and $5.125 billion in 2019.\nWael Ziadeh, founder and CEO of Zela Capital, said that the Russian-Ukrainian war had negatively affected foreign direct investment flows in the world, while inter-state assistance had increased to counter the negative consequences of the war.\nHe explained to Al-Mal that these negative effects included the exit of investment flows from some emerging countries, which led to the impact of their trade balance, especially as their imports of food and oil more than their exports, for example Turkey and many European countries, as well as Sri Lanka.\nOn the other hand, the war represents a positive area for these countries, especially in activating the stock market sector, he said, adding that in this context, the Egyptian Exchange has opportunities to attract more foreign investments in the coming period.\nHe predicted that Egypt will take no more than six months to recover its trade balance once the war is over, as the prices of petroleum products and food will fall rapidly, as they rose rapidly after the outbreak of the war.\nThe objectives of the Egyptian government published in July 2021 in the second and final review report of the Credit Standby Arrangement Program signed with the International Monetary Fund, amounting to about $5.4 billion, indicated that the percentage of net foreign direct investments of GDP will rise to 2.5% in the current fiscal year compared to 2% in the last fiscal year, adding that it recorded 1.4% in the fiscal year 2021 / 2020, 2% in 2019 and 2.6% in 2019. / 2018.\nThese targets pointed out that the proportion of net foreign direct investment will jump to 3% of GDP in the fiscal year 2025 / 2024 compared to 2.9% in 2023 / 2024.\nThe government also expected in the report to increase the volume of foreign direct investment flows in the local market to about 11.7 billion in the current fiscal year against 8.6 billion dollars in the last fiscal year 2022 / 2021 to rise to 14.9 billion in the next fiscal year (2023 / 2024) and 16.5 billion in 2025 / 2024.\nAccording to the Central Bank of Egypt \u2019 s forecasts issued in its statistical bulletin for May, the proportion of net foreign direct investment in GDP declined to about 1.3% in the fiscal year 2020 / 2021 compared to 2% in the fiscal year 2019 / 2020, adding that it was 2.7% in the fiscal year 2018 / 2019 and 3.1% in the year 2017 / 2018.\nEconomist Hani Geneina predicted that the value of net foreign direct investments in the local market will exceed 10 billion dollars in the coming period, due to several different factors, including the decline in the prices of shares of companies in the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar.\nHowever, Egypt was the second largest recipient of foreign direct investment in the African continent, he said, adding that recent pledges from Gulf countries to invest about $22 billion in various sectors will boost foreign direct investment in the future.\nThe number of new green projects in Egypt has more than tripled to $5.6 billion, according to the UNCTAD report, pointing out that for example, the UAE real estate company Reportage announced a real estate project worth $1.5 billion.\nAccording to the report, the volume of foreign direct investment flows to North Africa declined by 5% to $9.3 billion last year.\nGeneina told Al-Mal that the flows of foreign direct investments to the markets are divided into three types, the first is the acquisition of one company on another by more than 10%, pointing out that this investment happened last fiscal year, such as the acquisition of the UAE Holding \u201cADQ \u201d on several Egyptian companies, pointing out the importance of this type of investment, but it is not very useful in the list of foreign investments.\nThis type of rapid investment is encouraged by the decline in both stock prices on the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar, as well as the recent government stimulus measures that included the implementation of the state ownership document.\nThe document of state ownership announced by the government in mid-June revealed the most prominent sectors that will witness the stabilization or reduction of government investments (while allowing the participation of the private sector), a number of activities in the transport, education, mining, real estate, electricity, telecommunications and sports sectors.\nGeneina said that the second type of flows is the reinvestment of a foreign company present in the market for its profits again, pointing out that this type is classified in the balance of payments as foreign direct investments.\nHe added that the most prominent local sectors that will go to this type of investment is oil and gas, due to the high value of its profits achieved last fiscal year, and will therefore reinvest its large financial surpluses during the current fiscal year.\nHe pointed out that the third type of investment is the most difficult, which is the establishment of a new company or project from the beginning, and the employment of new workers, pointing out that for example, Dana Gas announced that it will expand its operations implemented in the local market.\nThis area is likely to witness an increase during the current fiscal year, especially in the oil and gas sectors and related sectors, namely petrochemicals and fertilizers, especially by Gulf investments in light of the features announced recently by the government, namely the state ownership document, the gold license, as well as the large financial surpluses they have, which motivates them to invest in the local market.\nIn mid-May, Prime Minister Mostafa Madbouly announced a number of concessions on the industrial sector, most notably the issuance of the golden license for some projects, pointing out that it will be granted once and include three areas as a start, namely green hydrogen, electric car manufacturing and infrastructure, seawater desalination projects and renewable energy.\nGeneina stressed the importance of the government encouraging foreign companies to reinvest their profits in the local market instead of transferring them to parent companies abroad by providing incentives to urge them to take this step.\nAccording to the latest UNCTAD report, Mozambique ranked third in the list of foreign investment flows to 15 African countries last year, and its inflows rose by 68% to $5.102 billion compared to $3.035 billion in 2020, while it recorded 2.212 billion in 2019.\nNigeria ranked fourth on the list, attracting inflows of 4.844 billion over the past year, an increase of 103 percent from the previous year, the data added, adding that it recorded 2.385 billion in 2020 and 2.305 billion in 2019.\nEthiopia followed in fifth place, and foreign direct investment inflows increased last year by 79% to $4.259 billion compared to $2.381 billion in 2020.\nIn the sixth place came \u00ab Congo \u00bb with the volume of flows of $3.691 billion, a decline of 8% from its value in 2020, and recorded 4.016 billion dollars, followed by Ghana in the seventh place in the list and increased flows by 39% to reach 2.614 billion dollars during 2021 compared to 1.876 billion in 2020.\nAccording to data from the UNCTAD list, foreign direct investment flows in Senegal jumped by 21% to 2.232 billion against 1.846 billion dollars in the previous comparison period.\nAccording to the report, the value of flows to Morocco increased by 52% last year to $2.153 billion, and a major international financing deal was announced there, a $20 billion construction project for a 3,800km transmission line to the UK with a capacity of 3.6 gigawatts, sponsored by English company Xlinks.\nThe Democratic Republic of the Congo ranked 10th on the list, with investments up 14% to $1.870 billion compared to $1.647 billion in 2020.\nGabon came in eleventh place, with direct investment flows falling by 5% last year to record 1.635 billion dollars compared to 1.717 billion in 2020, followed by Uganda, with flows rising by 31% to 1.142 billion dollars compared to 874 million in 2020.\nTanzania ranked 13th, with foreign investment up 35 percent in 2021 to $922 million compared to $685 million in 2020.\nAccording to the bulletin, investment flows in Algeria decreased by 24% last year to $870 million compared to $1.143 million in 2020, pointing to the decline of investments in Tunisia to $660 million compared to $652 million in 2020 to be ranked 15th.\nEsraa Ahmed, a macro-economic analyst at the investment bank \u201cAhly Pharos \u201d, agrees with Geneina \u2019 s opinion as she expects the volume of net foreign direct investment in Egypt to rise to about $10 billion during the current fiscal year (2022 / 2023), up from levels that will not exceed $7 billion in the fiscal year ending 2021 / 2022.\nShe added that this rise is driven by the Gulf investment flows that have been announced recently, and the acquisition deals that we see are witnessing activity during the current period.\nThere are other factors that may prevent net foreign direct investment from rising to larger numbers in the near future due to the continuation of the war in Ukraine and its repercussions on the global economy.\nAccording to Ahmed, these factors are the economic situation of the European Union, which is an important partner for Egypt in terms of trade and investment, in addition to the general reluctance globally to risk starting new projects, and the prevailing outlook for emerging markets and the risks of their currencies.\nOn the sectors that may witness foreign inflows during the coming period, she said that the most prominent of them are clean energy, new infrastructure driven by the expansion of the state in this field, in addition to digital financial services, and some branches of manufacturing industries.\nFor his part, Numan Khalid, a macro-economic analyst at Arqaam Capital, said that the current circumstances in the world prevent the possibility of predicting the volume of foreign direct investment flows in the local market during the coming period.\nHe added that most of the investments come from the Gulf market, especially from Saudi Arabia and the UAE, pointing out that these two countries have benefited greatly from the recent increases in oil prices, and thus have a great financial solvency through which to invest in surrounding countries, especially in Egypt, which is one of their target markets.\nHe pointed out that health, hotels, real estate and the financial sector will witness an increase in the volume of investment flows to them during the coming period.\nDuring his participation in the Qatar Economic Forum last June, the Minister of Finance, Mohamed Maait, looked forward to increasing the volume of Gulf investments with the transformation of their deposits in Egypt into real investments that benefit from the promising development opportunities available in various fields.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0022.json.gz:32626","uncompressed_offset":898064754,"url":"almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B5%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D9%88%D9%82%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7/","warc_date":"2022-07-27T06:42:16.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e>","warc_url":"https://almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B5%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D9%88%D9%82%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7/"},"created":"2022-07-27T07:35:24.000Z","lang":"eng"},"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125":{"id":"da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d_927341125","text":"FDI flows to North Africa down 5% in 2021\nForeign direct investment to North Africa fell 5 percent to $9.3 billion for the whole of 2021, according to a report on \u201cInvesting in the World \u201d released by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) on June 9, 2022.\nThese investments, towards Tunisia, improved slightly from $652 million in 2020 to $660 million in 2021.\nThe same investment to Morocco increased by 52 percent to 2.2 billion dollars in 2021, compared with a 12 percent drop to 1.5 billion dollars in Egypt.\nDespite the decline in these investments in Egypt, it remains the second country to benefit from the inflow of foreign direct investment in Africa.\nAccording to the same report, the flow of foreign direct investment in Africa reached a record level of $83 billion for the whole of 2021, more than double the investment achieved for the whole of 2020.\nDespite this significant growth, the flow of investment to Africa in 2021 represented only 5.2 percent of the global total, compared to 4.1 percent in 2020.\nMost African countries saw a slight increase in foreign direct investment (FDI) in 2021.\nThese investments developed in South, East and West Africa, while they maintained their previous levels in Central Africa, while declining in North Africa.\nEuropeans remain the most important investors in Africa, led by investors from the United Kingdom ($65 billion) and France ($60 billion).\nIncreased investments in renewable energy\nDespite the overall positive trend of foreign direct investment towards Africa, the announcement of new projects remained weak at $39 billion and shows only a weak recovery compared to $32 billion recorded in 2020 and less than $77 billion recorded in 2019.\nIn parallel, the number of international projects in the field of renewable energies in Africa increased to an estimated 71 projects, almost double the 36 projects completed in 2011.\nAmong these projects is a $20 billion project that aims to export wind energy to the UK from Morocco.\nBy laying 3,800 km of submarine cables.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0018.json.gz:4737","uncompressed_offset":927341125,"url":"ar.webmanagercenter.com/2022/06/15/337032/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D9%81%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AB%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%86%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8/","warc_date":"2022-06-15T13:37:53.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:da89937a-32d7-40db-beb3-46050cdb3c6d>","warc_url":"https://ar.webmanagercenter.com/2022/06/15/337032/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%AA%D8%AF%D9%81%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AB%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AC%D9%86%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8/"},"created":"2022-06-15T14:14:26.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1033","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1033","narrative_id":"1033"},"responses":[{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"The global trend toward a 4-day workweek is gaining momentum, with many countries and companies adopting this model to improve employee well-being and productivity."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"Data from the largest trial ever to have taken place in the UK found that productivity among workers increased by 22%, job applications went up 88%, and absenteeism went down by 66%."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"Employees who work a 4-day week also report being less tired and happier, which can lead to increased job satisfaction and loyalty."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"The concept of a 4-day workweek is not new, but it has gained popularity in recent years, with Google searches for \"4 day week jobs\" exploding by 1,011% in early 2022 compared to 2021."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"Some companies, such as M&S, have already adopted this model, with one of their executives, Katie Bickerstaffe, championing the cause and finding that it gives her the freedom to spend time with her kids."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"However, implementing a 4-day workweek can be challenging, particularly in terms of equity and business continuity, with leaders needing to be convinced of its benefits."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, many countries, such as the UAE, are adopting a shorter working week, with some emirates having formally adopted a 4.5-day working model."},{"citations":{"d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a_492757152":1.0},"text":"Studies have shown that employees who work a 4-day week can achieve the same levels of productivity as those working a 5-day week, while also showing positive levels of job satisfaction, teamwork, and work-life balance."},{"citations":{"dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091_121712082":1.0},"text":"Overall, the trend toward a 4-day workweek is driven by the desire to improve employee well-being and productivity, and while there are challenges to implementation, the benefits are clear."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"The global trend toward a 4-day workweek is gaining momentum, with many countries and companies adopting this model to improve employee well-being and productivity."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"Data from the largest trial ever to have taken place in the UK found that productivity among workers increased by 22%, job applications went up 88%, and absenteeism went down by 66%."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"Employees who work a 4-day week also report being less tired and happier, which can lead to increased job satisfaction and loyalty."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"The concept of a 4-day workweek is not new, but it has gained popularity in recent years, with Google searches for \"4 day week jobs\" exploding by 1,011% in early 2022 compared to 2021."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"Some companies, such as M&S, have already adopted this model, with one of their executives, Katie Bickerstaffe, championing the cause and finding that it gives her the freedom to spend time with her kids."},{"citations":{"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":1.0},"text":"However, implementing a 4-day workweek can be challenging, particularly in terms of equity and business continuity, with leaders needing to be convinced of its benefits."},{"citations":{"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, many countries, such as the UAE, are adopting a shorter working week, with some emirates having formally adopted a 4.5-day working model."},{"citations":{"d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a_492757152":1.0},"text":"Studies have shown that employees who work a 4-day week can achieve the same levels of productivity as those working a 5-day week, while also showing positive levels of job satisfaction, teamwork, and work-life balance."},{"citations":{"dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091_121712082":1.0},"text":"Overall, the trend toward a 4-day workweek is driven by the desire to improve employee well-being and productivity, and while there are challenges to implementation, the benefits are clear."}],"references":["dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091_121712082","efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548","1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648","d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a_492757152"],"documents":{"dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091_121712082":{"id":"dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091_121712082","text":"Brazil test week closed 3 September from some companies trial\nCentral News Agency\nTo improve the quality of life of employees, Brazil will test the possibility of working four days a week, use 80% of the time and maintain 100% productivity under the same salary conditions, and the 15 companies participating in the trial will decide how to implement the plan from September.\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.\nNonprofit organization 4 Day Week Global and Brazilian think tank Reconnect _ Happiness at Work today announced at a press conference in Sao Paulo that 15 Brazilian companies will pilot a four-day week starting in September.\nGenerally speaking, the working day in Brazil is Monday to Friday, and only special industries work on Saturdays and Sundays, and the maximum working hours can not exceed 44 hours per week, 8 hours per day, and overtime can not exceed 2 hours.\nThe four-day workweek initiative, launched in New Zealand in 2019 and gaining more traction during the COVID-19 pandemic, has been tested so far in the United Kingdom, the United States, Spain, Australia and other countries, and the model will be carried out in Brazil by Global Four Days a Week in partnership with Reconnect _ Happiness at Work.\nAccording to Global 4 Days a Week, nearly 500 companies around the world test the possibility of working four days a week, and employees must commit to using 80% of the time and 100% of the time under the same salary conditions to improve their quality of life.\nGabriela Brasil, director of Global 4 Days a Week, stressed that the challenges of the initiative are not limited to local labor laws, but also a strong corporate and employee attendance culture, which will require extensive communication and adequate support from leadership to ensure employees feel safe and confident in the new work model.\nThe 15 participating companies will decide for themselves how to implement the plan and how many departments will enter the pilot phase, and with the help of the Global 4 Days a Week, they will meet from September 5 to learn the basic concepts and steps of the project.\nRenata Rivetti, founder of Reconnect and a specialist in corporate happiness, points out that it takes three months to redesign the workflow, and everything has to be done with great care, not only to propose a reduction in workload, but also to propose a new business model with results.\nThe pilot program began in December, and data on project performance was collected after 3 months.\nThe whole process ends after 6 months and the numbers are measured again.\nData from participating companies worldwide show that compared to the previous year, 36% improved performance, 42% reduced layoffs, 68% reduced employee burnout, 54% increased productivity, and 63% were more likely to attract talent.\nThe data confirm that the health and motivation of employees are higher, which brings higher productivity and greater profits to the company. When the company reduces the work pressure of employees and becomes more humane, the productivity of employees will also increase. (Editor: Zhang Zhixuan) 1120831\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0025.json.gz:20942","uncompressed_offset":121712082,"url":"www.nownews.com/news/6245305","warc_date":"2023-08-31T03:03:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:dc783c2a-d35b-4db2-9c97-e89d6704e091>","warc_url":"https://www.nownews.com/news/6245305"},"created":"2023-08-31T03:14:19.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a_492757152":{"id":"d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a_492757152","text":"To increase production and care for the family.\nSaudi writer calls for \"4\" days of work and study\nJournalist Omar Al-Omari calls for the application of the system of work and study for 4 days a week, considering that the subject has become worthy of study, as studies showed that employees who work (4) days a week achieved the same levels of productivity, but also showed positive levels in job satisfaction, teamwork and balance between work and caring for families, which increased their loyalty to the facilities in which they work.\nDecreased motivation to be in the workplace\n4 thoughts on \u201c4 days a week?! \u201d\nIn Makkah newspaper, Al-Omari says: There is no relationship between productivity and the length of work, and the headquarters of the school is not the only place to learn, contributed by the presence of modern technology and advanced communication system, artificial intelligence and speed of information exchange and automation, all in its great purpose to serve man and save his time from daily routines, thus decreasing the need to be in the workplace. Innovative thinking, wider spaces of creative products and the acquisition of new skills to make real progress and development difference and impact, and this can only be achieved by creating a comfortable balance between social life and human humanity and the harsh official working environment. \u201d\nBusiness Idea (4) days trending in recent months\nWhile the idea of working for four days has been popular in recent months, and has been successful in a number of developed countries recently, it is not a product of the moment, so recent studies have shown that employees who are overworked by long work periods and transport to work are actually less productive than the average productivity of employees who work in the same field for less time and have more freedom.\nEmployees achieved the same levels of productivity\n\u201cStudies have shown that employees who work with the idea of \u200b \u200b working four days a week achieved the same levels of productivity, but also showed positive levels of job satisfaction, teamwork, work-life balance and loyalty to the facilities in which they work.\nPeople feel happy and satisfied\n\u201cI believe that the idea of working four days a week will increase some of the important global rankings as a soft power in enhancing the presence on the world map, namely (World Happiness Index), (World Wellbeing Index) and (Quality of Life), thus reflecting this on the ranking of the best cities and places to live in the world. Other contributing factors include additional income, social support, family empowerment, quality of health and education, security, absence of corruption and the level of freedoms enjoyed by individuals. \u201d\nGreater care for families\nAccording to several European research findings, working four days a week promotes work-life balance and greater personal and social space for the individual; employees will be able to spend more time with their families, better reconcile care and work obligations, be more committed to their tasks and duties, and less likely to be stressed or take sick leave; as a result, they return to work ready to face new challenges in solving problems. And promote the presence of innovation and creativity in the work to achieve efficiency and competition. \u201d\nThe subject is worth studying.\n\u201cI think the topic has become worthy of study at the level of the number of school days and the number of working days to enhance the quality of life, create wider social spaces, and enhance the happiness and mental health index, \u201d concluded Al-Omari.\nNews you might like.\nNo stories found.\nSabq Electronic Newspaper\nsabq.org","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0001.json.gz:41678","uncompressed_offset":492757152,"url":"sabq.org/saudia/ov9y3x6lv5","warc_date":"2023-01-17T13:58:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d5e7633e-4964-44ea-86b2-578d7f85d75a>","warc_url":"https://sabq.org/saudia/ov9y3x6lv5"},"created":"2023-01-17T14:17:01.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648":{"id":"1ca23fc5-1e30-4aa8-ac99-04ecc30df58b_831866648","text":"The four-day work week is welcome, but some challenges remain\n\nThis shift has thrown up interesting questions on macro and micro levels that over time will need answering\n\nBeta V.1.0 - Powered by automated translation\n\nThe sin of presenteeism is shaping up as a pre-pandemic anachronism, and the principal reason for this is not just remote working but an emerging historic global shift towards a shorter working week.\n\nThe global headaches from supply constraints following Covid-19 disruption have overshadowed equally profound changes in the labour market. For some bosses, there is rationing not just of the number of workers but the time they are willing to work. As people reassess their work-life balance, responsible employers and some countries are looking at the advantages of compressed hours on the job.\n\nThe UAE is a trailblazer in this regard, with most emirates having formally adopted a 4.5-day working model. Sharjah has gone further by opting for a four-day model. Reporting last week in this newspaper found that its residents said they are healthier and happier, enjoying more weekend flexibility and having more time with their families.\n\nMany forecasts over recent years have been very wide of the mark about the economic trajectory of the big developed economies. The Resolution Foundation, a UK-based think tank that looks at work, points out that in analysing the pandemic, \u201cmany feared a house price bust, expected the inflation spike to be small/short-lived, said unemployment/insolvencies for workers/firms respectively would surge and claimed this would be a \u2018she-cession\u2019. None happened\u201d.\n\nTechnology is the driver of all this, and the trend may over time become irresistible\n\nAnalysis of Google searches in the UK from an employment agency recently reported the four-day work week had gained popularity among people on the hunt for their next job opportunity. \u201cGoogle searches for \"4 day week jobs\" exploded a spectacular 1,011 per cent in early 2022, when compared to 2021,\u201d according to the firm\u2019s research.\n\nOne of Britain\u2019s biggest and best-known corporate brands, the department store M&S, has hired a well-known female executive who is a prominent four-day week champion, Katie Bickerstaffe. She said her role was compatible with shorter hours, even though it is a round-the-clock operation.\n\n\u201cWe\u2019re a seven-days-a-week, 24-hour operation and that\u2019s what you do, but I\u2019ve always done that [four days] because it gives me the freedom to spend some downtime with my kids and not feel that I don\u2019t have the opportunity to do that during the week,\u201d she explained.\n\nThe news coincided with the announcement that 70 UK companies had voluntarily joined a scheme to alter the working week basis of their business. Signing on to a pledge to pay 100 per cent of wages for 80 per cent of the hours worked means much more than just creating new rotas. It means altering the internal working patterns of the business and finding new ways to accommodate latency in the workforce.\n\nNot everyone is convinced this can deliver a kind of workplace nirvana.\n\nThe Centre for Policy Studies carried out some research last year that estimated that a four-day week would have a big cost to the economy if productivity levels remained constant. The annual shortfall to the economy would be \u00a345 billion ($55.42bn). On more generous calculations, if a 6 per cent increase in productivity could be achieved in the first decade of the reform, the loss overall could be pared back to \u00a317bn. The analyst behind the figures believes the evidence for productivity gains from compressing hours and having shorter working weeks is extremely limited.\n\nThat is not much of an argument for not experimenting with shorter weeks. Employees already job-share and expect work-from-home arrangements throughout the work force. In office-based roles or project work, the flexibility to complete the workload that comes with the job most obviously lends itself to working with a defined, shorter time frame.\n\nThere are hurdles for other jobs. Customer-facing roles or service functions will still need to be provided across a far longer time-frame than four days or 32 hours. Unlike in Sharjah, there is no clear directive in the UK for a common day that extends the weekend. Indeed, many people working four days chose a non-consecutive day, such as Wednesday, for the non-working option.\n\nWithout the government plumping for Friday as part of a three-day weekend, it is likely that businesses will experience co-ordination both internally and with clients and supplies if substantial numbers in the workforce are missing in action for part of the working week.\n\nThere are also concerns around the equality of the development. Can it be true that more flexibility would allow women, in particular, to better balance childcare obligations and thus erode the disadvantage with men?\n\nAnd as the work-from-home phenomenon has shown, the higher-paid employees have snapped up the main benefits from structural changes in how people work. There is little to suppose that this trend would not emerge from the four-day week.\n\nTechnology is, of course, the driver of all this, and the trend may over time become irresistible.\n\nCertainly, the difficulties of drawing an absolute boundary between the working day and your time revolve around the fact that your email is always in your pocket on the phone. That is double-edged. It would be difficult for employers to play another card: offering people four days\u2019 pay, not the salaried five.\n\nPublished: June 13, 2022, 4:00 AM","url":"https://www.thenationalnews.com/opinion/comment/2022/06/13/the-four-day-work-week-is-welcome-but-some-challenges-remain/"},"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548":{"id":"efbf8e21-e4ed-43ac-86a1-7217a6030d69_660392548","text":"New normal | Will 2024 be the year of the four-day week boom? Probably not\u2026\n\nAt one point in time, flexible working was a prime example of the benefits that truly had the power to lure and retain talent.\n\nThose days are now behind us.\n\nThis isn\u2019t because the prospect of working from home, or altering office hours around childcare or medical appointments isn\u2019t still alluring. In fact, far from it. It\u2019s because in the interim, the world experienced a massive shift. One that not only forced many businesses to adopt remote working policies or face the prospect of inactivity, but also changed the perceptions of workers about their careers, and the value of wellbeing in their working lives.\n\nIn a post-pandemic world, the concept of flexible working is largely considered a given. This is acutely true among companies that understand the persistent challenges in the talent market. So, where do we go from here? Where are those looking to push the boundaries of their benefits offering to turn? The answer is the four-day week.\n\nYou\u2019ve likely heard the words \u2018four-day week\u2019 uttered at conferences, or read it plastered all over LinkedIn. In short, whilst there\u2019s some variation in implementation, for most adopting a four-day week involves quite literally ditching one full working day. Employees work their normal hours, minus one fifth, and get paid the same amount for their effort.\n\nThe concept may sound ludicrous to some, yet the value of the idea goes far beyond simply being a valued benefit. Data from the largest trial ever to have taken place in the UK, as reported by Buffer, found that productivity among workers increased by 22%, job applications went up 88%, absenteeism went down by 66%. Employees are also reportedly less tired and happier.\n\nSo, we have an exciting new concept with stellar outcomes when trialled and the vast majority of businesses are yet to adopt it. Inevitably, this will be the next big thing in 2024, right? In reality, this is doubtful. Here\u2019s why.\n\nWhilst flexible working has been adopted en masse, let\u2019s not forget the impetus that caused this boom \u2013 the pandemic. According to data from IPSE, the proportion of workers reporting they work exclusively at home rose from 5.7 per cent in January 2020 to 43.1 per cent in April 2020. Whilst flexible working was no new concept in early 2020, the pandemic served as the catalyst for huge change, convincing many traditionalists that ditching the nine-to-five and introducing remote working could actually work.\n\nThe pandemic was the biggest trial of such a concept in recent history. And herein lies the issue with the four-day week. Leaders need to be convinced. Yes, it\u2019s likely that it will grow in 2024, but without a major shift in working culture to encourage those who dismiss it to give it a try, there\u2019ll be no sudden boom. So no, 2024 will not be the \u2018year of the four-day week\u2019, but for early adopters, it could well be a vastly positive development.\n\n\n\nYou are currently previewing this article.\n\nThis is the last preview available to you for 30 days.\n\nTo access more news, features, columns and opinions every day, create a free myGrapevine account.","url":"https://www.hrgrapevine.com/content/article/2023-11-09-will-2024-be-the-year-of-the-four-day-week-boom-probably-not"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1034","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1034","narrative_id":"1034"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The concept of a 4-day workweek has been gaining traction globally, with many companies and countries experimenting with this new approach to work."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"According to a survey, half of the respondents said they would be more productive if they worked fewer days, and 10% were even willing to cut their pay."},{"citations":{},"text":"This shift towards a shorter workweek is driven by the desire to improve employee well-being and productivity, as well as to reduce costs and increase competitiveness."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"A six-month trial conducted by the nonprofit organization 4 Day Week Global found that workers reported less fatigue, more positive work, and happier feelings about their daily work, personal life, finances, and emotional situation."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"Additionally, companies that implemented a 4-day workweek also received benefits such as increased productivity and satisfaction, higher earnings, and lower turnover."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"Some lawmakers are also pushing for legislation to reduce the number of working days, with Maryland lawmakers introducing a proposal to encourage public and private companies to adopt a 4-day workweek."},{"citations":{"08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027":1.0},"text":"Many business owners believe that a 4-day workweek is an effective solution to cope with problems, with 27% of American businessmen saying they had already transferred their employees to a 4-day schedule, and 35% planning to do so in the near future."},{"citations":{"08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027":1.0},"text":"However, it's worth noting that the phrase \"four-day work week\" does not necessarily mean that the company actually works only four out of five working days, and on the other days, its employees do not go on calls and do not answer phone calls."},{"citations":{"08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027":1.0},"text":"In fact, it can mean that the employee of the company works, for example, 30 hours instead of the standard 40."},{"citations":{"e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651":1.0},"text":"Despite the potential benefits, implementing a 4-day workweek can be tricky, with questions around who can and can't participate, whether the four-day workweek means longer working hours, and what happens if there's still work to be done once Friday rolls around."},{"citations":{"e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651":1.0},"text":"Several companies, including tech companies Bolt and Buffer, have permanently removed a day from the workweek to better suit employee needs."},{"citations":{"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157":1.0},"text":"Other companies, such as Unilever, are also trialing a 4-day workweek, with trials taking place in several countries, including the US, UK, and Spain."},{"citations":{"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157":1.0},"text":"However, not all sectors have found success with a 4-day workweek, with the Wellcome trust shelving its plans to try out four-day working after concluding it was \"too operationally complex to implement\"."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Despite the challenges, many experts believe that a 4-day workweek can have numerous benefits, including cost savings, improved productivity, and better quality output from staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"In fact, a survey by the Henley Business School found that 66% of businesses that implemented a 4-day workweek reported cost savings, 64% reported improved productivity, and 64% reported better quality output from staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of flexibility and trust in the workplace, with many employees working from home and demonstrating that they can be productive and efficient outside of the traditional office environment."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"As a result, many companies are rethinking their approach to work and considering a 4-day workweek as a way to improve employee well-being and productivity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"According to Jack E. Gold, founder and principal analyst at research firm J. Gold Associates, \"Keeping employees happy and motivated makes for far more productive employees, no matter what hours they work\"."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Additionally, a 4-day workweek can also have benefits for hiring and retention, with 68% of survey respondents that had adopted a 4-day week reporting that it had helped them attract and retain staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"The so-called Great Resignation has also contributed to interest in a shorter workweek, with many companies struggling to hire and retain workers."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"As a result, some experts believe that a 4-day workweek could be a relatively easy benefit to extend to help ease the challenge in the short term."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"However, implementing a 4-day workweek can also pose challenges, including concerns around staffing costs and the potential impact on business continuity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"According to a survey, 65% of companies that did not offer a 4-day week said they were worried about staffing costs, while 45% said they were concerned about the impact on business continuity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Despite the challenges, many companies are experimenting with a compressed workweek, with the same hours across four days instead of five."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"While the UK numbers are perhaps higher than expected, with less than 1% of job postings including the term \"four-day week\", numerous organizations have adopted or trialed a shorter workweek for staff since the start of the pandemic."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"In fact, a Gallup survey of full-time U.S. employees found that only 5% put in four days a week, with the vast majority (84%) working five days."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"However, with the pandemic highlighting the importance of flexibility and trust in the workplace, it's likely that we'll see more companies experimenting with a 4-day workweek in the future."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"Overall, the trend towards a 4-day workweek is driven by the desire to improve employee well-being and productivity, as well as to reduce costs and increase competitiveness."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"As more companies and countries experiment with this new approach to work, it's likely that we'll see a shift towards a more flexible and sustainable work environment."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The concept of a 4-day workweek has been gaining traction globally, with many companies and countries experimenting with this new approach to work."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"According to a survey, half of the respondents said they would be more productiv