670974651":1.0},"text":"Despite the potential benefits, implementing a 4-day workweek can be tricky, with questions around who can and can't participate, whether the four-day workweek means longer working hours, and what happens if there's still work to be done once Friday rolls around."},{"citations":{"e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651":1.0},"text":"Several companies, including tech companies Bolt and Buffer, have permanently removed a day from the workweek to better suit employee needs."},{"citations":{"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157":1.0},"text":"Other companies, such as Unilever, are also trialing a 4-day workweek, with trials taking place in several countries, including the US, UK, and Spain."},{"citations":{"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157":1.0},"text":"However, not all sectors have found success with a 4-day workweek, with the Wellcome trust shelving its plans to try out four-day working after concluding it was \"too operationally complex to implement\"."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Despite the challenges, many experts believe that a 4-day workweek can have numerous benefits, including cost savings, improved productivity, and better quality output from staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"In fact, a survey by the Henley Business School found that 66% of businesses that implemented a 4-day workweek reported cost savings, 64% reported improved productivity, and 64% reported better quality output from staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of flexibility and trust in the workplace, with many employees working from home and demonstrating that they can be productive and efficient outside of the traditional office environment."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"As a result, many companies are rethinking their approach to work and considering a 4-day workweek as a way to improve employee well-being and productivity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"According to Jack E. Gold, founder and principal analyst at research firm J. Gold Associates, \"Keeping employees happy and motivated makes for far more productive employees, no matter what hours they work\"."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Additionally, a 4-day workweek can also have benefits for hiring and retention, with 68% of survey respondents that had adopted a 4-day week reporting that it had helped them attract and retain staff."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"The so-called Great Resignation has also contributed to interest in a shorter workweek, with many companies struggling to hire and retain workers."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"As a result, some experts believe that a 4-day workweek could be a relatively easy benefit to extend to help ease the challenge in the short term."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"However, implementing a 4-day workweek can also pose challenges, including concerns around staffing costs and the potential impact on business continuity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"According to a survey, 65% of companies that did not offer a 4-day week said they were worried about staffing costs, while 45% said they were concerned about the impact on business continuity."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"Despite the challenges, many companies are experimenting with a compressed workweek, with the same hours across four days instead of five."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"While the UK numbers are perhaps higher than expected, with less than 1% of job postings including the term \"four-day week\", numerous organizations have adopted or trialed a shorter workweek for staff since the start of the pandemic."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"In fact, a Gallup survey of full-time U.S. employees found that only 5% put in four days a week, with the vast majority (84%) working five days."},{"citations":{"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":1.0},"text":"However, with the pandemic highlighting the importance of flexibility and trust in the workplace, it's likely that we'll see more companies experimenting with a 4-day workweek in the future."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"Overall, the trend towards a 4-day workweek is driven by the desire to improve employee well-being and productivity, as well as to reduce costs and increase competitiveness."},{"citations":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":1.0},"text":"As more companies and countries experiment with this new approach to work, it's likely that we'll see a shift towards a more flexible and sustainable work environment."}],"references":["4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730","08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027","62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245","e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651","e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157"],"documents":{"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245":{"id":"62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5_581400245","text":"My channel\n* Drag categories can be customized sorting\nRecover Default OK\nSetup\nAlert\nTrump Appears in Court, \"1 Truth\" Exposed, Self-reported Height 6 feet 2, Shrunk 1 inch\nNot even interstate abortions...\nIdaho passes \"the strictest abortion law in the country\"\nDon't want to work...\n33% of employees are willing to resign to find a \u201c4 days a week \u201d job\nAccording to a March survey of 868 people by Monster, a job advisory website, a four-day week is becoming popular, with 61% of respondents preferring to work four days rather than five days a week and 33% willing to quit their current job to get fewer days.\nVicki Salemi, a career expert at Monster, points out that this is a significant proportion, and the result is a shift in workers to rethink how they work.\nSalami said many people still feel empowered to look forward to more flexibility at work, and some seasonal factors may also have an impact, such as some people planning future summer trips and therefore want to work fewer days.\nHalf of the respondents in the survey said they would be more productive if they worked fewer days, and 10% were even willing to cut their pay.\nFor decades, a four-day workweek has been seen as an unattainable work benefit, but this is changing, and more global experiments now confirm that companies can do it.\nIn a six-month trial conducted by the nonprofit organization 4 Day Week Global, workers reported less fatigue, more positive work, and happier feelings about their daily work, personal life, finances and emotional situation, and companies also received more benefits, such as increased productivity and satisfaction, higher earnings, and lower turnover.\nSome lawmakers are trying to push through the law with positive test results in an attempt to reduce the number of working days.\nMaryland lawmakers introduced a new proposal in January to encourage public and private employers to experiment with shortening working days without cutting wages or benefits.\nIn Congress, Representative Mark Takano of California once again proposed the 32-Hour Workweek Act, which, if passed, would reduce the current standard legal working hours from 40 to 32 hours, and would require overtime pay for work beyond the time limit.\nIn the future, more and more companies are likely to try to reduce the number of working days, especially in the face of the economic challenges of not being able to raise or promote employees.\nAccording to a recent Payscale report, last year, the proportion of companies offering four-day working days reached the 10% threshold for the first time.\nLabor Benefits in California\nThe last one.\nKENYA has a lot of weird rules...\nStudents only eat sushi for lunch, class is on the 1st floor\nExtended reading\nSuper-popular\nMore >","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:15984","uncompressed_offset":581400245,"url":"www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/121617/7084061","warc_date":"2023-04-08T01:54:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:62269ac0-ab8d-4c7c-874a-b9ab3a98a2d5>","warc_url":"https://www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/121617/7084061"},"created":"2023-04-08T03:04:21.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651":{"id":"e47bad82-5cc3-4d6d-a752-d965ddaf0f26_670974651","text":"Work life\n\nSummer Fridays walked so the four-day workweek could run\n\nEmployees are now in favor of flexibility over temporary time off.\n\n\u00b7 3 min read\n\nLevel up your career and your life with Sidekick\n\nCareer advice, productivity hacks, entertainment, and more. If it\u2019s worth your time, it\u2019s in here.\n\nWhat\u2019s top of mind at the water cooler.\n\nThe legend of the Summer Friday: Once upon a time, for three sacred months every year between Memorial Day and Labor Day, employees were allowed to clock out after lunch every Friday and head immediately to the bar.\n\nIt\u2019s said that the tradition started in NYC in the \u201960s as companies searched for ways to boost employee productivity and morale during the summer months. (There\u2019s even a brand named after it!) If you were lucky enough to work somewhere that offered this perk (usually publishing or advertising), your weekend started with midday happy hours and early bird beach days while friends at less generous corporations smoldered with jealousy.\n\nBut with the push toward remote work, Summer Fridays have become a ghost of workplace past as they may have ushered in something even better: the four-day workweek.\n\nAs companies scrambled to deal with office closures during the pandemic, most work suddenly became remote. Facing Covid variant after variant and a resistance to returning to the office, some employers like tech companies Bolt and Buffer opted to permanently remove a day from the workweek to better suit employee needs. A jumbo Summer Friday! Perfect, right?\n\nUnfortunately, the exact logistics of the four-day workweek have been tricky. Who can and can\u2019t participate? Does the four-day workweek mean longer working hours? What happens if there\u2019s still work to be done once Friday rolls around?\n\nTo get some insight, Sidekick spoke with Alicia Garcia, chief culture officer at MasterControl and Jes Osrow, diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) expert and founder of The Rise Journey consultancy, who had these thoughts to share:\n\n  \u2022 Fixed schedules \u2260 productivity. While a five-day, nine-to-five workweek has worked for most US-based companies, that doesn\u2019t mean employees produce their best work during that time.\n  \u2022 Flexibility is king. \u201cThe biggest issue with policies like the four-day workweek or Summer Fridays is that they\u2019re still rigid. Whether it\u2019s a four-day or five-day workweek, the exact days and times employees are required to work are fixed\u2026When approached by employees, the most common request is \u2018flexibility,\u2019\u201d said Garcia.\n  \u2022 Flexibility isn\u2019t an option for everyone. \u201cWe\u2019re not thinking about essential workers, we\u2019re not thinking about folks on the ground, and we\u2019re not thinking about grocery store owners. It\u2019s important to recognize that even though we do talk the big talk about a four-day workweek, it only applies to a small fraction of workers in the US and/or globally,\u201d Osrow explained.\n\nAs the highly discussed \u2728future of work\u2728 continues to develop, employees are looking for more flexibility. Whether that means working remotely from far-flung corners of the world or logging off a little early to go pick your children up from daycare\u2014employers should take notes, not dictate them.\u2014MW\n\nLevel up your career and your life with Sidekick\n\nCareer advice, productivity hacks, entertainment, and more. If it\u2019s worth your time, it\u2019s in here.","url":"https://www.morningbrew.com/sidekick/stories/summer-fridays-flexible-work"},"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157":{"id":"e9e88feb-fe4c-4b14-9a0e-e6455c754862_420211157","text":"Rise of the four day week? Bank becomes largest British company to slash hours for staff\n\nDIGITAL bank Atom has become the largest company in the UK to introduce a four day week without cutting pay for any of its staff.\n\nLink copied\n\nHome working is \u2018regressive\u2019 for women claims Rachel Johnson\n\nThe app based bank has confirmed it introduced the new four day week on November 1 for all of its 430 employees with the majority choosing to adopt it. Previously Atom employees worked a 37.5 hour week across five days but this will now reduce to a 34 hour week spread over four days. Staff taking up the reduced hours option will see their shifts lengthen slightly, working 8.5 hours instead of 7.5. It is expected most employees will take Monday or Friday as the default day off apart from those in operational or services roles whose days will vary to allow seven day a week customer support. Mark Mullen, CEO of Atom, explained experiences during the pandemic had \"exploded many of the myths of the modern workplace\" with changes not needing to stop at working from home.\n\nMr Mullen said: \u201cA four-day week will provide our employees with more opportunities to pursue their passions, spend time with their families, and build a healthier work/life balance.\n\n\"We firmly believe that this will prove beneficial for our employees\u2019 wellbeing and happiness and that it will have an equally positive impact on business productivity and customer experience.\"\n\nBen Willmott, Head of Public Policy at the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development cautioned a shorter working week would only be sustainable by smarter working to improve productivity.\n\nMr Willmott explained: \"\u201cIt is undoubtedly a positive move for employers to seek to reduce people's working hours without compromising pay.\n\n\"However, the challenge of simply reducing people\u2019s working hours without other changes is that you can increase exposure to work intensity and stress, which is already one of the main causes of working time lost to sickness absence.\"\n\nWorkers will see hours cut but not salaries (Image: Getty)\n\nAtom CEO Mark Mullen (Image: Atom )\n\nAtom points to the evolving history of working patterns as evidence for the need to change.\n\nThe standard five day working week was first popularised by US carmaker Henry Ford in the 1920s and subsequently taken up by Boots in the UK in 1934.\n\nFrom there most other companies began to follow suit whereas previously a six day week had been more common.\n\nIn Iceland a trial was run by Reykjavik City Council this year to introduce four day weeks to workplaces such as preschools, social services and hospitals.\n\nThe five day week was introduced by carmaker Henry Ford in the 1920s (Image: Getty)\n\nWidely reported to be a success trials are also now taking place by consumer giant Unilever in New Zealand.\n\nThe idea of a four day week has not always worked for all sectors though.\n\nIn 2019 the Wellcome trust shelved its plans to try out four day working after concluding it was \"too operationally complex to implement.\"\n\nMr Mullen commented: \u201cWhile we appreciate a four-day working week will not be right for all workplaces, the move to working from home has proved that working practices that may have seemed years away can be introduced rapidly.\"\n\n\"We are proud to be one of the first businesses to introduce a four-day week for all our employees, and we hope many others follow suit.\"\n\nDON'T MISS:\u00a0\nUK courts can freeze stolen Crypto\u00a0[LATEST]\nEuro slides over lockdown fears\u00a0[ANALYSIS]\nCold Weather Payment Scheme: Could you be eligible?\u00a0[REVEALED]\n\nIceland has been trialling a four day week (Image: Getty)\n\nAs well as benefits to employee welfare Atom also believe a shorter working week could reduce the environmental impact of companies.\n\nThe group cites a 2021 study by environmental organisation Platform London which found a UK wide switch to four day working by 2025 could lower CO2 emissions by over 20 percent.\n\nAtom was launched in 2016 as the UK's first app based bank offering savings accounts, mortgages and business loans.","url":"https://www.express.co.uk/finance/city/1525624/atom-bank-british-company-four-day-week"},"08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027":{"id":"08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f_878798027","text":"ENTRY TO THE SITE\nVideo mixer RGBLink Mini - a godsend for streamers, journalists and bloggers\nVideo review.\nCompact video mixer, which has a fairly modest price and very immodest...\nLogitech Rally Video Review\nIn 2020, video conferencing has become the main format of communication, and if you need to prepare for this...\nVideo review of Wize mounts\nVideo wall mounts from Wize provide a balance of quality and price.\nWize is...\nDown with five days?\n24.11.2022 17: 30\nThe transition to a four-day working week is widely discussed around the world.\nThere are several reasons: the impact of the pandemic, economic problems, shortage of personnel, supply disruptions, etc.\nThere is another difficulty: the \u201cculture of vanity \u201d that has developed in recent years, when work dominates other aspects of human life, which leads to the\u201c burnout \u201d of workers.\nAll of the above has led to the fact that many business owners today believe that a four-day working week is an effective solution in order to cope with problems.\nSo, in 2021, 27% of American businessmen (owners of companies) out of 1,300 respondents said that they had already transferred their employees to such a schedule, and 35% were going to do so in the near future.\nAssuming that such statistics are representative of business in the US as a whole, it means that at least a quarter of all companies are already operating under the new scheme: four days a week instead of five.\nHowever, the phrase \u201cfour-day work week \u201d does not necessarily mean that the company actually works only four out of five working days, and on the other days its employees do not go on calls and do not answer phone calls.\nIt can mean that the employee of the company works, for example, 30 hours instead of the standard 40.\nIn any case, judging by the results of the survey, most business owners believe that this approach has huge advantages.\nMainly because it increases employee satisfaction.\nThose stop thinking that they live only for the sake of work, become more motivated, increase the productivity of their work, reduce the turnover of personnel.\nOf the 35% of business owners who are considering switching to a shorter work week, 84% believe that such a schedule will give them some (48%) or a significant (36%) advantage over competitors.\nAnd half of those who have already switched to four days of work instead of five, say that they have already received this advantage.\nExperts believe that this approach is applicable to any type of activity, including installation companies.\nHowever, there is no official data that at least one integrator firm in the United States really adheres to this practice.\nSubscribe to our news","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0035.json.gz:57223","uncompressed_offset":878798027,"url":"www.avreport.ru/news/article/article/doloi-pjatidnevku/","warc_date":"2022-11-24T22:34:19.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:08c71a3b-8df7-4914-bf64-4b617a2a7d1f>","warc_url":"https://www.avreport.ru/news/article/article/doloi-pjatidnevku/"},"created":"2022-11-24T23:33:36.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730":{"id":"4c2db427-4932-4b7c-977a-dfac0181fffd_255105730","text":"Four-day workweek\u2019s popularity grew during the pandemic \u2014 survey\n\nAs companies scrambled during the COVID-19 outbreak to reorient their workplace procedures and processes, one idea that gained ground was a shorter workweek.\n\nMore businesses adopted a four-day week during the COVID-19 pandemic as the shift to remote working spurred a major rethinking of work practices, according to a poll of senior leaders at 500 UK businesses by the University of Reading\u2019s Henley Business School.\n\nThe survey, an update to research from 2019, showed that 21% of respondents adopted a four-day workweek for all staff in 2021, up from 18% in 2019. The majority of respondents (65%) said a four-day workweek is in place for at least some of their workers, up from 50% who said that in 2019. A four-day workweek is defined in the report as involving a reduction from five to four workdays for the same pay or a compressed workweek with the same hours across four days instead of five.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nThough a four-day workweek has gained popularity, the UK numbers are perhaps higher than expected; job posting site Indeed told Computerworld that less than 1% of job postings on March 11 included the term \u201cfour-day week,\u201d for example. A Gallup survey of full-time U.S. employees in March 2020\u00a0\u2014 prior to the pandemic \u2014 indicated that only 5% put in four days a week, with the vast majority (84%) working five days (and 11% working six days each week).\n\nThat said, numerous organizations have adopted or trialled a shorter workweek for staff since the start of the pandemic, including firms such as Atom Bank, Bolt, Buffer, and Kickstarter. And pilot projects are under way in several countries, including the US, UK, and Spain.\n\nSuch projects are not new, of course; Microsoft launched a trial at its Japan offices in 2019 that resulted in higher productivity, for example, while the UK\u2019s Wellcome Trust ran into issues around complexity with its own project the same year.\n\nA shorter workweek has been talked about for decades, but a shift from the five-day, 40-hour week that has been the standard for over a century has so far failed to gain momentum.\n\nWhat\u2019s behind the recent interest in the idea? One reason is that the widespread, and largely successful, shift to remote work during the pandemic showed the benefits of a more flexible approach to work, said Rita Fontinha, associate professor in Strategic Human Resource Management at the University of Reading\u2019s Henley Business School.\n\n\u201cThe pandemic led to a situation where most firms were forced to implement remote work and this has accelerated previous discussions that we have been having over the last two decades on flexible working,\u201d said Fontinha. \u201cWorking from home led to increased trust [between employers and employees] and awareness of other ways of measuring performance that go beyond presenteeism. The pandemic showed that flexibility works.\u201d\n\nReport highlights four-day week advantages\n\nThe Henley Business School survey pointed to several advantages for businesses that implemented a four-day workweek, including costs savings (66%), improved productivity (64%), better quality output from staff (64%), and \u00a0less-stressed workers (78%).\n\nImproved employee wellbeing is connected to business outcomes too, said Jack E. Gold, founder and principal analyst at research firm J.\u00a0Gold Associates.\n\n\u201cKeeping employees happy and motivated makes for far more productive employees, no matter what hours they work,\u201d said Gold. \u201cMaximizing employee productivity is a much more important way to gain business value than hours worked.\u201d\n\nAnother benefit, noted by 68% of survey respondents that had adopted a four day week, involved hiring and retention. \u201cPeople were less likely to take sick leave, people were more productive, and it was easier to attract new staff, and to retain them,\u201d said Fontinha.\n\nThe so-called Great Resignation is also likely contributing to interest in a shorter workweek.\n\n\u201cWhat\u2019s different now than prior to the pandemic is that we\u2019re seeing a temporary spike in the difficulty that firms are having in hiring and retaining workers, and the four-day work week is a relatively easy benefit to extend to help ease the challenge in the short term,\u201d said David Brodeur-Johnson, principal analyst at research firm Forrester.\n\nA shorter workweek can mean challenges\n\nThe survey also highlighted several challenges around implementing a shorter workweek, though employer concerns have softened during the pandemic.\n\nAmong companies that did not offer a four-day week, 65% said they were worried staffing costs would outweigh any productivity benefits (though that number was down from 80%). The biggest challenge cited by employers was meeting customer demands (75%), while 70% thought a shorter week would be too complicated to manage.\n\nSome companies may find a switch to a four-day week easier than others, said Fontinha. IT-focused firms are more likely to switch, she said, largely due to the relative ease with which tech worker output can be tracked in comparison with other roles. \u201cAreas where we were less likely to see the four-day week were sectors that involve contact with customers, or healthcare, for example,\u201d she said.\n\nA shorter workweek is also more suited to companies with a relatively homogenous workforce in terms of job roles, she said, meaning large businesses with a diverse workforce may find a short workweek complicated to roll out. At the same time, the smallest companies might not have the resources to support the shift, said Fontinha, adding that there are steps all businesses can take to implement a four-day week, even if they are more gradual.\n\n\u201cHaving this overnight shift to a four-day working week will be hard for smaller firms,\u201d she said. \u201cWhat we suggest is a progressive reduction in working hours, moving towards a four-day working week by assessing how things are going and how needs are being met, how productive people are.\u201d\n\nEven if the benefits outweigh the costs for many, businesses should consider their reasons for moving to a four-day week. While a shorter week provides clear benefits to work/life balance and employee wellbeing, Brodeur-Johnson warns against adopting a four-day week as a shortcut to improving employee experience. \u201c[T]he science is clear that what really engages people is being able to make progress in meaningful work every day; to know that they can and are succeeding,\u201d he said.\n\n\u201cEmployee experience peaks when we can leave work knowing that we made a difference, and had a really good day,\" he said. \"It also comes from having a supportive manager, a supportive team environment, and feeling recognized and seen uniquely for the work that we do.\n\n\u201cAll of these things are much harder for businesses to do for their people, because it involves behavior changes, manager development, culture changes, deeper resourcing and more that a four-day work week won\u2019t solve on its own.\u201d\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2022 IDG Communications, Inc.\n\n7 inconvenient truths about the hybrid work trend\nShop Tech Products at Amazon","url":"https://www.computerworld.com/article/3654208/four-day-workweeks-popularity-grew-during-the-pandemic-survey.html"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1035","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1035","narrative_id":"1035"},"responses":[{"citations":{"0bd2cf9d-c5d0-4427-91a2-a4d0a81b57b2_1054928507":1.0},"text":"Biohacking is a concept that involves using various methods and techniques to optimize one's health and well-being, with the goal of prolonging life and improving overall quality of life."},{"citations":{"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":1.0},"text":"The term \"biohacking\" originated in Silicon Valley and refers to the practice of reprogramming one's mind and body to live better."},{"citations":{"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":1.0},"text":"Biohacking enthusiasts use a range of techniques, including nutrition, physical activity, supplement intake, and medical screenings, to achieve their goals."},{"citations":{"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":1.0},"text":"One popular method used by biohacking enthusiasts is intermittent fasting, which involves concentrating diet in a precise time span of the day, and should be done under medical supervision."},{"citations":{"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":1.0},"text":"In addition to nutrition and physical activity, biohacking also involves taking care of sleep, as sleep debt can accelerate aging, with 30-40 percent of people sleeping too little."},{"citations":{"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":1.0},"text":"Biohacking aims to modify dormant functional responses, from muscular or cardiovascular function to flexibility, and involves regaining possession of the body and the mind-body axis, starting with stress management."},{"citations":{"a76144f6-85cb-430b-92e8-d25a00492c0f_535307822":1.0},"text":"The pursuit of longevity, a key aspect of biohacking, is expected to be worth 600 billion yuan in 2025, and involves a range of health products, including metformin, resveratrol, and rapamycin."},{"citations":{"a76144f6-85cb-430b-9