ate the evidence for different methods and techniques before adopting them."}],"references":["a76144f6-85cb-430b-92e8-d25a00492c0f_535307822","7330daf3-723a-424d-a476-023fed1467cf_546361925","73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384","0f2ceda1-1145-419b-adad-243aa48471c2_868441574"],"documents":{"7330daf3-723a-424d-a476-023fed1467cf_546361925":{"id":"7330daf3-723a-424d-a476-023fed1467cf_546361925","text":"TV legend Davinia Taylor has revealed how well she is feeling after undertaking a new lifestyle that involves biohacking.\n\nBiohacking occurs when someone changes their nutrition and lifestyle in order to make themselves healthier. Each person who biohacks does so in a different way whether it\u2019s cutting out alcohol, taking supplements, or engaging in anti-ageing procedures.\n\nDavinia \u2013 who starred in Hollyoaks \u2013 has explained that her biohacking involves cold-water therapy and removing inflammatory foods from her diet.\n\nAs a result of her new lifestyle, which also includes the use of saunas and supplements, Davinia has said that she now feels healthier than she ever has before.\n\nSpeaking to Hello! Davinia said that she entered a difficult period of poor mental health after the death of her mother when she was 35.\n\nShe added: \u201cBoredom drove me to drink and then to eat unhealthily. I don\u2019t want to go into my 50s feeling bored, so I had to find another way to get the dopamine I crave.\u201d\n\nOn the techniques she uses for her biohacking, Davinia reveals that one of her routine acts is taking supplements from a company she founded. Known as WillPowders which contain collagen, protein, bone broth, and MCT (a healthy form of saturated fat) they have become an essential part of her routine.\n\nDavinia explained: \u201cIf I don\u2019t have my morning keto creamer and collagen, I\u2019m going to end up binging on croissants or brownies. It\u2019s how I\u2019m wired after my 1980s upbringing.\u201d\n\nThis isn\u2019t the first time Davinia has spoken about biohacking. Earlier this year she told the Evening Standard that it wasn\u2019t a case of taking big measures to improve one\u2019s health.\n\nShe said: \u201cThere's so much doom and gloom\u2026 There's so much doom and gloom\u2026There are so many little hacks you can do just to make yourself feel mentally better.\u201d\n\nDavinia highlighted the benefits of cold-water therapy, a method she said can be cheap to access: \u201cThe water\u2019s freezing in this country two-thirds of the time. And on the few months a year when it\u2019s not, just go to the supermarket, buy some ice bags and empty them into the bath.\u201d","url":"https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/hollyoaks-legend-turns-biohacking-after-33248825"},"a76144f6-85cb-430b-92e8-d25a00492c0f_535307822":{"id":"a76144f6-85cb-430b-92e8-d25a00492c0f_535307822","text":"My channel\n* Drag categories can be customized sorting\nRecover Default OK\nSetup\nAlert\nCalifornia Covid-19 Testing, Vaccines, Medications No Longer Free Than Medical Insurance\nFrom the seating arrangements to the glasses on the table, the details are everywhere.\n\"Aging can be cured\" nutrition scholar: long life is not a dream\nThe United States is aging, with more and more elderly people reaching the age of 65 every day. \"Ageing is a disease, a treatable disease,\" says Serena Poon, a nutritionist and researcher on long-term health.\nSerena and her business partner, Harvard geneticist David Sinclair, are on a global tour to educate listeners and potential investors on the concept of healthy longevity.\nUntil last year, Serena wanted to live to be 120, and now she is reluctant to give specific figures, but is passionate about the future of human life in old age; \"aging will become easier to solve than cancer,\" Hinckler said in her book.\nWe can treat ageing in our lifetime, \"he said.\nIn recent years, the pursuit of longevity of the gene gold rush has been promoted as a decathlon industry, is expected to be worth 600 billion yuan in 2025.\nHealth products such as metformin, resveratrol and rapamycin are seen as revolutionary miracles in delaying aging; in the pursuit of a longer and healthier life, the basics of nutrition, exercise, sleep, a lot of biomarkers, emotional health and social engagement are all areas that need to be improved and continuously monitored.\nLongevity has developed multiple dimensions in recent years, and for scientists and tech giants, it is a huge, accelerating field of research, the holy grail of \u201cbiohacking, \u201d and a potential treasure trove of biotech wealth.\nLongevity has become a buzzword and industry, in part because of huge advances and investment in research, and the pursuit of longevity is a perpetual theme of history, faith and mythology; S. Jay Olshansky, who specializes in aging at the University of Illinois, says promoting anti-aging elixirs is \u201cthe second oldest profession in the world \u201d and the difference is that modern technology is finally keeping up. the pace of this idea.\nInvest in Cancer Hackers\nThe last one.\nApproval for Chinese-funded plant, Michigan town officials removed\nThe next one.\nMRI is $2500 for 3 months.\nExtended reading\nSuper-popular\nMore >","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0032.json.gz:21379","uncompressed_offset":535307822,"url":"www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/121148/7568359","warc_date":"2023-11-12T05:27:21.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a76144f6-85cb-430b-92e8-d25a00492c0f>","warc_url":"https://www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/121148/7568359"},"created":"2023-11-12T06:29:26.000Z","lang":"eng"},"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384":{"id":"73dc4426-e3fb-40cb-8c2d-9236031101af_161823384","text":"Home \u00bb biohacking, reprogramming mind and body to live better\n\nbiohacking, reprogramming mind and body to live better\n\nby admin\n\nIt\u2019s called \u201cbiohacking\u201d and it comes from Silicon Valley. Listen: The long life diet: the longevity formula is calorie restriction \u2026\n\nAccess the Premium article and all the contents of the site\nwith the dedicated app, newsletters, podcasts and live updates.\n\nSPECIAL OFFER\n\nBEST OFFER\n\nANNUAL\n\n79,99\u20ac\n\n19\u20ac\nFor 1 year\n\nCHOOSE NOW\n\nMONTHLY\n\n6,99\u20ac\n\n\u20ac1 PER MONTH\nFor 6 months\n\nCHOOSE NOW\n\nSPECIAL OFFER\n\nBEST OFFER\n\nANNUAL\n\n79,99\u20ac\n\n11,99\u20ac\nFor 1 year\n\nCHOOSE NOW\n\nMONTHLY\n\n6,99\u20ac\n\n\u20ac2 PER MONTH\nFor 12 months\n\nCHOOSE NOW\n\n\u2013 or \u2013\n\nSubscribe by paying with Google\n\nSPECIAL OFFER\n\nRead the article and the entire website ilmessaggero.it\n\n1 Year for \u20ac9.99 89,99\u20ac\n\nor\n\u20ac1 per month for 6 months\n\nAutomatic Renewal. Turn off whenever you want.\n\n\n  \u2022 Unlimited access to articles on site and app\n  \u2022 The 7:30 Good Morning newsletter\n  \u2022 The Ore18 newsletter for updates of the day\n  \u2022 The podcasts of our signatures\n  \u2022 Insights and live updates\n\nIt\u2019s called \u201cbiohacking\u201d and comes from Silicon Valley.\n\nA relatively new word that comes from the union of \u201cbiology\u201d and \u201chacker\u201d and indicates the attempt to positively influence the functioning of the organism, by hacking, ie trying to \u201cforce\u201d, one\u2019s genetic heritage. A strategy to live better and longer launched years ago by Californian top managers and which then spread throughout the world. How to upgrade the \u201coperating system\u201d of the human body? No manipulation, here we are talking about \u201creprogramming\u201d and new lifestyles. \u201cOur genetic heritage has enormous unexpressed potential that can be activated,\u201d he explains Fabio Piccinidoctor and psychoanalyst, researcher of Food Sciences of theMarche Polytechnic University, author of the book \u201cBiohacking Techniques: how to optimize metabolism to increase health and longevity\u201d. \u201cBiohacking aims to activate epigenetic modifications by awakening dormant genes to enhance the body\u2019s resources.\u201d While genetics studies the structure of DNA, epigenetics the way genes express themselves, i.e. how much they are turned on or off. \u201cWe\u2019re talking about a set of strategies that aim to strengthen the body from a physical and mental point of view, first of all through nutrition, sleep quality, physical activity, cognitive stimulation\u201d. One of the pillars of biohacking and the intermittent fasting, Piccini adds, which plans to concentrate the diet in a precise time span of the day (to be followed always under medical supervision). \u00abBut it is equally important to take care of sleep, we know very well that sleep debt accelerates aging and that 30-40 percent of people sleep too little. Just as it is essential to check thehydration. Physical training must also be intermittent, with recovery periods in place to allow the muscle layers to rebuild. And then, you have to keep learning something at any age, another pillar of biohacking: studying music or a new language, for example, to counteract cognitive degeneration\u201d.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The dashboard of Xbox Series X will have a higher resolution-\n\nTHE QUALITY OF LIFE\n\nSandra Milo is one of the supporters of this well-being and longevity strategy. \u00abI\u2019m lucky, at 90 I\u2019m in full health and I still have a great desire to enjoy life. I don\u2019t know if it\u2019s a matter of genetics, nor do I think there is a \u201cmagic formula\u201d of longevity, but I have certainly always been careful to lead a healthy life. There is nothing more beautiful than reaching old age with a smile and in full autonomy \u00bb, says the actress who baptized the first Biohacking Suite in Rome. \u201cOur mission is not so much to lengthen life but to improve its quality by lowering the rate of morbidity,\u201d explains Dr. Claudio Urbani, specialist in regenerative medicine, neuroscience and stress therapy, head of the longevity center Umb. \u00abBiohacking aims to modify dormant functional responses from non-use, from muscular or cardiovascular function to flexibility. It is about regaining possession of the body and the mind-body axis, starting with stress management\u00bb. Diagnosing your own state of \u201caging\u201d involves a series of tests. \u00abThe measurement of oxidative stress which measures the quantity of free radicals and indicates any inflammatory states, plethysmography to evaluate the functionality of the microcirculation of the legs, impedancemetry to study body composition, fat and lean mass, nutritional status and hydration level. And only after the check is a tailor-made program created for each person. Among the suggested therapies, there is also that of the cold which stimulates the metabolism and reduces inflammation \u00bb.\n\n\u00a9 breaking latest news\n\nRead the full article\non The Messenger\n\nSee also\u00a0 first portrait of genetic diversity, more effective treatments from cancer to infertility\n\nYou may also like\n\nThis website uses cookies to improve your experience. We'll assume you're ok with this, but you can opt-out if you wish. Accept Read More\n\nPrivacy & Cookies Policy","url":"https://www.breakinglatest.news/health/biohacking-reprogramming-mind-and-body-to-live-better/"},"0f2ceda1-1145-419b-adad-243aa48471c2_868441574":{"id":"0f2ceda1-1145-419b-adad-243aa48471c2_868441574","text":"Advertisement\nThis ad is displayed using third party content and we do not control its accessibility features.\nClose Banner\nAdvertisement\nThis ad is displayed using third party content and we do not control its accessibility features.\n\nBiohacking & Toxic Masculinity: How Women Dismantled The Boys Club\n\nAuthor: Medical reviewer:\nBeauty & Health Editor\nBy Jamie Schneider\nBeauty & Health Editor\nJamie Schneider is the Beauty Editor at mindbodygreen. She has a B.A. in Organizational Studies and English from the University of Michigan, and her work has appeared in Coveteur, The Chill Times, and Wyld Skincare.\nMedical review by\nBindiya Gandhi, M.D.\nPhysician\nDr. Bindiya Gandhi is an American Board Family Medicine\u2013certified physician who completed her family medicine training at Georgia Regents University/Medical College of Georgia.\nImage by Sonja Lekovic / Stocksy\nWe carefully vet all products and services featured on mindbodygreen using our commerce guidelines. Our selections are never influenced by the commissions earned from our links.\n\nTake a quick search for \u201cbiohacker\u201d on TikTok (a tag with over 137 million views), and you\u2019ll discover a slew of men discussing their muscle gains, testosterone levels, and cold plunge routines. You\u2019ll see some women on the page, but the space is undoubtedly dominated by male energy. And think of the outspoken biohackers you may listen to on podcasts\u2014chances are most of them are men, too.\u00a0\n\nThis gendered approach to biohacking, while pervasive, is simply misguided. But now, women are asserting their authority in health optimization, and we expect their emphasis to soar in the year ahead.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nMeet the experts\n\nMolly Maloof. M.D.\n\nMolly Maloof. M.D. provides health optimization and personalized medicine to high-achieving entrepreneurs, investors, and technology executives. Since 2012, she has worked as an advisor or consultant to more than 50 companies in the digital health, consumer health, and biotechnology industries. Her company, Adamo Bioscience, is working on sexual health optimization.\n\nGabrielle Lyon, D.O.\n\nGabrielle Lyon, D.O. is a board-certified family physician leading a disruption in modern medicine that focuses on the largest organ in the body: skeletal muscle. With a background that includes a combined research and clinical fellowship in geriatrics and nutritional sciences at Washington University and undergraduate training in nutritional sciences at the University of Illinois, she is a subject-matter expert on protein for health, performance, aging, and disease prevention.\u00a0\n\nStacy Salvi\n\nStacy Salvi is the vice president of product and strategy at the medical device company Movano Health\u2014the creator of the Evie Ring, the first medical-grade health wearable designed for women.\n\nMona Vand, PharmD\n\nMona Vand, PharmD studied pharmacy at Massachusetts College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences before developing her platform that shares holistic wellness advice.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nWhy biohacking isn\u2019t just for \u201cbros\u201d\n\n\u201cWomen are the original biohackers,\u201d declares family physician, Molly Maloof, M.D. \u201cOur hormones change throughout our lives, and this requires us to adapt accordingly.\u201d Our biology means that women often need to constantly edit their health routines and experiment with lifestyle habits as time goes on. Isn\u2019t that the very definition of biohacking?\u00a0\n\nLet's back up: Here at mindbodygreen, we think of \u201cbiohacking\u201d as the practice of making lifestyle tweaks to optimize health and promote longevity. Not shortcuts\u2014contrary to popular belief\u2014but low-lift, everyday habits that complement and enhance an existing well-being routine. Think: optimizing your exercise regimen using tools and techniques (the \u201cbiohacks\u201d) to enhance muscle growth. It\u2019s essentially all about advancing health with \u201cdo it yourself\u201d biology\u2014a topic that can pique anyone\u2019s interest, regardless of gender.\u00a0\n\n\u201c[Women] have a most complex physiological lifecycle that requires us to track and manage fertility, pregnancy, breastfeeding, sexuality, perimenopause, and menopause. So we should be looking at biohacking as a path to even greater health and owning the opportunity to improve our lives,\u201d says Maloof.\u00a0\n\nYet many women feel intimidated to enter the biohacking scene as it exists today, turned off by the male-dominated energy in the room.\n\nWomen are the original biohackers\n\nMolly Maloof, M.D\n\n\u201cBiohacking has always grabbed my attention, and I want to learn, but it sometimes makes me really stressed out, because I go into this state of perfectionism where I have to do all the things,\u201d says doctor of pharmacy and wellness practitioner Mona Vand, PharmD. \u201cThe few biohackers that I followed were all males\u2026 it just doesn't really resonate with my energy.\u201d\u00a0\n\nThis male energy is not only frustrating but can potentially harm women\u2019s health in the long run. After all, building muscle, prioritizing protein, and keeping an eye on various health metrics are crucial for longevity\u2014in some cases, these proactive measures can save lives. When women don\u2019t get involved, it can totally impact their well-being.\u00a0\n\n\u201cPhysical strength is nonnegotiable,\u201d says functional medicine doctor Gabrielle Lyon, D.O. \u201cI've been a physician since 2006, and I've never heard someone say, \u2018I regret being physically strong.\u2019\u201d And the muscle-building space impacts more than just physiological changes, she says. \u201cYou optimize fertility, you make healthier babies, you help the epigenetics of your child,\u201d Lyon adds. \u201cYou age better, your skin is better, you're less likely to fall and break a hip\u2026 There's nothing that doesn't get better the stronger you are.\u201d\u00a0\n\nSo let\u2019s be clear: Dismantling the biohacking boy\u2019s club is not just about helping women feel included; there are real health implications at stake here.\u00a0\n\nWhy the biohacker space actually really needs a dose of feminine energy\n\nI\u2019d be remiss not to mention how biohacking culture can easily become synonymous with hustle culture (some experts don\u2019t even like to use the term, as it implies you can achieve optimal health with quick fixes). But as more women enter the biohacking space, we expect it to become more intuitive and less about hitting every single benchmark. From there, we predict women will focus more on sustainable changes long-term instead of a gazillion quick hacks.\n\n\u201cI used to think it was a flex to do a million things at the same time and habit stack,\u201d Vand recounts. \u201cI now carve out time for doing things that have no efficiency to them, that are strictly for joy or rest and relaxation, versus benefiting my longevity or health. It can be a little bit obsessive when you get into this thought pattern, and I just don't resonate with it.\u201d\u00a0\n\nThis doesn\u2019t mean biohacking will become \u201csofter\u201d as it embraces feminine energy. But there\u2019s an opportunity here for women to introduce some much-needed flexibility into a space that has long felt needlessly rigid.\u00a0\n\nHow the biohacker game is changing \u2014 and where it\u2019s headed next\n\nThanks to a growing awareness that healthcare protocols should not be gendered, more women are now starting to pay attention to markers of performance like lean muscle, hormetic stressors, VO2 max, HRV, zone 2 training, etc. \u201cCold plunging, saunas, and harder, more physical activities are not just for the boys anymore,\u201d adds Lyon\u2014and we expect an even bigger shift to come in 2024.\u00a0\n\n\u201cI think it\u2019s super exciting to see biohacking become more mainstream and more women joining the conversation,\u201d adds Maloof. She praises apps like Wild.AI, for women who aim to make lifestyle adjustments based on their menstrual cycle, and Zero, for women who want to dabble in time-restricted eating, both of which have helped to herald the shift.\u00a0\n\nOther existing health optimization companies are now inviting women into the conversation by introducing specific features informed by their unique physiology. WHOOP, for example, is currently working on upgrades to their popular health-tracking band: \u201cWe did a study recently where we learned a lot about how a woman's body changes during pregnancy and how her heart rate variability (HRV) will evolve. It'll decrease, and then about seven weeks before she gives birth, it will increase sharply,\u201d explains Will Ahmed, WHOOP founder and CEO, on the mindbodygreen podcast\n\nIf a woman didn\u2019t know that this was supposed to happen, she might look at this stark increase with a critical (or anxious) eye. \u201cWe've been able to take population-level data on pregnant women and now have a feature in the app, where a woman can see how her body is evolving alongside what other pregnant women are experiencing,\u201d he adds.\u00a0\n\nSimilarly, creatine supplements\u2014from the ingredients to the packaging\u2014are no longer marketed toward dudes looking to bulk up, and we are certainly here for it. After all, muscle mass is a predictor of longevity and healthspan, so supplements that promote it can help all of us \u201chack\u201d our health in a big way.\n\nAnd as Lyon notes, women have lower endogenous creatine stores compared to men (meaning, they have less available). And the amino acid has been associated with significantly increased muscle mass1 in both men and women, without increasing the risk of adverse outcomes2, like weight gain. \u201cMost of the women in my practice will go on creatine, and they find anecdotally that it really improves both anaerobic and aerobic exercise performance,\u201d Lyon shares.\u00a0\n\nNot to mention the supplement\u2019s brain health perks: Taking creatine has been shown to benefit both working memory and processing speed3 as well as cognitive longevity4. \u201cIt is above and beyond simply sport performance,\u201d adds Lyon, who has certainly seen an uptick in women curious about creatine.\u00a0\n\nAs women feel intimidated (or even restricted) by biohacking spaces, some experts have taken it upon themselves to create new ones that center the feminine. For example, neuropsychophysiologist Kayla Osterhoff, MPH, offers a Women's Biohacking Mini Course, consisting of lifestyle routines and tips aligned with female physiology.\u00a0\n\nOsterhoff also recently presented at the 2023 Dragonfly Live Conference\u2014among other female biohackers\u2014to discuss the latest advancements in women's well-being and the \u201chealth revolution\u201d that\u2019s sweeping the mainstream. This conference aims to gather the \u201cwho's-who\u201d in the health space to discuss cutting-edge strategies and innovations that optimize well-being\u2014by having women biohackers at the forefront of the conversation, we can expect them to hit the main stage in a broader sense.\u00a0\n\nOr take the brand new Evie Ring, the first medical-grade health wearable designed for women, created by medical device company Movano Health. The technology ties hormonal information to a woman\u2019s sleep, activity, and heart health data (among other metrics).\u00a0\n\nFor instance, \u201cIf we notice a more restless night of sleep in the luteal phase, we'll point it out and also give some strategies for how somebody may attack their day, despite having not gotten as good of a night of sleep,\u201d says Stacy Salvi, vice president of product and strategy at Movano Health. Similarly, \u201cWe know that there are cardiovascular implications when your estrogen drops, so they would want to keep a better look on the function of their heart,\u201d she adds. \u201cThis would be something that they would be able to do from our app.\u201d\u00a0\n\nEven the design itself was made with women in mind: The ring features an open band meant to accommodate how women\u2019s fingers change in size throughout the day, so it can stay comfortable.\u00a0\n\nTo avoid needless stress, Evie also limits the amount of goals you can set on the app. \u201cYou can only set three at a time, because we do not want to overwhelm [users] with a bunch of different things,\u201d says Salvi. \u201cI mean, I'm an overachiever. I probably would set every single goal and then fail at them.\u201d And heaven knows we don\u2019t need yet another way for busy, overwhelmed women to feel like they\u2019re failing in a society with unsurmountable standards.\u00a0\n\nForecasting the future\n\nA woman walks up to the weight rack in 2024. She sees the usual suspects\u2014bros pounding protein shakes and grunting through their bicep curls\u2014but now she also sees a fair amount of women on the scene. They\u2019ve got creatine supplements! Fitness trackers! Kettlebells! (And no, they aren\u2019t pink.)\n\nGranted, we still have a ways to go before women feel totally embraced by the biohacking space (we\u2019d first have to close the centuries-long gender gap in science and medicine), but it\u2019s clear that the arena is becoming way less of a boy\u2019s club.\u00a0\u201cAnd the world is ready, my friend,\u201d says Lyon. \u201cThe world is absolutely ready for this.\u201d\u00a0\n\nWatch Next\n\nEnjoy some of our favorite clips from classes\n\nWatch Next\n\nEnjoy some of our favorite clips from classes\n\nWhat Is Meditation?\n\nMindfulness/Spirituality | Light Watkins\n\nBox Breathing\n\nMindfulness/Spirituality | Gwen Dittmar\n\nWhat Breathwork Can Address\n\nMindfulness/Spirituality | Gwen Dittmar\n\nThe 8 Limbs of Yoga - What is Asana?\n\nYoga | Caley Alyssa\n\nTwo Standing Postures to Open Up Tight Hips\n\nYoga | Caley Alyssa\n\nHow Plants Can Optimize Athletic Performance\n\nNutrition | Rich Roll\n\nWhat to Eat Before a Workout\n\nNutrition | Rich Roll\n\nHow Ayurveda Helps Us Navigate Modern Life\n\nNutrition | Sahara Rose\n\nMessages About Love & Relationships\n\nLove & Relationships | Esther Perel\n\nLove Languages\n\nLove & Relationships | Esther Perel\n\nRelated Videos (10)\n\nWhat Is Meditation?\n\nBox Breathing\n\nWhat Breathwork Can Address\n\nThe 8 Limbs of Yoga - What is Asana?\n\nTwo Standing Postures to Open Up Tight Hips\n\nHow Plants Can Optimize Athletic Performance\n\nWhat to Eat Before a Workout\n\nHow Ayurveda Helps Us Navigate Modern Life\n\nMessages About Love & Relationships\n\nLove Languages\n\nAdvertisement\nThis ad is displayed using third party content and we do not control its accessibility features.\n\nMore On This Topic\n\nmore Health\nAdvertisement\nThis ad is displayed using third party content and we do not control its accessibility features.\nAdvertisement\nThis ad is displayed using third party content and we do not control its accessibility features.","url":"https://www.mindbodygreen.com/articles/bro-biohacking-ends"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1037","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1037","narrative_id":"1037"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue with significant historical, cultural, and political implications."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision has been criticized by various parties, including Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who view it as a threat to the monument's multicultural heritage."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"Historian Ilber Ortayli has expressed concerns that the large number of visitors to Hagia Sophia could lead to a catastrophic structural failure if not addressed immediately, citing the significant damage the monument has undergone since its conversion into a mosque."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"The Turkish Association of Art Historians has also reported damage to the historic Imperial Gate in Hagia Sophia, with a picture clearly depicting the damage to the oak wood."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"A video from 2022 shows fragments falling from the dome of Hagia Sophia, raising serious questions over the safety of the former Orthodox Christian cathedral, now a mosque."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"The president of the Turkish Art History Association, Serif Yasar, has argued for the restoration of the monument as soon as possible."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's decision has been seen by many as a political move to shore up his Islamo-nationalist base, with some observers believing that he is compensating for his weakened internal position by erasing part of the country's multiculturalism."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, but has drawn criticism from those who urge Turkey to protect important Byzantine monuments, both of which have been listed as World Heritage Sites by the United Nations."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy highlights the complex and sensitive nature of cultural heritage sites, and the need for careful consideration and dialogue in their management and preservation."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue with significant historical, cultural, and political implications."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision has been criticized by various parties, including Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who view it as a threat to the monument's multicultural heritage."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"Historian Ilber Ortayli has expressed concerns that the large number of visitors to Hagia Sophia could lead to a catastrophic structural failure if not addressed immediately, citing the significant damage the monument has undergone since its conversion into a mosque."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"The Turkish Association of Art Historians has also reported damage to the historic Imperial Gate in Hagia Sophia, with a picture clearly depicting the damage to the oak wood."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"A video from 2022 shows fragments falling from the dome of Hagia Sophia, raising serious questions over the safety of the former Orthodox Christian cathedral, now a mosque."},{"citations":{"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":1.0},"text":"The president of the Turkish Art History Association, Serif Yasar, has argued for the restoration of the monument as soon as possible."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's decision has been seen by many as a political move to shore up his Islamo-nationalist base, with some observers believing that he is compensating for his weakened internal position by erasing part of the country's multiculturalism."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, but has drawn criticism from those who urge Turkey to protect important Byzantine monuments, both of which have been listed as World Heritage Sites by the United Nations."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy highlights the complex and sensitive nature of cultural heritage sites, and the need for careful consideration and dialogue in their management and preservation."}],"references":["d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018","08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018":{"id":"9ba1561a-fc64-4cc3-b0ee-218d2b7a3e8d_609947018","text":"[ditty_news_ticker id=\"27897\"] Video Shows Fragments Falling from the Dome of Hagia Sophia - Orthodox Christian Laity\n\nVideo Shows Fragments Falling from the Dome of Hagia Sophia\n\n0\n\nSource: Greek Reporter\n\nA still from a recently released video shows visitors rushing to take cover as fragments fall from the dome of Hagia Sophia. Credit: Daily Motion/BirG\u00fcn\n\nA video from 2022 that came to light recently shows fragments falling on visitors from the dome of Hagia Sophia, the former epicenter of Christian worship at Constantinople, today\u2019s Istanbul.\n\nThe footage released by the Turkish newspaper,\u00a0BirG\u00fcn, raises serious questions over the safety of the former Orthodox Christian cathedral, now a mosque.\n\nBirG\u00fcn\u00a0notably quoted officials as saying that \u201cpieces are falling from the roof, due to the humidity created by the crowd, but no precautions are being taken\u201d.\n\nThe president of the Turkish Art History Association, Serif Yasar, argued for restoration of the monument as soon as possible, suggesting that \u201cIf Hagia Sophia is not restored, it will collapse with the first earthquake.\u201d\n\nThe monument was restored as a mosque three years ago after serving as a museum from 1935-2020 and has since received 21 million visitors, according to Turkey\u2019s tourism and culture minister.\n\nYasar added that when the church was a museum, the scientific council overseeing it urged that groups of no more than 25 people should be allowed to enter the building at any one time.\n\nThis enormous lift in visitation has likely brought to the forefront the need for repairs and it was indeed reported in September that the Turkish government had decided to start long-term maintenance of Hagia Sophia.\n\nTurkey to implement visitor management policy at Hagia Sophia\n\nIn early October Turkish historian Ilber Ortayli\u00a0expressed fears\u00a0that the large number of visitors to Hagia Sophia could lead to a catastrophic structural failure if not addressed immediately.\n\nWriting in the\u00a0H\u00fcrriyet daily, Ortayli said that the monument, which attracts three million pilgrims annually apart from tourists, has undergone significant damage since its conversion into a mosque.\n\nHe asserted that even a modest number of 20-30 thousand people annually, including scientists, historians, archaeologists, representatives of the Muslim religion, politicians, and public officials, could be considered excessive for the endurance of the monument.\n\nIn June 2022 a number of tiles of the ancient\u00a0marble floors in Hagia Sophia were damaged\u00a0by heavy machines used to clean the site.\n\nIn April 2022, The Turkish Association of Art Historians stated that the historic Imperial Gate in Hagia Sophia had been badly damaged.\n\nThe group posted a picture clearly depicting the damage to the oak wood of\u00a0the 15-century-old gate.\n\nTurkey unveiled plans in late October\u00a0for a visitor management policy at Hagia Sophia, including charging foreign tourists with an entrance fee to be implemented starting Jan. 15.\n\nMinister of Culture and Tourism Mehmet Nuri Ersoy said that extensive restoration work is underway in various sections of Hagia Sophia, now a mosque, with plans to progress to other parts upon their completion.\n\nHe emphasized that, based on UNESCO\u2019s recommendations, a visitor management plan would be enforced to enhance the quality and safety of visits while preserving the historical significance of the site.\n\nRelated Articles\nOfficials argue for repairs to Hagia Sophia after footage shows fragments falling from the dome \u2013 Neos Kosmos\n\nShare.","url":"https://ocl.org/video-shows-fragments-falling-from-the-dome-of-hagia-sophia/"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":{"id":"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","text":"Turkey officially opens the Byzantine church and museum \"Khora\" as a mosque (PHOTOS)\nWorld News\n\"Kari Mosque\" in the Museum and Monastery of \"Khora\"\nCopy Link https: / / www.rt.com / xhpk\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Monday officially opened the Kari Mosque in Istanbul \u2019 s Byzantine Museum and Monastery of Khora, four years after the church dedicated a mosque to Muslims.\nOn Monday, Erdogan oversaw the official remote opening of the Khora mosque and a number of restored sites from the conference hall of his residence in Ankara.\nErdogan said during the opening ceremony, which was broadcast on Turkish television, \"May it be a good start.\"\nOne of the first worshipers at the mosque told Anadolu Agency: \u201cI have been waiting for its opening for four years, and I have been honored to pray in such a place. \u201d\nAnadolu quoted another serum as saying: \u201cThank God for showing us these days, I hope we come here from time to time and do our prayers. \u201d\nThe site near the walls of the old city of Istanbul is famous for its fine mosaics and frescoes.\nThe church dates back to the 4th century, although the edifice took its present form during the 11th and 12th centuries.\nGreece has criticized the Turkish government \u2019 s decision to return it to use as a mosque, accusing Ankara of \u201cpersonal insult \u201d to another World Heritage site, saying the decisions to turn Hagia Sophia and Khora back into mosques are steps aimed at strengthening the support base of conservatives and the religious trend of Erdogan \u2019 s ruling party amid an economic downturn.\nThe museum was built \"Khora\" monastery, in 534, the building was converted into \"Kari Mosque\" at the beginning of the 16th century, it was used as a mosque for more than four centuries and was converted into a museum in 1945 by a Turkish ministerial decision.\nIn August 2020, President Recep Tayyip Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum, known as a \u201cbottomless church \u201d in Turkish, into mosques.\nThe conversion of the two churches into mosques was praised by Muslims, but drew criticism from Greece and other countries that urged Turkey to protect important Byzantine monuments, both of which have been listed as World Heritage Sites by the United Nations.\nSource: A B\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0012.json.gz:13896","uncompressed_offset":954300905,"url":"arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/","warc_date":"2024-05-06T23:13:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/"},"created":"2024-05-07T00:44:47.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1038","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1038","narrative_id":"1038"},"responses":[{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various stakeholders."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, has a rich history as both a Byzantine cathedral and an Ottoman mosque, making its reconversion a sensitive topic."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"President Erdogan's decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been met with criticism from Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who have expressed concerns about the implications of this decision on religious tolerance and freedom."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the decision as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"In addition to the criticism from religious institutions, many observers believe that President Erdogan's decision is a political move aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base, particularly in the face of a bad economy and a lack of political perspective."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has also been seen as a way for President Erdogan to erase part of the country's multiculturalism and promote a more nationalist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, who view it as a national win for Turkey, with many worshippers expressing their pride and happiness at being able to pray at the historic site."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"However, the decision has also been criticized for its potential impact on the cultural and historical significance of the Hagia Sophia, with many arguing that it should be preserved as a museum and a symbol of the country's rich cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In 2018, President Erdogan had refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"However, he made an about-turn in 2020, announcing the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque and quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet, saying \"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul\"."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has also been followed by the conversion of a second ancient Byzantine church, the Chora Church, into a mosque, which has been criticized by the Greek Orthodox Church and other stakeholders."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Chora Church into a mosque was announced shortly after the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The first Friday prayers at the Kariye Mosque, formerly the Chora Church, were attended by hundreds of worshippers, who filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"President Erdogan has stated that the Kariye Mosque will remain open to all, despite the criticism from Greece and other stakeholders."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"The Turkish president has also emphasized the importance of protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO's cultural heritage and making it available for the benefit of the nation and all humanity."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"In August 2020, President Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum into mosques, which was praised by Muslims but drew criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex issue that involves religious, cultural, and political dimensions, and its implications will likely be felt for years to come."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a highly controversial issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various stakeholders, and its implications will depend on how the Turkish government balances its commitment to religious freedom and cultural heritage with its political agenda."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various stakeholders."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, has a rich history as both a Byzantine cathedral and an Ottoman mosque, making its reconversion a sensitive topic."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"President Erdogan's decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been met with criticism from Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who have expressed concerns about the implications of this decision on religious tolerance and freedom."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the decision as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"In addition to the criticism from religious institutions, many observers believe that President Erdogan's decision is a political move aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base, particularly in the face of a bad economy and a lack of political perspective."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The decision to reconvert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has also been seen as a way for President Erdogan to erase part of the country's multiculturalism and promote a more nationalist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, who view it as a national win for Turkey, with many worshippers expressing their pride and happiness at being able to pray at the historic site."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"However, the decision has also been criticized for its potential impact on the cultural and historical significance of the Hagia Sophia, with many arguing that it should be preserved as a museum and a symbol of the country's rich cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In 2018, President Erdogan had refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"However, he made an about-turn in 2020, announcing the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque and quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet, saying \"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul\"."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has also been followed by the conversion of a second ancient Byzantine church, the Chora Church, into a mosque, which has been criticized by the Greek Orthodox Church and other stakeholders."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Chora Church into a mosque was announced shortly after the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The first Friday prayers at the Kariye Mosque, formerly the Chora Church, were attended by hundreds of worshippers, who filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"President Erdogan has stated that the Kariye Mosque will remain open to all, despite the criticism from Greece and other stakeholders."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"The Turkish president has also emphasized the importance of protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO's cultural heritage and making it available for the benefit of the nation and all humanity."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"In August 2020, President Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum into mosques, which was praised by Muslims but drew criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex issue that involves religious, cultural, and political dimensions, and its implications will likely be felt for years to come."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a highly controversial issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various stakeholders, and its implications will depend on how the Turkish government balances its commitment to religious freedom and cultural heritage with its political agenda."}],"references":["d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":{"id":"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","text":"Turkey officially opens the Byzantine church and museum \"Khora\" as a mosque (PHOTOS)\nWorld News\n\"Kari Mosque\" in the Museum and Monastery of \"Khora\"\nCopy Link https: / / www.rt.com / xhpk\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Monday officially opened the Kari Mosque in Istanbul \u2019 s Byzantine Museum and Monastery of Khora, four years after the church dedicated a mosque to Muslims.\nOn Monday, Erdogan oversaw the official remote opening of the Khora mosque and a number of restored sites from the conference hall of his residence in Ankara.\nErdogan said during the opening ceremony, which was broadcast on Turkish television, \"May it be a good start.\"\nOne of the first worshipers at the mosque told Anadolu Agency: \u201cI have been waiting for its opening for four years, and I have been honored to pray in such a place. \u201d\nAnadolu quoted another serum as saying: \u201cThank God for showing us these days, I hope we come here from time to time and do our prayers. \u201d\nThe site near the walls of the old city of Istanbul is famous for its fine mosaics and frescoes.\nThe church dates back to the 4th century, although the edifice took its present form during the 11th and 12th centuries.\nGreece has criticized the Turkish government \u2019 s decision to return it to use as a mosque, accusing Ankara of \u201cpersonal insult \u201d to another World Heritage site, saying the decisions to turn Hagia Sophia and Khora back into mosques are steps aimed at strengthening the support base of conservatives and the religious trend of Erdogan \u2019 s ruling party amid an economic downturn.\nThe museum was built \"Khora\" monastery, in 534, the building was converted into \"Kari Mosque\" at the beginning of the 16th century, it was used as a mosque for more than four centuries and was converted into a museum in 1945 by a Turkish ministerial decision.\nIn August 2020, President Recep Tayyip Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum, known as a \u201cbottomless church \u201d in Turkish, into mosques.\nThe conversion of the two churches into mosques was praised by Muslims, but drew criticism from Greece and other countries that urged Turkey to protect important Byzantine monuments, both of which have been listed as World Heritage Sites by the United Nations.\nSource: A B\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0012.json.gz:13896","uncompressed_offset":954300905,"url":"arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/","warc_date":"2024-05-06T23:13:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/"},"created":"2024-05-07T00:44:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":{"id":"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","text":"World News\nErdogan: Church of the Savior in Khora to be converted into a mosque: it will remain open to all\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, in the presence of Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, confirmed the conversion of the ancient Orthodox Church of the Saviour in Istanbul to a mosque, despite calls from Greece not to go ahead with the move.\nSpeaking at a joint news conference with Mitsotakis in Ankara, Erdogan said: \"The Karye Mosque in its new form will remain open to all.\"\nThe Turkish president said he had told the Greek prime minister, \u201cWe opened the Carr\u00e9 mosque for prayers and visits after careful restoration work in accordance with the decision we made in 2020. \u201d\n\u201cWe attach great importance to protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO \u2019 s cultural heritage and making it available for the benefit of our nation and all humanity. \u201d\nThe Greek prime minister has opposed the conversion of the church, which contains frescoes representing the \"judgment\" dating back to the 14th century, into a mosque.\nThese were the details of the news Erdogan confirmed the conversion of the Church of the Saviour in Khora to a mosque: it will remain open to everyone for today, we hope that we have succeeded by giving you the details and full information and to follow all our news you can subscribe to the system of alerts or one of our different systems to provide you with everything new.\nIt should also be noted that the original news has been published and is available on the bulletin (Lebanon) has been verified by the editorial team in Gulf 365 and may have been modified and may have been transferred in full or quoted from it and you can read and follow up on the news from its main source.\nAdvertisements\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0013.json.gz:17131","uncompressed_offset":427727559,"url":"gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html","warc_date":"2024-05-18T01:44:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b>","warc_url":"https://gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html"},"created":"2024-05-18T02:25:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1039","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1039","narrative_id":"1039"},"responses":[{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue with significant historical, cultural, and political implications."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision has been met with criticism from various parties, including Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who have expressed concerns about the preservation of the site's cultural heritage and its designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's move has been seen as a political maneuver to shore up his Islamo-nationalist base, with many observers believing that he is compensating for his weakened internal position by erasing part of the country's multiculturalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the conversion of the Chora Church, also known as the Kariye Mosque, as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"In 2020, Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum into mosques, a decision that was praised by Muslims but drew criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the two churches into mosques has been viewed as a national win for Turkey by some, with Muslim worshippers expressing pride and happiness at the decision."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"However, others have expressed intense dissatisfaction with the move, citing concerns about the preservation of the site's cultural heritage and the implications for religious tolerance and freedom."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"Erdogan has stated that the Kariye Mosque will remain open to all, and that the Turkish government attaches great importance to protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO's cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Overall, the controversy surrounding the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex and multifaceted issue that reflects deeper tensions between cultural heritage, religious identity, and political power."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue with significant historical, cultural, and political implications."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision has been met with criticism from various parties, including Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, who have expressed concerns about the preservation of the site's cultural heritage and its designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's move has been seen as a political maneuver to shore up his Islamo-nationalist base, with many observers believing that he is compensating for his weakened internal position by erasing part of the country's multiculturalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the conversion of the Chora Church, also known as the Kariye Mosque, as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":1.0},"text":"In 2020, Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum into mosques, a decision that was praised by Muslims but drew criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the two churches into mosques has been viewed as a national win for Turkey by some, with Muslim worshippers expressing pride and happiness at the decision."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"However, others have expressed intense dissatisfaction with the move, citing concerns about the preservation of the site's cultural heritage and the implications for religious tolerance and freedom."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"Erdogan has stated that the Kariye Mosque will remain open to all, and that the Turkish government attaches great importance to protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO's cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Overall, the controversy surrounding the reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex and multifaceted issue that reflects deeper tensions between cultural heritage, religious identity, and political power."}],"references":["d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905":{"id":"d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52_954300905","text":"Turkey officially opens the Byzantine church and museum \"Khora\" as a mosque (PHOTOS)\nWorld News\n\"Kari Mosque\" in the Museum and Monastery of \"Khora\"\nCopy Link https: / / www.rt.com / xhpk\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Monday officially opened the Kari Mosque in Istanbul \u2019 s Byzantine Museum and Monastery of Khora, four years after the church dedicated a mosque to Muslims.\nOn Monday, Erdogan oversaw the official remote opening of the Khora mosque and a number of restored sites from the conference hall of his residence in Ankara.\nErdogan said during the opening ceremony, which was broadcast on Turkish television, \"May it be a good start.\"\nOne of the first worshipers at the mosque told Anadolu Agency: \u201cI have been waiting for its opening for four years, and I have been honored to pray in such a place. \u201d\nAnadolu quoted another serum as saying: \u201cThank God for showing us these days, I hope we come here from time to time and do our prayers. \u201d\nThe site near the walls of the old city of Istanbul is famous for its fine mosaics and frescoes.\nThe church dates back to the 4th century, although the edifice took its present form during the 11th and 12th centuries.\nGreece has criticized the Turkish government \u2019 s decision to return it to use as a mosque, accusing Ankara of \u201cpersonal insult \u201d to another World Heritage site, saying the decisions to turn Hagia Sophia and Khora back into mosques are steps aimed at strengthening the support base of conservatives and the religious trend of Erdogan \u2019 s ruling party amid an economic downturn.\nThe museum was built \"Khora\" monastery, in 534, the building was converted into \"Kari Mosque\" at the beginning of the 16th century, it was used as a mosque for more than four centuries and was converted into a museum in 1945 by a Turkish ministerial decision.\nIn August 2020, President Recep Tayyip Erdogan signed a decree on the conversion of the Hagia Sophia Cathedral and the Kari Museum, known as a \u201cbottomless church \u201d in Turkish, into mosques.\nThe conversion of the two churches into mosques was praised by Muslims, but drew criticism from Greece and other countries that urged Turkey to protect important Byzantine monuments, both of which have been listed as World Heritage Sites by the United Nations.\nSource: A B\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0012.json.gz:13896","uncompressed_offset":954300905,"url":"arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/","warc_date":"2024-05-06T23:13:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d766c719-43c0-4423-80e6-89c1f9dc9d52>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/world/1562600-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%B7%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF/"},"created":"2024-05-07T00:44:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":{"id":"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","text":"World News\nErdogan: Church of the Savior in Khora to be converted into a mosque: it will remain open to all\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, in the presence of Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, confirmed the conversion of the ancient Orthodox Church of the Saviour in Istanbul to a mosque, despite calls from Greece not to go ahead with the move.\nSpeaking at a joint news conference with Mitsotakis in Ankara, Erdogan said: \"The Karye Mosque in its new form will remain open to all.\"\nThe Turkish president said he had told the Greek prime minister, \u201cWe opened the Carr\u00e9 mosque for prayers and visits after careful restoration work in accordance with the decision we made in 2020. \u201d\n\u201cWe attach great importance to protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO \u2019 s cultural heritage and making it available for the benefit of our nation and all humanity. \u201d\nThe Greek prime minister has opposed the conversion of the church, which contains frescoes representing the \"judgment\" dating back to the 14th century, into a mosque.\nThese were the details of the news Erdogan confirmed the conversion of the Church of the Saviour in Khora to a mosque: it will remain open to everyone for today, we hope that we have succeeded by giving you the details and full information and to follow all our news you can subscribe to the system of alerts or one of our different systems to provide you with everything new.\nIt should also be noted that the original news has been published and is available on the bulletin (Lebanon) has been verified by the editorial team in Gulf 365 and may have been modified and may have been transferred in full or quoted from it and you can read and follow up on the news from its main source.\nAdvertisements\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0013.json.gz:17131","uncompressed_offset":427727559,"url":"gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html","warc_date":"2024-05-18T01:44:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b>","warc_url":"https://gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html"},"created":"2024-05-18T02:25:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1040","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1040","narrative_id":"1040"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various quarters."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been viewed as a highly politicized move by Erdogan, aimed at shoring up his Islamo-nationalist base, particularly in the face of a weakened economy and lack of political perspective."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, has a rich history as both a Byzantine cathedral and an Ottoman mosque, and its conversion has been criticized by Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the decision as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque was announced in 2020, despite his earlier refusal to do so, with him telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque before talking about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, with many viewing it as a national win for Turkey, and a symbol of the Conquest."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"However, the decision has also been criticized for its potential to undermine the country's multiculturalism, with many observers believing that Erdogan is using the move to erase part of the country's multicultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is not an isolated incident, with another ancient Byzantine church, the Chora Church, also being converted into a mosque, known as the Kariye Mosque."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"The Kariye Mosque, which spent 79 years as a museum, was reopened for prayers in 2020, with Erdogan stating that it would remain open to all, despite criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Kariye Mosque into a mosque has been viewed as a highly symbolic move, with Erdogan quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet, saying \"Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul\"."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding the conversion of the Hagia Sophia and the Kariye Mosque into mosques has sparked a heated debate about the role of religion in Turkish politics, with many critics arguing that Erdogan is using the move to consolidate his power and appeal to his Islamist base."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In response to the criticism, Erdogan has stated that the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a matter of Turkish history and culture, and that it is a decision that has been made to protect the country's heritage."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"However, critics argue that the decision is a highly politicized move, aimed at undermining the country's secular traditions and promoting a more Islamist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia and the Kariye Mosque into mosques has also sparked concerns about the preservation of the country's cultural heritage, with many critics arguing that the move could lead to the erosion of the country's multicultural identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the controversy surrounding the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various quarters, with many critics arguing that the move is a highly politicized decision aimed at promoting Erdogan's Islamist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been criticized by Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, and has sparked concerns about the preservation of the country's cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a decision that has significant implications for the future of Turkish politics and society, and one that will continue to be debated and contested in the years to come."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The controversy surrounding Turkish President Erdogan's reconversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque in 2020 is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various quarters."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been viewed as a highly politicized move by Erdogan, aimed at shoring up his Islamo-nationalist base, particularly in the face of a weakened economy and lack of political perspective."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, has a rich history as both a Byzantine cathedral and an Ottoman mosque, and its conversion has been criticized by Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The Greek Orthodox Church has decried the decision as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom\"."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Erdogan's decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque was announced in 2020, despite his earlier refusal to do so, with him telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque before talking about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been praised by Muslims, with many viewing it as a national win for Turkey, and a symbol of the Conquest."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"However, the decision has also been criticized for its potential to undermine the country's multiculturalism, with many observers believing that Erdogan is using the move to erase part of the country's multicultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is not an isolated incident, with another ancient Byzantine church, the Chora Church, also being converted into a mosque, known as the Kariye Mosque."},{"citations":{"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":1.0},"text":"The Kariye Mosque, which spent 79 years as a museum, was reopened for prayers in 2020, with Erdogan stating that it would remain open to all, despite criticism from Greece and other countries."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Kariye Mosque into a mosque has been viewed as a highly symbolic move, with Erdogan quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet, saying \"Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul\"."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"The controversy surrounding the conversion of the Hagia Sophia and the Kariye Mosque into mosques has sparked a heated debate about the role of religion in Turkish politics, with many critics arguing that Erdogan is using the move to consolidate his power and appeal to his Islamist base."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"In response to the criticism, Erdogan has stated that the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a matter of Turkish history and culture, and that it is a decision that has been made to protect the country's heritage."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"However, critics argue that the decision is a highly politicized move, aimed at undermining the country's secular traditions and promoting a more Islamist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The conversion of the Hagia Sophia and the Kariye Mosque into mosques has also sparked concerns about the preservation of the country's cultural heritage, with many critics arguing that the move could lead to the erosion of the country's multicultural identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the controversy surrounding the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a complex issue that has sparked intense debate and criticism from various quarters, with many critics arguing that the move is a highly politicized decision aimed at promoting Erdogan's Islamist agenda."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision to convert the Hagia Sophia into a mosque has been criticized by Greece, the U.S. State Department, and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide, and has sparked concerns about the preservation of the country's cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a mosque is a decision that has significant implications for the future of Turkish politics and society, and one that will continue to be debated and contested in the years to come."}],"references":["08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559":{"id":"9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b_427727559","text":"World News\nErdogan: Church of the Savior in Khora to be converted into a mosque: it will remain open to all\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, in the presence of Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, confirmed the conversion of the ancient Orthodox Church of the Saviour in Istanbul to a mosque, despite calls from Greece not to go ahead with the move.\nSpeaking at a joint news conference with Mitsotakis in Ankara, Erdogan said: \"The Karye Mosque in its new form will remain open to all.\"\nThe Turkish president said he had told the Greek prime minister, \u201cWe opened the Carr\u00e9 mosque for prayers and visits after careful restoration work in accordance with the decision we made in 2020. \u201d\n\u201cWe attach great importance to protecting any monument that is part of UNESCO \u2019 s cultural heritage and making it available for the benefit of our nation and all humanity. \u201d\nThe Greek prime minister has opposed the conversion of the church, which contains frescoes representing the \"judgment\" dating back to the 14th century, into a mosque.\nThese were the details of the news Erdogan confirmed the conversion of the Church of the Saviour in Khora to a mosque: it will remain open to everyone for today, we hope that we have succeeded by giving you the details and full information and to follow all our news you can subscribe to the system of alerts or one of our different systems to provide you with everything new.\nIt should also be noted that the original news has been published and is available on the bulletin (Lebanon) has been verified by the editorial team in Gulf 365 and may have been modified and may have been transferred in full or quoted from it and you can read and follow up on the news from its main source.\nAdvertisements\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0013.json.gz:17131","uncompressed_offset":427727559,"url":"gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html","warc_date":"2024-05-18T01:44:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9dd219f6-2d94-4cd6-a905-bbd3c87a161b>","warc_url":"https://gulf365.net/world-news/12557019/%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%BA%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%83%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%91%D8%B5-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AC%D8%AF-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A8%D9%82%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AC%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B9.html"},"created":"2024-05-18T02:25:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1041","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1041","narrative_id":"1041"},"responses":[{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The current research on traditional Indian medicine is focused on integrating it into mainstream medical practice, with support from organizations such as the World Health Organisation (WHO)."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The WHO is working with the UK\u2019s All-Party Parliamentary Group on Indian Traditional Sciences to facilitate research projects on traditional medicine."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In India, the government is documenting medicinal herbs and healers of tribal communities across the country, with a pilot project in Uttarakhand resulting in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The project involves chemical analysis of the plants to find the active ingredients, using techniques such as HPLC."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"Ayurveda, a traditional Indian system of medicine, believes in using herbs, spices, and minerals to treat diseases, and diet therapy and lifestyle adjustments such as yoga and meditation are also used."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is also setting up a global centre for traditional medicine in Hyderabad, with support from the WHO, to promote the use of traditional medicine and provide a reliable evidence base for its practices and products."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The centre will focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products, and will help countries integrate these practices into their health systems."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"The Ayush ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine, and is harnessing the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities in G20 countries for the benefit of humankind."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is focused on promoting its use and providing a reliable evidence base for its practices and products, with support from organizations such as the WHO and the Indian government."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The current research on traditional Indian medicine is focused on integrating it into mainstream medical practice, with support from organizations such as the World Health Organisation (WHO)."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The WHO is working with the UK\u2019s All-Party Parliamentary Group on Indian Traditional Sciences to facilitate research projects on traditional medicine."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In India, the government is documenting medicinal herbs and healers of tribal communities across the country, with a pilot project in Uttarakhand resulting in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The project involves chemical analysis of the plants to find the active ingredients, using techniques such as HPLC."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"Ayurveda, a traditional Indian system of medicine, believes in using herbs, spices, and minerals to treat diseases, and diet therapy and lifestyle adjustments such as yoga and meditation are also used."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is also setting up a global centre for traditional medicine in Hyderabad, with support from the WHO, to promote the use of traditional medicine and provide a reliable evidence base for its practices and products."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The centre will focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products, and will help countries integrate these practices into their health systems."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"The Ayush ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine, and is harnessing the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities in G20 countries for the benefit of humankind."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is focused on promoting its use and providing a reliable evidence base for its practices and products, with support from organizations such as the WHO and the Indian government."}],"references":["cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576","ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076","12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395","cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701","98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869","af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638"],"documents":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":{"id":"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576","text":"Archive / Lifestyle\nThe World Health Organization is interested in alternative medicine.\nMohamed Ismail - Cairo - DPA -\nMany people use traditional medicine \u2013 but what do these methods really do?\nA new WHO centre intends to explore this.\nThe center is based in India, a country where alternative medicine is so important that it even has its own ministry \u2013 which specializes in Ayurveda, Yoga, Physiotherapy, Greek Medicine, Master and Homeopathy.\nIndian Prime Minister Narendra Modi attended the opening of the centre in Jamnagar in mid-April, saying: \u201cIndia \u2019 s traditional medicine system is not just a cure.\nIt \u2019 s a comprehensive science of life. \u201d\nAccording to the World Health Organization (WHO), the Indian government is supporting the centre with US $250 million (230 million euros).\nWHO President Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said: \u201cThe center aims to be an engine of innovation, moving towards an agenda of evidence, data and sustainability in traditional medicine, \u201d adding that the center would connect traditional medicine practitioners around the world and help set standards for research.\nTraditional medicine is a broad field.\nAccording to the World Health Organization \u2019 s statement for the center, 80% of the world \u2019 s population uses traditional medicine, which includes among other things acupuncture, Ayurvedic medicine and herbal blends.\nTraditional medicine is also represented in modern science.\nAccording to the World Health Organization, about 40% of all drugs approved today are derived from natural substances.\nThe discovery of aspirin, for example, is based on ancient recipes made from the bark of the willow tree.\nThe research for artemisinin for use in the fight against malaria, for which the Nobel Prize was awarded in 2015, began with the study of ancient texts of Chinese medicine.\nGeorge Rochmeyer of Cochrane, an international network that provides the scientific basis for decisions in the health field, said it makes sense at least to take a closer look at treatment methods that have been developed over centuries, to verify the reasonableness of these methods, and to conduct clinical studies on them in case of doubt.\nCochrane reviews are systematic reviews that collect all scientific evidence on a specific issue from medicine or other health sciences.\nHowever, Rochmeyer also stressed that besides the examples of traditional methods cited by the WHO, which form the basis of currently developed treatments, there are likely many other examples where traditional methods of careful review have proven ineffective or even dangerous, such as phlebotomy, noting that spending too much money on studies to review a therapeutic practice is always a matter of discretion.\nRochmeyer stated that there are many Cochrane reviews about the use of traditional methods such as acupuncture in certain cases, but: \u201cFrom my personal experience at Cochrane, I would say that I have not come across many reviews that have shown really compelling evidence for traditional therapeutic practice. \u201d\nThis is often due to the fact that when searching for these treatments we find only a few often-poorly conducted studies that cannot prove or disprove any benefit from them \u2013 which brings us back to the question of whether the already limited research funds should be invested in a scientifically unreasonable procedure \u2013 for example, homeopathy.\nProfessor Emeritus Edzard Ernst, a longtime professor of alternative medicine at the University of Exeter, noted that while it was necessary to wait and see who would lead the center and what it would do, the WHO press release was full of exaggerations.\nThe World Health Organization says it also wants to use new technologies at the new center for the study of traditional medicine \u2014 via artificial intelligence and big data, for example.\nThe center is expected to focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products.\nIn addition, the center is supposed to help countries integrate these practices into their health systems.\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0013.json.gz:30702","uncompressed_offset":261399576,"url":"alkhaleej365.com/lifestyle/11546295/%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B8%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84.html","warc_date":"2022-05-07T16:07:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7>","warc_url":"https://alkhaleej365.com/lifestyle/11546295/%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B8%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84.html"},"created":"2022-05-07T16:21:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":{"id":"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638","text":"Govt to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities\n\nCentre to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities across country\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand\n\nThe Centre is working on documenting medicinal herbs and healers of the tribal communities across the country. A pilot from Uttarakhand has been completed, resulting in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants. The exercise, officials said, will be carried out in more states.\u00a0\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand. Apart from documenting the plant and healers, they also documented the Sanskrit names of these plants.\u00a0\n\nIn Kerala, the Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham was given the responsibility, All India Institute of Medical Studies Jodhpur in Rajasthan, Pravara Institute of Medical Sciences Ahmedabad for Maharashtra, and Patanjali carried it out in Uttarakhand.\u00a0\n\nWhile the others are carrying it out, Patanjali\u2019s series of seven tomes are ready. In the hill state three districts were chosen, which included Pithoragarh and Udham Singh Nagar, all phytodiversity was documented by a team of over 50-50 people over a period of two years.\u00a0\n\nWhen asked about the Sanskrit nomenclature, the official said that it was a way of directing attention to the functionality of the plant.\u00a0\n\n\u201cThe National Medicinal Plant Board says there are over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented. But in three districts alone, we found 900 plants,\u201d a senior official of the ministry said. \u201cTribal medicine holds considerable interest among researchers.\u201d\n\nChemical analysis of all these plants was carried out, to find the active ingredient in the plant, with the help of an HPLC machine, officials said. Apart from that, samples of these were preserved, along with data on their therapeutic use. The official said that permissions from the biodiversity board were also taken.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nIn addition to that, the Hyderabad-based National Institute of Pharmaceutical Education and Research (NIPER) carried out a similar exercise in their areas where they found three medicinal plants, which when combined can be a cure for malaria. A similar exercise was carried out by the same team in the Rashtrapati Bhawan as well.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nHealers in tribal communities in the areas that use these plants were also documented, along with data of their areas of expertise. In all, 750 healers were documented.\u00a0\n\nOfficials said that after the successful pilot, the ministry has sent it to the AYUSH ministry, urging them to take it further across the country using SC/ST components from their funds. Officials also said that details of these plants will be put up online.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\nCheck out all newsletters\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\n\u00a0","url":"https://www.deccanherald.com/national/centre-to-document-medicinal-herbs-of-tribal-communities-across-country-1112440.html"},"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":{"id":"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701","text":"India \u2019 s medical facilities speed up the development of intelligent system to help rural remote consultation\nAuthor \uff1a 01 Source of Medical Clinic\nPublished: Updated:\nFor many Hong Kong people, India may look like a relatively backward and populous country, with a population of 1.4 billion, and it is hard to imagine how the local medical system can accommodate such a large population.\nThe author went to the local area to participate in the large-scale international engineering alliance conference, found that the local medical facilities are developing rapidly, the number of hospital beds in the country has increased by 40% in the past 10 years, and some large hospitals have added intelligent equipment to assist in the diagnosis and daily operation of the hospital.\nIf you have the ability to increase investment in the future, coupled with the development of local information technology, and gradually trend towards intelligent development, I believe that it is not difficult to see the emergence of comprehensive intelligent hospitals, so that patient services are more efficient and no longer subject to geographical restrictions.\nAuthor: Yuan Pak Leung, Former President of the Institution of Senior Engineers and Engineers\nI am the Vice-Chairman of the International Engineering Technologists Agreement and the Chairman of the British delegation chaired a review meeting of the agreement in New Delhi, India.\nAs the Vice President of the International Engineering Technologists Agreement (IETTA), I went to New Delhi, India, to attend this year \u2019 s IETTA conference hosted by my host, and also chaired the annual meeting held in India in the same capacity as the chairman of the Seoul Accord.\nOver the course of more than 10 days, I have met many people in the engineering industry from all over India, some from the medical industry, so I have the opportunity to learn more about the development of local hospital facilities.\nAccording to the local industry, the number of hospitals and beds in India has increased rapidly over the past decade. For example, from 2010 to 2020, the total number of beds in the country has increased from about 1.2 million to more than 1.7 million, an increase of more than 40%.\nAs of 2023, the market share of hospital spending across India, including public and private hospitals, is in the hundreds of billions of dollars. However, the number of beds per 1,000 people is still relatively low globally.\nOn both sides of a highway in New Delhi, I saw 20 medical statues placed by Yatharth Hospital to thank and honor the work of \u201canti-virus warriors \u201d during the COVID-19 pandemic.\nHowever, unlike in Hong Kong, Indian hospitals are dominated by private hospitals, accounting for 70% of the total number of beds.\nSome people in the local industry admit that this reflects that the investment in public health care is not enough at present, but it is understood that the local public sector is trying to catch up with the demand, but the demand is too large and it is difficult to meet 100%.\nTherefore, ensuring equitable access to quality health care is a challenge for local authorities, especially in remote areas such as mountains or rural areas.\nIt is said that there is a medical culture in India with a long history in Asia that can alleviate some of the medical needs of the general population.\nIt is a system of traditional medicine called Ayurveda, which is called Ayurveda. It is composed of two Sanskrit words, ayur refers to life and veda means knowledge.\nTogether, they mean \u201cknowledge of life \u201d and are considered to be one of the most ancient forms of holistic natural medicine in the world, originating from ancient India, for thousands of years. Ayurveda and Chinese medicine have many things in common, especially the focus of both is on the patient, not on the disease.\nIts core concept is to maintain their own spiritual balance and harmony, will make people physically healthy, the theory that life should avoid excessive hyperactivity, because it will lead to too much stomach acid, so that people become irritable, anxiety and other problems.\nExcessive hyperactivity can also affect the joints, mucous membranes, and fats that protect our body structure, leading to obesity and depression, and people \u2019 s physical and mental activities, including breathing, blood circulation, and nervous system if over-regulation, can bring anxiety, constipation, joint pain and so on.\nAyurveda emphasizes the uniqueness of the individual and regulates and prevents diseases according to the physical and psychological characteristics of the individual.\nIn general, Ayurveda believes that a variety of herbs, spices, minerals, etc. can be used to treat diseases, and diet therapy is used to adjust the diet according to the body, while lifestyle adjustments include yoga, meditation and massage.\nIn addition to its unique medical concept, India \u2019 s relatively advanced information technology development, I believe it can also be an opportunity to make up for the lack of medical services.\nIn fact, many local hospitals have begun to add intelligent systems, such as electronic medical record system, remote medical system and the application of digital technology, which improve the ability of doctors to treat patients, and increase the ability of remote consultation, so that patients in remote rural areas can benefit.\nIn order to increase the efficiency of consultation and make more accurate diagnosis, local doctors will also use wearable devices to understand the patient \u2019 s physical condition, and even use intelligent systems to help make clinical decisions.\nThe conference hotel I stayed at offers authentic Indian Ayurveda healing massages, including the Ayurveda oil drip, which is said to be effective in helping to relieve stress.\nThe author believes that Hong Kong and India have very different cultural backgrounds, but they are also working hard to promote the development of intelligent hospitals.\nHowever, some local technology industry people pointed out that, regardless of whether the two places or other regions should pay more attention to the convenience and efficiency of intelligent systems, there are opportunities for network security risks or personal data leakage, so there are challenges when using different smart technologies.\nWith the rapid development of the local medical system with advanced technology, I believe that if the world can introduce more intelligent elements in its medical system, and continue to invest in it, coupled with the policy support of government departments, we can cite each other, exchange learning and practice verification, I believe that it is not difficult to build a fully intelligent hospital in the future, and hope that this efficient service model can meet the increasing medical demand of society.\n\"01 Medical Clinic\" cooperates with senior engineer Yuan Pak Leung to launch a column \"Source Road Has You\" every Monday to share the big and small things of engineering and medical care.\nYuan Pak Leung has always been committed to promoting the professional development of the engineering profession and is the former President of the Hong Kong Institution of Engineers.\nThe decades of professional journey are worth remembering, and I am convinced that the latter may understand the key points of the engineering profession.\nIf you have the source, let everyone experience it together.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0018.json.gz:40633","uncompressed_offset":536799701,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/1040317/%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E9%86%AB%E7%99%82%E8%A8%AD%E6%96%BD%E7%99%BC%E5%B1%95%E6%8F%90%E9%80%9F-%E6%99%BA%E8%83%BD%E5%8C%96%E7%B3%BB%E7%B5%B1%E5%8A%A9%E9%84%89%E9%83%8A%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%95%8F%E8%A8%BA","warc_date":"2024-07-21T23:40:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/1040317/%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E9%86%AB%E7%99%82%E8%A8%AD%E6%96%BD%E7%99%BC%E5%B1%95%E6%8F%90%E9%80%9F-%E6%99%BA%E8%83%BD%E5%8C%96%E7%B3%BB%E7%B5%B1%E5%8A%A9%E9%84%89%E9%83%8A%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%95%8F%E8%A8%BA"},"created":"2024-07-22T00:45:20.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":{"id":"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076","text":"Tuesday 10 August 2021 1:10 pm\n\nLong Covid cure? Researchers to trial traditional Indian herb treatment\n\nThe London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine will work with the All India Institute of Ayurveda to determine whether a traditional Indian herb can help people recover from long Covid.\n\nAshwagandha, commonly known as Indian winter cherry, is traditionally used in the Indian Ayurvedic system of medicine to boost energy, reduce stress and strengthen the immune system.\n\nExperts said recent trials had proven the herb\u2019s efficacy in reducing anxiety, stress, improving muscle strength and reducing fatigue symptoms in patients with chronic diseases.\n\nLong Covid patients can suffer from cognitive dysfunction, poor mental health, extreme fatigue and muscle weakness.\n\nIt is estimated these symptoms affect 10 to 20 per cent of Covid survivors and can last for one to three months or longer in many cases.\n\nThe study, funded by the Ministry of Ayush of the Government of India, will include a double-blind clinical trial involving 2,000 people living in the UK with long Covid.\n\nHalf of the trial participants will take 500mg Ashwagandha tablets twice a day for three months, while the other half will be given a placebo.\n\nResearchers will randomly select participants to have a monthly follow-up of self-reported quality of life, impairment to activities of daily living, mental and physical health symptoms, supplement use and adverse events.\n\nThe study is expected to last for over a year.\n\n\u201cAshwagandha has been shown to reduce symptoms of other conditions that are similar to those of long Covid, so we are hopeful that it will be an effective way to combat the condition,\u201d said Sanjay Kinra, professor in clinical epidemiology at the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine.\n\nThe research is also supported by the UK\u2019s All-Party Parliamentary Group on Indian Traditional Sciences and the Traditional Complementary and Integrative Medicine Unit at the World Health Organisation (WHO).\n\nResearch is the only way to ensure appropriate integration of traditional medicine knowledge into mainstream medical practice,\u201d said technical officer at WHO Geneva, Geetha Krishnan, who helped to facilitate the research project.\n\nShare","url":"https://www.cityam.com/long-covid-cure-researchers-to-trial-traditional-indian-herb-treatment/"},"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":{"id":"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395","text":"News\nNews\n\nM&A\n\nFeature\nFeature\n\nMedical Specialties\nMedical Specialties\n\nData & Analytics\nData & Analytics\n\nBrand Solutions\nBrand Solutions\n\nView Site\n\nG20 science advisors to discuss pre-competitive collaboration, traditional knowledge\n\nOnce it reaches a certain level of maturity, of course different countries will have their take. But pre-competitive R&D (research and development) space is what we think should be something where we should work:\n\nNew Delhi: In a bid to bolster the fight against future pandemics, India's top scientific advisor Prof Ajay Kumar Sood has urged G20 countries to collaborate in developing vaccine platforms by cooperating with each other in the pre-competitive research and development phase.\n\nIn a video interview Sood, who will chair the Chief Scientific Advisors' Roundtable (CSAR) of G20 countries next week, said India will also present its traditional systems of medicine and seek to harness the knowledge of indigenous communities of different countries.\n\nMaking a strong pitch for collaboration among G20 nations in drug development, Sood, the principal scientific advisor to the government, said there is enormous scope for cooperation in the pre-competitive research and development space.\n\n\"Once it reaches a certain level of maturity, of course different countries will have their take. But pre-competitive R&D (research and development) space is what we think should be something where we should work,\" he said.\n\nSood identified emerging technologies for environmental surveillance as another area for cooperation.\n\n\"This is something which has to be done by all countries. A lot of it is happening but there are many other countries which will need a helping hand. So, we should be ready to take everyone along,\" he said.\n\nPre-competitive collaboration involves two or more companies operating within the same industry coming together to address a shared problem or pain point that doesn't impact direct business competition or contribute to unfair advantage.\n\n\"When there is a pandemic, you cannot live in isolation. We have seen it in COVID, all countries will have to fight it together and it has to be eradicated or controlled at all places. If it does not, then it will linger on and that is what you are seeing for COVID,\" Sood said.\n\nHe said the CSAR meeting in Uttarakhand's Ramnagar from March 28-30 will also focus on harnessing the benefits of traditional knowledge in healthcare.\n\n\"Traditional medicine has a very important role to play but it should be put in scientific context. All that work has to be done. When you have traditional medicines, how can we put it on a platform where it meets the acceptance of science,\" he said.\n\nSood said India has a very rich tradition of Ayurveda, Siddha and Unani and all of them have a role to play. It could be to build up immunity or strength or to address the symptoms of a disease, adding \" whatever you think, it is possible\".\n\n\"We should not try to limit ourselves to only what we call modern medicine,\" he said, making a strong pitch for diversity in various systems of medicine.\n\nSood also talked about harnessing the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities in G20 countries for the benefit of humankind.\n\n\"These are very, very old traditions. The goal should be, what we call traditional knowledge, it is really tested over centuries. It is very important that we take this traditional knowledge along with the other streams,\" Sood said.\n\nSood said the Ayush ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine.\n\n\"The Ayush ministry is doing that. This word was coined a few years back ayurvedic biology to address the issue of scientific validity. I am sure that in other countries there are parallel efforts. Because these tribal, traditional things are also very important and we need to learn from them,\" Sood said.\n\nThe three-day meeting in Ramnagar will focus on four broad themes Opportunities in One Health for better disease control and pandemic preparedness; Synergising global efforts to expand the access to scholarly scientific knowledge; Diversity, equity, inclusion and accessibility in science and technology (S&T); and an Institutional mechanism for inclusive, continuous and action-oriented global S&T policy dialogue.\n\nGet latest Industry insights and analysis in your inbox\n\nLearn from updates & industry leaders Daily.\n\nGreat, We will keep you updated\n\nDownload our App for Realtime updates\n\nDownload App\n\nFollow and connect with us on , Facebook, Linkedin, Youtube\nPartners:","url":"https://health.economictimes.indiatimes.com/amp/news/industry/g20-science-advisors-to-discuss-pre-competitive-collaboration-traditional-knowledge/98989510"},"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":{"id":"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869","text":"Telangana\n\nCentre in favour of locating global centre for traditional medicine in Hyderabad\n\nThe city is likely to have another jewel in its crown if the Central Government\u2019s latest request relating to the setting up of a global centre for traditional medicine proposed by the World Health Organisation (WHO) is any indication.\n\nUnion Minister for Tourism, Culture and Development of North East Region G. Kishan Reddy has requested the State Government to identify a suitable parcel of land for setting up the institute in the city. In a letter addressed to Chief Minister K. Chandrasekhar Rao, the Union Minister asked him to resolve the issues pertaining to identification of land and spot a parcel of land.\n\nHe said that the country is known for its traditional medicines, including Ayurveda, yoga, Unani, naturopathy, Sowa-Ripa and Siddha to name a few, which are recognised worldwide. The COVID pandemic had further highlighted the benefits of traditional medicine and demonstrated the power of Ayurveda to the world.\n\n\u201cIndia is regarded as the pharmacy of the world and focus on traditional medicine aligns with Prime Minister Narendra Modi\u2019s emphasis on prevention of diseases and wellness,\u201d he said. He recalled that the WHO director general had announced intentions of setting up a global centre for traditional medicine in India on the occasion of World Ayurveda Day in November 2020.\n\nThe Union AYUSH Ministry was considering setting up of the centre in Hyderabad as traditional scientific research institutions like CCMB, CSIR, NIN, IICT, and FDTRC would further complement the approach towards an integrated holistic medicine. The Government of Telangana had been communicated for their inputs on the extent of support for setting up of the global centre, he said, adding that the global centre would benefit the city and the State.\n\n\nOur code of editorial values\n\nPrintable version | Feb 18, 2022 8:35:17 pm | https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/telangana/centre-in-favour-of-locating-global-centre-for-traditional-medicine-in-hyderabad/article65062674.ece","url":"https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/telangana/centre-in-favour-of-locating-global-centre-for-traditional-medicine-in-hyderabad/article65062674.ece"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1042","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1042","narrative_id":"1042"},"responses":[{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is a rapidly growing field, with various institutions and organizations working together to promote its development and integration into mainstream medical practice."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The World Health Organization (WHO) is one of the key players in this field, and has established a Traditional Complementary and Integrative Medicine Unit to support research and development of traditional medicine, including Indian herbal medicine."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"According to Geetha Krishnan, a technical officer at WHO Geneva, research is the only way to ensure appropriate integration of traditional medicine knowledge into mainstream medical practice."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In India, the government is also taking steps to promote the development of traditional Indian medicine, including the documentation of medicinal herbs and healers of tribal communities across the country."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The union ministry of tribal affairs has carried out this initiative in several states, including Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra, and Uttarakhand, and has documented over 1,400 medicinal plants in a five-volume book series."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Medicinal Plant Board has also identified over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented, highlighting the vast potential of Indian herbal medicine."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Chemical analysis of these plants has been carried out to find the active ingredient in the plant, with the help of an HPLC machine, and the results are expected to contribute to the development of new drugs and therapies."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In addition to the government initiatives, several institutions and research centers are also working on the development of Indian herbal medicine, including the Patanjali research center in Uttarakhand, which has documented over 900 plants in three districts."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The All India Institute of Medical Studies Jodhpur in Rajasthan, and the Pravara Institute of Medical Sciences Ahmedabad in Maharashtra are also involved in this initiative."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"The use of Indian herbal medicine is not limited to the treatment of specific diseases, but also includes prevention and wellness, with a focus on diet therapy, yoga, meditation, and massage."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"Ayurveda, a traditional system of medicine in India, believes that a variety of herbs, spices, minerals, and other substances can be used to treat diseases, and that diet and lifestyle adjustments are essential for maintaining health."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is also promoting the use of technology, including electronic medical record systems, remote medical systems, and digital technology, to improve the delivery of healthcare services and increase access to traditional Indian medicine."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The World Health Organization has also announced plans to set up a global center for traditional medicine in India, which will focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The center is expected to be located in Hyderabad, and will be supported by the Indian government with a funding of $250 million."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The center will also use new technologies, including artificial intelligence and big data, to study traditional medicine and develop new treatments and therapies."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The Indian government has also established a ministry of AYUSH, which is responsible for promoting and regulating the use of traditional Indian medicine, including Ayurveda, yoga, naturopathy, and other systems of medicine."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"The ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine, and is promoting the use of traditional knowledge and indigenous practices in healthcare."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"According to Dr. Sood, the goal of the AYUSH ministry is to promote diversity in various systems of medicine, and to harness the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities for the benefit of humankind."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The use of Indian herbal medicine has been shown to be effective in the treatment of various diseases, including COVID-19, and has the potential to contribute to the development of new drugs and therapies."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The Indian government and the World Health Organization are working together to promote the development and integration of traditional Indian medicine into mainstream medical practice, and to provide access to safe and effective healthcare services to people around the world."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is a rapidly growing field, with vast potential for the development of new treatments and therapies, and for the promotion of health and wellness."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is a rapidly growing field, with various institutions and organizations working together to promote its development and integration into mainstream medical practice."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The World Health Organization (WHO) is one of the key players in this field, and has established a Traditional Complementary and Integrative Medicine Unit to support research and development of traditional medicine, including Indian herbal medicine."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"According to Geetha Krishnan, a technical officer at WHO Geneva, research is the only way to ensure appropriate integration of traditional medicine knowledge into mainstream medical practice."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In India, the government is also taking steps to promote the development of traditional Indian medicine, including the documentation of medicinal herbs and healers of tribal communities across the country."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The union ministry of tribal affairs has carried out this initiative in several states, including Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra, and Uttarakhand, and has documented over 1,400 medicinal plants in a five-volume book series."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Medicinal Plant Board has also identified over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented, highlighting the vast potential of Indian herbal medicine."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Chemical analysis of these plants has been carried out to find the active ingredient in the plant, with the help of an HPLC machine, and the results are expected to contribute to the development of new drugs and therapies."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In addition to the government initiatives, several institutions and research centers are also working on the development of Indian herbal medicine, including the Patanjali research center in Uttarakhand, which has documented over 900 plants in three districts."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The All India Institute of Medical Studies Jodhpur in Rajasthan, and the Pravara Institute of Medical Sciences Ahmedabad in Maharashtra are also involved in this initiative."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"The use of Indian herbal medicine is not limited to the treatment of specific diseases, but also includes prevention and wellness, with a focus on diet therapy, yoga, meditation, and massage."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"Ayurveda, a traditional system of medicine in India, believes that a variety of herbs, spices, minerals, and other substances can be used to treat diseases, and that diet and lifestyle adjustments are essential for maintaining health."},{"citations":{"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is also promoting the use of technology, including electronic medical record systems, remote medical systems, and digital technology, to improve the delivery of healthcare services and increase access to traditional Indian medicine."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The World Health Organization has also announced plans to set up a global center for traditional medicine in India, which will focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The center is expected to be located in Hyderabad, and will be supported by the Indian government with a funding of $250 million."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The center will also use new technologies, including artificial intelligence and big data, to study traditional medicine and develop new treatments and therapies."},{"citations":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":1.0},"text":"The Indian government has also established a ministry of AYUSH, which is responsible for promoting and regulating the use of traditional Indian medicine, including Ayurveda, yoga, naturopathy, and other systems of medicine."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"The ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine, and is promoting the use of traditional knowledge and indigenous practices in healthcare."},{"citations":{"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":1.0},"text":"According to Dr. Sood, the goal of the AYUSH ministry is to promote diversity in various systems of medicine, and to harness the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities for the benefit of humankind."},{"citations":{"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":1.0},"text":"The use of Indian herbal medicine has been shown to be effective in the treatment of various diseases, including COVID-19, and has the potential to contribute to the development of new drugs and therapies."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"The Indian government and the World Health Organization are working together to promote the development and integration of traditional Indian medicine into mainstream medical practice, and to provide access to safe and effective healthcare services to people around the world."},{"citations":{"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current research and application of Indian herbal medicine is a rapidly growing field, with vast potential for the development of new treatments and therapies, and for the promotion of health and wellness."}],"references":["cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576","ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076","12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395","cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701","98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869","af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638"],"documents":{"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576":{"id":"cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7_261399576","text":"Archive / Lifestyle\nThe World Health Organization is interested in alternative medicine.\nMohamed Ismail - Cairo - DPA -\nMany people use traditional medicine \u2013 but what do these methods really do?\nA new WHO centre intends to explore this.\nThe center is based in India, a country where alternative medicine is so important that it even has its own ministry \u2013 which specializes in Ayurveda, Yoga, Physiotherapy, Greek Medicine, Master and Homeopathy.\nIndian Prime Minister Narendra Modi attended the opening of the centre in Jamnagar in mid-April, saying: \u201cIndia \u2019 s traditional medicine system is not just a cure.\nIt \u2019 s a comprehensive science of life. \u201d\nAccording to the World Health Organization (WHO), the Indian government is supporting the centre with US $250 million (230 million euros).\nWHO President Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said: \u201cThe center aims to be an engine of innovation, moving towards an agenda of evidence, data and sustainability in traditional medicine, \u201d adding that the center would connect traditional medicine practitioners around the world and help set standards for research.\nTraditional medicine is a broad field.\nAccording to the World Health Organization \u2019 s statement for the center, 80% of the world \u2019 s population uses traditional medicine, which includes among other things acupuncture, Ayurvedic medicine and herbal blends.\nTraditional medicine is also represented in modern science.\nAccording to the World Health Organization, about 40% of all drugs approved today are derived from natural substances.\nThe discovery of aspirin, for example, is based on ancient recipes made from the bark of the willow tree.\nThe research for artemisinin for use in the fight against malaria, for which the Nobel Prize was awarded in 2015, began with the study of ancient texts of Chinese medicine.\nGeorge Rochmeyer of Cochrane, an international network that provides the scientific basis for decisions in the health field, said it makes sense at least to take a closer look at treatment methods that have been developed over centuries, to verify the reasonableness of these methods, and to conduct clinical studies on them in case of doubt.\nCochrane reviews are systematic reviews that collect all scientific evidence on a specific issue from medicine or other health sciences.\nHowever, Rochmeyer also stressed that besides the examples of traditional methods cited by the WHO, which form the basis of currently developed treatments, there are likely many other examples where traditional methods of careful review have proven ineffective or even dangerous, such as phlebotomy, noting that spending too much money on studies to review a therapeutic practice is always a matter of discretion.\nRochmeyer stated that there are many Cochrane reviews about the use of traditional methods such as acupuncture in certain cases, but: \u201cFrom my personal experience at Cochrane, I would say that I have not come across many reviews that have shown really compelling evidence for traditional therapeutic practice. \u201d\nThis is often due to the fact that when searching for these treatments we find only a few often-poorly conducted studies that cannot prove or disprove any benefit from them \u2013 which brings us back to the question of whether the already limited research funds should be invested in a scientifically unreasonable procedure \u2013 for example, homeopathy.\nProfessor Emeritus Edzard Ernst, a longtime professor of alternative medicine at the University of Exeter, noted that while it was necessary to wait and see who would lead the center and what it would do, the WHO press release was full of exaggerations.\nThe World Health Organization says it also wants to use new technologies at the new center for the study of traditional medicine \u2014 via artificial intelligence and big data, for example.\nThe center is expected to focus on providing a reliable evidence base for policy and standards of traditional medicine practices and products.\nIn addition, the center is supposed to help countries integrate these practices into their health systems.\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0013.json.gz:30702","uncompressed_offset":261399576,"url":"alkhaleej365.com/lifestyle/11546295/%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B8%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84.html","warc_date":"2022-05-07T16:07:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cb9ef0c6-8b7e-40ec-a20a-a356d3083fe7>","warc_url":"https://alkhaleej365.com/lifestyle/11546295/%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B8%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84.html"},"created":"2022-05-07T16:21:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":{"id":"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638","text":"Govt to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities\n\nCentre to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities across country\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand\n\nThe Centre is working on documenting medicinal herbs and healers of the tribal communities across the country. A pilot from Uttarakhand has been completed, resulting in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants. The exercise, officials said, will be carried out in more states.\u00a0\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand. Apart from documenting the plant and healers, they also documented the Sanskrit names of these plants.\u00a0\n\nIn Kerala, the Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham was given the responsibility, All India Institute of Medical Studies Jodhpur in Rajasthan, Pravara Institute of Medical Sciences Ahmedabad for Maharashtra, and Patanjali carried it out in Uttarakhand.\u00a0\n\nWhile the others are carrying it out, Patanjali\u2019s series of seven tomes are ready. In the hill state three districts were chosen, which included Pithoragarh and Udham Singh Nagar, all phytodiversity was documented by a team of over 50-50 people over a period of two years.\u00a0\n\nWhen asked about the Sanskrit nomenclature, the official said that it was a way of directing attention to the functionality of the plant.\u00a0\n\n\u201cThe National Medicinal Plant Board says there are over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented. But in three districts alone, we found 900 plants,\u201d a senior official of the ministry said. \u201cTribal medicine holds considerable interest among researchers.\u201d\n\nChemical analysis of all these plants was carried out, to find the active ingredient in the plant, with the help of an HPLC machine, officials said. Apart from that, samples of these were preserved, along with data on their therapeutic use. The official said that permissions from the biodiversity board were also taken.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nIn addition to that, the Hyderabad-based National Institute of Pharmaceutical Education and Research (NIPER) carried out a similar exercise in their areas where they found three medicinal plants, which when combined can be a cure for malaria. A similar exercise was carried out by the same team in the Rashtrapati Bhawan as well.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nHealers in tribal communities in the areas that use these plants were also documented, along with data of their areas of expertise. In all, 750 healers were documented.\u00a0\n\nOfficials said that after the successful pilot, the ministry has sent it to the AYUSH ministry, urging them to take it further across the country using SC/ST components from their funds. Officials also said that details of these plants will be put up online.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\nCheck out all newsletters\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\n\u00a0","url":"https://www.deccanherald.com/national/centre-to-document-medicinal-herbs-of-tribal-communities-across-country-1112440.html"},"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701":{"id":"cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83_536799701","text":"India \u2019 s medical facilities speed up the development of intelligent system to help rural remote consultation\nAuthor \uff1a 01 Source of Medical Clinic\nPublished: Updated:\nFor many Hong Kong people, India may look like a relatively backward and populous country, with a population of 1.4 billion, and it is hard to imagine how the local medical system can accommodate such a large population.\nThe author went to the local area to participate in the large-scale international engineering alliance conference, found that the local medical facilities are developing rapidly, the number of hospital beds in the country has increased by 40% in the past 10 years, and some large hospitals have added intelligent equipment to assist in the diagnosis and daily operation of the hospital.\nIf you have the ability to increase investment in the future, coupled with the development of local information technology, and gradually trend towards intelligent development, I believe that it is not difficult to see the emergence of comprehensive intelligent hospitals, so that patient services are more efficient and no longer subject to geographical restrictions.\nAuthor: Yuan Pak Leung, Former President of the Institution of Senior Engineers and Engineers\nI am the Vice-Chairman of the International Engineering Technologists Agreement and the Chairman of the British delegation chaired a review meeting of the agreement in New Delhi, India.\nAs the Vice President of the International Engineering Technologists Agreement (IETTA), I went to New Delhi, India, to attend this year \u2019 s IETTA conference hosted by my host, and also chaired the annual meeting held in India in the same capacity as the chairman of the Seoul Accord.\nOver the course of more than 10 days, I have met many people in the engineering industry from all over India, some from the medical industry, so I have the opportunity to learn more about the development of local hospital facilities.\nAccording to the local industry, the number of hospitals and beds in India has increased rapidly over the past decade. For example, from 2010 to 2020, the total number of beds in the country has increased from about 1.2 million to more than 1.7 million, an increase of more than 40%.\nAs of 2023, the market share of hospital spending across India, including public and private hospitals, is in the hundreds of billions of dollars. However, the number of beds per 1,000 people is still relatively low globally.\nOn both sides of a highway in New Delhi, I saw 20 medical statues placed by Yatharth Hospital to thank and honor the work of \u201canti-virus warriors \u201d during the COVID-19 pandemic.\nHowever, unlike in Hong Kong, Indian hospitals are dominated by private hospitals, accounting for 70% of the total number of beds.\nSome people in the local industry admit that this reflects that the investment in public health care is not enough at present, but it is understood that the local public sector is trying to catch up with the demand, but the demand is too large and it is difficult to meet 100%.\nTherefore, ensuring equitable access to quality health care is a challenge for local authorities, especially in remote areas such as mountains or rural areas.\nIt is said that there is a medical culture in India with a long history in Asia that can alleviate some of the medical needs of the general population.\nIt is a system of traditional medicine called Ayurveda, which is called Ayurveda. It is composed of two Sanskrit words, ayur refers to life and veda means knowledge.\nTogether, they mean \u201cknowledge of life \u201d and are considered to be one of the most ancient forms of holistic natural medicine in the world, originating from ancient India, for thousands of years. Ayurveda and Chinese medicine have many things in common, especially the focus of both is on the patient, not on the disease.\nIts core concept is to maintain their own spiritual balance and harmony, will make people physically healthy, the theory that life should avoid excessive hyperactivity, because it will lead to too much stomach acid, so that people become irritable, anxiety and other problems.\nExcessive hyperactivity can also affect the joints, mucous membranes, and fats that protect our body structure, leading to obesity and depression, and people \u2019 s physical and mental activities, including breathing, blood circulation, and nervous system if over-regulation, can bring anxiety, constipation, joint pain and so on.\nAyurveda emphasizes the uniqueness of the individual and regulates and prevents diseases according to the physical and psychological characteristics of the individual.\nIn general, Ayurveda believes that a variety of herbs, spices, minerals, etc. can be used to treat diseases, and diet therapy is used to adjust the diet according to the body, while lifestyle adjustments include yoga, meditation and massage.\nIn addition to its unique medical concept, India \u2019 s relatively advanced information technology development, I believe it can also be an opportunity to make up for the lack of medical services.\nIn fact, many local hospitals have begun to add intelligent systems, such as electronic medical record system, remote medical system and the application of digital technology, which improve the ability of doctors to treat patients, and increase the ability of remote consultation, so that patients in remote rural areas can benefit.\nIn order to increase the efficiency of consultation and make more accurate diagnosis, local doctors will also use wearable devices to understand the patient \u2019 s physical condition, and even use intelligent systems to help make clinical decisions.\nThe conference hotel I stayed at offers authentic Indian Ayurveda healing massages, including the Ayurveda oil drip, which is said to be effective in helping to relieve stress.\nThe author believes that Hong Kong and India have very different cultural backgrounds, but they are also working hard to promote the development of intelligent hospitals.\nHowever, some local technology industry people pointed out that, regardless of whether the two places or other regions should pay more attention to the convenience and efficiency of intelligent systems, there are opportunities for network security risks or personal data leakage, so there are challenges when using different smart technologies.\nWith the rapid development of the local medical system with advanced technology, I believe that if the world can introduce more intelligent elements in its medical system, and continue to invest in it, coupled with the policy support of government departments, we can cite each other, exchange learning and practice verification, I believe that it is not difficult to build a fully intelligent hospital in the future, and hope that this efficient service model can meet the increasing medical demand of society.\n\"01 Medical Clinic\" cooperates with senior engineer Yuan Pak Leung to launch a column \"Source Road Has You\" every Monday to share the big and small things of engineering and medical care.\nYuan Pak Leung has always been committed to promoting the professional development of the engineering profession and is the former President of the Hong Kong Institution of Engineers.\nThe decades of professional journey are worth remembering, and I am convinced that the latter may understand the key points of the engineering profession.\nIf you have the source, let everyone experience it together.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0018.json.gz:40633","uncompressed_offset":536799701,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/1040317/%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E9%86%AB%E7%99%82%E8%A8%AD%E6%96%BD%E7%99%BC%E5%B1%95%E6%8F%90%E9%80%9F-%E6%99%BA%E8%83%BD%E5%8C%96%E7%B3%BB%E7%B5%B1%E5%8A%A9%E9%84%89%E9%83%8A%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%95%8F%E8%A8%BA","warc_date":"2024-07-21T23:40:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cb0b3c11-59e5-4764-a752-871d802b2a83>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/1040317/%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E9%86%AB%E7%99%82%E8%A8%AD%E6%96%BD%E7%99%BC%E5%B1%95%E6%8F%90%E9%80%9F-%E6%99%BA%E8%83%BD%E5%8C%96%E7%B3%BB%E7%B5%B1%E5%8A%A9%E9%84%89%E9%83%8A%E9%81%A0%E7%A8%8B%E5%95%8F%E8%A8%BA"},"created":"2024-07-22T00:45:20.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076":{"id":"ce13ec75-5d14-4993-a8f7-c31c1539b04b_1051680076","text":"Tuesday 10 August 2021 1:10 pm\n\nLong Covid cure? Researchers to trial traditional Indian herb treatment\n\nThe London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine will work with the All India Institute of Ayurveda to determine whether a traditional Indian herb can help people recover from long Covid.\n\nAshwagandha, commonly known as Indian winter cherry, is traditionally used in the Indian Ayurvedic system of medicine to boost energy, reduce stress and strengthen the immune system.\n\nExperts said recent trials had proven the herb\u2019s efficacy in reducing anxiety, stress, improving muscle strength and reducing fatigue symptoms in patients with chronic diseases.\n\nLong Covid patients can suffer from cognitive dysfunction, poor mental health, extreme fatigue and muscle weakness.\n\nIt is estimated these symptoms affect 10 to 20 per cent of Covid survivors and can last for one to three months or longer in many cases.\n\nThe study, funded by the Ministry of Ayush of the Government of India, will include a double-blind clinical trial involving 2,000 people living in the UK with long Covid.\n\nHalf of the trial participants will take 500mg Ashwagandha tablets twice a day for three months, while the other half will be given a placebo.\n\nResearchers will randomly select participants to have a monthly follow-up of self-reported quality of life, impairment to activities of daily living, mental and physical health symptoms, supplement use and adverse events.\n\nThe study is expected to last for over a year.\n\n\u201cAshwagandha has been shown to reduce symptoms of other conditions that are similar to those of long Covid, so we are hopeful that it will be an effective way to combat the condition,\u201d said Sanjay Kinra, professor in clinical epidemiology at the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine.\n\nThe research is also supported by the UK\u2019s All-Party Parliamentary Group on Indian Traditional Sciences and the Traditional Complementary and Integrative Medicine Unit at the World Health Organisation (WHO).\n\nResearch is the only way to ensure appropriate integration of traditional medicine knowledge into mainstream medical practice,\u201d said technical officer at WHO Geneva, Geetha Krishnan, who helped to facilitate the research project.\n\nShare","url":"https://www.cityam.com/long-covid-cure-researchers-to-trial-traditional-indian-herb-treatment/"},"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395":{"id":"12285aa1-5cd6-475f-82fe-271921520848_381225395","text":"News\nNews\n\nM&A\n\nFeature\nFeature\n\nMedical Specialties\nMedical Specialties\n\nData & Analytics\nData & Analytics\n\nBrand Solutions\nBrand Solutions\n\nView Site\n\nG20 science advisors to discuss pre-competitive collaboration, traditional knowledge\n\nOnce it reaches a certain level of maturity, of course different countries will have their take. But pre-competitive R&D (research and development) space is what we think should be something where we should work:\n\nNew Delhi: In a bid to bolster the fight against future pandemics, India's top scientific advisor Prof Ajay Kumar Sood has urged G20 countries to collaborate in developing vaccine platforms by cooperating with each other in the pre-competitive research and development phase.\n\nIn a video interview Sood, who will chair the Chief Scientific Advisors' Roundtable (CSAR) of G20 countries next week, said India will also present its traditional systems of medicine and seek to harness the knowledge of indigenous communities of different countries.\n\nMaking a strong pitch for collaboration among G20 nations in drug development, Sood, the principal scientific advisor to the government, said there is enormous scope for cooperation in the pre-competitive research and development space.\n\n\"Once it reaches a certain level of maturity, of course different countries will have their take. But pre-competitive R&D (research and development) space is what we think should be something where we should work,\" he said.\n\nSood identified emerging technologies for environmental surveillance as another area for cooperation.\n\n\"This is something which has to be done by all countries. A lot of it is happening but there are many other countries which will need a helping hand. So, we should be ready to take everyone along,\" he said.\n\nPre-competitive collaboration involves two or more companies operating within the same industry coming together to address a shared problem or pain point that doesn't impact direct business competition or contribute to unfair advantage.\n\n\"When there is a pandemic, you cannot live in isolation. We have seen it in COVID, all countries will have to fight it together and it has to be eradicated or controlled at all places. If it does not, then it will linger on and that is what you are seeing for COVID,\" Sood said.\n\nHe said the CSAR meeting in Uttarakhand's Ramnagar from March 28-30 will also focus on harnessing the benefits of traditional knowledge in healthcare.\n\n\"Traditional medicine has a very important role to play but it should be put in scientific context. All that work has to be done. When you have traditional medicines, how can we put it on a platform where it meets the acceptance of science,\" he said.\n\nSood said India has a very rich tradition of Ayurveda, Siddha and Unani and all of them have a role to play. It could be to build up immunity or strength or to address the symptoms of a disease, adding \" whatever you think, it is possible\".\n\n\"We should not try to limit ourselves to only what we call modern medicine,\" he said, making a strong pitch for diversity in various systems of medicine.\n\nSood also talked about harnessing the knowledge repositories of indigenous communities in G20 countries for the benefit of humankind.\n\n\"These are very, very old traditions. The goal should be, what we call traditional knowledge, it is really tested over centuries. It is very important that we take this traditional knowledge along with the other streams,\" Sood said.\n\nSood said the Ayush ministry is working on scientific validation of traditional systems of medicine.\n\n\"The Ayush ministry is doing that. This word was coined a few years back ayurvedic biology to address the issue of scientific validity. I am sure that in other countries there are parallel efforts. Because these tribal, traditional things are also very important and we need to learn from them,\" Sood said.\n\nThe three-day meeting in Ramnagar will focus on four broad themes Opportunities in One Health for better disease control and pandemic preparedness; Synergising global efforts to expand the access to scholarly scientific knowledge; Diversity, equity, inclusion and accessibility in science and technology (S&T); and an Institutional mechanism for inclusive, continuous and action-oriented global S&T policy dialogue.\n\nGet latest Industry insights and analysis in your inbox\n\nLearn from updates & industry leaders Daily.\n\nGreat, We will keep you updated\n\nDownload our App for Realtime updates\n\nDownload App\n\nFollow and connect with us on , Facebook, Linkedin, Youtube\nPartners:","url":"https://health.economictimes.indiatimes.com/amp/news/industry/g20-science-advisors-to-discuss-pre-competitive-collaboration-traditional-knowledge/98989510"},"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869":{"id":"98cb1295-a33e-4e2b-8dc2-ad49132f6a98_528404869","text":"Telangana\n\nCentre in favour of locating global centre for traditional medicine in Hyderabad\n\nThe city is likely to have another jewel in its crown if the Central Government\u2019s latest request relating to the setting up of a global centre for traditional medicine proposed by the World Health Organisation (WHO) is any indication.\n\nUnion Minister for Tourism, Culture and Development of North East Region G. Kishan Reddy has requested the State Government to identify a suitable parcel of land for setting up the institute in the city. In a letter addressed to Chief Minister K. Chandrasekhar Rao, the Union Minister asked him to resolve the issues pertaining to identification of land and spot a parcel of land.\n\nHe said that the country is known for its traditional medicines, including Ayurveda, yoga, Unani, naturopathy, Sowa-Ripa and Siddha to name a few, which are recognised worldwide. The COVID pandemic had further highlighted the benefits of traditional medicine and demonstrated the power of Ayurveda to the world.\n\n\u201cIndia is regarded as the pharmacy of the world and focus on traditional medicine aligns with Prime Minister Narendra Modi\u2019s emphasis on prevention of diseases and wellness,\u201d he said. He recalled that the WHO director general had announced intentions of setting up a global centre for traditional medicine in India on the occasion of World Ayurveda Day in November 2020.\n\nThe Union AYUSH Ministry was considering setting up of the centre in Hyderabad as traditional scientific research institutions like CCMB, CSIR, NIN, IICT, and FDTRC would further complement the approach towards an integrated holistic medicine. The Government of Telangana had been communicated for their inputs on the extent of support for setting up of the global centre, he said, adding that the global centre would benefit the city and the State.\n\n\nOur code of editorial values\n\nPrintable version | Feb 18, 2022 8:35:17 pm | https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/telangana/centre-in-favour-of-locating-global-centre-for-traditional-medicine-in-hyderabad/article65062674.ece","url":"https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/telangana/centre-in-favour-of-locating-global-centre-for-traditional-medicine-in-hyderabad/article65062674.ece"}}}
