-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400":1.0},"text":"The 2020 incident was reportedly linked to the worldwide protests following the death of George Floyd, with some individuals claiming that the fairy tale had racist elements."},{"citations":{"f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400":1.0},"text":"However, scholars of Hans Christian Andersen's work have disputed this claim, stating that they were not aware of any racist elements in the fairy tale."},{"citations":{"da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417_983057725":1.0},"text":"The repeated incidents of vandalism and damage to the Little Mermaid statue have raised questions about the motivations and intentions behind these acts."},{"citations":{"f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400":1.0},"text":"While some incidents may be attributed to random acts of vandalism, others appear to be linked to specific causes or protests, such as the 2017 incident against whale hunting."},{"citations":{"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268":1.0},"text":"The fact that the statue has been targeted multiple times over the years suggests that it has become a symbol of sorts, with different individuals and groups seeking to use it to make a statement or express their opinions."},{"citations":{"da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417_983057725":1.0},"text":"Overall, the Little Mermaid statue in Copenhagen has been subjected to a range of intentional damages and vandalism, reflecting a complex and multifaceted set of motivations and intentions."},{"citations":{"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268":1.0},"text":"The incidents of damage and vandalism have been well-documented, with various sources reporting on the different cases over the years."},{"citations":{"f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400":1.0},"text":"The statue's history of vandalism has also been noted by news agencies, with AFP reporting on the multiple incidents of damage and vandalism."},{"citations":{"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the Little Mermaid statue in Copenhagen has been a target of intentional damage and vandalism multiple times since its installation, with a range of incidents occurring over the years, including decapitation, explosions, and graffiti."}],"references":["da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417_983057725","4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268","f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400"],"documents":{"da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417_983057725":{"id":"da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417_983057725","text":"Danish little mermaid like cornerstone painted Russian flag tricolor\nA statue of the Little Mermaid, one of the most iconic tourist attractions in the Danish capital Copenhagen, was deliberately vandalized last night, and the cornerstone below the statue was painted with the white, blue and red colors of the Russian flag.\nAdvertisement\nThe Little Mermaid comes from the famous fairy tale of Danish writer Hans Christian Andersen, where the stone beneath the bronze statue is painted in three colors of the Russian flag.\nCopenhagen police told Agence France-Presse that since they arrived this morning, \"a case of vandalism has been filed\" and \"local investigations have been launched to trace traces\".\nIt is clear that this means supporting Moscow \u2019 s position in the Ukraine war.\nSome tourists, puzzled by this, took pictures of the damaged statue this morning.\nThe 175-kilogram Little Mermaid is a work by sculptor Edvard Eriksen, inspired by the Danish poet and writer Hans Christian Andersen \u2019 s 1837 fairy tale of the same name.\nThe statue, which sits next to a relatively secluded waterfront walkway, has been vandalized several times over the years, including two burglaries of its head in 1964 and 1998, and a severed arm in 1984. In 2003, the statue was blown loose with explosives and fell into the bay.\nIt has also been graffitied and painted several times, most recently in 2020 with the words \u201cracist fish. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0006.json.gz:19510","uncompressed_offset":983057725,"url":"www.rfi.fr/cn/%E5%9B%BD%E9%99%85%E6%8A%A5%E9%81%93/20230302-%E4%B8%B9%E9%BA%A6%E5%B0%8F%E7%BE%8E%E4%BA%BA%E9%B1%BC%E5%83%8F%E5%9F%BA%E7%9F%B3%E9%81%AD%E6%BC%86%E4%BF%84%E7%BD%97%E6%96%AF%E5%9B%BD%E6%97%97%E4%B8%89%E8%89%B2","warc_date":"2023-03-02T15:16:25.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:da2bd34b-42c4-4350-a229-2589da378417>","warc_url":"https://www.rfi.fr/cn/%E5%9B%BD%E9%99%85%E6%8A%A5%E9%81%93/20230302-%E4%B8%B9%E9%BA%A6%E5%B0%8F%E7%BE%8E%E4%BA%BA%E9%B1%BC%E5%83%8F%E5%9F%BA%E7%9F%B3%E9%81%AD%E6%BC%86%E4%BF%84%E7%BD%97%E6%96%AF%E5%9B%BD%E6%97%97%E4%B8%89%E8%89%B2"},"created":"2023-03-02T15:49:09.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400":{"id":"f535b8c5-32d1-4b5e-8c17-6635fe71fd07_946484400","text":"Russian Flag Painted on Copenhagen's Most Famous Landmark\n\nIt's the latest in a long line of attacks on Little Mermaid statue\nBy Rob Quinn, \u00a0Newser Staff\nPosted Mar 2, 2023 10:15 AM CST\n\nThe Little Mermaid statue in Copenhagen, one of Denmark's most famous landmarks, has been vandalized yet again, this time with the Russian flag. Authorities said Thursday that the white, blue, and red stripes of the Russian flag were painted on the stone the statue sits on, Reuters reports. Police said the vandalism was discovered early Thursday. \"We are of course launching an investigation to find out who did it and when and how it happened,\" a police spokesman said, per Jyllands-Posten.\n\nDenmark, like other European nations, has strongly criticized Russia's war against Ukraine. The small statue, a tribute to the Hans Christian Andersen fairy tale, sits off a waterfront promenade in the Danish capital. It has been vandalized many times since it was installed 110 years ago, AFP reports. It has been decapitated twice and was knocked off its base with explosives in 2003. In 2017, it was doused in red paint in a protest against whale hunting. In 2020, during worldwide protests after the death of George Floyd, the words \"racist fish\" were painted on the base, though Andersen scholars said they weren't aware of any racist elements in the fairy tale. (Read more The Little Mermaid stories.)\n\nWe use cookies. By Clicking \"OK\" or any content on this site, you agree to allow cookies to be placed. Read more in our privacy policy.\nGet the news faster.\nTap to install our app.\nX\nInstall the Newser News app\nin two easy steps:\n1. Tap in your navigation bar.\n2. Tap to Add to Home Screen.\n\nX","url":"https://www.newser.com/story/332238/little-mermaid-statue-vandalized-with-russian-flag.html"},"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268":{"id":"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268","text":"Unknown people draw Russian flag on a statue of a mermaid in Copenhagen\nCOPENHAGEN (AFP) - The iconic Little Mermaid statue in the Danish capital Copenhagen was vandalized on Wednesday night as unidentified people painted the Russian flag on its base.\nAnnouncement\nAn AFP correspondent reported that the Russian flag was painted under unknown circumstances on the stone above which a statue of the Little Mermaid, inspired by the heroine of one of the stories of the writer Hans Christian Andersen, was installed.\nDanish police said they were launching an investigation into the incident, without giving any indication of the source of the move, which shows clear support for Russia amid the ongoing war in Ukraine.\nA Copenhagen police spokesman told AFP: \"We are investigating the area in order to find any evidence.\"\nA small number of tourists in the area took pictures of the statue in the port of Copenhagen, which was vandalized on Thursday morning.\nThe Little Mermaid statue on a largely unfrequented promenade has been targeted several times since it was installed in 1913.\nIn 1964, the head of the nymph was stolen for the first time without being recovered.\nIn 1998, a group of vandals cut off the head of the statue again, but it was later restored.\nThis monument was exposed to the explosion in 2003.\nThe statue, created by Danish sculptor Edvard Eriksen, has also been targeted several times with graffiti or graffiti, most recently in 2020 with the inscription \u201cracist fish \u201d.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0006.json.gz:38440","uncompressed_offset":592630268,"url":"www.france24.com/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9/20230302-%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%B1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%86","warc_date":"2023-03-03T12:29:55.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4>","warc_url":"https://www.france24.com/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9/20230302-%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%B1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%86"},"created":"2023-03-03T12:51:55.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1047","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1047","narrative_id":"1047"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"Ocean acidification is a pressing issue that affects various aspects of marine life, including cephalopods and other species."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The increase in carbon dioxide levels in the air is harming marine life, particularly those with shells, such as oysters, clams, crabs, and lobsters, by turning the water acidic."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"A team of marine scientists found that the pH level of water in the Sunderbans estuary has dropped from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019, which is alarming for marine animals."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Ocean acidification occurs when the water's pH levels are lowered as a result of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, making it difficult for shellfish to build their shells."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The decline in pH level can affect the shell size and slow down the growth of reefs, as well as impact the growth and abundance of local shrimp."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Cephalopods, such as corals, use calcium carbonate to build their shells, and as the ocean acidifies, it becomes more difficult for them to create these shells."},{"citations":{"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":1.0},"text":"The impact of ocean acidification is not limited to coral reefs, but also affects other marine species, including zooplankton, which are a critical component of the Arctic food web."},{"citations":{"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":1.0},"text":"The absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere can increase the acidity of seawater, leading to various impacts on marine ecosystems, including changes in species distribution and disruptions to food webs."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Overall, ocean acidification has far-reaching consequences for marine life, and it is essential to take collective action to protect the oceans and mitigate the effects of climate change."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"Ocean acidification is a pressing issue that affects various aspects of marine life, including cephalopods and other species."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The increase in carbon dioxide levels in the air is harming marine life, particularly those with shells, such as oysters, clams, crabs, and lobsters, by turning the water acidic."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"A team of marine scientists found that the pH level of water in the Sunderbans estuary has dropped from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019, which is alarming for marine animals."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Ocean acidification occurs when the water's pH levels are lowered as a result of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, making it difficult for shellfish to build their shells."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The decline in pH level can affect the shell size and slow down the growth of reefs, as well as impact the growth and abundance of local shrimp."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Cephalopods, such as corals, use calcium carbonate to build their shells, and as the ocean acidifies, it becomes more difficult for them to create these shells."},{"citations":{"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":1.0},"text":"The impact of ocean acidification is not limited to coral reefs, but also affects other marine species, including zooplankton, which are a critical component of the Arctic food web."},{"citations":{"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":1.0},"text":"The absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere can increase the acidity of seawater, leading to various impacts on marine ecosystems, including changes in species distribution and disruptions to food webs."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Overall, ocean acidification has far-reaching consequences for marine life, and it is essential to take collective action to protect the oceans and mitigate the effects of climate change."}],"references":["d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362","4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678","e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048"],"documents":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":{"id":"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678","text":"Credits: Maxpixel\u00a0\n\nThe Logical Indian Crew\n\nRise In CO2 Levels In Air Is Wounding Sundarbans' Marine Life: Scientists \u200b\n\nThis has been analysed by a team of marine scientists working in the Sunderbans, who said ocean acidification is a part of global warming and climate change. The experts found the pH level of water dropping from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019.\n\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n\nA continuous increase in the carbon dioxide (CO2) levels in the air is harming the marine life of the Sunderbans estuary in West Bengal by turning it acidic. Animals, especially with shells such as oysters, clams, crabs, and lobsters, are prone to danger.\n\nThis has been analysed by a team of marine scientists working in the Sunderbans, who said ocean acidification is a part of global warming and climate change, Hindustan Times reported. The experts found the pH level of water dropping from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019.\n\nSpeaking to the media, Abhijit Mitra, former head of the marine science department (Calcutta University), informed that the western part of Sunderban, close to the urban area, had observed a massive drop in its pH level, while the central part is declining slowly.\n\nMitra said the decline affects the population of shelled organisms and their shell size as well, which has become thinner and smaller. Fishermen said that several fish and other animals have gotten smaller, and they hardly get big ones.\n\nTheir population has also fallen by 35-40 per cent in the western area.\n\n\"The size of Saccostrea cucullata, a species of edible oyster around Kakdwip and Namkhana fishing harbour, has dropped by over 40 per cent. In the central Sunderbans, the size of the species has dropped by around 20 percent,\" the media quoted him as saying.\n\nAsst. Professor of Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Punyasloke Bhadury, explained that water contains calcium and carbonate ions, which the shelled animals need to develop and corals to build the reef. But the acidity reduces these components in the water, affecting the shell size and slowing down the growth of reefs.\n\nExperts said the decline in the pH level is alarming. Just as the slightest drop in the pH level of a human body (pH 7.35 to 7.45) can make them sick, the same takes a heavy toll on marine animals.\n\nThe scientists said the decline is not just in Sunderbans but other estuaries as well.\n\nAlso Read: Rajasthan Bride Asks Father To Build Girls Hostel With Money Set Aside For Marriage\n\nContributors Suggest Correction\nWriter : Devyani Madaik\n,\nEditor : Palak Agrawal\n,\nCreatives : Devyani Madaik\n\nMust Reads","url":"https://thelogicalindian.com/environment/rise-in-co2-levels-in-air-is-wounding-sundarbans-marine-life-scientists-32217"},"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":{"id":"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048","text":"The Arctic region is currently undergoing rapid and significant changes, with acidification and warming occurring at alarming rates.\nThese shifts raise concerns about the resilience of marine communities in the face of such environmental shifts.\nMarine zooplankton, especially copepods, play a crucial role in the Arctic food web.\nHowever, differences in environmental conditions can disrupt zooplankton populations, leading to adverse consequences for the entire ecosystem.\nRecent research has focused on understanding the extent to which copepods in early life are exposed to environmental stressors, as they represent a critical bottleneck in the copepods life cycle.\nA study by Espinel Velasco et al.\n(2023) Explore the responses of 4-day-old Kalanos Hyperborius Lenobli to acidification (pH 7.5 and 8.1) and warming (0 and 3 \u00b0 C), both individually and collectively.\nThe study revealed that the larvae 'breathing rates increased significantly when exposed to a combination of acidification and warming.\nSurprisingly, exposure to these stressors individually did not produce the same effect.\nSurprisingly, the researchers did not find any noticeable differences in fat content and fatty acid composition in the larvae across various experimental treatments.\nWax esters, which make up about 75% of the fat reserve, and high amounts of long-chain fatty acids 20: 1 and 22: 1, necessary for copepods to reproduce, have been detected in all treatments.\nBy highlighting the sensitivity of larvae to the combined effects of acidification and warming, this study aligns with a growing body of evidence from relevant research.\nIt highlights the potential impacts of global change on Arctic copepod populations and stresses the importance of understanding early life stage responses to environmental stressors.\nQuestions and Answers:\nQ: What are zooplankton?\nA: Zooplankton refers to small, often microscopic, organisms that drift into the ocean or other bodies of water and serve as one of the main sources of food for many marine species.\nQ: What is the role of copepods in the Arctic food web?\nA: Copepods, especially calanotic copepods such as Calanus Hyperboreus, are a critical component of the Arctic food web.\nThey serve as a vital link between primary producers (such as phytoplankton) and higher trophic levels, serving as a food source for various marine species.\nQ: What is acidification?\nA: Acidification refers to the process of increasing acidity (lowering pH) in seawater due to the absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.\nThis occurs as a result of human activities, such as the burning of fossil fuels.\nQ: How does global warming affect marine ecosystems?\nA: Ocean warming can have various impacts on marine ecosystems, including changes in species distribution, changing reproductive cycles, and potential disruptions to the delicate balance of food webs.\nSource: Frontiers in Marine Science, DOI: 10.3389 / fmars.2023.1240673","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0031.json.gz:33636","uncompressed_offset":968649048,"url":"citylife.capetown/ar/science/interactive-effects-of-ocean-acidification-and-temperature-on-oxygen-uptake-rates-in-calanus-hyperboreus-nauplii/407473/","warc_date":"2023-10-31T00:03:23.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b>","warc_url":"https://citylife.capetown/ar/science/interactive-effects-of-ocean-acidification-and-temperature-on-oxygen-uptake-rates-in-calanus-hyperboreus-nauplii/407473/"},"created":"2023-10-31T01:21:39.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":{"id":"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362","text":"How climate change and warming waters are affecting the health of the oceans\n\n(NEW YORK) \u2014 Oceans do so much to sustain life on Earth, including bearing the brunt of global temperatures that have been steadily warming for decades.\n\nAn IPCC special report published in 2019 found that oceans \u2014 which make up more than 70% of the world\u2019s surface \u2014 have absorbed between 20% and 30% of human-made carbon dioxide emissions since the 1980s. They\u2019re also responsible for absorbing more than 93% of the \u201ccombined heat stored by warmed air, sea, and land, and melted ice\u201d since the 1970s, according to the Fifth Assessment report published in 2013 by the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.\n\nThe tipping point is near, experts told ABC News. But there are collective actions to take that could revitalize oceans to a healthier state \u2014 the theme of the United Nations World Oceans Day 2022.\n\n\u201cWe really see oceans as the biggest ally in the climate change crisis,\u201d Lea d\u2019Auriol, founder of nonprofit Oceanic Global, told ABC News.\n\nThis is how climate change is affecting the health of the world\u2019s oceans:\n\nSpecies are faced with adapting or becoming extinct\n\nCurrently, the oceans \u201care in a state of complete imbalance\u201d that has nearly doubled since the 1990s, d\u2019Auriol said. Look no further than the fishermen, who supply sustenance to more than three billion people who rely on seafood as their main source of protein, as witnesses that climate change is already here, d\u2019Auriol, said.\n\n\u201cIf you wanted to ask someone if climate change is really happening, probably the most surest answer you\u2019d get from anyone aside from a scientist is a fisherman,\u201d Arlo Hemphill, senior oceans campaigner for Greenpeace USA, told ABC News. \u201cBecause fishermen are seeing these things happen in real time.\u201d\n\nOne of the changes long-time fisherman are witnessing is the presence of new species venturing north as the area with their preferred water temperature expands.\n\nMarine organisms maintain the same temperature as the surrounding water, so that when temperature increases, so does the temperature of the organism, Martin Grosell, professor of ichthyology and chair of the University of Miami\u2019s Department of Marine Biology and Ecology, told ABC News. As the temperature rises, the organisms require more energy to move and survive. But, conversely, the levels of oxygen in the water decrease as the temperature warms, forcing the species to move, Grosell said.\n\nThe migrations may seem innocuous, but they are disrupting ecosystems all over the world, such as the phenology, or timing, of when grey seals give birth, Hemphill said.\n\nConversely, species are continuing to die off due to repeated events of marine heatwaves, Anne Christianson, director of international climate policy for the Center for American Progress, a public policy research organization, told ABC News.\n\nCoral reefs are among the most threatened marine ecosystems in the world, scientists say. Coral bleaching, a process that occurs when water is too warm and the corals expel algae from their tissues, causing them to turn completely white, is happening at \u201calarming\u201d rates \u2014 increasing by a rate of 4% per year \u2014 along with an uptick in mortality events along entire regions, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nA study published in the National Academy of Sciences found that coral reefs could stop growing in 10 years unless greenhouse gases are significantly reduced and that, under a worst-case scenario, 94% of all reefs could erode by 2050.\n\nReefs are often the indicator of the health of an ecosystem, Brenda Ekwurzel, director of climate science for the Union of Concerned Scientists, told ABC News.\n\nMammals that rely on Arctic ice, such as polar bears and ringed seals, one of the polar bears\u2019 main food sources that live their lives almost entirely on the ice, are also at risk, Ekwurzel said.\n\nVegetation such as mangroves, seagrass plants and marshes, some of the largest carbon sinks on the planet, which absorb and store carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, are also at risk of extinction, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThe number of dead zones are increasing\n\nA dead zone, or the process of hypoxia, occurs when an algal bloom sucks up all the oxygen in an area, making it impossible for marine life to survive \u2014 essentially a biological desert, according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.\n\nA study published in 2008 in Science found that there were 400 dead zones around the world. By 2019, the number of dead zones had increased to about 900, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThe dead zones often occur in regions with rampant nutrient runoff, such as at the base of the Mississippi River, where it empties into the Gulf of Mexico, Hemphill said.\n\nSea level rise will change coastal communities\n\nThe biggest contributor to sea level rise is the melting ice in the Arctic, which is heating up twice as fast as the rest of the world, according to the 2021 Arctic Report Card by NOAA. Increases in sea level rise of 6 inches to a foot since the Industrial Revolution may seem like small increments, but crucial infrastructure near oceans was not built to withstand the added inches of water, experts say.\n\nMillions of people living in coastlines around the world, including those in mega cities such as New York, Los Angeles and San Francisco, will be displaced by the rise in sea levels, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nCarbon dioxide emissions sparks ocean acidification\n\nOcean acidification, which occurs when water\u2019s pH levels are lowered as a result of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, is not directly caused by warming temperatures but rather by excess carbon dioxide emissions, Hemphill said.\n\n\u201cThe alarming thing about it is that shellfish everything from from microscopic plankton, to clams and crabs and coral reefs themselves use calcium carbonate to build their shells,\u201d he said. \u201cAnd as the ocean acidifies, it becomes more difficult to create the shells.\u201d\n\nOcean acidification, rather than coral bleaching, will likely be the culprit behind the demise of coral reefs, Ekwurzel said.\n\nCollective actions are necessary to protect the oceans\n\nIn line with the 2022 theme for World Oceans Day, \u201cRevitalization: Collective Action for the Ocean,\u201d scientists and conservationists are highlighting the need for individuals, communities, nonprofits, the private sector and governments to come together to create solutions, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThis includes ensuring the health of marine protected areas by eliminating housing, fishing zones and shipping traffic in the vicinity, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nGovernments will need to create policies to protect both human life and the health of the ocean, Christianson said.\n\n\u201cThere isn\u2019t one silver bullet for solving this crisis in the ocean and on land,\u201d Christianson said.\n\nHowever, the ticking time bomb is the race to drastically reduce global greenhouse gas emissions within the next decade, the experts said.\n\n\u201cWe can\u2019t afford to delay those solutions any longer,\u201d Ekwurzel said.\n\nAlong the path to properly protecting and preserving oceans is ridding the narrative that oceans are a separate environmental issue from climate change and the conservation of biodiversity, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\n\u201cBecause we do live on a water planet, and it\u2019s responsible for sustaining all life on Earth,\u201d she said.\n\nCopyright (C) 2022, ABC Audio. All rights reserved.","url":"https://wfin.com/abc-world-news/how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans&utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans"}}}
