 can affect the entire food chain, from zooplankton to marine mammals, and can have significant consequences for the food web and carbon cycle."},{"citations":{"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":1.0},"text":"Zooplankton, such as copepods, are a critical component of the Arctic food web and serve as a vital link between primary producers and higher trophic levels."},{"citations":{"54053584-4dc9-40d0-bbea-8b47295e1d6f_116363246":1.0},"text":"The decrease in pteropod populations in the Antarctic Ocean, due to ocean acidification, could have significant consequences for the food web and carbon cycle."},{"citations":{"54053584-4dc9-40d0-bbea-8b47295e1d6f_116363246":1.0},"text":"Pteropods are small sea creatures, including shelled sea butterflies, which are important for the ocean environment, but not much is known about them due to their size and sensitivity to captivity."},{"citations":{"eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd_390178312":1.0},"text":"A study on the impact of ocean acidification on shrimp found that changes in the pH of water can negatively affect these organisms, especially in the early stages of their life."},{"citations":{"eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd_390178312":1.0},"text":"The Kuwait Institute for Scientific Research found that ocean acidification and ocean surface warming can affect the growth and abundance of local shrimp."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Ocean acidification is not directly caused by warming temperatures, but rather by excess carbon dioxide emissions, which can make it harder for some ocean creatures to build and keep their shells."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"The alarming thing about ocean acidification is that shellfish, everything from microscopic plankton to clams and crabs and coral reefs themselves, use calcium carbonate to build their shells, which becomes more difficult as the ocean acidifies."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"Collective actions are necessary to protect the oceans, and individuals, communities, nonprofits, and the private sector must work together to address the issue of ocean acidification."},{"citations":{},"text":"The impact of ocean acidification on marine life is a complex issue, and further research is needed to understand the exact effects on different species and ecosystems."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"However, it is clear that ocean acidification is a pressing concern that requires immediate attention and action to mitigate its effects on marine life."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The decline in pH level of the water, from 8.3 to 7.9, in the Sunderbans, is a significant decrease, and the fact that it has dropped by over 40 per cent in some areas, such as Kakdwip and Namkhana fishing harbour, is alarming."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"The size of the species has also dropped by around 20 percent in the central Sunderbans, highlighting the severe impact of ocean acidification on marine life."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, ocean acidification is a significant threat to marine life, affecting not only coral reefs but also other species, such as shellfish, cephalopods, and marine mammals."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"The impact of ocean acidification on marine life is far-reaching, and it is essential to address this issue through collective actions and further research to mitigate its effects."},{"citations":{"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":1.0},"text":"The fact that ocean acidification is not directly caused by warming temperatures, but rather by excess carbon dioxide emissions, highlights the need to reduce our carbon footprint to protec