tures, but rather by excess carbon dioxide emissions, highlights the need to reduce our carbon footprint to protect the oceans."},{"citations":{"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":1.0},"text":"Overall, the impact of ocean acidification on marine life is a complex issue that requires immediate attention and action to ensure the long-term health of our oceans."}],"references":["d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362","4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678","e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048","eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd_390178312","54053584-4dc9-40d0-bbea-8b47295e1d6f_116363246"],"documents":{"eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd_390178312":{"id":"eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd_390178312","text":"Home of the Day\nSend Save Print PDF\nIn cooperation with the Foundation for the Advancement of Science and the Atomic Energy Agency\n\u00ab Research \u00bb conducted a study on the impact of \u00ab acidification \u00bb on shrimp\nThe Kuwait Institute for Scientific Research (KISR), in cooperation with the Kuwait Foundation for the Advancement of Sciences (KFAS) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), completed a study project to investigate the impact of ocean acidification and ocean surface warming on the growth and abundance of local shrimp.\nIn turn, the head of the project, researcher Lamia Muslim at the Center for Environmental and Life Sciences Research at the Institute, said that there are many animals that contain in their skeleton or shell calcium carbonate, and changes in the pH of water can negatively affect these organisms, especially in the early stages of their life. The sea and some phytoplankton species, but that does not mean that this is a positive thing because the increased growth of these organisms can disrupt the food chain, biodiversity and ecosystem mechanisms and construction.\nShe added that the presence of large amounts of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere leads to the occurrence of global warming and the rise of the surface of the oceans by between one and three degrees Celsius, and the rise of the water level to an amount ranging from 0.18 to 0.79 meters, which in turn leads to acidification and warming of the surface of the oceans, and therefore to change the chemistry of the ocean and threaten marine ecosystems.\nShe pointed out that the shrimp mothers were collected from Kuwaiti territorial waters during the breeding season to obtain eggs and shrimp larvae in sufficient numbers to conduct experiments on all stages of shrimp age, as the study experiments were conducted in the laboratories of the Institute in a controlled system simulating the expected climate changes in the future.\nThe results of the study confirmed that the warming of the surface of the oceans could have a greater impact than ocean acidification on the early life stages of shrimp larvae, as shrimp larvae exposed to high temperatures showed accelerated growth rates to reach the sizes of older shrimp, but with lower survival rates, it is very likely that lower survival and growth rates under future climate scenarios may lead to the emergence of smaller shrimp larvae. These larvae will undergo multiple molting processes over their life cycle making them vulnerable; furthermore, the study results suggest additional effects of combined exposure to ocean surface warming and acidification on egg-hatching success, survival, and shrimp larval development.\nAl-Musallam said: \u201cThe study is fully consistent across the entire life cycle of the M Nair shrimp, where high mortality of larvae at low pH and high water temperature indicates a possible collapse of this species of crustacean under conditions of increased ocean acidification and future warming of the ocean surface, which also leads to a significant reduction in shrimp stocks in the Arabian Gulf due to overfishing or reduced larval growth due to climate change. \u201d\nFor his part, dr.\nDr. Saifuddin Iqbaluddin, from the Center for Environmental and Life Sciences Research, said experts regularly measure water temperature and pH levels and look at how marine life might respond to these changes in the coming decades.\nAdd a new comment\nThe comment received from the participant or reader is an expression of his own opinion and does not reflect the opinion of the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Nahar\nView comments","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0034.json.gz:1438","uncompressed_offset":390178312,"url":"www.annaharkw.com/annahar/Article.aspx?id=920092","warc_date":"2021-11-22T03:10:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:eabaa8bc-af88-4b73-a1b2-dec0f49336fd>","warc_url":"https://www.annaharkw.com/annahar/Article.aspx?id=920092"},"created":"2021-11-22T03:55:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678":{"id":"4be17bf1-5442-40ce-8ca3-0eee3640016c_480614678","text":"Credits: Maxpixel\u00a0\n\nThe Logical Indian Crew\n\nRise In CO2 Levels In Air Is Wounding Sundarbans' Marine Life: Scientists \u200b\n\nThis has been analysed by a team of marine scientists working in the Sunderbans, who said ocean acidification is a part of global warming and climate change. The experts found the pH level of water dropping from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019.\n\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n  \u2022 Whatsapp\n  \u2022 Telegram\n  \u2022 Linkedin\n  \u2022 Print\n  \u2022 koo\n\nA continuous increase in the carbon dioxide (CO2) levels in the air is harming the marine life of the Sunderbans estuary in West Bengal by turning it acidic. Animals, especially with shells such as oysters, clams, crabs, and lobsters, are prone to danger.\n\nThis has been analysed by a team of marine scientists working in the Sunderbans, who said ocean acidification is a part of global warming and climate change, Hindustan Times reported. The experts found the pH level of water dropping from around 8.3 in the early 1980s to approximately 7.9 in 2019.\n\nSpeaking to the media, Abhijit Mitra, former head of the marine science department (Calcutta University), informed that the western part of Sunderban, close to the urban area, had observed a massive drop in its pH level, while the central part is declining slowly.\n\nMitra said the decline affects the population of shelled organisms and their shell size as well, which has become thinner and smaller. Fishermen said that several fish and other animals have gotten smaller, and they hardly get big ones.\n\nTheir population has also fallen by 35-40 per cent in the western area.\n\n\"The size of Saccostrea cucullata, a species of edible oyster around Kakdwip and Namkhana fishing harbour, has dropped by over 40 per cent. In the central Sunderbans, the size of the species has dropped by around 20 percent,\" the media quoted him as saying.\n\nAsst. Professor of Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Punyasloke Bhadury, explained that water contains calcium and carbonate ions, which the shelled animals need to develop and corals to build the reef. But the acidity reduces these components in the water, affecting the shell size and slowing down the growth of reefs.\n\nExperts said the decline in the pH level is alarming. Just as the slightest drop in the pH level of a human body (pH 7.35 to 7.45) can make them sick, the same takes a heavy toll on marine animals.\n\nThe scientists said the decline is not just in Sunderbans but other estuaries as well.\n\nAlso Read: Rajasthan Bride Asks Father To Build Girls Hostel With Money Set Aside For Marriage\n\nContributors Suggest Correction\nWriter : Devyani Madaik\n,\nEditor : Palak Agrawal\n,\nCreatives : Devyani Madaik\n\nMust Reads","url":"https://thelogicalindian.com/environment/rise-in-co2-levels-in-air-is-wounding-sundarbans-marine-life-scientists-32217"},"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048":{"id":"e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b_968649048","text":"The Arctic region is currently undergoing rapid and significant changes, with acidification and warming occurring at alarming rates.\nThese shifts raise concerns about the resilience of marine communities in the face of such environmental shifts.\nMarine zooplankton, especially copepods, play a crucial role in the Arctic food web.\nHowever, differences in environmental conditions can disrupt zooplankton populations, leading to adverse consequences for the entire ecosystem.\nRecent research has focused on understanding the extent to which copepods in early life are exposed to environmental stressors, as they represent a critical bottleneck in the copepods life cycle.\nA study by Espinel Velasco et al.\n(2023) Explore the responses of 4-day-old Kalanos Hyperborius Lenobli to acidification (pH 7.5 and 8.1) and warming (0 and 3 \u00b0 C), both individually and collectively.\nThe study revealed that the larvae 'breathing rates increased significantly when exposed to a combination of acidification and warming.\nSurprisingly, exposure to these stressors individually did not produce the same effect.\nSurprisingly, the researchers did not find any noticeable differences in fat content and fatty acid composition in the larvae across various experimental treatments.\nWax esters, which make up about 75% of the fat reserve, and high amounts of long-chain fatty acids 20: 1 and 22: 1, necessary for copepods to reproduce, have been detected in all treatments.\nBy highlighting the sensitivity of larvae to the combined effects of acidification and warming, this study aligns with a growing body of evidence from relevant research.\nIt highlights the potential impacts of global change on Arctic copepod populations and stresses the importance of understanding early life stage responses to environmental stressors.\nQuestions and Answers:\nQ: What are zooplankton?\nA: Zooplankton refers to small, often microscopic, organisms that drift into the ocean or other bodies of water and serve as one of the main sources of food for many marine species.\nQ: What is the role of copepods in the Arctic food web?\nA: Copepods, especially calanotic copepods such as Calanus Hyperboreus, are a critical component of the Arctic food web.\nThey serve as a vital link between primary producers (such as phytoplankton) and higher trophic levels, serving as a food source for various marine species.\nQ: What is acidification?\nA: Acidification refers to the process of increasing acidity (lowering pH) in seawater due to the absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.\nThis occurs as a result of human activities, such as the burning of fossil fuels.\nQ: How does global warming affect marine ecosystems?\nA: Ocean warming can have various impacts on marine ecosystems, including changes in species distribution, changing reproductive cycles, and potential disruptions to the delicate balance of food webs.\nSource: Frontiers in Marine Science, DOI: 10.3389 / fmars.2023.1240673","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0031.json.gz:33636","uncompressed_offset":968649048,"url":"citylife.capetown/ar/science/interactive-effects-of-ocean-acidification-and-temperature-on-oxygen-uptake-rates-in-calanus-hyperboreus-nauplii/407473/","warc_date":"2023-10-31T00:03:23.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e35a74c7-1c1d-4f5d-b2ec-ccc9befc043b>","warc_url":"https://citylife.capetown/ar/science/interactive-effects-of-ocean-acidification-and-temperature-on-oxygen-uptake-rates-in-calanus-hyperboreus-nauplii/407473/"},"created":"2023-10-31T01:21:39.000Z","lang":"eng"},"54053584-4dc9-40d0-bbea-8b47295e1d6f_116363246":{"id":"54053584-4dc9-40d0-bbea-8b47295e1d6f_116363246","text":"Newswise \u2014 When carbon dioxide (CO2) enters the oceans, it can make the water more acidic, which is called ocean acidification. This can make it harder for some ocean creatures, like pteropods, to build and keep their shells. Pteropods are important for the ocean environment.\n\nPteropods are small sea creatures, including shelled sea butterflies. Not much is known about them because of their size, and they don't survive well in captivity. A team of marine scientists studied the life cycles, abundance, and seasonal changes of shelled sea butterflies in the north-east Scotia Sea, where climate change is happening quickly.\n\nDr Clara Manno, a researcher at the British Antarctic Survey and the corresponding author of the study published in Frontiers in Marine Science, said that the decrease in pteropod populations in the Antarctic Ocean could have significant consequences for the food web and carbon cycle. She also said that understanding the life cycle of this important organism could help to predict the impact of ocean acidification on the Antarctic ecosystem.\n\nPopulation stability essential for species survival\n\nTo study the life cycle, abundance, and seasonal variability of shelled sea butterflies in the north-east Scotia Sea, a team of marine scientists collected sea butterflies in a sediment trap, a sampling device that was anchored at a depth of 400 meters. Since observing the entire life cycle of sea butterflies in a laboratory setting is impossible, the researchers had to gather information about their spawning, growth rate, and population structure. They were able to reconstruct the sea butterflies' life cycle for a year using the samples from the sediment trap.\n\nThe scientists found that the two most commonly collected species, Limacina rangii and Limacina retroversa, have different life cycles and therefore have different levels of vulnerability to changes in the ocean. During the winter months, L. rangii, which is a polar species, can be found as both adults and juveniles, while L. retroversa, a subpolar species, is only found as adults during the winter.\n\nSea butterflies that exist during the coldest season are more vulnerable to increased levels of ocean acidification. This is because ocean water is more acidic during this season than during other times of the year due to cooler temperatures that increase CO2 dissolution in the ocean. The researchers explained that the life stages of sea butterflies during this time are more exposed and vulnerable to the effects of ocean acidification.\n\nL. rangii has a survival advantage over L. retroversa because both adults and juveniles coexist during winter, which reduces the risk of population instability if one cohort is vulnerable. In contrast, if one cohort is removed from L. retroversa, the entire population could be at risk.\n\nProlonged exposure is a survival challenge\n\nThe researchers pointed out that although the two species are affected differently, both are likely to suffer harm if they are exposed to unfavorable conditions for prolonged periods.\n\nThe scientists cautioned that the intensifying and prolonged events of ocean acidification overlap with the spring spawning period, posing a threat to the most vulnerable life stage, the larvae. This could endanger the future populations of sea butterflies.\n\nThe research team plans to further study the sea butterflies in the Scotia Sea to see how they would be affected by the increase in the intensity and duration of ocean acidification events. They will study multiyear sediment trap samples to identify potential changes in the life cycle that may occur due to environmental changes. Dr Jessie Gardner of the British Antarctic Survey, lead author of the study, said this will be the next step in their research.\n\nJournal Link: Frontiers in Marine Science","url":"https://www.newswise.com/articles/climate-change-imperils-sea-butterfly-lifecycle"},"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362":{"id":"d381a959-ef93-41ce-aeb8-490a933c9477_186257362","text":"How climate change and warming waters are affecting the health of the oceans\n\n(NEW YORK) \u2014 Oceans do so much to sustain life on Earth, including bearing the brunt of global temperatures that have been steadily warming for decades.\n\nAn IPCC special report published in 2019 found that oceans \u2014 which make up more than 70% of the world\u2019s surface \u2014 have absorbed between 20% and 30% of human-made carbon dioxide emissions since the 1980s. They\u2019re also responsible for absorbing more than 93% of the \u201ccombined heat stored by warmed air, sea, and land, and melted ice\u201d since the 1970s, according to the Fifth Assessment report published in 2013 by the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.\n\nThe tipping point is near, experts told ABC News. But there are collective actions to take that could revitalize oceans to a healthier state \u2014 the theme of the United Nations World Oceans Day 2022.\n\n\u201cWe really see oceans as the biggest ally in the climate change crisis,\u201d Lea d\u2019Auriol, founder of nonprofit Oceanic Global, told ABC News.\n\nThis is how climate change is affecting the health of the world\u2019s oceans:\n\nSpecies are faced with adapting or becoming extinct\n\nCurrently, the oceans \u201care in a state of complete imbalance\u201d that has nearly doubled since the 1990s, d\u2019Auriol said. Look no further than the fishermen, who supply sustenance to more than three billion people who rely on seafood as their main source of protein, as witnesses that climate change is already here, d\u2019Auriol, said.\n\n\u201cIf you wanted to ask someone if climate change is really happening, probably the most surest answer you\u2019d get from anyone aside from a scientist is a fisherman,\u201d Arlo Hemphill, senior oceans campaigner for Greenpeace USA, told ABC News. \u201cBecause fishermen are seeing these things happen in real time.\u201d\n\nOne of the changes long-time fisherman are witnessing is the presence of new species venturing north as the area with their preferred water temperature expands.\n\nMarine organisms maintain the same temperature as the surrounding water, so that when temperature increases, so does the temperature of the organism, Martin Grosell, professor of ichthyology and chair of the University of Miami\u2019s Department of Marine Biology and Ecology, told ABC News. As the temperature rises, the organisms require more energy to move and survive. But, conversely, the levels of oxygen in the water decrease as the temperature warms, forcing the species to move, Grosell said.\n\nThe migrations may seem innocuous, but they are disrupting ecosystems all over the world, such as the phenology, or timing, of when grey seals give birth, Hemphill said.\n\nConversely, species are continuing to die off due to repeated events of marine heatwaves, Anne Christianson, director of international climate policy for the Center for American Progress, a public policy research organization, told ABC News.\n\nCoral reefs are among the most threatened marine ecosystems in the world, scientists say. Coral bleaching, a process that occurs when water is too warm and the corals expel algae from their tissues, causing them to turn completely white, is happening at \u201calarming\u201d rates \u2014 increasing by a rate of 4% per year \u2014 along with an uptick in mortality events along entire regions, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nA study published in the National Academy of Sciences found that coral reefs could stop growing in 10 years unless greenhouse gases are significantly reduced and that, under a worst-case scenario, 94% of all reefs could erode by 2050.\n\nReefs are often the indicator of the health of an ecosystem, Brenda Ekwurzel, director of climate science for the Union of Concerned Scientists, told ABC News.\n\nMammals that rely on Arctic ice, such as polar bears and ringed seals, one of the polar bears\u2019 main food sources that live their lives almost entirely on the ice, are also at risk, Ekwurzel said.\n\nVegetation such as mangroves, seagrass plants and marshes, some of the largest carbon sinks on the planet, which absorb and store carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, are also at risk of extinction, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThe number of dead zones are increasing\n\nA dead zone, or the process of hypoxia, occurs when an algal bloom sucks up all the oxygen in an area, making it impossible for marine life to survive \u2014 essentially a biological desert, according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.\n\nA study published in 2008 in Science found that there were 400 dead zones around the world. By 2019, the number of dead zones had increased to about 900, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThe dead zones often occur in regions with rampant nutrient runoff, such as at the base of the Mississippi River, where it empties into the Gulf of Mexico, Hemphill said.\n\nSea level rise will change coastal communities\n\nThe biggest contributor to sea level rise is the melting ice in the Arctic, which is heating up twice as fast as the rest of the world, according to the 2021 Arctic Report Card by NOAA. Increases in sea level rise of 6 inches to a foot since the Industrial Revolution may seem like small increments, but crucial infrastructure near oceans was not built to withstand the added inches of water, experts say.\n\nMillions of people living in coastlines around the world, including those in mega cities such as New York, Los Angeles and San Francisco, will be displaced by the rise in sea levels, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nCarbon dioxide emissions sparks ocean acidification\n\nOcean acidification, which occurs when water\u2019s pH levels are lowered as a result of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, is not directly caused by warming temperatures but rather by excess carbon dioxide emissions, Hemphill said.\n\n\u201cThe alarming thing about it is that shellfish everything from from microscopic plankton, to clams and crabs and coral reefs themselves use calcium carbonate to build their shells,\u201d he said. \u201cAnd as the ocean acidifies, it becomes more difficult to create the shells.\u201d\n\nOcean acidification, rather than coral bleaching, will likely be the culprit behind the demise of coral reefs, Ekwurzel said.\n\nCollective actions are necessary to protect the oceans\n\nIn line with the 2022 theme for World Oceans Day, \u201cRevitalization: Collective Action for the Ocean,\u201d scientists and conservationists are highlighting the need for individuals, communities, nonprofits, the private sector and governments to come together to create solutions, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nThis includes ensuring the health of marine protected areas by eliminating housing, fishing zones and shipping traffic in the vicinity, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\nGovernments will need to create policies to protect both human life and the health of the ocean, Christianson said.\n\n\u201cThere isn\u2019t one silver bullet for solving this crisis in the ocean and on land,\u201d Christianson said.\n\nHowever, the ticking time bomb is the race to drastically reduce global greenhouse gas emissions within the next decade, the experts said.\n\n\u201cWe can\u2019t afford to delay those solutions any longer,\u201d Ekwurzel said.\n\nAlong the path to properly protecting and preserving oceans is ridding the narrative that oceans are a separate environmental issue from climate change and the conservation of biodiversity, d\u2019Auriol said.\n\n\u201cBecause we do live on a water planet, and it\u2019s responsible for sustaining all life on Earth,\u201d she said.\n\nCopyright (C) 2022, ABC Audio. All rights reserved.","url":"https://wfin.com/abc-world-news/how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans&utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-climate-change-and-warming-waters-are-affecting-the-health-of-the-oceans"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1049","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1049","narrative_id":"1049"},"responses":[{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Syria's traditional glassblowing is an artisanal craft with a history dating back over two thousand years to the time of the Phoenicians."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has been an essential part of Syria's culture, with skilled glassblowing craftsmen found in towns such as Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The town of Urem Al-Kubra was famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen, but the war significantly affected this traditional craft, with many artisans forced to abandon their work."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"However, after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought the craft back to life, with Yassin Arab being one example of an artisan who has restored his small facility and started working again."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft of glassblowing was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"This listing is due to the craft's importance in Syria's culture and the need to preserve this ancient heritage, with artisans such as Hussein Najjar having spent 40 years working in the field."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Despite its importance, the craft is facing significant challenges, including a decline in demand and insufficient profits, which has led to many craftsmen stopping production and switching to other professions."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The current status of the craft is uncertain, with many workshops and shops closed, and thousands of craftsmen migrating or moving their work abroad."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"UNESCO's listing of the craft is a recognition of its importance and a call to action to preserve this traditional craft, which is an integral part of Syria's cultural identity."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Syria's traditional glassblowing is an artisanal craft with a history dating back over two thousand years to the time of the Phoenicians."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has been an essential part of Syria's culture, with skilled glassblowing craftsmen found in towns such as Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The town of Urem Al-Kubra was famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen, but the war significantly affected this traditional craft, with many artisans forced to abandon their work."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"However, after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought the craft back to life, with Yassin Arab being one example of an artisan who has restored his small facility and started working again."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft of glassblowing was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"This listing is due to the craft's importance in Syria's culture and the need to preserve this ancient heritage, with artisans such as Hussein Najjar having spent 40 years working in the field."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Despite its importance, the craft is facing significant challenges, including a decline in demand and insufficient profits, which has led to many craftsmen stopping production and switching to other professions."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The current status of the craft is uncertain, with many workshops and shops closed, and thousands of craftsmen migrating or moving their work abroad."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"UNESCO's listing of the craft is a recognition of its importance and a call to action to preserve this traditional craft, which is an integral part of Syria's cultural identity."}],"references":["2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831"],"documents":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":{"id":"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831","text":"What is the reality of traditional and traditional professions in Syria?\nDAMASCUS \u2013 The traditional professions and crafts in Syria were not immune to the repercussions of the war. In light of the difficult economic and security conditions that the country has been witnessing for more than a decade, these professions are suffering from an unprecedented decline related to production and market conditions, which makes them today threatened with extinction.\nThe head of the Union of Craftsmen in the province of Latakia Jihad Pro, in a recent statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan, the decline of the production of handicrafts and handicrafts of various kinds by 50% within the province, considering the high costs of production inputs and increased income taxes as direct reasons for this decline.\nBassam Qalaji, head of the artisanal association for confectionery in Damascus, told the local newspaper Global last month that more than half of the confectionery craftsmen had stopped producing and switched to other professions due to low demand and insufficient profits.\nSuccessive statements reveal the reality of Syrian traditional and traditional crafts, which are suffering under the weight of the economic decline that the country is suffering from.\nThis situation has prompted thousands of craftsmen to close their workshops and shops and switch to other jobs, or migrate and move their work abroad, amid the real threat of the disappearance of many traditional traditional traditional professions and handicrafts, which constitute vital sectors of the economic sector in the country and an integral part of its cultural identity.\nWhat are the main reasons for this decline?\nHow does it affect the economic life of the country?\nLack of support and unequal competition\nAnton, a 42-year-old Damascene craftsman and former owner of a mosaic workshop in rural Damascus, says his struggle for years to keep his workshop open, producing and selling enough to pay its workers has been futile.\nHe adds in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"I tried hard to maintain the workshop and its workers for as long as possible, but the constant high prices of wood (local and imported) in an inappropriate manner, the long interruption of electricity (16-18 hours a day), and the low demand for mosaic in the domestic and foreign market, all factors forced me to lay off workers, and later to close the workshop after months, during which I received only two orders.\"\nIn addition to these factors, Anton attributed the low demand for \"original\" mosaics and other handicrafts and heritage artifacts (copperware, damask, antika, textiles) to:\nThe reality of the market at the moment in the absence of tourists.\n\u2022 The decline of external demand for the commodity as a result of the interruption of trade relations with foreign markets.\n\u2022 Migration of brokers and traders and thus reduced export.\n\u2022 Unequal competition.\nWith heritage products becoming \u201cmore than luxury \u201d for Syrians suffering from poor purchasing power (average monthly salaries of about $20), and the lack of support for craftsmen and awareness of the importance and authenticity of these products by trade unions and government agencies, Syria \u2019 s craftsmen face major challenges to continue their craft.\nAlthough there are no accurate figures on the number of craftsmen who have been driven by working conditions to emigrate outside the country, the head of the Damascus Craftsmen \u2019 s Union, Ali Qarmashti, revealed in an interview with the local news website Click News last year that the percentage of Damascene craftsmen migrating has become very high, especially among young people.\nRepellent economic and social policies\nIn addition to the direct economic factors that led to the decline of traditional crafts during the past few years, represented by the high prices of raw materials, the poor reality of services, and the decline of the sale and purchase movement, there were indirect factors that affected these crafts.\nSyrian economist Younis Karim believes that the artisan crisis began in 2008 after being subjected to great pressures due to the change of the general economic orientation in the country.\nHe said in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"Since 2008, the authorities have put their hands on the spread of these industries due to the importance of their geographical location, and work to change their features in favor of wealthy investors, or provide them as donations to countries that Damascus seeks to establish bilateral relations with.\"\nAccording to the expert, the reality of the work of traditional crafts after 2011 became more complex and difficult with \"the continued adoption of economic and social policies by the regime that restrict the owners of these crafts, exclude them from support, take their places of deployment, in addition to the cessation of exhibitions and the difficulty of participating in external events because of the political positions of the regime.\nKarim explains that the family and social disintegration suffered by Syrians as a result of large-scale migration during the last decade was an added reason for the decline of these crafts, which \u201crelied on inheritance between generations of the same family as a tradition followed by Syrian craftsmen long ago. \u201d\nKilo to Piece and Pieces\nIt seems that some traditional crafts and crafts are in the same trench with traditional crafts in their war against extinction, where the owners of many traditional crafts are no less original than those of heritage, especially the confectioners from the high costs of raw materials in production, high costs of energy stands, and successive losses due to the reluctance of citizens to buy expensive Arabic sweets.\nSuhaib, 55, owner of a sweets shop in the Jazmatiya area of Damascus, told Al Jazeera Net: \"Days pass without selling a total of a kilo of various items, and two years ago the stagnation of goods in the shop became a familiar phenomenon to us, and had it not been for the holiday seasons, and some occasions and weddings held here and there, we would have closed long ago.\"\nAl-Halwani Al-Damascene adds in an interview with Al-Jazeera Net: \"Our profits, and the profits of most of the shops of Halwanis in Damascus, have decreased by a large percentage since the beginning of the economic crisis in the country.\"\nAl-Halwani pointed out that the price of a kilo of some varieties of Arabic sweets has exceeded 400 thousand pounds recently, adding: \"Which is not able for Syrians to buy, so we have become selling methods in which we rely on small quantities, so we sell baklava, crystal, shaped, asian, brominated and other items in ounces, grain (piece) and two grains to keep the sales movement, and do not stop customers from our shop.\"\nAs for the reasons why sweets in Damascus stopped working and many of them emigrated outside the country, Al-Halwani said: \u201cMany reasons start from the large annual taxes that are inconsistent with high operating costs and low profits, in addition to the high prices of commercial electricity and fuel needed to operate shops and laboratories, the huge increase in the prices of raw materials, the high wages of workers, and the reluctance of customers to buy these sweets except on occasions. \u201d\nHigh prices\nPrices of food, nuts and other components of Arabic sweets have risen by varying rates recently, as the price of a kilo of animal margarine reached 150 thousand pounds ($equivalent to about 2511 pounds), while the price of a kilo of pistachio love rose to 300 thousand, and the price of a kilo of walnuts to 120 thousand.\nThe prices of popular sweets such as Al-Barazek and Al-Ma \u2019 amoul in Damascus markets, by the holy month of Ramadan, were between 100 and 130 thousand pounds per kilo, while the prices of medium and luxury sweets such as \u201cAl-Belouria \u201d,\u201c Al-Mashkeel \u201d, \u201cKool and Shakour \u201d,\u201c Aish Al-Bulbul \u201d and \u201cBaklava \u201d ranged between 250 and 500 thousand per kilo, which is equivalent to the salary of a Syrian employee in the public sector.\nThe head of the artisanal association for confectionery industry, Bassam Qalaji, attributed this rise in confectionery prices to the government lifting subsidies on oil derivatives, which led to a direct increase in costs by 150%, pointing out that raising the price of electricity by 5 times will lead to an increase in the price of about 650 products.\nQalaji said in a statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan last month that the largest number of confectionery craftsmen emigrated, and their first destination was Algeria followed by Germany.\nIn March last year, the head of the artisanal association for the confectionery industry revealed that 70% of the workshops of the confectionery industry were closed due to the economic crisis and the low demand for sweets and refreshments.\nA severe blow to the economy\nThis gradual disappearance of traditional crafts is a painful blow to the Syrian economy, says economist Younis Karim, \u201cFor decades these crafts have been the largest incubator of Syrian labor, and their contribution to the economy before 2011 ranged from 40 to 50%. \u201d\nThis is what Matanios Habib, a researcher and former Syrian oil minister, said in a research paper entitled \u201cThe private sector in Syria \u201d (2005), when he pointed out that the private industrial sector in Syria tended to invest in crafts for fear of nationalization policies, whether during the era of Syrian-Egyptian unity (1958-1961) or after the revolution of March 8 (1967).\nKarim stresses that the crisis of workers in traditional crafts, such as confectioners and others, dates back to before 2011, specifically to the period between 2007 and 2009, when there was \u201can attempt by the regime to pressure the owners of traditional crafts and crafts by forcing them to pay taxes, and to keep them away from city centers in favor of large investors. \u201d\nYounis Karim believes that the gradual demise of these crafts will have negative effects on the Syrian economy because of their role in \"providing job opportunities beyond those provided by large laboratories and their excellence in ease of operation and achievement, and the ability to spread.\nSource: The Island","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0006.json.gz:67103","uncompressed_offset":286336831,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2024-03-12T15:53:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-03-12T16:08:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":{"id":"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","text":"Art of glassblowing returns again in Aleppo countryside liberated from terrorism\n\nThe town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province in northern Syria has historically been famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen. The war considerably affected this traditional craft inherited from our ancestors, but after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought it back to life. The artisan, Yassin Arab learned the glassblowing craft from his father when he was a child, and after the town was liberated from terrorism, he returned to his small facility, where he worked to restore it and start working again. Arab does not hide his enormous passion for the craft of glassblowing and his belief in the need to preserve this ancient Syrian heritage. Regarding the working mechanism, the artisan explained to SANA that he uses recycled glass, melts it again in the oven at high temperature, and then chooses a specific shape for its manufacture, whether hookah bottles, vases, plates, small jugs, fish houses for decoration, decorated cups and antiques of different sizes. After that, t he piece is blown, rotated and processed by the artisan until it takes its final shape using white and brown colors, and once the manufacturing of the product is finished, it is decorated and colored to give it the required aesthetics. For his part, Hussein Najjar noted that he learned the craft of blowing glass manually since he was young and has been working in this field for 40 years. He added that he is able to make any shape or glass container, using his imagination, and considered that the art of glassblowing is one of the types of plastic arts. Traditional glassblowing is a profession that dates back more than two thousand years (since the time of the Phoenicians) and was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent preservation. Source: Syrian Arab News Agency","url":"https://qatarpress.qa/art-of-glassblowing-returns-again-in-aleppo-countryside-liberated-from-terrorism/"}}}
