reasons for this decline?\nHow does it affect the economic life of the country?\nLack of support and unequal competition\nAnton, a 42-year-old Damascene craftsman and former owner of a mosaic workshop in rural Damascus, says his struggle for years to keep his workshop open, producing and selling enough to pay its workers has been futile.\nHe adds in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"I tried hard to maintain the workshop and its workers for as long as possible, but the constant high prices of wood (local and imported) in an inappropriate manner, the long interruption of electricity (16-18 hours a day), and the low demand for mosaic in the domestic and foreign market, all factors forced me to lay off workers, and later to close the workshop after months, during which I received only two orders.\"\nIn addition to these factors, Anton attributed the low demand for \"original\" mosaics and other handicrafts and heritage artifacts (copperware, damask, antika, textiles) to:\nThe reality of the market at the moment in the absence of tourists.\n\u2022 The decline of external demand for the commodity as a result of the interruption of trade relations with foreign markets.\n\u2022 Migration of brokers and traders and thus reduced export.\n\u2022 Unequal competition.\nWith heritage products becoming \u201cmore than luxury \u201d for Syrians suffering from poor purchasing power (average monthly salaries of about $20), and the lack of support for craftsmen and awareness of the importance and authenticity of these products by trade unions and government agencies, Syria \u2019 s craftsmen face major challenges to continue their craft.\nAlthough there are no accurate figures on the number of craftsmen who have been driven by working conditions to emigrate outside the country, the head of the Damascus Craftsmen \u2019 s Union, Ali Qarmashti, revealed in an interview with the local news website Click News last year that the percentage of Damascene craftsmen migrating has become very high, especially among young people.\nRepellent economic and social policies\nIn addition to the direct economic factors that led to the decline of traditional crafts during the past few years, represented by the high prices of raw materials, the poor reality of services, and the decline of the sale and purchase movement, there were indirect factors that affected these crafts.\nSyrian economist Younis Karim believes that the artisan crisis began in 2008 after being subjected to great pressures due to the change of the general economic orientation in the country.\nHe said in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"Since 2008, the authorities have put their hands on the spread of these industries due to the importance of their geographical location, and work to change their features in favor of wealthy investors, or provide them as donations to countries that Damascus seeks to establish bilateral relations with.\"\nAccording to the expert, the reality of the work of traditional crafts after 2011 became more complex and difficult with \"the continued adoption of economic and social policies by the regime that restrict the owners of these crafts, exclude them from support, take their places of deployment, in addition to the cessation of exhibitions and the difficulty of participating in external events because of the political positions of the regime.\nKarim explains that the family and social disintegration suffered by Syrians as a result of large-scale migration during the last decade was an added reason for the decline of these crafts, which \u201crelied on inheritance between generations of the same family as a tradition followed by Syrian craftsmen long ago. \u201d\nKilo to Piece and Pieces\nIt seems that some traditional crafts and crafts are in the same trench with traditional crafts in their war against extinction, where the owners of many traditional crafts are no less original than those of heritage, especially the confectioners from the high costs of raw materials in production, high costs of energy stands, and successive losses due to the reluctance of citizens to buy expensive Arabic sweets.\nSuhaib, 55, owner of a sweets shop in the Jazmatiya area of Damascus, told Al Jazeera Net: \"Days pass without selling a total of a kilo of various items, and two years ago the stagnation of goods in the shop became a familiar phenomenon to us, and had it not been for the holiday seasons, and some occasions and weddings held here and there, we would have closed long ago.\"\nAl-Halwani Al-Damascene adds in an interview with Al-Jazeera Net: \"Our profits, and the profits of most of the shops of Halwanis in Damascus, have decreased by a large percentage since the beginning of the economic crisis in the country.\"\nAl-Halwani pointed out that the price of a kilo of some varieties of Arabic sweets has exceeded 400 thousand pounds recently, adding: \"Which is not able for Syrians to buy, so we have become selling methods in which we rely on small quantities, so we sell baklava, crystal, shaped, asian, brominated and other items in ounces, grain (piece) and two grains to keep the sales movement, and do not stop customers from our shop.\"\nAs for the reasons why sweets in Damascus stopped working and many of them emigrated outside the country, Al-Halwani said: \u201cMany reasons start from the large annual taxes that are inconsistent with high operating costs and low profits, in addition to the high prices of commercial electricity and fuel needed to operate shops and laboratories, the huge increase in the prices of raw materials, the high wages of workers, and the reluctance of customers to buy these sweets except on occasions. \u201d\nHigh prices\nPrices of food, nuts and other components of Arabic sweets have risen by varying rates recently, as the price of a kilo of animal margarine reached 150 thousand pounds ($equivalent to about 2511 pounds), while the price of a kilo of pistachio love rose to 300 thousand, and the price of a kilo of walnuts to 120 thousand.\nThe prices of popular sweets such as Al-Barazek and Al-Ma \u2019 amoul in Damascus markets, by the holy month of Ramadan, were between 100 and 130 thousand pounds per kilo, while the prices of medium and luxury sweets such as \u201cAl-Belouria \u201d,\u201c Al-Mashkeel \u201d, \u201cKool and Shakour \u201d,\u201c Aish Al-Bulbul \u201d and \u201cBaklava \u201d ranged between 250 and 500 thousand per kilo, which is equivalent to the salary of a Syrian employee in the public sector.\nThe head of the artisanal association for confectionery industry, Bassam Qalaji, attributed this rise in confectionery prices to the government lifting subsidies on oil derivatives, which led to a direct increase in costs by 150%, pointing out that raising the price of electricity by 5 times will lead to an increase in the price of about 650 products.\nQalaji said in a statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan last month that the largest number of confectionery craftsmen emigrated, and their first destination was Algeria followed by Germany.\nIn March last year, the head of the artisanal association for the confectionery industry revealed that 70% of the workshops of the confectionery industry were closed due to the economic crisis and the low demand for sweets and refreshments.\nA severe blow to the economy\nThis gradual disappearance of traditional crafts is a painful blow to the Syrian economy, says economist Younis Karim, \u201cFor decades these crafts have been the largest incubator of Syrian labor, and their contribution to the economy before 2011 ranged from 40 to 50%. \u201d\nThis is what Matanios Habib, a researcher and former Syrian oil minister, said in a research paper entitled \u201cThe private sector in Syria \u201d (2005), when he pointed out that the private industrial sector in Syria tended to invest in crafts for fear of nationalization policies, whether during the era of Syrian-Egyptian unity (1958-1961) or after the revolution of March 8 (1967).\nKarim stresses that the crisis of workers in traditional crafts, such as confectioners and others, dates back to before 2011, specifically to the period between 2007 and 2009, when there was \u201can attempt by the regime to pressure the owners of traditional crafts and crafts by forcing them to pay taxes, and to keep them away from city centers in favor of large investors. \u201d\nYounis Karim believes that the gradual demise of these crafts will have negative effects on the Syrian economy because of their role in \"providing job opportunities beyond those provided by large laboratories and their excellence in ease of operation and achievement, and the ability to spread.\nSource: The Island","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0006.json.gz:67103","uncompressed_offset":286336831,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2024-03-12T15:53:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-03-12T16:08:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477":{"id":"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477","text":"A year of hard work to document and preserve the Syrian tangible and intangible heritage locally and internationally\nDamascus-Sana\nThe Syrian heritage, both tangible and intangible, forms an important pillar within the World Heritage system, and is a key factor in strengthening the cultural identity of the Syrian people, building the present and protecting the future.\nDuring 2022, the Ministry of Culture and its concerned institutions, in particular the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums and the Directorate of Intangible Cultural Heritage, focused on organizing a series of events and seminars and signing a series of agreements related to the importance and mechanisms of preserving this heritage in its various components.\nAmong the most important Syrian activities and works related to tangible and intangible heritage during 2022 are:\nDuring the year, Syria held several discussions on the loan of Syrian artifacts damaged during the terrorist war on Syria for restoration and display in the Sultanate of Oman, and signed a joint statement on cooperation to preserve cultural heritage with the People \u2019 s Republic of China.\nSyria participated in the International Forum of the Convention for the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage in the Russian city of Kazan, and the Scientific Conference on Archaeology in the Hungarian capital, and participated in a virtual lecture within the international conference on the protection of the Syrian cultural heritage after the war.\n\u2013 The archaeological missions returned to excavations in 2022, including the joint Syrian-Italian archaeological mission, which began its work for the first season at the archaeological site of Amrit, and the discovery of a funerary burial and some archaeological finds and discoveries dating back to the Roman era in Amrit by the joint excavation team between the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums and the Department of Tartus Antiquities.\n\u2013 The national expertise of the Directorate General of Antiquities worked to expand the work to discover the entire rare archaeological mosaic painting in the city of Rastan, which dates back to the Roman era, and reached a length of 20 meters and a width of 6 meters.\n\u2013 Completion of the restoration work of the Arc de Triomphe in the ancient city of Palmyra, which was destroyed by terrorist organizations in 2015, and the second phase of the restoration project began with the signing of a memorandum of understanding between the Directorate of Antiquities, the Syrian Secretariat and the Institute of the History of Material Culture of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the Russian Federation.\n\u2013 Holding a workshop \u201cRestoring Syrian Heritage and Reviving Local Communities \u201d at Expo 2020 Dubai, in which local, Arab and international bodies specialized in antiquities participated.\n\u2013 In the National Museum in Damascus and in tribute to the lives and sacrifices of about 27 martyrs who rose during the terrorist war on Syria in defense of the Syrian cultural heritage, an exhibition of recovered archaeological treasures 3 entitled (Salute to the martyrs of the General Directorate of Antiquities and Museums) was opened within the days of Syrian culture.\n\u2013 The opening of a painting exhibition entitled \u201cRestoration of Syrian Heritage by Theo Vitit \u2019 s Vision \u201d at the National Museum in Damascus, which is a painting of restoration and excavation works in Syrian archaeological sites, painted by the Dutch artist and archaeologist Theo Vitit in 2018 and 2021, and was presented in the Netherlands to introduce the Western community to what happened to the Syrian cultural heritage.\nIn Damascus Castle, the first national screening of the film Siriacus Section, directed by Olivier Bourgeois, was launched in 2022 in cooperation between the Ministry of Culture, the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums, and the Syrian Trust for Development. The film, which won more than 17 international awards, talks about the solidarity of a small group of archaeologists and museum curators with the escalation of the terrorist war on Aleppo in 2015. The National Museum of Aleppo.\nThe Directorate of Antiquities, in cooperation with the European Center for Byzantine and Post-Byzantine Monuments and the Department of Antiquities at the University of Damascus, organized a digital exhibition on historical mosaics in Syria, entitled \u201cSyria is still the source of arts \u201d.\n\u2013 The beginning of the year witnessed the return of five Syrian destructive artifacts to the National Museum in Damascus at the initiative of the management of the Naboo Museum in Beirut, and the pieces are various funerary destructive statues from the collections of the Naboo Museum previously purchased from European auction houses.\nThe second leg of the Syrian Antiquities Exhibition, entitled \u201cThe Wonderful Syria \u201d, was opened in Chengdu, Sichuan Province, southwest China, which lasted until May. During this period, special scientific seminars and cultural events were held in connection with the exhibition, in which the Department of Antiquities and Museums participated with 195 important artifacts and collections of Syrian museums.\nIn 2022, the Directorate of Intangible Cultural Heritage has been active in most governorates, focusing on monitoring, studying and documenting the national intangible heritage and preparing the necessary plans to search for, study and inventory the elements of this heritage and include them in the national register, in cooperation with governmental and non-governmental institutions, local communities and international organizations.\nThe Directorate of Heritage organized a workshop on Syrian intangible cultural heritage at Al-Assad National Library, in preparation for the development of a national strategy for intangible cultural heritage in Syria.\n\u2013 The project (Windows 5) was organized, whose musical evenings varied between documentation and promotion of Syrian heritage songs, and many heritage festivals were held in the provinces.\n\u2013 The project of documenting the elements of the Syrian intangible heritage in ancient Homs, implemented by the Ministry of Culture in cooperation with the Syrian Secretariat and civil society, was launched in 2022 to preserve the elements of this heritage, and work continued on the project of documenting the elements of the intangible heritage in Tartus province.\nWithin the framework of the implementation of the plan to preserve the element of the theater of shadow imagination Karkouz and Aiwaz after registration on the list of urgent conservation of the world humanitarian heritage at UNESCO, the Syrian Secretariat for Development continued the third professional training after Damascus and Suwayda, for youth cadres in the city of Aleppo.\nThe Syrian Secretariat for Development has developed the \u201cLiving Heritage \u201d program with the local community in Aleppo governorate, the main axes for the preservation of the Aleppo cod, which was registered on the Representative List of Human Heritage at UNESCO by the end of 2021 with the participation of a group of governmental and civil authorities, artists, musicians, researchers and interested in the Arab, musical and art of cod.\nAt the international level:\nSyria has been elected vice-president of the ninth session of the General Assembly of the States Parties to the 2003 UNESCO Convention for the Safeguarding of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity for a two-year term 2022-2024.\nSyria participated in the UNESCO World Conference on Cultural Policies and Sustainable Development, Mondiacult 2022, in Mexico.\n\u2013 In 2022, a scientific research by the son of the city of Aleppo, Antoine Makdis, related to how to recover from the effects of war through independent cultural production based on intangible cultural heritage won the first place in the competition of the Foundation of Santgrata, specialized in the Italian cultural economy.\n\u2013 An integrated archaeological project in the Baal Shemin Temple in Palmyra has been shortlisted for the third cycle of ICCROM Sharjah Award for the Conservation and Protection of Cultural Heritage in the Arab Region 2020-2022.\nRasha Mahfoudh and Mays Al-Ani\nFollow SANA news on Telegram https: / / t.me / SyrianArabNewsAgency","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0039.json.gz:9803","uncompressed_offset":205807477,"url":"www.sana.sy/?p=1811638","warc_date":"2022-12-31T16:19:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f>","warc_url":"https://www.sana.sy/?p=1811638"},"created":"2022-12-31T16:34:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":{"id":"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","text":"Art of glassblowing returns again in Aleppo countryside liberated from terrorism\n\nThe town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province in northern Syria has historically been famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen. The war considerably affected this traditional craft inherited from our ancestors, but after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought it back to life. The artisan, Yassin Arab learned the glassblowing craft from his father when he was a child, and after the town was liberated from terrorism, he returned to his small facility, where he worked to restore it and start working again. Arab does not hide his enormous passion for the craft of glassblowing and his belief in the need to preserve this ancient Syrian heritage. Regarding the working mechanism, the artisan explained to SANA that he uses recycled glass, melts it again in the oven at high temperature, and then chooses a specific shape for its manufacture, whether hookah bottles, vases, plates, small jugs, fish houses for decoration, decorated cups and antiques of different sizes. After that, t he piece is blown, rotated and processed by the artisan until it takes its final shape using white and brown colors, and once the manufacturing of the product is finished, it is decorated and colored to give it the required aesthetics. For his part, Hussein Najjar noted that he learned the craft of blowing glass manually since he was young and has been working in this field for 40 years. He added that he is able to make any shape or glass container, using his imagination, and considered that the art of glassblowing is one of the types of plastic arts. Traditional glassblowing is a profession that dates back more than two thousand years (since the time of the Phoenicians) and was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent preservation. Source: Syrian Arab News Agency","url":"https://qatarpress.qa/art-of-glassblowing-returns-again-in-aleppo-countryside-liberated-from-terrorism/"},"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":{"id":"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262","text":"Samples of the Damascene Literary Heritage Attend an Exhibition and Seminar in the Culture of Infection\nDamascus-Sana\nIn the exhibition \u201cHeritage Crafts are Inherited by the Fragrance of History \u201d hosted by the Adawi Cultural Center, the artworks varied between glass decoration, Damascene brocade and various handicrafts.\nThe exhibition was followed by an introductory seminar on these arts for the Sheikhs of Carr and craftsmen specialized in these professions under the supervision of the handicraft trainer Rowaa Yousef.\nYoussef Lassana explained that the exhibition was dedicated to traditional professions in general and handicrafts, especially such as brocade, painting on glass, Islamic motifs and handicrafts to maintain their continuity and importance.\nMohammed Bassam Rayhan Sheikh Al-Karar in painting on glass and decoration spoke in his intervention about the history of this craft, its forms, fields of work and materials used in it, pointing out that the glass, which was the first to be invented by the Phoenicians, evolved in Damascus throughout history and was painted on the mishkat and lanterns using oxides and various materials, thermal colors, acrlik and others.\nThe Damascene brocade craftsman Mohammed Rankous explained in his intervention that this cloth is made of natural silk and golden reed yarns and attributed to Damascus because it took its character, heritage and environment, such as the painting of Omar Khayyam, the Levantine Rose, grape clusters, the lover and the beloved, and the octagonal geometric drawings, pointing out that this craft entered the cultures of different civilizations.\nNasruddin Mohammed is a graduate of applied arts and a drawing teacher who participated in paintings for his students from children and boys. In his intervention, he explained the history of the Damascene plant decoration, its methods, types and schools such as Andalusian, Persian and Damascene, and its differences in decoration, diggings, mirrors and miniatures, indicating that its history dates back to the Andalusian civilization, which was its main creativity in palaces and buildings.\nMohammed Sabha is a bridal craftsman who participated in a group of decorative glass works for brides and explained that he has completed a model of a waterfall flowing from an electric mountain that is operated by hand from cardboard, wood and cork inspired by his ideas.\nRana Ayoub participated in a group of works of three-dimensional models and miniatures of the Levant environment. She explained that she chose this environment because she grew up and lived in it and adored it. It is necessary to inform future generations of their heritage and history, pointing out that she works with cork, wood, natural materials, gypsum, ceramic paste and others.\nBilal Ahmed","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0026.json.gz:34512","uncompressed_offset":505232262,"url":"www.sana.sy/?p=1475724","warc_date":"2021-09-13T18:33:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422>","warc_url":"https://www.sana.sy/?p=1475724"},"created":"2021-09-13T19:00:59.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
