ent Homs."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The current status of the craft is precarious, with many craftsmen struggling to continue their work due to low demand and insufficient profits."},{"citations":{"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477":1.0},"text":"Overall, Syria's traditional glassblowing is a vital part of the country's cultural identity, and efforts must be made to preserve and promote this craft to ensure its survival."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Syria's traditional glassblowing is an artisanal craft with a rich history dating back over two thousand years to the time of the Phoenicians."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has been an essential part of Syria's culture, with skilled glassblowing craftsmen producing various items such as hookah bottles, vases, plates, and decorated cups."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"However, the craft has suffered significantly due to the war and economic decline, with many craftsmen forced to close their workshops and switch to other professions."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Despite this, some artisans have brought the craft back to life, with Yassin Arab being a notable example, who learned the craft from his father and has worked to restore his facility and start working again."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The importance of traditional glassblowing in Syria's culture has been recognized by UNESCO, which included it in the List of Intangible Cultural Heritage in Need of Urgent Safeguarding in December 2023."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"This recognition highlights the need to preserve this ancient Syrian heritage, which is considered one of the types of plastic arts."},{"citations":{"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477":1.0},"text":"Efforts are being made to document and preserve the elements of Syria's intangible cultural heritage, including traditional glassblowing, through projects such as the \"Windows 5\" project and the documentation of elements of the Syrian intangible heritage in ancient Homs."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The current status of the craft is precarious, with many craftsmen struggling to continue their work due to low demand and insufficient profits."},{"citations":{"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477":1.0},"text":"Overall, Syria's traditional glassblowing is a vital part of the country's cultural identity, and efforts must be made to preserve and promote this craft to ensure its survival."}],"references":["2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477","a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831"],"documents":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":{"id":"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831","text":"What is the reality of traditional and traditional professions in Syria?\nDAMASCUS \u2013 The traditional professions and crafts in Syria were not immune to the repercussions of the war. In light of the difficult economic and security conditions that the country has been witnessing for more than a decade, these professions are suffering from an unprecedented decline related to production and market conditions, which makes them today threatened with extinction.\nThe head of the Union of Craftsmen in the province of Latakia Jihad Pro, in a recent statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan, the decline of the production of handicrafts and handicrafts of various kinds by 50% within the province, considering the high costs of production inputs and increased income taxes as direct reasons for this decline.\nBassam Qalaji, head of the artisanal association for confectionery in Damascus, told the local newspaper Global last month that more than half of the confectionery craftsmen had stopped producing and switched to other professions due to low demand and insufficient profits.\nSuccessive statements reveal the reality of Syrian traditional and traditional crafts, which are suffering under the weight of the economic decline that the country is suffering from.\nThis situation has prompted thousands of craftsmen to close their workshops and shops and switch to other jobs, or migrate and move their work abroad, amid the real threat of the disappearance of many traditional traditional traditional professions and handicrafts, which constitute vital sectors of the economic sector in the country and an integral part of its cultural identity.\nWhat are the main reasons for this decline?\nHow does it affect the economic life of the country?\nLack of support and unequal competition\nAnton, a 42-year-old Damascene craftsman and former owner of a mosaic workshop in rural Damascus, says his struggle for years to keep his workshop open, producing and selling enough to pay its workers has been futile.\nHe adds in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"I tried hard to maintain the workshop and its workers for as long as possible, but the constant high prices of wood (local and imported) in an inappropriate manner, the long interruption of electricity (16-18 hours a day), and the low demand for mosaic in the domestic and foreign market, all factors forced me to lay off workers, and later to close the workshop after months, during which I received only two orders.\"\nIn addition to these factors, Anton attributed the low demand for \"original\" mosaics and other handicrafts and heritage artifacts (copperware, damask, antika, textiles) to:\nThe reality of the market at the moment in the absence of tourists.\n\u2022 The decline of external demand for the commodity as a result of the interruption of trade relations with foreign markets.\n\u2022 Migration of brokers and traders and thus reduced export.\n\u2022 Unequal competition.\nWith heritage products becoming \u201cmore than luxury \u201d for Syrians suffering from poor purchasing power (average monthly salaries of about $20), and the lack of support for craftsmen and awareness of the importance and authenticity of these products by trade unions and government agencies, Syria \u2019 s craftsmen face major challenges to continue their craft.\nAlthough there are no accurate figures on the number of craftsmen who have been driven by working conditions to emigrate outside the country, the head of the Damascus Craftsmen \u2019 s Union, Ali Qarmashti, revealed in an interview with the local news website Click News last year that the percentage of Damascene craftsmen migrating has become very high, especially among young people.\nRepellent economic and social policies\nIn addition to the direct economic factors that led to the decline of traditional crafts during the past few years, represented by the high prices of raw materials, the poor reality of services, and the decline of the sale and purchase movement, there were indirect factors that affected these crafts.\nSyrian economist Younis Karim believes that the artisan crisis began in 2008 after being subjected to great pressures due to the change of the general economic orientation in the country.\nHe said in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"Since 2008, the authorities have put their hands on the spread of these industries due to the importance of their geographical location, and work to change their features in favor of wealthy investors, or provide them as donations to countries that Damascus seeks to establish bilateral relations with.\"\nAccording to the expert, the reality of the work of traditional crafts after 2011 became more complex and difficult with \"the continued adoption of economic and social policies by the regime that restrict the owners of these crafts, exclude them from support, take their places of deployment, in addition to the cessation of exhibitions and the difficulty of participating in external events because of the political positions of the regime.\nKarim explains that the family and social disintegration suffered by Syrians as a result of large-scale migration during the last decade was an added reason for the decline of these crafts, which \u201crelied on inheritance between generations of the same family as a tradition followed by Syrian craftsmen long ago. \u201d\nKilo to Piece and Pieces\nIt seems that some traditional crafts and crafts are in the same trench with traditional crafts in their war against extinction, where the owners of many traditional crafts are no less original than those of heritage, especially the confectioners from the high costs of raw materials in production, high costs of energy stands, and successive losses due to the reluctance of citizens to buy expensive Arabic sweets.\nSuhaib, 55, owner of a sweets shop in the Jazmatiya area of Damascus, told Al Jazeera Net: \"Days pass without selling a total of a kilo of various items, and two years ago the stagnation of goods in the shop became a familiar phenomenon to us, and had it not been for the holiday seasons, and some occasions and weddings held here and there, we would have closed long ago.\"\nAl-Halwani Al-Damascene adds in an interview with Al-Jazeera Net: \"Our profits, and the profits of most of the shops of Halwanis in Damascus, have decreased by a large percentage since the beginning of the economic crisis in the country.\"\nAl-Halwani pointed out that the price of a kilo of some varieties of Arabic sweets has exceeded 400 thousand pounds recently, adding: \"Which is not able for Syrians to buy, so we have become selling methods in which we rely on small quantities, so we sell baklava, crystal, shaped, asian, brominated and other items in ounces, grain (piece) and two grains to keep the sales movement, and do not stop customers from our shop.\"\nAs for the reasons why sweets in Damascus stopped working and many of them emigrated outside the country, Al-Halwani said: \u201cMany reasons start from the large annual taxes that are inconsistent with high operating costs and low profits, in addition to the high prices of commercial electricity and fuel needed to operate shops and laboratories, the huge increase in the prices of raw materials, the high wages of workers, and the reluctance of customers to buy these sweets except on occasions. \u201d\nHigh prices\nPrices of food, nuts and other components of Arabic sweets have risen by varying rates recently, as the price of a kilo of animal margarine reached 150 thousand pounds ($equivalent to about 2511 pounds), while the price of a kilo of pistachio love rose to 300 thousand, and the price of a kilo of walnuts to 120 thousand.\nThe prices of popular sweets such as Al-Barazek and Al-Ma \u2019 amoul in Damascus markets, by the holy month of Ramadan, were between 100 and 130 thousand pounds per kilo, while the prices of medium and luxury sweets such as \u201cAl-Belouria \u201d,\u201c Al-Mashkeel \u201d, \u201cKool and Shakour \u201d,\u201c Aish Al-Bulbul \u201d and \u201cBaklava \u201d ranged between 250 and 500 thousand per kilo, which is equivalent to the salary of a Syrian employee in the public sector.\nThe head of the artisanal association for confectionery industry, Bassam Qalaji, attributed this rise in confectionery prices to the government lifting subsidies on oil derivatives, which led to a direct increase in costs by 150%, pointing out that raising the price of electricity by 5 times will lead to an increase in the price of about 650 products.\nQalaji said in a statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan last month that the largest number of confectionery craftsmen emigrated, and their first destination was Algeria followed by Germany.\nIn March last year, the head of the artisanal association for the confectionery industry revealed that 70% of the workshops of the confectionery industry were closed due to the economic crisis and the low demand for sweets and refreshments.\nA severe blow to the economy\nThis gradual disappearance of traditional crafts is a painful blow to the Syrian economy, says economist Younis Karim, \u201cFor decades these crafts have been the largest incubator of Syrian labor, and their contribution to the economy before 2011 ranged from 40 to 50%. \u201d\nThis is what Matanios Habib, a researcher and former Syrian oil minister, said in a research paper entitled \u201cThe private sector in Syria \u201d (2005), when he pointed out that the private industrial sector in Syria tended to invest in crafts for fear of nationalization policies, whether during the era of Syrian-Egyptian unity (1958-1961) or after the revolution of March 8 (1967).\nKarim stresses that the crisis of workers in traditional crafts, such as confectioners and others, dates back to before 2011, specifically to the period between 2007 and 2009, when there was \u201can attempt by the regime to pressure the owners of traditional crafts and crafts by forcing them to pay taxes, and to keep them away from city centers in favor of large investors. \u201d\nYounis Karim believes that the gradual demise of these crafts will have negative effects on the Syrian economy because of their role in \"providing job opportunities beyond those provided by large laboratories and their excellence in ease of operation and achievement, and the ability to spread.\nSource: The Island","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0006.json.gz:67103","uncompressed_offset":286336831,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2024-03-12T15:53:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-03-12T16:08:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477":{"id":"7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f_205807477","text":"A year of hard work to document and preserve the Syrian tangible and intangible heritage locally and internationally\nDamascus-Sana\nThe Syrian heritage, both tangible and intangible, forms an important pillar within the World Heritage system, and is a key factor in strengthening the cultural identity of the Syrian people, building the present and protecting the future.\nDuring 2022, the Ministry of Culture and its concerned institutions, in particular the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums and the Directorate of Intangible Cultural Heritage, focused on organizing a series of events and seminars and signing a series of agreements related to the importance and mechanisms of preserving this heritage in its various components.\nAmong the most important Syrian activities and works related to tangible and intangible heritage during 2022 are:\nDuring the year, Syria held several discussions on the loan of Syrian artifacts damaged during the terrorist war on Syria for restoration and display in the Sultanate of Oman, and signed a joint statement on cooperation to preserve cultural heritage with the People \u2019 s Republic of China.\nSyria participated in the International Forum of the Convention for the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage in the Russian city of Kazan, and the Scientific Conference on Archaeology in the Hungarian capital, and participated in a virtual lecture within the international conference on the protection of the Syrian cultural heritage after the war.\n\u2013 The archaeological missions returned to excavations in 2022, including the joint Syrian-Italian archaeological mission, which began its work for the first season at the archaeological site of Amrit, and the discovery of a funerary burial and some archaeological finds and discoveries dating back to the Roman era in Amrit by the joint excavation team between the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums and the Department of Tartus Antiquities.\n\u2013 The national expertise of the Directorate General of Antiquities worked to expand the work to discover the entire rare archaeological mosaic painting in the city of Rastan, which dates back to the Roman era, and reached a length of 20 meters and a width of 6 meters.\n\u2013 Completion of the restoration work of the Arc de Triomphe in the ancient city of Palmyra, which was destroyed by terrorist organizations in 2015, and the second phase of the restoration project began with the signing of a memorandum of understanding between the Directorate of Antiquities, the Syrian Secretariat and the Institute of the History of Material Culture of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the Russian Federation.\n\u2013 Holding a workshop \u201cRestoring Syrian Heritage and Reviving Local Communities \u201d at Expo 2020 Dubai, in which local, Arab and international bodies specialized in antiquities participated.\n\u2013 In the National Museum in Damascus and in tribute to the lives and sacrifices of about 27 martyrs who rose during the terrorist war on Syria in defense of the Syrian cultural heritage, an exhibition of recovered archaeological treasures 3 entitled (Salute to the martyrs of the General Directorate of Antiquities and Museums) was opened within the days of Syrian culture.\n\u2013 The opening of a painting exhibition entitled \u201cRestoration of Syrian Heritage by Theo Vitit \u2019 s Vision \u201d at the National Museum in Damascus, which is a painting of restoration and excavation works in Syrian archaeological sites, painted by the Dutch artist and archaeologist Theo Vitit in 2018 and 2021, and was presented in the Netherlands to introduce the Western community to what happened to the Syrian cultural heritage.\nIn Damascus Castle, the first national screening of the film Siriacus Section, directed by Olivier Bourgeois, was launched in 2022 in cooperation between the Ministry of Culture, the Directorate General of Antiquities and Museums, and the Syrian Trust for Development. The film, which won more than 17 international awards, talks about the solidarity of a small group of archaeologists and museum curators with the escalation of the terrorist war on Aleppo in 2015. The National Museum of Aleppo.\nThe Directorate of Antiquities, in cooperation with the European Center for Byzantine and Post-Byzantine Monuments and the Department of Antiquities at the University of Damascus, organized a digital exhibition on historical mosaics in Syria, entitled \u201cSyria is still the source of arts \u201d.\n\u2013 The beginning of the year witnessed the return of five Syrian destructive artifacts to the National Museum in Damascus at the initiative of the management of the Naboo Museum in Beirut, and the pieces are various funerary destructive statues from the collections of the Naboo Museum previously purchased from European auction houses.\nThe second leg of the Syrian Antiquities Exhibition, entitled \u201cThe Wonderful Syria \u201d, was opened in Chengdu, Sichuan Province, southwest China, which lasted until May. During this period, special scientific seminars and cultural events were held in connection with the exhibition, in which the Department of Antiquities and Museums participated with 195 important artifacts and collections of Syrian museums.\nIn 2022, the Directorate of Intangible Cultural Heritage has been active in most governorates, focusing on monitoring, studying and documenting the national intangible heritage and preparing the necessary plans to search for, study and inventory the elements of this heritage and include them in the national register, in cooperation with governmental and non-governmental institutions, local communities and international organizations.\nThe Directorate of Heritage organized a workshop on Syrian intangible cultural heritage at Al-Assad National Library, in preparation for the development of a national strategy for intangible cultural heritage in Syria.\n\u2013 The project (Windows 5) was organized, whose musical evenings varied between documentation and promotion of Syrian heritage songs, and many heritage festivals were held in the provinces.\n\u2013 The project of documenting the elements of the Syrian intangible heritage in ancient Homs, implemented by the Ministry of Culture in cooperation with the Syrian Secretariat and civil society, was launched in 2022 to preserve the elements of this heritage, and work continued on the project of documenting the elements of the intangible heritage in Tartus province.\nWithin the framework of the implementation of the plan to preserve the element of the theater of shadow imagination Karkouz and Aiwaz after registration on the list of urgent conservation of the world humanitarian heritage at UNESCO, the Syrian Secretariat for Development continued the third professional training after Damascus and Suwayda, for youth cadres in the city of Aleppo.\nThe Syrian Secretariat for Development has developed the \u201cLiving Heritage \u201d program with the local community in Aleppo governorate, the main axes for the preservation of the Aleppo cod, which was registered on the Representative List of Human Heritage at UNESCO by the end of 2021 with the participation of a group of governmental and civil authorities, artists, musicians, researchers and interested in the Arab, musical and art of cod.\nAt the international level:\nSyria has been elected vice-president of the ninth session of the General Assembly of the States Parties to the 2003 UNESCO Convention for the Safeguarding of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity for a two-year term 2022-2024.\nSyria participated in the UNESCO World Conference on Cultural Policies and Sustainable Development, Mondiacult 2022, in Mexico.\n\u2013 In 2022, a scientific research by the son of the city of Aleppo, Antoine Makdis, related to how to recover from the effects of war through independent cultural production based on intangible cultural heritage won the first place in the competition of the Foundation of Santgrata, specialized in the Italian cultural economy.\n\u2013 An integrated archaeological project in the Baal Shemin Temple in Palmyra has been shortlisted for the third cycle of ICCROM Sharjah Award for the Conservation and Protection of Cultural Heritage in the Arab Region 2020-2022.\nRasha Mahfoudh and Mays Al-Ani\nFollow SANA news on Telegram https: / / t.me / SyrianArabNewsAgency","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0039.json.gz:9803","uncompressed_offset":205807477,"url":"www.sana.sy/?p=1811638","warc_date":"2022-12-31T16:19:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7e46e552-d536-4298-9de6-ae4d30ecb53f>","warc_url":"https://www.sana.sy/?p=1811638"},"created":"2022-12-31T16:34:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":{"id":"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","text":"Art of glassblowing returns again in Aleppo countryside liberated from terrorism\n\nThe town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province in northern Syria has historically been famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen. The war considerably affected this traditional craft inherited from our ancestors, but after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought it back to life. The artisan, Yassin Arab learned the glassblowing craft from his father when he was a child, and after the town was liberated from terrorism, he returned to his small facility, where he worked to restore it and start working again. Arab does not hide his enormous passion for the craft of glassblowing and his belief in the need to preserve this ancient Syrian heritage. Regarding the working mechanism, the artisan explained to SANA that he uses recycled glass, melts it again in the oven at high temperature, and then chooses a specific shape for its manufacture, whether hookah bottles, vases, plates, small jugs, fish houses for decoration, decorated cups and antiques of different sizes. After that, t he piece is blown, rotated and processed by the artisan until it takes its final shape using white and brown colors, and once the manufacturing of the product is finished, it is decorated and colored to give it the required aesthetics. For his part, Hussein Najjar noted that he learned the craft of blowing glass manually since he was young and has been working in this field for 40 years. He added that he is able to make any shape or glass container, using his imagination, and considered that the art of glassblowing is one of the types of plastic arts. Traditional glassblowing is a profession that dates back more than two thousand years (since the time of the Phoenicians) and was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent preservation. Source: Syrian Arab News Agency","url":"https://qatarpress.qa/art-of-glassblowing-returns-again-in-aleppo-countryside-liberated-from-terrorism/"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1052","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1052","narrative_id":"1052"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"Syria's traditional glassblowing is an artisanal craft that has been a significant part of the country's cultural heritage for centuries."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has a rich history, with evidence of glassblowing dating back to the time of the Phoenicians, over two thousand years ago."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"In Damascus, the craft of glassblowing has been passed down from generation to generation, with skilled artisans creating intricate and beautiful pieces using traditional techniques."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The importance of glassblowing in Syria's culture cannot be overstated, as it is considered one of the country's most valuable and iconic traditional crafts."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The craft is not only a source of pride for Syrians but also an important part of the country's economic sector, with many artisans relying on it as a source of income."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Unfortunately, the current status of the craft is precarious, with many artisans struggling to continue their work due to economic decline and lack of support."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"According to recent reports, more than half of the confectionery craftsmen in Syria have stopped producing and switched to other professions due to low demand and insufficient profits."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"This decline has prompted thousands of craftsmen to close their workshops and shops, and many have even migrated to other countries in search of better opportunities."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"As a result, the number of craftsmen practicing traditional glassblowing has significantly decreased, putting the craft at risk of disappearing."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"In recognition of the importance of preserving this traditional craft, UNESCO has listed Syrian glassblowing on the List of Intangible Cultural Heritage in Need of Urgent Safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"This listing is a testament to the craft's cultural significance and the need for urgent action to protect it."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The listing is also a recognition of the efforts of artisans like Yassin Arab, who has worked tirelessly to restore the craft in his town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Arab's dedication to the craft is inspiring, and his work is a testament to the importance of preserving traditional skills and techniques."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The reasons for the decline of traditional glassblowing in Syria are complex and multifaceted."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"One of the main reasons is the lack of support and unequal competition, which has made it difficult for artisans to continue their work."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Additionally, the economic decline in Syria has led to a decrease in demand for traditional crafts, making it difficult for artisans to make a living."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The situation is further exacerbated by the fact that many young people are not interested in learning traditional crafts, preferring instead to pursue more modern and lucrative careers."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, there are still many artisans in Syria who are dedicated to preserving the traditional craft of glassblowing."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Artisans like Hussein Najjar, who has been working in the field for 40 years, are keeping the craft alive through their skill and dedication."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Najjar's ability to create intricate and beautiful pieces using traditional techniques is a testament to the importance of preserving this craft."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"The Russian artist Yuri Lishin, who has participated in many exhibitions in the world, has also recognized the importance of preserving traditional glassblowing techniques."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Syria's traditional glassblowing is a valuable and iconic craft that is in need of urgent safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has a rich history and cultural significance, and its preservation is essential for maintaining Syria's cultural identity."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"While the current status of the craft is precarious, there are still many artisans who are dedicated to preserving it."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"It is essential that efforts are made to support these artisans and to promote the craft, in order to ensure its survival for future generations."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"This can be achieved through initiatives such as training programs, financial grants, and exhibitions, which can help to raise awareness and promote the craft."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the preservation of traditional glassblowing in Syria requires a collective effort from artisans, organizations, and governments, and it is essential that we take action to protect this valuable craft."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"Syria's traditional glassblowing is an artisanal craft that has been a significant part of the country's cultural heritage for centuries."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has a rich history, with evidence of glassblowing dating back to the time of the Phoenicians, over two thousand years ago."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"In Damascus, the craft of glassblowing has been passed down from generation to generation, with skilled artisans creating intricate and beautiful pieces using traditional techniques."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The importance of glassblowing in Syria's culture cannot be overstated, as it is considered one of the country's most valuable and iconic traditional crafts."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The craft is not only a source of pride for Syrians but also an important part of the country's economic sector, with many artisans relying on it as a source of income."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Unfortunately, the current status of the craft is precarious, with many artisans struggling to continue their work due to economic decline and lack of support."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"According to recent reports, more than half of the confectionery craftsmen in Syria have stopped producing and switched to other professions due to low demand and insufficient profits."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"This decline has prompted thousands of craftsmen to close their workshops and shops, and many have even migrated to other countries in search of better opportunities."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"As a result, the number of craftsmen practicing traditional glassblowing has significantly decreased, putting the craft at risk of disappearing."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"In recognition of the importance of preserving this traditional craft, UNESCO has listed Syrian glassblowing on the List of Intangible Cultural Heritage in Need of Urgent Safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"This listing is a testament to the craft's cultural significance and the need for urgent action to protect it."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The listing is also a recognition of the efforts of artisans like Yassin Arab, who has worked tirelessly to restore the craft in his town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Arab's dedication to the craft is inspiring, and his work is a testament to the importance of preserving traditional skills and techniques."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The reasons for the decline of traditional glassblowing in Syria are complex and multifaceted."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"One of the main reasons is the lack of support and unequal competition, which has made it difficult for artisans to continue their work."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"Additionally, the economic decline in Syria has led to a decrease in demand for traditional crafts, making it difficult for artisans to make a living."},{"citations":{"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":1.0},"text":"The situation is further exacerbated by the fact that many young people are not interested in learning traditional crafts, preferring instead to pursue more modern and lucrative careers."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, there are still many artisans in Syria who are dedicated to preserving the traditional craft of glassblowing."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Artisans like Hussein Najjar, who has been working in the field for 40 years, are keeping the craft alive through their skill and dedication."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Najjar's ability to create intricate and beautiful pieces using traditional techniques is a testament to the importance of preserving this craft."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"The Russian artist Yuri Lishin, who has participated in many exhibitions in the world, has also recognized the importance of preserving traditional glassblowing techniques."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Syria's traditional glassblowing is a valuable and iconic craft that is in need of urgent safeguarding."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"The craft has a rich history and cultural significance, and its preservation is essential for maintaining Syria's cultural identity."},{"citations":{"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":1.0},"text":"While the current status of the craft is precarious, there are still many artisans who are dedicated to preserving it."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"It is essential that efforts are made to support these artisans and to promote the craft, in order to ensure its survival for future generations."},{"citations":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":1.0},"text":"This can be achieved through initiatives such as training programs, financial grants, and exhibitions, which can help to raise awareness and promote the craft."},{"citations":{"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the preservation of traditional glassblowing in Syria requires a collective effort from artisans, organizations, and governments, and it is essential that we take action to protect this valuable craft."}],"references":["03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893","2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262","a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831"],"documents":{"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893":{"id":"03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b_1020573893","text":"Exhibition of craft products by Syrian and Russian artists in the public park in Aleppo\nHalab-Sana\nOn the grounds of the public park in the city of Aleppo, the activities of the exhibition of craft products were launched today, with the participation of 20 craftsmen and artists from Syria and the Russian Federation.\nThe exhibition, which is organized by the Ministry of Industry in cooperation with the Russian Cultural Center in Damascus, the Federation of Artisans in Aleppo, and the Association of the Syrian Professional Center, includes a collection of heritage and artistic works, paintings of Ajami thread, ornaments and handicrafts of wool, orphans, leather, rugs, carpets, bamboo and silver.\nAccording to the President of the Union of Artisans in Aleppo, Mohammed Hossam Hallak, in a statement to SANA correspondent, the exhibition aims to highlight the traditional handicrafts and crafts and folklore professions to revive them by training the younger generations and mastering their industry to preserve them.\nMustafa al-Nu, President of the Syrian Professional Center Association, pointed out that the association worked to attract professionals and handicrafts, and provided them with financial grants to encourage them to continue their work, to preserve these crafts from extinction, in addition to training young people wishing to learn these crafts and develop them to suit the times.\nThe Russian artist Yuri Lishin, famous for the manufacture of blowing on glass, talked about his professionalism for more than 54 years, and his participation in many exhibitions in the world, indicating that his visit to Syria to learn about the glass industry, and participate in workshops on the manufacture of hand glass in Syria.\nA number of participants noted the importance of the exhibition, which allows for the marketing of their products, where Zakaria Sultan, who works in the craft of silver and peat breaking, explained that he participates with silver and copper products and accessories made by hand in various forms for swimming pools, steadfastness, image cadres and chandeliers, in addition to grafting copper on wood, calling for providing the necessary support to maintain this profession.\nThe craftsman Ayman Saeed presented the results of the drawing on wood, which is called Ajami art, and stated that he learned to make this art and plant motifs and painting in Arabic calligraphy in the association, and became a trainer contributing to the revival of heritage, and that the exhibition is an important opportunity to market his products.\nArtist Tala Naravyan participated in watercolor, oil and other paintings painted with pencils and charcoal, talking about the Armenian and Arab heritage and the neighborhoods of Aleppo and its citadel, pointing out that she participates to introduce people to the components of the rich Syrian heritage through painting because it constitutes the language of the world.\nSamira Misto, who works in the craft of making the ancient traditional macrame, using colored threads and ropes to decorate the Koran, mirrors, clothes and jewelry, pointed out that she is working to develop this profession by adding beads and tree trunks to revive and preserve it.\nQusay Razzouk\nFollow SANA news on Telegram https: / / t.me / SyrianArabNewsAgency\nLook, too.\nAleppo Public Park","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0034.json.gz:33792","uncompressed_offset":1020573893,"url":"www.sana.sy/?p=1787673","warc_date":"2022-11-19T14:59:53.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:03e27b3c-b23e-41f3-9e54-cfcd0927063b>","warc_url":"https://www.sana.sy/?p=1787673"},"created":"2022-11-19T16:06:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831":{"id":"a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed_286336831","text":"What is the reality of traditional and traditional professions in Syria?\nDAMASCUS \u2013 The traditional professions and crafts in Syria were not immune to the repercussions of the war. In light of the difficult economic and security conditions that the country has been witnessing for more than a decade, these professions are suffering from an unprecedented decline related to production and market conditions, which makes them today threatened with extinction.\nThe head of the Union of Craftsmen in the province of Latakia Jihad Pro, in a recent statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan, the decline of the production of handicrafts and handicrafts of various kinds by 50% within the province, considering the high costs of production inputs and increased income taxes as direct reasons for this decline.\nBassam Qalaji, head of the artisanal association for confectionery in Damascus, told the local newspaper Global last month that more than half of the confectionery craftsmen had stopped producing and switched to other professions due to low demand and insufficient profits.\nSuccessive statements reveal the reality of Syrian traditional and traditional crafts, which are suffering under the weight of the economic decline that the country is suffering from.\nThis situation has prompted thousands of craftsmen to close their workshops and shops and switch to other jobs, or migrate and move their work abroad, amid the real threat of the disappearance of many traditional traditional traditional professions and handicrafts, which constitute vital sectors of the economic sector in the country and an integral part of its cultural identity.\nWhat are the main reasons for this decline?\nHow does it affect the economic life of the country?\nLack of support and unequal competition\nAnton, a 42-year-old Damascene craftsman and former owner of a mosaic workshop in rural Damascus, says his struggle for years to keep his workshop open, producing and selling enough to pay its workers has been futile.\nHe adds in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"I tried hard to maintain the workshop and its workers for as long as possible, but the constant high prices of wood (local and imported) in an inappropriate manner, the long interruption of electricity (16-18 hours a day), and the low demand for mosaic in the domestic and foreign market, all factors forced me to lay off workers, and later to close the workshop after months, during which I received only two orders.\"\nIn addition to these factors, Anton attributed the low demand for \"original\" mosaics and other handicrafts and heritage artifacts (copperware, damask, antika, textiles) to:\nThe reality of the market at the moment in the absence of tourists.\n\u2022 The decline of external demand for the commodity as a result of the interruption of trade relations with foreign markets.\n\u2022 Migration of brokers and traders and thus reduced export.\n\u2022 Unequal competition.\nWith heritage products becoming \u201cmore than luxury \u201d for Syrians suffering from poor purchasing power (average monthly salaries of about $20), and the lack of support for craftsmen and awareness of the importance and authenticity of these products by trade unions and government agencies, Syria \u2019 s craftsmen face major challenges to continue their craft.\nAlthough there are no accurate figures on the number of craftsmen who have been driven by working conditions to emigrate outside the country, the head of the Damascus Craftsmen \u2019 s Union, Ali Qarmashti, revealed in an interview with the local news website Click News last year that the percentage of Damascene craftsmen migrating has become very high, especially among young people.\nRepellent economic and social policies\nIn addition to the direct economic factors that led to the decline of traditional crafts during the past few years, represented by the high prices of raw materials, the poor reality of services, and the decline of the sale and purchase movement, there were indirect factors that affected these crafts.\nSyrian economist Younis Karim believes that the artisan crisis began in 2008 after being subjected to great pressures due to the change of the general economic orientation in the country.\nHe said in an interview with Al Jazeera Net: \"Since 2008, the authorities have put their hands on the spread of these industries due to the importance of their geographical location, and work to change their features in favor of wealthy investors, or provide them as donations to countries that Damascus seeks to establish bilateral relations with.\"\nAccording to the expert, the reality of the work of traditional crafts after 2011 became more complex and difficult with \"the continued adoption of economic and social policies by the regime that restrict the owners of these crafts, exclude them from support, take their places of deployment, in addition to the cessation of exhibitions and the difficulty of participating in external events because of the political positions of the regime.\nKarim explains that the family and social disintegration suffered by Syrians as a result of large-scale migration during the last decade was an added reason for the decline of these crafts, which \u201crelied on inheritance between generations of the same family as a tradition followed by Syrian craftsmen long ago. \u201d\nKilo to Piece and Pieces\nIt seems that some traditional crafts and crafts are in the same trench with traditional crafts in their war against extinction, where the owners of many traditional crafts are no less original than those of heritage, especially the confectioners from the high costs of raw materials in production, high costs of energy stands, and successive losses due to the reluctance of citizens to buy expensive Arabic sweets.\nSuhaib, 55, owner of a sweets shop in the Jazmatiya area of Damascus, told Al Jazeera Net: \"Days pass without selling a total of a kilo of various items, and two years ago the stagnation of goods in the shop became a familiar phenomenon to us, and had it not been for the holiday seasons, and some occasions and weddings held here and there, we would have closed long ago.\"\nAl-Halwani Al-Damascene adds in an interview with Al-Jazeera Net: \"Our profits, and the profits of most of the shops of Halwanis in Damascus, have decreased by a large percentage since the beginning of the economic crisis in the country.\"\nAl-Halwani pointed out that the price of a kilo of some varieties of Arabic sweets has exceeded 400 thousand pounds recently, adding: \"Which is not able for Syrians to buy, so we have become selling methods in which we rely on small quantities, so we sell baklava, crystal, shaped, asian, brominated and other items in ounces, grain (piece) and two grains to keep the sales movement, and do not stop customers from our shop.\"\nAs for the reasons why sweets in Damascus stopped working and many of them emigrated outside the country, Al-Halwani said: \u201cMany reasons start from the large annual taxes that are inconsistent with high operating costs and low profits, in addition to the high prices of commercial electricity and fuel needed to operate shops and laboratories, the huge increase in the prices of raw materials, the high wages of workers, and the reluctance of customers to buy these sweets except on occasions. \u201d\nHigh prices\nPrices of food, nuts and other components of Arabic sweets have risen by varying rates recently, as the price of a kilo of animal margarine reached 150 thousand pounds ($equivalent to about 2511 pounds), while the price of a kilo of pistachio love rose to 300 thousand, and the price of a kilo of walnuts to 120 thousand.\nThe prices of popular sweets such as Al-Barazek and Al-Ma \u2019 amoul in Damascus markets, by the holy month of Ramadan, were between 100 and 130 thousand pounds per kilo, while the prices of medium and luxury sweets such as \u201cAl-Belouria \u201d,\u201c Al-Mashkeel \u201d, \u201cKool and Shakour \u201d,\u201c Aish Al-Bulbul \u201d and \u201cBaklava \u201d ranged between 250 and 500 thousand per kilo, which is equivalent to the salary of a Syrian employee in the public sector.\nThe head of the artisanal association for confectionery industry, Bassam Qalaji, attributed this rise in confectionery prices to the government lifting subsidies on oil derivatives, which led to a direct increase in costs by 150%, pointing out that raising the price of electricity by 5 times will lead to an increase in the price of about 650 products.\nQalaji said in a statement to the local newspaper Al-Watan last month that the largest number of confectionery craftsmen emigrated, and their first destination was Algeria followed by Germany.\nIn March last year, the head of the artisanal association for the confectionery industry revealed that 70% of the workshops of the confectionery industry were closed due to the economic crisis and the low demand for sweets and refreshments.\nA severe blow to the economy\nThis gradual disappearance of traditional crafts is a painful blow to the Syrian economy, says economist Younis Karim, \u201cFor decades these crafts have been the largest incubator of Syrian labor, and their contribution to the economy before 2011 ranged from 40 to 50%. \u201d\nThis is what Matanios Habib, a researcher and former Syrian oil minister, said in a research paper entitled \u201cThe private sector in Syria \u201d (2005), when he pointed out that the private industrial sector in Syria tended to invest in crafts for fear of nationalization policies, whether during the era of Syrian-Egyptian unity (1958-1961) or after the revolution of March 8 (1967).\nKarim stresses that the crisis of workers in traditional crafts, such as confectioners and others, dates back to before 2011, specifically to the period between 2007 and 2009, when there was \u201can attempt by the regime to pressure the owners of traditional crafts and crafts by forcing them to pay taxes, and to keep them away from city centers in favor of large investors. \u201d\nYounis Karim believes that the gradual demise of these crafts will have negative effects on the Syrian economy because of their role in \"providing job opportunities beyond those provided by large laboratories and their excellence in ease of operation and achievement, and the ability to spread.\nSource: The Island","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0006.json.gz:67103","uncompressed_offset":286336831,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2024-03-12T15:53:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a6ed48a1-ed5f-494b-9ab5-4af27c7035ed>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/ebusiness/2024/3/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9?traffic_source=rss"},"created":"2024-03-12T16:08:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807":{"id":"2a417b11-2e84-4732-8f7e-117ba083ce22_938338807","text":"Art of glassblowing returns again in Aleppo countryside liberated from terrorism\n\nThe town of Urem Al-Kubra in Aleppo province in northern Syria has historically been famous for its skilled glassblowing craftsmen. The war considerably affected this traditional craft inherited from our ancestors, but after the liberation of the city from terrorism, some artisans have brought it back to life. The artisan, Yassin Arab learned the glassblowing craft from his father when he was a child, and after the town was liberated from terrorism, he returned to his small facility, where he worked to restore it and start working again. Arab does not hide his enormous passion for the craft of glassblowing and his belief in the need to preserve this ancient Syrian heritage. Regarding the working mechanism, the artisan explained to SANA that he uses recycled glass, melts it again in the oven at high temperature, and then chooses a specific shape for its manufacture, whether hookah bottles, vases, plates, small jugs, fish houses for decoration, decorated cups and antiques of different sizes. After that, t he piece is blown, rotated and processed by the artisan until it takes its final shape using white and brown colors, and once the manufacturing of the product is finished, it is decorated and colored to give it the required aesthetics. For his part, Hussein Najjar noted that he learned the craft of blowing glass manually since he was young and has been working in this field for 40 years. He added that he is able to make any shape or glass container, using his imagination, and considered that the art of glassblowing is one of the types of plastic arts. Traditional glassblowing is a profession that dates back more than two thousand years (since the time of the Phoenicians) and was included in December 2023 by UNESCO on the list of intangible cultural heritage of humanity that needs urgent preservation. Source: Syrian Arab News Agency","url":"https://qatarpress.qa/art-of-glassblowing-returns-again-in-aleppo-countryside-liberated-from-terrorism/"},"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262":{"id":"59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422_505232262","text":"Samples of the Damascene Literary Heritage Attend an Exhibition and Seminar in the Culture of Infection\nDamascus-Sana\nIn the exhibition \u201cHeritage Crafts are Inherited by the Fragrance of History \u201d hosted by the Adawi Cultural Center, the artworks varied between glass decoration, Damascene brocade and various handicrafts.\nThe exhibition was followed by an introductory seminar on these arts for the Sheikhs of Carr and craftsmen specialized in these professions under the supervision of the handicraft trainer Rowaa Yousef.\nYoussef Lassana explained that the exhibition was dedicated to traditional professions in general and handicrafts, especially such as brocade, painting on glass, Islamic motifs and handicrafts to maintain their continuity and importance.\nMohammed Bassam Rayhan Sheikh Al-Karar in painting on glass and decoration spoke in his intervention about the history of this craft, its forms, fields of work and materials used in it, pointing out that the glass, which was the first to be invented by the Phoenicians, evolved in Damascus throughout history and was painted on the mishkat and lanterns using oxides and various materials, thermal colors, acrlik and others.\nThe Damascene brocade craftsman Mohammed Rankous explained in his intervention that this cloth is made of natural silk and golden reed yarns and attributed to Damascus because it took its character, heritage and environment, such as the painting of Omar Khayyam, the Levantine Rose, grape clusters, the lover and the beloved, and the octagonal geometric drawings, pointing out that this craft entered the cultures of different civilizations.\nNasruddin Mohammed is a graduate of applied arts and a drawing teacher who participated in paintings for his students from children and boys. In his intervention, he explained the history of the Damascene plant decoration, its methods, types and schools such as Andalusian, Persian and Damascene, and its differences in decoration, diggings, mirrors and miniatures, indicating that its history dates back to the Andalusian civilization, which was its main creativity in palaces and buildings.\nMohammed Sabha is a bridal craftsman who participated in a group of decorative glass works for brides and explained that he has completed a model of a waterfall flowing from an electric mountain that is operated by hand from cardboard, wood and cork inspired by his ideas.\nRana Ayoub participated in a group of works of three-dimensional models and miniatures of the Levant environment. She explained that she chose this environment because she grew up and lived in it and adored it. It is necessary to inform future generations of their heritage and history, pointing out that she works with cork, wood, natural materials, gypsum, ceramic paste and others.\nBilal Ahmed","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0026.json.gz:34512","uncompressed_offset":505232262,"url":"www.sana.sy/?p=1475724","warc_date":"2021-09-13T18:33:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:59b71ca2-4087-4e93-9b19-beb1564fe422>","warc_url":"https://www.sana.sy/?p=1475724"},"created":"2021-09-13T19:00:59.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1053","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1053","narrative_id":"1053"},"responses":[{"citations":{"16a00b71-6e6c-4015-b1b2-d5437d613bb8_463765569":1.0},"text":"The global avocado consumption has increased significantly in recent years, with New Zealanders buying over 80 million avocados last season, a record high."},{"citations":{"fd214626-2761-443a-aee5-3562ee536d85_342391363":1.0},"text":"This rising demand has led to economic benefits for some countries, such as increased exports and revenue, with European avocado imports rising by 23% compared to the same week in 2023."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"However, this increased demand has also had negative environmental impacts, such as deforestation, soil erosion, and chemical contamination of water sources, particularly in Mexico, where avocado cultivation has depleted local water supplies."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"In addition, the social effects on local farming communities have been significant, with land grabbing, community displacement, labor exploitation, and the displacement of indigenous communities."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"The avocado industry has become a major player in the global market, with countries like Mexico producing around 80% of the world's avocados, and other countries like Peru and Chile also being major producers."},{"citations":{"114d1622-c9c5-4614-b132-9c9189790987_442554566":1.0},"text":"The production of avocados requires huge amounts of water, with annual per capita consumption being around seven kilograms per person in Mexico, where avocado is a staple in the cuisine."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"To mitigate the negative impacts of the avocado industry, governments and companies can promote sustainable farming practices, reduce water use, and provide financial incentives to farmers."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"Overall, the rising demand for avocados has had both positive and negative impacts on the countries that produce them, and it is essential to address the environmental and social concerns associated with the industry."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"16a00b71-6e6c-4015-b1b2-d5437d613bb8_463765569":1.0},"text":"The global avocado consumption has increased significantly in recent years, with New Zealanders buying over 80 million avocados last season, a record high."},{"citations":{"fd214626-2761-443a-aee5-3562ee536d85_342391363":1.0},"text":"This rising demand has led to economic benefits for some countries, such as increased exports and revenue, with European avocado imports rising by 23% compared to the same week in 2023."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"However, this increased demand has also had negative environmental impacts, such as deforestation, soil erosion, and chemical contamination of water sources, particularly in Mexico, where avocado cultivation has depleted local water supplies."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"In addition, the social effects on local farming communities have been significant, with land grabbing, community displacement, labor exploitation, and the displacement of indigenous communities."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"The avocado industry has become a major player in the global market, with countries like Mexico producing around 80% of the world's avocados, and other countries like Peru and Chile also being major producers."},{"citations":{"114d1622-c9c5-4614-b132-9c9189790987_442554566":1.0},"text":"The production of avocados requires huge amounts of water, with annual per capita consumption being around seven kilograms per person in Mexico, where avocado is a staple in the cuisine."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"To mitigate the negative impacts of the avocado industry, governments and companies can promote sustainable farming practices, reduce water use, and provide financial incentives to farmers."},{"citations":{"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":1.0},"text":"Overall, the rising demand for avocados has had both positive and negative impacts on the countries that produce them, and it is essential to address the environmental and social concerns associated with the industry."}],"references":["9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657","114d1622-c9c5-4614-b132-9c9189790987_442554566","16a00b71-6e6c-4015-b1b2-d5437d613bb8_463765569","fd214626-2761-443a-aee5-3562ee536d85_342391363"],"documents":{"fd214626-2761-443a-aee5-3562ee536d85_342391363":{"id":"fd214626-2761-443a-aee5-3562ee536d85_342391363","text":"Avocado imports rise in Europe, decline in China\n\nMore News Top Stories\n\nSpecialized intelligence company Avobook's week 29 report noted interesting movements in the global avocado market.\n\nEuropean avocado imports saw a 23% rise compared to the same week in 2023. Interestingly, the report points out that this has not induced a price reduction.\n\n. The interesting thing, the report points out, is that this has not induced a price reduction.\u00a0\n\nSomething different can be observed in China, where arrivals from Peru have decreased by more than half year-on-year. Peruvian supplies usually dominate the market at this time of the year.\n\nIn the case of the United States, Avobook explains that Mexican supplies account for 40% of the market, while California's account for 28%, and Peru's, 24%. The scenario in the U.S. market shows slightly lower prices than the previous week in all grades.\n\nReview the full report here.\n\n\nThe Global Avocado Summit, organized by the Chilean Avocado Committee and the Yentzen Group, will be held on November 21 at the Casino Monticello event center in Chile.\n\nSubscribe to our newsletter","url":"https://www.freshfruitportal.com/news/2024/07/24/avocado-imports-rise-in-europe-decline-in-china/"},"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657":{"id":"9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4_195587657","text":"Avocado: Between Environmental Impacts and Global Market Controllers\nIn the Mexican state of Michoac\u00e1n, which produces about 80% of the world \u2019 s avocado, avocado cultivation has depleted local water supplies and caused severe environmental damage, with studies showing that avocado cultivation has led to deforestation, soil erosion and chemical contamination of water sources.\n(Getty)\nIn recent years, the avocado industry has become a staple in many diets around the world, and its popularity has increased greatly due to the multiple health benefits.\nHowever, the demand for this fruit has led to harmful environmental effects and the emergence of a mafia that controls the production and distribution of avocados in some countries.\nA Chilean study published recently said that avocado cultivation has caused severe water shortages, as well as in Peru, where large farmers have dominated the avocado market since the 1990s, where cultivation requires huge amounts of water, the production of one kilogram of avocado, consumes about 1,000 liters of water, much more than other crops such as tomatoes or oranges.\nAccording to a report by the Water Footprint Network, the production of one kilogram of tomatoes requires about 300 liters of water, and the high water use of avocado production has led to water scarcity and depletion of aquifers in some areas.\nIn the Mexican state of Michoac\u00e1n, which produces about 80% of the world \u2019 s avocado, avocado cultivation has depleted local water supplies and caused severe environmental damage, with studies showing that avocado cultivation has led to deforestation, soil erosion and chemical contamination of water sources.\nAccording to the report, moving avocados from the production site to the market also has a significant impact on the climate, as avocados are grown mainly in developing countries, and are exported to developed countries such as the United States, Europe and Japan, and the transport of avocados over long distances contributes to greenhouse gas emissions harmful to the environment. Approximately 5.4 kg of carbon dioxide emissions per kg of avocado.\nAvocado production has also led to the emergence of a mafia that controls the production and distribution of avocados in some countries, where the avocado mafia operates mainly in Mexico, where it controls the production and export of avocados, and this mafia, according to media reports, consists of criminal organizations that use violence and intimidation to control the production and distribution of avocados, and often extort money from farmers. The avocado mafia uses violence to eliminate competitors and dominate the export market, as studies have shown that these gangs are responsible for deforestation, land grabbing and violence against indigenous communities in Mexico.\nAccording to dozens of studies published in recent years, avocado cultivation also has negative effects on local communities. In some areas, demand for avocados has led to land grabbing, community displacement, labor exploitation, and avocado cultivation in the Mexican state of Michoac\u00e1n has led to the displacement of indigenous communities and the exploitation of often paid migrant workers. Some studies have shown that the expansion of avocado cultivation has displaced traditional crops, leading to food insecurity and loss of biodiversity.\nAccording to the study, governments around the world can take various measures to mitigate the impact of this agriculture on the climate, and one way is to promote sustainable avocado farming practices that reduce water use and reduce the use of chemicals. Protect the environment, provide financial incentives to farmers and enact laws that will deter illegal and criminal practices in these countries.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0012.json.gz:13665","uncompressed_offset":195587657,"url":"www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/04/24/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%81%D9%88%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A3%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%83%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-04-24T16:35:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9f7babf6-335c-4686-b3fe-7602641d29a4>","warc_url":"https://www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8-48/2023/04/24/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%81%D9%88%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A3%D8%AB%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%83%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-04-24T16:43:27.000Z","lang":"eng"},"114d1622-c9c5-4614-b132-9c9189790987_442554566":{"id":"114d1622-c9c5-4614-b132-9c9189790987_442554566","text":"Mexican avocado production to fall in 2021-22 - FreshFruitPortal.com\n\nMexican avocado production to fall in 2021-22\n\nMexican avocado production is forecast to fall by eight percent year-on-year in the 2021-22 season, according to a USDA GAIN report.\n\nThe country is expected to produce 2.33 million metric tons (MMT) between July 2021 and June 2022, following a record volume year in the previous season.\n\n\"Growers state that they are expecting needed tree recovery after record productivity and production (especially in Michoac\u00e1n) in the MY 2020/21 season,\" the report said.\n\n\"Additionally, insufficient rainfall and high temperatures are likely to reduce production and yields in non-Michoacan producing states.\"\n\nMexico is forecasted to export 1.33 MMT in 2021-22, eight percent lower than the previous season, on lower production. Exports to the U.S. are forecasted at 1.04 MMT.\n\nMichoac\u00e1n, the only state with phytosanitary approvals to export to the U.S. typically exports approximately 85 percent of production.\n\nAccording to the USDA, profit margins for export to the U.S. are typically more than 50 percent higher than supplies sold to the domestic market. Michoac\u00e1n also exported 22 percent greater volumes in 2020/21 than the previous MY to non-U.S. markets, on increased production.\u00a0Canada, Japan, and Spain were the main destinations.\n\nInternational demand for avocados from Mexico continues to increase, and producers without access to the U.S. market continue to seek international markets with higher profitability than the domestic market. Jalisco exported 26 percent more volume than the previous marketing year in 2020/21, mainly to Japan, Canada, France and Spain.\n\nPlanted and harvested areas are forecasted at 227,126 hectares (ha) and 225,910 ha respectively, with a national yield of 10.30 metric tons per hectare (MT/ha).\n\nHarvest reaches peak from October to February, with average supply from March to May, and low season from June to September.\n\nAnnual per capita consumption is seven kilograms (approximately 15 pounds) per person. While a staple in Mexican cuisine, avocado consumption has not grown in recent years because of high prices driven by increased international demand.\n\nSubscribe to our newsletter","url":"https://www.freshfruitportal.com/news/2021/10/15/mexican-avocado-production-to-fall-in-2021-22/"},"16a00b71-6e6c-4015-b1b2-d5437d613bb8_463765569":{"id":"16a00b71-6e6c-4015-b1b2-d5437d613bb8_463765569","text":"Smashing news: Early season avocados just 80 cents each\n\nForks at the ready, avo fans \u2013 with the harvest just beginning, the fruit is already going cheap.\n\nA scan of supermarket prices on Tuesday revealed avocados, harvested from August to February, were already selling for as little as 80 cents a pop.\n\nA Countdown spokesperson said grower investment over the last couple of years meant it had a good supply of New Zealand-grown fruit.\n\n\u201cOver the last year, avocado sales have increased by more than 25%,\u201d they said.\n\nREAD MORE:\n* Coronavirus: Kiwis urged to eat more avocado after industry takes Covid-19 hit\n* How many others squeezed that avocado you just bought (and squeezed)?\n* Stolen avocados likely being sold at roadside stalls\n\nFoodstuffs spokesperson Emma Wooster\u200b said more than 31 million avocados were sold in its New World, Pak \u2018n Save and Four Square stores last year.\n\n\u201cWe expect to see great value and availability on avocados continue as crops grow larger \u2013 great news as we know New Zealanders love some avo on their morning toast,\u201d Wooster said.\n\nNZ Avocado chief executive Jen Scoular\u200b said New Zealanders bought more than 80 million avocados last season, which was \u201ca record, and a great one.\u201d\n\n\u201cWith increased prices for fruit and vegetables, and our new season crop available, it\u2019s a great time for Kiwis to grab an extra couple of avocados in their weekly shopping and try avocados in new ways.\u201d\n\nBut the bargain-basement prices come at a cost to avocado growers, who have already had a tough couple of years.\n\nRepeated Covid-19 lockdowns, shipping problems and changing shopping habits had all impacted on growers\u2019 ability to shift their produce.\n\nOn top of that, increased production in Australia, usually New Zealand\u2019s biggest export market, resulted in an \u201cavalanche\u201d of avocados there last year.\n\nThe oversupply led to prices hitting a 15-year low of $1 each and a 76% slump in New Zealand\u2019s exports across the Tasman.\n\nScoular said New Zealand produced about 1.5% of global avocado supply, and she believed demand in Asia could be \u201cincreased significantly with good investment in that market development.\u201d","url":"https://www.stuff.co.nz/business/129584353/smashing-news-early-season-avocados-just-80-cents-each"}}}
