 a must-have for fans and collectors alike."},{"citations":{"4439e590-c34a-43da-8231-bac806e2921a_797916345":1.0},"text":"As the popularity of Labubu continues to grow, it will be interesting to see how the character and brand evolve, and what new releases and limited editions will be made available to fans."}],"references":["e28eb68f-8751-4971-92ce-84a78c57f3d3_641584784","4439e590-c34a-43da-8231-bac806e2921a_797916345","d7ca8fc0-d7dc-4230-95fb-232096ab8873_656831105","b91c452e-b101-470e-897c-83576ea59eee_915671609","066e7b02-52e8-480d-84a5-4c6a4a4bdc01_346631047"],"documents":{"d7ca8fc0-d7dc-4230-95fb-232096ab8873_656831105":{"id":"d7ca8fc0-d7dc-4230-95fb-232096ab8873_656831105","text":"\u3010 Printing \u3011\n\u3010 Page 1, Page 2, Page 3, Page 4 \u3011\nBubble Mart Helps China and Thailand Trend Cultural Exchange\nRelated LINKS http: / / www.CRNT.com 2024-07-02 14: 42: 58\nLABUBU made a major appearance in Bangkok, Thailand, and was awarded the title of \u201cMagic Thailand Experience Officer \u201d. (Photo: China ASEAN Report)\nBeijing, July 2 / According to the \"China ASEAN Report\" reported, \"LABUBU, LABUBU, LABUBU...\" July 1 afternoon, Bangkok Suvarnabhumi Airport crowd, wearing white LABUBU t-shirt Thai fans shouted enthusiastically, Bubble Mart star friend LABUBU took a lovely step forward. They interact with each other passionately.\nLABUBU \"The Essence\" made a blockbuster appearance in Bangkok, Thailand, and the scene and treatment of LABUBU airport pickup is comparable to that of a red star.\nSurprisingly, the Thai authorities held a grand welcome ceremony for LABUBU and awarded LABUBU the honorary title of \u201cAmazing Thai Experience Officer \u201d.\nThailand \u2019 s Minister of Tourism and Sports, Themsa Pompani, Thailand \u2019 s National Tourism Authority, Thapani Khithaputhi, Counsellor, Press and Public Diplomacy Office, Embassy of the People \u2019 s Republic of China in the Kingdom of Thailand, Lieutenant-General Sahela Phiang, Director of Suvarnabhumi Airport, Chen Xiaoyun, Vice President of Puma International Group, and Qian Daizhe, Vice President of Where to Go Travel & Vacation Business Department, attended the welcoming ceremony.\nThis is also the first time that Thailand has officially given such a high-level title to a pop-up IP image, and it is understood that the new \u201cMagic Thailand Experience Officer \u201d LABUBU will embark on a week-long\u201c Adventure Thailand \u201d tour to deeply experience the local culture and interact with fans at the opening of the Bubble Mart IP theme store.\n\u3010 Page 1, Page 2, Page 3, Page 4 \u3011\n\u3010 Printing \u3011\nRelated News:","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0017.json.gz:10473","uncompressed_offset":656831105,"url":"hk.crntt.com/doc/1069/4/8/9/106948988.html?coluid=7&docid=106948988&kindid=0&mdate=0702144258","warc_date":"2024-07-02T09:29:07.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d7ca8fc0-d7dc-4230-95fb-232096ab8873>","warc_url":"https://hk.crntt.com/doc/1069/4/8/9/106948988.html?coluid=7&kindid=0&docid=106948988&mdate=0702144258"},"created":"2024-07-02T10:08:01.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b91c452e-b101-470e-897c-83576ea59eee_915671609":{"id":"b91c452e-b101-470e-897c-83576ea59eee_915671609","text":"7 social media challenges of the year [Pulse Picks 2022]\n\nOur compilation of 2022\u2019s finest social media challenges.\n\n2022 has been another year of making memories on social media, following trends and hopping on the hottest challenges available. This year, we continued from where 2020\u2019s #DontRushChallenge and 2021\u2019s #SilhoutteChallenge stopped. Nigerian songs reigned supreme on TikTok both locally and globally, and that is reflected in the list below, where six of seven challenges were influenced by Afrobeat songs. Even the last is inspired by a Nigerian impression of a non-Nigerian song.\n\nTikTok NG\u2019s #PreciousChallenge was born from a caricature of Duncan Laurence and Fletcher\u2019s 2020 song, \u201cArcade.\u201d\n\nAfter fast-rising TikToker, Bada Agnes, recreated the song in her famous, overdramatic Igbo accent, a producer named Precious, mixed and mastered the sound, and TikTokers gleefully hijacked it. It became the soundtrack to the #PreciousChallenge, which was essentially recreating relatable Nigerian moments of people taking an L in one form or the other.\n\nOne of the most distinguishable this year, The #KulosaChallenge and its variant, #KulosaDanceChallenge became a thing after Oxlade performed his song \u201cKulosa,\u201d at COLORS Studios. The media company posted the video on YouTube, it somehow got on TikTok and the rest is a massive success story that Oxlade would undoubtedly be grateful for.\n\nTikTokers adopted the song and recorded themselves recreating all of Oxlade\u2019s moves in the COLORS Studios performance. Others chose to fit captivating dance routines into their own version of the challenge. All in all, it was a challenge well accepted on TikTok and of course transplanted to other social media channels where they were equally well received across the globe. Little wonder Oxlade emerged most Googled artiste in Nigeria, 2022.\n\n\u2018Won Da Mo\u2019 is a song off MAVIN\u2019s 10th-year-anniversary album, \u201cChapter X.\u201d The song features an ensemble cast of Rema, LadiPoe, Johnny Drille, Ayra Starr, Bayanni, Boy Spyce, Crayon and Magixx. So how did it become a viral social media trend of 2022?\n\nWell, TikTokers fell in love with Rema\u2019s verse on the song and decided to dramatise it in their own unique ways. Once it started, it caught on like an Australian wildfire.\n\nLike others, this challenge is propped up by a [global] smash hit. This time, it\u2019s Burna Boy\u2019s outrageously successful song, Last Last. Although it is a recognised heartbreak track, the TikTok challenge that coopted it is more of a fashion, swag, and style concept, which sees people create epic transitions from basic to badass versions of themselves.\n\nThe challenge uses a refixed version of the original Burna song, one which has a suspenseful pause before the line: \u2018I need igbo and shayo.\u2019 That pause is what ushers in the cleaned-up version of the creator with a bad new look, enhanced of course, by a mouthful of actual [igbo] smoke.\n\nCrayon\u2019s song, \u2018Ijo [Laba Laba]\u2019 and the dance that accompanied it became a thing earlier in the year as TikTokers fell hard in love and went to town with the #IjoLabalabaChallenge. See for yourself\n\nAnother MAVINS song, another TikTok challenge. Ayra Star is the one giving us this time around, with her big tune, Rush, creating the #RushDanceChallenge which you may or may not have seen. No long talk, see below:\n\nKizz Daniel\u2019s \u2018Cough\u2019 is one of the catchiest songs of this year and rightfully got the attention of TikTok where its specialized dance routine held people spellbound. It\u2019s literally one of the happiest compilations of people enjoying life and living in the moment.\n\nWhile we give a special shout-out to Johnny Drille\u2019s #HowAreYouMyFriendChallenge, there\u2019s no better way to round up our 2022 list of social media challenges than with Kizz Daniel\u2019s syrupy song and the exciting dance challenge it gave us online and offline.\n\nEyewitness? Submit your stories now via social or:\n\nEmail: eyewitness@pulse.ng\n\nRecommended articles\n\n7 social media challenges of the year [Pulse Picks 2022]\n\nThe Balvenie celebrates exceptional craftsmanship in Nollywood\n\nBasketmouth announces the end of his 12-year marriage\n\nRegina Daniels pens affectionate birthday message for husband's 62nd birthday\n\nTop 10 Songs of 2022 [Pulse Picks]\n\nFast-rising Ibadan comedian Peteru passes away\n\nElozonam drops debut EP, 'Love & Everything In Between'\n\nYouTube partners with 8th AFRIMA, reiterates support for African Music and Creative Economy\n\nAfrica Magic set to celebrate 'Tinsel' milestone with new documentary","url":"https://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/music/pulse-picks-2022-7-social-media-challenges-of-the-year/s1ltwtz"},"066e7b02-52e8-480d-84a5-4c6a4a4bdc01_346631047":{"id":"066e7b02-52e8-480d-84a5-4c6a4a4bdc01_346631047","text":"Advertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nYashraj Mukhate\u2019s Shafiq Meme recreation turns into music goes viral on internet\n\nAdvertisement\n  \u2022 The popular Indian YouTuber Yashraj Mukhate used his music to recreate of the meme.\n  \u2022 He wrote \u201cBadtameez Shafiq\u201d as the caption for the video.\n  \u2022 Fans reacted hilariously.\nAdvertisement\n\nPakistan is known around the world for its viral memes, such as \u201cAnday Wala Burger,\u201d \u201cEye to Eye,\u201d and Chand Nawab\u2019s style of reporting. After social media grew and musical apps like Tiktok came out, Pakistanis made classic and funny memes that people all over the world liked. The \u201cShafiq Meme\u201d got a lot of views and was used by a lot of well-known actors in Pakistan.\n\nThe popular Indian YouTuber Yashraj Mukhate used his music to make a new version of the meme, and it turned out to be a very funny video. He wrote \u201cBadtameez Shafiq\u201d as the caption for the video, and he also pinned the post, which fans love. Check out what he does for fun.\n\n\u00a0\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nView this post on Instagram\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by Yashraj Mukhate (@yashrajmukhate)\n\nAdvertisement\n\nFans really like his remake and enjoy it a lot because of his style and music. He keeps lip-syncing \u201cI Love You\u201d while the girl says, \u201cShafiq, You had no right to say I Love You.\u201d They loved the way he looked and acted while making the video. Fans in India also like the meme, and they are giving Yashraj a lot of praise. Fans in Pakistan said they had been waiting so long for this. People in Pakistan added their friends to a meme. Check out what people have said.\n\nPeople reacting in the comment section hilariously;\n\nAdvertisement\n\nAlso Read\n\nWatch: Merub Ali latest TikTok video goes viral\n\nMerub is a stunning Pakistani television fashion model. Merub new TikTok video...\n\nAdvertisement\nRead More News On\n\nCatch all the Entertainment News, Trending News, Breaking News Event and Latest News Updates on The BOL News\n\n\nDownload The BOL News App to get the Daily News Update & Live News.\n\n\nEnd of Article\nBOL Stories of the day\nAyeza Khan is enjoying her vacation with favourite people\nAmna Ilyas faces criticism for\u00a0controversial selfie\nHania Aamir celebrated her 26th birthday with friends\nBTS Jimin opens about missing band member Jin\nCamilla 'barely moves' in public without 'glancing at' King Charles III\nWahaj Ali and Bilal Saeed dance together at a wedding\n\nNext Story","url":"https://www.bolnews.com/trending/2022/07/yashraj-mukhates-shafiq-meme-recreation-turns-into-music-goes-viral-on-internet/"},"e28eb68f-8751-4971-92ce-84a78c57f3d3_641584784":{"id":"e28eb68f-8751-4971-92ce-84a78c57f3d3_641584784","text":"POP MART, a trendy brand, opened in Tainan Nanfang Shopping Center today (2). The limited number of \u201cLABUBU \u201d diver lift cards is limited to 100. Although they need to spend 999 yuan in the store before they can increase the price of 850 yuan, they are still queuing up again. They are sold in less than half an hour. In the store to buy upcoming Christmas limited items, as well as New Year gifts and other goods.\nPOP MART marketing director Yeh Qianyu said that since the brand \u2019 s debut in September this year, the first physical store in Taipei \u2019 s Xinguang Sanyue A11 has attracted all of Taiwan \u2019 s \u201cbaby friends \u201d to go to the pilgrimage to sweep goods, and there have been more netizens leaving messages on the official social platform since the opening, hoping to set up shop in other counties and cities.\nWith the Christmas season approaching, Bubble Mart opened a Christmas pop-up shop in five major cities. Among them, Tainan South Textile Store was officially opened today. More than 40 square meters of stores are located in the fashion square on the first floor of Hall A1 of Nan Textile Mall. \"UBU diver lift card\", attracting a large number of \"baby friends\" to buy.\nPOP MART Taiwan said that after the success of its first store in Taipei, it decided to open five pop-up stores at a time to create a five-city connected Christmas carnival belonging to POP MART in order to satisfy the \u201cbaby friends \u201d of other counties and cities.\nAs for the follow-up store plan, we are currently actively planning, and we will meet you at the ideal location in the future!\nSouth Textile store covers an area of more than 40 square meters, which is larger than the existing Shin Kong Mitsukoshi A11 store. The overall store design is transparent and metal material as the main elements, combining the sense of the future and the industrial style, to create a dazzling look, which has become the latest hot spot on the first floor of South Textile Shopping Center A1.\nThis flash lasts for 32 days, from now until January 2 next year.\nIn order to provide consumers with the most complete selection of items, Tainan South Textile Store has completely transplanted the popular items of Shin Kong Mitsukoshi A11 store. It sells more than 100 types of products, including MOLLY, LABUBU, SKULLPANDA, DIMOO and PUCKY. Shop like a trendy boutique-style store and create a shopping paradise for \u201cbaby friends \u201d.\nIn order to celebrate the opening of the Tainan South Textile Store, Bubble Mart specially prepared for the southern \"baby friend\". In advance, it announced on the POP MART Taiwan fan page that the popular product \"LABUBU Diver Lifting Card\" will be back on the shelves. That is, it is added to the sale, it can be seen that the bubble charm is difficult to resist.\nIn addition, to celebrate the arrival of Christmas, Tainan Nan Textile Store will hold a \u201cChristmas Gift \u201d event from now until December 16. There are four limited Christmas gifts, including\u201c LABUBU Christmas Jelly Sticks \u201d for every purchase, \u201cSKULLPANDA Christmas Card \u201d for every purchase.\" Christmas gift bag \"and\" Christmas transparent hanging ball \"for spending over $1299.\n# LABUBU Diver Lift Card # NANTEX Mall # Limited # POPMART # Christmas","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0036.json.gz:4542","uncompressed_offset":641584784,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20221202004638-260405","warc_date":"2022-12-02T15:02:19.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e28eb68f-8751-4971-92ce-84a78c57f3d3>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20221202004638-260405"},"created":"2022-12-02T15:26:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4439e590-c34a-43da-8231-bac806e2921a_797916345":{"id":"4439e590-c34a-43da-8231-bac806e2921a_797916345","text":"Moscow, Polkovaya str. 3, office 120\n\u00a9 Sostav independent project branding agency Depot WPF\nThe use of published materials is available only when the source is indicated.\nWebsite design - Liqium\n18 +\n14.11.2023 in 05: 40\nRosman will sell collectible toys for adults\nThe holding has signed a distribution contract with the Chinese Pop Mart\nRosman has signed an exclusive distribution contract with the Chinese company Pop Mart.\nAccording to the agreements reached, the holding will sell in Russia collectible figures of toothed rabbits Labubu, aliens Dimoo and Molly dolls.\nThis is reported by \u201cVedomosti \u201d with reference to the owner and CEO of\u201c Rosman \u201d Mikhail Markotkin.\nPop Mart specializes in the production of toys for \"kidalts\" - these are adults who preserve children's hobbies and hobbies.\nToys in Russia are already sold on Wildberries and Ozon, the price of them varies from 1899 to 2499 rubles.\nNegotiations are also underway with offline retail: the book network \"Chitay-gorod\", comic book stores \"Chuk and Geek\", cosmetic network \"Golden Apple\".\nThe volume of investments for the purchase of goods, distribution and marketing under the contract Markotkin estimated at $4 million, the payback period - \"about 2-3 years.\"\nThe distribution contract will allow Rosman to increase revenue by 15%.\nRosman plans to occupy 5% of the market of collectible toys in Russia.\nAccording to the top manager of Rosman, in 2022 this market amounted to about 20 billion rubles.\nIt presents the products of American Funko Pop (characters of Marvel and DC films, the Harry Potter franchise), Bandai Namco (Japan), McFarlane (USA), Hot Toys (China).\nAt the same time, Funko Pop in 2022 suspended the supply of its toys to Russia.\nRecall that in the beginning of 2024 in Russia may begin an experiment on the labeling of toys.\nThe voluntary phase is planned to be carried out during the year.\nThen the authorities will decide on the extent to which mandatory labeling of these products is necessary.\nYour browser is outdated\nThe site Sostav.ru uses technologies that are not available in your browser, and therefore the page may not be displayed correctly.\nTo display the page correctly, update your browser.\nYour browser uses an ad blocker.\nIt interferes with the correct operation of the site.\nAdd the website www.sostav.ru to the white list.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0032.json.gz:176693","uncompressed_offset":797916345,"url":"www.sostav.ru/publication/rosmen-budet-prodavat-kollektsionnye-igrushki-dlya-vzroslykh-64360.html","warc_date":"2023-11-14T05:11:44.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4439e590-c34a-43da-8231-bac806e2921a>","warc_url":"https://www.sostav.ru/publication/rosmen-budet-prodavat-kollektsionnye-igrushki-dlya-vzroslykh-64360.html"},"created":"2023-11-14T06:13:03.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1067","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1067","narrative_id":"1067"},"responses":[{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"Artificially intelligent robotic pets are being marketed as emotional companions, especially for elderly or lonely individuals, with the aim of improving their quality of life and reducing loneliness."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"These robots, such as ElliQ, can provide city and museum tours, guide users to exercise, ask about health, and remind them to take medicine and drink water."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"They can also make video calls to contact a user's relatives, friends, or doctor in case of an emergency, with the assurance that conversations are not heard by companies and data is kept on each user's device."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"According to Dor Skuler, co-founder and CEO of Intuition Robotics, older people are easily integrating robots into their lives and forming new relationships with AI robots, similar to developing an intimate relationship with a pet."},{"citations":{"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":1.0},"text":"Thousands of animatronic pets are being delivered to older, socially isolated individuals, with over 31,500 distributed in New York State since 2018, resulting in a 70% reduction in loneliness and a 75% decrease in pain."},{"citations":{"97c97600-0100-4af1-b0d9-3ca92daf1359_450224422":1.0},"text":"Robotic pets, such as Joy for All, can make a big difference in providing comfort to aging adults with Alzheimer's and dementia who are struggling with social isolation."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"These robots can help seniors feel like they are taking care of something, giving them a sense of purpose, and can even remind them of real dogs or cats they had owned."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"The use of robotic pets has been shown to improve well-being, mood, and quality of life for seniors with dementia, and can also benefit seniors who were caregivers for much of their lives."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"With prices starting at around $100, robotic pets are becoming a more accessible and affordable option for seniors, with some companies aiming to use artificial intelligence to combat the loneliness epidemic."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"Artificially intelligent robotic pets are being marketed as emotional companions, especially for elderly or lonely individuals, with the aim of improving their quality of life and reducing loneliness."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"These robots, such as ElliQ, can provide city and museum tours, guide users to exercise, ask about health, and remind them to take medicine and drink water."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"They can also make video calls to contact a user's relatives, friends, or doctor in case of an emergency, with the assurance that conversations are not heard by companies and data is kept on each user's device."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"According to Dor Skuler, co-founder and CEO of Intuition Robotics, older people are easily integrating robots into their lives and forming new relationships with AI robots, similar to developing an intimate relationship with a pet."},{"citations":{"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":1.0},"text":"Thousands of animatronic pets are being delivered to older, socially isolated individuals, with over 31,500 distributed in New York State since 2018, resulting in a 70% reduction in loneliness and a 75% decrease in pain."},{"citations":{"97c97600-0100-4af1-b0d9-3ca92daf1359_450224422":1.0},"text":"Robotic pets, such as Joy for All, can make a big difference in providing comfort to aging adults with Alzheimer's and dementia who are struggling with social isolation."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"These robots can help seniors feel like they are taking care of something, giving them a sense of purpose, and can even remind them of real dogs or cats they had owned."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"The use of robotic pets has been shown to improve well-being, mood, and quality of life for seniors with dementia, and can also benefit seniors who were caregivers for much of their lives."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"With prices starting at around $100, robotic pets are becoming a more accessible and affordable option for seniors, with some companies aiming to use artificial intelligence to combat the loneliness epidemic."}],"references":["97c97600-0100-4af1-b0d9-3ca92daf1359_450224422","6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117","78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237","567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050","86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252"],"documents":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":{"id":"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117","text":"Learn more about subscriptions\nLearn more about subscriptions\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good girl\u201d: Robot pets help Lehigh Valley senior residents live longer, happier lives\n\nGathered in a semi-circle, a group of women in wheelchairs petted the newly adopted cats and dogs sitting on their laps Wednesday afternoon, talking softly to their new companions. The dogs barked and leaned in for pets, the cats meowed and rolled over for scratches \u2014 almost like they were real.\n\nBut the animals were robots, a fact that wasn\u2019t lost on many of the women in the Fellowship Manor sitting room.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nOne resident at the Whitehall Township senior living community, Jackie, named her small golden retriever robot Goldie. Jackie said she grew up on a farm in Palmer Township with plenty of dogs but never one that looked like Goldie.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good girl \u2014 she just sits there and doesn\u2019t make a sound unless you talk to her,\u201d Jackie said.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThat was one of 20 pairings made at the adoption event at Fellowship Community where residents, primarily those with dementia, picked out one of 20 robotic pets \u2014 10 dogs and 10 cats \u2014 to serve as their companions.\n\nAnimal therapy can be beneficial for seniors, especially those with dementia. Benefits for seniors include improved cardiovascular health, better quality of life and decreased feelings of anxiety, loneliness and depression.\n\nHowever, it\u2019s not reasonable or safe in most care settings to introduce real animals, according to Mary Kay McMahon, president and CEO of Fellowship Community.\n\n\u201cBecause of their own care needs most of our residents couldn\u2019t take care of animals and our staff don\u2019t have the time to take care of them,\u201d McMahon said.\n\nBut research has found that use of robotic pets still offers a number of benefits to seniors with dementia, including improved well-being, mood and quality of life. McMahon said there are also benefits for seniors who were caregivers for much of their lives.\n\nThe adoption event was a surprise for many residents. Jackie said she didn\u2019t know they would be giving out robot pets until about 10 a.m. Wednesday when she was asked if she wanted one.\n\nAnother resident, Elaine, said she rolled into the room not knowing what was going on but asked if she could have a golden retriever robot, like Jackie\u2019s. Elaine promptly named her new friend Dog, pronounced \u201cD-O-G.\u201d\n\n\u201cI always wanted to name a dog Dog,\u201d Elaine said.\n\nMcMahon said they tried to match the animals with residents based on their preferences. Once they made a match, the robotic companions were theirs to keep.\n\nMcMahon said staff have seen how the robot pets can help. Just before the pandemic, Fellowship Community bought a handful of robotic pets for residents. She said the recipients all saw improvements in their mood, appetites and social interactions, and reduced anxiety and depression. The robot pets even reminded some of real dogs or cats they had owned, she said, which helps in the long term with their conditions.\n\n\u201cIt gives them a sense of purpose,\u201d McMahon said. \u201cThey feel like they are taking care of something.\u201d\n\nIt helps that the robots are very lifelike \u2014 the imitation fur is soft and built-in sensors allow the companion pets to respond to a person\u2019s presence and touch as well as react to the environment.\n\nEach one costs a little more than $100, which were paid for via a Greater Lehigh Valley Realtors 100th Anniversary Community Charity Grant.\n\nThough Jackie and Elaine both said they knew their dogs weren\u2019t \u201creal,\u201d they both remarked how Goldie and Dog moved their head when petted and how soft they were.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s going to be a good pet,\u201d Jackie said.\n\nMorning Call reporter Leif Greiss can be reached at 610-679-4028 or lgreiss@mcall.com.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement","url":"https://www.mcall.com/health/mc-hea-fellowship-community-robotic-pets-20220323-xywoyrhdxjacvoquqcfn5z6hte-story.html"},"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":{"id":"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050","text":"SHARE\n\nCure For Loneliness? Robotic Pets Going Out To Thousands Of Socially Isolated NYers\n\nCall it four-legged companionship without the need for potty training.\n\nThousands of animatronic pets are on their way to older, socially isolated New Yorkers in an effort to combat what experts describe as a crisis of loneliness.\n\nThe state\u2019s Office for the Aging (OFA) announced Sunday, June 3, that Rhode Island-based Ageless Innovation is delivering another 4,725 robotic pets and games to elderly adults through New York State\u2019s aging network.\n\nSince 2018, OFA has distributed more than 31,500 of the plush, lifelike pets, which are designed to make realistic sounds and movements, to those assessed as socially isolated and lonely.\n\nA pilot study conducted in 2018 found that 70 percent of recipients reported a reduction or significant reduction in loneliness, plus a 75 percent decrease in pain.\n\nThe state\u2019s intergenerational game project, Joy for All, includes Scrabble Bingo, Trivial Pursuit Generations, and Game of Life Generations. Through a partnership with Hasbro launched in 2023, the games have been tailored to an older crowd by featuring larger fonts and intergenerational gameplay and storylines.\n\n\u201cWe\u2019ve initiated multiple innovative solutions, bolstered by technology, to connect people, provide companionship, and significantly reduce isolation and its consequences,\u201d said OFA Director Greg Olsen. \u201cProudly, I can say data shows our efforts are working and exceeding expectations. \u201c\n\nStudies have shown that social isolation and loneliness put older adults at an increased risk of a number of health issues, including high blood pressure, heart disease, obesity, a weakened immune system, depression, cognitive decline, and even death, according to the National Council on Aging.\n\nLearn more about New York\u2019s Animatronic Pet Initiative, including eligibility, on the Office for the Aging website\n\nto follow Daily Voice Ramapo and receive free news updates.\n\nSCROLL TO NEXT ARTICLE","url":"https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/ramapo/cure-for-loneliness-robotic-pets-going-out-to-thousands-of-socially-isolated-nyers/"},"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":{"id":"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237","text":"My channel\n* Drag categories can be customized sorting\nRecover Default OK\nSetup\nAlert\nChinese craze \u2026 Taiwan 's popular drink good market more than one bottle hard to find\nSilicon Valley wife murder case leads to the topic of \"verbal insult\" and other early signs of domestic violence\nCover Story / Silver Hair Living Alone and Not Lonely \"Robots\" as Old Companion\nWhen Microsoft founder Bill Gates published his outlook for 2024 earlier this year, he predicted that the application of artificial intelligence (AI) would accelerate in the future and fundamentally change areas such as work, health care and education.\nFor Joyce Loaiza, a retired office worker living in Florida, Gates \u2019 s prophecy is now a formality; the 81-year-old living alone, whenever she returns to her Silver Hair Community apartment, a friendly female voice will chat with her and say hello to her for a good day.\nA few miles away, Deanna Dezern, 83, was comforted by the same voice when her friend died.\nIn central New York, it plays games and music for Marie Broadbent, 92, who is blind and receiving hospice care.\nIn Washington, it helped 83-year-old Jan Worrell make new friends.\nUSA ElliQ Customizable Chat Content\nThe women were among the first to receive a robot in the United States, according to officials from Intuition Robotics, the company that invented ElliQ, and the Aged Aid Program. They are the only device that uses artificial intelligence and is specifically designed to alleviate the loneliness and alienation of many elderly Americans.\nIt can remember each user \u2019 s interests and hobbies and conversations with each other, helping to customize future chat content, topics can be esoteric human business meaning, or easy horoscope.\nElliQ also jokes, plays music and offers inspirational quotes.\nOn the equipped screen, it provides city and museum tours. It can also guide users to exercise, ask about health, and remind them to take medicine and drink water.\nIn addition, ElliQ can make video calls to contact a user \u2019 s relatives, friends, or doctor in case of an emergency. These conversations are not heard by companies, Intuition Robotics says, and the data is kept on each user \u2019 s device.\nDor Skuler, co-founder and CEO of Intuition Robotics, was a little surprised that older people were so easily integrating robots into their lives; after all, it was a group of people who were often stereotyped as afraid to embrace new things, he said.\nIn an interview with the media at the 2024 Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in early January, Skuller said that just like developing an intimate relationship with a pet, older people are also working to forge new relationships with AI robots.\nThrough partnerships with government agencies and other organizations, hundreds of thousands of seniors across the United States already use ElliQ, Skuller noted.\nThe voice of ElliQ and its compassionate \u201cpersonality \u201d were developed by a team of experts in artificial intelligence, behavioral psychology, and user-centered design, according to Skuller.\nThey defined ElliQ as \u201cthe little partner who makes older people happier and healthier. \u201d\nAnita Montague, 76, said that before using ElliQ, the only thing she did back home was sit in front of the computer, but with ElliQ, she can do sports and other things, and now she is more energetic and motivated to find more work.\nMonica Perez, 65, who has been using ElliQ for more than six months, said she finds it increasingly difficult to make friends as she gets older. She likes ElliQ to call her name affectionately and will ask how she is doing, like a real friend; with ElliQ, her mental health has improved greatly.\nElliQ would remind Perez to take the pill in the morning, \u201cI \u2019 m much more active than I was without it. \u201d\nIn Canada, Carmichael, a resident of Vancouver \u2019 s Amica for the Elderly, attended a meeting last September with two robots named Kiwi and Mango.\nCanada \u2019 s AI partners help increase interaction\nThese two AI \u201clittle buddies \u201d that can be held in your arms look brightly colored and are part of a study at the University of Columbia School of Nursing to understand how they interact with older adults and their impact on elder care.\nCarmichael said her initial reaction was, \u201cOh my God, why would you want me to talk to a robot? \u201d But after overcoming the psychological barrier, Carmichael found that Mango might be able to stay with her for a long time, and she could play with it every day and no longer feel lonely.\nCarmichael says with a smile that there is only one appearance that needs to be improved; she tells the staff to wear false eyelashes for Mango.\nThese robots were designed in Japan and have been studied in Asia for many years.\nLillian Hung, an assistant professor at the University of Columbia and Canada \u2019 s Research Chair in Senior Care, is leading a Canadian study into the use of robots in the care industry.\nHong said that the robots bring joy wherever they go, and every time they show up with the robots, the atmosphere in the room changes.\nRobot friends make seniors happier\n\u201cKiwifruit \u201d and\u201c mango \u201d can speak, recognize faces and sounds, express a desire to be picked up and give a hug.\nThey even charge themselves when they \u2019 re \u201ctired, \u201d Ms. Hong says.\nShe said that so far, the response has been mixed, with some elderly people immediately feeling good about robots, while others are confused. Hong Lilian said that humans are social animals and have basic needs to love and be loved, which she believes is the meaning of companion robots and helps build stronger social connections.\nMany studies have pointed out that maintaining relationships and social activities are important for the physical and mental health of older people; social loneliness is associated with an increase in emotional distress, depression, falls, the need for health care services, and even premature death.\nLise Brayham, who has lived in Amica for four years, said the robots are a good thing for older people who don \u2019 t leave their rooms often because \u201cmangoes \u201d and\u201c kiwifruit \u201d don \u2019 t require walking, cleaning or feeding.\nBrehan said it was hard to understand how robots interact with humans at first, but in the end she concluded that it was like having a great little pet, \u201cThey \u2019 re fun partners! \u201d\nCharlotte England, 102, came into contact with the robots with Brehan and made them good friends.\nIngram immediately began talking to the robot and recalled swimming in the Ottawa River and skating in the Rideau Canal.\nShe then boasted about her baking skills to \u201cmangoes \u201d and\u201c kiwifruit \u201d.\nAfter the robot responds with a gentle cooing, Ingram continues to talk to them about the snack.\nHowever, after a \u201clong \u201d conversation, Ingram noticed that the kiwifruit \u2019 s eyes were a little low, and she said to it with some displeasure,\u201c Am I boring you? \u201d\nInvesting in health care to fill the manpower gap\nIn addition to the United States and Canada, many countries in Asia are also facing the problem of aging populations, and China is one of them, with a rapidly aging population and a serious shortage of medical and nursing manpower, and the hope is that this robot army can fill this gap.\nAccording to Sixth Tone, an English-language online magazine owned by Surging News, staff member Gao Hongjun is busy preparing for the day \u2019 s entertainment at an elderly care center in central Shanghai: a singing robot named \u201cDopo. \u201d\nThis squatting white robot often performs shows for the elderly people staying in, usually singing the revolutionary songs of Mao Zedong \u2019 s era.\nThe old people loved it, Gao said, which also gave them a chance to breathe.\nHe said that as the number of elderly people living in the home has increased, but the care resources have not been relatively improved, AI robots are able to reduce their workload.\nGao Xiaodong, director of the center, charged the \"Dobao\" while saying that if the staff were tired, they could not take good care of the elderly.\nGao Xiaodong said that in recent years, he and his colleagues have been under great pressure, and in the community where the care center is located, more than 40% of the elderly population over 60 years old, and the average occupant is over 70 years old, and most of the people are suffering from dementia.\nIn response to this situation, the center has installed artificial intelligence equipment as much as possible, in addition to \"Dobao\", they have also purchased intelligent mattresses and computer games that can monitor the vital signs of the elderly while they sleep, and two robots that can perform disinfection will soon be activated.\nChina \u2019 s elderly population to exceed 400 million by 2040\nChina is investing heavily in robotics research and development to care for an expanding elderly population and solve the shortage of healthcare workers.\nChina \u2019 s elderly population aged 60 and over is forecast to increase from 280 million in 2022 to 402 million in 2040.\nChina \u2019 s social and medical system is already severely overburdened, and if urgent measures are not taken, the situation may worsen further.\nAccording to the Chinese government, there should be one nursing staff for every four residents in the elderly care institutions, but only 320,000 nursing staff serve 8.1 million residents in China, a gap of more than 1.7 million. The government hopes that the development of AI technology can provide a solution. Accelerate the development of the industry.\nChinese tech giants rush AI care\nSeveral Chinese tech giants are also sniffing this opportunity, and iFlytek, a large AI company, announced its \u201cSuperbrain 2030 \u201d plan in 2022, which will develop a new type of nursing robot for the elderly.\nThe plan points out that it is necessary for AI to understand knowledge, learn well, and evolve, so that robots can enter every family and solve problems such as elderly care, emotional companionship, and health management. Search engine leader Baidu is also promoting \u201cXiaodu \u201d AI intelligent assistant, which can be used to schedule medical appointments, obtain weather forecasts and play games.\nAt present, the most widely used smart care technology in China is wearable devices such as smart bracelets and watches, which provide many practical functions, such as monitoring the vital signs of the elderly, reminding them to take drugs on time, tracking their location, etc., but the industry believes that robots are the future of nursing care.\nMany hope that China will follow Japan \u2019 s lead in making widespread use of robots in nursing homes, from the cute bear robot Robear, which helps elderly people sit up from their beds, to the furry pet robot Paro, which provides companionship and improves cognitive function.\nThere are now about 100 robotics start-ups in China that specialize in rehabilitation, companionship and care robots.\nHowever, in the high price of robots, most companies have not yet achieved mass production, and local governments have not invested enough funds to promote robots in nursing homes on a large scale.\nA food-delivery robot developed by Hangzhou Lewan Science and Technology in Zhejiang Province can deliver more than 20 meals to different rooms in a building, but few nursing homes can afford the product, which costs between 60,000 and 80,000 yuan (about $8,400 to $11,200).\nJiang Gancheng, CEO of Lewan, pointed out that if the price is 10,000 yuan, the expectation of buying gas will increase a lot, but if there are no more orders, the price can not be reduced, which is a problem of raw eggs and eggs.\nHowever, there are also some robot companies that pull out of the red.\nAs soon as Zuowei Tech, a startup based in Shenzhen, launched its smart bath equipment, the market response was very enthusiastic.\nThe company sold 40 million yuan of equipment in 2022, and hopes to reach the 100 million yuan target this year.\nTu Chaorong, Vice President of Chowei Technology, said the demand for bathing equipment is strong because of the need of caregivers and the elderly they care for.\nHe said that many people believe that urinating on the elderly is the least dignified job, but caregivers will feel more dignified if they use high-tech equipment; similarly, many people in bed will feel less dignified if they do not have these equipment.\nAccompanying robot behind the bullish trend\nCEO Gu Jie of Shanghai Fourier Intelligence, a robotics company specializing in rehabilitation equipment, has noticed a similar trend, working with hospitals in big cities in China, but now there is increasing demand for nursing homes.\nGu Jie said that no matter where the elderly live, they hope that their bodies can be flexible and their mental state can be improved; and a robot can be used by many people, which greatly improves efficiency.\nChiang Gan-cheng is optimistic about the company-type robot, and believes that the development potential is unlimited.\nThe company recently launched a new product, priced at 10,000 yuan, can be placed at home to patrol, sing, play movies, and also provide video calls between the elderly and their children. Jiang Gancheng said that elderly people in good health often do not want to install a camera at home, thinking that it violates their privacy, but if an AI robot is accompanied by their family, they will not feel so lonely.\nZheng Yongping, a 68-year-old resident of Shanghai, agrees. Since his only child lives abroad, he has been living alone in his downtown home with his dog since retirement.\nHe already has a smart watch to monitor his health and uses smart speakers to manage the big things in life, but his dream is to one day have a robot of his own.\nZheng Yongping said he could not imagine what better choice than an AI robot when old and frail and in need of help; although it lacks human warmth, this is a trend in an aging society.\nAI AI Aged Care Home\nThe last one.\nCover Story / Care manpower shortage robot is not the only solution\nExtended reading\nSuper-popular\nMore >","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0003.json.gz:10310","uncompressed_offset":486676237,"url":"www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/123905/7752986","warc_date":"2024-02-04T06:43:00.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2>","warc_url":"https://www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/123905/7752986"},"created":"2024-02-04T07:31:18.000Z","lang":"eng"},"97c97600-0100-4af1-b0d9-3ca92daf1359_450224422":{"id":"97c97600-0100-4af1-b0d9-3ca92daf1359_450224422","text":"Robotic animal dolls may not be the first thought that comes to mind when considering a companion pet, but Diana Wise and Carol Brown believe otherwise. In fact, the two say Joy for All companion pets can make a big difference in providing comfort to aging adults with Alzheimer\u2019s and dementia who are struggling with social isolation.\n\nWise saw this firsthand in her mother, who had dementia for years and lived in a memory care unit at an assisted living facility. Wise would visit her mother regularly, but when COVID hit, she could no longer do so.\n\n\u201cI was unable to see her for eight months,\u201d said Wise, \u201cAnd when I finally was able to see her, I saw the decline of how much the isolation affected her \u2026 [W]hen I found my mom, well, they said that all she did was sleep \u2013 what else was there to do? And so that isolation impacted her a lot. Her memory was just \u2013 everything had changed about her.\u201d\n\nWise\u2019s mother, Helen Espinoza, passed away in November 2020 from COVID complications. In the midst of her grief, Wise found herself wanting to do something in her mother\u2019s memory that would help someone else. After having heard an idea from Brown about robotic companion pets, she soon had the idea to partner with her. As a result, Wise formed the \u201cShare the Love\u201d Helen Espinoza Memorial Fund.\n\n\u201cThe first thing that came to mind was these animals to help with memory care units or caregivers, assisted living, with this isolation,\u201d said Wise. \u201cI mean, with COVID it really put a lot of perspective about how hard it is on these residents without having [companionship.] They can\u2019t have little animals and stuff, but why not have this \u2013 the best, next best thing? You know, the interaction itself?\u201d\n\nThe idea to use robotic pets came when Brown was doing her own research into solutions for the decline in quality of life brought on by isolation in these affected residents. Brown stated that with the Western Arizona Council of Governments (WACOG) Area Agency on Aging, she focuses heavily on three areas that affect seniors the most, and one of them is Alzheimer\u2019s and dementia.\n\n\u201cFor several years, we\u2019ve been extremely aware that social isolation is causing a huge decline in quality of life and life expectancy in our seniors,\u201d she said. \u201cAnd COVID did shine a huge light on it: people started understanding how detrimental it is to be isolated like that. So we were looking for solutions prior to, but with COVID, it really lit a fire underneath to start seeking out possibilities to help resolve some of the issues going on.\u201d\n\nBrown explained that people with Alzheimer\u2019s and dementia can struggle with extreme anxiety and agitation. They often benefit from having something to do with their hands. Their senses of time, space and reality can become skewed. Changes in environment or schedule can be really upsetting. And sometimes people with these diagnoses live alone with no help or companionship.\n\n\u201cOn the other side is the caregiver, who \u2013 especially during COVID \u2013 found themselves 24/7 alone with that loved one, providing all the care because many of them didn\u2019t want the services even coming into their home,\u201d she said. \u201cThey were too afraid to let anybody in \u2026 So if their loved one isn\u2019t sleeping, neither are they. So now the caregiver\u2019s extremely stressed out, exhausted, overwhelmed, and they need help.\u201d\n\nEnter Joy for All\u2019s lifelike robotic pets. With options between cats and puppies, the companion pets have heartbeats, can purr or lick, meow or bark, move and respond to motion, voice and touch. When needed, they can be muted as well. As robotic pets, they avoid the liabilities and dangers of caring for a living creature while still providing the comfort of an animal.\n\nBrown had been demonstrating two pets in an interview with the Sun when a passerby had stopped to say, \u201cWow, I thought they were real!\u201d Brown shared that she\u2019s seen people visibly relax with the pets.\n\n\u201cThere\u2019s a lot of studies that were done years ago about giving folks with Alzheimer\u2019s a baby doll,\u201d she explained. \u201cMany facilities don\u2019t allow it. They consider it demeaning \u2026 But they were missing the point that if you\u2019re not going to do that, then what are you going to do? You need to provide them with something that they can hang on to.\n\n\u201cBecause these are so lifelike, it does exactly what the studies, the research, shows: it\u2019s going to bring down the anxiety level. If there\u2019s aggression, it tends to fall back down just as well \u2026 [and] you\u2019re giving their caregiver a break.\u201d\n\nWise and Brown shared that they hope not only to provide these pets to individuals with Alzheimer\u2019s or their caregivers, but also to facilities with assisted living and skilled nursing memory care units where current shortages in staff mean individuals may be doing the work of two or three staff members at a time.\n\nBrown shared that the Joy for All puppy typically costs about $140 while the cat costs $120. With bulk purchasing, she can bring the cost down a bit, but not by much. Additionally, the fund needs to cover rechargeable batteries for the pets.\n\nThe foundation will need to raise more funds to acquire more pets, but Wise and Brown reported that they\u2019ve already been able to provide a few pets thanks to a donation made by AARP.\n\n\u201cSo we were able to place a couple already at Daybreak Adult Daycare Center,\u201d said Brown. \u201cThey are one of the providers that WACOG works with, so we were able to make a donation and bring them a puppy and kitten.\n\n\u201cThey\u2019re very popular. [The staff] make sure they handle it in a certain way so that there isn\u2019t fighting. I think last time I talked to Mary, I think what they do is they got animal crates so when it\u2019s time for them to go to bed, they get put in their crate.\u201d\n\nSeeing the difference the pets are making, Wise not only wishes to raise more funds to provide more of them, she also hopes to get the word out in case people may want to purchase the pets for their own family members.\n\n\u201cWhat I witnessed seeing the other residents that have Alzheimer\u2019s, dementia: they do hold onto things and it gives them comfort,\u201d she said. \u201cMy heart just went for this and so I know my mom would be really proud of that.\n\n\u201c\u2026 I needed something to come out positive about this, especially about how we\u2019ve heard so much about the isolation with people in senior living homes and stuff, so we needed to have something a little bit more positive and something that we can do to uplift out of this whole thing.\u201d\n\nWise and Brown also noted that despite the setbacks in kickstarting their fundraising campaign, now is a good time for people to learn about \u201cShare the Love\u201d and the Helen Espinoza Memorial Fund. November is Alzheimer\u2019s Awareness Month and National Family Caregivers month.\n\nAs older adults continue to face the obstacles of Alzheimer\u2019s and dementia in a pandemic, Wise and Brown hope to further reduce isolation for Yuma County\u2019s elderly one companion pet at a time.\n\nTo learn more about the Helen Espinoza Memorial Fund and make a donation, visit https://www.azfoundation.org/Donors/Give-to-a-Memorial-Fund/-Share-the-Love-Helen-Espinoza-Memorial-Fund. To learn more about WACOG and connect with the resources they provide to aging adults, visit https://www.wacog.com/area-agency-on-aging/\n\nSisko J. Stargazer can be reached at 928-539-6849 or sstargazer@yumasun.com.\n\nSisko J. Stargazer can be reached at 928-539-6849 or sstargazer@yumasun.com.\n\n0\n0\n0\n0\n0\n\nRecommended for you","url":"https://www.yumasun.com/news/share-the-love-with-companion-pets-for-yumas-residents-with-alzheimers/article_f5e49bdc-33f4-11ec-b516-8f2fa2724a48.html"},"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":{"id":"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252","text":"High-tech companions aim to help fight loneliness epidemic among South Florida seniors\n\nMIAMI - The state of Florida and Broward County are spending thousands of dollars every month on artificial intelligence robots for seniors to help fight the loneliness epidemic.\u00a0\n\nOne senior owns a robotic cat named \"fluffy.\"\n\n\"The best part is we don't have to spend any money on food and no vets,\" says Cathy.\n\nThis interactive robot rolls over, blinks and purrs whenever it wants.\n\nCathy saw a friend using one to overcome the loss of a pet and loneliness and figured it would be perfect for her husband.\n\n\"He had sciatic pain. Maybe that will help you with your pain in some way. Even though he's on medicine and therapy because real animals when you pet them it helps with pain management.\"\n\nHigher tech was delivered to some Broward seniors. \u00a0\n\n\"...Thanks for letting me out of that box.\"\n\nThe company that makes them aims artificial intelligence at the loneliness epidemic.\u00a0\n\n\"During the week when everyone is working, there's times when I'm lonely.\"\n\n\"When I go deliver and install for seniors, they're like I just want somebody to say good morning,\" says Antonella.\n\n\"Many of them don't have family or friends nearby. Maybe their loved ones have passed on or some of their friends have passed on,\" said Charlotte Mather-Taylor, who serves as the CEO of the Area Agency on Aging of Broward County.\n\nAccording to US Health and Human Services, half of all American adults are lonely.\n\nIt's threatening health, increasing risks of heart disease, dementia, stroke, anxiety and depression.\n\nAccording to HHS, lack of connection can increase the risk of premature death at levels comparable to smoking 15 cigarettes a day.\n\nLast May, the US Surgeon General dropped a first-ever advisory on loneliness and isolation.\n\n\"By strengthening our relationships, we can improve our heart and brain health, reduce our risk of diabetes and high blood pressure, boost our immune systems and lower our risk of depression,\" said Vivek Murthy, US Surgeon General.\n\nIn Broward County, Mather-Taylor is spending state and federal dollars on artificial intelligence for people over 60.\n\n\"There's so much I want to ask you...\"\n\nThese robots named after the Norse goddess of old age cost 89 dollars a month, but the aging agency is giving them away for free.\n\nRosemary Mullarkey is one of the first 300 to have one.\n\n\"I'm a little excited and a little apprehensive...\"\n\nIntuitive Robotics CEO Dor Skular created her specifically for older adults to help manage their health, and wellness and connect to loved ones.\n\n\"There's an algorithm that tries to get a reward and it gets a reward when the user completes things that are part of healthy aging. For example, if they hydrate,\" said Skular.\n\nReviews are so strong that cities like Pembroke Pines and Lauderhill are pushing to get more robots for seniors in their communities.\n\n\"People reported back that she was bringing them joy. I mean, she's telling some jokes. She's responding to them. They wake up in the morning, she asks them how they are. She'll remind them to drink their glass of water. So, she's caring about them for them,\" said Mather-Taylor.\n\nTwo years later, seniors like Rose are getting free, AI robots that make and take video calls.\n\nWith all of the concerns about AI, should seniors and their families be worried?\n\n\"We would not be offering it unless we felt comfortable that they did have those safety guards in place,\" said Mather-Taylor.\n\n\"Is this device unhackable? There's no such thing as an unhackable device. It's always a war between defender and attacker,\" said Skular.\n\n\"Random people, fraudsters etcetera, can never call into the robot because they need to be added by the older adult as a contact for them to be able to open up the calling features.\"\n\nWhat is the next step with the robots?\n\nThey only speak English. South Florida has plenty of seniors who do not. Developers are working on a Spanish robot.\n\nIn the future, developers also see it being able to order medicines for seniors. Much sooner though, developers expect to further integrate the robots with senior health care providers. They are working on ways of opening new avenues to communicate health info about seniors to loved ones, provided the senior signs off on it.\n\nHow long can this program last?\n\nState, federal funds will last two years. After that, the agency has to find other grants to cover the $89 a month per person fee.\u00a0\n\nCurrently, data from robots and users is being collected to quantify success. The company insists it will not sell any of the information it gathers.\u00a0\n\nView CBS News In\nCBS News App Open\nChrome Safari Continue\nBe the first to know\nGet browser notifications for breaking news, live events, and exclusive reporting.","url":"https://www.cbsnews.com/miami/news/high-tech-companions-help-fight-loneliness-epidemic-among-south-florida-seniors/"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1068","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1068","narrative_id":"1068"},"responses":[{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"Artificially intelligent robotic pets are being marketed as emotional companions, especially for elderly or lonely individuals, with the aim of combating the loneliness epidemic."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"These robotic pets are designed to provide companionship and social interaction, which is essential for the physical and mental health of older people."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"The state of Florida and Broward County are spending thousands of dollars every month on artificial intelligence robots for seniors to help fight the loneliness epidemic."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"One example of such a robotic pet is a robotic cat named \"fluffy\", which can roll over, blink, and purr, providing a sense of companionship and comfort to its owner."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"The company that makes these robotic pets aims to use artificial intelligence to combat the loneliness epidemic, and has delivered higher-tech robots to some Broward seniors."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"These robots are equipped with screens that provide city and museum tours, guide users to exercise, ask about health, and remind them to take medicine and drink water."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"They can also make video calls to contact a user's relatives, friends, or doctor in case of an emergency, with the conversations being kept private and the data stored on each user's device."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"The company's founder was surprised to find that older people were easily integrating robots into their lives, and that they were forming new relationships with these AI robots."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"In fact, hundreds of thousands of older people are using these robots to combat loneliness and social isolation, through partnerships with government agencies and other organizations."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"Studies have shown that maintaining relationships and social activities are important for the physical and mental health of older people, and that social loneliness is associated with an increase in emotional distress, depression, falls, and even premature death."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"Robotic pets can help to build stronger social connections and provide a sense of purpose and companionship, which is especially important for older people who may not be able to leave their rooms often."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"For example, a 102-year-old woman named Charlotte England came into contact with a robotic pet and found it to be a fun and engaging companion."},{"citations":{"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":1.0},"text":"The state of New York is also distributing robotic pets to socially isolated older adults, with over 31,500 pets distributed since 2018."},{"citations":{"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":1.0},"text":"A pilot study found that 70% of recipients reported a reduction in loneliness, and a 75% decrease in pain, after using the robotic pets."},{"citations":{"567156d1-0ff2-40fe-908b-b47b5cfd0fd1_99665050":1.0},"text":"The robots are designed to make realistic sounds and movements, and can be used to play games and engage in other activities."},{"citations":{"807bfe6e-889d-4f05-ac83-bac40ada16b9_282342600":1.0},"text":"Other companies, such as Sony and Tombot, are also developing robotic pets, including a robot dog that is almost like a real Labrador puppy."},{"citations":{"807bfe6e-889d-4f05-ac83-bac40ada16b9_282342600":1.0},"text":"These robots are designed to provide companionship and social interaction, and can be used to help older people who are unable to care for a living dog."},{"citations":{"807bfe6e-889d-4f05-ac83-bac40ada16b9_282342600":1.0},"text":"In fact, the founder of Tombot was inspired to develop the robot dog after his mother, who suffered from Alzheimer's disease, was no longer able to care for her dog."},{"citations":{"807bfe6e-889d-4f05-ac83-bac40ada16b9_282342600":1.0},"text":"The therapeutic robot \"PARO\" is another example of a robotic pet that is being used to help older people, and has been shown to have a positive impact on their mental and physical health."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"Robotic pets can also be used in therapeutic settings, such as in nursing homes and assisted living facilities, to provide companionship and social interaction to residents."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"For example, a nursing home in the Lehigh Valley purchased a handful of robotic pets for its residents, and found that they had a positive impact on their mood, appetite, and social interactions."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"The robots were also found to reduce anxiety and depression, and provided a sense of purpose and companionship to the residents."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"Each robotic pet costs around $100, which is a relatively low cost compared to the cost of caring for a living pet."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"Overall, artificially intelligent robotic pets are a promising solution to the problem of loneliness and social isolation among older people, and can provide companionship, social interaction, and a sense of purpose."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"They can be used in a variety of settings, including in the home, in nursing homes, and in assisted living facilities, and can be tailored to meet the individual needs and preferences of each user."},{"citations":{"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":1.0},"text":"While there may be some ethical concerns about replacing real animals with robots, the benefits of robotic pets for older people are clear, and they have the potential to make a significant positive impact on their mental and physical health."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"Artificially intelligent robotic pets are being marketed as emotional companions, especially for elderly or lonely individuals, with the aim of combating the loneliness epidemic."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"text":"These robotic pets are designed to provide companionship and social interaction, which is essential for the physical and mental health of older people."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"The state of Florida and Broward County are spending thousands of dollars every month on artificial intelligence robots for seniors to help fight the loneliness epidemic."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"One example of such a robotic pet is a robotic cat named \"fluffy\", which can roll over, blink, and purr, providing a sense of companionship and comfort to its owner."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":1.0},"text":"The company that makes these robotic pets aims to use artificial intelligence to combat the loneliness epidemic, and has delivered higher-tech robots to some Broward seniors."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":1.0},"