decline of LiveJournal can be attributed to the failure of social media platforms to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"Other social networking sites, such as SixDegrees.com, Friendster, and Myspace, also faced similar challenges and ultimately declined in popularity."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"In contrast, platforms like Reddit, which was launched less than a year after Digg, were able to thrive and grow their user base, with unique page views increasing by 50% and averaging around 900,000 per day."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"Overall, the story of LiveJournal serves as a reminder of the rapidly changing landscape of social media and the importance of adapting to new trends and technologies."}],"references":["9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229","53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342","bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633"],"documents":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":{"id":"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633","text":"Rewrite this title: Reddit thrives from Digg v4 disaster\nNext article will help you: Reddit is thriving from the Digg v4 disaster\nSince the launch of Digg \u2019 s latest version, v4, last week, the less warm reception has caused a massive influx of traffic to their competitor \u2013 Reddit.\nReddit was launched less than a year after Digg \u2019 s launch, and it wasn \u2019 t very popular, but it had very loyal users.\nHowever, starting Sunday night, the four-person team saw an increase in new users, unique items, and the number of page views in staggering numbers.\nChief programmer, Chris Slaw, stated that unique page views alone have increased by 50% \u2013 averaging around 900,000 per day since Monday morning.\nThey also report between 13 and 14 million total page views per day.\nApproximately 25% of the site \u2019 s visitors were people who signed up for the site and became \u201cjunior editors \u201d as Chris calls them on the site.\nBlog site.\nAs their numbers grew so fast, Reddit employees were surprised that the site didn \u2019 t crash.\nTheir blog also says that they work most days within the site \u2019 s peak capacity and that they \u201ccould never have survived such an unexpected surge. \u201d\nEvelyn Rosley of Tech Crunch spoke with Slough and says they are currently working on new features to keep Redditors happy and to make sure the site can maintain its new and larger user base, including a redesigned user interface.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0029.json.gz:50539","uncompressed_offset":287908633,"url":"choq.fm/rewrite-this-title-%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%8A%D8%B2%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%B1-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AB%D8%A9-digg-v4/","warc_date":"2023-10-10T14:04:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21>","warc_url":"https://choq.fm/rewrite-this-title-%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%8A%D8%B2%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%B1-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AB%D8%A9-digg-v4/"},"created":"2023-10-10T14:16:15.000Z","lang":"eng"},"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":{"id":"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342","text":"Regulators Seem to Think That Facebook Is the Internet\n\nThat\u2019s a problem.\n\nIn 1997, SixDegrees.com was the first real attempt at social networking, creating a space where users could upload their information and list their friends. The site peaked at approximately 3.5 million users before it shut down in 1999.\n\nSince then, a series of social networking business models have emerged, each time offering more advanced tools for user interaction. LiveJournal, a site for keeping up with school friends, combined blogging and social networking features inspired by the WELL; Friendster was a social network that allowed for increased interaction and control by users; Myspace had open membership and gave users the freedom to customize their pages. In 2005, it\u2014and its 25 million user base\u2014was sold to News Corp. But within three years, Myspace had been surpassed by Facebook, which launched in 2004 for college students and opened to everyone in 2006.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nAs that history shows, in the early days of the internet, disruption was profound and constant: New companies emerged in music, video, e-commerce, publishing, and telephony on an almost yearly basis. The internet appeared to be a space where competition could thrive.\n\nNot anymore.\n\nToday, disruption happens in much smaller ways. The examples are getting fewer because economies of scale have concentrated innovation in the hands of a few players.\n\nMore often, disruption comes from regulation\u2014for better or, often, for worse. Current regulation attempts focus on the actions and behavior of some actors\u2014chiefly Facebook\u2014while creating unintended consequences for the internet, particularly fragmentation, or the splintering of the global internet into one that more closely hews territorial borders.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIt\u2019s understandable that both the public and regulators might think that regulating \u201cthe internet\u201d means focusing on the biggest players. Much of it has to do with the fact that users are often exposed to various types of illegal behavior and content through some of the most popular services that exist on the internet. Fix misinformation, or extremism, or ideological silos, or security on Facebook, the thinking goes, and you\u2019ve fixed it on the internet as a whole.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nBut this is an unhelpful and misguided narrative. First, the internet is not a monolith, so treating it as if it is simply will not work. Second, many of the issues regulators are trying to address are not internet problems; they are societal. Terrorism, child abuse, and mis- and disinformation are not an offspring of the internet; they existed before the internet, and they will continue to exist after it as they are ingrained in human societies. Yet, they are treated as if they are exclusively internet problems. Third, and most importantly, regulators should stop thinking of the internet as Facebook and treating it as such. In the internet regulatory landscape, there is a mixed bag of different issues, and Facebook\u2019s involvement in all of them, direct or indirect, adds to the current complexity. Content moderation, privacy, intermediary liability, competition, encryption\u2014these are all broader issues related to the internet, not just Facebook. Yet, the pattern that has emerged is to treat them as Facebook issues. What this means is that, instead of focusing on trying to address them in ways appropriate for the entire internet ecosystem, they are addressed through the Facebook lens. This has been quite accurately characterized as the \u201cFacebook Derangement Syndrome.\u201d\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThe global regulatory agenda is replete with such examples. In the United Kingdom, the Online Safety legislation wants to ban end-to-end encryption because of Facebook\u2019s plan to introduce it as a default setting in its Messenger service. On the other side of the Commonwealth, Australia recently introduced a media bargaining code mainly targeting Facebook. Facebook famously \u201cleft\u201d the country before renegotiating a new agreement. Similarly, in what seems to be a coordinated effort, Canada has vowed to work with Australia in an attempt to impose regulatory restrictions on Facebook.\n\nAnd this trend is not limited to the Commonwealth.\n\nIndia\u2019s new intermediary guidelines aim at tightening a regulatory grip on Facebook and its partner company WhatsApp while Brazil\u2019s fake news bill, which got approved by the Senate, is focusing on content moderation on Facebook and traceability on WhatsApp. In France, there have been conversations about the introduction of \u201cnew rules\u201d for Facebook, while Germany\u2019s Network Enforcement Law\u2014NetzDG\u2014was drafted with the primary focus of taming Facebook. Finally, in the United States, the Trump administration issued an unsuccessful executive order that aimed to regulate Facebook for bias.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nThis approach of limiting regulation to Facebook is not entirely unusual. It reflects the principal-agent conundrum that, over the years, has allowed companies like Facebook to \u00a0propose policies and deploy tools that can have an impact on the way regulation gets to be enforced. The principal-agent problem is predominantly characterized by conflict of interest and moral hazards. Due to information asymmetries, the agent holds the bargaining power, and this creates a few unknowns: The principal is in no position to know the information the agent holds. Even when she does, she cannot be certain that the agent is acting to her best interest. So, the principal ends up focusing squarely on the agent, disregarding any peripheral issues that might be significant.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThe principal-agent problem may help explain why governments appear ready to introduce regulation targeting Facebook; however, it does not help explain why, in the process of doing so, the main loser is the internet and its users.\n\nOver the past couple of years, Facebook has said, \u201cWe support regulation,\u201d and \u201cwe want updated internet regulations to set clear guidelines for addressing today\u2019s toughest challenges.\u201d This statement would be significant if it did not come across as self-serving. At this stage, regulation is inescapable and Facebook knows it\u2014as does the rest of big tech. In an effort to adapt to this new reality, companies often take advantage of their dominant position to drive regulatory processes, often at the expense of regulation itself.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIn this context, the question we should be asking is not whether regulation is appropriate, but what are the real implications of regulating in such a manner? There is already an argument that focusing on a few, big players has an impact on the health of innovation and the ability of newcomers to compete. And, then, there is the internet. The internet\u2019s global reach is one of its main strengths. It is a feature, not a bug. Among other things, it allows the maintenance of supply chains all over the world; it allows people to communicate; it lowers costs; and it makes information sharing easier, all the while helping to address societal issues like poverty or climate change.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nTo this end, the attempt to regulate based on one\u2014or a handful\u2014of companies can jeopardize this very important goal of the internet. It can create fragmentation, in the sense of not allowing data to flow across borders or networks to interconnect, and this can be very real and have a very big impact. It can impose limits on the way information and data gets to be shared and the way networks may interoperate. These are significant trade-offs, and they must be part of any regulation\u2019s process.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nSo where do we go from here?\n\nFor sure, the answer cannot be to stop regulating. We must accept, however, that the current approach often generates unintended consequences that only superficially affect those who must be regulated.\n\nIn this light, a possible way forward is to experiment with regulation. Experimental regulation is a relatively underused approach, yet it is flexible enough to accommodate dynamic markets, like the internet. Originally associated with the work of John Dewey, this idea is premised on the fact that, in policymaking, the way we approach theories and strategies of justice depends on \u201cthe experience of their pursuit; it is these changes that then allow us to consider how best to achieve our objectives.\u201d The advantage of this thinking is that it considers unintended consequences as an opportunity to better define appropriate regulatory frameworks and how to achieve the desired goals.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nInternet regulation does not experiment enough, and when it does, it appears to have the wrong focus. In Australia, for instance, the effort to ensure robust journalism in an age of disinformation in social media platforms led to a \u201clink tax\u201d that undermines the architecture, history, and economics of the internet. This is partly due to the role big tech companies play in the regulatory process. One of the immediate things one can observe with internet regulation is the process some actors deploy: In the beginning, they operate in favor of sustaining existing policies and bureaucracies. The thinking is that longevity brings legitimacy, and as a result, the policy becomes its own cause. Once this strategy is embedded in process, these powerful forces move toward pushing their own regulatory agenda.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIt is for this reason that there is a certain appeal toward flexible regulatory systems that allow different units to experiment with different approaches and make room for assessments that separate the relevant from the nonrelevant and preexisting rules. Although experimentation neither offers a drastic approach nor aims to replace traditional routes of regulation, it can limit the risks of politicization, as politics become more context focused.\n\nOne of the first things we need is an internet impact assessment that looks at the different parts of the internet\u2019s infrastructure and the effect that regulation may have. It is no longer just about regulating a few actors. It is about protecting the global infrastructure that we all depend on daily.\n\nThe internet has a Facebook problem, but the internet is not Facebook.\n\nThis article represents the views of the author and not those of his employer, the Internet Society. Facebook is an organization member of the Internet Society.\u00a0\n\nFuture Tense is a partnership of Slate, New America, and Arizona State University that examines emerging technologies, public policy, and society.\n\nAdvertisement","url":"https://slate.com/technology/2021/08/facebook-internet-regulation.html?via=rss"},"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":{"id":"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229","text":"23 / 06 / 2023 - 13: 25\nThe rise and fall of social networking sites: major projects that have faded over the past years\nIn recent years, the Internet has seen the rapid rise and subsequent disappearance of social media platforms, which according to studies can be attributed to the failure to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives.\n(Getty)\nThe rapid development of the digital age has brought many changes to the ways of communication over the past years, as the Internet world has witnessed the rise and fall of various communication sites, platforms that once flourished and flourished but eventually faded into oblivion.\nIn recent years, the Internet has seen the rapid rise and subsequent disappearance of social media platforms, which according to studies can be attributed to the failure to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives, which also indicate the rapid pace of technological progress and the need for continuous innovation.\nMySpace has enjoyed unprecedented popularity during the mid-2000s, providing users with a platform to connect, share media and express themselves creatively, however, the decline of MySpace began when Facebook emerged as a dominant force in the social media landscape, studies show that MySpace failed to adapt to the changing preferences of their user base. This resulted in a loss of relevance and decreased user engagement.\nLaunched in 2004, Orkut was a pioneer in social networking, particularly in countries such as Brazil and India, and despite its early success, Orkut struggled to combat spam, privacy concerns and the rise of rival platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.\nAs studies indicate, the lack of innovation and failure to address these issues eventually led to their demise in 2014, which also happened with the site \"First Messenger\" which was once an integral part of the lives of many people on the Internet, allowing users to communicate in real time and facilitate conversations and enhance communication between users. Like WhatsApp and Facebook Messenger, they have wiped out the site \u2019 s last hope of survival, amidst this massive and rapid technological development.\nIn 2011, Google Plus was launched, which was aimed at competing with Facebook and creating a social network within Google \u2019 s ecosystem, and despite the company \u2019 s vast resources, it failed to attract a large user base, which led to the fall of the app in 2019, which led to the company \u2019 s closure of the project due to a decline in the number of users.\nIn another example, Vine had gained immense popularity with its unique six-second videos, which served as a breeding ground for budding creators and led to numerous viral trends, however, Vine \u2019 s downfall is attributed to its failure to monetize content effectively, and the emergence of rival and powerful platforms such as Instagram and Snapchat.\nDelicious is a harsh example of the fall of a social media platform, where the site faced major challenges due to the lack of effective monetization strategies, and the emergence of new competitors on the platform, which led to a sharp decline in the user base, and ultimately sold and re-launched, under new ownership.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0018.json.gz:42903","uncompressed_offset":740013229,"url":"www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/2023/06/23/%D8%B5%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%87%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B7-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B9-%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-06-23T11:27:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7>","warc_url":"https://www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/2023/06/23/%D8%B5%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%87%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B7-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B9-%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-06-23T11:56:23.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1070","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1070","narrative_id":"1070"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The history of LiveJournal is a fascinating story of how a simple journaling application transformed into a popular blogging platform, and eventually, its decline in popularity."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"LiveJournal was created by Brad Fitzpatrick, who initially developed it as a personal journaling tool, but later transformed it into a website that others could use as well."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"At its peak, LiveJournal had more than 2.5 million active accounts, but its peak was almost 10 years ago, in early 2005, and since then, most of the English-speaking world seemed to have forgotten about it."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"The platform's unique features, such as friend groups, custom user profiles, and comment threading, made it different from other blogging platforms, allowing users to connect with each other and share their thoughts and experiences."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"LiveJournal's early success can be attributed to its innovative approach to social networking, which combined blogging and social networking features, inspired by the WELL, a pioneering online community."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"The site's popularity grew rapidly, and by 2005, it had become one of the leading blogging platforms, with a large and active user base."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"However, the rise of other social media platforms, such as Facebook, which launched in 2004, and later, other blogging sites, led to a decline in LiveJournal's popularity."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"The failure of social media platforms to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives, also contributed to LiveJournal's decline."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"Other social media platforms, such as Google Plus, Vine, and Delicious, also faced similar challenges, and ultimately, failed to attract and retain a large user base."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"Google Plus, for example, was launched in 2011, but despite its vast resources, it failed to attract a large user base, leading to its decline and eventual closure in 2019."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"Vine, on the other hand, gained immense popularity with its unique six-second videos, but its failure to monetize content effectively, and the emergence of rival platforms, such as Instagram and Snapchat, led to its decline."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"Delicious, another social media platform, faced major challenges due to the lack of effective monetization strategies, and the emergence of new competitors, leading to a sharp decline in its user base."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"In contrast, Reddit, which was launched less than a year after Digg, was able to thrive, despite initial challenges, and eventually became one of the leading social media platforms."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"Reddit's success can be attributed to its ability to adapt to changing trends, and its commitment to providing a platform for users to share and discuss content."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"The site's unique features, such as its voting system, and comment threading, allowed users to engage with each other, and share their thoughts and experiences."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"Today, LiveJournal is no longer a leading blogging platform, but its legacy continues to be felt, and its impact on the blogging community remains significant."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"The story of LiveJournal serves as a reminder of the importance of adapting to changing trends, and the need for social media platforms to continuously innovate and improve their services."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the history of LiveJournal is a complex and fascinating story, which highlights the challenges and opportunities faced by social media platforms, and the importance of innovation and adaptability in the rapidly changing digital landscape."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The history of LiveJournal is a fascinating story of how a simple journaling application transformed into a popular blogging platform, and eventually, its decline in popularity."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"LiveJournal was created by Brad Fitzpatrick, who initially developed it as a personal journaling tool, but later transformed it into a website that others could use as well."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"At its peak, LiveJournal had more than 2.5 million active accounts, but its peak was almost 10 years ago, in early 2005, and since then, most of the English-speaking world seemed to have forgotten about it."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"The platform's unique features, such as friend groups, custom user profiles, and comment threading, made it different from other blogging platforms, allowing users to connect with each other and share their thoughts and experiences."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_94574