a sharp decline in its user base."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"In contrast, Reddit, which was launched less than a year after Digg, was able to thrive, despite initial challenges, and eventually became one of the leading social media platforms."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"Reddit's success can be attributed to its ability to adapt to changing trends, and its commitment to providing a platform for users to share and discuss content."},{"citations":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":1.0},"text":"The site's unique features, such as its voting system, and comment threading, allowed users to engage with each other, and share their thoughts and experiences."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"Today, LiveJournal is no longer a leading blogging platform, but its legacy continues to be felt, and its impact on the blogging community remains significant."},{"citations":{"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":1.0},"text":"The story of LiveJournal serves as a reminder of the importance of adapting to changing trends, and the need for social media platforms to continuously innovate and improve their services."},{"citations":{"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the history of LiveJournal is a complex and fascinating story, which highlights the challenges and opportunities faced by social media platforms, and the importance of innovation and adaptability in the rapidly changing digital landscape."}],"references":["9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229","53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342","bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633"],"documents":{"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633":{"id":"bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21_287908633","text":"Rewrite this title: Reddit thrives from Digg v4 disaster\nNext article will help you: Reddit is thriving from the Digg v4 disaster\nSince the launch of Digg \u2019 s latest version, v4, last week, the less warm reception has caused a massive influx of traffic to their competitor \u2013 Reddit.\nReddit was launched less than a year after Digg \u2019 s launch, and it wasn \u2019 t very popular, but it had very loyal users.\nHowever, starting Sunday night, the four-person team saw an increase in new users, unique items, and the number of page views in staggering numbers.\nChief programmer, Chris Slaw, stated that unique page views alone have increased by 50% \u2013 averaging around 900,000 per day since Monday morning.\nThey also report between 13 and 14 million total page views per day.\nApproximately 25% of the site \u2019 s visitors were people who signed up for the site and became \u201cjunior editors \u201d as Chris calls them on the site.\nBlog site.\nAs their numbers grew so fast, Reddit employees were surprised that the site didn \u2019 t crash.\nTheir blog also says that they work most days within the site \u2019 s peak capacity and that they \u201ccould never have survived such an unexpected surge. \u201d\nEvelyn Rosley of Tech Crunch spoke with Slough and says they are currently working on new features to keep Redditors happy and to make sure the site can maintain its new and larger user base, including a redesigned user interface.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0029.json.gz:50539","uncompressed_offset":287908633,"url":"choq.fm/rewrite-this-title-%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%8A%D8%B2%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%B1-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AB%D8%A9-digg-v4/","warc_date":"2023-10-10T14:04:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:bd531fbc-1741-4053-8a7a-8c680a91df21>","warc_url":"https://choq.fm/rewrite-this-title-%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%8A%D8%B2%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%B1-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AB%D8%A9-digg-v4/"},"created":"2023-10-10T14:16:15.000Z","lang":"eng"},"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342":{"id":"53771f36-e205-47fa-9bad-b8de615490f6_945743342","text":"Regulators Seem to Think That Facebook Is the Internet\n\nThat\u2019s a problem.\n\nIn 1997, SixDegrees.com was the first real attempt at social networking, creating a space where users could upload their information and list their friends. The site peaked at approximately 3.5 million users before it shut down in 1999.\n\nSince then, a series of social networking business models have emerged, each time offering more advanced tools for user interaction. LiveJournal, a site for keeping up with school friends, combined blogging and social networking features inspired by the WELL; Friendster was a social network that allowed for increased interaction and control by users; Myspace had open membership and gave users the freedom to customize their pages. In 2005, it\u2014and its 25 million user base\u2014was sold to News Corp. But within three years, Myspace had been surpassed by Facebook, which launched in 2004 for college students and opened to everyone in 2006.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nAs that history shows, in the early days of the internet, disruption was profound and constant: New companies emerged in music, video, e-commerce, publishing, and telephony on an almost yearly basis. The internet appeared to be a space where competition could thrive.\n\nNot anymore.\n\nToday, disruption happens in much smaller ways. The examples are getting fewer because economies of scale have concentrated innovation in the hands of a few players.\n\nMore often, disruption comes from regulation\u2014for better or, often, for worse. Current regulation attempts focus on the actions and behavior of some actors\u2014chiefly Facebook\u2014while creating unintended consequences for the internet, particularly fragmentation, or the splintering of the global internet into one that more closely hews territorial borders.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIt\u2019s understandable that both the public and regulators might think that regulating \u201cthe internet\u201d means focusing on the biggest players. Much of it has to do with the fact that users are often exposed to various types of illegal behavior and content through some of the most popular services that exist on the internet. Fix misinformation, or extremism, or ideological silos, or security on Facebook, the thinking goes, and you\u2019ve fixed it on the internet as a whole.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nBut this is an unhelpful and misguided narrative. First, the internet is not a monolith, so treating it as if it is simply will not work. Second, many of the issues regulators are trying to address are not internet problems; they are societal. Terrorism, child abuse, and mis- and disinformation are not an offspring of the internet; they existed before the internet, and they will continue to exist after it as they are ingrained in human societies. Yet, they are treated as if they are exclusively internet problems. Third, and most importantly, regulators should stop thinking of the internet as Facebook and treating it as such. In the internet regulatory landscape, there is a mixed bag of different issues, and Facebook\u2019s involvement in all of them, direct or indirect, adds to the current complexity. Content moderation, privacy, intermediary liability, competition, encryption\u2014these are all broader issues related to the internet, not just Facebook. Yet, the pattern that has emerged is to treat them as Facebook issues. What this means is that, instead of focusing on trying to address them in ways appropriate for the entire internet ecosystem, they are addressed through the Facebook lens. This has been quite accurately characterized as the \u201cFacebook Derangement Syndrome.\u201d\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThe global regulatory agenda is replete with such examples. In the United Kingdom, the Online Safety legislation wants to ban end-to-end encryption because of Facebook\u2019s plan to introduce it as a default setting in its Messenger service. On the other side of the Commonwealth, Australia recently introduced a media bargaining code mainly targeting Facebook. Facebook famously \u201cleft\u201d the country before renegotiating a new agreement. Similarly, in what seems to be a coordinated effort, Canada has vowed to work with Australia in an attempt to impose regulatory restrictions on Facebook.\n\nAnd this trend is not limited to the Commonwealth.\n\nIndia\u2019s new intermediary guidelines aim at tightening a regulatory grip on Facebook and its partner company WhatsApp while Brazil\u2019s fake news bill, which got approved by the Senate, is focusing on content moderation on Facebook and traceability on WhatsApp. In France, there have been conversations about the introduction of \u201cnew rules\u201d for Facebook, while Germany\u2019s Network Enforcement Law\u2014NetzDG\u2014was drafted with the primary focus of taming Facebook. Finally, in the United States, the Trump administration issued an unsuccessful executive order that aimed to regulate Facebook for bias.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nThis approach of limiting regulation to Facebook is not entirely unusual. It reflects the principal-agent conundrum that, over the years, has allowed companies like Facebook to \u00a0propose policies and deploy tools that can have an impact on the way regulation gets to be enforced. The principal-agent problem is predominantly characterized by conflict of interest and moral hazards. Due to information asymmetries, the agent holds the bargaining power, and this creates a few unknowns: The principal is in no position to know the information the agent holds. Even when she does, she cannot be certain that the agent is acting to her best interest. So, the principal ends up focusing squarely on the agent, disregarding any peripheral issues that might be significant.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThe principal-agent problem may help explain why governments appear ready to introduce regulation targeting Facebook; however, it does not help explain why, in the process of doing so, the main loser is the internet and its users.\n\nOver the past couple of years, Facebook has said, \u201cWe support regulation,\u201d and \u201cwe want updated internet regulations to set clear guidelines for addressing today\u2019s toughest challenges.\u201d This statement would be significant if it did not come across as self-serving. At this stage, regulation is inescapable and Facebook knows it\u2014as does the rest of big tech. In an effort to adapt to this new reality, companies often take advantage of their dominant position to drive regulatory processes, often at the expense of regulation itself.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIn this context, the question we should be asking is not whether regulation is appropriate, but what are the real implications of regulating in such a manner? There is already an argument that focusing on a few, big players has an impact on the health of innovation and the ability of newcomers to compete. And, then, there is the internet. The internet\u2019s global reach is one of its main strengths. It is a feature, not a bug. Among other things, it allows the maintenance of supply chains all over the world; it allows people to communicate; it lowers costs; and it makes information sharing easier, all the while helping to address societal issues like poverty or climate change.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nTo this end, the attempt to regulate based on one\u2014or a handful\u2014of companies can jeopardize this very important goal of the internet. It can create fragmentation, in the sense of not allowing data to flow across borders or networks to interconnect, and this can be very real and have a very big impact. It can impose limits on the way information and data gets to be shared and the way networks may interoperate. These are significant trade-offs, and they must be part of any regulation\u2019s process.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nSo where do we go from here?\n\nFor sure, the answer cannot be to stop regulating. We must accept, however, that the current approach often generates unintended consequences that only superficially affect those who must be regulated.\n\nIn this light, a possible way forward is to experiment with regulation. Experimental regulation is a relatively underused approach, yet it is flexible enough to accommodate dynamic markets, like the internet. Originally associated with the work of John Dewey, this idea is premised on the fact that, in policymaking, the way we approach theories and strategies of justice depends on \u201cthe experience of their pursuit; it is these changes that then allow us to consider how best to achieve our objectives.\u201d The advantage of this thinking is that it considers unintended consequences as an opportunity to better define appropriate regulatory frameworks and how to achieve the desired goals.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nInternet regulation does not experiment enough, and when it does, it appears to have the wrong focus. In Australia, for instance, the effort to ensure robust journalism in an age of disinformation in social media platforms led to a \u201clink tax\u201d that undermines the architecture, history, and economics of the internet. This is partly due to the role big tech companies play in the regulatory process. One of the immediate things one can observe with internet regulation is the process some actors deploy: In the beginning, they operate in favor of sustaining existing policies and bureaucracies. The thinking is that longevity brings legitimacy, and as a result, the policy becomes its own cause. Once this strategy is embedded in process, these powerful forces move toward pushing their own regulatory agenda.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIt is for this reason that there is a certain appeal toward flexible regulatory systems that allow different units to experiment with different approaches and make room for assessments that separate the relevant from the nonrelevant and preexisting rules. Although experimentation neither offers a drastic approach nor aims to replace traditional routes of regulation, it can limit the risks of politicization, as politics become more context focused.\n\nOne of the first things we need is an internet impact assessment that looks at the different parts of the internet\u2019s infrastructure and the effect that regulation may have. It is no longer just about regulating a few actors. It is about protecting the global infrastructure that we all depend on daily.\n\nThe internet has a Facebook problem, but the internet is not Facebook.\n\nThis article represents the views of the author and not those of his employer, the Internet Society. Facebook is an organization member of the Internet Society.\u00a0\n\nFuture Tense is a partnership of Slate, New America, and Arizona State University that examines emerging technologies, public policy, and society.\n\nAdvertisement","url":"https://slate.com/technology/2021/08/facebook-internet-regulation.html?via=rss"},"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229":{"id":"9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7_740013229","text":"23 / 06 / 2023 - 13: 25\nThe rise and fall of social networking sites: major projects that have faded over the past years\nIn recent years, the Internet has seen the rapid rise and subsequent disappearance of social media platforms, which according to studies can be attributed to the failure to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives.\n(Getty)\nThe rapid development of the digital age has brought many changes to the ways of communication over the past years, as the Internet world has witnessed the rise and fall of various communication sites, platforms that once flourished and flourished but eventually faded into oblivion.\nIn recent years, the Internet has seen the rapid rise and subsequent disappearance of social media platforms, which according to studies can be attributed to the failure to adapt to changing trends, privacy concerns, intense competition, and the emergence of more alternatives, which also indicate the rapid pace of technological progress and the need for continuous innovation.\nMySpace has enjoyed unprecedented popularity during the mid-2000s, providing users with a platform to connect, share media and express themselves creatively, however, the decline of MySpace began when Facebook emerged as a dominant force in the social media landscape, studies show that MySpace failed to adapt to the changing preferences of their user base. This resulted in a loss of relevance and decreased user engagement.\nLaunched in 2004, Orkut was a pioneer in social networking, particularly in countries such as Brazil and India, and despite its early success, Orkut struggled to combat spam, privacy concerns and the rise of rival platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.\nAs studies indicate, the lack of innovation and failure to address these issues eventually led to their demise in 2014, which also happened with the site \"First Messenger\" which was once an integral part of the lives of many people on the Internet, allowing users to communicate in real time and facilitate conversations and enhance communication between users. Like WhatsApp and Facebook Messenger, they have wiped out the site \u2019 s last hope of survival, amidst this massive and rapid technological development.\nIn 2011, Google Plus was launched, which was aimed at competing with Facebook and creating a social network within Google \u2019 s ecosystem, and despite the company \u2019 s vast resources, it failed to attract a large user base, which led to the fall of the app in 2019, which led to the company \u2019 s closure of the project due to a decline in the number of users.\nIn another example, Vine had gained immense popularity with its unique six-second videos, which served as a breeding ground for budding creators and led to numerous viral trends, however, Vine \u2019 s downfall is attributed to its failure to monetize content effectively, and the emergence of rival and powerful platforms such as Instagram and Snapchat.\nDelicious is a harsh example of the fall of a social media platform, where the site faced major challenges due to the lack of effective monetization strategies, and the emergence of new competitors on the platform, which led to a sharp decline in the user base, and ultimately sold and re-launched, under new ownership.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0018.json.gz:42903","uncompressed_offset":740013229,"url":"www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/2023/06/23/%D8%B5%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%87%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B7-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B9-%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-06-23T11:27:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9119d2a4-5189-427f-a26b-e1fe15af2bf7>","warc_url":"https://www.arab48.com/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7/2023/06/23/%D8%B5%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%87%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%B7-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B9-%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-06-23T11:56:23.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1071","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1071","narrative_id":"1071"},"responses":[{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The medication shortage is a growing global concern, with the number of drug shortages reaching a record high of 323 drugs in the first three months of 2024, according to data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah Drug Information Service."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"This surge in drug shortages has been steady since 2021, with organizations tracking drug shortages for the first time in 2001."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The shortages affect various categories of drugs, including sterile injectable generic drugs, cancer chemotherapy drugs, and emergency drugs stored in hospital vans and procedural areas."},{"citations":{"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":1.0},"text":"Hospital pharmacists are reporting a critical shortage of chemotherapy drugs, with nearly all hospitals facing overall medicine supply gaps, and 99% reporting some drug supply shortages."},{"citations":{"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":1.0},"text":"The scarcity of key drugs is prompting hospitals to find or substitute drugs and change treatment plans as needed, with 1 in 3 health systems forced to delay, cancel, or ration care."},{"citations":{"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476":1.0},"text":"The affected drugs include widely used medications such as diabetes drugs Ozempic and Mounjaro, allergy treatment drug adrenaline, and common antibiotic amoxicillin for children."},{"citations":{"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607":1.0},"text":"The FDA has also reported 111 drug shortages, including heart disease drug digoxin injection, chemical drug Dacarbazine, and some antibiotics."},{"citations":{"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607":1.0},"text":"The supply chain crisis and labor shortages are contributing to the medication shortage, with 60% of pharmacies surveyed dealing with supply chain disruptions and nearly 70% struggling to fill staff vacancies."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The medication shortage has significant implications for healthcare systems, with the average shortage affecting at least half a million patients, many of them elderly."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"Overall, the medication shortage is a complex issue with far-reaching consequences, requiring urgent attention and action from healthcare systems and policymakers."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The medication shortage is a growing global concern, with the number of drug shortages reaching a record high of 323 drugs in the first three months of 2024, according to data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah Drug Information Service."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"This surge in drug shortages has been steady since 2021, with organizations tracking drug shortages for the first time in 2001."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The shortages affect various categories of drugs, including sterile injectable generic drugs, cancer chemotherapy drugs, and emergency drugs stored in hospital vans and procedural areas."},{"citations":{"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":1.0},"text":"Hospital pharmacists are reporting a critical shortage of chemotherapy drugs, with nearly all hospitals facing overall medicine supply gaps, and 99% reporting some drug supply shortages."},{"citations":{"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":1.0},"text":"The scarcity of key drugs is prompting hospitals to find or substitute drugs and change treatment plans as needed, with 1 in 3 health systems forced to delay, cancel, or ration care."},{"citations":{"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476":1.0},"text":"The affected drugs include widely used medications such as diabetes drugs Ozempic and Mounjaro, allergy treatment drug adrenaline, and common antibiotic amoxicillin for children."},{"citations":{"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607":1.0},"text":"The FDA has also reported 111 drug shortages, including heart disease drug digoxin injection, chemical drug Dacarbazine, and some antibiotics."},{"citations":{"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607":1.0},"text":"The supply chain crisis and labor shortages are contributing to the medication shortage, with 60% of pharmacies surveyed dealing with supply chain disruptions and nearly 70% struggling to fill staff vacancies."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"The medication shortage has significant implications for healthcare systems, with the average shortage affecting at least half a million patients, many of them elderly."},{"citations":{"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":1.0},"text":"Overall, the medication shortage is a complex issue with far-reaching consequences, requiring urgent attention and action from healthcare systems and policymakers."}],"references":["d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049","3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607","039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968","5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476"],"documents":{"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607":{"id":"3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8_980828607","text":"US supply chain crisis continues, FDA points to 111 drug shortages\nGlobal Social Hotspot 16: 35 2021 / 12 / 05\nShare:\nThe supply chain crisis in the United States continues, and many goods are facing shortages.\nThe US media said that the US pharmacies have a number of critical prescription drugs in stock. The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) pointed out that about 111 drugs are out of stock in the United States. The FDA stressed that it will continue to take measures to monitor the supply chain.\n\u3010 Omicron variant \u3011 Travellers must have a negative test within 48 hours for entering the United Kingdom \u3010 Next \u3011\nThe Federal Reserve warned on Wednesday that large parts of the United States had begun to be affected by supply chain disruptions and labor shortages last month.\nAccording to the FDA website, 111 drugs are out of stock in the United States, including the heart disease drug digoxin injection, the chemical drug Dacarbazine and some antibiotics.\nThe authorities say there are many reasons for the shortage, including production problems, quality problems, drugs and even the suspension of production.\nAccording to the FDA, about 80% of the manufacturers of active pharmaceutical ingredients are located overseas, and the manufacturers have provided the FDA with most of the drug shortage information.\nThe Administration will also work closely with these manufacturers to address the drug shortage.\n\u3010 Omicron variant \u3011 Study: Omicron carries a cold virus gene or helps avoid the immune system \u3010 Next \u3011\nLong Island Newspaper Newsday quoted Tom D'Angelo, president of the New York State Association of Pharmacists, as saying the shipping of a large number of medicines, including those for common blood pressure and for the treatment of colds and flu, was blocked.\nBecause of supply chain problems, the owner of a New York drugstore said there were fewer brands for some drugs, including Ibuprofen.\nThe National Association of Community Pharmacists (NCPA) released a survey last month that found that most non-chain pharmacies are struggling to fill employee vacancies and cope with supply chain disruptions.\nSixty percent of pharmacies surveyed said they were dealing with supply chain disruptions, and nearly 70 percent said it was difficult to fill staff vacancies.\nStay abreast of the latest development of mutant virus and epidemic vaccine, download the Hong Kong Economic Times App for free now \u3010 Click here\nEditor-in-Chief: Cheng Kam-ling\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook\nSubscribe to the Hong Kong Economic Times email newsletter\nReceive first-hand financial news Learn more about investment and financial knowledge Submit my consent to receive promotional messages from Hong Kong Economic Times Group. You may also check the privacy policy of this website Terms of Use","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0035.json.gz:16242","uncompressed_offset":980828607,"url":"inews.hket.com/article/3124205/%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E4%BE%9B%E6%87%89%E9%8F%88%E5%8D%B1%E6%A9%9F%E6%8C%81%E7%BA%8C%20FDA%E6%8C%87111%E6%AC%BE%E8%97%A5%E7%89%A9%E7%9F%AD%E7%BC%BA","warc_date":"2021-12-05T07:21:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8>","warc_url":"https://inews.hket.com/article/3124205/%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E4%BE%9B%E6%87%89%E9%8F%88%E5%8D%B1%E6%A9%9F%E6%8C%81%E7%BA%8C%20FDA%E6%8C%87111%E6%AC%BE%E8%97%A5%E7%89%A9%E7%9F%AD%E7%BC%BA"},"created":"2021-12-05T08:57:41.000Z","lang":"eng"},"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476":{"id":"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476","text":"Meitu\nThe first quarter of the United States serious drug shortage 323 drugs urgent cancer patients also have to be diverted and rationed!\nCHU HENG NETWORK NEWS CENTER 2024-04-16 10: 42\nAccording to the latest data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists (ASHP) and the Utah Center for Drug Information Services, a total of 323 drugs in the United States were in severe shortages in the first quarter of this year, surpassing the record of 320 in 2014.\nAmong the drugs affected are the widely used diabetes drugs Ozempic and Mounjaro, the allergy treatment drug adrenaline, the common antibiotic amoxicillin for children, chemotherapy drugs and injections commonly used in hospitals in intensive care.\nASHP CEO Paul Abramowitz said in a statement that almost all categories of drugs are facing shortages, with non-patented sterile injectable drugs, including cancer chemotherapy drugs, and emergency drugs stored in hospital emergency vans and operating areas, the shortage of such drugs is the most worrying.\nAccording to the American Cancer Society, chemotherapy is one of the top five drugs most affected by the shortage, which threatens to have a devastating impact on patients, and some hospitals and clinics say doctors have had to divert patients to ration their medications because of a shortage of some chemotherapy drugs.\nIn addition, ASHP noted that the continued nationwide shortage of ADHD drugs is \u201ca problem for clinicians and patients. \u201d\nThe shortage of popular drugs is even more acute, with Mounjaro, the diabetes drug known as the \u201cslimming pill \u201d, already in dire straits.\nIn response, Lilly said that the \u201cunprecedented surge in demand \u201d for Mounjaro and its similar drug Zepbound has led to a shortage in the market, which the company is struggling to cope with.\nLilly is ramping up investments to boost production at Mounjaro and Zepbound in the second half of 2024.\nThe company said it expects intermittent supply disruptions in the near term due to unprecedented demand.\nHow to cure the drug shortage\nThe last major \u201cdrug shortage \u201d in U.S. history occurred in 2014, and it has only been alleviated in the years since.\nSince 2021, the drug shortage situation seems to be increasing, and scholars in the field of medical health and economics in the United States believe that the reason for most drug shortages in the United States is the fragmentation of the drug supply chain.\nThe White House this month proposed spending between $3.26 billion and $5.11 billion over the next decade to help address the nation \u2019 s drug shortage.\nThe bill requires approval and funding from the U.S. Congress.\nU.S. researchers and policymakers believe that a complete solution to the \u201cdrug shortage \u201d may require changes to the business model of the U.S. pharmaceutical industry, including measures to increase the price of generic drugs to attract more drug manufacturers.\nPolicymakers recommend giving the FDA more power to access more information about drug shortages and impending shortages.\nCurrently, the FDA relies primarily on phone calls to manufacturers asking if they can increase their supply to understand the situation.\nThe American Society of Health System Pharmacists said it is working with the federal government to advise the government on measures to address the drug shortage, including that Congress should require manufacturers to be more transparent on any supply chain issues and encourage more diversity in supply chains.\nAccording to Abramowitz, \u201cThe federal government still has a lot of work to do to fundamentally address drug shortages, and the American Society of Health System Pharmacists will continue to engage regularly with policymakers to guide them in drafting and passing new legislation to address drug shortages and continue to advocate vigorously for proven solutions on behalf of our members. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:6247","uncompressed_offset":193716476,"url":"news.cnyes.com/news/id/5525954","warc_date":"2024-04-16T03:48:48.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b>","warc_url":"https://news.cnyes.com/news/id/5525954"},"created":"2024-04-16T04:04:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":{"id":"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049","text":"As drug shortage list grows, many hospitals face tough decisions on rationing care\n\nMore than half of hospital pharmacists are reporting a critical shortage of chemotherapy drugs and nearly all are reporting overall medicine supply gaps as prescription drug shortages near an all time high, according to a new survey.\n\nHospital pharmacists said drug shortages have forced 1 in 3 health systems to delay, cancel or ration care or switch to alternate drugs to continue to treat patients. And 99% are reporting some drug supply shortages, an American Society of Health-System Pharmacists survey of more than 1,000 pharmacists released Thursday found.\n\nThe organization reported shortages of 309 drugs, near the all-time high of 320 shortages in 2014. The scarcity of key drugs is prompting hospitals to find or substitute drugs and change treatment plans as needed.\n\n\u201cIn some cases, there are no alternatives to the affected drugs, which puts patients at risk,\" ASHP Chief Executive Officer Paul W. Abramowitz said in a statement. \"This issue requires quick action from Congress to address the underlying causes of shortages and ensure patients have the medications they need.\u201d\n\nCancer drug shortages\n\nIn June, the Food and Drug Administration said it will temporarily allow overseas drug manufacturers to import some chemotherapy drugs.\n\nThe FDA allowed Qilu Pharmaceutical, a drug manufacturer in China, to import the injectable chemotherapy drug cisplatin in 50-milligram vials. Toronto pharmaceutical company Apotex Corp. will distribute the medication in the United States.\n\nMore than a dozen cancer drugs have been in shortage in recent months, including cisplatin and carboplatin, used to treat lung, breast, prostate and gynecologic cancers. The National Cancer Institute said cisplatin and similar drugs are prescribed for 10% to 20% of all cancer patients.\n\nIn June, the National Comprehensive Cancer Network released a survey of 27 academic cancer centers that found 93% reported shortages of carboplatin and 70% faced shortages of cisplatin.\n\nWhen cancer hospitals face such shortages, they attempt to make sure there's enough medication for patients to finish the course of treatment, said Mike Ganio, ASHP's senior director of pharmacy practice and quality.\n\nCancer hospitals facing such shortages might change medications for new patients starting on chemotherapy, said Ganio, a former pharmacy manager at an academic cancer center.\n\n\"You try to keep that patient on the same regimen as much as you can, unless they're failing it for some reason, and then you would switch,\" Ganio said.\n\nSteroids, hormonal drugs also in short supply\n\nMore than 1 in 5 hospital pharmacists also reported shortages for steroids, hormonal drugs and oral liquids such as lidocaine, ibuprofen and amoxicillin.\n\nA smaller number of pharmacists said heart medications, emergency prefilled syringes and drugs used for intensive care unit patients were in short supply. Others reported shortages of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder medicines, antimicrobial drugs and injectable opioids.\n\nIn all, about two-thirds of pharmacists said the shortages were \"moderately impactful,\" which means they are managing shortages but patients are affected.\n\nPharmacists are managing the shortages by offering therapeutic alternatives, buying different vial sizes or concentrations and rationing medicines.\n\nThis article originally appeared on USA TODAY: Survey: Drug shortages are widespread, hospitals ration care","url":"https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/drug-shortage-list-grows-many-153710918.html?src=rss"},"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":{"id":"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968","text":"General Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nGeneral Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nAn Unexpected Catastrophe in the World \u2019 s Largest Country: The Complete Story of U.S. Drug Shortages\nThe deficit is at a record level.\nAccording to data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah Drug Information Service, organizations began tracking drug shortages for the first time in 2001. Steady since 2021 \u2013 now reaching a record high of 323 drugs in the first three months of 2024.\nPaul Abramowitz, CEO of the American Society of Health System Pharmacists, wrote in a blog post on Thursday: \u201cIt \u2019 s been a long time to end drug shortages, \u201d and wrote:\u201c All drug classes are vulnerable to shortages, some of the most worrisome shortages include sterile injectable generic drugs, including cancer chemotherapy drugs and emergency drugs stored in hospital vans and procedural areas. It is dangerous for doctors and patients. \u201d\nIn addition to the 32 chemotherapy drugs that are deficient, the five categories of drugs with the greatest deficiency include central nervous system stimulants, antimicrobials, hormonal agents, and intravenous fluids. [1] The Drug Deficiency Database maintained by the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah is based on voluntary reports from practitioners, patients, and others that have been confirmed by manufacturers. The U.S. drug is in short supply, because it captures broader effects on service providers and patients.\nThe crisis has lasted a year and a half.\nMore than half of the treatment shortages have lasted for more than two years, according to an analysis by health consultancy IQVIA, and the average shortage affects at least half a million patients, many of them elderly, according to the US Office of Health and Human Services under the Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation, which shared its analysis with Congress in May.\nGrowing demand can play a role in drug shortages, as with the recent shortage of weight-loss drugs, but often manufacturing and quality problems, such as supply chain gaps and downtime, are the root cause. And varied.\nBut the American Society of Health System Pharmacists has \u201cserious concerns \u201d about parts of this proposal, especially financial sanctions imposed on hospitals that lack the resources to comply with the recommendations, Abramowitz wrote:\u201c We all know that managing shortages is not enough and is not a sustainable solution to the worsening crisis, and there is still a lot of work to be done at the federal level to fix the root causes of drug shortages. \u201d\nWhy Shortage Occurs\nShortages can be caused by high demand, as with the recent shortage of weight-loss drugs, but this is not usually the main problem.\nThe FDA also blames manufacturing and quality problems, supply chain gaps, and downtime, and Dr. Emily Tucker, a drug shortage expert and an assistant professor of industrial engineering at Clemson University, says that when there is an indication of shortages, large health systems often also proactively place large orders, adding to the system \u2019 s stress.\n\u201cI don \u2019 t blame anyone.\n\u201cWhen I talk to all the stakeholders \u2013 whether it \u2019 s wholesalers, manufacturers, or the government \u2013 everyone wants this problem to end, \u201d she said.\nLack of transparency\nDr. Julie Grallo, chief medical officer and executive vice president of the American Society of Clinical Oncology, told the House Committee earlier that the shortage puts providers in a terrible position: \u201cThe drug shortage crisis is forcing providers to make impossible choices, and it is also hindering the development of new drugs. Health drugs are purchased only on a price basis, and manufacturers do not have to disclose the source of their acquisition of the ingredients.\nThe shortage of this generic chemical drug came due to the closure of one factory in India that manufactures the active ingredient after a surprise FDA inspection found \u201csignificant quality issues, \u201d says Jarallo:\u201c We didn \u2019 t know, and there was no transparency regarding the company \u2019 s supply of the majority of active pharmaceutical ingredients to all manufacturers across the board.\nKnowing this in advance, we could have responded much faster, \u201d Dr. Steven Schundlemeyer, director of the PRIME Institute of the University of Minnesota School of Pharmacy, which focuses on economic and management issues, told the committee that as with defense contractors in the United States, New Zealand requires manufacturers to disclose their suppliers, and that information is required.\nEasily accessible in the database.\nRelated Topics","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:7051","uncompressed_offset":1066817968,"url":"www.elbalad.news/6171019","warc_date":"2024-04-14T16:44:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0>","warc_url":"https://www.elbalad.news/6171019"},"created":"2024-04-14T18:21:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
