The US media said that the US pharmacies have a number of critical prescription drugs in stock. The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) pointed out that about 111 drugs are out of stock in the United States. The FDA stressed that it will continue to take measures to monitor the supply chain.\n\u3010 Omicron variant \u3011 Travellers must have a negative test within 48 hours for entering the United Kingdom \u3010 Next \u3011\nThe Federal Reserve warned on Wednesday that large parts of the United States had begun to be affected by supply chain disruptions and labor shortages last month.\nAccording to the FDA website, 111 drugs are out of stock in the United States, including the heart disease drug digoxin injection, the chemical drug Dacarbazine and some antibiotics.\nThe authorities say there are many reasons for the shortage, including production problems, quality problems, drugs and even the suspension of production.\nAccording to the FDA, about 80% of the manufacturers of active pharmaceutical ingredients are located overseas, and the manufacturers have provided the FDA with most of the drug shortage information.\nThe Administration will also work closely with these manufacturers to address the drug shortage.\n\u3010 Omicron variant \u3011 Study: Omicron carries a cold virus gene or helps avoid the immune system \u3010 Next \u3011\nLong Island Newspaper Newsday quoted Tom D'Angelo, president of the New York State Association of Pharmacists, as saying the shipping of a large number of medicines, including those for common blood pressure and for the treatment of colds and flu, was blocked.\nBecause of supply chain problems, the owner of a New York drugstore said there were fewer brands for some drugs, including Ibuprofen.\nThe National Association of Community Pharmacists (NCPA) released a survey last month that found that most non-chain pharmacies are struggling to fill employee vacancies and cope with supply chain disruptions.\nSixty percent of pharmacies surveyed said they were dealing with supply chain disruptions, and nearly 70 percent said it was difficult to fill staff vacancies.\nStay abreast of the latest development of mutant virus and epidemic vaccine, download the Hong Kong Economic Times App for free now \u3010 Click here\nEditor-in-Chief: Cheng Kam-ling\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook\nSubscribe to the Hong Kong Economic Times email newsletter\nReceive first-hand financial news Learn more about investment and financial knowledge Submit my consent to receive promotional messages from Hong Kong Economic Times Group. You may also check the privacy policy of this website Terms of Use","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0035.json.gz:16242","uncompressed_offset":980828607,"url":"inews.hket.com/article/3124205/%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E4%BE%9B%E6%87%89%E9%8F%88%E5%8D%B1%E6%A9%9F%E6%8C%81%E7%BA%8C%20FDA%E6%8C%87111%E6%AC%BE%E8%97%A5%E7%89%A9%E7%9F%AD%E7%BC%BA","warc_date":"2021-12-05T07:21:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:3cb6d465-6538-4ce4-9d4f-649316109ee8>","warc_url":"https://inews.hket.com/article/3124205/%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E4%BE%9B%E6%87%89%E9%8F%88%E5%8D%B1%E6%A9%9F%E6%8C%81%E7%BA%8C%20FDA%E6%8C%87111%E6%AC%BE%E8%97%A5%E7%89%A9%E7%9F%AD%E7%BC%BA"},"created":"2021-12-05T08:57:41.000Z","lang":"eng"},"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476":{"id":"5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b_193716476","text":"Meitu\nThe first quarter of the United States serious drug shortage 323 drugs urgent cancer patients also have to be diverted and rationed!\nCHU HENG NETWORK NEWS CENTER 2024-04-16 10: 42\nAccording to the latest data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists (ASHP) and the Utah Center for Drug Information Services, a total of 323 drugs in the United States were in severe shortages in the first quarter of this year, surpassing the record of 320 in 2014.\nAmong the drugs affected are the widely used diabetes drugs Ozempic and Mounjaro, the allergy treatment drug adrenaline, the common antibiotic amoxicillin for children, chemotherapy drugs and injections commonly used in hospitals in intensive care.\nASHP CEO Paul Abramowitz said in a statement that almost all categories of drugs are facing shortages, with non-patented sterile injectable drugs, including cancer chemotherapy drugs, and emergency drugs stored in hospital emergency vans and operating areas, the shortage of such drugs is the most worrying.\nAccording to the American Cancer Society, chemotherapy is one of the top five drugs most affected by the shortage, which threatens to have a devastating impact on patients, and some hospitals and clinics say doctors have had to divert patients to ration their medications because of a shortage of some chemotherapy drugs.\nIn addition, ASHP noted that the continued nationwide shortage of ADHD drugs is \u201ca problem for clinicians and patients. \u201d\nThe shortage of popular drugs is even more acute, with Mounjaro, the diabetes drug known as the \u201cslimming pill \u201d, already in dire straits.\nIn response, Lilly said that the \u201cunprecedented surge in demand \u201d for Mounjaro and its similar drug Zepbound has led to a shortage in the market, which the company is struggling to cope with.\nLilly is ramping up investments to boost production at Mounjaro and Zepbound in the second half of 2024.\nThe company said it expects intermittent supply disruptions in the near term due to unprecedented demand.\nHow to cure the drug shortage\nThe last major \u201cdrug shortage \u201d in U.S. history occurred in 2014, and it has only been alleviated in the years since.\nSince 2021, the drug shortage situation seems to be increasing, and scholars in the field of medical health and economics in the United States believe that the reason for most drug shortages in the United States is the fragmentation of the drug supply chain.\nThe White House this month proposed spending between $3.26 billion and $5.11 billion over the next decade to help address the nation \u2019 s drug shortage.\nThe bill requires approval and funding from the U.S. Congress.\nU.S. researchers and policymakers believe that a complete solution to the \u201cdrug shortage \u201d may require changes to the business model of the U.S. pharmaceutical industry, including measures to increase the price of generic drugs to attract more drug manufacturers.\nPolicymakers recommend giving the FDA more power to access more information about drug shortages and impending shortages.\nCurrently, the FDA relies primarily on phone calls to manufacturers asking if they can increase their supply to understand the situation.\nThe American Society of Health System Pharmacists said it is working with the federal government to advise the government on measures to address the drug shortage, including that Congress should require manufacturers to be more transparent on any supply chain issues and encourage more diversity in supply chains.\nAccording to Abramowitz, \u201cThe federal government still has a lot of work to do to fundamentally address drug shortages, and the American Society of Health System Pharmacists will continue to engage regularly with policymakers to guide them in drafting and passing new legislation to address drug shortages and continue to advocate vigorously for proven solutions on behalf of our members. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:6247","uncompressed_offset":193716476,"url":"news.cnyes.com/news/id/5525954","warc_date":"2024-04-16T03:48:48.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:5ce83679-158d-4b58-b20f-9f406ab7e58b>","warc_url":"https://news.cnyes.com/news/id/5525954"},"created":"2024-04-16T04:04:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2b594cc2-e41f-46db-a26c-7a42ec0c6695_921023273":{"id":"2b594cc2-e41f-46db-a26c-7a42ec0c6695_921023273","text":"A global study by The Lancet found that there are about 6.4 million doctors missing in the world.\nTo date, more than 12.8 million specialists with a medical diploma work in the field of health care, but much more is needed.\nStaffing capacity\nThe study, titled \u201cMeasuring human resource affordability for health and its relationship to universal health coverage for 204 countries and territories from 1990 to 2019: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study, \u201d was published May 23 in The Lancet.\nThe authors studied the number of doctors, nurses and midwives, dental and pharmaceutical staff and found that as of 2019, there were shortages of doctors in 132 countries.\nGlobally, there are more than 43 million health workers missing when we compare the current level of coverage with the targets needed to achieve universal health coverage.\n\u201cThis is the most comprehensive and comprehensive assessment to date of the global health workforce.\nAdequate numbers of health workers are necessary for the normal functioning of health systems, so it is important to own such data so that countries can make informed decisions and plan for the future, \u201d said the study \u2019 s senior author, director of health organization at the Institute of Health Metrics and Assessment (IHME) at the University of Washington School of Medicine, Dr. Rafael Lozano.\nAs of 2019, there were 104 million healthcare workers worldwide, including 12.8 million doctors, 29.8 million nurses and midwives, 4.6 million dental workers, and 5.2 million pharmacists and pharmacists.\nThe study revealed more than a tenfold difference in the availability of health workers across regions and between countries.\nThe greatest shortage of doctors is in South Asia, where there is a shortage of 2.57 million doctors; in sub-Saharan Africa, there is a shortage of about 1.92 million doctors, in Southeast Asia, East Asia and Oceania - 995,000, in North Africa and the Middle East - 636,000 doctors.\nOn average, there are 16.7 doctors per 10,000 people in the world.\nDensity ranges from 2.9 physicians per 10,000 population in sub-Saharan Africa to 38.3 per 10,000 in Central and Eastern Europe and Central Asia.\nCuba unexpectedly stands out among other countries with an indicator of 84.4 doctors per 10 thousand people (for comparison: 2.1 doctors per 10 thousand in Haiti).\nThe availability of health workers in general is closely related to the level of social and economic development of the region, the authors of the study noted.\nHealth standards\n\u201cThere are various strategies and policy approaches that can help address staffing shortages, and they need to be tailored to the individual situation in each country.\nWe hope that these assessments can be used to prioritize policy actions and inform future planning.\nAchieving high levels of effective health coverage requires a significant increase in the number of health workers worldwide, \u201d the press release said.\nExperts assessed staffing based on the UN Sustainable Development Goals and the WHO Health Personnel 2030 strategy.\nThe authors of the study called on the leaders of countries to pay attention to the problem of shortage of medical workers and to develop comprehensive programs to solve it\nOverall, experts estimate that an additional 6.4 million doctors, 30.6 million nurses, 3.3 million dentists and 2.9 million pharmacists and pharmacists are required to reach the minimum thresholds.\n\u201cWe do not consider these minimum thresholds mandatory, rather desirable.\nWe propose to use them as guidelines, and then the program developers in each country should take into account their own situation and their own experience.\nIn some places, the healthcare system works better with fewer staff, and in some places worse with more staff.\nThe threshold is a convenient and innovative metric for determining gaps, but it should be remembered that this is not only a matter of quantity, but also of quality, \u201d the study says.\nShare the link:\nPadtrymats \u201cPeople \u2019 s Will \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0017.json.gz:133747","uncompressed_offset":921023273,"url":"www.nv-online.info/2022/06/13/mirovoe-zdravoohranenie-ispytyvaet-deficit-vrachej.html","warc_date":"2022-06-13T13:25:26.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2b594cc2-e41f-46db-a26c-7a42ec0c6695>","warc_url":"https://www.nv-online.info/2022/06/13/mirovoe-zdravoohranenie-ispytyvaet-deficit-vrachej.html"},"created":"2022-06-13T14:04:19.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049":{"id":"d940eba4-d6df-4958-a023-bfd57f6a9042_207602049","text":"As drug shortage list grows, many hospitals face tough decisions on rationing care\n\nMore than half of hospital pharmacists are reporting a critical shortage of chemotherapy drugs and nearly all are reporting overall medicine supply gaps as prescription drug shortages near an all time high, according to a new survey.\n\nHospital pharmacists said drug shortages have forced 1 in 3 health systems to delay, cancel or ration care or switch to alternate drugs to continue to treat patients. And 99% are reporting some drug supply shortages, an American Society of Health-System Pharmacists survey of more than 1,000 pharmacists released Thursday found.\n\nThe organization reported shortages of 309 drugs, near the all-time high of 320 shortages in 2014. The scarcity of key drugs is prompting hospitals to find or substitute drugs and change treatment plans as needed.\n\n\u201cIn some cases, there are no alternatives to the affected drugs, which puts patients at risk,\" ASHP Chief Executive Officer Paul W. Abramowitz said in a statement. \"This issue requires quick action from Congress to address the underlying causes of shortages and ensure patients have the medications they need.\u201d\n\nCancer drug shortages\n\nIn June, the Food and Drug Administration said it will temporarily allow overseas drug manufacturers to import some chemotherapy drugs.\n\nThe FDA allowed Qilu Pharmaceutical, a drug manufacturer in China, to import the injectable chemotherapy drug cisplatin in 50-milligram vials. Toronto pharmaceutical company Apotex Corp. will distribute the medication in the United States.\n\nMore than a dozen cancer drugs have been in shortage in recent months, including cisplatin and carboplatin, used to treat lung, breast, prostate and gynecologic cancers. The National Cancer Institute said cisplatin and similar drugs are prescribed for 10% to 20% of all cancer patients.\n\nIn June, the National Comprehensive Cancer Network released a survey of 27 academic cancer centers that found 93% reported shortages of carboplatin and 70% faced shortages of cisplatin.\n\nWhen cancer hospitals face such shortages, they attempt to make sure there's enough medication for patients to finish the course of treatment, said Mike Ganio, ASHP's senior director of pharmacy practice and quality.\n\nCancer hospitals facing such shortages might change medications for new patients starting on chemotherapy, said Ganio, a former pharmacy manager at an academic cancer center.\n\n\"You try to keep that patient on the same regimen as much as you can, unless they're failing it for some reason, and then you would switch,\" Ganio said.\n\nSteroids, hormonal drugs also in short supply\n\nMore than 1 in 5 hospital pharmacists also reported shortages for steroids, hormonal drugs and oral liquids such as lidocaine, ibuprofen and amoxicillin.\n\nA smaller number of pharmacists said heart medications, emergency prefilled syringes and drugs used for intensive care unit patients were in short supply. Others reported shortages of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder medicines, antimicrobial drugs and injectable opioids.\n\nIn all, about two-thirds of pharmacists said the shortages were \"moderately impactful,\" which means they are managing shortages but patients are affected.\n\nPharmacists are managing the shortages by offering therapeutic alternatives, buying different vial sizes or concentrations and rationing medicines.\n\nThis article originally appeared on USA TODAY: Survey: Drug shortages are widespread, hospitals ration care","url":"https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/drug-shortage-list-grows-many-153710918.html?src=rss"},"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968":{"id":"039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0_1066817968","text":"General Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nGeneral Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nAn Unexpected Catastrophe in the World \u2019 s Largest Country: The Complete Story of U.S. Drug Shortages\nThe deficit is at a record level.\nAccording to data from the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah Drug Information Service, organizations began tracking drug shortages for the first time in 2001. Steady since 2021 \u2013 now reaching a record high of 323 drugs in the first three months of 2024.\nPaul Abramowitz, CEO of the American Society of Health System Pharmacists, wrote in a blog post on Thursday: \u201cIt \u2019 s been a long time to end drug shortages, \u201d and wrote:\u201c All drug classes are vulnerable to shortages, some of the most worrisome shortages include sterile injectable generic drugs, including cancer chemotherapy drugs and emergency drugs stored in hospital vans and procedural areas. It is dangerous for doctors and patients. \u201d\nIn addition to the 32 chemotherapy drugs that are deficient, the five categories of drugs with the greatest deficiency include central nervous system stimulants, antimicrobials, hormonal agents, and intravenous fluids. [1] The Drug Deficiency Database maintained by the American Society of Health System Pharmacists and the University of Utah is based on voluntary reports from practitioners, patients, and others that have been confirmed by manufacturers. The U.S. drug is in short supply, because it captures broader effects on service providers and patients.\nThe crisis has lasted a year and a half.\nMore than half of the treatment shortages have lasted for more than two years, according to an analysis by health consultancy IQVIA, and the average shortage affects at least half a million patients, many of them elderly, according to the US Office of Health and Human Services under the Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation, which shared its analysis with Congress in May.\nGrowing demand can play a role in drug shortages, as with the recent shortage of weight-loss drugs, but often manufacturing and quality problems, such as supply chain gaps and downtime, are the root cause. And varied.\nBut the American Society of Health System Pharmacists has \u201cserious concerns \u201d about parts of this proposal, especially financial sanctions imposed on hospitals that lack the resources to comply with the recommendations, Abramowitz wrote:\u201c We all know that managing shortages is not enough and is not a sustainable solution to the worsening crisis, and there is still a lot of work to be done at the federal level to fix the root causes of drug shortages. \u201d\nWhy Shortage Occurs\nShortages can be caused by high demand, as with the recent shortage of weight-loss drugs, but this is not usually the main problem.\nThe FDA also blames manufacturing and quality problems, supply chain gaps, and downtime, and Dr. Emily Tucker, a drug shortage expert and an assistant professor of industrial engineering at Clemson University, says that when there is an indication of shortages, large health systems often also proactively place large orders, adding to the system \u2019 s stress.\n\u201cI don \u2019 t blame anyone.\n\u201cWhen I talk to all the stakeholders \u2013 whether it \u2019 s wholesalers, manufacturers, or the government \u2013 everyone wants this problem to end, \u201d she said.\nLack of transparency\nDr. Julie Grallo, chief medical officer and executive vice president of the American Society of Clinical Oncology, told the House Committee earlier that the shortage puts providers in a terrible position: \u201cThe drug shortage crisis is forcing providers to make impossible choices, and it is also hindering the development of new drugs. Health drugs are purchased only on a price basis, and manufacturers do not have to disclose the source of their acquisition of the ingredients.\nThe shortage of this generic chemical drug came due to the closure of one factory in India that manufactures the active ingredient after a surprise FDA inspection found \u201csignificant quality issues, \u201d says Jarallo:\u201c We didn \u2019 t know, and there was no transparency regarding the company \u2019 s supply of the majority of active pharmaceutical ingredients to all manufacturers across the board.\nKnowing this in advance, we could have responded much faster, \u201d Dr. Steven Schundlemeyer, director of the PRIME Institute of the University of Minnesota School of Pharmacy, which focuses on economic and management issues, told the committee that as with defense contractors in the United States, New Zealand requires manufacturers to disclose their suppliers, and that information is required.\nEasily accessible in the database.\nRelated Topics","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:7051","uncompressed_offset":1066817968,"url":"www.elbalad.news/6171019","warc_date":"2024-04-14T16:44:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:039b72ee-9139-416e-9f1b-92b866fc03b0>","warc_url":"https://www.elbalad.news/6171019"},"created":"2024-04-14T18:21:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
