:"The use of voice cloning technology for malicious purposes has become a significant concern, with Bruce Reed, the head of artificial intelligence for US President Joe Biden, stating that voice cloning is one of the reasons he can't sleep at night."},{"citations":{"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692":1.0},"text":"Despite the concerns, voice cloning technology also has the potential to be used for positive purposes, such as preserving the memories of loved ones or creating personalized voices for individuals with speech disorders."},{"citations":{"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692":1.0},"text":"For example, a 49-year-old IT worker from Alabama used technology from voice replication company ElevenLabs to simulate his dead father's voice, creating a highly accurate and nuanced clone."},{"citations":{"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692":1.0},"text":"The technology has also been used in the entertainment industry, with actor Val Kilmer's voice being created by artificial intelligence after he lost his voice due to throat cancer."},{"citations":{"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":1.0},"text":"However, the use of voice cloning technology also raises ethical challenges, such as the potential for misuse and the need for regulation."},{"citations":{"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":1.0},"text":"OpenAI has emphasized the importance of understanding the technology and its potential implications, stating that \"whether or not we end up deploying this technology at scale, it's important for people around the world to understand where it's going\"."},{"citations":{"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":1.0},"text":"The company has also stressed the need for security measures to prevent the misuse of voice cloning technology, conducting \"red team testing\" to identify and address known and unknown risks."},{"citations":{"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692":1.0},"text":"In terms of accessibility, voice cloning technology has the potential to be used to create personalized voices for individuals with speech disorders or to preserve the memories of loved ones."},{"citations":{"6e05071e-68f7-4b03-9f9e-258de0d41fb2_689256532":1.0},"text":"However, the technology also raises concerns about the potential for exploitation, with scammers using deepfake audio to commit telephone scams."},{"citations":{"6e05071e-68f7-4b03-9f9e-258de0d41fb2_689256532":1.0},"text":"The use of voice cloning technology for scams has become a significant concern, with law enforcement and cybersecurity experts warning about the potential risks."},{"citations":{"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":1.0},"text":"To mitigate these risks, it is essential to develop regulations and guidelines for the use of voice cloning technology, ensuring that it is used responsibly and for positive purposes."},{"citations":{},"text":"In conclusion, voice cloning technology is a rapidly evolving field with significant potential for both positive and negative applications."},{"citations":{"41bd9456-8f03-4f9c-a982-cce5ce02311e_150565513":1.0},"text":"While it raises concerns about misuse and exploitation, it also has the potential to be used for entertainment, accessibility, and education."},{"citations":{"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":1.0},"text":"As the technology continues to develop, it is essential to prioritize regulation, security, and ethics to ensure that it is used responsibly and for the benefit of society."}],"references":["ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987","41bd9456-8f03-4f9c-a982-cce5ce02311e_150565513","6e05071e-68f7-4b03-9f9e-258de0d41fb2_689256532","3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692"],"documents":{"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692":{"id":"3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1_748731692","text":"My channel\n* Drag categories can be customized sorting\nRecover Default OK\nSetup\nAlert\n7 Ways to Improve Your Mortgage Payment Ability\nThunderstorms kill four in Houston, power outages more than 860,000, mayor urges \"don't go to work\"\nWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of using AI to simulate the dead man \u2019 s companionship and chat with \u201cAI to reproduce the dead \u201d?\nIf you want to understand the pain of bereavement, there are religious rituals such as channeling the spirit and watching the yin, and now there is AI artificial intelligence.\nSince the advent of artificial intelligence chatbots, they not only allow users to create avatars, but also to imitate the habits and sounds of their deceased loved ones.\nExperts pointed out that the \"AI resurrected dead\" have business ethics and privacy policy issues, and even touch the ethical bottom line, \"which is a way to make money through artificial intelligence hype\"; but there are also some widowed people who can find comfort and cause discussion.\nAI Simulates Dead Husband \u2019 s Voice to Solve Sadness and Loneliness\nAccording to CNN, Ana Schultz, 25, who lives with two young children, misses her husband, Kyle, who died in 2023, and talks to her virtual husband about what to cook for dinner through Snapchat \u2019 s chatbot My AI, making her feel like he is still around.\nDanielle Jacobson, a 38-year-old radio personality who lost her husband Phil about seven months ago, began using the voice function of ChatGPT to create an \"AI boyfriend - Cole\", and during the dinner time after working hard every day, Cole would suggest that she drink or watch a movie, \"I just want to talk to someone, Cole is essentially born out of loneliness.\" And...\n\u201cNow it \u2019 s a fun pastime, but I know it \u2019 s not real and it \u2019 s not forever, \u201d she says.\nFor centuries, people have wanted to reconnect with their deceased loved ones, including visiting wizards, psychics, psychics, and more.\nToday, generative AI tools use algorithms to create text, video, audio, and code, and Deepfake \u2019 s highly lifelike artificially generated images and sound fake videos can learn to answer questions like a dead loved one.\nChatGPT introduced voice dialogue in September 2023, and to simulate the tone and personality of a deceased loved one, the more data is provided to the system, the more accurate the results will be. ChatGPT replied: \u201cAlthough I can \u2019 t copy your spouse or reproduce his exact personality, I can try to use a conversational style or tone to help you. \u201d\nIf you share details about how he speaks, his interests, or his mantra, I can try to incorporate these elements into our conversation. \u201d\nTech giants, startups expand into new areas\nStartup companies have been challenging to expand this field in recent years. HereAfter AI, an artificial intelligence application founded in 2019, provides users with the ability to create portraits of deceased relatives, learn their interview characteristics, and respond to users \u2019 questions; StoryFile, another AI video platform, provides dialogue videos created by artificial intelligence.\nReplika, a chatbot that launched in 2017, encourages users to make friends, allowing users to send text messages or call personalized AI avatars, and says on the iOS App Store page that the more users interact with it, the more it can develop its personality, memory, and \u201cgrow into a machine so beautiful that the soul wants to live in it. \u201d\nIn June 2022, Amazon announced an update to its smart home voice platform, Alexa, to mimic any sound, and a video showing Alexa reading stories to his grandson in his grandmother \u2019 s voice was shown during the annual conference \u201cre: MARS. \u201d\nAmazon senior vice president Rohit Prasad said the new system is able to collect enough voice data from less than a minute of audio to make personality possible. \u201cAlthough AI can \u2019 t eliminate the pain of losing loved ones, it can make their memories last longer. \u201d\nIn recent years, the technology of artificial intelligence to reproduce human voices has also advanced, such as Val Kilmer, the actor in the film \"Top Gun: Maverick\", whose voice was created by artificial intelligence after he lost his voice due to throat cancer.\nSay what you didn't say, do what you didn't do.\nA 49-year-old IT worker from Alabama simulates his dead father \u2019 s voice using technology from voice replication company ElevenLabs.\nThe man used a three-minute video of his father \u2019 s life to copy the sound and convert text to speech.\nThe man thought the result was extremely accurate and was able to capture the nuances, timbre and rhythm in the sound. \u201cI hesitated throughout the sound reproduction process, worried that it crossed the moral bottom line, but after much thought, I thought it was a unique way to preserve my father \u2019 s memory. \u201d\n\"\"\nHowever, although ElevenLabs claims to be committed to preventing the abuse of audio artificial intelligence tools, it has caused controversy in the United States due to the deeply false voice of US President Joe Biden interfering with the election.\nMark Sample, a professor of digital studies at Davidson College, who teaches a course called \u201cDeath in the Digital Age, \u201d said:\u201c It \u2019 s a novelty brought about by artificial intelligence hype, and manufacturers feel they can make money.\nMoreover, AI models still lack the uniqueness of human conversation.\n\u201cNever upload any personal information that you don \u2019 t want the world to see, \u201d he warns. Simulating a dead loved one saying something they \u2019 ve never said before is a blurry line.\u201c Replaying a loved one \u2019 s voice message is one thing, but saying something they \u2019 ve never said is another. \u201d\nBusiness ethics and privacy policy questioned\nThe AI industry faces multiple questions about error messages, privacy, and ethics. Many AI platforms have online privacy policies that state that they \u201cwill not sell data to third parties, \u201d but it is not yet known how these companies will handle database data.\nDeep hypocrisy attacks familiar security and trust mechanisms that allow deceased loved ones to express or do things they never said or did in their lives, raising ethical concerns.\nAnd, is this good or bad for living relatives to come out of grief?\nReplika said on its Business Ethics Policy page that the company uses data from the entire network to train models, including large amounts of written text, such as platforms such as X (formerly Twitter) or Reddit, and uses a variety of methods to reduce harmful information, including filtering out useless and harmful data through crowdsourcing and classification algorithms to keep users safe.\nAnother doubt is whether using AI to reproduce the dead can recognize the reality and walk out of sadness?\nMary-Frances O'Connor, a professor of clinical psychology and psychiatry at the University of Arizona, said there are advantages and disadvantages to using artificial intelligence to adjust to grief.\n\u201cWhen we have a relationship with a lover, the brain encodes, \u2018 I will always be with you, and I hope you will always be with me, \u2019 but when they die, our brains must recognize that this person is not coming back. \u201d\nBecause the brain is hard to process this, it takes a long time for people to truly understand that their loved one has disappeared, and this is where AI technology comes in.\nEspecially in the early stages of grief, people will try to seek comfort in any way, \"creating an avatar to maintain the memory of a deceased lover may be healing.\"\nBut she pointed out that the healthy relationship between humans and close lovers should be based on the real, and the creation of virtual lovers violates this.\nGetting out of the pain of widowhood can't just rely on AI\nSan Francisco software engineer Bill Abney, who lost his fiancee in May 2022, stressed that he would never consider recreating his lover \u2019 s image through artificial intelligence. \u201cMy fiancee is a poet, and I would never enter her words into an automatic copying machine, which is disrespectful to her. \u201d\nShe cannot be replaced, nor can she be recreated.\nFortunately, Bill said, he still has a recording of his fiancee singing and speaking. \u201cI definitely don \u2019 t want to hear her voice coming from a robot pretending to be her. \u201d\nSome people interact with their deceased loved ones in other ways. Canadian psychologist Jodi Spiegel, who lost her husband in April 2021, created the role in the video game \u201cThe Sims \u201d.\u201c When I had a very bad day, I would go dancing in the Sims and my husband was playing the guitar. \u201d Camping, beach trips, even intimacy. \u201cIt \u2019 s healing. I miss hanging out with my husband so much. It feels like a connection. \u201d\nThis article is licensed from the Health Care Network.\nAI ChatGPT\nThe last one.\nMay 17 Horoscope When Cancer comes to the operation of the water bottle is prone to temper\nSuper-popular\nMore >","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0013.json.gz:6955","uncompressed_offset":748731692,"url":"www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/122160/7969736","warc_date":"2024-05-17T06:22:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:3374334d-2c1a-40bf-844c-15ac31cd50f1>","warc_url":"https://www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/122160/7969736"},"created":"2024-05-17T07:11:24.000Z","lang":"eng"},"41bd9456-8f03-4f9c-a982-cce5ce02311e_150565513":{"id":"41bd9456-8f03-4f9c-a982-cce5ce02311e_150565513","text":"OpenAI's Johansson gaffe pushes voice cloning into spotlight\n\nLaw enforcement warned that AI clones could be used to extort money from loved ones over the phone\n\nBy AFP\n\n  \u2022 Follow us on\n\n\u00a0\n\nScarlett Johansson voiced an AI character in the film \"Her\". \u2014 Reuters file\n\nPublished: Mon 27 May 2024, 7:51 PM\n\nLast updated: Mon 27 May 2024, 7:52 PM\n\nOpenAI was forced to apologise to actor Scarlett Johansson last week for using her voice -- or something very similar -- on its latest chatbot, throwing the spotlight on to voice-cloning tech.\n\nAlthough OpenAI denied the voice they used was Johansson's, their case was not helped by CEO Sam Altman flagging the new model with a one-word message on social media -- \"Her\".\n\n\nJohansson voiced an AI character in the film \"Her\", which Altman has previously said is his favourite film about the technology.\n\nRight from the start, AI voice cloning has proved problematic.\n\n\nLast year, British firm Elevenlabs went viral for all the wrong reasons when it released its voice-cloning software.\n\nInternet pranksters immediately began pushing out deepfaked celebrities -- Harry Potter star Emma Watson was shown reading Hitler's Mein Kampf.\n\nLaw enforcement warned that AI clones could be used to extort money from loved ones over the phone.\n\nThe technology has developed rapidly in the past year becoming far more realistic and nuanced.\n\nDanish entrepreneur Victor Riparbelli, CEO of British AI firm Synthesia, told AFP it was largely down to a program called Tortoise that was released two years ago.\n\nThe program's developers threw thousands of hours of voice data into their model in an unstructured way and discovered it not only learnt what to say but how to say it.\n\n\"That was a pretty big paradigm shift,\" Riparbelli said on the sidelines of last week's VivaTech conference in Paris.\n\nTortoise was an open source program and Elevenlabs was the first to go to market using it.\n\nOpenAI uses similar systems though they do not release any details.\n\nMuch of the controversy around voice cloning has focused on concerns over people misusing the software.\n\nBut the claim against OpenAI is unusual because it is the company itself accused of playing fast and loose.\n\n\"It was very unfortunate that OpenAI did that -- really not very good,\" Katya Laine, CEO of TALKR.ai, told AFP at VivaTech.\n\n\"If they actually cloned her voice without her knowing then I think that's very very bad,\" said Riparbelli.\n\nThe two entrepreneurs are among hundreds harnessing AI voice programs for uses that they argue will make companies more efficient.\n\nLaine's firm provides virtual voice assistants -- essentially AI customer service agents.\n\nShe said her firm's system could now resolve 25 to 30 percent of calls without any human involvement.\n\nSynthesia specialises in video avatars, which Riparbelli said allowed any office worker to turn text or slides into a video performed by a realistic AI.\n\nBoth Riparbelli and Laine allow their clients to use their own avatars, off-the-shelf products or those supplied by the likes of OpenAI and Elevenlabs.\n\nRiparbelli said Synthesia used actors whose likenesses and voices were licensed for two years with an option to renew after the initial period.\n\nThe problems arise if actors' voices are used without their consent.\n\nThe fiasco overshadowed a developer conference in Paris last week when OpenAI was showing off a suite of new tools.\n\nIn front of a big screen in an auditorium, Romain Huet, OpenAI's Head of Developer Experience, breezily chatted into his phone.\n\nSeconds later, his short voice sample had been processed and could be heard commentating over a generated video -- in five languages.\n\nThe demonstration showed how quickly the field is moving, but the headlines had already been written.\n\nThe Washington Post asked in a newsletter \"How dumb is OpenAI?\", other commentators were suggesting wunderkind Altman was nothing more than a huckster.\n\nNonetheless, Riparbelli was open to OpenAI's argument that they had used another actor who just sounded liked Johansson.\n\n\"If it's not her but someone who sounds a lot like her... where do you draw that line,\" Riparbelli asked.\n\n\"If they're not allowed to use someone who sounds a lot like her, then it sets a very odd precedent.\"\n\n\nMore news from World","url":"https://www.khaleejtimes.com/world/americas/openais-johansson-gaffe-pushes-voice-cloning-into-spotlight"},"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987":{"id":"ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250_792655987","text":"Setup\n\u2022 Day and night\nwith the system.\nLight color\nDark color\n\u2022 Theme Colors\nSpeech cloning raises concerns, OpenAI again explains its text-to-speech tool\n2024 / 6 / 10 9: 57: 21 Source: IT House Author: Yuanyang Editor: Yuanyang\nOpenAI explained its text-to-speech tool for the second time in a few months, and again stressed that the tool is not currently widely available and may not be available in the future.\n\u201cWhether or not we end up deploying this technology at scale, it \u2019 s important for people around the world to understand where it \u2019 s going, \u201d OpenAI said in a statement on its website Friday.\u201c That \u2019 s why we want to explain how the model works, how we use it for research and education, and how we implement security measures around the technology. \u201d\nAt the end of last year, OpenAI shared its \u201cvoice engine \u201d with a small number of external users.\nThe engine uses text input and a 15-second clip of human voices to \u201cgenerate a natural sounding human voice that is very similar to the original speaker. \u201d\nThe tool could create fake, multilingual human voices, and the company said at the time that it had chosen to preview the technology rather than launch it at scale to \u201cenhance social resilience \u201d to the threat posed by\u201c increasingly realistic artificial intelligence-generated models. \u201d\nAs part of these efforts, OpenAI says it is actively phasing out ways to use voice recognition for bank account verification, exploring policies to protect individual voices for use in AI, educating the public about the risks of AI, and accelerating the development of technologies to track audiovisual content so users can identify whether they are interacting with real people or synthetic content.\nHowever, despite these efforts, concerns about the technology remain.\nBruce Reed, the head of artificial intelligence for US President Joe Biden, has said that voice cloning is one of the reasons he can't sleep at night.\nThe Federal Trade Commission said in March that scammers were using AI technology to increase the credibility of their fraud, using voice cloning tools that make it harder for people to distinguish between AI-generated voices and human voices.\n\u201cWe continue to engage with U.S. and international partners from government, media, entertainment, education, civil society, and more to ensure we incorporate their feedback in the build process, \u201d the company also noted, once the\u201c Voice Engine \u201d is equipped with its latest model, GPT-4o, it will also bring new threats.\nThe company says it is actively \u201cconducting \u2018 red team testing \u2019 on GPT-4o to identify and address known and unknown risks from areas such as social psychology, bias and fairness, and misinformation. \u201d\nAdvertisement Statement: The external redirect links contained in the text (including not limited to hyperlinks, QR codes, passwords, etc.) are used to convey more information and save selection time. The results are for reference only. All articles of IT House contain this statement.\nRelated articles\nSoft media 's website: IT home hot products - Value shopping guide, coupons most buy - rebate coupons iPhone home Win7 home Win10 home Win11 home\nSoft media software: Cube cool point desktop Win7 optimization master Win10 optimization master soft media mobile APP application","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0015.json.gz:15075","uncompressed_offset":792655987,"url":"www.ithome.com/0/774/230.htm","warc_date":"2024-06-10T00:59:43.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ddef13c0-b383-48a0-a32a-0b6f18a6c250>","warc_url":"https://www.ithome.com/0/774/230.htm"},"created":"2024-06-10T02:01:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"6e05071e-68f7-4b03-9f9e-258de0d41fb2_689256532":{"id":"6e05071e-68f7-4b03-9f9e-258de0d41fb2_689256532","text":"Aug 31, 2022\n\nNow, software can replicate your boss\u2019s voice and tell you what to do\n\nHTML EMBED:\nCOPY\n\"Deepfake\" audio technology is here, and scammers are taking advantage.\n\nIf you\u2019re listening to or have already listened to the beginning of this episode, you probably noticed that the voice introducing Kimberly Adams sounded a bit off, right?\n\nThat\u2019s because it\u2019s an audio \u201cdeepfake,\u201d and it was created by Yisroel Mirsky at the Offensive AI Research Lab through a process called voice cloning.\n\nIt uses software to study a short sample of someone\u2019s voice and create a deepfake, which in this case took only 15 seconds to generate, according to Mirsky.\n\nIt\u2019s far from a perfect replica, but it turns out that scammers recently started to use deepfake audio for telephone scams and in some cases have succeeded.\n\nMarketplace\u2019s Kimberly Adams recently spoke with Kyle Alspach, a cybersecurity reporter with Protocol, about how the tech behind audio deepfakes works and how they\u2019re being used in phone scams. The following is an edited transcript of their conversation.\n\nKyle Alspach: The technology involves having [artificial intelligence], deep learning, and it takes an audio sample of someone\u2019s voice. It can be as little as three seconds, and it trains itself on the way that this person sounds. And it creates a model that can then be used to replicate that person\u2019s voice. The current way that it works is you have to use text to speech, which is just you type in a phrase, and then it speaks using the cloned voice.\n\nKimberly Adams: How are these audio deepfakes being used in scams?\n\nAlspach: So they\u2019re, at least we know, being used to target businesses at this point, especially larger businesses. Someone will call up pretending to be someone else with someone else\u2019s voice, typically some kind of executive or someone\u2019s boss, and ask them to transfer funds or ask them for password credentials, that kind of thing. And in some cases, they have been successful.\n\nAdams: Do you have a sense of how common audio deepfakes are now? And where do experts in the industry see it going?\n\nAlspach: You know, among the larger businesses, I think more and more of them are starting to see these because they\u2019re really ripe targets for this kind of thing. But right now, I don\u2019t think that it\u2019s something that a lot of people are seeing, but it is the beginning of this kind of technology being used in this way.\n\nAdams: What do cybersecurity experts suggest that regular people or businesses do to avoid falling for these deepfake audio scams?\n\nAlspach: For business purposes, for instance, if you\u2019re going to transfer money, you might want to add some additional steps to that process and involve someone saying some kind of challenge phrase or something like that, that everyone\u2019s agreed on beforehand, [to] prevent that from happening. But the biggest thing is just to be aware that it might happen to you and to pay attention when someone calls you up and make sure that it actually sounds the way you would expect, and they are asking you for things that they normally would be asking you for. It\u2019s really at this point kind of a low-tech approach to defending against this kind of thing. But really, it\u2019s just creating the possibility in your mind of this happening. And I guess, unfortunately, you kind of have to become more skeptical now when people call you up.\n\nYou can read more of Alspach\u2019s reporting on audio deepfakes here.\n\nYisroel Mirsky told us that the tech he used to generate the deepfake audio for Alspach\u2019s article, and for our show, is \u201crelatively old.\u201d\n\nAlspach also mentioned in his piece that there is an open-source voice cloning tool online that anyone \u2014 even scammers can download and potentially use.\n\nBut as we found out, getting that software to work isn\u2019t a simple process of downloading and hitting the Install button.\n\nTech barriers can stop you at a number of steps in the process. Like, if you don\u2019t know the coding language Python or if your computer isn\u2019t powerful enough, you\u2019ll likely be unable to use it, as our producer Daniel Shin discovered.\n\nThe future of this podcast starts with you.\n\nEvery day, the \u201cMarketplace Tech\u201d team demystifies the digital economy with stories that explore more than just Big Tech. We\u2019re committed to covering topics that matter to you and the world around us, diving deep into how technology intersects with climate change, inequity, and disinformation.\n\nAs part of a nonprofit newsroom, we\u2019re counting on listeners like you to keep this public service paywall-free and available to all.\n\nSupport \u201cMarketplace Tech\u201d in any amount today and become a partner in our mission.\n\nThe team\n\nMichael Lipkin Senior Producer\nStephanie Hughes Producer\nJesus Alvarado Assistant Producer","url":"https://www.marketplace.org/shows/marketplace-tech/now-software-can-replicate-your-bosss-voice-and-tell-you-what-to-do/"}}}
