rk, through the Roots & Shoots program and other initiatives, has inspired a new generation of leaders to take action, and has promoted conservation and sustainability globally."},{"citations":{"1fa58c5e-416a-418f-8de6-22f4a81873e8_687307734":1.0},"text":"As Goodall herself said, \"We need nature for our own physical and psychological well-being,\" and it is up to us to take action to protect the environment and promote sustainability."},{"citations":{"c5c9dcd7-2094-4279-8fff-f72974fdcec3_355332791":1.0},"text":"The collaboration between the Expo City Dubai and the Roots & Shoots program is a significant milestone in Goodall's efforts to engage young people and future generations in environmental action."},{"citations":{"4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9_55984504":1.0},"text":"The establishment of the Jane Goodall Primary School in Taiwan is a significant step towards promoting conservation and sustainability education, and is a testament to Goodall's enduring legacy."},{"citations":{"95f67cee-331c-42fd-9d52-cb7bad432c19_898632871":1.0},"text":"Goodall's work has been recognized and celebrated globally, with her recent endeavors focusing on empowering young people to take action in conservation and sustainability."},{"citations":{"4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9_55984504":1.0},"text":"The Conservation Asia project, which runs from August 2021 to December 2025, is one of the initiatives supported by the Tang Prize Foundation, and aims to promote conservation and sustainability in the region."},{"citations":{"95f67cee-331c-42fd-9d52-cb7bad432c19_898632871":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Jane Goodall's continuing impact on global issues, particularly on conservation, is a testament to her tireless efforts and dedication to creating a better world for all living beings."}],"references":["c5c9dcd7-2094-4279-8fff-f72974fdcec3_355332791","95f67cee-331c-42fd-9d52-cb7bad432c19_898632871","f684acbb-658a-47ca-aaad-05e0fb187180_520597399","1fa58c5e-416a-418f-8de6-22f4a81873e8_687307734","4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9_55984504"],"documents":{"f684acbb-658a-47ca-aaad-05e0fb187180_520597399":{"id":"f684acbb-658a-47ca-aaad-05e0fb187180_520597399","text":"Jane Goodall wants University of Wisconsin-Madison students to walk away with one message Sunday: Do not give up hope.\u00a0\n\nIt\u2019s a strategy the world-renowned ethologist and conservationist has found effective in spurring action, even as headlines catastrophizing climate change inundate people with a sense of doom.\u00a0\n\n\u201cI don't agree with scientists who say the tipping point has already reached the point of no return with climate change and loss of biodiversity,\u201d Goodall told the Cap Times. \u201cWe still have a window of time. But if we lose hope, fall into apathy and don't take action, then we're doomed.\u201d\u00a0\n\nGoodall is best known for her groundbreaking work in the early \u201860s as a primatologist. At 26, she began studying chimpanzees in Tanzania, becoming the first to observe that the animals make and use tools. Now part of the world\u2019s longest-running study of wild chimpanzees, her findings have forever changed scientific understanding of primates and humans\u2019 relationship to them.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nGoodall\u2019s legacy also endures through her activism. In 1977, she founded the Jane Goodall Institute, a global conservation nonprofit. One of the organization\u2019s programs, Roots & Shoots, educates young people in over 60 countries to work on environmental, conservation and humanitarian issues.\u00a0\n\nIn 2021, Goodall additionally published \u201cThe Book of Hope: A Survival Guide for Trying Times,\u201d which details her hope in the world\u2019s ability to make change despite its environmental challenges.\u00a0\n\nGoodall will speak Sunday at 7 p.m. in UW-Madison\u2019s Memorial Union for the Wisconsin Union\u2019s Distinguished Lecture Series. Tickets for the event sold out among students within 90 minutes, but the public can still register to watch the online livestream.\u00a0\n\nIn a virtual interview with the Cap Times, Goodall spoke from the Edgewater Hotel about climate deniers, how she remains optimistic and what the audience can expect from her on Sunday.\u00a0\n\nWill you have time to explore Madison this weekend, or will you mostly be working?\n\nIt\u2019s all working. Not mostly \u2014 all. But the hotel has a lovely view overlooking the lake with all the ice. My life turns out to be work, meeting lovely people and just having an occasional moment to walk in a bit of nature.\n\nWhat can people expect to learn from you on Sunday?\u00a0\n\nI hope they take away the message that every single one of them makes a difference every single day of their lives, and they can choose what sort of difference they make. I think that\u2019s the most important message that anybody can have \u2014 that they, as an individual, matter and have a role to play.\u00a0\n\nYour platform revolves around this message of hope. What might be the harm in catastrophizing?\u00a0\n\nIt makes people lose hope. If you\u2019re told that nothing you can do will avert the planet heating up to a point where life is no longer possible and that we\u2019re destroying the ecosystems on which we depend, then why bother doing anything?\u00a0\n\nThe important thing is to realize we still have time, but we have to take action. We have to each do our bit. It may seem small, but billions of small, ethical actions make change.\u00a0\n\nMuch of your work focuses on involving young people within conservation efforts. What inspires you about the attitudes of younger generations toward animals and the environment?\u00a0\n\nThey are much more aware, which isn\u2019t surprising. When I was young, \"environmentalism\" wasn\u2019t even a word.\u00a0\n\nYoung people are surrounded by doom and gloom. The radio\u2019s full of it, the internet's full of it, the television's full of it, the press is full of it, and so they're much more aware. Fortunately, there are enough people saying it's not too late, and that inspires them and galvanizes them into action.\n\nDo you think those attitudes are much different from older generations?\n\nThey are different because older generations either didn't understand what was happening because of ignorance, or they don't want to understand because they want to carry on with business as usual. They want to go on making money in the short term at the expense of future generations.\u00a0\n\nSometimes I don\u2019t think they\u2019re thinking like that. I don't think they're deliberately understanding that they're harming the future for their children and grandchildren. But they're simply not thinking in the way that we should be thinking today.\n\nIs it still worth trying to change their minds?\n\nYes, yes, yes, yes, yes! How to change the minds of the older people? Through storytelling, not through pointing fingers, not through making people angry, not by telling them they're bad, but by reaching into the heart. I\u2019ll give you one example.\u00a0\n\nThis CEO of a huge international corporation told me he was working to get his company ethical for three reasons. One, because we're using our nature's finite natural resources faster than nature can replenish them. Second, consumer pressure \u2014 people are beginning to demand ethically produced products.\n\nBut what really tipped the balance, he said, was his little girl of 8. She came back from school one day and said, \u201cDaddy, they're telling me that what you're doing is hurting the planet. That's not true, is it, Daddy? Because it's my planet.\u201d That reached his heart. That's the way you change people.\n\nWhen did you realize this approach of storytelling could persuade people?\n\nI think it was probably part of my nature. I'm not confrontational. I'm fighting for change, yes, but not by confronting. People must change from within. I don't believe you can change them by hammering them with facts that they don't want to listen to.\u00a0\n\nWhen I first went to the medical research labs where the scientists kept chimps in 5-foot by 5-foot cages, it was one of the worst experiences of my life. I came out shaken, trying not to cry. I was taken into a room with the top people from the National Institute of Health in the department of animal experimentation. I realized they were waiting for me to speak.\u00a0\n\nI said, \u201cI imagine all of you are caring and compassionate people, and maybe feel just as I did about what's going on in there.\u201d When you think of it, that was very clever. They couldn\u2019t admit they weren\u2019t caring and compassionate, could they?\u00a0\n\nInstead of telling them they were bad people, I showed them pictures of the chimpanzees in the wild, making their nests, playing, lying around. In their minds, they could contrast it with the cages where these very social beings were kept for 30 to 40 years. I know it did get into some of their hearts because they told me so. It made some labs completely change the way that they operated.\n\nWhen you meet somebody, or a group of people, you may not realize that you've made a difference \u2014 but you may have planted seeds that will grow and cause change in some of the hearts.\n\nWhat mistakes did you make early on in your career that emerging activists and young people can learn from?\u00a0\n\nI was saved from making mistakes in the early days. Before I went to Africa to study chimps, I was working at London Zoo. The chimps were in terrible conditions. So when I got back from my first stint in Africa, the zoo arranged a press conference. I thought now I could really tell the world how bad the chimps were treated!\n\nI happened to be having dinner that night with a very powerful man that I met in Tanzania, and I told him about my plan with great excitement. There was dead silence. He said, \u201cDo you realize that the head of the London Zoo is Solly Zuckerman, Winston Churchill's wartime adviser? A very, very powerful man. Do you think he's going to take it lying down when you criticize his zoo?\u201d\u00a0\n\nHe said, \u201cJust tell me three things that are the most important to change.\u201d I told him, and within two weeks, they were all done. There was no confrontation. That was a lesson that came just in time for me not to make that mistake.\u00a0\n\nSo it\u2019s about activists getting rid of their own personal egos.\u00a0\n\nExactly. What people want is to have their name out there and to say, \u201cI did it. I changed this.\u201d It\u2019s learning to not want to be recognized for change. The main thing is to make the change. Not \u201cme\u201d making the change.\u00a0\n\nThis powerful man obviously didn't want me to say that the chimps were being treated badly. He immediately agreed, but didn\u2019t want it out in the press. Give Solly Zuckerman the credit. That\u2019s fine \u2014 as long as it changes.\u00a0\n\nThis is a lesson I talk about with our youth. I tell them not to be confrontational. Your goal: Is it to glorify yourself? To be the champion? Or do you really want change?\u00a0\n\nWhat do people still not understand about your work and its relevance today?\n\nClimate change deniers, people who don\u2019t want to make a difference, probably don\u2019t understand. What they really think is hard to tell. But are there really people who deny that climate change is happening? Probably not. When they admit it\u2019s real, they say it\u2019s natural and that it\u2019s not manmade. Do they really believe that? I can\u2019t believe they do \u2014 but that\u2019s what they say. They don\u2019t want to lose face, and making people lose face isn\u2019t a good way to make change.\u00a0\n\nWhat makes you think they don\u2019t really believe what they\u2019re saying?\n\nWell, I can't think of anybody with any ounce of intelligence could believe it. That's why.\n\nHow often do you come across those kinds of people?\u00a0\n\nNot very often. They tend to avoid me.\u00a0\n\nKayla Huynh joined the Cap Times in 2021 and covers higher education. She graduated from Northwestern University with a master's degree in journalism after attending UW-Madison.\n\nSupport Kayla's work and local journalism by becoming a\u00a0Cap Times member.\n\nTo comment on this story, submit a\u00a0letter to the editor.","url":"https://captimes.com/news/education/jane-goodalls-in-madison-and-ready-to-spread-hope/article_569c257d-4b7c-5e7f-8c93-41f7b2d60438.html"},"c5c9dcd7-2094-4279-8fff-f72974fdcec3_355332791":{"id":"c5c9dcd7-2094-4279-8fff-f72974fdcec3_355332791","text":"Expo Dubai collaborates with Roots and Shoots programme\nT + T - normal size\nExpo City Dubai has announced its collaboration with the Gene Goodall Institute \u2019 s Roots & Shoots programme, a global initiative to connect with young people and stimulate action for the benefit of people and the environment.\nThis initiative reflects the commitment of Expo City Dubai, which recently hosted the COP28 Climate Summit, to protect the environment and advance human progress through meaningful collaboration and partnerships, and its ongoing quest to engage young people and future generations and provide them with more opportunities to learn, raise awareness and contribute to environmental action.\nDr. Jane Goodall is a leading animal behavioural scientist and environmental activist, one of the world \u2019 s leading names in environmental and wildlife protection, founder of the Jane Goodall Institute and UN Peace Ambassador.\nDr. Jane Goodall is set to establish the region \u2019 s first permanent office for Roots and Shoots at the Terra Sustainability Pavilion, the centre of Expo City \u2019 s environmental education programmes, and through collaboration, the initiative will help make the world a better place for people, organisms and the environment.\nMarjan Freedouni, Head of Education and Culture at Expo City Dubai, said that Expo City Dubai is committed to stimulating action and collaboration to preserve the environment, as part of its vision to be an inclusive, action-oriented community and a hub for climate solutions.\nExpo City Dubai and Roots and Shoots have had an amazing positive impact, and our collaboration embodies our shared mission to inspire and empower young people, while providing exciting educational opportunities outside the classroom that enable young people to learn about and participate in environmental activities.\nDr Jane Goodall said: \u201cBy working together with like-minded organisations such as Expo City Dubai, we can create sustainable change and greater community engagement, and we aim to engage more students from all backgrounds in the Roots and Shoots programme to have a greater impact on environmental and humanitarian challenges.\nEmail","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0002.json.gz:13059","uncompressed_offset":355332791,"url":"www.albayan.ae/uae/news/2024-01-23-1.4805413","warc_date":"2024-01-22T21:47:13.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:c5c9dcd7-2094-4279-8fff-f72974fdcec3>","warc_url":"https://www.albayan.ae/uae/news/2024-01-23-1.4805413"},"created":"2024-01-22T22:13:20.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9_55984504":{"id":"4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9_55984504","text":"\u2022 En\nAsia \u2019 s first \u201cJane Goodall Primary School \u201d to open in Taiwan\nDr. Jane Goodall (Source Taiwan English News)\nThe Tang Prize Foundation and Jane Goodall International signed a cooperation agreement today (11) to support conservation and education efforts in three countries: Taiwan, Malaysia and India. The first experimental primary school in Asia focusing on conservation and sustainability issues will be opened in Taiwan. Jane Goodall Institute of Taiwan.\n2020 Tang Prize Sustainable Development Laureate Dr. Jane Goodall, who was selected as a Tang Prize Laureate last year, began to use the $10 million research grant from the prize to launch sustainable conservation efforts this year. One of the projects is called Conservation Asia, which runs from August 2021 to December 2025.\nThe Tang Prize Education Foundation hopes to spread the power and spirit of the Tang Prize to promote sustainable development through this collaboration with the Genghuad International Association, and to carry on the Genghuad philosophy: \u201cHuman disrespect for nature has caused climate change and biodiversity crisis, and human beings should take responsibility for protecting ecosystems. \u201d\nThe main purpose of the Asia Conservation Project is to support conservation and education efforts in Taiwan, Malaysia and India, starting with the establishment of the first experimental primary school in Asia focusing on conservation and sustainability issues in Taiwan, called the Jane Goodall Sustainability Academy.\nThe second is Project Monyet, which raises awareness about the conservation of primates on the Malaysian peninsula through activities such as workshops and collaborates with scientists to document wildlife species.\nFinally, there is the Hope Project in India, which builds a connection between young people and nature through activities such as workshops and nurtures their understanding, awareness and action of nature.\nIn addition, Conservation Asia will host a Youth Forum each year to help teams work together and share the fruits of their work, produce and deliver impactful and diverse teaching resources and materials to rebuild the lost connection between humanity and nature.\nWe believe that bringing children closer to nature from a young age will help foster children \u2019 s ecological literacy and caring for the planet. In addition to establishing a solid foundation in the local area, we are also committed to creating and sharing influential and diverse teaching materials to increase citizen engagement and raise public awareness of the importance of wildlife. Create a vibrant sharing platform through events such as summits, workshops, and more.\nShe went on to share that Taiwan \u2019 s first Zhengude Elementary School will guide students to understand the mysteries of nature \u2019 s operation, allowing children to explore in the learning environment, and cultivate three core principles of knowledge (understanding), compassion (care) and mobility.\nChen Zhenchuan, CEO of the Tang Prize Education Foundation, said that according to United Nations statistics, by 2050, more than two-thirds of the world \u2019 s population and about 6.4 billion people will live in cities, that is, under the rapid development of science and technology and urbanization, human intensive activities will accelerate the destruction of the earth \u2019 s ecology and environment and resource depletion, resulting in more green land being turned into an artificial environment. Severe disasters continue to occur, including typhoons and floods, major earthquakes, forest fires, infectious diseases, etc.\nTherefore, it is more necessary to solve the problem of habitat fragmentation and maintain biodiversity through environmental and ecological protection education, so as to realize the vision of human beings and nature living side by side.\n\u25b3 Photo provided by Tang Prize Education Foundation\n\u25b3 The Tang Prize Education Foundation and Jane Goodall International concluded the signing ceremony of the Agreement on Conservation in Asia today. (Photo courtesy of Tang Prize Education Foundation)","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0023.json.gz:8854","uncompressed_offset":55984504,"url":"www.taiwannews.com.tw/ch/news/4268178","warc_date":"2021-08-11T08:07:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4c0ee3ad-3947-4c32-9bdc-e1ea45fa3dd9>","warc_url":"https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/ch/news/4268178"},"created":"2021-08-11T08:11:24.000Z","lang":"eng"},"95f67cee-331c-42fd-9d52-cb7bad432c19_898632871":{"id":"95f67cee-331c-42fd-9d52-cb7bad432c19_898632871","text":"World-famous for her research with chimpanzees, Jane Goodall now focuses on the human condition\n\nApr 21, 2024 | 0 comments\n\nBy Michelle Cohan\n\nIn 1960, on the banks of Lake Tanganyika, Tanzania, one young British woman would set out to change what we know about primates forever.\n\nJane Goodall, in 1960, searching an African forest for chimpanzees.\n\nJane Goodall defied conventional scientific methods by immersing herself in the jungle, which led to groundbreaking discoveries about chimpanzees; most notably that they use tools, are omnivores and that they are socially complex beings.\n\nMore than six decades later, her unorthodox field work \u2013 and her conservation efforts \u2013 are still celebrated around the world.\n\nToday, the recently-turned 90-year-old\u2019s work looks a little different \u2013 taking place mostly indoors, and with a different crowd. Through her program called \u201cRoots & Shoots,\u201d Goodall empowers young people to create change within their communities. And for her, this work is just as significant.\n\nCNN spoke with Goodall recently during a trip to South Africa, where she observed some of the projects local Johannesburg students are heading up as part of Roots & Shoots.\n\nThe interview has been edited for length and clarity.\n\nCNN: The younger generation has so much they can learn from elders. Who made an impact on your life?\n\nGoodall: I think it\u2019s really important, this exchange of information from the elders to the youngers. I was really lucky; I had an amazing mother. I was born loving animals, and she supported that love of animals. I was one-and-a-half years old, and she came into my room and she found I\u2019d taken a whole handful of wriggling earthworms into my bed. Most mothers would\u2019ve [said], \u2018Oh, throw these dirty things [away].\u2019 She just said, \u2018Jane, I think they might die without the Earth, you better take them into the garden.\u2019 And so she nurtured this inherent love I had \u2026 in all the insects, the birds, the animals, everybody around me.\n\nJane Goodall\n\nCNN:\u00a0Roots & Shoots is active in 70 countries, where hundreds of thousands of young people are making an impact within their communities. How did the program come about?\n\nGoodall: When I began Roots & Shoots in Tanzania in 1991, it was because I was meeting young people then who had lost hope. Young people who felt we\u2019d compromised their future. And the reason they\u2019re losing hope, it\u2019s obvious: climate change, loss of biodiversity. I could go on listing, listing, listing \u2026 but when they said there was nothing they could do about it, then I thought, \u2018No, that\u2019s not true.\u2019\n\nWe worked out that Roots & Shoots\u2019 main message [would be that] every individual has a role to play. And that we needed to think holistically in terms of helping the\u00a0environment, people and animals, because we are all interrelated. That\u2019s where it began.\n\nCNN: What is the most important message to convey to the younger generation?\n\nGoodall: The goal that I have is helping young people understand that there is a window of time [to save the planet]. Unfortunately, today I [still] meet more and more people who are losing hope. So many people feel helpless and hopeless because [they question] what can they can do as an individual.\n\nBut what people have to understand is when it\u2019s 2 million, 1 billion, 2 billion, 3 billion, all taking small actions to make the world a better place, that is changing the world. What matters is people understanding that as an individual, what they do makes a difference. Not because it\u2019s just them, but because they are not alone.\n\nCNN: Does climate innovation and technology give you hope?\n\nGoodall: Yeah, I think that if we look around at what\u2019s happening to the planet, we need to grab onto every single thing we can that will help us to move forward out of the disaster that we have created. And if we look at solar energy, if we look at wind energy and the power of tide energy, then these things are good.\n\nThe problem has been to get government support. So governments tend to put money into the fossil fuel industry,\u00a0rather than to support the new emerging technologies that will enable us to live in a more harmonious way with the natural world. If we don\u2019t do that, our future is doomed. And unfortunately, it\u2019s not only our future, but so many of the other animals that so many of us love. We have to take action now.\n\nCNN: What message do you have for the world?\n\nGoodall: A message to the world would be, don\u2019t forget that you as an individual make an impact on the environment every single day. And it\u2019s up to you to choose what sort of impact you make. I think once everybody understands the role that they play, whoever they are, is so desperately important, then we move towards a better world.\n\nEditor\u2019s note: At one of Goodall\u2019s recent presentations in California, 93-year-old movie actor and director Clint Eastwood was in the audience. Asked why he was there, Eastwood said he supported Goodall\u2019s work and added that he was a big fan of 90-year-olds.\n_________________\n\nCredit: CNN\n\nCuencaHighLife\n\nDani News\n\nGoogle ad\n\nGoogle ad\n\nThai Lotus News\n\nFund Grace News\n\nThe Cuenca Dispatch\n\nWeek of April 14\n\nTrial of Carlos P\u00f3lit: First Week of Revelations Sheds Light on Corruption in Correista Regime.\n\nRead more\n\nInsecurity affects tourism in Manab\u00ed as nine cruise ships canceled their arrival in Manta.\n\nRead more\n\nEcuador Gains Ground with Palm Heart, Secures 75% of the Global Market.\n\nRead more\n\nCountry living News\n\nGran Colombia Suites News\n\nQuinta Maria News","url":"https://cuencahighlife.com/world-famous-for-her-work-with-chimpanzees-jane-goodall-at-90-focuses-on-improving-the-human-condition/"},"1fa58c5e-416a-418f-8de6-22f4a81873e8_687307734":{"id":"1fa58c5e-416a-418f-8de6-22f4a81873e8_687307734","text":"Leading conservationist Dr Jane Goodall warns next generation faces a 'bleak future' without action\n\nCOP15, the once-in-decade global biodiversity summit, began in Montreal on Wednesday. Ahead of the conference, ITV News spoke to one of the world's most famous and inspiring conservationists, Dr Jane Goodall.\n\n\nWith an estimated one million plant and animal species facing extinction, the scale of the issues being grappled with by nations at COP15 in Montreal could hardly be greater.\n\nEntire ecosystems face collapse if we do not act, so how best to overcome this challenge?\n\nDr Jane Goodall has spent a lifetime trying to understand, protect and educate others about the natural world. She\u2019s witnessed devastating habitat loss but also examples of where, given time, nature returns.\n\nShe paints a dark picture of what happens if politicians fail to rise to the occasion, saying the \u201cprice of failure is condemning our children, our children's children, to a very, very bleak and grim future.\u201d\n\nTalking to ITV News in Parliament, where she was marking a significant moment in the campaign to ban trophy hunting, she explains how we need to view nature.\n\n\u201cI would say how important it is to realise that we are actually not separate from the natural world. We are part of it and more than that we depend on it. We depend on it for food, water, everything,\" she said.\n\n\"We depend on healthy ecosystems. An ecosystem is made up of an interrelated mix of animal and plant species living in that ecosystem. And as more and more animals and plants become extinct in that area, so the ecosystem eventually will collapse.\u201d\n\nDecades of witnessing animals, such as primates, up close has forged her understanding of our world. It was notable in a room full of animal welfare campaigners just how quiet it was when she spoke.\n\nIn Montreal, the world faces a choice but it\u2019s complicated. Delivering change includes finding a way of maintaining wealth. Making people poorer while saving plants and animals won\u2019t work, but Dr Jane Goodall sees options that will.\n\nShe concluded: \u201cWe need nature for our own physical and psychological well-being. That's proven again and again. We must not let these ecosystems collapse, we have this window of time, we have the tools, we know how we can do things. But will we?\u201d\n\n\nWant a quick and expert briefing on the biggest news stories? Listen to our latest\u00a0podcasts to find out What You Need To Know","url":"https://www.itv.com/news/2022-12-09/next-generation-faces-bleak-future-without-action-warns-dr-jane-goodall"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1081","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1081","narrative_id":"1081"},"responses":[{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is a rapidly advancing field, with several countries and companies leading the way in research and innovation."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"China is currently the leader in government funding for quantum computing, with an allocation of $15.3 billion."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The country is also home to companies that are making significant advancements in quantum computing, with one company planning to increase the number of qubits to 1121 this year and intends to show a device for a thousand qubits after 2025."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"In addition to China, other countries such as the United States, Russia, and those in Europe are also investing heavily in quantum computing research and development."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The United States is currently the leading market for quantum computing, with companies such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft driving growth through their presence and investment in research and development activities."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"Russia is also making significant progress in quantum computing, with work underway on four key physical platforms: superconducting qubits, photonic circuits, neutral atoms, and trapped ions."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"Investments in quantum computing startups reached $2.35 billion in 2022, with venture investors around the world investing heavily in this field."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The number of patents issued and published in all subfields of quantum computing is also increasing, with almost 1,600 patents issued in 2022."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"Overall, the development of quantum computing is a global effort, with several countries and companies playing important roles in advancing this field."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is a rapidly advancing field, with several countries and companies leading the way in research and innovation."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"China is currently the leader in government funding for quantum computing, with an allocation of $15.3 billion."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The country is also home to companies that are making significant advancements in quantum computing, with one company planning to increase the number of qubits to 1121 this year and intends to show a device for a thousand qubits after 2025."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"In addition to China, other countries such as the United States, Russia, and those in Europe are also investing heavily in quantum computing research and development."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The United States is currently the leading market for quantum computing, with companies such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft driving growth through their presence and investment in research and development activities."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"Russia is also making significant progress in quantum computing, with work underway on four key physical platforms: superconducting qubits, photonic circuits, neutral atoms, and trapped ions."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"Investments in quantum computing startups reached $2.35 billion in 2022, with venture investors around the world investing heavily in this field."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"The number of patents issued and published in all subfields of quantum computing is also increasing, with almost 1,600 patents issued in 2022."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"Overall, the development of quantum computing is a global effort, with several countries and companies playing important roles in advancing this field."}],"references":["9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795","9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656"],"documents":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795","text":"People 's Daily Online > > Economy and Technology\n\"Origin Goku\" stable operation shows what\nMay 12, 2024 08: 54 | Source: Economic Daily\nSmall number\nOriginal title: \"The source of Goku\" stable operation shows what\nAs of May 7, China's third-generation autonomous superconducting quantum computer \"Origin Wukong\" has attracted more than 8 million visits worldwide.\nPreviously, it was successfully connected to three supercomputing centers such as the Yangtze River Delta hub Wuhu cluster computing power public service platform, marking the formal completion of China's \"four calculations in one\" system of general computing, intelligent computing, supercomputing and measurement.\nWhat does the stable operation of \"Origin Goku\" show?\n\"Genyuan Wukong\" is China's third-generation autonomous superconducting quantum computer, equipped with 72-bit autonomous superconducting quantum chips.\nThe computer is named \"Wukong\", which means that it is as powerful as the traditional Chinese mythological figure Sun Wukong and can change 72 times.\n\"Benyuan Wukong\" was independently developed by the Benyuan Quantum team and launched on January 6 this year. Since the launch of the line, the average daily global visit is about 66,700 times, and the average daily completion of nearly 1,500 computing tasks.\nQuantum computing is a cutting-edge emerging technology that has great potential in artificial intelligence, biomedicine, financial analysis and other fields.\nIf the general purpose traditional computer is compared to a bicycle, the quantum computer is like an airplane.\nTo break down 300 large numbers, it takes 150,000 years to make use of a trillionth of a conventional computer, and 1 second to make use of a trillionth of a quantum computer.\nThe biggest advantage of quantum computers is their powerful computing power, but compared with traditional computers, the technology is immature, the manufacturing cost is high, and the reliability is not strong.\nChina's quantum computing technology is in the transition stage from laboratory research and development to industrial application.\n\"Genyuan Wukong\" equipped with hardware, chips, operating systems and application software are autonomous and controllable, and the localization rate is more than 80%, which marks the basic formation of China's superconducting quantum computer industry chain.\nIn the four months since its launch, \"Benyuan Wukong\" has successfully completed more than 178,000 computing tasks for users in 120 countries, and countries with quantum computers such as the United States, Japan and Canada have shown great concern for \"Benyuan Wukong\", among which the frequency of visits by US users is much higher than that of other countries.\nIn the field of quantum computing, developed countries led by the United States have started early, developed rapidly and have a high degree of industrial maturity, and have gradually established a \"quantum computing ecological chain.\"\nFor example, in 2017, IBM led the establishment of the Quantum Computing Industry Alliance (IBM Quantum Network), which has more than 250 members from the United States, Japan, South Korea, Germany, Australia and other countries, involving Fortune 500 companies, start-ups and academic institutions.\nHowever, although China started late in the quantum field, it has made rapid progress.\nA recent paper on global quantum information technology patents shows that from 2003 to 2022, China's quantum information technology patent applications accounted for 37% of the global total, surpassing the proportion of the United States slightly more than 28%.\n\"Origin Wukong\" is the first large-scale and long-term opening of China's quantum computing power to the world, indicating that China has officially entered the \"usable\" era of quantum computing power.\nLooking forward to the future, let the \"Wukong\" further play the power of the \"source\", it will take many efforts.\nWe should focus on making up for the shortcomings and strength of the weak, so that the key instruments and equipment of quantum computing can be fully replaced in China. We should support the building of the quantum chip industry chain and build a quantum computing power network. To change the situation of shortage of talents in the quantum field.\nComputing power is the new quality of productivity in the digital economy era, who has mastered the advanced computing power, who has mastered the \"winning chance\" of development.\nOn the international science and technology track of quantum computers, the layout and development of independent industrial chains is an inevitable choice for us to face the forefront of world science and technology, the main battlefield of the economy, and the major needs of the country.\n(Editor: Yang Xi, Chen Jian)\nPublic Number \uff1a People 's Network Finance\nShare it so more people can see it.\nBack to top","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0012.json.gz:25770","uncompressed_offset":116579795,"url":"finance.people.com.cn/n1/2024/0512/c1004-40234145.html","warc_date":"2024-05-12T01:44:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506>","warc_url":"http://finance.people.com.cn/n1/2024/0512/c1004-40234145.html"},"created":"2024-05-12T02:04:13.000Z","lang":"eng"},"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":{"id":"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985","text":"Quantum Computing Market was valued at nearly USD 234.06 billion by 2032\n\nPrudour Private Limited\n\nUpdated \u00b7 Mar 06, 2023\n\nQuantum Computing Market Overview\n\nPublished Via 11Press: Quantum computing is a rapidly developing market that is revolutionizing how we approach computing and data processing. By employing principles of quantum mechanics to perform computations, quantum computers are capable of solving problems that classical computers may find impossible or impracticable to resolve.\n\nThe global\u00a0quantum computing\u00a0market size is forecast to reach\u00a0USD 234.06 billion\u00a0by 2032 from\u00a0USD 10.13 billion\u00a0in 2022, rising at a compound annual growth rate\u00a0(CAGR) of 36.89%\u00a0during the forecast period.\n\nAt present, the quantum computing market is dominated by a few major players such as IBM, Google, Microsoft, and Honeywell. These firms are investing heavily in quantum computing research and development as well as creating quantum computing hardware and software systems.\n\nThe quantum computing market is expected to have a profound effect on industries such as healthcare, finance, logistics, and energy. Some key applications of quantum computing include drug discovery, supply chain optimization, financial modeling, and climate modeling.\n\nThough the quantum computing market is promising, it still faces several obstacles such as high costs of hardware, a shortage of skilled experts in this area, and technical difficulties when building large-scale quantum computers. With ongoing research and development efforts, however, these problems should be overcome within the coming years, leading to even greater growth and innovation in this space.\n\nKey Takeaways\n\n  \u2022 The global quantum computing market size was valued at\u00a0USD 234.06 billion\u00a0in 2022 and is expected to grow at a\u00a0CAGR of around 36.89% from 2022 to 2032.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing is capable of solving problems that would be intractable or impossible for classical computers to solve.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market is dominated by a few major players, including IBM, Google, Microsoft and Honeywell.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market is expected to have a profound effect on numerous industries, such as healthcare, finance, logistics and energy.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing has many important applications such as drug discovery, supply chain optimization, financial modeling and climate modeling.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market remains plagued by several obstacles, such as the high cost of quantum computing hardware, lack of qualified quantum computing experts and technical difficulties in building and running large-scale quantum computing systems.\n  \u2022 Research and development are expected to overcome these obstacles within the next couple of years, propelling even greater growth and innovation in the quantum computing market.\n\nRequest For Sample Report:\u00a0https://market.us/report/quantum-computing-market/request-sample/\n\nRegional Snapshot\n\n  \u2022 North America:\u00a0North America is currently the leading market for quantum computing, with the United States playing a major role. Major companies such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft are driving this growth through their presence and investment in research and development activities related to quantum computing. This region boasts numerous key players such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft which are driving demand within this region.\n  \u2022 Europe:\u00a0Europe is an increasingly important market for quantum computing, with countries such as the UK, Germany, and France investing heavily in research and development. Through partnerships between quantum computing companies and other technology firms as well as the growing adoption of quantum computing across various industries, this region\u2019s market is experiencing rapid expansion.\n  \u2022 Asia Pacific:\u00a0The quantum computing market in Asia Pacific is expected to experience significant growth over the coming years due to increased investments in research and development by countries like China, Japan, and South Korea. Furthermore, there have been an increasing number of collaborations between companies using quantum computing with academic institutions as well as its increasing adoption across industries like healthcare and finance \u2013 all contributing factors for market expansion within this region.\n  \u2022 The Rest of the World:\u00a0Countries such as Brazil, South Africa, and the UAE are expected to experience significant growth in the quantum computing market over the coming years due to increased investments in research and development efforts as well as the growing adoption of quantum computing across various industries. These factors are fueling this region\u2019s meteoric rise in this region.\n\nDrivers\n\n  \u2022 Quantum Computing Gaining Adoption in Various Industries:\u00a0Quantum computing is seeing an uptick in popularity across a range of industries, such as healthcare, finance, logistics, and energy \u2013 as companies seek to use their power to solve complex problems and gain an edge in competition.\n  \u2022 Investments in Quantum Computing Research and Development:\u00a0Governments, academic institutions, and private companies have made substantial investments in quantum computing research and development, spurring innovation and progress within the field.\n  \u2022 Growing Number of Partnerships and Collaborations:\u00a0There has been an uptick in partnerships and collaborations between quantum computing companies and other technology firms, as well as academic institutions and research organizations. This trend is propelling the development of new quantum computing hardware and software systems, as well as its adoption across various industries.\n  \u2022 Increasing Access to Cloud-Based Quantum Computing Services:\u00a0The growing availability of cloud-based quantum computing services is making it simpler for companies and researchers to utilize this cutting-edge technology, spurring adoption and innovation within the field.\n\nRestraints\n\n  \u2022 Limited Access to Qualified Quantum Computing Experts:\u00a0Unfortunately, there is currently a shortage of highly experienced quantum computing specialists, making it challenging for companies to construct and sustain quantum computing systems.\n  \u2022 Technical Challenges in Building and Maintaining Large-Scale Quantum Computing Systems:\u00a0The development of large-scale quantum computing systems is still in its early stages, so there are numerous technical obstacles that must be overcome, such as noise reduction, error correction, and scalability.\n  \u2022 Limited Quantum Computing Applications:\u00a0Although the list of potential applications for quantum computing is growing, the number of practical ones that have been developed and implemented remains limited. This can make it challenging for companies to justify investing in quantum computing technology.\n  \u2022 Regulatory Challenges:\u00a0Quantum computing technology may face regulatory restrictions, particularly around data privacy and security. This could create additional obstacles to the adoption and investment in the technology.\n\nOpportunities\n\n  \u2022 Growing Number of Partnerships and Collaborations:\u00a0The growing number of partnerships and collaborations among quantum computing companies, other technology firms, academic institutions, and research organizations is creating opportunities for the development of new quantum computing hardware and software systems as well as its adoption across various industries.\n  \u2022 Advancements in Quantum Computing Hardware and Software:\u00a0With the rapid progress being made in the development of quantum computing hardware and software, new opportunities will present themselves for applying this technology across various industries and fields.\n  \u2022 The growing availability of cloud-based quantum computing services:\u00a0Cloud-based quantum computing services are making it simpler for companies and researchers to access and utilize quantum computing technology, spurring adoption and innovation within the field.\n  \u2022 Growth of Quantum Computing as a Service:\u00a0As more companies and researchers embrace the potential of quantum computing, cloud-based quantum computing services are creating exciting new business opportunities for those offering these solutions.\n  \u2022 Potential for Breakthroughs in Areas such as Drug Discovery, Finance, and Energy:\u00a0Quantum computing holds the potential to unravel complex issues in fields like drug discovery, finance, and energy \u2013 leading to major breakthroughs and advances. This presents companies with unique opportunities for those who can develop and implement quantum computing solutions in these sectors.\n\nChallenges\n\n  \u2022 Technical Challenges in Constructing and Running Large Quantum Computing Systems:\u00a0As quantum computing systems continue to emerge, numerous technical obstacles must be overcome such as noise reduction, error correction, and scalability. These issues make it challenging for companies to construct and run these massive quantum computers efficiently.\n  \u2022 Limited Access to Qualified Quantum Computing Experts:\u00a0There is currently a shortage of highly experienced quantum computing professionals, making it difficult for companies to construct and maintain quantum computing systems. This shortage could potentially restrict the growth of this industry in the coming years.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing Applications:\u00a0While quantum computing has many potential uses, the number of practical applications that have been created and implemented remains limited. This could make investing in quantum computing technology and research on practical applications an attractive prospect.\n\nGrow your profit margin with Market.us\u00a0Get this Report\n\nRecent Developments\n\n  \u2022 Google Claims Quantum Supremacy:\u00a0In 2019, Google claimed to have achieved quantum supremacy by performing a calculation on its quantum computer that even the most powerful supercomputers would take thousands of years to complete. This was seen as an important milestone in the advancement of quantum computing technology.\n  \u2022 IBM Launches Quantum Computing Program for Students:\u00a0In 2020, IBM unveiled a quantum computing program specifically tailored towards students that provides them with access to IBM\u2019s resources and tools, as well as a platform for learning and collaboration.\n  \u2022 Honeywell Achieves Quantum Computer Record Performance:\u00a0On March 20, 2021, Honeywell revealed its creation of a quantum computer with an astonishing quantum volume of 512. This feat marked an amazing advancement in quantum computing technology and demonstrated how rapidly progress has been made since then.\n  \u2022 Amazon Web Services Announces Quantum Computing Service:\u00a0On June 2021, Amazon Web Services (AWS) announced the launch of its own quantum computing service called Amazon Bracket. This offering gives customers access to various vendors\u2019 hardware as well as tools and resources for developing and testing quantum algorithms.\n\nKey Market Segments\n\nType\n\n  \u2022 Hardware\n  \u2022 Software\n  \u2022 Services\n\nApplication\n\n  \u2022 Defense\n  \u2022 Healthcare & pharmaceuticals\n  \u2022 Chemicals\n  \u2022 Banking & Finance\n  \u2022 Energy & power\n\nKey Market Players\n\n  \u2022 D-Wave Systems\n  \u2022 Google\n  \u2022 IBM\n  \u2022 Intel\n  \u2022 Microsoft\n  \u2022 1QB Information Technologies\n  \u2022 Anyon Systems\n  \u2022 Cambridge Quantum Computing\n  \u2022 ID Quantique\n  \u2022 IonQ\n  \u2022 QbitLogic\n  \u2022 QC Ware\n  \u2022 Quantum Circuits\n  \u2022 Qubitekk\n  \u2022 QxBranch\n  \u2022 Rigetti Computing\n\nNature Insights\n\n  \u2022 Progress is being made in the development of quantum computing hardware:\u00a0Despite the challenges facing large-scale quantum computing systems, progress is being made on quantum computing hardware. This includes creating quantum processors with increasingly more qubits and creating new materials suitable for use in quantum computers.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing software is still in its early stages:\u00a0While progress is being made with quantum computing hardware, software development for quantum computation remains at a standstill. This presents an immense challenge to the industry as developing efficient quantum algorithms is essential to realizing its full potential.\n  \u2022 Collaboration is essential to the advancement of quantum computing:\u00a0Collaboration between companies, academic institutions, and research organizations is essential for progress in this industry. This includes joint efforts to develop new hardware and software systems as well as collaborations that promote quantum computing across various industries.\n\nReport Scope\n\nReport Attribute Details\nThe market size value in 2022 USD 10.13 Bn\nRevenue forecast by 2032 USD 234.6 Bn\nGrowth Rate CAGR Of 36.89%\nRegions Covered North America, Europe, Asia Pacific, Latin America, and Middle East & Africa, and the Rest of the World\nHistorical Years 2017-2022\nBase Year 2022\nEstimated Year 2023\nShort-Term Projection Year 2028\nLong-Term Projected Year 2032\n\nContact us\n\nContact Person: Mr. Lawrence John\n\nMarket.us (Powered By Prudour Pvt. Ltd.)\n\nTel: +1 718 618 4351\n\nSend Email: [email\u00a0protected]\n\nFAQ.\n\nWhat is quantum computing?\n\nQuantum computing is a type of processing data using quantum mechanics. It relies on principles such as superposition, entanglement, and interference which enable quantum computers to perform calculations that would be impossible with classical computers.\n\nWhat are some potential applications of quantum computing?\n\nQuantum computing holds great promise for revolutionizing industries such as drug discovery, finance, energy, and logistics. Potential uses include creating new drugs and materials, optimizing supply chains and logistics networks, and even improving weather forecasting models with greater precision.\n\nWhat are some of the challenges facing the quantum computing market?\n\nThe quantum computing market faces numerous obstacles, such as technical difficulties in building and running large-scale quantum computers, high costs associated with quantum computing hardware, a scarcity of highly qualified quantum experts, and an absence of practical applications developed and deployed.\n\nWho are some of the major players in the quantum computing market?\n\nMajor companies operating within this space include IBM, Google, Microsoft, Honeywell, Intel, and Rigetti Computing. These firms are actively developing and commercializing quantum computing hardware and software systems.\n\nWhat is the outlook for the quantum computing market?\n\nOverall, analysts anticipate a bright future for quantum computing, with continued investment and innovation anticipated in the coming years. Though still in its early stages of development, its potential advantages are immense - leading to rapid industry growth over the coming years.\n\nPrudour Private Limited\n\nThe team behind market.us, marketresearch.biz, market.biz and more. Our purpose is to keep our customers ahead of the game with regard to the markets. They may fluctuate up or down, but we will help you to stay ahead of the curve in these market fluctuations. Our consistent growth and ability to deliver in-depth analyses and market insight has engaged genuine market players. They have faith in us to offer the data and information they require to make balanced and decisive marketing decisions.","url":"https://www.enterpriseappstoday.com/news/quantum-computing-market-was-valued-at-nearly-usd-234-06-billion-by-2032.html"},"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":{"id":"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656","text":"Investments in quantum computing startups reached $2.35 billion in 2022\nQuantum technologies have great potential for both science and business, and attract large investments in different countries of the world, including Russia.\nThis is stated in the analytical report \"Quantum Computing: Prospects for Business\", which was prepared jointly with the Federal State Unitary Enterprise \"VNIIA named after N.L. Dukhov\" and the Institute of Artificial Intelligence AIRI.\n\u201cIncreasing attention in the world is paid to supporting start-ups in the field of quantum technologies.\nIn 2022, venture investors around the world invested $2.35 billion in them.\nAlso last year, almost 1,600 patents were issued and published in all subfields of quantum computing: from physical implementations of quantum equipment and error correction to AI [artificial intelligence] and machine learning.\nVideo of the day\nLeading countries, realizing the breakthrough potential of this direction, include quantum technologies in national programs and allocate increasing budgets for research.\nThe leader is China with $15.3 billion in government funding.\nDevelopment programs have the leading technological corporations of the world.\nSo, which has made a quantum processor for 433 qubits [qubit or quantum bit - the main unit of information in quantum processors and quantum computing], plans this year to increase the number of qubits to 1121, and intends to show a device for a thousand qubits after 2025.\nThe intention to develop a full stack of technologies for quantum computing announced and has already released to the market quantum chips on spin qubits.\nIn Russia, work on quantum computing is underway on four key physical platforms: superconducting qubits, photonic circuits, neutral atoms, and trapped ions.\nThe Russian Federation has also formed a pool of organizations, including companies, scientific institutions and universities that conduct research and development, study the applicability of quantum computing to practical tasks.\n\u201cQuantum computing can give the world an impetus to the development of new industries based on the processing of big data.\nIn addition, they can improve the performance and efficiency of artificial intelligence algorithms, the accuracy of models and simulations of complex systems (such as molecules of new drugs, chemical reactions or physical processes), as well as provide a new level of calculations in finance and logistics, new solutions to climate problems and cryptographic algorithms that will provide a higher level of security.\nThe authors of the report come to the conclusion that although no one in the world has been able to demonstrate practical quantum superiority, nevertheless, companies should plan today what will happen after its achievement.\nQuantum computing is able to integrate seamlessly into data processing workflows, using adaptation tools for popular programming languages and interfaces.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0027.json.gz:171094","uncompressed_offset":399146656,"url":"finance.rambler.ru/economics/51460047-investitsii-v-startapy-sfery-kvantovyh-vychisleniy-v-2022-godu-dostigli-2-35-mlrd/","warc_date":"2023-09-21T14:34:01.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b>","warc_url":"https://finance.rambler.ru/economics/51460047-investitsii-v-startapy-sfery-kvantovyh-vychisleniy-v-2022-godu-dostigli-2-35-mlrd/"},"created":"2023-09-21T14:46:42.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
