 on the other hand, accounted for slightly more than 28% of global quantum information technology patent applications during the same period."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"China's progress in quantum computing is also evident in the development of its own quantum computer, \"Genyuan Wukong\", which is equipped with autonomous and controllable hardware, chips, operating systems, and application software."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The localization rate of \"Genyuan Wukong\" is more than 80%, marking the basic formation of China's superconducting quantum computer industry chain."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"Other countries, such as India, are also investing in quantum computing, although the number of people working on quantum computing in India is relatively small compared to the United States."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"There are currently only four people in India working on superconducting qubit research, compared to at least 20 academic labs and numerous companies in the United States."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"However, India is not too late to the game, and investing in quantum computing now could lead to breakthroughs that make the technology useful."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"In fact, investing in quantum computing is crucial for countries to stay ahead of the curve, with the UK announcing a \u00a32.5bn investment in the quantum sector."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"This investment will support the development of quantum computers and facilitate long-term growth in the field."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is not without its challenges, however, with obstacles such as the high manufacturing cost and low reliability of quantum computers."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, progress is being made in the development of quantum computing hardware, with companies such as IBM and Google creating quantum processors with increasingly more qubits."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The creation of new materials suitable for use in quantum computers is also an area of ongoing research and development."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"In addition to hardware, quantum computing software is also still in its early stages of development, with companies such as D-Wave Systems, Google, and IBM working on developing tools and resources for quantum algorithms."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"In terms of successes, \"Genyuan Wukong\" has successfully completed more than 178,000 computing tasks for users in 120 countries since its launch."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The frequency of visits by US users to \"Genyuan Wukong\" is also much higher than that of other countries, indicating a high level of interest in the technology."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is a rapidly growing field, with various companies and countries investing heavily in research and development to stay ahead of the curve."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Overall, the development of quantum computing is a complex and challenging field, but one that has the potential to revolutionize the way we approach computing and problem-solving."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The key market segments in the quantum computing field include hardware, software, and services, with applications in defense, healthcare and pharmaceuticals, chemicals, banking and finance, and energy and power."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The key market players in the field include D-Wave Systems, Google, IBM, Intel, Microsoft, and numerous other companies."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"The investment in quantum computing is expected to continue to grow, with the UK's \u00a32.5bn investment in the quantum sector being a notable example."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"This investment will support the development of quantum computers and facilitate long-term growth in the field."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the development of quantum computing is a rapidly growing field, with various companies and countries investing heavily in research and development to stay ahead of the curve."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The successes and lessons learned along the way will be crucial in shaping the future of the field and realizing the potential of quantum computing."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The development of quantum computing is a rapidly growing field, with various companies and countries investing heavily in research and development to stay ahead of the curve."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Currently, North America is the leading market for quantum computing, with the United States playing a major role, driven by companies such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"These companies are driving growth through their presence and investment in research and development activities related to quantum computing, with numerous key players in the region."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"In addition to North America, Europe is also an increasingly important market for quantum computing, with countries such as the UK, Germany, and France investing heavily in research and development."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Partnerships between quantum computing companies and other technology firms, as well as the growing adoption of quantum computing, are contributing to the growth of the market in Europe."},{"citations":{"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":1.0},"text":"China is also a major player in the field of quantum computing, with the government allocating $15.3 billion in funding for research and development."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"This investment has enabled China to make rapid progress in the field, with the country accounting for 37% of global quantum information technology patent applications from 2003 to 2022."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The United States, on the other hand, accounted for slightly more than 28% of global quantum information technology patent applications during the same period."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"China's progress in quantum computing is also evident in the development of its own quantum computer, \"Genyuan Wukong\", which is equipped with autonomous and controllable hardware, chips, operating systems, and application software."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The localization rate of \"Genyuan Wukong\" is more than 80%, marking the basic formation of China's superconducting quantum computer industry chain."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"Other countries, such as India, are also investing in quantum computing, although the number of people working on quantum computing in India is relatively small compared to the United States."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"There are currently only four people in India working on superconducting qubit research, compared to at least 20 academic labs and numerous companies in the United States."},{"citations":{"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":1.0},"text":"However, India is not too late to the game, and investing in quantum computing now could lead to breakthroughs that make the technology useful."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"In fact, investing in quantum computing is crucial for countries to stay ahead of the curve, with the UK announcing a \u00a32.5bn investment in the quantum sector."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"This investment will support the development of quantum computers and facilitate long-term growth in the field."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is not without its challenges, however, with obstacles such as the high manufacturing cost and low reliability of quantum computers."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, progress is being made in the development of quantum computing hardware, with companies such as IBM and Google creating quantum processors with increasingly more qubits."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The creation of new materials suitable for use in quantum computers is also an area of ongoing research and development."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"In addition to hardware, quantum computing software is also still in its early stages of development, with companies such as D-Wave Systems, Google, and IBM working on developing tools and resources for quantum algorithms."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"In terms of successes, \"Genyuan Wukong\" has successfully completed more than 178,000 computing tasks for users in 120 countries since its launch."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":1.0},"text":"The frequency of visits by US users to \"Genyuan Wukong\" is also much higher than that of other countries, indicating a high level of interest in the technology."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The development of quantum computing is a rapidly growing field, with various companies and countries investing heavily in research and development to stay ahead of the curve."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"Overall, the development of quantum computing is a complex and challenging field, but one that has the potential to revolutionize the way we approach computing and problem-solving."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The key market segments in the quantum computing field include hardware, software, and services, with applications in defense, healthcare and pharmaceuticals, chemicals, banking and finance, and energy and power."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The key market players in the field include D-Wave Systems, Google, IBM, Intel, Microsoft, and numerous other companies."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"The investment in quantum computing is expected to continue to grow, with the UK's \u00a32.5bn investment in the quantum sector being a notable example."},{"citations":{"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":1.0},"text":"This investment will support the development of quantum computers and facilitate long-term growth in the field."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the development of quantum computing is a rapidly growing field, with various companies and countries investing heavily in research and development to stay ahead of the curve."},{"citations":{"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":1.0},"text":"The successes and lessons learned along the way will be crucial in shaping the future of the field and realizing the potential of quantum computing."}],"references":["8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839","9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656","977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795","9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985"],"documents":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_116579795","text":"People 's Daily Online > > Economy and Technology\n\"Origin Goku\" stable operation shows what\nMay 12, 2024 08: 54 | Source: Economic Daily\nSmall number\nOriginal title: \"The source of Goku\" stable operation shows what\nAs of May 7, China's third-generation autonomous superconducting quantum computer \"Origin Wukong\" has attracted more than 8 million visits worldwide.\nPreviously, it was successfully connected to three supercomputing centers such as the Yangtze River Delta hub Wuhu cluster computing power public service platform, marking the formal completion of China's \"four calculations in one\" system of general computing, intelligent computing, supercomputing and measurement.\nWhat does the stable operation of \"Origin Goku\" show?\n\"Genyuan Wukong\" is China's third-generation autonomous superconducting quantum computer, equipped with 72-bit autonomous superconducting quantum chips.\nThe computer is named \"Wukong\", which means that it is as powerful as the traditional Chinese mythological figure Sun Wukong and can change 72 times.\n\"Benyuan Wukong\" was independently developed by the Benyuan Quantum team and launched on January 6 this year. Since the launch of the line, the average daily global visit is about 66,700 times, and the average daily completion of nearly 1,500 computing tasks.\nQuantum computing is a cutting-edge emerging technology that has great potential in artificial intelligence, biomedicine, financial analysis and other fields.\nIf the general purpose traditional computer is compared to a bicycle, the quantum computer is like an airplane.\nTo break down 300 large numbers, it takes 150,000 years to make use of a trillionth of a conventional computer, and 1 second to make use of a trillionth of a quantum computer.\nThe biggest advantage of quantum computers is their powerful computing power, but compared with traditional computers, the technology is immature, the manufacturing cost is high, and the reliability is not strong.\nChina's quantum computing technology is in the transition stage from laboratory research and development to industrial application.\n\"Genyuan Wukong\" equipped with hardware, chips, operating systems and application software are autonomous and controllable, and the localization rate is more than 80%, which marks the basic formation of China's superconducting quantum computer industry chain.\nIn the four months since its launch, \"Benyuan Wukong\" has successfully completed more than 178,000 computing tasks for users in 120 countries, and countries with quantum computers such as the United States, Japan and Canada have shown great concern for \"Benyuan Wukong\", among which the frequency of visits by US users is much higher than that of other countries.\nIn the field of quantum computing, developed countries led by the United States have started early, developed rapidly and have a high degree of industrial maturity, and have gradually established a \"quantum computing ecological chain.\"\nFor example, in 2017, IBM led the establishment of the Quantum Computing Industry Alliance (IBM Quantum Network), which has more than 250 members from the United States, Japan, South Korea, Germany, Australia and other countries, involving Fortune 500 companies, start-ups and academic institutions.\nHowever, although China started late in the quantum field, it has made rapid progress.\nA recent paper on global quantum information technology patents shows that from 2003 to 2022, China's quantum information technology patent applications accounted for 37% of the global total, surpassing the proportion of the United States slightly more than 28%.\n\"Origin Wukong\" is the first large-scale and long-term opening of China's quantum computing power to the world, indicating that China has officially entered the \"usable\" era of quantum computing power.\nLooking forward to the future, let the \"Wukong\" further play the power of the \"source\", it will take many efforts.\nWe should focus on making up for the shortcomings and strength of the weak, so that the key instruments and equipment of quantum computing can be fully replaced in China. We should support the building of the quantum chip industry chain and build a quantum computing power network. To change the situation of shortage of talents in the quantum field.\nComputing power is the new quality of productivity in the digital economy era, who has mastered the advanced computing power, who has mastered the \"winning chance\" of development.\nOn the international science and technology track of quantum computers, the layout and development of independent industrial chains is an inevitable choice for us to face the forefront of world science and technology, the main battlefield of the economy, and the major needs of the country.\n(Editor: Yang Xi, Chen Jian)\nPublic Number \uff1a People 's Network Finance\nShare it so more people can see it.\nBack to top","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0012.json.gz:25770","uncompressed_offset":116579795,"url":"finance.people.com.cn/n1/2024/0512/c1004-40234145.html","warc_date":"2024-05-12T01:44:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506>","warc_url":"http://finance.people.com.cn/n1/2024/0512/c1004-40234145.html"},"created":"2024-05-12T02:04:13.000Z","lang":"eng"},"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738":{"id":"977c1b08-f457-4592-b30f-316ec69ce838_634867738","text":"While the UK considers where to channel investment, we need to ensure that quantum technology is at the forefront of those considerations.\n\nQuantum will not only drive our economy, but will also help create new opportunities in different sectors, ranging from healthcare to agriculture.\n\nAt the Global Investment Summit (GIS) last month, Prime Minister Rishi Sunak announced a three-fold increase, up to \u00a329.5bn, from the world\u2019s leading investors in new UK projects and capital.\n\nThese funds will be channelled into \u201chigh-growth projects\u201d in the UK, including quantum technology.\n\nIt is great to see quantum being recognised as a potential game changer in the future of the UK economy, and it is important that we continue this momentum.\n\nQuantum\u2019s economic and social value\n\nQuantum provides an exciting opportunity for the economy because the technology has a wide range of possible applications.\n\nThe last decade has seen an 81% growth in the quantum sector and now contributes an estimated \u00a31.7bn to the UK economy. Financial services, healthcare and climate change - all major sectors in the UK ecosystem - are just three of the areas that will be enhanced by quantum.\n\nThe ability to optimise complex financial portfolios in real-time or simulate molecular interactions with unprecedented accuracy could reshape sectors in their entirety. Molecular interaction simulation can assist the healthcare industry to an immense extent.\n\nPossibilities include being able to improve the process of accurately modelling how new drugs will impact different types of conditions and diseases - leading to breakthroughs in serious and harder-to-treat illnesses.\n\nThis technology will also help us in the battle against climate change, specifically in its ability to predict weather more accurately. Current computational power for measuring CO2 does not always predict the correct climate outcome, as we saw with the MET office\u2019s prediction for Storm Ciaran.\n\nAs quantum technology is introduced into these sectors, it will forecast weather more accurately than our current conventional methods, therefore enhancing the precision of new data.\n\nHowever, in order to see these possibilities realised, quantum needs investment from the government; it needs further development and innovation to be able to reach its potential.\n\nNurturing this sector is crucial not only to cement the UK as a leader in this technology, but to enable us to develop the tools that can tackle pressing global issues, whether that is developing more solar farms or investing in nuclear energy.\n\nInvestment moves to boost growth\n\nEarlier in 2023, the UK government published its 10-year vision, the National Quantum Strategy. This outlines \u00a32.5bn of public and private investment into the rapidly growing quantum sector.\n\nAt the GIS, Oxford Quantum Circuits stated its intention to raise \u00a385m for research and development projects, while SBI Investment - Japan\u2019s foremost venture capital fund - is leading the raise. This raise will be the largest for Series B in quantum computing ever in the UK, supporting the need for investment to empower growth.\n\nQuantum computers need to be developed and operated by the brightest minds in the field to solve the world\u2019s most pressing challenges \u2013 from climate change to accelerated drug discovery.\n\nIt is crucial that we make investments that induce growth in all sectors, combating concerns about additional capital in quantum being 'snake oil'.\n\nInvestment in devices and systems which rely on quantum mechanics will provide capabilities that classical machines cannot; it is just a matter of time.\n\nFacilitating long-term growth\n\nWhile investment in quantum has not always led to growth, with several smaller enterprises struggling in the short term, it is important that we are supporting research and innovation in this sector in order to facilitate long-term growth.\n\nQuantum technology has a unique power to solve problems that classical computers cannot manage.\n\nWhen performing complex calculations, quantum is able to pinpoint a more precise answer among the billions of alternate possibilities.\n\nTherefore, with the potential for groundbreaking advancements and transformative applications, quantum computing is set to drive innovation, reshape industries, and unlock new possibilities we can hardly fathom today, culminating in growth.\n\nGraeme Malcolm OBE is the chief executive and founder of M Squared","url":"https://www.insider.co.uk/news/quantum-investment-always-equal-growth-31722772"},"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839":{"id":"8bd5be6b-d422-4a7a-94ad-0f5c141c23ea_425862839","text":"Register Now : Join us for AWS presents TRANSFORMING A BILLION LIVES webinar on Wednesday, 19th April 2023 | 3.00pm onwards\nyou are here: HomeNewsBusiness\n\nIndia is not too late in quantum computing: Tata Institute of Fundamental Research's Rajamani Vijayaraghavan\n\nInvestment in quantum tech has crossed $36 billion globally. It is billed to be the next big thing in tech after semiconductors and artificial intelligence. Tata Institute of Fundamental Research (TIFR) scientist says India is lagging, but can catch up\n\nApril 06, 2023 / 11:23 AM IST\n\nProfessor Rajamani Vijayaraghavan\n\nWhen Professor Rajamani Vijayaraghavan was not present at a quantum tech conference in New Delhi last week, he was missed by his peers.\n\nAs scientists, bureaucrats, military officers and startup executives gathered for a conversation on the way forward for India\u2019s quantum technology ambitions, the general feeling was that Vijayaraghavan should have been there.\n\nQuantum computing taps the unique behaviour of quantum physics to solve certain problems that are too complex for traditional computing.\n\nIf semiconductor technology was the first giant leap in computing and Artificial Intelligence is the current disruptor, it is probably going to be quantum technology next. Quantum computing, conceived by Nobel Prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman in the early 1980s, was mostly studied in university labs in the US and Europe until the turn of the millennium.\n\nAs advances took place, tech behemoths like Google, International Business Machines (IBM) and Intel threw their hat in the ring with billions of dollars in investment. According to an estimate, China has invested $15 billion even as global funding in the technology has topped $36 billion.\n\nAt the New Delhi conclave last week, a senior defence official said the wars of the future will be fought on the quantum front. While sizeable quantum computers do not yet exist, the fear among governments and industry is that it will be a Y2K moment once the technology comes to life.\n\nApart from strategic affairs, quantum tech is also expected to play a central role in areas like drug discovery, financial modelling, weather forecasting and fighting climate change.\n\nMoneycontrol spoke with Professor Vijayaraghavan, a quantum computing scientist at Tata Institute of Fundamental Research (TIFR) who returned to the country a decade ago after studying at the universities of Cambridge, Yale and Berkeley, to take stock of India\u2019s progress in the area.\n\nEdited excerpts:\u00a0\n\nAt the quantum tech conclave in Delhi last week, it seemed as though most Indian quantum start-ups are working on secure communications rather than quantum computing. Why so? \u00a0\n\nSee, in terms of the technology required for doing quantum key distribution (for secure communications), or associated areas like quantum random number generators, it is now fairly well developed internationally. Also, the essential tools and core pieces of hardware and things you need are relatively low-cost and easily available, compared to quantum computing.\n\nIf you shift to quantum computing, even if you just take a very basic estimate, it needs about a million dollars just to set up a very basic lab. This was the kind of funding that was given to me when I started in TIFR about 10 years ago, just to have a very basic setup and do simple experiments.\n\nI'm not even talking about the resources you need to develop prototypes and technology. And even this $1 million is an underestimate, because there are other facilities, which were already existing in the institute for device fabrication, clean rooms, and other tools. If I count all of those, then you are talking about a couple of million dollars, at the very least, to get started.\n\nNow, of course, a company could hire these resources from other places. But such facilities don't exist in India, and as of now, even internationally, they are limited, where a company with no infrastructure of their own, but just the idea and expertise could go to a place and say, hey, you know, here is my design, manufacture this for me, and we will put it together.\n\nExperts say that India first missed the bus in taking a lead in semiconductor technology and now even in artificial intelligence. They say it is now or never if we want to be leaders in quantum computing. What is your take?\u00a0\u00a0\n\nI broadly agree with it, but let me expand on that. Before something becomes close to technology, there is decades of basic research where they are not even thinking about technology. I started my PhD in the year 2001, i.e. over 22 years back. And that was a turning point when the field of quantum computing was taking off. That was on the back of basic research in quantum computing from the 1980s.\n\nIt is absolutely true that if you want to do this, you have to do it now. And with this particular technology, we are not so far behind. Barring a few areas where things have sort of more or less been figured out, we still need several breakthroughs. Even though it looks like IBM has reached so many qubits (a qubit is the basic unit of information in quantum computing) and Google that many, they still don't have a useful quantum computer today. None of these quantum computers that exist anywhere in the world are really useful in the sense that they can replace something to do the work much better.\n\nAt how many qubits do you think we can solve real world problems better than existing supercomputers?\n\nIt really depends on what you mean by qubits. So there is this notion of physical qubits and logical qubits. The difference is that physical qubits are unstable. Unlike conventional bits in our regular computers, which are extremely stable, and you don't have to worry about them at all, these things are not stable. They actually randomly change their state and give rise to errors. And this happens over a certain timescale, which can be as short as 10s of microseconds or a few milliseconds.\n\nToday\u2019s quantum computers are essentially limited in how long you can use them, or essentially, what is the longest calculation you can run before you can't trust the results of what the computer is outputting. This is a fundamental problem across all quantum computing platforms today. There are some clear paths to solve this, but it is not clear which particular method would win.\n\n\nAnd this is where I want to go back to my earlier point that India is not too late. If we invest now, we could create those breakthroughs that can make this technology useful. If enough people start working, and it's not just one or two people in the entire country, then you can hope that these breakthroughs can happen here. And then that will allow us to take a lead in some areas.\n\nIn your estimate, how many people are working on quantum computing in India vis-a-vis the US or other countries?\n\nFor superconducting qubit research, as of now, there are four people in India. I was the first one who started about 10 years ago, and then two others started maybe about six and four years ago, and one has just joined.\n\nIn the US, there are at least 20 or more academic labs, in addition to Google, IBM, or national labs like Fermilab, and I'm not even counting theoretical groups. Many of them have been working for over 20 years or so. And you know, similarly, in Europe, there will be at least 10 to 15 labs just in superconducting quantum computing.\n\n\nIf you look into some of the other subfields like trapped ion quantum computing, it's even smaller.\n\nOne of the major issues in advanced research is brain drain. Many of our best researchers still tend to settle abroad. Is more funding alone going to solve this to an extent? What tipped the scales for you to return?\n\nDecisions about moving back to India can be very complicated, you know. There are all kinds of personal and professional reasons, but the point is very simple. You cannot attract someone to come to India to work in a field that requires a certain level of investment by telling them that we will not give it to you.\n\nFor me, I always wanted to come back to India and do something if it is possible. And once I finished my PhD, I started looking around and realised that there are lots of labs, which are fairly high-tech and at the cutting edge. Funding seemed to have improved in the previous few years or decade. It was important that I would be able to do the kind of research I was interested in doing rather than compromise. If that had not happened, I would have taken up a job abroad.\n\nHas the funding scenario gotten better since then?\n\nIt's now becoming better, at least among the bigger institutes, but it's still quite a challenge. There is no real guarantee that you will get the kind of funding needed for experimental quantum research, and we are trying to solve this problem with the new funding programmes.\n\nThere is a reluctance to invest so much money in a new person. The idea of a startup grant is very clear in the West \u2013 your offer letter clearly says that you will get $1 million and you have to spend it in the next four to five years\u2026 everything is spelt out. We are not able to do that.\u00a0 You have to keep your fingers crossed and hope for the best.\n\nThis actually does pose a barrier to entry because it's not competitive. If I have offers from an Indian institute, where everything is ambiguous, and some other foreign Institute, where everything is clearly spelt out, then it is very difficult to make a decision in favour of the former. Unless, of course, there are personal reasons to be in the country.\n\nIt should be a much more streamlined process for the government to disburse funds now as many new advanced research and academic institutes have come up. What are we missing here?\u00a0\n\nOh, no. It is not easy at all. The bigger institutes have some advantages in terms of flexibility of using their funds, but it is not easy to get big grants. Currently, the amount that you can get for a standard Department of Science and Technology (DST) project is Rs 10 lakh-50 lakh. That\u2019s the typical range. Special programmes can provide bigger funding but they are rare.\n\nUsually, it is easier to get big funding when a new institute is being built to set up new facilities. From thereon, things get tougher as you reach a steady state. Look, you need investment if you want to work in quantum tech. Of course, one can make a call that \u2018Okay, we cannot afford this research, so we will not do it.\u2019 But if you want to, there is no other option, you have to find ways to support this.\n\nA few years back, the DST started a programme called QUEST (Quantum Enabled Science and Technology) where 50 scientists got funded with a combined funding of about Rs 200 crores. It was the first major effort in funding quantum tech research where an individual group could have hoped to get something of the order of Rs. 5 to 10 crore, which is the minimum you need to set up a lab working in quantum tech.\n\nWas this part of the Rs 8,000 crore quantum national mission announced in the 2020 budget?\u00a0\n\nNo, this was a different programme where the first discussions started in 2017 and the money started coming in\u00a0 2019-2020. Unfortunately, it was right in the middle of the pandemic, when you know, things were shut, and we couldn't spend the money. On top of that, as part of the pandemic-related things, the government made it very difficult to import things.\n\nThe National Mission on Quantum Technology and Applications (NMQTA) with a proposed budget of Rs 8,000 crore is expected to launch sometime soon. Probably, you know, in the next few months. We have been working on it.\n\nCan you tell us more about the import policy?\n\nIt was introduced in the summer of 2020. This was not a science policy. This was a government procurement policy. You know, on the face of it, it seems like a good idea. They wanted to encourage Indian industry and push for self-reliance. On paper, it sounds great. And it might even work for certain types of government procurement.\n\nThey're basically saying that if you're supported by government funds, you have to prioritise Indian-manufactured goods. And the way they implemented it is by saying that if something costs more than Rs 5 lakh and you want to import it, you have to go through a new procedure and get a waiver before you can even float a global tender.\n\nIn the beginning, we were surprised, and we said, okay, maybe they just didn't think about scientific procurement. So, in a few months, they will fix it but it didn't happen. It took about six to seven months before some exception was given. But there is no blanket exception given for scientific procurement.\n\nThey reduced the number of signatures required by one and made some exceptions. Unfortunately, even there, because of a lack of clarity, every institute has interpreted the rules differently. And we are definitely facing a lot of problems still. In the best-case scenario, we are still wasting about three months just to get approval to import an item.\n\nDoes most scientific procurement happen from abroad?\n\nThe problem is to assume that there is an Indian option and we are actively choosing not to use it. That is not the case for 99 percent or even more. It is a well-known fact that for scientific high-tech equipment, there is no manufacturing happening in India\u2026 there are no companies which exist. But, we have to now prove it with paperwork to get the waiver. Even if we invest Rs 8,000 crore, it won\u2019t work if these kinds of policies are not fixed. We are wasting a bulk of the time just doing this paperwork, and not actually doing research.\n\nIt might be more fruitful if you create opportunities in the nation for companies to come together and manufacture at least some of the things in India. But, when you have not had a manufacturing base in a certain technology for decades, how can you start doing that overnight? And in many cases, it might not even make economic sense for a company because it's a niche market.\n\nIs it possible for India to build an indigenous quantum computer?\u00a0\n\n\nIn today's globalised world, nothing is going to be fully indigenous. For superconducting qubits, you can innovate the design of the chip and make it here, but the lithographic machines and dilution refrigerators have to come from outside.\n\nThere is a section which says we can just use quantum computing on the cloud that foreign tech companies provide. Isn\u2019t there a possibility that the use cases of quantum on the cloud will be limited?\u00a0\n\nAs I said earlier, none of the available quantum computers are doing anything useful better than classical computers at present. When it happens in the future, and it will, you might be able to use cloud-based systems for many applications. On one hand, we can continue to be just a leader in the software layer. One could decide that we will develop the best quantum software in the world, but we will never develop any hardware.\n\nThe problem really comes when you start talking about strategic applications \u2013 whether the cloud company will provide you with the best systems they have access to. That's the fundamental question we have to ask ourselves.\n\nWe don\u2019t have a quantum computer, but startups are providing a solution called quantum key distribution (QKD) for secure communications. How do we know it is really secure if they have not been tested against a quantum computing hack?\n\nQKD fundamentally relies on the fact that if somebody tries to interfere, you will know. And the trick in any secret communication is that if two parties can exchange a key without anybody else knowing, then the information you transmit using encoding based on that key is secure. Quantum key distribution is a method where the laws of physics guarantee that the key you have exchanged has not been intercepted by anybody else. Because the moment somebody intercepts, you will know and you will discard that key. It cannot be broken by even a quantum computer. So you don't need to test it against a quantum computer.\n\nA bureaucrat was saying that enterprises are concerned that they might be sold classical computing solutions in the garb of quantum tech. So the government is trying to bring a quantum certification programme. Would it have the bandwidth to do such accreditation?\n\nYou have to look at this slightly differently. There are things in quantum which are impossible in classical. So if whatever you're purchasing is actually carrying out that task, it cannot do it the classical way. And if there are applications where both classical and quantum can do that, then it is unclear why you would bother unless there is a cost advantage or a performance advantage for the quantum solution.\n\nAs a business or an enterprise that wants some problem solved, you will put the problem statement, and the quantum company will say this is the solution. So, why do you care what is inside?\u200b The bureaucrat was probably referring to quantum communication systems where you want some central body to verify that the system is really secure and meets certain standards. I believe the government is setting up such bodies for various quantum technologies.\n\nDeepsekhar Choudhury Deepsekhar covers tech and startups at Moneycontrol. Tweets at @deepsekharc","url":"https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/india-is-not-too-late-in-quantum-computing-tata-institute-of-fundamental-researchs-rajamani-vijayaraghavan-10371621.html"},"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985":{"id":"9d67d90b-c58f-4444-aaaa-88164c533333_281634985","text":"Quantum Computing Market was valued at nearly USD 234.06 billion by 2032\n\nPrudour Private Limited\n\nUpdated \u00b7 Mar 06, 2023\n\nQuantum Computing Market Overview\n\nPublished Via 11Press: Quantum computing is a rapidly developing market that is revolutionizing how we approach computing and data processing. By employing principles of quantum mechanics to perform computations, quantum computers are capable of solving problems that classical computers may find impossible or impracticable to resolve.\n\nThe global\u00a0quantum computing\u00a0market size is forecast to reach\u00a0USD 234.06 billion\u00a0by 2032 from\u00a0USD 10.13 billion\u00a0in 2022, rising at a compound annual growth rate\u00a0(CAGR) of 36.89%\u00a0during the forecast period.\n\nAt present, the quantum computing market is dominated by a few major players such as IBM, Google, Microsoft, and Honeywell. These firms are investing heavily in quantum computing research and development as well as creating quantum computing hardware and software systems.\n\nThe quantum computing market is expected to have a profound effect on industries such as healthcare, finance, logistics, and energy. Some key applications of quantum computing include drug discovery, supply chain optimization, financial modeling, and climate modeling.\n\nThough the quantum computing market is promising, it still faces several obstacles such as high costs of hardware, a shortage of skilled experts in this area, and technical difficulties when building large-scale quantum computers. With ongoing research and development efforts, however, these problems should be overcome within the coming years, leading to even greater growth and innovation in this space.\n\nKey Takeaways\n\n  \u2022 The global quantum computing market size was valued at\u00a0USD 234.06 billion\u00a0in 2022 and is expected to grow at a\u00a0CAGR of around 36.89% from 2022 to 2032.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing is capable of solving problems that would be intractable or impossible for classical computers to solve.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market is dominated by a few major players, including IBM, Google, Microsoft and Honeywell.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market is expected to have a profound effect on numerous industries, such as healthcare, finance, logistics and energy.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing has many important applications such as drug discovery, supply chain optimization, financial modeling and climate modeling.\n  \u2022 The quantum computing market remains plagued by several obstacles, such as the high cost of quantum computing hardware, lack of qualified quantum computing experts and technical difficulties in building and running large-scale quantum computing systems.\n  \u2022 Research and development are expected to overcome these obstacles within the next couple of years, propelling even greater growth and innovation in the quantum computing market.\n\nRequest For Sample Report:\u00a0https://market.us/report/quantum-computing-market/request-sample/\n\nRegional Snapshot\n\n  \u2022 North America:\u00a0North America is currently the leading market for quantum computing, with the United States playing a major role. Major companies such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft are driving this growth through their presence and investment in research and development activities related to quantum computing. This region boasts numerous key players such as IBM, Google, and Microsoft which are driving demand within this region.\n  \u2022 Europe:\u00a0Europe is an increasingly important market for quantum computing, with countries such as the UK, Germany, and France investing heavily in research and development. Through partnerships between quantum computing companies and other technology firms as well as the growing adoption of quantum computing across various industries, this region\u2019s market is experiencing rapid expansion.\n  \u2022 Asia Pacific:\u00a0The quantum computing market in Asia Pacific is expected to experience significant growth over the coming years due to increased investments in research and development by countries like China, Japan, and South Korea. Furthermore, there have been an increasing number of collaborations between companies using quantum computing with academic institutions as well as its increasing adoption across industries like healthcare and finance \u2013 all contributing factors for market expansion within this region.\n  \u2022 The Rest of the World:\u00a0Countries such as Brazil, South Africa, and the UAE are expected to experience significant growth in the quantum computing market over the coming years due to increased investments in research and development efforts as well as the growing adoption of quantum computing across various industries. These factors are fueling this region\u2019s meteoric rise in this region.\n\nDrivers\n\n  \u2022 Quantum Computing Gaining Adoption in Various Industries:\u00a0Quantum computing is seeing an uptick in popularity across a range of industries, such as healthcare, finance, logistics, and energy \u2013 as companies seek to use their power to solve complex problems and gain an edge in competition.\n  \u2022 Investments in Quantum Computing Research and Development:\u00a0Governments, academic institutions, and private companies have made substantial investments in quantum computing research and development, spurring innovation and progress within the field.\n  \u2022 Growing Number of Partnerships and Collaborations:\u00a0There has been an uptick in partnerships and collaborations between quantum computing companies and other technology firms, as well as academic institutions and research organizations. This trend is propelling the development of new quantum computing hardware and software systems, as well as its adoption across various industries.\n  \u2022 Increasing Access to Cloud-Based Quantum Computing Services:\u00a0The growing availability of cloud-based quantum computing services is making it simpler for companies and researchers to utilize this cutting-edge technology, spurring adoption and innovation within the field.\n\nRestraints\n\n  \u2022 Limited Access to Qualified Quantum Computing Experts:\u00a0Unfortunately, there is currently a shortage of highly experienced quantum computing specialists, making it challenging for companies to construct and sustain quantum computing systems.\n  \u2022 Technical Challenges in Building and Maintaining Large-Scale Quantum Computing Systems:\u00a0The development of large-scale quantum computing systems is still in its early stages, so there are numerous technical obstacles that must be overcome, such as noise reduction, error correction, and scalability.\n  \u2022 Limited Quantum Computing Applications:\u00a0Although the list of potential applications for quantum computing is growing, the number of practical ones that have been developed and implemented remains limited. This can make it challenging for companies to justify investing in quantum computing technology.\n  \u2022 Regulatory Challenges:\u00a0Quantum computing technology may face regulatory restrictions, particularly around data privacy and security. This could create additional obstacles to the adoption and investment in the technology.\n\nOpportunities\n\n  \u2022 Growing Number of Partnerships and Collaborations:\u00a0The growing number of partnerships and collaborations among quantum computing companies, other technology firms, academic institutions, and research organizations is creating opportunities for the development of new quantum computing hardware and software systems as well as its adoption across various industries.\n  \u2022 Advancements in Quantum Computing Hardware and Software:\u00a0With the rapid progress being made in the development of quantum computing hardware and software, new opportunities will present themselves for applying this technology across various industries and fields.\n  \u2022 The growing availability of cloud-based quantum computing services:\u00a0Cloud-based quantum computing services are making it simpler for companies and researchers to access and utilize quantum computing technology, spurring adoption and innovation within the field.\n  \u2022 Growth of Quantum Computing as a Service:\u00a0As more companies and researchers embrace the potential of quantum computing, cloud-based quantum computing services are creating exciting new business opportunities for those offering these solutions.\n  \u2022 Potential for Breakthroughs in Areas such as Drug Discovery, Finance, and Energy:\u00a0Quantum computing holds the potential to unravel complex issues in fields like drug discovery, finance, and energy \u2013 leading to major breakthroughs and advances. This presents companies with unique opportunities for those who can develop and implement quantum computing solutions in these sectors.\n\nChallenges\n\n  \u2022 Technical Challenges in Constructing and Running Large Quantum Computing Systems:\u00a0As quantum computing systems continue to emerge, numerous technical obstacles must be overcome such as noise reduction, error correction, and scalability. These issues make it challenging for companies to construct and run these massive quantum computers efficiently.\n  \u2022 Limited Access to Qualified Quantum Computing Experts:\u00a0There is currently a shortage of highly experienced quantum computing professionals, making it difficult for companies to construct and maintain quantum computing systems. This shortage could potentially restrict the growth of this industry in the coming years.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing Applications:\u00a0While quantum computing has many potential uses, the number of practical applications that have been created and implemented remains limited. This could make investing in quantum computing technology and research on practical applications an attractive prospect.\n\nGrow your profit margin with Market.us\u00a0Get this Report\n\nRecent Developments\n\n  \u2022 Google Claims Quantum Supremacy:\u00a0In 2019, Google claimed to have achieved quantum supremacy by performing a calculation on its quantum computer that even the most powerful supercomputers would take thousands of years to complete. This was seen as an important milestone in the advancement of quantum computing technology.\n  \u2022 IBM Launches Quantum Computing Program for Students:\u00a0In 2020, IBM unveiled a quantum computing program specifically tailored towards students that provides them with access to IBM\u2019s resources and tools, as well as a platform for learning and collaboration.\n  \u2022 Honeywell Achieves Quantum Computer Record Performance:\u00a0On March 20, 2021, Honeywell revealed its creation of a quantum computer with an astonishing quantum volume of 512. This feat marked an amazing advancement in quantum computing technology and demonstrated how rapidly progress has been made since then.\n  \u2022 Amazon Web Services Announces Quantum Computing Service:\u00a0On June 2021, Amazon Web Services (AWS) announced the launch of its own quantum computing service called Amazon Bracket. This offering gives customers access to various vendors\u2019 hardware as well as tools and resources for developing and testing quantum algorithms.\n\nKey Market Segments\n\nType\n\n  \u2022 Hardware\n  \u2022 Software\n  \u2022 Services\n\nApplication\n\n  \u2022 Defense\n  \u2022 Healthcare & pharmaceuticals\n  \u2022 Chemicals\n  \u2022 Banking & Finance\n  \u2022 Energy & power\n\nKey Market Players\n\n  \u2022 D-Wave Systems\n  \u2022 Google\n  \u2022 IBM\n  \u2022 Intel\n  \u2022 Microsoft\n  \u2022 1QB Information Technologies\n  \u2022 Anyon Systems\n  \u2022 Cambridge Quantum Computing\n  \u2022 ID Quantique\n  \u2022 IonQ\n  \u2022 QbitLogic\n  \u2022 QC Ware\n  \u2022 Quantum Circuits\n  \u2022 Qubitekk\n  \u2022 QxBranch\n  \u2022 Rigetti Computing\n\nNature Insights\n\n  \u2022 Progress is being made in the development of quantum computing hardware:\u00a0Despite the challenges facing large-scale quantum computing systems, progress is being made on quantum computing hardware. This includes creating quantum processors with increasingly more qubits and creating new materials suitable for use in quantum computers.\n  \u2022 Quantum computing software is still in its early stages:\u00a0While progress is being made with quantum computing hardware, software development for quantum computation remains at a standstill. This presents an immense challenge to the industry as developing efficient quantum algorithms is essential to realizing its full potential.\n  \u2022 Collaboration is essential to the advancement of quantum computing:\u00a0Collaboration between companies, academic institutions, and research organizations is essential for progress in this industry. This includes joint efforts to develop new hardware and software systems as well as collaborations that promote quantum computing across various industries.\n\nReport Scope\n\nReport Attribute Details\nThe market size value in 2022 USD 10.13 Bn\nRevenue forecast by 2032 USD 234.6 Bn\nGrowth Rate CAGR Of 36.89%\nRegions Covered North America, Europe, Asia Pacific, Latin America, and Middle East & Africa, and the Rest of the World\nHistorical Years 2017-2022\nBase Year 2022\nEstimated Year 2023\nShort-Term Projection Year 2028\nLong-Term Projected Year 2032\n\nContact us\n\nContact Person: Mr. Lawrence John\n\nMarket.us (Powered By Prudour Pvt. Ltd.)\n\nTel: +1 718 618 4351\n\nSend Email: [email\u00a0protected]\n\nFAQ.\n\nWhat is quantum computing?\n\nQuantum computing is a type of processing data using quantum mechanics. It relies on principles such as superposition, entanglement, and interference which enable quantum computers to perform calculations that would be impossible with classical computers.\n\nWhat are some potential applications of quantum computing?\n\nQuantum computing holds great promise for revolutionizing industries such as drug discovery, finance, energy, and logistics. Potential uses include creating new drugs and materials, optimizing supply chains and logistics networks, and even improving weather forecasting models with greater precision.\n\nWhat are some of the challenges facing the quantum computing market?\n\nThe quantum computing market faces numerous obstacles, such as technical difficulties in building and running large-scale quantum computers, high costs associated with quantum computing hardware, a scarcity of highly qualified quantum experts, and an absence of practical applications developed and deployed.\n\nWho are some of the major players in the quantum computing market?\n\nMajor companies operating within this space include IBM, Google, Microsoft, Honeywell, Intel, and Rigetti Computing. These firms are actively developing and commercializing quantum computing hardware and software systems.\n\nWhat is the outlook for the quantum computing market?\n\nOverall, analysts anticipate a bright future for quantum computing, with continued investment and innovation anticipated in the coming years. Though still in its early stages of development, its potential advantages are immense - leading to rapid industry growth over the coming years.\n\nPrudour Private Limited\n\nThe team behind market.us, marketresearch.biz, market.biz and more. Our purpose is to keep our customers ahead of the game with regard to the markets. They may fluctuate up or down, but we will help you to stay ahead of the curve in these market fluctuations. Our consistent growth and ability to deliver in-depth analyses and market insight has engaged genuine market players. They have faith in us to offer the data and information they require to make balanced and decisive marketing decisions.","url":"https://www.enterpriseappstoday.com/news/quantum-computing-market-was-valued-at-nearly-usd-234-06-billion-by-2032.html"},"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656":{"id":"9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b_399146656","text":"Investments in quantum computing startups reached $2.35 billion in 2022\nQuantum technologies have great potential for both science and business, and attract large investments in different countries of the world, including Russia.\nThis is stated in the analytical report \"Quantum Computing: Prospects for Business\", which was prepared jointly with the Federal State Unitary Enterprise \"VNIIA named after N.L. Dukhov\" and the Institute of Artificial Intelligence AIRI.\n\u201cIncreasing attention in the world is paid to supporting start-ups in the field of quantum technologies.\nIn 2022, venture investors around the world invested $2.35 billion in them.\nAlso last year, almost 1,600 patents were issued and published in all subfields of quantum computing: from physical implementations of quantum equipment and error correction to AI [artificial intelligence] and machine learning.\nVideo of the day\nLeading countries, realizing the breakthrough potential of this direction, include quantum technologies in national programs and allocate increasing budgets for research.\nThe leader is China with $15.3 billion in government funding.\nDevelopment programs have the leading technological corporations of the world.\nSo, which has made a quantum processor for 433 qubits [qubit or quantum bit - the main unit of information in quantum processors and quantum computing], plans this year to increase the number of qubits to 1121, and intends to show a device for a thousand qubits after 2025.\nThe intention to develop a full stack of technologies for quantum computing announced and has already released to the market quantum chips on spin qubits.\nIn Russia, work on quantum computing is underway on four key physical platforms: superconducting qubits, photonic circuits, neutral atoms, and trapped ions.\nThe Russian Federation has also formed a pool of organizations, including companies, scientific institutions and universities that conduct research and development, study the applicability of quantum computing to practical tasks.\n\u201cQuantum computing can give the world an impetus to the development of new industries based on the processing of big data.\nIn addition, they can improve the performance and efficiency of artificial intelligence algorithms, the accuracy of models and simulations of complex systems (such as molecules of new drugs, chemical reactions or physical processes), as well as provide a new level of calculations in finance and logistics, new solutions to climate problems and cryptographic algorithms that will provide a higher level of security.\nThe authors of the report come to the conclusion that although no one in the world has been able to demonstrate practical quantum superiority, nevertheless, companies should plan today what will happen after its achievement.\nQuantum computing is able to integrate seamlessly into data processing workflows, using adaptation tools for popular programming languages and interfaces.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0027.json.gz:171094","uncompressed_offset":399146656,"url":"finance.rambler.ru/economics/51460047-investitsii-v-startapy-sfery-kvantovyh-vychisleniy-v-2022-godu-dostigli-2-35-mlrd/","warc_date":"2023-09-21T14:34:01.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9b9f8be2-d6b8-4d95-9482-f8415bab065b>","warc_url":"https://finance.rambler.ru/economics/51460047-investitsii-v-startapy-sfery-kvantovyh-vychisleniy-v-2022-godu-dostigli-2-35-mlrd/"},"created":"2023-09-21T14:46:42.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1083","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1083","narrative_id":"1083"},"responses":[{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoth's extinction is a complex phenomenon that has been debated by scientists for centuries, with climate change and early human hunting being the two main factors considered."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"According to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"A 2021 study published in Nature concluded that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"However, some scientists argue that humans may have been the main factor in their extinction, as mammoths survived climate change before humans appeared and would probably survive to this day had it not been for the added pressure humans placed on them."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"An international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity, and that the warming of the climate itself, particularly rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The speed of climate change was also a crucial factor, as the mammoths could not adapt quickly enough when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"Recent studies suggest that hunger caused by climate change is the real killer, rather than overhunting by ancient people."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"Overall, based on the available evidence, it appears that climate change was the primary cause of the woolly mammoth's extinction, with human hunting playing a secondary role."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoth's extinction is a complex phenomenon that has been debated by scientists for centuries, with climate change and early human hunting being the two main factors considered."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"According to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"A 2021 study published in Nature concluded that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"However, some scientists argue that humans may have been the main factor in their extinction, as mammoths survived climate change before humans appeared and would probably survive to this day had it not been for the added pressure humans placed on them."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"An international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity, and that the warming of the climate itself, particularly rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The speed of climate change was also a crucial factor, as the mammoths could not adapt quickly enough when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"Recent studies suggest that hunger caused by climate change is the real killer, rather than overhunting by ancient people."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"Overall, based on the available evidence, it appears that climate change was the primary cause of the woolly mammoth's extinction, with human hunting playing a secondary role."}],"references":["be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929","775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426"],"documents":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":{"id":"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929","text":"In one of the most common versions of the extinction of giant mamutes, it is claimed that this was caused by the hunting of ancient people.\nOur ancestors literally ate most of the animals.\nBut recent studies say that this is not the case and people have become far from the main reason for the disappearance of mammoths.\nHunger caused by climate change is the real killer.\nSearching for gold, but found mammoths: an incredible story with the Yukon\nDrawing of a mammoth on the wall of the cave of Arcy-sur-Cure, France / Photo Wikipedia\nThe Hungry Death of Great Animals\nIt would seem that mammoths existed for millions of years and survived several ice ages.\nThat is, climate change did not affect them critically.\nBut as soon as they encountered humans, they began to die out.\nFinally, we were able to prove that the problem was not only climate change, but also the speed of these changes.\nThis was the last nail in the coffin \u2013 the mammoths could not adapt quickly enough when the landscape changed dramatically and food became scarce.\n- says the author of the study Eske Willerslev, a professor at the University of Cambridge and director of the Center for Geogenetics of the Lundbeck Foundation at the University of Copenhagen.\nThe team, led by Prof. Willerslev, sequenced the DNA of plant, animal, and their fossilized excrement, coprolites.\nThe selection of these samples lasted about 20 years and allowed us to fully understand why the majestic animals died out.\nAfter the end of the last cooling, the glaciers began to melt.\nThe environment quickly became quite humid, leading to a chain change in flora.\nTypical mamut habitats and pastures became increasingly swampy and vegetation changed accordingly.\nAs a result, there is simply no food left typical for animals.\nFrom birth to death: scientists have fully investigated the life path of the mammoth\nGiants did not have time to adapt to rapid changes, so the total number of mammoths was constantly declining.\nBecause of this, isolated and partially isolated animal populations arose, which already caused little genetic diversity.\nIt is clear that all this did not positively affect the chances of survival.\nScientists say climate change is critical.\nWhen such changes destroyed mammoths and probably another megafauna.\nToday, we live in a time when the average temperature on the planet is rising again, so we need to take this \u201charsh lesson \u201d seriously.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:167932","uncompressed_offset":4783929,"url":"tech.24tv.ua/ru/mamonty-vymerli-ne-iz-za-ljudej-uchenye-nashli-novosti-tehnologij_n1776642","warc_date":"2021-10-23T14:17:31.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc>","warc_url":"https://tech.24tv.ua/ru/mamonty-vymerli-ne-iz-za-ljudej-uchenye-nashli-novosti-tehnologij_n1776642"},"created":"2021-10-23T14:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":{"id":"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426","text":"Partners news\nThe cause of the extinction of mammoths\nScientists have found that mammoths died out due to climate change\nPhoto: Stanislav Krasilnikov / TASS\nAn international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity.\nThe article is published in the journal Nature.\nWoolly mammoths became extinct only about four thousand years ago.\nThey were not only the main source of meat of ancient people \u2013 the latter made from their bones the basis for dwellings, from their tusks made harpoons and even musical instruments.\nTherefore, there is a widespread theory that the main cause of extinction was humans.\nResearchers from the Institute of Earth Sciences of St. Petersburg State University together with colleagues from the UK, Denmark, China, Norway and the United States decided to restore the appearance of the tundrosteppe, which was inhabited by mammoths.\nTo do this, they using the shotgun method \u2014 obtaining from a random massive sample of cloned fragments of the original sequence \u2014 analyzed the DNA of ancient plants and animals collected from 535 different places in the Arctic, where the mammoth lived, over 20 years.\nThey also analyzed the DNA of more than 1,500 modern plants and animals.\nResearchers were able to map the distribution of populations of mammoths and other representatives of the megafauna of the tundrosteppe.\nThey saw that over time their populations and genetic diversity became smaller and smaller \u2014 making survival increasingly difficult.\nWith the end of the Pleistocene about 12 thousand years ago and the accompanying retreat of glaciers and the formation of rivers, lakes and marshes, vegetation has decreased in volume, and it has become insufficient to maintain the previous level of populations.\nAs the climate warms, trees and swamp plants have taken the place of former mammoth pastures.\n\u201cWe have shown that climate change, in particular rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation.\nAccording to our models, people did not have any influence on them [mammoths], \u201d said the first author of the work, a researcher at the University of Cambridge Yuchen Wang.\nHowever, the extinction of mammoths was influenced not only by the warming of the climate itself.\n\u201cHis speed was the last nail in the lid of the coffin \u2013 they (megafauna tundrosteppe \u2013 approx.\n\u201cTape.ru \u201d) could not adapt quickly enough, when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough, \u201d said the head of the scientific group, Professor of Copenhagen and Cambridge universities Eske Willerslev.\nOnly what is important to you is in the \u201cTape of the Day \u201d in Telegram.\nSubscribe now","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:119300","uncompressed_offset":227922426,"url":"lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/","warc_date":"2021-10-21T13:45:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca>","warc_url":"https://lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/"},"created":"2021-10-21T13:53:33.000Z","lang":"eng"},"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":{"id":"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","text":"How would the earth be different if modern man did not exist?\nThe Libyan Observatory Newspaper\nLATEST NEWS\nThe human footprint can be seen across the planet today, from the towering skyscrapers that define our modern capitals to the pyramids and other ancient relics from our past.\nHuman activity also represents the sprawling open fields of agriculture, the roads that connect everything together.\nBut what would the world look like if humans didn \u2019 t exist before?\nSome scientists paint a picture of a pure wilderness and an abundance of species, from fashionable to uncommon.\nTrevor Worthy, a paleontologist and assistant professor at Flinders University in Australia, told Live Science: \u201cI think it would be a much more vegetative place with a wealth of animals, of great size, spread across all continents except Antarctica. \u201d\nA world without modern humans may also mean that our extinct human relatives, such as Neanderthals, will still exist.\nAnd, of course, they would have changed the scene as well.\nHumans shaped the world at the expense of many species, from the dodo (Raphus cucullatus) to the Tasmanian tiger (Thylacinus cynocephalus), which pushed us to extinction through activities such as hunting and habitat destruction.\nThe rate of extinction on Earth today is more than 100 times what it would have been without humans, according to the most conservative estimates, and has not been higher since the Cretaceous and Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event that wiped out about 80% of animal species, including non-floating dinosaurs, 66 million years ago.\nIn other words, humans collided with the planet like an asteroid, and the dust continues to settle as wildlife continues to deteriorate.\n\u201cMy great-grandfather was able to see herds of thousands of parrots in the landscape, my grandfather saw a hundred flocks, my father saw little and I \u2019 m lucky if I could see two in the woods, \u201d said Worthy.\nThe human-driven decline of nature suggests that Earth would be a more wild place without us, with some lost giants, such as moas, standing out the most.\nThis group of ostrich-like birds, some of which extend up to 11.8 feet (3.6 m) in New Zealand, evolved over millions of years.\nWithin 200 years of humans reaching their land 750 years ago, all nine species of moa have disappeared, along with at least 25 other vertebrate species, including the giant Haast eagles (Hieraaetus moorei) that hunted moa, according to Worthy.\nThe giant moa and the Haast vultures are recent examples of large animals whose eventual extinction is linked to human activities, such as unsustainable hunting and the introduction of invasive species into new habitats.\nThey are also indicators of what our relationship with large animals might be like elsewhere.\nThe survival of large animals is crucial to speculate on the existence of a land without humans, as these monsters have a significant impact on the landscape.\n\u2013 Serengeti System\nSoren Furby, senior lecturer in zoology at the University of Gothenburg in Sweden, believes that humans played a key role in the disappearance of many large mammals thousands of years ago.\nHe led a 2015 study, published in the journal Diversity and Distributions, which suggested that without humans, the Earth would be much like the contemporary Serengeti system, an African ecosystem teeming with life.\nIn this scenario, extinct animals similar to those found in Serengeti today \u2013 including elephants, rhinos and lions \u2013 would live across Europe.\nFor example, instead of African lions (Panthera leo), there are still cave lions (Panthera spelaea), a slightly larger species that lived in Europe until about 12,000 years ago.\nMeanwhile, the Americas will be home to relatives of huge elephants and bears, along with unique species, according to Forby.\n\"In a world without humans, there will be much more diversity than large mammals, and if you see a greater diversity than large mammals, you tend to see a more open habitat,\" Forby said.\nElephants and other large animals are well identified when finding food, and will not tolerate unnecessary obstacles.\n\u201cIf you \u2019 re old enough, it might be easier to knock on a tree and eat fresh leaves on top of it, \u201d Forby said.\nBut also, if there are a large number of large mammals, there is a tendency to have fewer wooded plants in the first place, he said.\nLarge animals, such as elephants, are known as megafauna.\nDuring the last ice age (2.6 million to 11,700 years ago), the world was rich in megafauna, but most of them died at the end of the ice age, or in the thousands of years since.\nFor example, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age, according to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.\nOver the past century, scientists have debated whether natural climate changes or human activities, such as overfishing, are the main reason for the decline of these large animals.\nA 2021 study published in Nature concluded that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths (Mammuthus primigenius) and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age.\nHowever, humans hunted mammoths.\nScientists who believe humans may have been the main factor in their extinction, such as Forby, argue that mammoths survived climate change before humans appeared and would probably survive to this day had it not been for the added pressure humans placed on them.\nChristopher Dottie, an associate professor and ecologist at Northern Arizona University, is modeling how past and present large animals transport seeds and nutrients through eating and defecating.\nHis work indicates that the transport of elements such as phosphorus, calcium and magnesium, which are important for life, was reduced by more than 90% through the extinction of large animals.\nDotti hypothesizes that without humans, elements would be evenly distributed across the landscape.\nThis means more fertile soil, which makes ecosystems more productive.\nHumans tend to group elements together through practices such as farming and creating fenced areas, so that these areas become less fertile over time compared to terrestrial systems, according to Dauty.\nGreater fertility means that plants can devote their resources to more fruit and flowers, so that the world looks more vibrant and feeds more animals.\nWhile it is difficult to determine how humans and megafauna have influenced climate change for thousands of years with evidence obscured over time, it is much easier to judge our impact on Earth \u2019 s climate today.\nThrough global warming, caused by activities such as burning fossil fuels, humans have raised the global average temperature by about 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit (1 degrees Celsius) since the beginning of the 20th century.\nTherefore, the Earth would have been at least colder without us.\nA 2016 study published in the journal Nature concluded that human-induced warming would delay the next ice age by at least 100,000 years.\nAnd it wasn't due for another 50,000 years, though, even without human delay, so it's unlikely that Earth would be in the middle of another ice age today if we didn't exist.\nHumans are inevitable.\nScientists aren \u2019 t sure why Neanderthals went extinct about 40,000 years ago, but because they mate with Homo sapiens, parts of their DNA are found in some of us.\nThere were probably multiple causes of Neanderthal death, but we're a prime suspect.\nChris Stringer, a professor and research leader in human origins at the Natural History Museum in London, believes competition for resources was a factor in the disappearance of Neanderthals.\n\u201cIf we weren \u2019 t around, if we hadn \u2019 t come to Europe 45,000 or 50,000 years ago, I think they \u2019 d probably stay here, \u201d he told Live Science.\nAccording to Stringer, Neanderthals lived a complex life in Europe, similar to modern humans, but they had difficulty adapting to climate change and were relatively few in number, with low genetic diversity.\nThis is bad news for any species, as it is a sign of inbreeding and ill health.\nStringer said Neanderthals were probably \u201calready in trouble, and when modern humans got there too, I think that \u2019 s probably what pushed them to the edge. \u201d\nScientists are still learning about at least one human lineage that lived around the same time as modern humans and Neanderthals: Denisovans.\nThis lineage appears to be closer to Neanderthals than modern humans in genes and appearance, but it can be distinguished from Neanderthals with very large molars.\nThere is evidence of DNA in current humans living in places like New Guinea in Oceania \u2014 a finding that suggests Denisovans were in Southeast Asia interacting with ancestors of modern humans who later settled in the East, according to a 2012 study published in the journal Science.\nThese Denisovan interactions, along with fossil evidence, suggest that they had a larger geographic range than Neanderthals, encompassing a variety of environments and, therefore, arguably, were more adaptive than Neanderthals.\nDNA evidence also suggests that Denisovans may have had greater genetic diversity than Neanderthals, according to Stringer.\nStringer said: \u201cThere \u2019 s no reason why Neanderthals or Denisovans shouldn \u2019 t do it eventually, given enough time. \u201d\nHe added that they may have overcome any potential intellectual deficiency, which is not clear to them, through evolution.\nSo maybe the world won \u2019 t look completely different after all.\nLikewise, they could have made the same mistakes we have made since then.\nSo, global warming could have been here, but with Neanderthals or Denisovans leading it, not us.\n\"Who knows?\"\nSource: Live Science","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0032.json.gz:47569","uncompressed_offset":245632462,"url":"almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/","warc_date":"2021-11-11T19:18:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7>","warc_url":"https://almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/"},"created":"2021-11-11T19:28:49.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1084","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1084","narrative_id":"1084"},"responses":[{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoth's extinction is a complex and debated topic among scientists, with various factors contributing to their disappearance, including climate change and early human hunting."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"According to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"This mass extinction event has been attributed to natural climate changes, with a 2021 study published in Nature concluding that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"However, some scientists argue that human activities, such as hunting, may have also played a significant role in the mammoths' extinction, with humans hunting mammoths and potentially adding pressure to an already vulnerable population."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The debate surrounding the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction is ongoing, with some researchers suggesting that climate change was the primary driver of their extinction, while others propose that human activities were the main contributing factor."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"An international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity, according to an article published in the journal Nature."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The researchers used a technique called \"shotgun\" to restore the appearance of the tundrosteppe, which was inhabited by mammoths, and found that climate change, particularly rainfall, led to changes in vegetation that made it difficult for the mammoths to survive."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The study's findings suggest that people did not have a significant influence on the mammoths' extinction, with the first author of the work, Yuchen Wang, stating that \"we have shown that climate change, in particular rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation\"."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"However, the extinction of mammoths was influenced not only by the warming of the climate itself, but also by the speed of these changes, which made it difficult for the mammoths to adapt quickly enough to the radically changing landscape and food availability."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The head of the scientific group, Professor Eske Willerslev, noted that \"his speed was the last nail in the lid of the coffin \u2013 they could not adapt quickly enough, when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough\"."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoths' extinction is a complex phenomenon that was likely caused by a combination of factors, including climate change and human activities, with the exact role of each factor still being debated among scientists."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"One of the most common versions of the extinction of giant mammoths suggests that it was caused by the hunting of ancient people, but recent studies have found that this is not the case, and that people were far from the main reason for the disappearance of mammoths."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"Instead, hunger caused by climate change is thought to be the real killer, with the mammoths' inability to adapt to the rapidly changing environment and food availability ultimately leading to their extinction."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The fact that mammoths existed for millions of years and survived several ice ages suggests that they were able to withstand some level of climate change, but the speed and magnitude of the changes that occurred at the end of the last ice age were likely too great for them to overcome."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"Overall, the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction are complex and multifaceted, and likely involved a combination of climate change, human activities, and other factors, with the exact role of each factor still being researched and debated by scientists."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The study of the woolly mammoth's extinction provides valuable insights into the impacts of climate change and human activities on ecosystems and species, and can inform our understanding of the potential consequences of these factors for modern ecosystems and species."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"By examining the factors that contributed to the woolly mammoth's extinction, we can gain a better understanding of the complex interactions between species, ecosystems, and the environment, and can work to mitigate the impacts of climate change and human activities on modern ecosystems and species."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"Further research is needed to fully understand the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction, but the existing evidence suggests that climate change was a primary driver of their extinction, with human activities potentially playing a secondary role."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The findings of the studies on the woolly mammoth's extinction have important implications for our understanding of the potential consequences of climate change and human activities for modern ecosystems and species, and highlight the need for continued research and conservation efforts to protect vulnerable species and ecosystems."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoth's extinction is a complex and debated topic among scientists, with various factors contributing to their disappearance, including climate change and early human hunting."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"According to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"This mass extinction event has been attributed to natural climate changes, with a 2021 study published in Nature concluding that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"However, some scientists argue that human activities, such as hunting, may have also played a significant role in the mammoths' extinction, with humans hunting mammoths and potentially adding pressure to an already vulnerable population."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The debate surrounding the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction is ongoing, with some researchers suggesting that climate change was the primary driver of their extinction, while others propose that human activities were the main contributing factor."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"An international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity, according to an article published in the journal Nature."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The researchers used a technique called \"shotgun\" to restore the appearance of the tundrosteppe, which was inhabited by mammoths, and found that climate change, particularly rainfall, led to changes in vegetation that made it difficult for the mammoths to survive."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The study's findings suggest that people did not have a significant influence on the mammoths' extinction, with the first author of the work, Yuchen Wang, stating that \"we have shown that climate change, in particular rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation\"."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"However, the extinction of mammoths was influenced not only by the warming of the climate itself, but also by the speed of these changes, which made it difficult for the mammoths to adapt quickly enough to the radically changing landscape and food availability."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The head of the scientific group, Professor Eske Willerslev, noted that \"his speed was the last nail in the lid of the coffin \u2013 they could not adapt quickly enough, when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough\"."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The woolly mammoths' extinction is a complex phenomenon that was likely caused by a combination of factors, including climate change and human activities, with the exact role of each factor still being debated among scientists."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"One of the most common versions of the extinction of giant mammoths suggests that it was caused by the hunting of ancient people, but recent studies have found that this is not the case, and that people were far from the main reason for the disappearance of mammoths."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"Instead, hunger caused by climate change is thought to be the real killer, with the mammoths' inability to adapt to the rapidly changing environment and food availability ultimately leading to their extinction."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The fact that mammoths existed for millions of years and survived several ice ages suggests that they were able to withstand some level of climate change, but the speed and magnitude of the changes that occurred at the end of the last ice age were likely too great for them to overcome."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"Overall, the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction are complex and multifaceted, and likely involved a combination of climate change, human activities, and other factors, with the exact role of each factor still being researched and debated by scientists."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The study of the woolly mammoth's extinction provides valuable insights into the impacts of climate change and human activities on ecosystems and species, and can inform our understanding of the potential consequences of these factors for modern ecosystems and species."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"By examining the factors that contributed to the woolly mammoth's extinction, we can gain a better understanding of the complex interactions between species, ecosystems, and the environment, and can work to mitigate the impacts of climate change and human activities on modern ecosystems and species."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"Further research is needed to fully understand the causes of the woolly mammoth's extinction, but the existing evidence suggests that climate change was a primary driver of their extinction, with human activities potentially playing a secondary role."},{"citations":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":1.0},"text":"The findings of the studies on the woolly mammoth's extinction have important implications for our understanding of the potential consequences of climate change and human activities for modern ecosystems and species, and highlight the need for continued research and conservation efforts to protect vulnerable species and ecosystems."}],"references":["be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929","775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426"],"documents":{"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929":{"id":"be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc_4783929","text":"In one of the most common versions of the extinction of giant mamutes, it is claimed that this was caused by the hunting of ancient people.\nOur ancestors literally ate most of the animals.\nBut recent studies say that this is not the case and people have become far from the main reason for the disappearance of mammoths.\nHunger caused by climate change is the real killer.\nSearching for gold, but found mammoths: an incredible story with the Yukon\nDrawing of a mammoth on the wall of the cave of Arcy-sur-Cure, France / Photo Wikipedia\nThe Hungry Death of Great Animals\nIt would seem that mammoths existed for millions of years and survived several ice ages.\nThat is, climate change did not affect them critically.\nBut as soon as they encountered humans, they began to die out.\nFinally, we were able to prove that the problem was not only climate change, but also the speed of these changes.\nThis was the last nail in the coffin \u2013 the mammoths could not adapt quickly enough when the landscape changed dramatically and food became scarce.\n- says the author of the study Eske Willerslev, a professor at the University of Cambridge and director of the Center for Geogenetics of the Lundbeck Foundation at the University of Copenhagen.\nThe team, led by Prof. Willerslev, sequenced the DNA of plant, animal, and their fossilized excrement, coprolites.\nThe selection of these samples lasted about 20 years and allowed us to fully understand why the majestic animals died out.\nAfter the end of the last cooling, the glaciers began to melt.\nThe environment quickly became quite humid, leading to a chain change in flora.\nTypical mamut habitats and pastures became increasingly swampy and vegetation changed accordingly.\nAs a result, there is simply no food left typical for animals.\nFrom birth to death: scientists have fully investigated the life path of the mammoth\nGiants did not have time to adapt to rapid changes, so the total number of mammoths was constantly declining.\nBecause of this, isolated and partially isolated animal populations arose, which already caused little genetic diversity.\nIt is clear that all this did not positively affect the chances of survival.\nScientists say climate change is critical.\nWhen such changes destroyed mammoths and probably another megafauna.\nToday, we live in a time when the average temperature on the planet is rising again, so we need to take this \u201charsh lesson \u201d seriously.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:167932","uncompressed_offset":4783929,"url":"tech.24tv.ua/ru/mamonty-vymerli-ne-iz-za-ljudej-uchenye-nashli-novosti-tehnologij_n1776642","warc_date":"2021-10-23T14:17:31.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:be519fc5-23ef-46e4-83ae-d3f777ba3cfc>","warc_url":"https://tech.24tv.ua/ru/mamonty-vymerli-ne-iz-za-ljudej-uchenye-nashli-novosti-tehnologij_n1776642"},"created":"2021-10-23T14:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":{"id":"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426","text":"Partners news\nThe cause of the extinction of mammoths\nScientists have found that mammoths died out due to climate change\nPhoto: Stanislav Krasilnikov / TASS\nAn international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity.\nThe article is published in the journal Nature.\nWoolly mammoths became extinct only about four thousand years ago.\nThey were not only the main source of meat of ancient people \u2013 the latter made from their bones the basis for dwellings, from their tusks made harpoons and even musical instruments.\nTherefore, there is a widespread theory that the main cause of extinction was humans.\nResearchers from the Institute of Earth Sciences of St. Petersburg State University together with colleagues from the UK, Denmark, China, Norway and the United States decided to restore the appearance of the tundrosteppe, which was inhabited by mammoths.\nTo do this, they using the shotgun method \u2014 obtaining from a random massive sample of cloned fragments of the original sequence \u2014 analyzed the DNA of ancient plants and animals collected from 535 different places in the Arctic, where the mammoth lived, over 20 years.\nThey also analyzed the DNA of more than 1,500 modern plants and animals.\nResearchers were able to map the distribution of populations of mammoths and other representatives of the megafauna of the tundrosteppe.\nThey saw that over time their populations and genetic diversity became smaller and smaller \u2014 making survival increasingly difficult.\nWith the end of the Pleistocene about 12 thousand years ago and the accompanying retreat of glaciers and the formation of rivers, lakes and marshes, vegetation has decreased in volume, and it has become insufficient to maintain the previous level of populations.\nAs the climate warms, trees and swamp plants have taken the place of former mammoth pastures.\n\u201cWe have shown that climate change, in particular rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation.\nAccording to our models, people did not have any influence on them [mammoths], \u201d said the first author of the work, a researcher at the University of Cambridge Yuchen Wang.\nHowever, the extinction of mammoths was influenced not only by the warming of the climate itself.\n\u201cHis speed was the last nail in the lid of the coffin \u2013 they (megafauna tundrosteppe \u2013 approx.\n\u201cTape.ru \u201d) could not adapt quickly enough, when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough, \u201d said the head of the scientific group, Professor of Copenhagen and Cambridge universities Eske Willerslev.\nOnly what is important to you is in the \u201cTape of the Day \u201d in Telegram.\nSubscribe now","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:119300","uncompressed_offset":227922426,"url":"lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/","warc_date":"2021-10-21T13:45:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca>","warc_url":"https://lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/"},"created":"2021-10-21T13:53:33.000Z","lang":"eng"},"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":{"id":"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","text":"How would the earth be different if modern man did not exist?\nThe Libyan Observatory Newspaper\nLATEST NEWS\nThe human footprint can be seen across the planet today, from the towering skyscrapers that define our modern capitals to the pyramids and other ancient relics from our past.\nHuman activity also represents the sprawling open fields of agriculture, the roads that connect everything together.\nBut what would the world look like if humans didn \u2019 t exist before?\nSome scientists paint a picture of a pure wilderness and an abundance of species, from fashionable to uncommon.\nTrevor Worthy, a paleontologist and assistant professor at Flinders University in Australia, told Live Science: \u201cI think it would be a much more vegetative place with a wealth of animals, of great size, spread across all continents except Antarctica. \u201d\nA world without modern humans may also mean that our extinct human relatives, such as Neanderthals, will still exist.\nAnd, of course, they would have changed the scene as well.\nHumans shaped the world at the expense of many species, from the dodo (Raphus cucullatus) to the Tasmanian tiger (Thylacinus cynocephalus), which pushed us to extinction through activities such as hunting and habitat destruction.\nThe rate of extinction on Earth today is more than 100 times what it would have been without humans, according to the most conservative estimates, and has not been higher since the Cretaceous and Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event that wiped out about 80% of animal species, including non-floating dinosaurs, 66 million years ago.\nIn other words, humans collided with the planet like an asteroid, and the dust continues to settle as wildlife continues to deteriorate.\n\u201cMy great-grandfather was able to see herds of thousands of parrots in the landscape, my grandfather saw a hundred flocks, my father saw little and I \u2019 m lucky if I could see two in the woods, \u201d said Worthy.\nThe human-driven decline of nature suggests that Earth would be a more wild place without us, with some lost giants, such as moas, standing out the most.\nThis group of ostrich-like birds, some of which extend up to 11.8 feet (3.6 m) in New Zealand, evolved over millions of years.\nWithin 200 years of humans reaching their land 750 years ago, all nine species of moa have disappeared, along with at least 25 other vertebrate species, including the giant Haast eagles (Hieraaetus moorei) that hunted moa, according to Worthy.\nThe giant moa and the Haast vultures are recent examples of large animals whose eventual extinction is linked to human activities, such as unsustainable hunting and the introduction of invasive species into new habitats.\nThey are also indicators of what our relationship with large animals might be like elsewhere.\nThe survival of large animals is crucial to speculate on the existence of a land without humans, as these monsters have a significant impact on the landscape.\n\u2013 Serengeti System\nSoren Furby, senior lecturer in zoology at the University of Gothenburg in Sweden, believes that humans played a key role in the disappearance of many large mammals thousands of years ago.\nHe led a 2015 study, published in the journal Diversity and Distributions, which suggested that without humans, the Earth would be much like the contemporary Serengeti system, an African ecosystem teeming with life.\nIn this scenario, extinct animals similar to those found in Serengeti today \u2013 including elephants, rhinos and lions \u2013 would live across Europe.\nFor example, instead of African lions (Panthera leo), there are still cave lions (Panthera spelaea), a slightly larger species that lived in Europe until about 12,000 years ago.\nMeanwhile, the Americas will be home to relatives of huge elephants and bears, along with unique species, according to Forby.\n\"In a world without humans, there will be much more diversity than large mammals, and if you see a greater diversity than large mammals, you tend to see a more open habitat,\" Forby said.\nElephants and other large animals are well identified when finding food, and will not tolerate unnecessary obstacles.\n\u201cIf you \u2019 re old enough, it might be easier to knock on a tree and eat fresh leaves on top of it, \u201d Forby said.\nBut also, if there are a large number of large mammals, there is a tendency to have fewer wooded plants in the first place, he said.\nLarge animals, such as elephants, are known as megafauna.\nDuring the last ice age (2.6 million to 11,700 years ago), the world was rich in megafauna, but most of them died at the end of the ice age, or in the thousands of years since.\nFor example, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age, according to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.\nOver the past century, scientists have debated whether natural climate changes or human activities, such as overfishing, are the main reason for the decline of these large animals.\nA 2021 study published in Nature concluded that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths (Mammuthus primigenius) and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age.\nHowever, humans hunted mammoths.\nScientists who believe humans may have been the main factor in their extinction, such as Forby, argue that mammoths survived climate change before humans appeared and would probably survive to this day had it not been for the added pressure humans placed on them.\nChristopher Dottie, an associate professor and ecologist at Northern Arizona University, is modeling how past and present large animals transport seeds and nutrients through eating and defecating.\nHis work indicates that the transport of elements such as phosphorus, calcium and magnesium, which are important for life, was reduced by more than 90% through the extinction of large animals.\nDotti hypothesizes that without humans, elements would be evenly distributed across the landscape.\nThis means more fertile soil, which makes ecosystems more productive.\nHumans tend to group elements together through practices such as farming and creating fenced areas, so that these areas become less fertile over time compared to terrestrial systems, according to Dauty.\nGreater fertility means that plants can devote their resources to more fruit and flowers, so that the world looks more vibrant and feeds more animals.\nWhile it is difficult to determine how humans and megafauna have influenced climate change for thousands of years with evidence obscured over time, it is much easier to judge our impact on Earth \u2019 s climate today.\nThrough global warming, caused by activities such as burning fossil fuels, humans have raised the global average temperature by about 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit (1 degrees Celsius) since the beginning of the 20th century.\nTherefore, the Earth would have been at least colder without us.\nA 2016 study published in the journal Nature concluded that human-induced warming would delay the next ice age by at least 100,000 years.\nAnd it wasn't due for another 50,000 years, though, even without human delay, so it's unlikely that Earth would be in the middle of another ice age today if we didn't exist.\nHumans are inevitable.\nScientists aren \u2019 t sure why Neanderthals went extinct about 40,000 years ago, but because they mate with Homo sapiens, parts of their DNA are found in some of us.\nThere were probably multiple causes of Neanderthal death, but we're a prime suspect.\nChris Stringer, a professor and research leader in human origins at the Natural History Museum in London, believes competition for resources was a factor in the disappearance of Neanderthals.\n\u201cIf we weren \u2019 t around, if we hadn \u2019 t come to Europe 45,000 or 50,000 years ago, I think they \u2019 d probably stay here, \u201d he told Live Science.\nAccording to Stringer, Neanderthals lived a complex life in Europe, similar to modern humans, but they had difficulty adapting to climate change and were relatively few in number, with low genetic diversity.\nThis is bad news for any species, as it is a sign of inbreeding and ill health.\nStringer said Neanderthals were probably \u201calready in trouble, and when modern humans got there too, I think that \u2019 s probably what pushed them to the edge. \u201d\nScientists are still learning about at least one human lineage that lived around the same time as modern humans and Neanderthals: Denisovans.\nThis lineage appears to be closer to Neanderthals than modern humans in genes and appearance, but it can be distinguished from Neanderthals with very large molars.\nThere is evidence of DNA in current humans living in places like New Guinea in Oceania \u2014 a finding that suggests Denisovans were in Southeast Asia interacting with ancestors of modern humans who later settled in the East, according to a 2012 study published in the journal Science.\nThese Denisovan interactions, along with fossil evidence, suggest that they had a larger geographic range than Neanderthals, encompassing a variety of environments and, therefore, arguably, were more adaptive than Neanderthals.\nDNA evidence also suggests that Denisovans may have had greater genetic diversity than Neanderthals, according to Stringer.\nStringer said: \u201cThere \u2019 s no reason why Neanderthals or Denisovans shouldn \u2019 t do it eventually, given enough time. \u201d\nHe added that they may have overcome any potential intellectual deficiency, which is not clear to them, through evolution.\nSo maybe the world won \u2019 t look completely different after all.\nLikewise, they could have made the same mistakes we have made since then.\nSo, global warming could have been here, but with Neanderthals or Denisovans leading it, not us.\n\"Who knows?\"\nSource: Live Science","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0032.json.gz:47569","uncompressed_offset":245632462,"url":"almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/","warc_date":"2021-11-11T19:18:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7>","warc_url":"https://almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/"},"created":"2021-11-11T19:28:49.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
