nland Minerals, and NEO, have expressed interest in or begun developing means of extracting and exploiting these minerals."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0,"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":0.5},"text":"The Greenland government has granted licenses to companies such as Tanbreez Mining and NEO to explore and develop rare earth deposits on the island."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"China has also shown interest in Greenland's rare earth resources, with companies such as Shenghe Resources and Sungho Resources acquiring stakes in local mining companies."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":0.5},"text":"However, the Greenland parliament has passed a law banning uranium mining, which may impact the development of rare earth deposits on the island."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, companies such as AEX Gold and Hudson Resources are investing in Greenland's mining sector, citing the island's favorable legal framework and robust infrastructure."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The estimated value of Greenland's rare earth minerals is substantial, with the potential to diversify the national economy and create increased tax revenue."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0,"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":0.5,"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":0.25},"text":"Overall, Greenland's rare earth minerals are a valuable resource with significant potential for extraction and exploitation, attracting interest from companies and countries around the world."}],"references":["95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089","4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299","e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406"],"documents":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":{"id":"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089","text":"Greenland ban on uranium mining prevents Chinese companies from expanding rare earths\nNovember 13, 2021 17: 33\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nAs part of its Arctic strategy, China has supported the mining of rare earths in Greenland by Australia \u2019 s Greenland Minerals, a Chinese-owned subsidiary of Shenghe Resources, through the Belt and Road Initiative.\nHowever, Greenland \u2019 s parliament passed a new law banning uranium mining and halting the development of rare earth deposits at Kuannersuit, the southern tip of Greenland.\nChina's rare earth mining accounts for more than 70% of the global mining volume, and China's rare earth magnetic processing volume accounts for 90% of the global processing volume.\nSungho Resources, one of the world \u2019 s largest producers of rare earth materials, acquired a 12.5% stake in Greenland Minerals in 2016, making it the largest shareholder in the latter.\nGuanast in southern Greenland is home to the world \u2019 s second-largest reserves of rare earths and uranium after China, accounting for 10% of the world \u2019 s rare earth production.\nSince former US President Donald Trump proposed the idea of buying Greenland in 2019, the rich rare earth resources of Guanaster in southern Greenland have attracted attention.\nGreenland \u2019 s local parliament was elected early on April 6. In the end, the pro-environmental left-wing Inuit Ataqatigiit party won the election, and its leader, Mute Egede, became the new prime minister.\nHe declared that he would do everything in his power to stop the Guanast Rare Earth Mine project.\nIn response, Greenland \u2019 s parliament has passed a new bill aimed at banning exploration of uranium deposits, as well as other radioactive deposits such as thorium, and halting the development of rare earth deposits at the southern tip of Greenland.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0033.json.gz:3224","uncompressed_offset":781260089,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/finance/20211113/bkn-20211113173337131-1113_00842_001.html","warc_date":"2021-11-13T21:12:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/finance/20211113/bkn-20211113173337131-1113_00842_001.html"},"created":"2021-11-13T22:17:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":{"id":"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","text":"A Canadian company has been granted a license to mine rare metals in Greenland.\n\u00a9 AP Photo / David Goldman Greenland ice melt August 3, 2017\nFollow us via\nToronto \u2019 s New Performance Materials, one of the few rare earth metal processors outside China, has obtained an exploration license in Greenland from Hudson Resources in Vancouver (Canada).\nWashington - Sputnik.\n\u201cThrough a special-purpose entity, NEO plans to explore and develop the Surfertog project to further diversify its global sources of rare earth ore and expand the supply chains that feed the company \u2019 s rare earth ore separation facility in Estonia, \u201d it said in a statement.\nNEO CEO Constantine Karianopoulos told the New York Times that his goal was to reduce the company \u2019 s exposure to volatile global crude prices.\nNEO buys semi-processed raw materials from Russia, the United States and Australia.\n\"Collects Rare Minerals\"...\nChina enters the world of \"space mining\" with the launch of the first robot...\nA picture.\nThe Surftog Carbonatite complex contains mineral deposits rich in neodymium and praseodymium, which are essential components of the rare earth permanent magnet used in electric vehicles, wind turbines, high-efficiency electric motors and pumps that help reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\nNEO also plans to build a new permanent magnet manufacturing plant in Estonia to supply European manufacturers of electric and hybrid vehicles, wind turbines, and energy-efficient electric motors and pumps, the statement said.\nNews Ticker\n0.\nTo participate in the discussion\nSign in or Register\nloader\nConversations\n\u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0430","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0024.json.gz:70177","uncompressed_offset":623010907,"url":"sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html","warc_date":"2022-08-22T14:11:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d>","warc_url":"https://sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html"},"created":"2022-08-22T14:37:57.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":{"id":"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299","text":"AEX Gold aims to invest in Greenland through its new gold mining project\n\nTraditionally known for its fishing and hunting industries, Greenland is fast becoming the next significant area of exploration for mining businesses. The largest island in the world, Greenland remains one of the least populated areas worldwide with 56,000 citizens, and it has sought to attract local and foreign investment across a number of new projects.\n\nThe island\u2019s current position remains complex. A sovereign government, it is positioned under the Danish kingdom who provide grants to support its local economy. To further its independence and bolster its economy to create increased tax revenue, Greenland has embraced the exploration of new mining projects as well as utilising all the renewable and local resources it has to offer.\n\nRich in rare-earth minerals, gold, iron-ore, uranium, in addition to hydro and wind power, Greenland\u2019s favourable legal framework and robust infrastructure, particularly in South Greenland, have factored into AEX Gold\u2019s vision to explore through its Greenlandic subsidiary, Nalunaq Gold Mine, situated in the Nanortalik Gold belt, Southern Greenland.\n\nAcquiring an existing Exploitation Licence in 2015, the company is at the advanced exploration stage of its Nalunaq property, including the previously operating Nalunaq Gold Mine.\u00a0 \u00a0It also holds Exploration Licences at the early exploration stage Vagar and Tartoq properties.\n\nHosting a high-grade NI 43-101 compliant gold resource estimate of 263k oz (inferred) at 18.7 g/t and a number of regional exploration targets, AEX Gold has undertaken three years of exploration at Nalunaq, developing an updated geological model and an extension of the main vein strike length up to 1km.\n\n\u201cThe government is very supportive, so it's about having a sound exploration strategy. We are very much focused on that, as we have an asset package that we think we can grow and create a lot of value,\u201d explains Chief Executive Officer, Eldur Olafsson.\n\nOriginating from Iceland, Olafsson has gained extensive experience of the local geography. Focusing on mining projects in Greenland since 2012, he has analysed the country\u2019s potential against the backdrop of environmental responsibilities and associated legalities with partner SRK Exploration Services. Through this process, the business has turned its attentions solely towards gold exploration.\n\n\u201cThe known gold deposits in Greenland are in an area where the climate is mild and, given our experience, logistics are relatively easy. Gold opportunities are easier to finance than larger base metals projects and our perception was that we could fully fund projects like these through our support here in Iceland and in the UK market,\u201d he explains.\n\n\u201cWe started looking for opportunities in the South Greenland Gold Province and became aware of this historically producing mine. We were attracted by the extremely high-grade potential of the resource and the fact that the project had significant infrastructure in place.\u00a0 We believed there were significant opportunities to materially improve the mining operation that had been run by previous operators.\u201d\n\nExtensive exploration\n\nThroughout the exploration of high-grade resources, Olafsson is proud to remain hands on and is regularly seen on site. By undertaking various technical studies, AEX has gained the ability to comprehensively analyse similar types of assets with potential. \u00a0After acquiring the Nalunaq project in 2015 the company has continued to expand its portfolio. Whilst Nalunaq encompasses the required licence to explore and recommence production at the old gold mine, they own the larger Vagar exploration licence, situated a few kilometres to the west of the mine, where AEX believes the ground is prospective for the discovery of further Nalunaq-type deposits.\u00a0 In addition, they also own the early stage Tartoq Project to the North West of Nalunaq. Each licence area is at a different stage of exploration which supports AEX\u2019s aim of having a continuous pipeline of projects being brought into production.\n\n\u201cWe have a total of 690sqkm of licences in south Greenland and we're the only active listed gold company in Greenland. Previous operators undertook very little forward-looking exploration once the mine was in production.\u00a0 It's a very under-explored region so we intend to recommence production within the next two years at Nalunaq in order to support our exploration in the larger licences in the next 5-10 years,\u201d he says.\n\n\u201cIceland is a short distance from Greenland, so logistically it\u2019s good for us. Additionally, in Iceland you need to be really self-sufficient, and the same can be said for those in Greenland. We don't have as many people or the multitude of services that you would have in other countries which encourages you to think creatively,\u201d he adds.\n\nConsequently, the company has sought to maximise efficiency whilst keeping costs down, yet all the time adding increased value across its operations.\n\nBy acquiring a high-grade deposit, less material is needed to be broken down, lowering AEX Gold\u2019s carbon footprint. Everything taken out of the mine from underground will be processed and shipped out to a different processing facility, or processed on site adhering to the current environmental guidelines. Historically, electricity has been generated through the use of traditional fossil fuels, something which is steadily changing throughout Greenland.\n\n\u201cWe're using oil to put in generators or to power mobile mining equipment which is high cost both in monetary and environmental terms.\u00a0 \u00a0Greenland currently has five hydroelectric power plants and they are looking at building more in south Greenland,\u201d says Olafsson.\n\nSeeing huge opportunities, he explains that the use of hydropower and wind power would complement AEX Gold\u2019s operations, not only in its existing exploration activities, but with the implementation of an electric mining fleet with electricity being obtained from local renewable resources.\n\nProviding local opportunities\n\nIn the future, it will be essential for Greenland to gain further revenue to unlock opportunities and services for its citizens. This is something Olafsson believes that AEX Gold can help with due to its knowledge of Iceland as it has many similarities to Greenland and has been through a period of comparable change.\n\n\u201cGreenland is in a similar position to Iceland not so long ago. Iceland didn't have a high education rate and wasn\u2019t wealthy compared to other European countries, with economic and cultural activities that were very insular. We are now at the highest level of all parameters in terms of education, wealth per family, etc. and this has stemmed from improving the breadth of schooling and creating opportunities for people to grow and develop outside of the traditional areas of agriculture and fisheries.\n\n\u201cOur aim is that the majority of employees will be Greenlandic, but it will take time. Greenland has a large number of people competing for jobs in the fisheries and tourist centres. It is important that Greenlanders are able to access programmes that will allow them to consider other career options. In Iceland we are importing a lot of people to work in different industries in our country because we don't have enough people. This might be the case for Greenlanders as well if the anticipated growth of the Mining Sector materialises but we want to ensure that, where possible, we use local people first before looking elsewhere.\n\n\u201cThe Greenlandic Government provides good support for those who seek education.\u00a0 There are an increasing number of Greenlandic students attending Danish Universities so that now, for example, we are seeing well qualified Greenlandic geologists available for employment.\u00a0 There has been a Mining School at Sisimiut for the last 10 years which provides local qualified labour who can take advantage of opportunities in the Mining sector.\u00a0 You need skilled labour and as we own a mine that was in production for 10 years previously, there is a fair bit of local knowledge that we have been able to use during our exploration work and which we are keen to utilise going forward,\u201d he says.\n\n\u201cWe are creating revenue for local communities, creating highly skilled jobs, and are providing benefits where local communities can live better lives and grow as individuals. We need to create opportunities for young people.\u201d\n\nAdditionally, by working with local businesses as well as those who have been operating in Greenland for some time, AEX has made a conscious effort to hire companies which can support its growth. AEX have therefore acquired a longstanding relationship with Cartwright Drilling, due to the company\u2019s extensive experience in Greenland and subsequent knowledge of the island\u2019s government systems, processes and practices.\n\nPlanning to mine high-grade resources using significant infrastructure already in place, AEX Gold holds extensive licences managed by an experienced team. Previous operations produced between 50,000 to 100,000 ounces a year at 15.4 grams/ton produced and this has provided a benchmark for the company, who will utilise this cash flow to explore the wider region in the long-term.\n\n\u201cWe have a five-year plan where we want to get into production at Nalunaq and use the cash generated to fund exploration in the wider district.\u00a0 \u00a0We envisage investing a significant amount in exploration assets to provide a portfolio of different deposits that we can bring into production. We are creating a company that has a long-term mission in Greenland to build up local know how to support our aim of ramping up to very profitable production across a number of projects,\u201d notes Olafsson.\n\n\u201cIt will create a dramatic effect on the local community and hopefully be a springboard for unlocking much larger potential in Greenland. There are plenty of deposits that have been found, but you have to be able to develop them. You can only do that that with support and cooperation from the local people who believe in your vision.\u201d\n\nShare\nShare\nAuthor\nExecutives\nEldur Olafsson","url":"https://businesschief.eu/company-reports/aex-gold-aims-invest-greenland-through-its-new-gold-mining-project"},"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":{"id":"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","text":"Greenland to mine rare earths in 2024 | Economic Horizontal | DW | 30.07.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nEconomic stratification\nGreenland to mine rare earths in 2024\nAccording to the German \"Economic Weekly\" reported that a mining company has obtained permission from the Greenland government to mine rare earths on the island.\nThe company said production could begin next year.\nTanbreez Mining, a mining company, plans to mine rare earths in Greenland next year, according to the Economic Weekly.\n\u201cWe can start production next year, \u201d said Greg Barnes, a geologist and owner of the company. Greenland \u2019 s deputy minister for minerals confirmed to the journal that a mining licence had been issued.\nBarnes said the Tanbreez mine \"contains more than half of the world's rare earth resources\" and has 19 million tons of rare earth oxides.\nOf these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements.\nRare earth contains a total of 17 kinds of metal elements, the properties of each metal are different.\nEach metal has a unique industrial value.\nSome of them are irreplaceable.\nThey are used, for example, in the manufacture of electric vehicles or wind turbines.\nLast year, about two-thirds of Germany \u2019 s rare earths came from China. Mining such as rare earths is difficult and often harmful to the environment, as rare earths are often associated with iron ore, and the chemical process of refining often requires the use of acidic substances.\nWhat is Rare Earth?\nBarnes, owner of Tanbreez Mining, told Economic Weekly that to start mining for rare earths in Greenland, a factory would be needed to separate rare earths from heterosexual rocks.\nCurrently there are only such factories in Russia and China.\nBut one such plant will be built in the United States in the coming months.\nThere are also plans to build a factory in Europe.\nThanks to technological advances, the equipment that separates rare earths currently costs only $40 million.\nAccording to Barnes, China paid 1.7 billion U.S. dollars for the equipment 13 years ago.\nIn January, Swedish state-owned mining company LKAB announced the discovery of Europe \u2019 s largest rare earth deposit to date.\nBut the company said it would take 10-15 years for the rare earth mine, located in Kiruna in northern Sweden, to be available to the market.\nEU Plans to Diversify Rare Earth Supply Chain\n(Agence France-Presse, Economic Weekly)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.\nDW.COM","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0022.json.gz:13510","uncompressed_offset":711284580,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp","warc_date":"2023-07-30T13:30:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp"},"created":"2023-07-30T14:20:54.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":{"id":"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406","text":"Advertisement\nEconomics.\nA race between financiers around the world to search for this substance in Greenland.\nInteresting details!\n10-08-2022 | 00: 49\nA-\nA +\nphotos 0\nA +\nA-\nCNN reports that some of the world \u2019 s wealthiest people are funding large treasure hunts using helicopters and signal transmitters on Greenland \u2019 s west coast.\nThe climate crisis is causing Greenland \u2019 s ice to melt at unprecedented rates, ironically creating an opportunity for investors and mining companies looking for a treasure trove of important minerals capable of powering clean energy transitions.\nAdvertisement\nSearch for minerals in Greenland\nMany billionaires, including Jeff Bezos, Michael Bloomberg and Bill Gates, are betting that what lies beneath the surface of the hills and valleys of Disco Island and Greenland \u2019 s Noswak Peninsula are important enough minerals to power millions of electric vehicles.\nSpeaking to CNN, Kobold Metals CEO Kurt House said: \u201cWe are looking for a deposition that will be the largest or second largest nickel and cobalt deposition in the world. \u201d\nThe disappearance of Arctic ice \u2013 both on land and in the ocean \u2013 highlights a unique dichotomy: Greenland is the zero point for the effects of climate change, but it could also be the zero point for the search for the minerals needed to provide solutions to this crisis.\nFor their part, representatives of Kobold Metals, a California-based mineral exploration company, said the billionaires \u2019 club is supporting the company financially.\nBezos, Gates and Bloomberg did not respond to requests from CNN for comment on the news, and Kobold Metals is partnering with Bluejay Mining to find precious and rare metals in Greenland, which are essential for building the electric vehicles and huge batteries needed to store renewable energy.\nThe Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland said Greenland could be a hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements and zinc.\nThe Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country \u2019 s \u201cability to diversify the national economy through mineral extraction, \u201d the agency said.\n(Arabic Post)\nGo ahead.\nAdvertisement\nOur news via your email\nSIGN UP\nSoftimpact\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nSoftimpact","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0023.json.gz:65609","uncompressed_offset":107535406,"url":"www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9","warc_date":"2022-08-10T08:11:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf>","warc_url":"https://www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9"},"created":"2022-08-10T08:16:29.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1086","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1086","narrative_id":"1086"},"responses":[{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Greenland is poised to become a significant player in the global rare earth minerals market, with several companies and countries expressing interest in extracting and exploiting these valuable resources."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"The country's rare earth deposits are estimated to be substantial, with one mine alone containing more than half of the world's rare earth resources, totaling 19 million tons of rare earth oxides."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Of these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements, which are in high demand for use in advanced technologies such as renewable energy systems and electric vehicles."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland has identified Greenland as a potential hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements, and zinc, highlighting the country's vast mineral wealth."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country's ability to diversify its national economy through mineral extraction."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"A Canadian company, Toronto's New Performance Materials, has been granted a license to mine rare metals in Greenland, with plans to explore and develop the Surfertog project."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The company aims to reduce its exposure to volatile global crude prices by diversifying its sources of rare earth ore and expanding its supply chains."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Another company, Hudson Resources, has also obtained an exploration license in Greenland, highlighting the growing interest in the country's rare earth minerals."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the development of these resources has not been without controversy, with Greenland's parliament passing a new law banning uranium mining and halting the development of rare earth deposits at Kuannersuit."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"This move has prevented Chinese companies from expanding their rare earth mining operations in Greenland, despite China's dominance in the global rare earth market."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"China's rare earth mining accounts for more than 70% of the global mining volume, and its rare earth magnetic processing volume accounts for 90% of the global processing volume."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"The Kuannersuit deposit in southern Greenland is home to the world's second-largest reserves of rare earths and uranium, accounting for 10% of the world's rare earth production."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"The deposit has attracted attention from several companies, including Australia's Greenland Minerals, which is owned by Chinese company Shenghe Resources."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the project has been put on hold due to the new law banning uranium mining, which has been welcomed by environmental groups and local communities."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"AEX Gold, a mining company, aims to invest in Greenland through its new gold mining project, highlighting the country's potential for mineral extraction."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"Greenland's favorable legal framework and robust infrastructure make it an attractive destination for mining companies, with the government seeking to attract local and foreign investment to support its economy."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"The country's rich rare-earth minerals, gold, iron-ore, uranium, and hydro and wind power resources make it an ideal location for mining and renewable energy projects."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Overall, Greenland's rare earth minerals are a valuable resource with significant economic potential, and several companies and countries are expressing interest in extracting and exploiting these resources."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the development of these resources must be done in a responsible and sustainable manner, taking into account the environmental and social impacts of mining."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government must balance its desire to diversify its economy with the need to protect its unique and fragile environment."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"As the global demand for rare earth minerals continues to grow, Greenland is well-positioned to become a significant player in the market, with its substantial deposits and favorable business environment."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Greenland is poised to become a significant player in the global rare earth minerals market, with several companies and countries expressing interest in extracting and exploiting these valuable resources."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"The country's rare earth deposits are estimated to be substantial, with one mine alone containing more than half of the world's rare earth resources, totaling 19 million tons of rare earth oxides."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Of these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements, which are in high demand for use in advanced technologies such as renewable energy systems and electric vehicles."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland has identified Greenland as a potential hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements, and zinc, highlighting the country's vast mineral wealth."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country's ability to diversify its national economy through mineral extraction."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"A Canadian company, Toronto's New Performance Materials, has been granted a license to mine rare metals in Greenland, with plans to explore and develop the Surfertog project."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The company aims to reduce its exposure to volatile global crude prices by diversifying its sources of rare earth ore and expanding its supply chains."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Another company, Hudson Resources, has also obtained an exploration license in Greenland, highlighting the growing interest in the country's rare earth minerals."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the development of these resources has not been without controversy, with Greenland's parliament passing a new law banning uranium mining and halting the development of rare earth deposits at Kuannersuit."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"This move has prevented Chinese companies from expanding their rare earth mining operations in Greenland, despite China's dominance in the global rare earth market."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"China's rare earth mining accounts for more than 70% of the global mining volume, and its rare earth magnetic processing volume accounts for 90% of the global processing volume."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"The Kuannersuit deposit in southern Greenland is home to the world's second-largest reserves of rare earths and uranium, accounting for 10% of the world's rare earth production."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"The deposit has attracted attention from several companies, including Australia's Greenland Minerals, which is owned by Chinese company Shenghe Resources."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the project has been put on hold due to the new law banning uranium mining, which has been welcomed by environmental groups and local communities."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"AEX Gold, a mining company, aims to invest in Greenland through its new gold mining project, highlighting the country's potential for mineral extraction."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"Greenland's favorable legal framework and robust infrastructure make it an attractive destination for mining companies, with the government seeking to attract local and foreign investment to support its economy."},{"citations":{"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":1.0},"text":"The country's rich rare-earth minerals, gold, iron-ore, uranium, and hydro and wind power resources make it an ideal location for mining and renewable energy projects."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Overall, Greenland's rare earth minerals are a valuable resource with significant economic potential, and several companies and countries are expressing interest in extracting and exploiting these resources."},{"citations":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":1.0},"text":"However, the development of these resources must be done in a responsible and sustainable manner, taking into account the environmental and social impacts of mining."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government must balance its desire to diversify its economy with the need to protect its unique and fragile environment."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"As the global demand for rare earth minerals continues to grow, Greenland is well-positioned to become a significant player in the market, with its substantial deposits and favorable business environment."}],"references":["95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089","4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299","e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406"],"documents":{"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089":{"id":"cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc_781260089","text":"Greenland ban on uranium mining prevents Chinese companies from expanding rare earths\nNovember 13, 2021 17: 33\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nAs part of its Arctic strategy, China has supported the mining of rare earths in Greenland by Australia \u2019 s Greenland Minerals, a Chinese-owned subsidiary of Shenghe Resources, through the Belt and Road Initiative.\nHowever, Greenland \u2019 s parliament passed a new law banning uranium mining and halting the development of rare earth deposits at Kuannersuit, the southern tip of Greenland.\nChina's rare earth mining accounts for more than 70% of the global mining volume, and China's rare earth magnetic processing volume accounts for 90% of the global processing volume.\nSungho Resources, one of the world \u2019 s largest producers of rare earth materials, acquired a 12.5% stake in Greenland Minerals in 2016, making it the largest shareholder in the latter.\nGuanast in southern Greenland is home to the world \u2019 s second-largest reserves of rare earths and uranium after China, accounting for 10% of the world \u2019 s rare earth production.\nSince former US President Donald Trump proposed the idea of buying Greenland in 2019, the rich rare earth resources of Guanaster in southern Greenland have attracted attention.\nGreenland \u2019 s local parliament was elected early on April 6. In the end, the pro-environmental left-wing Inuit Ataqatigiit party won the election, and its leader, Mute Egede, became the new prime minister.\nHe declared that he would do everything in his power to stop the Guanast Rare Earth Mine project.\nIn response, Greenland \u2019 s parliament has passed a new bill aimed at banning exploration of uranium deposits, as well as other radioactive deposits such as thorium, and halting the development of rare earth deposits at the southern tip of Greenland.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0033.json.gz:3224","uncompressed_offset":781260089,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/finance/20211113/bkn-20211113173337131-1113_00842_001.html","warc_date":"2021-11-13T21:12:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:cbf1d513-b13d-46cf-961f-a94c596437cc>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/finance/20211113/bkn-20211113173337131-1113_00842_001.html"},"created":"2021-11-13T22:17:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":{"id":"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","text":"A Canadian company has been granted a license to mine rare metals in Greenland.\n\u00a9 AP Photo / David Goldman Greenland ice melt August 3, 2017\nFollow us via\nToronto \u2019 s New Performance Materials, one of the few rare earth metal processors outside China, has obtained an exploration license in Greenland from Hudson Resources in Vancouver (Canada).\nWashington - Sputnik.\n\u201cThrough a special-purpose entity, NEO plans to explore and develop the Surfertog project to further diversify its global sources of rare earth ore and expand the supply chains that feed the company \u2019 s rare earth ore separation facility in Estonia, \u201d it said in a statement.\nNEO CEO Constantine Karianopoulos told the New York Times that his goal was to reduce the company \u2019 s exposure to volatile global crude prices.\nNEO buys semi-processed raw materials from Russia, the United States and Australia.\n\"Collects Rare Minerals\"...\nChina enters the world of \"space mining\" with the launch of the first robot...\nA picture.\nThe Surftog Carbonatite complex contains mineral deposits rich in neodymium and praseodymium, which are essential components of the rare earth permanent magnet used in electric vehicles, wind turbines, high-efficiency electric motors and pumps that help reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\nNEO also plans to build a new permanent magnet manufacturing plant in Estonia to supply European manufacturers of electric and hybrid vehicles, wind turbines, and energy-efficient electric motors and pumps, the statement said.\nNews Ticker\n0.\nTo participate in the discussion\nSign in or Register\nloader\nConversations\n\u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0430","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0024.json.gz:70177","uncompressed_offset":623010907,"url":"sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html","warc_date":"2022-08-22T14:11:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d>","warc_url":"https://sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html"},"created":"2022-08-22T14:37:57.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299":{"id":"4ae7f149-1ea4-4da8-9d73-8f0641b266ca_887720299","text":"AEX Gold aims to invest in Greenland through its new gold mining project\n\nTraditionally known for its fishing and hunting industries, Greenland is fast becoming the next significant area of exploration for mining businesses. The largest island in the world, Greenland remains one of the least populated areas worldwide with 56,000 citizens, and it has sought to attract local and foreign investment across a number of new projects.\n\nThe island\u2019s current position remains complex. A sovereign government, it is positioned under the Danish kingdom who provide grants to support its local economy. To further its independence and bolster its economy to create increased tax revenue, Greenland has embraced the exploration of new mining projects as well as utilising all the renewable and local resources it has to offer.\n\nRich in rare-earth minerals, gold, iron-ore, uranium, in addition to hydro and wind power, Greenland\u2019s favourable legal framework and robust infrastructure, particularly in South Greenland, have factored into AEX Gold\u2019s vision to explore through its Greenlandic subsidiary, Nalunaq Gold Mine, situated in the Nanortalik Gold belt, Southern Greenland.\n\nAcquiring an existing Exploitation Licence in 2015, the company is at the advanced exploration stage of its Nalunaq property, including the previously operating Nalunaq Gold Mine.\u00a0 \u00a0It also holds Exploration Licences at the early exploration stage Vagar and Tartoq properties.\n\nHosting a high-grade NI 43-101 compliant gold resource estimate of 263k oz (inferred) at 18.7 g/t and a number of regional exploration targets, AEX Gold has undertaken three years of exploration at Nalunaq, developing an updated geological model and an extension of the main vein strike length up to 1km.\n\n\u201cThe government is very supportive, so it's about having a sound exploration strategy. We are very much focused on that, as we have an asset package that we think we can grow and create a lot of value,\u201d explains Chief Executive Officer, Eldur Olafsson.\n\nOriginating from Iceland, Olafsson has gained extensive experience of the local geography. Focusing on mining projects in Greenland since 2012, he has analysed the country\u2019s potential against the backdrop of environmental responsibilities and associated legalities with partner SRK Exploration Services. Through this process, the business has turned its attentions solely towards gold exploration.\n\n\u201cThe known gold deposits in Greenland are in an area where the climate is mild and, given our experience, logistics are relatively easy. Gold opportunities are easier to finance than larger base metals projects and our perception was that we could fully fund projects like these through our support here in Iceland and in the UK market,\u201d he explains.\n\n\u201cWe started looking for opportunities in the South Greenland Gold Province and became aware of this historically producing mine. We were attracted by the extremely high-grade potential of the resource and the fact that the project had significant infrastructure in place.\u00a0 We believed there were significant opportunities to materially improve the mining operation that had been run by previous operators.\u201d\n\nExtensive exploration\n\nThroughout the exploration of high-grade resources, Olafsson is proud to remain hands on and is regularly seen on site. By undertaking various technical studies, AEX has gained the ability to comprehensively analyse similar types of assets with potential. \u00a0After acquiring the Nalunaq project in 2015 the company has continued to expand its portfolio. Whilst Nalunaq encompasses the required licence to explore and recommence production at the old gold mine, they own the larger Vagar exploration licence, situated a few kilometres to the west of the mine, where AEX believes the ground is prospective for the discovery of further Nalunaq-type deposits.\u00a0 In addition, they also own the early stage Tartoq Project to the North West of Nalunaq. Each licence area is at a different stage of exploration which supports AEX\u2019s aim of having a continuous pipeline of projects being brought into production.\n\n\u201cWe have a total of 690sqkm of licences in south Greenland and we're the only active listed gold company in Greenland. Previous operators undertook very little forward-looking exploration once the mine was in production.\u00a0 It's a very under-explored region so we intend to recommence production within the next two years at Nalunaq in order to support our exploration in the larger licences in the next 5-10 years,\u201d he says.\n\n\u201cIceland is a short distance from Greenland, so logistically it\u2019s good for us. Additionally, in Iceland you need to be really self-sufficient, and the same can be said for those in Greenland. We don't have as many people or the multitude of services that you would have in other countries which encourages you to think creatively,\u201d he adds.\n\nConsequently, the company has sought to maximise efficiency whilst keeping costs down, yet all the time adding increased value across its operations.\n\nBy acquiring a high-grade deposit, less material is needed to be broken down, lowering AEX Gold\u2019s carbon footprint. Everything taken out of the mine from underground will be processed and shipped out to a different processing facility, or processed on site adhering to the current environmental guidelines. Historically, electricity has been generated through the use of traditional fossil fuels, something which is steadily changing throughout Greenland.\n\n\u201cWe're using oil to put in generators or to power mobile mining equipment which is high cost both in monetary and environmental terms.\u00a0 \u00a0Greenland currently has five hydroelectric power plants and they are looking at building more in south Greenland,\u201d says Olafsson.\n\nSeeing huge opportunities, he explains that the use of hydropower and wind power would complement AEX Gold\u2019s operations, not only in its existing exploration activities, but with the implementation of an electric mining fleet with electricity being obtained from local renewable resources.\n\nProviding local opportunities\n\nIn the future, it will be essential for Greenland to gain further revenue to unlock opportunities and services for its citizens. This is something Olafsson believes that AEX Gold can help with due to its knowledge of Iceland as it has many similarities to Greenland and has been through a period of comparable change.\n\n\u201cGreenland is in a similar position to Iceland not so long ago. Iceland didn't have a high education rate and wasn\u2019t wealthy compared to other European countries, with economic and cultural activities that were very insular. We are now at the highest level of all parameters in terms of education, wealth per family, etc. and this has stemmed from improving the breadth of schooling and creating opportunities for people to grow and develop outside of the traditional areas of agriculture and fisheries.\n\n\u201cOur aim is that the majority of employees will be Greenlandic, but it will take time. Greenland has a large number of people competing for jobs in the fisheries and tourist centres. It is important that Greenlanders are able to access programmes that will allow them to consider other career options. In Iceland we are importing a lot of people to work in different industries in our country because we don't have enough people. This might be the case for Greenlanders as well if the anticipated growth of the Mining Sector materialises but we want to ensure that, where possible, we use local people first before looking elsewhere.\n\n\u201cThe Greenlandic Government provides good support for those who seek education.\u00a0 There are an increasing number of Greenlandic students attending Danish Universities so that now, for example, we are seeing well qualified Greenlandic geologists available for employment.\u00a0 There has been a Mining School at Sisimiut for the last 10 years which provides local qualified labour who can take advantage of opportunities in the Mining sector.\u00a0 You need skilled labour and as we own a mine that was in production for 10 years previously, there is a fair bit of local knowledge that we have been able to use during our exploration work and which we are keen to utilise going forward,\u201d he says.\n\n\u201cWe are creating revenue for local communities, creating highly skilled jobs, and are providing benefits where local communities can live better lives and grow as individuals. We need to create opportunities for young people.\u201d\n\nAdditionally, by working with local businesses as well as those who have been operating in Greenland for some time, AEX has made a conscious effort to hire companies which can support its growth. AEX have therefore acquired a longstanding relationship with Cartwright Drilling, due to the company\u2019s extensive experience in Greenland and subsequent knowledge of the island\u2019s government systems, processes and practices.\n\nPlanning to mine high-grade resources using significant infrastructure already in place, AEX Gold holds extensive licences managed by an experienced team. Previous operations produced between 50,000 to 100,000 ounces a year at 15.4 grams/ton produced and this has provided a benchmark for the company, who will utilise this cash flow to explore the wider region in the long-term.\n\n\u201cWe have a five-year plan where we want to get into production at Nalunaq and use the cash generated to fund exploration in the wider district.\u00a0 \u00a0We envisage investing a significant amount in exploration assets to provide a portfolio of different deposits that we can bring into production. We are creating a company that has a long-term mission in Greenland to build up local know how to support our aim of ramping up to very profitable production across a number of projects,\u201d notes Olafsson.\n\n\u201cIt will create a dramatic effect on the local community and hopefully be a springboard for unlocking much larger potential in Greenland. There are plenty of deposits that have been found, but you have to be able to develop them. You can only do that that with support and cooperation from the local people who believe in your vision.\u201d\n\nShare\nShare\nAuthor\nExecutives\nEldur Olafsson","url":"https://businesschief.eu/company-reports/aex-gold-aims-invest-greenland-through-its-new-gold-mining-project"},"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":{"id":"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","text":"Greenland to mine rare earths in 2024 | Economic Horizontal | DW | 30.07.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nEconomic stratification\nGreenland to mine rare earths in 2024\nAccording to the German \"Economic Weekly\" reported that a mining company has obtained permission from the Greenland government to mine rare earths on the island.\nThe company said production could begin next year.\nTanbreez Mining, a mining company, plans to mine rare earths in Greenland next year, according to the Economic Weekly.\n\u201cWe can start production next year, \u201d said Greg Barnes, a geologist and owner of the company. Greenland \u2019 s deputy minister for minerals confirmed to the journal that a mining licence had been issued.\nBarnes said the Tanbreez mine \"contains more than half of the world's rare earth resources\" and has 19 million tons of rare earth oxides.\nOf these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements.\nRare earth contains a total of 17 kinds of metal elements, the properties of each metal are different.\nEach metal has a unique industrial value.\nSome of them are irreplaceable.\nThey are used, for example, in the manufacture of electric vehicles or wind turbines.\nLast year, about two-thirds of Germany \u2019 s rare earths came from China. Mining such as rare earths is difficult and often harmful to the environment, as rare earths are often associated with iron ore, and the chemical process of refining often requires the use of acidic substances.\nWhat is Rare Earth?\nBarnes, owner of Tanbreez Mining, told Economic Weekly that to start mining for rare earths in Greenland, a factory would be needed to separate rare earths from heterosexual rocks.\nCurrently there are only such factories in Russia and China.\nBut one such plant will be built in the United States in the coming months.\nThere are also plans to build a factory in Europe.\nThanks to technological advances, the equipment that separates rare earths currently costs only $40 million.\nAccording to Barnes, China paid 1.7 billion U.S. dollars for the equipment 13 years ago.\nIn January, Swedish state-owned mining company LKAB announced the discovery of Europe \u2019 s largest rare earth deposit to date.\nBut the company said it would take 10-15 years for the rare earth mine, located in Kiruna in northern Sweden, to be available to the market.\nEU Plans to Diversify Rare Earth Supply Chain\n(Agence France-Presse, Economic Weekly)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.\nDW.COM","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0022.json.gz:13510","uncompressed_offset":711284580,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp","warc_date":"2023-07-30T13:30:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp"},"created":"2023-07-30T14:20:54.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":{"id":"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406","text":"Advertisement\nEconomics.\nA race between financiers around the world to search for this substance in Greenland.\nInteresting details!\n10-08-2022 | 00: 49\nA-\nA +\nphotos 0\nA +\nA-\nCNN reports that some of the world \u2019 s wealthiest people are funding large treasure hunts using helicopters and signal transmitters on Greenland \u2019 s west coast.\nThe climate crisis is causing Greenland \u2019 s ice to melt at unprecedented rates, ironically creating an opportunity for investors and mining companies looking for a treasure trove of important minerals capable of powering clean energy transitions.\nAdvertisement\nSearch for minerals in Greenland\nMany billionaires, including Jeff Bezos, Michael Bloomberg and Bill Gates, are betting that what lies beneath the surface of the hills and valleys of Disco Island and Greenland \u2019 s Noswak Peninsula are important enough minerals to power millions of electric vehicles.\nSpeaking to CNN, Kobold Metals CEO Kurt House said: \u201cWe are looking for a deposition that will be the largest or second largest nickel and cobalt deposition in the world. \u201d\nThe disappearance of Arctic ice \u2013 both on land and in the ocean \u2013 highlights a unique dichotomy: Greenland is the zero point for the effects of climate change, but it could also be the zero point for the search for the minerals needed to provide solutions to this crisis.\nFor their part, representatives of Kobold Metals, a California-based mineral exploration company, said the billionaires \u2019 club is supporting the company financially.\nBezos, Gates and Bloomberg did not respond to requests from CNN for comment on the news, and Kobold Metals is partnering with Bluejay Mining to find precious and rare metals in Greenland, which are essential for building the electric vehicles and huge batteries needed to store renewable energy.\nThe Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland said Greenland could be a hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements and zinc.\nThe Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country \u2019 s \u201cability to diversify the national economy through mineral extraction, \u201d the agency said.\n(Arabic Post)\nGo ahead.\nAdvertisement\nOur news via your email\nSIGN UP\nSoftimpact\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nSoftimpact","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0023.json.gz:65609","uncompressed_offset":107535406,"url":"www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9","warc_date":"2022-08-10T08:11:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf>","warc_url":"https://www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9"},"created":"2022-08-10T08:16:29.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
