hich is increasingly concerned about India's growing proximity to the US."},{"citations":{"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":1.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, the India-Russia relationship remains strong, with the two nations having a Special and Privileged Strategic Partnership, as acknowledged by Prime Minister Modi and President Putin in their recent phone call."},{"citations":{"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":1.0},"text":"The two leaders have agreed to remain in regular touch with each other on a range of issues, and Putin's recent visit to India was seen as a significant development in the field of foreign affairs."},{"citations":{"d749981a-0acd-425d-8652-51e8701d6755_959152834":1.0},"text":"Russia considers India a \"great power\" and a \"time-tested friend\", with President Putin expressing his happiness at being in India and looking forward to strengthening bilateral ties."},{"citations":{"d749981a-0acd-425d-8652-51e8701d6755_959152834":1.0},"text":"The mutual investments between the two nations stand at around $38 million, with a significant portion of Russian investment in India, and the two countries cooperate greatly in the military and technical spheres."},{"citations":{"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":1.0},"text":"The relationship between India and Russia has been built over decades, with the Soviet Union being India's greatest ally in the 20th century, as noted in."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"However, the rise of China as a global power has introduced a new dynamic in the India-Russia relationship, with Russia seeking to strengthen its ties with China to counter the US-led international order."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"This has led to a complex situation, with India having to navigate its relationships with both Russia and the US, while also dealing with the challenge posed by a rising China."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"The India-Russia relationship has been affected by India's rivalry with China, with Russia's growing proximity to China introducing a new element of tension in the bilateral ties."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"China and India are not allies, and their relationship has been marked by tension, particularly over border disputes."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"However, there have been recent efforts to improve relations between the two nations, with China congratulating Prime Minister Modi on his election victory and expressing a desire to resolve border disputes."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"The relationship between Russia and China has undergone a significant transformation, with the two nations having warmed up to each other in recent years, despite being rivals since the Sino-Soviet split during the Cold War."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"The Russian president's first foreign trip after his re-election was to Beijing, and the two nations have agreed to strengthen their ties, with President Xi Jinping and President Putin describing their relationship as the \"best in history\"."},{"citations":{"331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654":1.0},"text":"India has sought to diversify its defense purchases outside of Russia, but more than 60% of its weapons still come from Russia, making it essential for India to maintain a strong relationship with Russia to ensure the supply of spare parts."},{"citations":{"331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654":1.0},"text":"The India-Russia relationship has come under strain in recent years, particularly as India has become closer to the US, with mutual concerns over the rise of China."},{"citations":{"331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654":1.0},"text":"However, the relationship remains strong, with the two nations having a long history of cooperation, and India continues to see Russia as an important partner in its foreign policy."},{"citations":{"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the India-Russia relationship has evolved significantly under Prime Minister Modi and President Putin, with a complex interplay of factors influencing the dynamics of their bilateral ties, particularly in the context of India's rivalry with China."},{"citations":{"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":1.0},"text":"The relationship remains strong, with the two nations having a Special and Privileged Strategic Partnership, and India continues to see Russia as an important partner in its foreign policy."},{"citations":{"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":1.0},"text":"However, the growing proximity between Russia and China introduces a new element of tension in the bilateral ties, and India will have to navigate this complex situation carefully to maintain its relationships with both Russia and the US."}],"references":["18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163","d749981a-0acd-425d-8652-51e8701d6755_959152834","331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654","1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519"],"documents":{"d749981a-0acd-425d-8652-51e8701d6755_959152834":{"id":"d749981a-0acd-425d-8652-51e8701d6755_959152834","text":"New Delhi | Jagran News Desk: Prime Minister Narendra Modi met visiting Russian president Vladimir Putin at Delhi\u2019s Hyderabad House on Monday evening. Prime Minister said that India-Russia ties are stronger than ever.\n\nPrime Minister Modi added that despite the challenges posed by the pandemic, there has been no change in the relationship between India and Russia. He further pointed out that the two countries cooperated during the COVID-19 crisis too, in the field of vaccine and humanitarian support. \"The relation between India and Russia is truly a unique and reliable model of interstate friendship,\" Prime Minister Narendra Modi said.\n\n\"You (Putin) should be credited for the strategic partnership between our countries for the 3 decades,\" PM Modi said, acknowledging Russian President Vladimir Putin's role in nurturing the bilateral traditions between India and Russia.\n\nIndia a great power, time-tested friend: Vladimir Putin\n\nRussian President Vladimir Putin said that Russia considers India 'a great power' and a 'time tested' friend. \"The relations between our nations are growing and I am looking into the futur,\" Putin added while further asserting his happiness at being in India, saying that he is 'happy to travel to India'.\n\n\"Currently mutual investments stand at about 38 million with a bit more investment coming from the Russian side. We cooperate greatly in military and technical sphere like no other country. We develop high technologies together as well as produce in India,\" Putin said.\n\nThis is the first in-person meeting between PM Modi and President Putin after their meeting on the sidelines of BRICS summit in Brazil in 2019 before the beginning of COVID-19 pandemic. Both the leaders are scheduled to hold deliberations to review the prospects of bilateral relations and recalibrate the long standing India-Russia friendship.\n\n\"The agenda for the dialogue will cover political and defence issues of mutual interest. The establishment of this new mechanism of two plus two dialogue is expected to further strengthen the strategic partnership between the two countries,\" Ministry of External Affairs spokesperson Arindam Bagchi had said earlier.\n\nPosted By: Mukul Sharma","url":"https://english.jagran.com/india/pm-modi-meets-vladimir-putin-in-delhi-india-a-timetested-friend-says-russian-president-10035975"},"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163":{"id":"18a87794-ba47-4d33-a1b5-bf97307dd44b_224507163","text":"Top\n\nOld friends\n\nX\n\nOn Monday, PM Modi spoke over the phone with Russian President Vladimir Putin. The phone call reportedly was a follow-up on many of the issues raised during Putin's recent India visit on December 6. According to a statement by the PMO, the two leaders have agreed to remain in regular touch with each other on a range of issues covered under the India-Russia Special and Privileged Strategic Partnership. Insofar as visits from foreign dignitaries and leaders go, Putin's visit to India earlier this month was arguably the most consequential development for India in the field of foreign affairs for quite some time. India, as may be known, has a long and storied relationship with Russia and its precursor, the Soviet Union. From the earliest days, the friendship between the two nations had a strong strategic undertone with both sides supporting each other on the world stage whenever necessary. Indeed, the Soviet Union was undeniably India's greatest ally in the 20th century against the machinations of the western powers like the US that did not take kindly to India announcing itself to be a 'socialist' nation. From Kashmir to the Bangladesh Liberation War, Russia has stood by India in defence of its strategic interests. As a proof of the relationship, a majority of military equipment India currently possesses was either directly supplied by Moscow or is otherwise of Russian origin. In recent years, with the fall of the Soviet Union and India's move towards liberalising its economy, India has ventured out into the world to make a new set of friends. This time around, it is India and the US that are getting along like a house on fire. India has deliberately sought to widen its field diplomatically and militarily in order to not be tied down to a single nation with the rather pragmatic understanding that there are no permanent relationships in international politics. In more recent times, Russia and India have somewhat drifted further apart as Russia bands together with India's rival China to take on the hegemony of the western world that is held up by the US. While India has no interest in joining the US in its power games against Russia, it is very much interested in leveraging its relationship with the west in its struggle to contain a belligerent China. It is here that India has had to perform a tremendous tight-rope walk, particularly following the 2014 annexation of Crimea by Russia. On the one hand, you have America that wishes to limit or even extinguish India's strategic relationship with Russia. On the other, you have Russia that is increasingly concerned and agitated by India drawing ever closer to the US's sphere of influence as it joins America in endeavours like the Quad grouping. Of particular concern to both sides is India's continuing dependence on Russia for military equipment. The US, already having sanctioned Turkey for the same, looks on menacingly as it threatens India with sanctions for buying the S-400 missile system. Russia, of course, is not only interested in keeping its old defence ties but even expanding them, as it has been recently teasing India with the possibility of being the first nation in the world to buy the improved S-500 missile system. In this regard, Putin's visit to India could be termed as symbolic. Since the beginning of the pandemic, Putin has only ventured out twice from his country, with the second trip being the one to India. His tone and body language during the meeting with PM Modi spoke volumes of the importance he attaches to maintaining the ties with India. Aside from underscoring the good working relationship he has with India's PM, the visit also highlighted that despite the recent turns of history, the two nations still have much to share and collectively work towards. Common concern in regards to the Taliban and Afghanistan is one such area that the two sides are looking to cooperate on in the near future. Another is strengthening existing defence ties between the two nations. Underscoring its strategic independence, India has decided to continue with its defence dealings with Russia, discussing the purchase of the S-400 missile system while also finalising a long-pending Rs 5,000 crore deal for the production of over five lakh AK-203 rifles in a joint Indo-Russian deal. But all said and done, the future of India's relationship with Russia still has some shades of uncertainty. Primary amongst them is the ongoing escalation between Moscow and NATO in regards to Ukraine and eastern Europe. If Russia should choose to brave threats of western sanctions to take action in Ukraine, where does this leave India? Can India still continue its balancing game between east and west at a time when geopolitics are heating up to a boiling point? That remains to be seen.\n\nNext Story","url":"http://www.millenniumpost.in/editorial/old-friends-462727"},"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519":{"id":"1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d_1036017519","text":"Archive | Countries | Persons | Catalog | News | Discussions | Jokes | Contacts | PDA\n| Central Asia | Afghanistan | Kazakhstan | Kyrgyzstan | Tajikistan | Turkmenistan | Uzbekistan |\nNews & Events\n|\nSaturday, 06.07.2024\n13: 32 What is known about the new President of Iran Masoud Peseshkian\nNazarbayev \u2019 s Big Friend Sold Assets in Kazakhstan 21 Times Cheaper\n13: 00 Middle East: Israel is trying on the role of an energy hub\n12: 56 Why India is walking on a tightrope between the US and Russia\nPrevious articleAncient alphabet of the vanished civilization of Tartes discovered in Spain\n12: 42 Aktau seaport to receive international status\n10: 09 Why does Russia continue to sell uranium to the United States?\nIt is difficult to explain to Sevastopol children...\n10: 05 Tokayev arrives in Azerbaijan on working visit\n10: 02 The US is getting closer to Central Asia: why did the \u201ccorridor \u201d from across the ocean arrive in Baku, - SP\n09: 28 Bishkek.\nMP Azhibayev fought with the security guard of the shopping center\n09: 19 Russia is ready to save Assange.\nThe decision is up to him.\n09: 18 \"The Third Force\" of the Global South, - Vl.Mozhegov\n09: 17 Foreign political parties banned in Uzbekistan\n09: 14 Erdogan does not lose hope: what cat ran between Russia and Turkey, - Kamran Hasanov\n09: 13 In Tajikistan, fines for smoking increased threefold\n09: 09 \"The fate of the battle for Donbass is being decided.\"\nThe Russian army liberates Chasov Yar\n09: 06 Who is settling accounts with the arrested General Commander Popov?\n09: 04 Azerbaijani, reformist leader Masud Pezeshkian wins presidential election in Iran\n01: 38 Oleg Tsarev: Russian is not about nationality, but about self-identification\n01: 32 Eastern NATO already exists and operates, - A. Koshkin\n01: 29 In the US, they are in a hurry to create an AI that can easily destroy humanity, - V. Prokhvatilov\n00: 44 Kazakhstan again began to detain trucks of Russian cargo carriers\nA group of influential Democrats asked Biden to withdraw from the election\nWill the propaganda of sexual deviations be banned in Kazakhstan? - Vladislav Yuritsyn\nIran tests itself for conservatism, - E.Baynazarov\nTom Slater: Labour Restoration will split Britain into flaps\nFriday, 05.07.2024\n18: 28 Medinsky, who merged the negotiations in Istanbul, continues to do the same\n15: 41 Downing Street \u2019 s Larry Cat Farewell Shits in Sunaku \u2019 s Boots (British Humor)\n15: 35 In Kyrgyzstan revealed another anti-government conspiracy\n15: 31 Hungarian Prime Minister Orban brought Putin another peaceful \u201cdeceitful PR plan \u201d\n15: 12 Charles III promptly ordained Cyrus Starmer to the 80th Prime Minister of Great Britain\n15: 09 Tokayev endowed the KNB with new functions\n14: 33 New York Times: Which of Starmer's British Prime Ministers?\n14: 29 Colonel Andersen: \"The Red Sea was a shame for the US Navy\"\n14: 27 The new building of the government of Tajikistan is ready: we show and tell what it is inside\n14: 23 SCO: breakthrough to Europe, - Bulat Sultanov\n13: 30 Biden still has moments of enlightenment, - P. Baker et al.\n12: 10 The subject of discord: what is the niqab and is it possible to wear it in Russia\n12: 01 The West praises the Russian ministers.\nWhat \u2019 s wrong here? \u2013 Katasonov\n11: 59 German Foreign Minister Berbok got into another scandal with migrants\n11: 48 Daniyar Ashimbayev: How it was \u2026 the background of the emergence of the SCO, the EAEU\n11: 05 Rector of the Kyrgyz State Academy of Physical Culture and Sports Azizbayev detained for extorting bribes\n10: 53 Astana Declaration of the SCO - \"mirror\" of Kyrgyzstan's foreign policy - Ismail Dairov\n10: 49 Barysh Ergin: The dollar is over.\nThe BRICS countries made three important steps\n10: 48 What does the admission of Belarus to the Shanghai Cooperation Organization mean?\n10: 44 Macron is missing somewhere..., - \"Politico\"\n10: 42 Escalation of confrontation between Russia and the West is coming, - J. Beeb\n10: 00 Moscow proposes plan for peace in Ukraine to SCO summit - V.Skosyrev\n09: 49 \"The world in the American way\" - as a briefly postponed war, - Y.Borisov\n09: 28 The end of Rishi Sunak: the elections in the UK ended in disaster for the ruling party, - A. Yashlavsky\n08: 55 White House discusses return of control over Afghanistan, - I. Subbotin\nArchive\n\u00a9 CentrAsiaTop\nCenterAsia |\nWhy India is walking the tightrope between the US and Russia\n12: 56 7 / 6 / 2024\nWhy India is walking the tightrope between the US and Russia\n05.07.2024\nAfter the Cold War, which began in the 1950s, split the world into two camps, the newly independent India became the founder of the Non-Aligned Movement, a group of countries that did not side with either Washington or Moscow.\nUnder Prime Minister Narendra Modi, India retained some elements of this policy unchanged, while abandoning others.\nIn particular, Modi has strengthened ties with the United States, in which he sees a partner in the confrontation with a more assertive China.\nAt the same time, he continued to develop his country \u2019 s long-standing ties with Russia.\nAs a sign of Russia \u2019 s important role for India, Modi will meet with President Vladimir Putin on July 8 during his first foreign visit to a fellow leader after being elected for a third term.\nBut these relations are becoming increasingly complex as Russia strengthens ties with China, seeking its broader support.\nChina and India are not allies.\n1.\nIs India an ally of the United States?\nIndia and the United States have been strategic partners for at least two decades, which means they can build relationships and cooperate militarily, but are not official treaty bound allies.\nAlthough they have much in common \u2013 both countries are large and diverse democracies \u2013 New Delhi pursues its own interests in ways that sometimes conflict with US interests.\nFor example, India has refused to condemn Russia in the conflict with Ukraine, while an alleged plot of assassins in the United States has triggered a criminal investigation in which senior Indian officials are implicated, according to prosecutors.\nThe basis of relations remains the transformation of China into an assertive regional power.\nChina and India are long-time rivals with a bitter border dispute, and the US is seeking to draw India as a counterweight to Beijing \u2019 s rise.\nIndia is part of the Quartet, a regional security dialogue with the United States, Japan and Australia.\nA group of senior U.S. officials recently visited India to discuss cooperation in technology, security and foreign investment.\n2.\nWhat is India \u2019 s relationship with Russia?\nAlthough India openly declared its non-alignment during the Cold War, it maintained warm relations with Moscow and was wary of the United States, which was closer to India \u2019 s main rival, Pakistan.\nIndia and Russia maintain strong ties to this day.\nThe basis of this relationship is India \u2019 s status as a reliable buyer of Russian arms and crude oil.\nToday, Russia remains India \u2019 s largest arms supplier, although, according to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, shipments have declined from about two-thirds of India \u2019 s arms imports more than a decade ago to just over one-third today as India seeks to diversify its sources of arms supplies.\nRussia also remains India \u2019 s largest oil supplier, although sanctions imposed on Russian oil exports have affected Russian oil imports to India.\nIndia also stands out among the leading democracies for its unwillingness to criticize Russia and abstained from voting at the United Nations, which condemned Russia for the conflict in Ukraine.\n3.\nWhat is India \u2019 s relationship with China?\nRelations have been tense for years.\nThe source of tension was a territorial dispute along their common border that lasted decades and over which the two countries fought a war in 1962.\nThe dispute flared up again in 2020, culminating in a series of deadly skirmishes and prompting New Delhi to ban Chinese smartphone apps and limit Chinese investment in India.\nRecently, there have been rumors of a relaxation of tension.\nIn May, Beijing appointed its first ambassador to India in 18 months.\nAfter his arrival, he expressed a desire to improve relations between the two countries.\nChina also congratulated Modi on winning the election in June, and a Chinese official said the countries were on a \"healthy and stable path.\"\nThe two countries agreed on further negotiations to resolve the border dispute.\n4.\nHow are relations between Russia and China changing?\nRussia and China have been rivals since the Sino-Soviet split during the Cold War (a rivalry that also brought Russia and India closer together).\nBut relations have noticeably warmed as both countries united in their opposition to the US-led international order.\nThe Russian president made his first foreign trip to Beijing after he was re-elected for a third presidential term in March.\nAt the July summit on security in Kazakhstan, Chinese President Xi Jinping and Vladimir Putin said that relations between them are \u201cthe best in history, \u201d and both sides vowed to jointly defend\u201c calm and stability in the region. \u201d\nChina has become another major buyer of Russian oil, gas and coal, helping Russia counter Western sanctions.\n5.\nHow does the United States view relations between India and Russia?\nWashington still views India as a bulwark preventing China from spreading its influence in the Indo-Pacific region.\nWhile he has occasionally criticized India for alleged human rights abuses and the treatment of minorities, India \u2019 s ties with Moscow have come at minimal political cost.\nFollowing a recent visit by senior US officials, Deputy Secretary of State Kurt Campbell said the US side had raised the issue of India \u2019 s ties with Russia, as well as accusations of India \u2019 s involvement in a plot to murder for hire.\nBut he also said that the United States is confident in its relations with India and wants to expand cooperation between the two countries.\nAccording to some analysts, the US sees India as an important ally in its quest to contain China, so it does not want to risk antagonizing officials in New Delhi.\nPrepared by ProFinance.Ru based on Bloomberg materials.\nSource - ProFinance.Ru\nPermanent address of the article - https: / / centrasia.org / newsA.php? st = 1720259760\nNews of Kazakhstan\n- Working schedule of the head of state\n- How the SCO was created\n- About SCO and SCO +\n- Maulen Ashimbayev and Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov opened a monument to the Turkmen poet Makhtumkuli Fragi\n- Issues of development of fodder production were discussed in the Government\nKanat Bozumbayev held a meeting on the development of a package of urgent measures for the development of the western regions of the country\n- Working schedule of the head of state\n- Personnel reshuffles\n- Ruslan Zhaksylykov took part in the meeting of the CIS Council of Defense Ministers\n- Working schedule of the head of state\nGo to the version with frames\n\u00a9 CentrAsiaTop","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0017.json.gz:199231","uncompressed_offset":1036017519,"url":"centrasia.org/newsA.php?st=1720259760","warc_date":"2024-07-06T09:47:59.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:1be2e208-2533-4d08-9d1d-83cf9ae7af6d>","warc_url":"https://centrasia.org/newsA.php?st=1720259760"},"created":"2024-07-06T11:13:34.000Z","lang":"eng"},"331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654":{"id":"331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f_360260654","text":"...\n...\n...\n...\nIndia between Russia and America\nI'm sorry.\nThe Merciful\nPosted in: Last Updated:\nAs a non-permanent member of the United Nations Security Council, India abstained last week to condemn Russia, the largest and most capable country in Europe and Asia, for its military operation in Ukraine.\nWestern countries voted in the Security Council to demand that Russia stop its operation in Ukraine and withdraw its troops immediately, but Russia responded by vetoing a council resolution.\nThe reason for India's abstention was that it believed that non-alignment on this issue was in its national interests, while siding with one side meant harassing the other in a situation where both the United States and Russia were important to India and its national interests.\nAbstaining in the Security Council has thus allowed India to avoid taking sides and being dragged into a crisis in distant places.\nThe challenge for India, which has no direct interests in Ukraine apart from evacuating its mostly student citizens there, is to make sure there is no reaction to the crisis on its relations with Russia, a key defense partner, or with the United States, which is crucial to addressing growing problems with China in the region.\nThe Ukraine crisis also comes at a time when India is in the process of acquiring five S-400 Triumph air defense missile systems from Russia and needs an exception from the United States, which has already sanctioned Turkey under the Countering America \u2019 s Adversaries Through Sanctions Act (CAATSA) for possessing the same S-400 missiles from Russia.\nMoscow has already begun delivering missiles to New Delhi, which is seen as an important element of defence readiness for India, which has an unstable border with both Pakistan and China.\nRussia and India have been allies since the Cold War, and defense cooperation has long been a cornerstone of their relationship.\nIndia has sought to diversify its defense purchases outside of Russia, from countries such as Israel, the United States and others.\nBut more than 60 percent of India \u2019 s weapons continue to come from Russia, which means India needs to continue to get spare parts from Moscow.\nThere is no doubt that the relationship between India and Russia has come under strain, as New Delhi has become closer to Washington, amid mutual concerns over a range of issues, including the rise of China.\nTheir relationship has deepened over the past decade and they are now partners, along with Japan and Australia, in the Quadripartite Security Forum.\nRussia, in turn, has become closer to China and Pakistan even as its relations with the United States and the West deteriorate.\nBut developments in Afghanistan, where the withdrawal of U.S. troops has brought the Taliban back to power, have led to New Delhi \u2019 s increased political engagement with Moscow as India seeks access to Central Asia.\nThere is no doubt that India is trying to maintain a delicate balance between Russia and the United States, taking sides in the Ukraine conflict will only lead to problems for India, especially since it has no direct interests in Ukraine.\nThere have also been reports that Russia has quietly worked behind the scenes to defuse tensions between India and China following the 2020 border clashes.\nAs a result, Prime Minister Narendra Modi was among the few world leaders to have spoken by phone with President Vladimir Putin in the midst of the Ukraine crisis.\nModi appealed to President Putin for an immediate halt to military actions and \u201ccalled on all parties to return to diplomatic negotiations and dialogue. \u201d\nAt the same time, Modi also spoke to Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky and expressed \u201creadiness to contribute in any way to the peace efforts. \u201d\nFor India, the sooner this crisis is resolved, the better, especially because of its fears that the focus of the United States and its other allies may shift from the Indo-Pacific and the China Sea to a crisis in Europe over the dispute over Ukraine \u2019 s accession to NATO.\nIt is clear, however, that the United States and its NATO allies will avoid indulging in a direct armed conflict in Ukraine.\nWhile the EU has imposed some sanctions, including closing airspace to Russian aircraft, New Delhi \u2019 s biggest concern is that it will not get an exemption from Washington over the Triumph missile system and that tougher economic sanctions could lead to a spike in oil prices.\nAlthough the Russian and Ukrainian delegates have agreed to meet to discuss and resolve the conflict, an early resolution of the crisis seems elusive.\nIt is clear that Moscow is determined to create a demilitarized buffer zone between Russia and NATO member states.\nBut there is no doubt that a peaceful solution is the best way forward to end a crisis of this magnitude.\n* Chairman of the Centre for Islamic Studies, New Delhi\nQuote from \"The Union\"\nDisclaimer: All published articles represent the opinion of their authors only.\nMost Read Common Topics","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0006.json.gz:57286","uncompressed_offset":360260654,"url":"www.alarabiya.net/politics/2022/03/05/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%87%D9%86%D8%AF-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%88%D8%A3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A7","warc_date":"2022-03-05T19:25:57.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:331c1964-cad2-46bd-8bf4-1a709da9006f>","warc_url":"https://www.alarabiya.net/politics/2022/03/05/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%87%D9%86%D8%AF-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%88%D8%A3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A7"},"created":"2022-03-05T19:55:22.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1089","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1089","narrative_id":"1089"},"responses":[{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0},"text":"Japan is recognized as the best country in terms of waste disposal, with the key to its success being the gradual development of a sense of garbage sorting through half a century of sustained efforts and strict laws and regulations."},{"citations":{"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491":1.0},"text":"The European Union, particularly Belgium, is also a leader in waste sorting, with 91% of the population sorting garbage."},{"citations":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":1.0},"text":"South Korea has implemented a successful waste management system, with a waste charging system introduced in 1995, which has reduced the overall waste disposal volume by 40% and increased the recycling rate to over 60%."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"The city of Seoul has achieved remarkable results in waste management, introducing a series of supporting measures to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste, and living habits."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"Singapore has a well-organized and highly efficient waste management system, with a recycling rate of 51.7% in 2020, and a model that other countries can learn from."},{"citations":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":1.0},"text":"The Swiss government has introduced a tax on garbage bags to subsidize waste disposal costs, but some Swiss citizens have resorted to leaving their waste in neighboring France, prompting the French government to crack down on \"smuggling\" garbage."},{"citations":{"a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b_357271582":1.0},"text":"Taiwan has also made significant progress in waste management, with the introduction of a waste levy policy and a complex and effective waste management system."},{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0,"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":0.5,"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":0.25},"text":"The role of the government is crucial in promoting and implementing successful waste sorting and recycling practices, as seen in the examples of Japan, South Korea, and Singapore."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0},"text":"Japan is recognized as the best country in terms of waste disposal, with the key to its success being the gradual development of a sense of garbage sorting through half a century of sustained efforts and strict laws and regulations."},{"citations":{"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491":1.0},"text":"The European Union, particularly Belgium, is also a leader in waste sorting, with 91% of the population sorting garbage."},{"citations":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":1.0},"text":"South Korea has implemented a successful waste management system, with a waste charging system introduced in 1995, which has reduced the overall waste disposal volume by 40% and increased the recycling rate to over 60%."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"The city of Seoul has achieved remarkable results in waste management, introducing a series of supporting measures to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste, and living habits."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"Singapore has a well-organized and highly efficient waste management system, with a recycling rate of 51.7% in 2020, and a model that other countries can learn from."},{"citations":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":1.0},"text":"The Swiss government has introduced a tax on garbage bags to subsidize waste disposal costs, but some Swiss citizens have resorted to leaving their waste in neighboring France, prompting the French government to crack down on \"smuggling\" garbage."},{"citations":{"a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b_357271582":1.0},"text":"Taiwan has also made significant progress in waste management, with the introduction of a waste levy policy and a complex and effective waste management system."},{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0,"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":0.5,"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":0.25},"text":"The role of the government is crucial in promoting and implementing successful waste sorting and recycling practices, as seen in the examples of Japan, South Korea, and Singapore."}],"references":["a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b_357271582","e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268","ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058","614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491","fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826"],"documents":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":{"id":"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826","text":"\u3010 Printing \u3011\nSwiss garbage smugglers evade high charges in France\nRelated LINKS http: / / www.CRNT.com 2024-04-23 10: 11: 12\nBeijing, April 23 (Xinhua) -- According to a report by the British environmental consultancy Eunomia, the global recycling rate ranking in 2017, Hong Kong ranked 24th, and Switzerland ranked 9th.\nSince 2012, the Swiss government has introduced a tax on garbage bags to subsidize waste disposal costs, but the high fees have led some Swiss to leave their waste in neighboring France.\nTo this end, the French government cracked down on \"smuggling\" garbage, blocking nearly 10 tons of garbage from Switzerland, and fined 150 euros each.\nSouth Korea has implemented garbage charging since 1995, and the overall waste disposal volume has been greatly reduced by 40%, and the recycling rate has reached more than 60%.\nCompared to \u201cone size fits all \u201d measures, the Korean government implemented the waste reduction plan in a step-by-step manner.\nWaste charging is carried out in the form of bag charging, and then gradually expanded to restrict the use of disposable products, recycling of kitchen waste, etc., to deal with waste in a multi-pronged manner.\nThe environmental equation \u201c3R \u201d has a priority: reduce waste, reuse, and recycle. Lisa Ramsden, a member of Greenpeace America, pointed out that large food and daily necessities companies have been promoting recycling for many years, but the results have not been good, so the\u201c naked buy \u201d consumption model of Reuse and Refill, that is, self-purchased containers. Buy the required items to really reduce waste at the source.\n\u3010 Printing \u3011\nRelated News:","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:24636","uncompressed_offset":561459826,"url":"hk.crntt.com/doc/1069/2/7/3/106927337.html?coluid=7&docid=106927337&kindid=0&mdate=0423101112","warc_date":"2024-04-23T01:29:20.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2>","warc_url":"https://hk.crntt.com/doc/1069/2/7/3/106927337.html?coluid=7&kindid=0&docid=106927337&mdate=0423101112"},"created":"2024-04-23T02:29:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491":{"id":"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491","text":"ROP, or How will Kyrgyzstan recycle its waste?\nIn Bishkek, a seminar was held on the topic of extended producer responsibility (EPR) for the disposal of goods and packaging, organized by the WasteNet.KG. project.\nThe seminar was attended by producers of products, government authorities, waste processing enterprises, non-governmental and international organizations and experts.\nDirector of CSR Central Asia Agency Asel Arstanbekova noted that the issues of environmental safety, social responsibility of producers are very acute.\n\u201cIn many countries, the topic of social expanded responsibility is already active and, having studied their experience, we would like to determine what is applicable for Kyrgyzstan, \u201d she said.\nWasteNet.KG expert Natalia Baidakova presented the concept of the concept of extended producer responsibility (EPR), its implementation mechanisms, and the ultimate goal of which is to reduce and gradually reduce to zero the disposal of waste that can be used in recycling and recycling.\nHow is the situation with the ROP in Kyrgyzstan?\nThe issue of waste accumulation in Kyrgyzstan is reflected in many strategic documents, such as the National Development Strategy of Kyrgyzstan until 2040, the Green Economy Concept, and the Green Economy Development Program.\nMore than 40 laws include waste issues.\nThe main ones are the law on environmental protection, on industrial waste, which was adopted back in 2001.\nNaturally, this document needs to be amended and supplemented.\nIn addition, a classification of hazardous waste based on international standards has been developed and adopted.\nThe legislation specifies that separate collection of waste should be carried out, for use as secondary resources it is prohibited to use hazardous waste as secondary raw materials.\nBut at the same time, many norms are absent, for example, there is no definition of what secondary waste is, there are no norms regulating the collection and processing of secondary raw materials, there are no norms for stimulating the processing of secondary materials, and so on.\nThe legislation undoubtedly requires changes, another thing is what these changes will be.\nOn March 19, 2021, a decree of the President of Kyrgyzstan on measures to ensure environmental and climate security was adopted.\nA number of points were aimed at improving the efficiency of waste management, implementing separate collection of garbage, including stimulating the creation of recycling enterprises.\nIn 2019, a number of laws were also amended, for example, the law of consumption production, the procedure for handling hazardous mercury-containing waste.\nWhat now?\nIn Kyrgyzstan, favorable conditions have been created for the organization of an effective management system and the introduction of expanded producer responsibility.\nThus, in December 2021, the Action Plan of the Cabinet of Ministers on the implementation of the National Development Program of the Kyrgyz Republic until 2026 was approved, which provides for the implementation of a number of measures to improve the waste management system.\nThe measures are aimed at introducing amendments and additions to laws, regulatory legal acts, including in terms of introducing the principles of the concept of extended responsibility of manufacturers of ROP for the disposal of goods and packaging.\nExperience of other countries and international companies\nAleksandara Akirman, Caucasus and Central Asia Public Relations Manager at The Coca-Cola Foundation, noted that almost all global manufacturers of goods and packaging have committed to transfer from 8 to 10% of secondary raw materials to new packaging.\n\u201cIn the next five to ten years, the companies intend to use more environmentally friendly materials, develop new types of packaging, provide for collection and processing.\nAt the same time, companies are trying to work with government authorities in their respective countries to ensure that such systems develop.\nNow in Kyrgyzstan there is a linear economy of packaging, in which most packages go to landfill, are dumped in the form of garbage.\nAlmost 100% of the primary material is used.\nWhile in a circular economy, plastic packaging is used endlessly.\nThe new packaging needs to be recycled.\nSuch a circular economy is possible.\nIn more than 30 countries around the world, we produce packaging from recycled materials, \u201d she said.\nThe OECD Environment Directorate, economist and environmentalist Frisief Lubinger in his speech noted that at present the ROP system is actively developing and is beginning to be used more intensively around the world.\n\"The transition to PPE is particularly active in North America, Europe and a number of transition economies, but it should be noted that in transition economies, additional resources are needed to make the system fully operational,\" he added.\nNext, Givi Kalandadze, an expert from Georgia, the chairman of the operator of the ROP, said that the country has a special law on waste management, which has a special section under number 9 dedicated to the ROP.\n\u201cAlso, the law has an important section dedicated to responsible persons who monitor the ROP.\nSuch a manager should be in each organization and be responsible for coordination, for cooperation with stakeholders in waste management. \"\nExperts from Kazakhstan and Russia also spoke about the system of implementation of the ROP in their countries, about successes and failures.\nIn addition, during the event, it was noted that the first place in the ROP system for packaging is occupied by the countries of the European Union, in which Belgium is the leader, where 91% of the population sorts garbage.\nNext are the countries of the Middle East, followed by the countries of Africa, then Latin America, followed by Canada, then the countries of Southeast Asia and close the list of the countries of the former USSR.\nAuthor: Munara Borombaeva.\nPhoto: Vlad Ushakov\nSource: Kuramastory\nTell us your news:\nBACK TO TOP\nBACK TO","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0010.json.gz:92446","uncompressed_offset":338756491,"url":"www.vb.kg/doc/416583_rop_ili_kak_kyrgyzstan_bydet_pererabatyvat_svoi_othody.html","warc_date":"2022-04-08T09:37:24.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86>","warc_url":"https://www.vb.kg/doc/416583_rop_ili_kak_kyrgyzstan_bydet_pererabatyvat_svoi_othody.html"},"created":"2022-04-08T09:56:32.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":{"id":"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058","text":"Bauhinia Party \uff5c Refresh Waste Charges\nAuthor: 01 Forum\nPublished: Updated:\nLike most Hong Kong people, I did not have any concept or awareness of garbage collection, until I heard that it was officially implemented on April 1 this year, and I began to pay attention to it.\nIn fact, the legislation on waste charging has been passed by the Legislative Council as early as August 2021, and the specific provisions of waste charging are actually very simple and clear, that is, based on the \"polluter pays\" principle, all waste, whether from individuals, families or groups, or according to the pre-purchased designated garbage bags, or according to the weight of the waste, the \"entry fee\".\nAs for the government's intention to implement waste charging, it is also very clear and simple, that is, to force the public to reduce waste and recycle through charging, and promote the sustainable development of ecology.\nAuthor \uff1a Zhou Xiaojao\nAlthough the rules are simple and clear, it is not so easy to really land.\nIn order to pay less, people will try to pack more garbage into garbage bags. How should those crowded garbage bags be tracked and handled? In order to pay less, people will dispose of their garbage in public places such as streets, parks, markets, shopping malls, etc., how should such behavior be identified and enforced? As for the different groups that produce large amounts of waste, as well as the property, cleaning, refuse collection and other organizations that assist in the disposal of waste, a series of countermeasures are also required.\nIt is in view of the complexity of implementation that the Government has set aside a preparation period of up to 18 months for the formal implementation of the Ordinance.\nHowever, the general public, like the author, did not really start to pay attention to the new policy, which will affect every household, until the first two or three months of its implementation, and there was a lot of uncertainty and doubt. Ming. \"\nBut the question is, is the disruption caused by garbage charges really just a problem of insufficient publicity?\nHow to deal with garbage is an old problem faced by cities, especially large cities.\nSpecifically, there are three core issues surrounding the garbage problem: First, how to control the amount of garbage generated? Second, how to encourage the classification of garbage management? Third, how to deal with different types of garbage? The first issue mainly relates to the source of garbage: how to avoid excessive packaging?\nHow to promote the environmental protection of packaging materials? The second issue relates to the recycling of waste: how to guide the public to separate and collect different types of waste according to the difficulty of recycling? The third issue relates to the fate of waste: simple stacking, centralized landfill or recycling, incineration and power generation?\nIn response to the above garbage issue, Hong Kong has not made a satisfactory response for a long time, let alone effective action.\nThe lunch boxes purchased on the street are still foam or plastic that cannot be decomposed. Shopping bags provided by shopping malls are also plastic products, and the goods purchased from the mainland are wrapped in plastic layer after layer.\nThere was a time when Hong Kong encouraged the classification of kitchen waste and the production of agricultural fertilizer from kitchen waste. Unfortunately, this good practice failed to persist, and the public has not formed a self-awareness of garbage classification.\nA large amount of waste has been sent to the countryside to landfill without any sorting. The existing three major landfills are already overwhelmed, and facilities such as waste power generation have taken more than 10 years to start.\nSolving the waste problem itself is a systematic project, involving all aspects, coupled with the interests of thousands of households and changes in living habits, so each country in the disposal of the waste issue mostly adopt a gradual, tailored, durable strategy.\nJapan is recognized as the best country in terms of waste disposal. The key to its success is the gradual development of a sense of garbage sorting through half a century of sustained efforts and strict laws and regulations.\nMainland China also tries to start with garbage sorting, although there is a strong enforcement force, but the government still dare not play a game of chess across the country, but choose some cities to pilot first, and then gradually push to the whole country.\nIn contrast, Hong Kong, which has been lagging behind on garbage disposal, naively uses \u201cpolluter pays \u201d as the ultimate\u201c killer \u2019 s mace \u201d in an attempt to \u201cget it done. \u201d\nThis mentality is understandable, but can a simple, one-size-fits-all waste charge really solve the waste problem facing Hong Kong?\nCan you encourage eco-friendly packaging?\nCan you promote garbage separation?\nMore importantly, can the current waste charging design really reduce the amount of waste generated?\nI am afraid the answers to these questions are not as optimistic as the Government thinks.\nIf Hong Kong \u2019 s waste challenge is not effectively addressed, then what is the point of this policy, which costs the time and money of all citizens and stakeholders?\nFor example, in order to make up for the long-term inaction on reclamation, the SAR Government hastily launched the HK $trillion-dollar Lantau Island Construction Project in the absence of full consultation with the community, making it difficult for the project to ride under the current internal and external environment. The awkward situation.\nThe author is not sure whether garbage collection will also face similar experiences, but if the publicity and communication in the next few months can not convince the community that the relevant garbage collection policy can effectively solve the garbage problem faced by Hong Kong, then it is necessary for the SAR Government to suspend the implementation of the relevant policy, and redesign the plan to be more gradual and targeted, focusing on effectively solving the waste generation, waste management and recycling. A series of policies, and consistent implementation.\nIn fact, the above doubts about the government \u2019 s waste charging policy have emerged since the government first introduced the relevant bill to the Legislative Council in 2018.\nAlthough the Bills Committee set up at that time to scrutinize the relevant bills supported the direction of the Government's waste reduction policy, it also made a large number of recommendations on the effective implementation of the relevant policies. Some members even held different views on whether the relevant fees could achieve the preset targets.\nThe Government has also responded to the views of the Bills Committee, including improving waste reduction and recycling measures and providing assistance to those in need.\nRegrettably, these reasonable measures should be perfect in the two years after the passage of the relevant regulations in the preparatory stage either in the form, or the lack of publicity, and ultimately let this in the design of the innate deficiencies, in the landing and inadequate preparation of the waste reduction policy is likely to fall into the eyes of the public \"workers hurt money\" and abandoned halfway.\nThe author, Zhou Xiaojui, is a researcher at the Bauhinia Institute for Policy Studies.\nThe article is only the opinion of the author and does not represent the position of Hong Kong 01.\nPlease email us at 01view @ hk01.com.\nPlease attach the author \u2019 s real name and contact details.\nIf not applicable, no notice will be given.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0006.json.gz:31723","uncompressed_offset":882356058,"url":"www.hk01.com/01%E8%AB%96%E5%A3%87/999193/%E7%B4%AB%E8%8D%8A%E9%BB%A8-%E5%86%8D%E8%AD%B0%E5%9E%83%E5%9C%BE%E6%94%B6%E8%B2%BB","warc_date":"2024-03-11T22:22:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/01%E8%AB%96%E5%A3%87/999193/%E7%B4%AB%E8%8D%8A%E9%BB%A8-%E5%86%8D%E8%AD%B0%E5%9E%83%E5%9C%BE%E6%94%B6%E8%B2%BB"},"created":"2024-03-11T23:24:06.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":{"id":"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268","text":"Hong Kong \u2019 s slow progress in environmental governance \u2013 why not look at the Greater Bay Area and the world?\nAuthor: Liu Mengting\nPublished: Updated:\nIn 2005, the SAR Government proposed to develop a recycling economy, that is, to reduce the environmental burden by repairing, recycling and extending the service life of materials, to find a way out for recycling recyclable materials, and to promote the development of related industries and promote economic diversification.\nHowever, more than a decade later, Hong Kong \u2019 s circular economy has not made much progress.\nIn this regard, some scholars suggest leveraging the advantages of the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area.\nAt the same time, Hong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy is not yet climate, and we must match the experience of \u201ctop students \u201d such as Korea, Taiwan and Singapore.\nCircular Economy Enemies the Greater Bay Area\nProfessor Patrick Poon, Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, The Hong Kong Polytechnic University, has been developing a patented technology for converting waste glass into environmentally friendly bricks since the 1990s, with a view to improving the recycling efficiency of waste glass.\nGreen brick is a kind of concrete brick, can effectively use construction waste and waste glass, the third generation of green brick has been put into the market as paving brick.\nFor more than 20 years, the technology has been optimized by scholars to the fifth generation, but it is still \u201ctechnology without market \u201d.\nIn an interview with \"Hong Kong 01\" recently, Poon mentioned the two main reasons why the development of the local green brick industry is hindered, which is also the dilemma faced by Hong Kong's circular economy.\nPan Chih-sheng says that the research on green bricks has been successful, but the price is not competitive. (photo by O'Cara)\nOne of the main reasons is that local manufacturing has caused the high enterprise products to lose market advantage. Poon analysis, because the whole production process of environmentally friendly bricks produced in Hong Kong is completed in Hong Kong, and the land price and labor in Hong Kong are very high, and the price has also risen with the water. It is necessary to open up the market to achieve maximum trade liberalization, so the possibility of contractors choosing Hong Kong materials for profit considerations is very low.\nOn the other hand, the Hong Kong government has not introduced relevant policies to require the actual use of environmentally friendly materials, in the absence of just the premise, the market share of environmentally friendly bricks is unstable, and the current use of the third generation of environmentally friendly bricks is about 20% more expensive than natural sand bricks, so the project side may not consider the use of environmentally friendly bricks.\nAnother major obstacle is that the government did not help. Pan Zhisheng pointed out that environmental protection bricks are made of recycled materials, although the quality and performance of the bricks are not lost to natural sand and stone, but the quality difference is greater.\nHowever, according to the existing government regulations, the two are regarded as the same, that is, the quality of environmentally friendly materials is too high, but it may still be regarded as unqualified due to the degree of quality difference. This single regulation is a constraint for the application of environmentally friendly bricks. If the outlook does not improve, it will be more difficult to attract investors.\nUnder such a vicious cycle, the government has no intention to invest or give support, and the environmental protection brick industry chain has become a dead end.\nThe recycling rate of local waste in Hong Kong is low, and exports are facing many restrictions.\nIn an interview with Hong Kong 01, Wong Woon-chung, director of the Johan Centre for Applied Forestry Research in the Pearl River Delta (PRD), Hong Kong Baptist University, pointed out that the land resources in Hong Kong are tight, such as the opening of a recycling plant for recycled materials will double the cost.\nMr Wong stressed that the circular economy requires complementary advantages from different regions. There is no way out if the development vision is limited to Hong Kong. (photo by Mr Cheng Tze-feng)\nWaste management in Hong Kong is inefficient and should be seen around the world\nSouth Korea, Singapore and Taiwan implemented waste levies in 1995, 1996 and 2000 respectively. Since then, they have gradually developed comprehensive and mature environmental policies with local characteristics.\nHong Kong's waste management system has been fragmented for many years, and it is time to look at the world and learn from advanced experience and thinking.\nHong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy has not been good for many years, and the climate should be on par with other regions. (Photo by Tsai Cheng-pong)\nKorea has introduced waste utilization measures in a multi-pronged manner to achieve long-term management, so the Korean waste management system is at the forefront of Asia.\nFor example, the city of Seoul, which has achieved the most remarkable results, introduced a series of supporting measures in a few years to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste and living habits after the implementation of the garbage levy system in 1995.\nIn contrast, the Hong Kong Government is always \"discussing\" with the industry and \"considering\" the initiatives of environmental protection groups.\nTaiwan is also a leader in waste management in Asia.\nThe Taiwan government sent a special cleaning team to collect household waste from residents using two types of recycling trucks \u2013 yellow garbage trucks are used to collect general waste from residents using official garbage bags, and white garbage trucks are used to collect raw and cooked food waste, plastic and other recyclable resources.\nAs early as 1997, the Taiwan Environmental Protection Agency launched the \"Resource Recovery 4-in-1 Program\", which fully mobilized the role of the government, manufacturers, consumers and licensed recycling enterprises in waste management, not only to skillfully distribute the financial costs, but also to reflect the principle of impartiality.\nSingapore has a small population, similar to Hong Kong, but the waste recycling work is more professional and centralized.\nIn Singapore, three waste management enterprises are licensed by the National Environment Agency (NEA) to provide waste collection and recycling services to residents in different parts of the country. The waste is meticulously classified into paper, plastic, glass and metal, and the garden waste is collected separately.\nIn the recycling process, incineration plants reduce the volume of waste by 90%, and then use 3% of non-incineration and non-recyclable waste to landfill to reduce the environmental burden.\nAccording to statistics, Singapore \u2019 s solid waste recycling rate reached 51.7% in 2020, a model that Hong Kong can learn from.\nAs for the administrative efficiency of the Mainland, it is also worth reflecting on the Hong Kong government. In July 2019, Shanghai implemented what has been described as the \u201cworld \u2019 s most stringent \u201d waste separation measure.\nFirst of all, its domestic waste is strictly divided into four categories, namely recyclables, hazardous waste, wet waste and dry waste; secondly, if individuals or units do not dispose of garbage in accordance with the classification, they will be punished with severe high fines.\nUnder the mandatory implementation of the government, Shanghai residents have achieved good environmental protection results after experiencing \"pain\".\nThe Garbage Levy Ordinance has already been introduced, but the Government must not be complacent about it, but must think about how to tie in with the Ordinance in the next step, and adopt a systematic and comprehensive thinking to achieve long-term waste management.\nLeave a comment...","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0029.json.gz:3319","uncompressed_offset":233172268,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C","warc_date":"2021-10-07T10:31:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C"},"created":"2021-10-07T10:41:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b_357271582":{"id":"a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b_357271582","text":"Waste management in Hong Kong starts early and matures late. How can we catch up with Taiwan, Shanghai, Korea and the tail lights of the starry cars?\nAuthor: 01 Weekly Report\nPublished: Updated:\nHong Kong's environmental protection policy has not made great progress. For many years, it seems that it has remained at the stage of \"blue waste paper, yellow aluminum cans, coffee plastic bottles\", and there is no plastic reduction policy.\nLast year, the mainland stopped the import of waste paper, and Hong Kong recyclers also stopped collecting waste paper.\nWhen the Government is faced with Members' questions on plastic reduction and countless initiatives by environmental groups, it is always in a state of \"discussion\" with the retail and restaurant industries, \"under consideration\", lest it harm the economic interests of the industry, and would rather harm the environmental benefits than see any actual action taken.\nOn July 1, 2019, the Shanghai Municipal Domestic Waste Management Ordinance was officially implemented.\nAt Haihong Bridge Station on the railway line, volunteers are promoting a little knowledge of garbage classification. (Visual China)\nOn the other hand, after years of vigorous promotion, waste management is well organized and highly efficient: South Korea \u2019 s waste management system is at the forefront of Asia, with Seoul being the most effective.\nThe local municipal authorities have the responsibility to collect, recycle and dispose of domestic and commercial solid waste. Waste management in Taiwan once lagged behind Hong Kong, but due to the early introduction of the waste levy policy by the Taiwan government, and then formulated a complex and effective waste management system, the situation in Singapore is gradually reversed. Shanghai launched the \u201cShanghai Municipal Domestic Waste Management Ordinance \u201d in 2019. The complicated measures have caused complaints from the public. Over time, the results can be said to be immediate after the people have familiarized themselves with the regulations.\nLooking at the situation in these four Asian regions, it is not difficult to imagine why there is no systematic waste management in Hong Kong today, when we look back at Hong Kong's garbage collection practices, which rely entirely on the people's consciousness to separate and unsupervised waste.\nFor more details, please read the 285th issue of Hong Kong 01 (4 October 2021), \u201cWhat should Hong Kong look for in Taiwan, Shanghai, Korea and Star? \u201d.\nClick here to try our weekly newsletter for more in-depth coverage.\n285 issues of Hong Kong 01 e-newsletter Other exclusive highlights:\nPull gate limit or energy consumption double control? China North and South electricity shortage is the same and different\nThe Expectations of Lam Cheng's Final Policy Address: Regaining the Dominant Power of Development and Restructuring the Land Economy\n\"Left glue\" opens up the land, imagines that the government is lagging behind the people.\nHas the central bank 'pacified' the property market twice in a week?\nSixteen Years of Progress: The Delayed Garbage Levy Ordinance\nAfter Meng Wanzhou's return to the motherland, the public opinion has been heated to examine Sino-US relations.\nLau Kwok-hoon: Regaining the \"True Hong Kong Speed\" and developing a new centre in New Territories North\nIs the time for UK to relax regulation of gene editing agriculture coming?\nAn Interview with Chu Hsing-hsiang and Hu Kuo-hsien\nLeave a comment...","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0029.json.gz:8791","uncompressed_offset":357271582,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E5%91%A8%E5%A0%B1/686457/%E6%B8%AF%E5%BB%A2%E7%89%A9%E7%AE%A1%E7%90%86%E6%97%A9%E8%B5%B7%E6%AD%A5%E9%81%B2%E6%88%90%E7%86%9F-%E5%A6%82%E4%BD%95%E8%BF%BD%E4%B8%8A%E5%8F%B0-%E6%BB%AC-%E9%9F%93-%E6%98%9F%E8%BB%8A%E5%B0%BE%E7%87%88","warc_date":"2021-10-08T12:22:26.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a14b3dd8-b9c0-4d9c-aacb-5ea7eea0793b>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E5%91%A8%E5%A0%B1/686457/%E6%B8%AF%E5%BB%A2%E7%89%A9%E7%AE%A1%E7%90%86%E6%97%A9%E8%B5%B7%E6%AD%A5%E9%81%B2%E6%88%90%E7%86%9F-%E5%A6%82%E4%BD%95%E8%BF%BD%E4%B8%8A%E5%8F%B0-%E6%BB%AC-%E9%9F%93-%E6%98%9F%E8%BB%8A%E5%B0%BE%E7%87%88"},"created":"2021-10-08T12:37:51.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1090","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1090","narrative_id":"1090"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The world is facing a significant challenge in managing waste, and some countries have developed effective waste sorting and recycling systems to address this issue."},{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0},"text":"Japan is recognized as one of the best countries in terms of waste disposal, with a gradual development of a sense of garbage sorting through half a century of sustained efforts and strict laws and regulations."},{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0},"text":"The key to Japan's success lies in its gradual and tailored approach to waste management, which has involved the implementation of strict laws and regulations to enforce proper waste sorting and disposal practices."},{"citations":{"ebecff75-7911-475b-94f2-13d4cab294fa_882356058":1.0},"text":"In contrast, countries like Hong Kong have struggled with waste management, with a lack of effective waste sorting and recycling systems in place."},{"citations":{"fe85cd45-bc66-422f-aed7-f8a4db64afa2_561459826":1.0},"text":"However, other countries such as South Korea have made significant progress in waste management, with the implementation of a waste levy system in 1995 that has reduced waste disposal by 24% and increased the recovery rate to over 60%."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"The city of Seoul in South Korea has been particularly successful in implementing a series of supporting measures to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste, and living habits."},{"citations":{"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491":1.0},"text":"The European Union is also a leader in waste management, with countries like Belgium achieving a recycling rate of 91%."},{"citations":{"614a165e-0153-49e3-bc27-f621c9caba86_338756491":1.0},"text":"The EU's success can be attributed to its implementation of a packaging waste directive that requires member states to achieve a minimum recycling rate for packaging waste."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"In Asia, countries like Singapore have also made significant progress in waste management, with a small population but a highly professional and centralized waste recycling system."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"Singapore's waste management system is characterized by a meticulous classification of waste into paper, plastic, glass, and metal, with garden waste collected separately."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"The country's incineration plants also reduce the volume of waste by 90%, with only 3% of non-incineration and non-recyclable waste sent to landfills."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"According to statistics, Singapore's solid waste recycling rate reached 51.7% in 2020, making it a model for other countries to follow."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"The government plays a crucial role in promoting and implementing effective waste sorting and recycling practices, with countries like South Korea and Singapore having implemented waste levies and recycling systems [3]."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"In South Korea, the government introduced waste utilization measures in a multi-pronged manner to achieve long-term management, resulting in a comprehensive and mature environmental policy."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"Similarly, in Singapore, the National Environment Agency (NEA) licenses waste management enterprises to provide waste collection and recycling services to residents, ensuring a high level of professionalism and centralization."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"In contrast, countries like Hong Kong have been criticized for their lack of effective waste management policies, with a fragmented waste management system that has not kept pace with other regions."},{"citations":{"13b98add-9f70-4376-9cea-bc8dd786e2c9_486645592":1.0},"text":"However, the Hong Kong government has recently implemented a garbage levy, which is expected to promote waste reduction and recycling."},{"citations":{"13b98add-9f70-4376-9cea-bc8dd786e2c9_486645592":1.0},"text":"The implementation of waste charging is seen as a cornerstone of the promotion of waste reduction and recycling, with many regions increasing recycling to reduce the amount of waste."},{"citations":{"13b98add-9f70-4376-9cea-bc8dd786e2c9_486645592":1.0},"text":"For example, in Korea, urban solid waste charging has been implemented since 1995, resulting in a significant reduction in waste disposal and an increase in the recovery rate."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"Overall, countries like Japan, South Korea, and Singapore have developed effective waste sorting and recycling systems, with a combination of government policies, public education, and infrastructure development [1] [3]."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"These countries have demonstrated that with a gradual and tailored approach, it is possible to achieve significant reductions in waste disposal and increases in recycling rates [1] [3]."},{"citations":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":1.0},"text":"As the world continues to grapple with the challenges of waste management, it is essential to learn from the experiences of these countries and implement effective waste sorting and recycling practices [1] [3]."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The world is facing a significant challenge in managing waste, and some countries