nts, the first of its kind at the international level, and will be updated annually with the latest figures, including measures that monitor the sector \u2019 s impact on a range of indicators, including pollutants, energy sources and water use, as well as social data, age data and gender wages in jobs related to the travel and tourism sector. Accuracy.\nJulia Simpson, President and CEO of the World Travel and Tourism Council (WTTC), announced in her opening speech the results of Environmental and Social Research (ESR).\nOne of the largest research projects, the World Travel and Tourism Council will be able to provide accurate reports and track the impact of various industry activities on the environment.\nShe explained that the tourism and travel sector is making great strides in decarbonization, stressing a focus in increasing the production of sustainable aviation fuel supported by government incentives, and also to greater use of renewable energy in national public electricity grids so as to promote the use of sustainable energy in hotel rooms.\nThe sector \u2019 s 8.1% share of the carbon footprint can be impacted by becoming more efficient and decoupling growth from the amount of energy consumed starting today, she said, noting that every decision and every step towards change will lead to a better and brighter future for all.\nFor his part, His Excellency the Minister of Tourism, Mr. Ahmed Al-Khatib, expressed his pleasure for the participation of the World Travel and Tourism Council in this important research that will follow the impact of future activities, stressing that the Kingdom recognizes that travelers and investors want policies that promote sustainability in the sector and that the Kingdom has embarked on a phase to make it a leader in the field of sustainable tourism.\n\u201cWithin the framework of the Saudi Green Initiative, we launched more than 60 initiatives last year to achieve this goal, the first batch of initiatives was investments in the green economy worth more than $186 billion, \u201d he said.\nPrevious estimates have indicated that the global travel and tourism sector is responsible for up to 11% of all global emissions, however, leading research by the World Travel and Tourism Council shows that the sector \u2019 s total greenhouse gas emissions reached only 8.1% in 2019 globally. Thermal.\nThese emissions have continued to decline continuously since 2010, as a result of technological developments, as well as the introduction of a number of energy efficiency measures to activities within the sector. Between 2010 and 2019, the GDP of the tourism and travel sector grew at a rate of 4.3% annually, while its environmental impact increased by only 2.4%.\nThe World Travel and Tourism Council will continue to release new data on the sector \u2019 s performance in these indicators over the course of 2023.\nGovernments around the world will have a tool to guide their decision-making and more accurately accelerate the process of environmental change.\nGo to the top button","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0035.json.gz:45272","uncompressed_offset":499344639,"url":"almnatiq.net/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%B1-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%86/","warc_date":"2022-11-29T21:13:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:5b952cf7-c179-453f-8644-d0cdcc3301f0>","warc_url":"https://almnatiq.net/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%81%D8%B1-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%B4%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%86/"},"created":"2022-11-29T21:38:58.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":{"id":"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106","text":"Point of view\nLin Chi-yin\nLin Chi-yin: \"Traveling Everywhere\" and \"Over-Travel\"\nEarlier, the Director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, Hsia Baolong, advocated the concept of \u201ctravel everywhere \u201d to fully explore Hong Kong \u2019 s tourism resources.\nTo speed up the implementation of the concept, the authorities are planning to set up a \"special class\" to bring together people inside and outside the Government for in-depth discussions.\nIn recent days, officials and legislators have expressed their views on the development of \"red tourism\", exploring new spots in the community, beautifying the streets, and presenting some scenes in the movies.\nSimply put, it may be the story behind the attraction, or the accumulated word of mouth on social media, and every tree and grass anywhere can become a tourist attraction.\nOf course, the author hopes that the \"class\" can launch various new ideas; and since the task of the class is to implement the concept of \"travel everywhere\", then how to implement the concept is the best for Hong Kong, the industry, the community and the public, the class can not ignore.\nThe University of Hong Kong campus has been forced by tourists, and the school has implemented reservation measures this month.\nHKU itself has a complete management structure, and the university can still implement crowd control according to the situation. However, if some scenic spots that go deep into the community or even close to residential buildings are really \"red hot\", it may not be easy to implement crowd control.\n\u201cEverywhere travel \u201d is a concept, the key to implementation lies in the ability of the authorities to foresee problems. If you rely only on\u201c see and see \u201d, it is very likely that good things will turn into bad things.\n\u201cAggressive \u201d Travel\nIn 2018, the word \u201covertourism \u201d was chosen as the Oxford English Dictionary \u2019 s word of the year, referring to the negative effects of overloading the area, declining quality of life and environmental damage caused by the influx of tourists to tourist attractions.\nFor example, Venice, Italy, which has long been affected by \u201covertourism \u201d, is not a\u201c once in a lifetime \u201d \u2013 the local population is only 50,000, and the number of daily tourists has exceeded the local population; during peak season, the number of daily visitors has even doubled.\nI have friends who visited the place more than a decade ago, and they all agreed to say that people are crowded and will not go again.\nIn addition to Venice, some European cities or small islands with a tourism-led economy (such as the Canarias in Spain) also face the problem of job opportunities, high prices, and a homogenization of shops. Multinational companies invest heavily in hotels and holiday cottages, which also lead to higher rents, which locals can \u2019 t afford.\nEven if tourism brings a lot of jobs to the region, it does not mean that the average person can earn a living wage.\nPeople in these places understand the importance of tourism to the local economy, but they do not want the tourism industry to be unlimited, resulting in the resources of the whole place are only for the service of tourists.\n\"Tourism Hazards\" and How to Deal with them\nIn Japanese society after the epidemic, a similar term, \"tourism nuisance\", has also appeared to describe problems such as traffic, noise, nuisance, and garbage pollution caused by too many tourists.\nThis phenomenon, in addition to the popularity of exchange rates, affordable air tickets, and people's desire to travel after the epidemic, social media will also have the effect of focusing on specific hot spots.\nIn the era of image-led, everyone can follow the picture, some places that were not originally planned as tourist attractions have begun to face sudden overcrowding.\nHong Kong people who love to visit Japan will not be unfamiliar with two \u201cattractions \u201d: the Daokou near Enojima Electric Railway \u2019 s Kamakura University Station, and a Lawson convenience store in Kawaguchi-cho.\nThe former is the \"holy place\" of the popular manga \"When Men are in the bottle\". In recent years, the crossing has been congested with traffic due to frequent visits by tourists to \"punch\", local people can not get on the electric train, and some tourists are dangerous for taking good photos. Lawson is also a \"punch\" attraction, and the picture is a convenience store with a beautiful view of Mount Fuji. of tourists are constantly crossing the road and parking without permission, causing local residents to feel troubled.\nToo many tourists can also lead to a decline in the quality of service, even in Japan, which values the spirit of \u201cwork people \u201d.\nWhen I visited Japan last year, I saw some shops find ways to deal with \u201ctourism hazards \u201d on their own, such as not allowing diners to take photos in the store, so that after the photos are uploaded to social media, it will cause more people to come and see them; limiting the number of diners to the number of people that the staff can serve, even if the seats are not full.\nHowever, some tourists always find it difficult to understand the intentions behind these arrangements, and I have heard some tourists complain: \"Obviously there is still a place, why not let us sit?\"\nWhen these conflicts can no longer be handled by businesses and residents themselves, how to strike a balance between \u201ctourism \u201d and\u201c public nuisance \u201d will gradually become a policy issue.\nThe most extreme way to deal with it is to \u201celiminate \u201d popular attractions \u2013 coincidentally, the authorities of Kawaguchiko recently erected a 20-meter-long and 2.5-meter-high\u201c black curtain \u201d in front of Lawson to drive away tourists who came to take photos.\nThe reason why the authorities have to take extreme measures is that management alone can not prevent tourists from rushing out of the road, which is actually to \"play the spot\".\nIn addition, there are more and more tourist cities and hotspots charging tourists \"admission fees\" or \"admission fees\", but this method can not play a large role.\nIn Venice, for example, the city has been charging a 5 euro entry fee (about HK $42) to \u201covernight \u201d travelers since last month.\nHowever, these fees simply cannot curb the huge demand for tourists, and the revenue is mainly used as a financial source to cope with \"excessive travel\", which can only cure the symptoms, not the root cause.\nThe Real Meaning of \u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d\nAt this point, some people may point out that the above problems will only become problems if we succeed in attracting tourists to Hong Kong; what we have to focus on is how to get more people to come to Hong Kong.\nHowever, how much tourism can bring to a city depends on the management and policies of the city, not on the remedial measures that can be taken.\nAlthough the share of tourism industry in Hong Kong's economy is far less than that of the \"tourist city\" mentioned above, Hong Kong can't wait to see that other places are looking for countermeasures for the \"tourism nuisance\", and even start to turn to attack, redefine the tourism industry from the planning level and actively promote tourist education.\nIn Amsterdam, the Netherlands, for example, the government announced last month that it would ban new hotels and limit the number of cruise ships to return the city to a livable and tourism-friendly city. In Kamakura, Japan, people are no longer concentrated at certain points by decentralizing transportation (such as the launch of electric tricycle rental business) and proactively promoting multiple circumnavigation routes (such as the travel routes at 13 locations of Kamakura Shogunate).\nThe main disadvantage of post-event remediation is that the difficulty and cost of solving the problem are greatly increased, which will also affect the experience of tourists. More than 10 years ago, the North District of Hong Kong also experienced a pharmacy every few steps, and the situation of residents in the North District driving out water consignors on their own, which hurt the feelings of the people of the two places.\nIn particular, there are many policy issues that can be foreseen in advance, and we do not have to go through them personally before we know what the problem is (for example, the legal problems faced by cleaners under the garbage levy will not be known until the moment of trial).\nSince there is a great deal of experience and policy measures in various places to refer to, the \u201cSpecial Class \u201d must also strike a balance between tourism and city operations when formulating tourist routes and supporting packages, otherwise the attraction will only lead to losses. After the city of Kamakura solved the problem of overcrowding of tourists, the tourism industry representative of Kanagawa Prefecture (that is, the seat of Kamakura City) pointed out:\u201c Attraction is not tourism. \u201d The amount of time it takes to win is certainly not appropriate.\n\u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d is not just about adding tourist attractions, but promoting quality tourism in a more nuanced and proactive way to avoid problems.\nThe author is a public policy consultant.\n\u25a0 Articles\n1.\nForum version is open park, welcome to submit.\nForum articles are limited to 2300 words. Please email to forum @ mingpao.com, fax: 2898 3783.\n2. The editor of this paper reserves the right to delete the article based on the space limit, but in order to maintain the main points and positions of the article as the principle; if you do not want the article to be deleted, please indicate.\n3.\nPlease attach the author's real name and contact information (can be published under a pen name), please do not submit one manuscript twice; if not applicable, without prior notice, except for those with postage return, this paper will not return the manuscript.\n4.\nNote to Contributors: Once a