News\nThe world today - spraying with water guns..\nAre tourist expulsions spreading in Europe?\nYou are now following the news of spraying with water guns.\nAre tourist expulsions spreading in Europe?\nFrom the World News section and now we leave you with the full details\nSAHAD MOHAMMED - Abu Dhabi on Friday 19 July 2024 04: 25 PM - Spain's tourism unrest has reached its peak in the past few days, with some locals in Barcelona spraying tourists with water guns and canned drinks, asking them to go back to where they came from.\nAngry residents, numbering about 3,000, blocked the entrances to hotels and cafes in the Barceloneta neighborhood in a symbolic attempt to express their indignation at the excessive tourist overcrowding in their city.\nThis is not the first time tourism has been highlighted as a problem in Spain, where the country, which attracted 85 million visitors in 2023, has seen a series of protests against excessive tourism in the country, especially in the city of Barcelona with a population of 1.6 million, which received more than 7.8 million visitors in 2023, leaving many locals unable to afford to live there due to high rental prices.\nFear of Protests in Europe\nSpain \u2019 s overcrowding problem, and the decision to confront it by locals, has highlighted the potential for anti-tourist protests to spread to the rest of Europe \u2019 s heavily tourist-ridden cities, as UNESCO \u2019 s Sustainable Tourism Project chief Peter Debrin warned.\nThe protests will certainly spread if European officials fail to address the negative impact of mass tourism on the lives of the local population, DeBrin says, noting that the situation in Spain has become very volatile, as the coming of civil society and its attempt to bring about change is critical, after all elected officials must respond to what the residents of their cities want.\nHe cited the 2021 ban on large cruise ships in Venice, Italy, which was passed after protests by residents, as cruise ships no longer pass through the Grand Canal, but are now docked away from Venice, helping to preserve the city \u2019 s structural and environmental integrity.\nBut despite the decision to ban large cruise ships in Venice, passengers continue to flock to its narrow lanes in the thousands, with Venice expected to attract about 540,000 cruise passengers this year, an increase of 9 percent compared to 2023, according to the North Adriatic Ports Authority.\nIn a bid to reduce crowds, Venice has imposed a 5 euro ($5.45) tourist tax on peak days this year, a measure that has so far failed to rein in tourist numbers, Euronews reported.\nQuality rather than quantity tourism\nLike Venice, Barcelona residents have long struggled with the global popularity of their city: every year, fewer locals say tourism benefits the city, while more people feel it is harmful, according to a survey conducted by the Barcelona City Council in 2023.\nUNESCO \u2019 s Sustainable Tourism Project Chief Officer Peter Debrin believes that Barcelona, which handles too many travelers, could join cities and countries that rely on a \u201cquality over quantity \u201d tourism strategy \u2013 prioritizing high-spending travelers, rather than budget ones \u2013 a strategy that gained momentum during the COVID-19 pandemic, when safety and employment concerns pushed destinations around the world to take in fewer affordable travelers. Instead of a lot of budget travelers.\nDebrin said Barcelona \u2019 s reliance on a \u201cquality rather than quantity \u201d tourism strategy helps correct another problem plaguing the city: tourists who behave badly, noting that for Barcelona residents, it \u2019 s not just about visitor numbers, but also how people behave, with Spaniards complaining for years about tourists drinking too much, throwing garbage and cigarettes on the streets.\nDebrin called on tourists to be more aware in their travel decisions, suggesting focusing on beautiful cities with fascinating tourist and cultural attractions, which are in need of more tourists.\nCivil Society Demands\nCivil society groups are calling on Barcelona officials to implement a number of policies aimed at \u201cdeclining tourism growth, \u201d such as increased tourism taxes, restrictions on cruise ships, and restrictions on short-term rental housing, just like the steps being explored in Amsterdam to crack down on buses, boutiques, new hotels and short-term rentals. In 2023, it asks some visitors, especially young British tourists, to\u201c stay away \u201d if they are travelling to the city for drugs or partying.\nThe most popular Spanish cities with tourists\nThe General Coordinator of the Association of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Mediterranean States (ASCAME) Anwar Zebawi, said in an interview to the site \"Economy dot Gulf\", that some tourist destinations in Spain already suffer from the problem of overcrowding, and these destinations are Barcelona, Malaga, Madrid and Valencia, as these four cities attract tourists more than their capacity, and the problem is that the largest number of these tourists, come in specific months of the year. Sixty percent of all tourists who visit Barcelona each year do so during the months between July and September, creating severe congestion, while the other 40 percent is spread over the rest of the year.\nAmplify for protests\nZibawi stressed that what everyone should realize, is that there is a kind of amplification of the recent protests in Barcelona, \u200b \u200b the city has not witnessed \"major\" demonstrations against tourists, as the problem of the local population is never with tourists, and the people who have been sprayed with water, very few and may not exceed the fingers of one hand, pointing out that what happened was directed against those who rent houses as hotel houses. Real estate, largely, deprived the local population, especially young people, of the possibility of obtaining apartments at an appropriate rental price.\nCauses of tourist overcrowding in Barcelona\nZibawi explains that one of the reasons that contribute to excessive tourist congestion in Barcelona, \u200b \u200b is to allow tourists to stay in tourist houses and chaos in this area, the city contains about 10 thousand houses that have a license to do these works, while there are about 30 thousand hotels operating without a license and in a way contrary to the law, the offer of houses for rent at competitive prices, in addition to cheap flights available in Europe make the cost of travel to Barcelona tourist destinations. This has exacerbated the phenomenon of excessive tourism.\nEuropean cities where protests could spread\nAccording to Zibawi, the European cities that can witness objections from the local population because of their suffering from excessive tourism, are Rome, Venice, some Italian islands, Crete in Greece, and some other Greek islands, while Amsterdam in the Netherlands, suffer from the problem of excessive tourism only, in some weeks of the year, especially at the end of the year. year.\nParis found a solution.\nZibawi pointed out that Paris had a major problem with the subject of overcrowding of tourists, and therefore prevented the work of hotel houses and raised the prices of hotels, where she saw that these steps contribute to making the cost of travel high, which prevents the tourist who does not have enough money to come, and this limits the phenomenon of overcrowding, pointing out that if the principle of quality tourism instead of quantity in Barcelona, this may solve the problem of overcrowding and contribute to the distribution of tourists in other areas. Spain.\nSolutions that can be resorted to\nFor his part, Amer Daboussi, executive partner of Eagle Travel Travel, said in an interview with Eqtisad.al-Khaleej that cities suffering from tourist congestion can face this phenomenon by adopting a policy of \"quality rather than quantity\", where this policy focuses on imposing high standards of hospitality to attract rich or well-resourced tourists, and get rid of the large numbers of tourists from the middle category. h its reception, which reduces the negative effects on the local community.\nDabbousi believes that cities can also resort to the solutions of imposing tourism taxes on foreign visitors, raising hotel prices, restricting the work of hotel house rental applications by imposing financial fees on these apartments and using the revenues collected to improve infrastructure in tourist areas, in addition to the need for affected countries to market new tourist destinations within them, which contributes to attracting visitors to areas outside the main tourist centers.\nExcessive damage from tourism\nCities facing the challenges of overcrowding, such as Bangkok in Thailand, Paris in France and New York in the United States, as well as some Greek and Spanish cities, must take measures to manage tourism sustainably and distribute tourism pressure in a way that preserves the quality of life of local residents and respects local culture. Eat and drink, making life more expensive for local residents.\nWe hope that we have succeeded in conveying the full details of the spraying with water guns..\nAre tourist expulsions spreading in Europe?\nIn God \u2019 s care and protection.\nAdvertisements\nYou may also read.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0018.json.gz:42800","uncompressed_offset":476571446,"url":"news.dotgulf.com/world-news/29733939/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%85---%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%B4-%D8%A8%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AF%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%87-%D9%87%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%AA%D8%B4%D8%B1-%D8%B9%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%89-%D8%B7%D8%B1%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%9F.html","warc_date":"2024-07-19T14:03:37.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e8218fac-be75-450d-a3c6-ce96b2808e2e>","warc_url":"https://news.dotgulf.com/world-news/29733939/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%85---%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%B4-%D8%A8%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AF%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%87-%D9%87%D9%84-%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%AA%D8%B4%D8%B1-%D8%B9%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%89-%D8%B7%D8%B1%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%9F.html"},"created":"2024-07-19T14:33:53.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":{"id":"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106","text":"Point of view\nLin Chi-yin\nLin Chi-yin: \"Traveling Everywhere\" and \"Over-Travel\"\nEarlier, the Director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, Hsia Baolong, advocated the concept of \u201ctravel everywhere \u201d to fully explore Hong Kong \u2019 s tourism resources.\nTo speed up the implementation of the concept, the authorities are planning to set up a \"special class\" to bring together people inside and outside the Government for in-depth discussions.\nIn recent days, officials and legislators have expressed their views on the development of \"red tourism\", exploring new spots in the community, beautifying the streets, and presenting some scenes in the movies.\nSimply put, it may be the story behind the attraction, or the accumulated word of mouth on social media, and every tree and grass anywhere can become a tourist attraction.\nOf course, the author hopes that the \"class\" can launch various new ideas; and since the task of the class is to implement the concept of \"travel everywhere\", then how to implement the concept is the best for Hong Kong, the industry, the community and the public, the class can not ignore.\nThe University of Hong Kong campus has been forced by tourists, and the school has implemented reservation measures this month.\nHKU itself has a complete management structure, and the university can still implement crowd control according to the situation. However, if some scenic spots that go deep into the community or even close to residential buildings are really \"red hot\", it may not be easy to implement crowd control.\n\u201cEverywhere travel \u201d is a concept, the key to implementation lies in the ability of the authorities to foresee problems. If you rely only on\u201c see and see \u201d, it is very likely that good things will turn into bad things.\n\u201cAggressive \u201d Travel\nIn 2018, the word \u201covertourism \u201d was chosen as the Oxford English Dictionary \u2019 s word of the year, referring to the negative effects of overloading the area, declining quality of life and environmental damage caused by the influx of tourists to tourist attractions.\nFor example, Venice, Italy, which has long been affected by \u201covertourism \u201d, is not a\u201c once in a lifetime \u201d \u2013 the local population is only 50,000, and the number of daily tourists has exceeded the local population; during peak season, the number of daily visitors has even doubled.\nI have friends who visited the place more than a decade ago, and they all agreed to say that people are crowded and will not go again.\nIn addition to Venice, some European cities or small islands with a tourism-led economy (such as the Canarias in Spain) also face the problem of job opportunities, high prices, and a homogenization of shops. Multinational companies invest heavily in hotels and holiday cottages, which also lead to higher rents, which locals can \u2019 t afford.\nEven if tourism brings a lot of jobs to the region, it does not mean that the average person can earn a living wage.\nPeople in these places understand the importance of tourism to the local economy, but they do not want the tourism industry to be unlimited, resulting in the resources of the whole place are only for the service of tourists.\n\"Tourism Hazards\" and How to Deal with them\nIn Japanese society after the epidemic, a similar term, \"tourism nuisance\", has also appeared to describe problems such as traffic, noise, nuisance, and garbage pollution caused by too many tourists.\nThis phenomenon, in addition to the popularity of exchange rates, affordable air tickets, and people's desire to travel after the epidemic, social media will also have the effect of focusing on specific hot spots.\nIn the era of image-led, everyone can follow the picture, some places that were not originally planned as tourist attractions have begun to face sudden overcrowding.\nHong Kong people who love to visit Japan will not be unfamiliar with two \u201cattractions \u201d: the Daokou near Enojima Electric Railway \u2019 s Kamakura University Station, and a Lawson convenience store in Kawaguchi-cho.\nThe former is the \"holy place\" of the popular manga \"When Men are in the bottle\". In recent years, the crossing has been congested with traffic due to frequent visits by tourists to \"punch\", local people can not get on the electric train, and some tourists are dangerous for taking good photos. Lawson is also a \"punch\" attraction, and the picture is a convenience store with a beautiful view of Mount Fuji. of tourists are constantly crossing the road and parking without permission, causing local residents to feel troubled.\nToo many tourists can also lead to a decline in the quality of service, even in Japan, which values the spirit of \u201cwork people \u201d.\nWhen I visited Japan last year, I saw some shops find ways to deal with \u201ctourism hazards \u201d on their own, such as not allowing diners to take photos in the store, so that after the photos are uploaded to social media, it will cause more people to come and see them; limiting the number of diners to the number of people that the staff can serve, even if the seats are not full.\nHowever, some tourists always find it difficult to understand the intentions behind these arrangements, and I have heard some tourists complain: \"Obviously there is still a place, why not let us sit?\"\nWhen these conflicts can no longer be handled by businesses and residents themselves, how to strike a balance between \u201ctourism \u201d and\u201c public nuisance \u201d will gradually become a policy issue.\nThe most extreme way to deal with it is to \u201celiminate \u201d popular attractions \u2013 coincidentally, the authorities of Kawaguchiko recently erected a 20-meter-long and 2.5-meter-high\u201c black curtain \u201d in front of Lawson to drive away tourists who came to take photos.\nThe reason why the authorities have to take extreme measures is that management alone can not prevent tourists from rushing out of the road, which is actually to \"play the spot\".\nIn addition, there are more and more tourist cities and hotspots charging tourists \"admission fees\" or \"admission fees\", but this method can not play a large role.\nIn Venice, for example, the city has been charging a 5 euro entry fee (about HK $42) to \u201covernight \u201d travelers since last month.\nHowever, these fees simply cannot curb the huge demand for tourists, and the revenue is mainly used as a financial source to cope with \"excessive travel\", which can only cure the symptoms, not the root cause.\nThe Real Meaning of \u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d\nAt this point, some people may point out that the above problems will only become problems if we succeed in attracting tourists to Hong Kong; what we have to focus on is how to get more people to come to Hong Kong.\nHowever, how much tourism can bring to a city depends on the management and policies of the city, not on the remedial measures that can be taken.\nAlthough the share of tourism industry in Hong Kong's economy is far less than that of the \"tourist city\" mentioned above, Hong Kong can't wait to see that other places are looking for countermeasures for the \"tourism nuisance\", and even start to turn to attack, redefine the tourism industry from the planning level and actively promote tourist education.\nIn Amsterdam, the Netherlands, for example, the government announced last month that it would ban new hotels and limit the number of cruise ships to return the city to a livable and tourism-friendly city. In Kamakura, Japan, people are no longer concentrated at certain points by decentralizing transportation (such as the launch of electric tricycle rental business) and proactively promoting multiple circumnavigation routes (such as the travel routes at 13 locations of Kamakura Shogunate).\nThe main disadvantage of post-event remediation is that the difficulty and cost of solving the problem are greatly increased, which will also affect the experience of tourists. More than 10 years ago, the North District of Hong Kong also experienced a pharmacy every few steps, and the situation of residents in the North District driving out water consignors on their own, which hurt the feelings of the people of the two places.\nIn particular, there are many policy issues that can be foreseen in advance, and we do not have to go through them personally before we know what the problem is (for example, the legal problems faced by cleaners under the garbage levy will not be known until the moment of trial).\nSince there is a great deal of experience and policy measures in various places to refer to, the \u201cSpecial Class \u201d must also strike a balance between tourism and city operations when formulating tourist routes and supporting packages, otherwise the attraction will only lead to losses. After the city of Kamakura solved the problem of overcrowding of tourists, the tourism industry representative of Kanagawa Prefecture (that is, the seat of Kamakura City) pointed out:\u201c Attraction is not tourism. \u201d The amount of time it takes to win is certainly not appropriate.\n\u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d is not just about adding tourist attractions, but promoting quality tourism in a more nuanced and proactive way to avoid problems.\nThe author is a public policy consultant.\n\u25a0 Articles\n1.\nForum version is open park, welcome to submit.\nForum articles are limited to 2300 words. Please email to forum @ mingpao.com, fax: 2898 3783.\n2. The editor of this paper reserves the right to delete the article based on the space limit, but in order to maintain the main points and positions of the article as the principle; if you do not want the article to be deleted, please indicate.\n3.\nPlease attach the author's real name and contact information (can be published under a pen name), please do not submit one manuscript twice; if not applicable, without prior notice, except for those with postage return, this paper will not return the manuscript.\n4.\nNote to Contributors: Once an article is published, we have exclusive local rights to publish the article in Chinese. This right also includes the right to republish the article in local and overseas media (including electronic media, such as Internet sites).\nIn addition, we have the right to grant the right to use the copy of the article to the relevant copying authorizing companies and organizations.\nThe above rights in this paper do not affect the copyright of the contributor and their rights and interests.\n(Criticism of current affairs articles published by this website is aimed at pointing out errors or deficiencies in relevant systems, policies or measures, with the aim of correcting or eliminating such errors or deficiencies, and improving them through lawful means, with no intention of inciting hatred, dissatisfaction or hostility towards the Government or other communities)\n[Lin Chi-yin]\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0014.json.gz:7215","uncompressed_offset":38011106,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A7%80%E9%BB%9E/article/20240528/s00012/1716827737305/%E6%9E%97%E7%B7%BB%E8%8C%B5-%E3%80%8C%E7%84%A1%E8%99%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D%E8%88%87%E3%80%8C%E9%81%8E%E5%BA%A6%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D","warc_date":"2024-05-28T03:20:38.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A7%80%E9%BB%9E/article/20240528/s00012/1716827737305/%E6%9E%97%E7%B7%BB%E8%8C%B5-%E3%80%8C%E7%84%A1%E8%99%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D%E8%88%87%E3%80%8C%E9%81%8E%E5%BA%A6%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D"},"created":"2024-05-28T03:25:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":{"id":"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654","text":"\nMenu\n\nSedona Film Festival presents \u2018Crowded Out\u2019\n\n\n\u201cCrowded Out\u201d is a powerful short documentary exploring over-tourism, featuring interviews with local residents and global experts. (Image provided by SIFF)\n\n\nOriginally Published: September 14, 2022 8:43 p.m.\n\nThe Sedona International Film Festival is proud to present the third film in its four-week Sustainable Tourism Film Series. \u201cCrowded Out: The Story of Overtourism\u201d will show on Thursday, Sept. 22 at the Mary D. Fisher Theatre at 4 p.m. The event will also include a selection of \u201cSustainable Travel: Where Next?\u201d short films along with a panel discussion.\n\n\u201cCrowded Out\u201d is a powerful short documentary exploring overtourism, featuring interviews with local residents and global experts.\n\nOvertourism occurs when there are too many visitors to a particular destination. When rent prices push out local tenants to make way for holiday rentals, when narrow roads become jammed with tourist vehicles, when tourists cannot view landmarks because of the crowds \u2013 these are all signs of overtourism.\n\nAnd it is the backlash from local residents that has made overtourism news. Cities such as Barcelona, Venice and Dubrovnik, and places once thought of as remote such as Iceland and Skye have suffered firsthand, and the protests by local residents have spread.\n\nThere has been decades of virtually uncontrolled growth, and it has crossed a threshold: in many destinations, tourism now demonstrably creates more problems than benefits.\n\nThis special event will also include a selection of short films from \u201cSustainable Travel: Where Next?\u201d This series includes short-form documentary films, featuring insightful stories from the global travel and tourism sector showing how they are driving sustainable travel and protecting these precious destinations.\n\nFollowing the screenings, there will be a panel discussion with representatives the City of Sedona, the Sedona Chamber of Commerce, Keep Sedona Beautiful and the tourism and hospitality industry here.\n\n\u201cCrowded Out: The Story of Overtourism\u201d will be shown at the Mary D. Fisher Theatre on Thursday, Sept. 22 at 4 p.m. Tickets are $12, or $9 for Film Festival members. For tickets and more information, please call 928-282-1177. Both the theatre and film festival office are located at 2030 W. Hwy. 89A, in West Sedona. For more information, visit: www.SedonaFilmFestival.org.\n\nThe final film in the Sustainable Tourism Series is:\n\nThursday, Sept. 29 at 4 p.m. \u201cVendemmia\u201d","url":"https://www.verdenews.com/news/2022/sep/14/sedona-film-festival-presents-crowded-out/"}}}
