 to ask me how I use AI now.\nIn fact, the application is too broad and too complicated. To make him understand it as soon as possible, I cite my entire workflow as an example.\nFor example, when writing an article, in the stage of collecting materials, AI helps me to make notes of books / meetings / lectures / courses with speech, and the content is accurate and the grammar is strict. It can also be converted into various forms of charts, different lengths and various articles.\nAt the writing stage, I will discuss with AI what different topics can be cut into perspective, such as this article I want to know how AI is changing our society, ask it to help me summarize the main views on the Internet, and I will continue to ask for some details, and also ask it to grab the latest data for me.\nNext, before po comes to the community, ask it to help me modify the typos and punctuation, the correction only takes a few seconds, and the text creation is basically completed.\nI asked my friend, do you think you can do better, faster and cheaper than AI?\n\u25b2 AI can help users to take notes with voice, and the content of speech to text is accurate and the grammar is strict. It can also be converted into various forms of charts, different lengths and various articles.\n(Chart / CFP)\nNext, the image creation.\nNow many devices, including WebCam and Monocular, the camera can lock the portrait to move in small amplitude, and even deliberately create a natural hand shake, self-portrait images are becoming more and more dependent on others.\nBefore the oral video, mainly rely on improvisation or reading, the former plays subtitles until the hand is broken, the latter has to get a reader to adjust the speed, now AI recognition subtitles are very common, the reader also evolved into the script will follow my words run (used readers will know how convenient this is), greatly speeding up the efficiency of recording videos.\nIt is also a technology derived from AI speech recognition: AI editing. Although it is not completely free from manual work, the editor is now editing by reading the text, without the need to listen with ears, which saves a lot of effort.\nMusic and images can be generated by AI, saving a lot of time to find materials and reducing the risk of copyright infringement.\nAs for the job that my friends are looking for, such as document processing and answering e-mail, I just write a SOP file to feed the robot, and it can do it flawlessly, and there is no need to rest for 24 hours.\nIt doesn \u2019 t matter if what is said above is not understood, in simple terms, I used to find two or three more people to deal with the process of chores, and it was replaced by AI, and AI did well and fast.\nAfter all, it was all simple work.\n\u25b2 Document processing, e-mail and other things, as long as you write a SOP file to feed the robot, it can do flawless, and 24 hours without rest.\n(Chart / CFP)\nMy friend is angry after hearing it.\nI said, but I still need someone to help me, because I \u2019 m saving a lot of time now, have more capacity, and have the opportunity to make more money.\nDo you do business sponsorship? Do you write creative scripts that are popular with young people? Do you have experience in IP marketing?\nHe was frustrated and said that he would not be those, as if he could only be eliminated.\nThen he complained to me, saying that Taiwan's industry is serious, only the technology industry can make money, and other people live in deep water.\nIn fact, every technological innovation is like this, the British textile industry in the 19th century industrialization, a group of textile workers are also very angry at their loss of work, in the factory to destroy the loom.\nThese people are called Luddites. Now Luddites have become synonymous with opposition to technological progress. Most people also know that Luddites are marginal beings who will eventually die.\nBut it is obviously not accurate to attribute the fierce competition to the struggle for literature. In the example above, I am also a writer, but my property has leapt with the industrial revolution.\nThe difference is that I did two things: the first is the investment trend, and the second is that I treat AI as extremely cheap capital and use it to make money.\nBut I have taken advantage of resources, like I do not mix badly, will mix better, and mixed badly, will only mix worse.\nTimes change too fast, now this environment can not guarantee that you listen carefully to the classroom to teach those textbooks out of the society to eat, talent needs a flexible brain, as well as a variety of information judgment, to keep up with the pace of faster and faster technological development.\nThen it is true that some people can not do, some people from the past to the present, all want to do the simplest job, they either can not find a job, or they have to get a lower salary than the robot.\n\u25b2 In the era of rapid technological changes, the advantages of language have been greatly weakened.\n(Image from Google Translate)\nIn fact, education must be reformed as soon as possible, we need new departments, abolish some old departments, and now it seems like the pure language department of the college is really harming students, ensuring that they graduate and lose their jobs. (This sentence is easy to be misunderstood, it seems that I am belittling a particular department, I am not necessary.) And...\nIn my experience as a minor in Japanese at university, although I can also study culture and history, the advantages of language have been greatly weakened, and the teaching syllabus must be adjusted.)\nThe gap between the rich and the poor is inevitable, and policies can only try to avoid too many poor people, otherwise there will be social unrest.\nPut on the beautiful idea of science fiction, before the civil unrest of mankind, I hope that robots will take care of our food like mothers.\nCan you think about it? \u2013 I love this post.\nWelcome to join the \"cloud theory fan group\" to see more!\n\u25cf This article is authorized to be reproduced from the \u201cXIX \u201d Facebook page.\nThe above remarks do not represent the position of this website. Welcome to submit \"Cloud Theory\" to let high-quality good articles be seen by more people, please send to editor88 @ ettoday.net or click here to submit, this website reserves the right to delete the text.\nHot Click \u300b\n\u25ba Erotic websites can really be used for united warfare!\nYou want color, you want health, you don't want to be watched.\n\u25ba Not \"internal waters\", not \"territorial waters\", but \"territorial waters\".\n\u25ba Ammunition Preemptive Panic The DPP may be the initiator of the war.\n\u25ba Can Singapore \u2019 s 3-Day Weekend Pass Taiwan \u2019 s Work-Time Revolution?\nShare with friends:\nFollow us\nBack to the top.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0017.json.gz:23401","uncompressed_offset":489651767,"url":"forum.ettoday.net/news/2770863","warc_date":"2024-07-04T21:13:30.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372>","warc_url":"https://forum.ettoday.net/news/2770863"},"created":"2024-07-04T21:50:56.000Z","lang":"eng"},"34ca5e20-323b-4667-a65f-dc1f2d3e15a9_578793469":{"id":"34ca5e20-323b-4667-a65f-dc1f2d3e15a9_578793469","text":"You will not miss us!\n8,008 followers\nWhy robots will take your job, and what to do - panic or rejoice\nWhy robots will take away your profession.\nIncreasingly, you can hear about the challenges posed by automation and cybernization to existing professions today.\nAnd we are talking not only about unmanned vehicles and chatbots replacing call center operators, but also about programs that can calculate bank loans and insurance rates, depriving analysts and, moreover, neural networks that claim to compete with highly qualified and creative employees.\nExemption from routine or danger of unemployment?\nA cause for concern or long-awaited freedom?\nHistory of the problem\nMechanisms of ancient times.\nCompetition has always existed \u2013 professions disappeared and arose, people fought for jobs with each other and with technology, philosophers and economists built forecasts and tried to predict the prospects and are still doing it.\nFor example, you can assess how much automation threatens your profession and how quickly robots will replace you by using Will Robots Take My Job.\nAristotle was the first to think about the possibility of transferring \u201cwork \u201d to machines.\nIn the first book of his Politics, he suggested that they could evolve to such an extent that the need for human labor would disappear.\nFor him, quite in line with the views of work at the time, as something distracting from participation in public life and personal development, this was an extremely optimistic forecast.\n\u201cWork \u201d in ancient Greece was considered to be the lot of the lower classes, and the mechanisms would only liberate slaves, considered nothing but\u201c machines of flesh and blood. \u201d\nThe reorientation of the economy to the export of wool led to the introduction of a policy of \u201cenclosures \u201d.\nThe real competition of a sufficiently large mass of people technology for the first time was only more than a millennium and a half later in England.\nAt first, the reorientation of the economy to wool exports led to the introduction of a policy of \u201cfencing \u201d, in which landlords expelled farmers from the fields in order to free the territory for sheep grazing, which led to the first massive surge of\u201c unemployment \u201d \u2013 albeit not in the current sense.\nThe then arising vagrancy and poverty contemporary of these events, the Chancellor of England and philosopher Thomas More described the famous \"sheep ate people.\"\nHowever, after a few decades it became clear that no \u2013 not eaten.\nThe former peasants were absorbed by the growing cities, where they found a new job in textile manufactures, processing the same wool obtained from shearing sheep.\nThis was the first example of how, by taking away one thing, \u201ctechnology \u201d is able to offer something different.\nBut we must admit: the process of urbanization was painful, the work that replaced the cultivation of land turned out to be hard and dirty, the gap with the traditional way of life was very traumatic, and the population of England as a result of hunger and the fight against vagrancy, which was conducted, including the use of gallows, decreased, according to some estimates by 30% (to understand the scale - the Soviet Union during the Second World War lost \"only\" 15% of the population).\nWorkers in a textile factory, late 18th century.\nThe next episode of the confrontation between people and technology occurred a century later in the same field of light industry - the invention in 1785 by Edmund Cartwright of a mechanical loom increased labor productivity forty times.\nJobs that had just been lost were once again lost.\nBut again temporarily \u2013 after spinning machines, others appeared and all of them demanded new resources, and their extraction \u2013 new types of labor.\nManufactures were replaced by factories, and muscle strength by the power of steam obtained from coal.\nMachine Destroyers\nThe Luddite movement.\nThis time, the changes that occurred were met with bayonets - there was a movement of Luddites.\nSabotage of work and direct action: attacks on factories and the destruction of machines caused a harsh reaction of the state, which sent troops to suppress the \u201carmy of Ned Ludd \u201d.\nIt is characteristic that no one at the top bothered to convey to the workers the idea that there will still be work for them, even if not the one to which they had time to get used.\nThe fact is that the \u201ctop \u201d themselves at that time did not think too much about how all this was arranged, and people were perceived as expendable material, while the inertia of consciousness of ordinary workers who had just recovered from the transition from the agrarian to the urban way of life was also very high.\nThe First Industrial Revolution at the beginning of the 18th century.\nThe theoretical basis for the interaction of technological innovations and the masses of labor began to be summed up only by economists and philosophers of the middle of the XIX century.\nThey were the first to suggest that the disappearance of certain types of work in the process of technological development entails the emergence of new ones, and \u201cwork \u201d as a whole is not something final, which may be\u201c not enough \u201d.\nThe First Industrial Revolution was in full swing and the optimism of its apologists only grew stronger over time.\nBy the end of the century, it seemed that progress would eliminate not only social problems and contradictions, but could also rid humanity of wars.\nHowever, while some spoke of the \"Luddite delusion\", others spoke of the \"enslavement of the masses\" and the need to hand over to the \"factory workers\", predicting that as long as the instruments of production are in the hands of the big proprietors, their employees will remain disenfranchised, and the lack of social security will cause explosions of unemployment at any moment.\nSecond wave\nThe Second Industrial Revolution.\nThe word \u201cunemployment \u201d came into being at that time.\nThe fact is that a peasant working in the fields or a craftsman who provides for the needs of himself and the small surrounding community could not face something like this - he himself formed his employment.\nWhen the scheme of selling labor on a strict schedule became mass within the framework of fulfilling a strictly regulated set of duties, the challenge arose to lose such an opportunity.\nThe Second Industrial Revolution was on the way.\nThe basics of streaming production were laid at the end of the 19th century, and by the beginning of the 20th century, the combination of Ford \u2019 s marketing strategy (he invented that the car was not an attribute of the elites, but a mass need) and the conveyor he introduced led to new changes that went beyond factories and factories.\nOn January 18, 1886, the first car invented by Karl Benz was released.\nIt was the emergence of technology on the streets of cities that brought a new wave of competition.\nLook at the photos of the streets of the beginning of the last century: here they are dammed with carts, among which a lonely clumsy car is trying to maneuver, but ten years later, the only horse frightened by the roar of engines and sobbing of klaxons is clutching to the sidewalks.\nHere it will be important to note how unpredictable this jump became: \u201cAt the beginning of the 20th century, the French Academy warned about an environmental disaster, which inevitably should lead to the accumulation of horse manure associated with the development of horse-drawn transport in Paris, \u201d recalls, reasoning about the prediction of the future Stanislav Lem.\nHowever, note: in those regions where human labor is cheaper, technology can not replace it, as we are shown, for example, rickshaws, until recently used their own muscle power and only with a sharp drop in the cost of small vehicles motorized.\nA more modern example is \u201ccomputer rickshaws \u201d \u2013 hundreds of thousands of low-skilled Chinese, hacked captchas all day, because their work costs less than the introduction of scripts.\nTechnological unemployment\nThe line of the American unemployed during the Great Depression.\nIn the 1930s, Maynard Keynes, who gave the world the theory of the \u201csocial state \u201d, from the attempts of which many economies have not recovered so far, introduced the term\u201c technological unemployment \u201d into mass circulation.\nSince then, the debate about whether the introduction of new technological solutions and opportunities can create a long-term job crisis or whether everything is limited to repurposing, when obsolete professions are replaced by new ones, and it is enough for people to change or improve their skills.\nUntil the end of the last decade, most experts were inclined to believe that \u201ctechnological unemployment \u201d is always a temporary phenomenon, leading to the renewal and improvement of the professionalism of workers.\nMechanical labor was replaced by physical labor, the operator - a profession more status and highly paid than the worker, the reduction of costs leads to the release of time - these are the main theses sounded then.\nPessimistic views remained largely the domain of marginals, such as Theodore Kaczynski, famous for his terrorist struggle against progress under the name of Unabomber and primitive philosophers.\nPessimism\nThe first full-fledged computer in the USSR BESM-1.\nCautious voices expressing doubts about the correctness of this approach sounded even then.\nAnd if in one of his speeches in 1962, President Kennedy said that \u201cif people are able to invent new machines that take away their jobs, even more so are able to invent new jobs, \u201d then two years later, a letter from scientists and activists concerned with the problem of technological unemployment, sent to his successor, Lyndon Johnson, stated that\u201c a revolution in cybernetics will create a separate nation of poor, unskilled unemployed. \u201d.\nTheorists disputed the impossibility of long-term unemployment, as did Martin Ford in the book \u201cLight in the Tunnel: Automation, Acceleration of Technology and the Economy of the Future \u201d or Marshall Brains in\u201c Robotic Nation \u201d.\nGasne-Peter Martin and Harald Schumann, in their Global Trap, describe a society in which the labor of twenty percent of the population is enough for the world economy to continue to develop.\nThere are those who see it as a threat and a danger, like Paul Krugmann in his article \u201cSympathy for the Luddites \u201d or Frey and Osborne in\u201c The Future of Work. \u201d\nIn addition, in practice, it turned out that technology is not so freeing up time \u2013 for example, representatives of professions requiring high qualifications, at least in the United States today work more than 30 years ago, and technologies that provide remote access to working tools allow them not to break away from professional tasks and in their \u201cfree time \u201d.\nIt is also important that new jobs, as it was noticed at the beginning of the XXI century, are created not so much by technology as by the change in the way of life that they entail.\nSo in the mid-2010s, nine out of ten working people are employed in professions that did not exist a century earlier, but only 5% of the jobs that appeared from 1993 to 2013 are in high-tech areas, such as IT or telecom.\nHowever, the question is whether this does not mean that indirectly they still arise due to technologies that provide an opportunity for development for the service sector.\nIs it bad?\nA shot from the film \"I, Robot\" (2004).\nHarvard economics professor Lawrence Summers, who previously served as U.S. Treasury Secretary, said in 2014 that he no longer believes that automation will always create new jobs and that it is not some hypothetical possibility in the future; it is something that is emerging now.\nIn his opinion, the changes will be very global and will lead to mass unemployment not only among low-skilled employees, but also for \u201cblue \u201d and\u201c white \u201d collar workers, because \u201cthere are many reasons to think that the software revolution will be even more significant than the agrarian one. \u201d\nThe robot prepares food.\nHowever, this is what allows us to look to the future with optimism.\nSummers \u2019 s thought of the meaning of the digital revolution echoes the position of futurologist Alvin Toffler.\nAs early as 1970, in his book Future Shock, he wrote that by comparing the Digital Revolution with the Industrial Revolution, we downplay its significance and it would be more correct to draw a parallel with the exit of mankind from caves and the transition from hunting and gathering to agriculture and cattle breeding.\nPotentially, this means that humanity is on the verge of an unprecedented, unknown written history civilizational leap of colossal proportions.\nAnd, due to the fact that the speed of changes in the world has increased many times and now, the fact that in the case of the end of the Stone Age, took millennia, is being carried out in front of one, a maximum of a couple or three generations, this breakthrough, of course, will be painful.\nHowever, having reviewed the usual way of life, the attitude to it and their values, will not humanity be able to break through to the conditions of life, previously even unimaginable.\n\"Terminator 2: Judgment Day\" (1991).\nWe are easily accustomed to such changes in \u201cwork \u201d as freelancing and remote work, quite calmly came to a repeated change of professions, instead of a continuous, decades-long\u201c career \u201d and even were able to include them in your life, saying that this is the way to find yourself.\nSo is it not time to begin to accustom ourselves to the idea that, as economic historian Robert Skidelsky said, \u201cSooner or later we will run out of work \u201d?\nAfter all, freelancing and remote employment are about freedom, about leaving the \u201coffice slavery \u201d and searching for the way of life that is convenient for us.\nYes, to get used to the idea that the traditional \u201cwork \u201d is over and now we will have to independently invent what to occupy ourselves will not be easy.\nIt will require responsibility, but it is freedom.\nIsn \u2019 t it time for us, joyfully exclaiming \u201cGlory to the robots! \u201d, to go in search of our place in the new world?\nWhy robots will take away your profession.\nThe fact that it is not only about robots, but also about the \u201cwork \u201d itself and the possibility of life without it, about the risks associated with negative scenarios of confrontation between people and machines and the possibilities of overcoming them, we will talk in the next parts of the cycle.\nsource\nIf you liked this post, please share it with your friends:\nAnd don't forget:\nSubscribe to my Instagram\nLink to the original source\nPicture of the day\ntop","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0036.json.gz:146667","uncompressed_offset":578793469,"url":"vopros-ik.mirtesen.ru/blog/43449348445/Pochemu-robotyi-otnimut-u-vas-rabotu-i-chto-delat-panikovat-ili-","warc_date":"2021-12-16T11:07:43.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:34ca5e20-323b-4667-a65f-dc1f2d3e15a9>","warc_url":"https://vopros-ik.mirtesen.ru/blog/43449348445/Pochemu-robotyi-otnimut-u-vas-rabotu-i-chto-delat-panikovat-ili-"},"created":"2021-12-16T11:36:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":{"id":"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300","text":"The new is the old well forgotten.\nWhere in the Network there was a fashionable insult to the opponents of AI\nIn the Internet discourse, deep in the study of sarcastic comments of anonymous persons, you can find the term \"Luddite\".\nThis label is often referred to as people who dare to express the slightest inclination to inhibit the constant development of artificial intelligence (AI).\nRelated video\nInterestingly, such prominent figures as Elon Musk, Stephen Hawking and Bill Gates have been awarded the Luddite Award, which is recognition of their cautionary position regarding the potential dangers associated with artificial intelligence.\nDuring the ceremony, Robert D. Atkinson, the organizer of the award, noted: \u201cUnfortunately, luminaries such as Elon Musk and Stephen Hawking have contributed to the feverish refraction of hands about the impending apocalypse of artificial intelligence, \u201d writes IFLScience.\nIn Focus.Technology appeared its own Telegram-channel.\nSubscribe not to miss the latest and exciting news from the world of science!\nAtkinson also explained: \"Do we consider any of them personally Luddites?\nNo, of course not.\nThey are pioneers of science and technology.\nBut they and others have done a disservice to the public \u2014 and undoubtedly have helped and comforted the increasingly common neo-Luddist impulse in modern society \u2014 by demonizing AI in the popular imagination.\nBut how did the term come about?\nIts roots can be traced back to the early 1800s in England.\nBefore the industrial revolution, skilled craftsmen who knew a lot about textile production made clothes using their own machines and specialized tools.\nHowever, a situation arose when new technologies and methods of mass production appeared, as a result of which artisans were unable to compete.\nThe result was a movement whose purpose was the destruction of the textile industry and the destruction of new machines.\nAlthough there is some truth to this story, it does not reflect the whole essence of the Luddite movement.\nTheir actions were not driven solely by a reaction to new technologies; rather, they were a response to the profound transformations taking place in their professional activities.\nWhile it is true that they often attacked a knitting machine known as a stocking frame, as well as other mechanized fixtures, their main concern was the labor practices associated with these machines.\nKevin Binfield, editor of the Luddite and Compassionate Works, explained their motives: \"They simply wanted machines to produce high-quality goods, and that these machines employed workers who had been trained and received fair wages.\nIt was their only concern. \u201d\nThe nickname \"Luddites\" comes from the nickname \"Ned Ludd\", an apocryphal figure who allegedly sabotaged a textile factory in 1779, although historical evidence suggests that this man was most likely a fictional one.\nIn a 2007 paper, researcher David Linton explained: \u201cSome say that a young man, possibly with cognitive impairment, named Ned Ludd once misunderstood an order and accidentally broke his frame machine.\nOthers argue that this was done deliberately, in a fit of anger.\nWhatever the motive, it seems to have become a joke phrase that whenever the machine breaks, for whatever reason, you can say something like, \"Ludd must have been here.\"\nFrom this construction, it is a short step to the ironic application of the name Ludd to vandalism for political purposes. \"\nBetween 1811 and 1816, the Luddite movement held sporadic and somewhat unorganized protests, characterized by the destruction of cars and the burning of factories.\nIn response, the mill owners resorted to extreme measures, using deadly force against the Luddites.\nIn April 1812, there was a grim turning point in Huddersfield, where at least four people died at the hands of the mill owners.\nIn retaliation, the Luddites killed the owner of the mill, William Horsfall, who boldly declared his intention to \"smear himself with Luddite blood to the saddles.\"\nHorsfall was shot while sitting on his horse.\nFaced with these uprisings, the government immediately sent thousands of soldiers to quell the protests.\nMoreover, they adopted a law according to which the breakdown of cars was subject to the death penalty or sending to colonies.\nSubsequently, the movement dissipated, but the stable expression \"Luddite\" could not accurately convey the ideals and goals of the Luddites.\nPreviously, Focus wrote about the first IPSO in the history of mankind.\nIt turns out that it was invented in Babylon and it concerns the Flood.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:112701","uncompressed_offset":370300,"url":"focus.ua/technologies/568281-novoe-eto-horosho-zabytoe-staroe-otkuda-v-seti-poyavilsya-modnoe-oskorblenie-dlya-protivnikov-ii","warc_date":"2023-05-24T09:27:51.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e>","warc_url":"https://focus.ua/technologies/568281-novoe-eto-horosho-zabytoe-staroe-otkuda-v-seti-poyavilsya-modnoe-oskorblenie-dlya-protivnikov-ii"},"created":"2023-05-24T09:27:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":{"id":"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062","text":"Brian Merchant, author: \u201cLuddites are more dangerous to the rich than Robin Hood\u201d\n\nThe Luddites have been a great historical resource. Any showy enemy of anything that looked like technological progress has been called a Luddite. Today with generative artificial intelligence and its critics, the word has been revived. The author and journalist Brian Merchant (Iowa City, USA, 1983) saw it coming and has written a book that reviews the Luddite revolt in England at the beginning of the 19th century and its similarities with current technologies: Blood in the Machine (Blood in the Machine, currently without a planned edition in Spanish) thus explores the origins of the current revolt against big technology.\n\nAlthough the book has appeared in the midst of the AI \u200b\u200bhype, Merchant began his research a decade ago: \u201cUber was growing and it was beginning to be seen that it was having a hard impact on taxi drivers, I heard the term Luddite from the pro-Uber sector and wrote an article titled You don't understand anything about Luddites\u201d. Now in his book he remembers that the Luddite revolt was a labor struggle, not anti-technology, at a time when unions were prohibited. In a conversation with EL PA\u00cdS from his residence in Los Angeles, Merchant clarifies the historical impact of the Luddites and the possible similar struggles that are being played today in Silicon Valley.\n\n1. The Luddites were not against progress\n\nThe labor revolt over the loss of rights was more important than the destruction of textile machines: \u201cThe biggest mistake about the Luddites is to say that they were against technology and progress,\u201d says Merchant. \u201cThey were against certain technologies because they recognized the way in which they were going to be used in their context against them as workers. It was a labor movement, against poverty, not anti-technology. The British Government began to mold them in this way almost immediately, it was keen to mock the Luddites and present the argument that they were against progress. It is very similar to how today people in positions of power in technology companies accuse those who complain about poor working conditions. It's the same story for 200 years.\u201d\n\nThe book quotes a phrase from historian Eric Hobsbawm that explains this stage: \u201cIt was collective bargaining through riots.\u201d According to Merchant, this tactic in a workers' struggle was very powerful for two reasons: \u201cFirst, it was symbolic because everyone understood that what they were destroying was not just a machine. It was also the specific machine used to transfer wealth from the workers to the employer. Second, it was useful because they destroyed the equipment that businessmen needed.\u201d\n\n2. Why Robin Hood is better accepted than Ned Ludd\n\nNed Ludd was a legendary character. No one knows for sure if he existed. It was the legend of a teenager who would have broken the first machines at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution. In 1811, rebellious workers used his legendary name to sign letters and further scare: \u201cLudd probably never existed. But the incarnation of it would become a mascot, an organizational tool, a wink: a powerful 19th-century meme,\u201d Merchant writes.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The Commander of the Land Forces meets in Muscat a number of Omani military leaders\n\nLudd lived near Nottingham (United Kingdom), like another legendary figure who has been better treated by history. There must be a reason, says Merchant: \u201cThe Luddites organized a popular and powerful rebellion. People wrote popular songs about them. They were like Robin Hood. But it is interesting that Robin Hood has endured as a positive light, while the Luddites have not. He suggests that the myth of Ned Ludd is in some ways more dangerous to the elites and the wealthy than that of Robin Hood, which is a little more nebulous and open. The Luddites say: go ahead and break the machines of your oppression. Robin Hood says: steal from the rich and give to the poor. \u201cI think that\u2019s a little more tolerable.\u201d\n\n3. How are they similar to today's problems?\n\nThe background of the book is that the history of the Luddites is similar to what happens today in Silicon Valley, where a small group of corporations dominate new technologies. \u201cThe way technologies are developed has basically not changed. You have a handful of people with access to enough capital or political influence to be able to build a factory and use automation technologies. \u201cBack then, the most aggressive owners didn\u2019t ask anyone how to find a way to make this a win-win.\u201d\n\nMerchant has received criticism for equating the great businessmen of 19th century England with 21st century America. But there are details that he does not see that far away: \u201cThe technology development process is in some ways even more undemocratic today than then. There is this immense pool of capital available to Silicon Valley innovators through venture capital. Uber wasn't profitable for 10 years, but they had access to that capital. Did anyone really like that? Did it work for workers and delivery people? Nothing mattered, they just had more money and moved on.\u201d\n\nSee also\u00a0 Just the mystery","url":"https://pledgetimes.com/brian-merchant-author-luddites-are-more-dangerous-to-the-rich-than-robin-hood/"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1100","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1100","narrative_id":"1100"},"responses":[{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The term Luddite originated in the early 19th century in England, where it referred to a group of workers who destroyed machinery in cotton and woolen mills, believing it threatened their jobs."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"These workers were not against progress, but rather against certain technologies that they recognized would be used against them as workers, leading to poverty and loss of rights."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was a labor struggle, not an anti-technology movement, and it was a response to the impact of industrialization on their livelihoods."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, the term Luddite has been revived to describe individuals who are opposed to new technologies, such as artificial intelligence, and the impact it may have on their jobs and industries."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"However, it is essential to understand that being a Luddite does not necessarily mean being against technology or progress, but rather being cautious about the consequences of new technologies on society and the economy."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"According to Brian Merchant, author of \"Blood in the Machine\", the Luddites have been misunderstood, and their movement was not against technology, but against the exploitation of workers by the owners of the machines."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was a response to the fact that new technologies were being used to replace human workers, leading to unemployment and poverty."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, similar concerns are being raised about the impact of artificial intelligence and automation on jobs and industries."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"Some individuals may be opposed to new technologies because they believe it will lead to job loss, decreased wages, and increased inequality."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"Others may be concerned about the potential risks and unintended consequences of new technologies, such as bias in AI decision-making or the loss of traditional skills."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The destruction of textile machines by the Luddites in the 19th century was a desperate attempt to preserve their livelihoods and way of life."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"Similarly, in the 21st century, some individuals may be resistant to new technologies because they feel it will disrupt their industries and livelihoods."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"For example, taxi drivers who have seen their jobs threatened by ride-hailing apps like Uber may be opposed to the technology because it has disrupted their traditional way of working."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"In Taiwan, there is a concern that the industry is becoming too reliant on technology, and that other industries and workers are being left behind."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The term Luddite has become synonymous with opposition to technological progress, but it is essential to understand the historical context and the reasons behind the movement."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, it is crucial to have a nuanced understanding of the impact of new technologies on society and the economy, and to consider the potential consequences of technological advancements on different industries and workers."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"According to Atkinson, some pioneers of science and technology have done a disservice to the public by demonizing AI in the popular imagination, which has contributed to the neo-Luddist impulse in modern society."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was not just about destroying machines, but about the struggle for workers' rights and the protection of traditional industries."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, the debate around new technologies and their impact on society is ongoing, and it is essential to consider the perspectives of different stakeholders, including workers, industries, and policymakers."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, being a Luddite in the 21st century means being cautious about the consequences of new technologies and advocating for a more nuanced understanding of the impact of technological advancements on society and the economy."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The term Luddite originated in the early 19th century in England, where it referred to a group of workers who destroyed machinery in cotton and woolen mills, believing it threatened their jobs."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"These workers were not against progress, but rather against certain technologies that they recognized would be used against them as workers, leading to poverty and loss of rights."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was a labor struggle, not an anti-technology movement, and it was a response to the impact of industrialization on their livelihoods."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, the term Luddite has been revived to describe individuals who are opposed to new technologies, such as artificial intelligence, and the impact it may have on their jobs and industries."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"However, it is essential to understand that being a Luddite does not necessarily mean being against technology or progress, but rather being cautious about the consequences of new technologies on society and the economy."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"According to Brian Merchant, author of \"Blood in the Machine\", the Luddites have been misunderstood, and their movement was not against technology, but against the exploitation of workers by the owners of the machines."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was a response to the fact that new technologies were being used to replace human workers, leading to unemployment and poverty."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, similar concerns are being raised about the impact of artificial intelligence and automation on jobs and industries."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"Some individuals may be opposed to new technologies because they believe it will lead to job loss, decreased wages, and increased inequality."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"Others may be concerned about the potential risks and unintended consequences of new technologies, such as bias in AI decision-making or the loss of traditional skills."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The destruction of textile machines by the Luddites in the 19th century was a desperate attempt to preserve their livelihoods and way of life."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"Similarly, in the 21st century, some individuals may be resistant to new technologies because they feel it will disrupt their industries and livelihoods."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"For example, taxi drivers who have seen their jobs threatened by ride-hailing apps like Uber may be opposed to the technology because it has disrupted their traditional way of working."},{"citations":{"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":1.0},"text":"In Taiwan, there is a concern that the industry is becoming too reliant on technology, and that other industries and workers are being left behind."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"The term Luddite has become synonymous with opposition to technological progress, but it is essential to understand the historical context and the reasons behind the movement."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, it is crucial to have a nuanced understanding of the impact of new technologies on society and the economy, and to consider the potential consequences of technological advancements on different industries and workers."},{"citations":{"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":1.0},"text":"According to Atkinson, some pioneers of science and technology have done a disservice to the public by demonizing AI in the popular imagination, which has contributed to the neo-Luddist impulse in modern society."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"The Luddite movement was not just about destroying machines, but about the struggle for workers' rights and the protection of traditional industries."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":1.0},"text":"In the 21st century, the debate around new technologies and their impact on society is ongoing, and it is essential to consider the perspectives of different stakeholders, including workers, industries, and policymakers."},{"citations":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, being a Luddite in the 21st century means being cautious about the consequences of new technologies and advocating for a more nuanced understanding of the impact of technological advancements on society and the economy."}],"references":["22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767","6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670","b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300","1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062"],"documents":{"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670":{"id":"6edd43dc-2150-40f6-a9cd-aaef5f42da45_31467670","text":"Blog post\n\nWe cannot buy tomorrow \u2014 using stories to understand technology change\n\nBy Mark P. McDonald | December 03, 2021 | 0 Comments\n\ntech NO logyPersonal ObservationHuman AbilityFuture of High TechDigital Society\n\nThe dynamic and accelerating rate of change, disruption, societal concerns, etc can make it difficult to see what it all means, the direction we are heading in.\u00a0 Speculative fiction is one of the ways that people try to make sense out of what can appear to be senseless.\u00a0 Gartner instituted a special project called \u201cStories from Planet B\u201c.\u00a0 The goal was to use stories and other artifacts to help stakeholders envision preferred and plausible futures in a way that is transformative, inspiring and disrupting.\n\nHere is my story, you can find the others at \u201cStories from Planet B\u201d on Gartner.com\n\nEnjoy\n\nMark\n\nYOU CANNOT BUY TOMORROW\n\nTara sat down, rubbing her leg to work out a cramp she had picked up on the walk from her house. She had delayed this to the last minute. \u201cCan\u2019t turn ten \u2018till you talk to the old men,\u201d her brother reminded her.\n\nTara cleared her throat. \u201cQuestion: What was it like at the start?\u201c\n\nResponse: Project 2207, Darius Senna, aged 105, recalling the founding of Pantos.\n\nThe front of the room darkened. \u201cTara. The name means star,\u201d came a man\u2019s voice from the darkness.\n\n\u201cDad says it\u2019s also a lubricant that has gone bad, \u2018Tar \u2014 ahh!\u2019\u201d \u00a0The room got even darker.\n\n\u201cWe call ourselves Pantos. The fifth wave of Planet B colonists, B5, like the vitamin,\u201d the man\u2019s voice continued.\n\nDarius Senna walked out of the darkness. He was wearing a blue collarless shirt rolled up at the sleeves, dark pants and brown boots. Tara noticed his rough hands, and his face, lined from UV rays. A bench appeared. He sat down.\n\n\u201cWe were not the first. The first were the explorers. They discovered Planet B, determined it could support life, and summoned us to our new home. Then came ships, filled with those who could afford to leave Earth behind.\u201d\n\nSenna leaned back. Tara noticed the old style comms implant on his wrist. \u201cSix centuries ago, the English sent ships carrying goldsmiths, jewelers, governors and soldiers to Jamestown. They sought to civilize their \u2018new world.\u2019 Likewise, the first ships to Planet B carried engineers bankers, officials \u2014 the cream of a curdled civilization.\u201d\n\nLooking out the window, Darius continued: \u201cThose first ships were technological marvels. Gossamer solar sails, filled with technology and terraforming equipment. They landed in the northern hemisphere of Planet B. When their technology failed, they starved, just like the colonists at Jamestown.\u201d\n\nHe paused and looked at Tara. \u201cAfter three more waves, some of them are still around, eating from waste regenerators, asking their tech why it doesn\u2019t work. We don\u2019t see them much. We think about them even less.\u201d Darius leaned forward, clasping his hands, just like Tara\u2019s father did when making a point. \u201cWe Pantos understand \u2014 the physical world feeds the digital world. When the physical does not work, the digital does not matter.\u201d\n\n\u201cOld Earth technology changed in the early 21st century. It turned inward. It became obsessed with experience, entertainment and consumption.\u201d His face hardened. \u201cBefore then, technology had made people\u2019s lives better. Then society went digital, and consumption mattered more.\u201d\n\nDarius unclasped his hands. \u201cData replaced reason. People focused on themselves. Technology meant looking down at a screen, not up at the world around them. People thought it was wonderful. Screens made them feel better.\u201d\n\nHe leaned back. Tara noticed the scar down the inside of his left arm. No one had scars anymore, not since the invention of Dermaplast. Darius saw her staring and, almost under his breath, said: \u201cWith their narrow datasets, myopic algorithms and self-centered beliefs, they couldn\u2019t see what was really coming. And they never did.\u201d\n\n\u201cI had just turned twenty-seven,\u201d Darius said. He paused, lost in a memory.\n\nHe resumed, \u201cWe Pantos are not Luddites. We are some of the finest innovators and engineers humanity has ever known. Old Earth technologies were advanced, but consumptive. They were great for solving little problems. Distributing products instantaneously, keeping their users\u2019 attention, showing each other how successful they were.\u201d\n\n\u201cBut when the big problems came, technology could not handle it. The heat, the drought, the pandemics, the inequalities, the authoritarian states. This was the world as it really was, not how it appeared online. Their technologies spent what resources they had, but could not create more. When their inherited wealth dried up, it all fell apart.\u201d\n\n\u201cYou know why we Pantos tell each other, \u2018You can\u2019t buy \u2026\u201d\n\n\u201c\u2026 Tomorrow,\u201d Tara finished. She heard that at least ten times a month.\n\n\u201cRight,\u201d Darius replied. \u201cWe say that when it\u2019s time to get to work.\u201d\n\n\u201cThe \u2018northerners\u2019 brought Earth\u2019s ethos of control and exploitation. Digital entertainment, not physical engagement. They binged on culture as they starved and froze to death. If you go up north you can see the graves of trillionaires, and screens looping videos demonstrating their importance.\u201d Darius went silent.\n\nTara waited, unsure of what to do next. \u201cIf we are not the first, then when did we get here?\u201d\n\nDarius looked Tara directly in the face. \u201cWe came in the last wave. We came on outdated ships driven by ions. The ships were cannibalized once we landed on the southern hemisphere, far from the first four failures.\u201d\n\nHe smiled, \u201cThe first waves came to Planet B in space limos. Pantos came in space beaters.\u201d\n\n\u201cPantos went to work. Our technology fits our hands, not our eyes. We built our homes, rather than having them printed. Building them ourselves proved we were here to stay. Doing things yourself teaches you the true costs and benefits of your actions.\u201d\n\nHe paused for a moment, and said: \u201cTara, remember to feed the Briax when you get home.\u201d\n\nShe knew. Doing builds ownership and responsibility; consuming builds nothing but your waistline.\n\nDarius resumed: \u201cTechnology is part of our agency. Planet B sustains life, but we are building a world to ensure our minds stay broad; we think before we act. We make mistakes, like we did at Junction.\u201d\n\nHe rubbed the inside of his left arm.\n\n\u201cFailure is acceptable when we learn from it. Unacceptable when it is a cost of doing business, or called an externality.\u201d\n\n\u201cWe stay strong, acknowledging challenges and celebrating progress. Technology encourages contribution, not consumption. Contribution brings meaning. Meaning motivates innovation and improvement. If it does not work for all of us, then it does not work well enough for any of us. We have much work to do. You know\u2026\u201d\n\n\u201cYou can\u2019t buy tomorrow,\u201d Tara repeated, reflexively.\n\nThe room brightened. Senna was gone, as was the bench. A woman\u2019s voice spoke up. \u201cCongratulations, Tara. Welcome to your next decade.\u201d\n\nTara stood up. As she was leaving, she thought she heard the woman say: \u201cAnother turning ten. A blessing.\u201d\n\n\u201cYes,\u201d came Senna\u2019s reply. \u201cOld enough to understand, and young enough to care.\u201d","url":"https://blogs.gartner.com/mark-mcdonald/2021/12/03/we-cannot-buy-tomorrow-using-stories-to-understand-technology-change/"},"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767":{"id":"22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372_489651767","text":"Does AI make the arts poorer?\nThe real difference between the rich and the poor is the human mind.\n\u25b2 Since we have AI tools, we can do things quickly and well with a simple prompt, and the cost is low. (Illustration / Reuters)\n2nd / Podcaster\nI had a friend who had been unemployed for a while and asked me if I had a job for him to do, such as simple things like keeping an account and sorting out documents.\nI said, if you asked me two years earlier, there must be, but unfortunately not now.\nIn the past, those chores took time, since the AI tool, as long as the simple prompt can be completed, the monthly fee is only a few hundred yuan, two or three hundred hourly wage students may not do so well.\nHe listened to me, didn \u2019 t believe it, and was curious to ask me how I use AI now.\nIn fact, the application is too broad and too complicated. To make him understand it as soon as possible, I cite my entire workflow as an example.\nFor example, when writing an article, in the stage of collecting materials, AI helps me to make notes of books / meetings / lectures / courses with speech, and the content is accurate and the grammar is strict. It can also be converted into various forms of charts, different lengths and various articles.\nAt the writing stage, I will discuss with AI what different topics can be cut into perspective, such as this article I want to know how AI is changing our society, ask it to help me summarize the main views on the Internet, and I will continue to ask for some details, and also ask it to grab the latest data for me.\nNext, before po comes to the community, ask it to help me modify the typos and punctuation, the correction only takes a few seconds, and the text creation is basically completed.\nI asked my friend, do you think you can do better, faster and cheaper than AI?\n\u25b2 AI can help users to take notes with voice, and the content of speech to text is accurate and the grammar is strict. It can also be converted into various forms of charts, different lengths and various articles.\n(Chart / CFP)\nNext, the image creation.\nNow many devices, including WebCam and Monocular, the camera can lock the portrait to move in small amplitude, and even deliberately create a natural hand shake, self-portrait images are becoming more and more dependent on others.\nBefore the oral video, mainly rely on improvisation or reading, the former plays subtitles until the hand is broken, the latter has to get a reader to adjust the speed, now AI recognition subtitles are very common, the reader also evolved into the script will follow my words run (used readers will know how convenient this is), greatly speeding up the efficiency of recording videos.\nIt is also a technology derived from AI speech recognition: AI editing. Although it is not completely free from manual work, the editor is now editing by reading the text, without the need to listen with ears, which saves a lot of effort.\nMusic and images can be generated by AI, saving a lot of time to find materials and reducing the risk of copyright infringement.\nAs for the job that my friends are looking for, such as document processing and answering e-mail, I just write a SOP file to feed the robot, and it can do it flawlessly, and there is no need to rest for 24 hours.\nIt doesn \u2019 t matter if what is said above is not understood, in simple terms, I used to find two or three more people to deal with the process of chores, and it was replaced by AI, and AI did well and fast.\nAfter all, it was all simple work.\n\u25b2 Document processing, e-mail and other things, as long as you write a SOP file to feed the robot, it can do flawless, and 24 hours without rest.\n(Chart / CFP)\nMy friend is angry after hearing it.\nI said, but I still need someone to help me, because I \u2019 m saving a lot of time now, have more capacity, and have the opportunity to make more money.\nDo you do business sponsorship? Do you write creative scripts that are popular with young people? Do you have experience in IP marketing?\nHe was frustrated and said that he would not be those, as if he could only be eliminated.\nThen he complained to me, saying that Taiwan's industry is serious, only the technology industry can make money, and other people live in deep water.\nIn fact, every technological innovation is like this, the British textile industry in the 19th century industrialization, a group of textile workers are also very angry at their loss of work, in the factory to destroy the loom.\nThese people are called Luddites. Now Luddites have become synonymous with opposition to technological progress. Most people also know that Luddites are marginal beings who will eventually die.\nBut it is obviously not accurate to attribute the fierce competition to the struggle for literature. In the example above, I am also a writer, but my property has leapt with the industrial revolution.\nThe difference is that I did two things: the first is the investment trend, and the second is that I treat AI as extremely cheap capital and use it to make money.\nBut I have taken advantage of resources, like I do not mix badly, will mix better, and mixed badly, will only mix worse.\nTimes change too fast, now this environment can not guarantee that you listen carefully to the classroom to teach those textbooks out of the society to eat, talent needs a flexible brain, as well as a variety of information judgment, to keep up with the pace of faster and faster technological development.\nThen it is true that some people can not do, some people from the past to the present, all want to do the simplest job, they either can not find a job, or they have to get a lower salary than the robot.\n\u25b2 In the era of rapid technological changes, the advantages of language have been greatly weakened.\n(Image from Google Translate)\nIn fact, education must be reformed as soon as possible, we need new departments, abolish some old departments, and now it seems like the pure language department of the college is really harming students, ensuring that they graduate and lose their jobs. (This sentence is easy to be misunderstood, it seems that I am belittling a particular department, I am not necessary.) And...\nIn my experience as a minor in Japanese at university, although I can also study culture and history, the advantages of language have been greatly weakened, and the teaching syllabus must be adjusted.)\nThe gap between the rich and the poor is inevitable, and policies can only try to avoid too many poor people, otherwise there will be social unrest.\nPut on the beautiful idea of science fiction, before the civil unrest of mankind, I hope that robots will take care of our food like mothers.\nCan you think about it? \u2013 I love this post.\nWelcome to join the \"cloud theory fan group\" to see more!\n\u25cf This article is authorized to be reproduced from the \u201cXIX \u201d Facebook page.\nThe above remarks do not represent the position of this website. Welcome to submit \"Cloud Theory\" to let high-quality good articles be seen by more people, please send to editor88 @ ettoday.net or click here to submit, this website reserves the right to delete the text.\nHot Click \u300b\n\u25ba Erotic websites can really be used for united warfare!\nYou want color, you want health, you don't want to be watched.\n\u25ba Not \"internal waters\", not \"territorial waters\", but \"territorial waters\".\n\u25ba Ammunition Preemptive Panic The DPP may be the initiator of the war.\n\u25ba Can Singapore \u2019 s 3-Day Weekend Pass Taiwan \u2019 s Work-Time Revolution?\nShare with friends:\nFollow us\nBack to the top.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0017.json.gz:23401","uncompressed_offset":489651767,"url":"forum.ettoday.net/news/2770863","warc_date":"2024-07-04T21:13:30.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:22fb44af-b845-48a5-b5f8-d0e80f19a372>","warc_url":"https://forum.ettoday.net/news/2770863"},"created":"2024-07-04T21:50:56.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300":{"id":"b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e_370300","text":"The new is the old well forgotten.\nWhere in the Network there was a fashionable insult to the opponents of AI\nIn the Internet discourse, deep in the study of sarcastic comments of anonymous persons, you can find the term \"Luddite\".\nThis label is often referred to as people who dare to express the slightest inclination to inhibit the constant development of artificial intelligence (AI).\nRelated video\nInterestingly, such prominent figures as Elon Musk, Stephen Hawking and Bill Gates have been awarded the Luddite Award, which is recognition of their cautionary position regarding the potential dangers associated with artificial intelligence.\nDuring the ceremony, Robert D. Atkinson, the organizer of the award, noted: \u201cUnfortunately, luminaries such as Elon Musk and Stephen Hawking have contributed to the feverish refraction of hands about the impending apocalypse of artificial intelligence, \u201d writes IFLScience.\nIn Focus.Technology appeared its own Telegram-channel.\nSubscribe not to miss the latest and exciting news from the world of science!\nAtkinson also explained: \"Do we consider any of them personally Luddites?\nNo, of course not.\nThey are pioneers of science and technology.\nBut they and others have done a disservice to the public \u2014 and undoubtedly have helped and comforted the increasingly common neo-Luddist impulse in modern society \u2014 by demonizing AI in the popular imagination.\nBut how did the term come about?\nIts roots can be traced back to the early 1800s in England.\nBefore the industrial revolution, skilled craftsmen who knew a lot about textile production made clothes using their own machines and specialized tools.\nHowever, a situation arose when new technologies and methods of mass production appeared, as a result of which artisans were unable to compete.\nThe result was a movement whose purpose was the destruction of the textile industry and the destruction of new machines.\nAlthough there is some truth to this story, it does not reflect the whole essence of the Luddite movement.\nTheir actions were not driven solely by a reaction to new technologies; rather, they were a response to the profound transformations taking place in their professional activities.\nWhile it is true that they often attacked a knitting machine known as a stocking frame, as well as other mechanized fixtures, their main concern was the labor practices associated with these machines.\nKevin Binfield, editor of the Luddite and Compassionate Works, explained their motives: \"They simply wanted machines to produce high-quality goods, and that these machines employed workers who had been trained and received fair wages.\nIt was their only concern. \u201d\nThe nickname \"Luddites\" comes from the nickname \"Ned Ludd\", an apocryphal figure who allegedly sabotaged a textile factory in 1779, although historical evidence suggests that this man was most likely a fictional one.\nIn a 2007 paper, researcher David Linton explained: \u201cSome say that a young man, possibly with cognitive impairment, named Ned Ludd once misunderstood an order and accidentally broke his frame machine.\nOthers argue that this was done deliberately, in a fit of anger.\nWhatever the motive, it seems to have become a joke phrase that whenever the machine breaks, for whatever reason, you can say something like, \"Ludd must have been here.\"\nFrom this construction, it is a short step to the ironic application of the name Ludd to vandalism for political purposes. \"\nBetween 1811 and 1816, the Luddite movement held sporadic and somewhat unorganized protests, characterized by the destruction of cars and the burning of factories.\nIn response, the mill owners resorted to extreme measures, using deadly force against the Luddites.\nIn April 1812, there was a grim turning point in Huddersfield, where at least four people died at the hands of the mill owners.\nIn retaliation, the Luddites killed the owner of the mill, William Horsfall, who boldly declared his intention to \"smear himself with Luddite blood to the saddles.\"\nHorsfall was shot while sitting on his horse.\nFaced with these uprisings, the government immediately sent thousands of soldiers to quell the protests.\nMoreover, they adopted a law according to which the breakdown of cars was subject to the death penalty or sending to colonies.\nSubsequently, the movement dissipated, but the stable expression \"Luddite\" could not accurately convey the ideals and goals of the Luddites.\nPreviously, Focus wrote about the first IPSO in the history of mankind.\nIt turns out that it was invented in Babylon and it concerns the Flood.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:112701","uncompressed_offset":370300,"url":"focus.ua/technologies/568281-novoe-eto-horosho-zabytoe-staroe-otkuda-v-seti-poyavilsya-modnoe-oskorblenie-dlya-protivnikov-ii","warc_date":"2023-05-24T09:27:51.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b37e4db6-8ec9-43ae-99d0-b3eda339940e>","warc_url":"https://focus.ua/technologies/568281-novoe-eto-horosho-zabytoe-staroe-otkuda-v-seti-poyavilsya-modnoe-oskorblenie-dlya-protivnikov-ii"},"created":"2023-05-24T09:27:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":{"id":"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062","text":"Brian Merchant, author: \u201cLuddites are more dangerous to the rich than Robin Hood\u201d\n\nThe Luddites have been a great historical resource. Any showy enemy of anything that looked like technological progress has been called a Luddite. Today with generative artificial intelligence and its critics, the word has been revived. The author and journalist Brian Merchant (Iowa City, USA, 1983) saw it coming and has written a book that reviews the Luddite revolt in England at the beginning of the 19th century and its similarities with current technologies: Blood in the Machine (Blood in the Machine, currently without a planned edition in Spanish) thus explores the origins of the current revolt against big technology.\n\nAlthough the book has appeared in the midst of the AI \u200b\u200bhype, Merchant began his research a decade ago: \u201cUber was growing and it was beginning to be seen that it was having a hard impact on taxi drivers, I heard the term Luddite from the pro-Uber sector and wrote an article titled You don't understand anything about Luddites\u201d. Now in his book he remembers that the Luddite revolt was a labor struggle, not anti-technology, at a time when unions were prohibited. In a conversation with EL PA\u00cdS from his residence in Los Angeles, Merchant clarifies the historical impact of the Luddites and the possible similar struggles that are being played today in Silicon Valley.\n\n1. The Luddites were not against progress\n\nThe labor revolt over the loss of rights was more important than the destruction of textile machines: \u201cThe biggest mistake about the Luddites is to say that they were against technology and progress,\u201d says Merchant. \u201cThey were against certain technologies because they recognized the way in which they were going to be used in their context against them as workers. It was a labor movement, against poverty, not anti-technology. The British Government began to mold them in this way almost immediately, it was keen to mock the Luddites and present the argument that they were against progress. It is very similar to how today people in positions of power in technology companies accuse those who complain about poor working conditions. It's the same story for 200 years.\u201d\n\nThe book quotes a phrase from historian Eric Hobsbawm that explains this stage: \u201cIt was collective bargaining through riots.\u201d According to Merchant, this tactic in a workers' struggle was very powerful for two reasons: \u201cFirst, it was symbolic because everyone understood that what they were destroying was not just a machine. It was also the specific machine used to transfer wealth from the workers to the employer. Second, it was useful because they destroyed the equipment that businessmen needed.\u201d\n\n2. Why Robin Hood is better accepted than Ned Ludd\n\nNed Ludd was a legendary character. No one knows for sure if he existed. It was the legend of a teenager who would have broken the first machines at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution. In 1811, rebellious workers used his legendary name to sign letters and further scare: \u201cLudd probably never existed. But the incarnation of it would become a mascot, an organizational tool, a wink: a powerful 19th-century meme,\u201d Merchant writes.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The Commander of the Land Forces meets in Muscat a number of Omani military leaders\n\nLudd lived near Nottingham (United Kingdom), like another legendary figure who has been better treated by history. There must be a reason, says Merchant: \u201cThe Luddites organized a popular and powerful rebellion. People wrote popular songs about them. They were like Robin Hood. But it is interesting that Robin Hood has endured as a positive light, while the Luddites have not. He suggests that the myth of Ned Ludd is in some ways more dangerous to the elites and the wealthy than that of Robin Hood, which is a little more nebulous and open. The Luddites say: go ahead and break the machines of your oppression. Robin Hood says: steal from the rich and give to the poor. \u201cI think that\u2019s a little more tolerable.\u201d\n\n3. How are they similar to today's problems?\n\nThe background of the book is that the history of the Luddites is similar to what happens today in Silicon Valley, where a small group of corporations dominate new technologies. \u201cThe way technologies are developed has basically not changed. You have a handful of people with access to enough capital or political influence to be able to build a factory and use automation technologies. \u201cBack then, the most aggressive owners didn\u2019t ask anyone how to find a way to make this a win-win.\u201d\n\nMerchant has received criticism for equating the great businessmen of 19th century England with 21st century America. But there are details that he does not see that far away: \u201cThe technology development process is in some ways even more undemocratic today than then. There is this immense pool of capital available to Silicon Valley innovators through venture capital. Uber wasn't profitable for 10 years, but they had access to that capital. Did anyone really like that? Did it work for workers and delivery people? Nothing mattered, they just had more money and moved on.\u201d\n\nSee also\u00a0 Just the mystery","url":"https://pledgetimes.com/brian-merchant-author-luddites-are-more-dangerous-to-the-rich-than-robin-hood/"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1101","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1101","narrative_id":"1101"},"responses":[{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The Mozart Effect, a concept that suggests listening to Mozart's music can temporarily improve cognitive performance, has been a topic of interest in recent research."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Studies have investigated the impact of Mozart's music on cognitive tasks, including spatial reasoning, but the results are not conclusive."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"A recent study found that listening to background classical music, including Mozart, while performing memory tasks neither improves nor impairs learning levels among people with mild cognitive impairment."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"However, the study also found that listening to \"high-arousal\" music may have a positive effect on people who are accustomed to using music as an emotional regulator in their everyday lives."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"Another study dispelled the myth that Mozart's music, specifically his major sonata KV448, can alleviate the symptoms of epilepsy."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The results of these studies suggest that the Mozart Effect may be more complex than previously thought and may depend on individual differences and how music is listened to."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The research also highlights the importance of considering interindividual parameters when investigating the impact of music on cognitive performance."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current evidence does not support the idea that listening to Mozart's music, including his Sonata for Two Pianos in D Major, can temporarily improve cognitive performance."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Further research is needed to fully understand the relationship between music and cognitive function."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The Mozart Effect, a concept that suggests listening to Mozart's music can temporarily improve cognitive performance, has been a topic of interest in recent research."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Studies have investigated the impact of Mozart's music on cognitive tasks, including spatial reasoning, but the results are not conclusive."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"A recent study found that listening to background classical music, including Mozart, while performing memory tasks neither improves nor impairs learning levels among people with mild cognitive impairment."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"However, the study also found that listening to \"high-arousal\" music may have a positive effect on people who are accustomed to using music as an emotional regulator in their everyday lives."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"Another study dispelled the myth that Mozart's music, specifically his major sonata KV448, can alleviate the symptoms of epilepsy."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The results of these studies suggest that the Mozart Effect may be more complex than previously thought and may depend on individual differences and how music is listened to."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The research also highlights the importance of considering interindividual parameters when investigating the impact of music on cognitive performance."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"Overall, the current evidence does not support the idea that listening to Mozart's music, including his Sonata for Two Pianos in D Major, can temporarily improve cognitive performance."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Further research is needed to fully understand the relationship between music and cognitive function."}],"references":["fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306","aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690"],"documents":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":{"id":"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690","text":"4/25/23 \u00b7 Research\n\nThe beneficial effects of music on memory may depend on how it is listened to\n\nThe initial results of the study of the 'Mozart effect' on neurodegeneration show that listening to classical music in the background has no benefits for learning\nThe research has been carried out with people experiencing mild cognitive impairment, and it did find individual differences when listening to 'high-arousal' music\n\nListening to 'high-arousal' music could have a positive effect on memory for people who are accustomed to using music as an emotional regulator (Image: Clem Onojeghuo, Unsplash)\n\nGiven the lack of effective treatments to counteract cognitive impairment, background music has traditionally been proposed as a possible therapeutic alternative for improving memory-related tasks. Its effect has long been the focus of debate, but this relationship has now been found to be possibly determined by new interindividual parameters, which means that it may be more complex than was previously thought. This is shown by research led by Marco Calabria, a researcher in the Cognitive Neurolab group of the Faculty of Health Sciences at the Universitat Oberta de Catalunya (UOC), who is now considering new experiments.\n\nThe initial results of the Mozart effect and memory in patients with cognitive impairment (MEM-COG) study, funded by the Spanish Ministry of Science and Innovation, suggest that listening to background classical music while performing memory tasks neither improves nor impairs learning levels among people with mild cognitive impairment (MCI). However, listening to more 'high-arousal' music was found to have a possible positive effect on people who are accustomed to using music as an emotional regulator in their everyday lives, which suggests there is potential for further hypotheses and research.\n\nThe study, which has been published as open access in the Journal of Alzheimer's Disease, was carried out with patients at the neuropsychology unit of Barcelona's Hospital de Sant Pau, and involved researchers at the hospital, Montreal's Concordia University and Madrid's Gregorio Mara\u00f1\u00f3n Health Research Institute.\n\nThere is no universal effect\n\n\"We found no general impact concerning the effect of music in terms of whether it had positive or negative effects on learning in cases of MCI, but we did find that it would be modulated for each individual. If people regularly use music as an emotional regulator in their daily life, such as to help them remain calm or for company, they will find it easier to obtain further benefits from music when they have to learn something new,\" explained Calabria, who has a PhD in Psychobiology.\n\nThe subjects of the study were people with mild amnestic cognitive impairment, i.e. they have memory problems as a result of an onset of neurodegeneration that is more specific in the parts of the brain dealing with aspects of learning and memory. The experiments consisted of observing 24 photographs of human faces. Participants were instructed to memorize them, and 10 minutes later, they were asked to look at a new series containing the previous 24 images and 24 new ones, in order to attempt to identify the ones that they had already seen.\n\nA classical choice\n\nThe first test was performed with the subjects listening to classical music in the information consolidation phase but not in the recovery phase, while in the second exercise it was repeated with the auditory stimulus during both phases. However, no significant differences were observed in terms of results.\n\nClassical music was used in these exercises because \"it's a type of music that falls between relaxing and arousing, and has proven to be the most effective for enhancing memory\". Furthermore, the fact that it is instrumental reduces the interference (that can come from lyrics) with the content that the participants have to learn in the memory task.\n\nA ray of light\n\nHowever, Calabria's team wanted to carry out a third experiment using popular music which was considered arousing rather than relaxing, and after a preliminary study, they used an instrumental version of Un rayo de sol (A ray of light), by the group Los Diablos. In that experiment, according to Calabria, the results suggested that \"the use of music as a strategy for mood regulation is associated with better performance in memory tasks.\"\n\nOngoing research\n\nThis finding opens up the possibility of further research to continue exploring the role of interindividual preferences and attitudes towards music among patients with MCI. The group plans to continue the project until late 2024.\n\nDuring this time, it will investigate whether background music could be more useful in other cognitive domains, such as in attention and concentration in patients with Parkinson's disease. The experiments will also involve the use of a new infrared spectroscopy device in the Neuro Lab, one of the recently opened new laboratories at the UOC, which will show the activation at the cerebral level while cognitive processes are taking place. This will help to determine whether or not there are any alterations in the brain's modulation, in which areas this takes place, and whether it depends on the type of person studied, regardless of the level of response to music.\n\nIn overall terms, this will help to find a type of marker which determines the people most likely to benefit from music in cognitive tasks. \"The more we know about how background music shapes cognitive processes, the better the use we can make of music as a therapeutic tool in cognitive stimulation,\" concluded Calabria, an expert in the study of cognitive processes and a member of teaching staff on the UOC's Master's Degree in Neuropsychology.\n\nThis research project receives funding from the Ministry of Science and Innovation of the Government of Spain, and contributes to Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) number 3, Good health and well-being.\n\nReference article:\n\nCalabria, Marco et al. 'Background Music and Memory in Mild Cognitive Impairment: The Role of Interindividual Differences'. 1 Jan. 2023: 815 \u2013 829. DOI: 10.3233/JAD-221051\n\nPress contact\n\nS\u00f2nia Armengou Casanovas\nsarmengouc@uoc.edu\n+34 619 413 823\n\n\u00a0\n\nUOC R&I\n\nThe UOC's research and innovation (R&I) is helping overcome pressing challenges faced by global societies in the 21st century by studying interactions between technology and human & social sciences with a specific focus on the network society, e-learning and e-health.\n\nOver 500 researchers and more than 50 research groups work in the UOC's seven faculties, its eLearning Research programme and its two research centres: the Internet Interdisciplinary Institute (IN3) and the eHealth Center (eHC).\n\nThe university also develops online learning innovations at its eLearning Innovation Center (eLinC), as well as UOC community entrepreneurship and knowledge transfer via the Hubbik platform.\n\nOpen knowledge and the goals of the United Nations 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development serve as strategic pillars for the UOC's teaching, research and innovation. More information: research.uoc.edu.\n\nExperts UOC\n\nPress contact\n\nYou may also be interested in\u2026\n\nMost popular\n\nSee more on Research","url":"https://www.uoc.edu/en/news/2023/097-music-dementia-neurodegeneration"},"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":{"id":"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306","text":"Gazeta.ru on desktop\nfor quick access\nInstall\nNot now\nScientists have dispelled the myth that Mozart \u2019 s music helps with epilepsy\nScientists from the University of Vienna have dispelled the myth that Mozart \u2019 s major sonata KV448 can alleviate the symptoms of epilepsy.\nThe results of the study are presented in the journal Scientific Reports.\nAccording to the authors of the work, they could not find evidence of the above theory.\nIn the past, it was believed that Mozart \u2019 s music had many positive effects on a person, for example, it increases the intelligence of the fetus if a pregnant woman listened to it.\nRecently, a number of studies have shown that KV448 sonata alleviates symptoms in patients with epilepsy.\nIn their work, scientists analyzed these studies, as well as other scientific literature.\nAs it turned out, there is no reliable evidence of the beneficial effect of the melody.\nAccording to the authors, erroneous results could have been obtained due to selective reporting and small samples.\nShare:\nDownloading\nFound a bug?\nClose","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0007.json.gz:70161","uncompressed_offset":388565306,"url":"www.gazeta.ru/science/news/2023/03/07/19907317.shtml","warc_date":"2023-03-09T05:27:39.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94>","warc_url":"https://www.gazeta.ru/science/news/2023/03/07/19907317.shtml"},"created":"2023-03-09T05:51:52.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1102","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1102","narrative_id":"1102"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The Mozart Effect is a concept that suggests listening to Mozart's music can temporarily improve cognitive performance, especially in spatial reasoning tasks."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"This idea has been debated and researched extensively, with some studies supporting its validity and others questioning its effectiveness."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Recent research, led by Marco Calabria, a researcher in the Cognitive Neurolab group of the Faculty of Health Sciences at the Universitat Oberta de Catalunya (UOC), has shed new light on the Mozart Effect."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"The initial results of the Mozart effect and memory in patients with cognitive impairment (MEM-COG) study, funded by the Spanish Ministry of Science and Innovation, suggest that listening to background classical music while performing memory tasks neither improves nor impairs learning levels among people with mild cognitive impairment (MCI)."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"However, the study found that listening to more 'high-arousal' music was found to have a possible positive effect on people who are accustomed to using music as an emotional regulator in their everyday lives."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"This finding suggests that the Mozart Effect may be more complex than previously thought, and that individual differences play a significant role in its effectiveness."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"Another study, published in Scientific Reports, found that Mozart's music had no beneficial effect on patients with epilepsy, contradicting previous claims."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"The researchers analyzed existing studies and found no reliable evidence to support the claim that Mozart's music alleviates symptoms in patients with epilepsy."},{"citations":{"fa060162-28a6-44ed-bbed-4d6960038a94_388565306":1.0},"text":"This study highlights the importance of rigorous research and data-driven analysis in understanding the Mozart Effect."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"In contrast, a review of a piano concerto performance noted the unique contribution of each instrumental sonority to the overall sound, and the relation between the instrumental sonorities and the solo piano work."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"The reviewer also noted the intensity and ferocity of the passages, which suggests that Mozart's music can evoke strong emotions and reactions."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"However, this review does not provide empirical evidence to support the Mozart Effect, and its findings are subjective and anecdotal."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"A program featuring Mozart's K. 491 piano concerto and K. 504 symphony was praised for its adventurousness and the complementarity of the two pieces."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"The program was noted for its dramatic qualities and the listener's curiosity about other works in the Mozart catalog."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"However, this review also does not provide empirical evidence to support the Mozart Effect, and its findings are subjective and anecdotal."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"A study on concert arias, including Mozart's K. 505, found that the dramatic qualities of the interpretations left the listener curious about other works in the Mozart catalog."},{"citations":{"162803ca-ac98-4ad7-b8cc-505a0c32954e_201587229":1.0},"text":"However, this study does not provide empirical evidence to support the Mozart Effect, and its findings are subjective and anecdotal."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the Mozart Effect is a complex and multifaceted concept that requires further research and data-driven analysis to fully understand its effectiveness."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"While some studies suggest that listening to Mozart's music can have a positive effect on cognitive performance, others have found no beneficial effect."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Individual differences, such as the use of music as an emotional regulator, may play a significant role in the effectiveness of the Mozart Effect."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Therefore, it is essential to approach the Mozart Effect with a critical and nuanced perspective, recognizing both its potential benefits and limitations."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The Mozart Effect is a concept that suggests listening to Mozart's music can temporarily improve cognitive performance, especially in spatial reasoning tasks."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"This idea has been debated and researched extensively, with some studies supporting its validity and others questioning its effectiveness."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.0},"text":"Recent research, led by Marco Calabria, a researcher in the Cognitive Neurolab group of the Faculty of Health Sciences at the Universitat Oberta de Catalunya (UOC), has shed new light on the Mozart Effect."},{"citations":{"aab9ac42-0f5b-421c-ba74-5502d6d8eca1_450572690":1.