ity to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, then considered valuable as gold.\nCats have also earned the nickname \u201csunny eye \u201d due to their ability to see in the dark.\nThis property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology.\nArchaeological studies conducted at the ancient Egyptian necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa have uncovered the burial of crocodiles, one of which has been preserved in the form of a practically whole mummy, providing a unique look at the ancient rites and veneration of animals in this culture.\nAuthor Petr Deryabin\nPetr Deryabin \u2013 journalist, correspondent of Pravda.Ru news service","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:108288","uncompressed_offset":297891389,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/","warc_date":"2023-12-21T15:51:28.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/"},"created":"2023-12-21T16:02:19.000Z","lang":"eng"},"27682f1d-0698-47e1-89a2-7ddb74fe2db0_36164407":{"id":"27682f1d-0698-47e1-89a2-7ddb74fe2db0_36164407","text":"You will not miss us!\n8,117 followers\n10 amazing facts about hygiene in ancient Egypt\nWaxing and other hygiene procedures in ancient Egypt.\nThere is an erroneous opinion that in the ancient world people had a very vague idea of \u200b \u200b hygiene and they practically did not follow the purity and smell of their body.\nBut scientists believe that the ancient Egyptians were a very advanced civilization, not only in terms of construction technology, but also in terms of hygiene.\n1.\nMint Breath\nEgypt - the cradle of dentistry. / Photo: listverse.com\nHesi-Re is considered to be the first dentist in the world to work during the pharaoh Djoser around 1600 BC (during the Third Dynasty of Egypt).\nHowever, the first evidence of dentistry dates back to 3000 BC.\nA papyrus guide was found with detailed instructions on how to heal wounds in the mouth.\nIt was at this time that dental surgery was born.\nAnd \u201cfor those whose breath smelled as bad as the armpits of the lower class, \u201d granulated honey was recommended in combination with a decoction of herbs and spices.\n2.\nParasites\nHaircut as a way to combat parasites. / Photo: listverse.com\nThe Egyptians actively tried to fight pests and parasites.\nIn an attempt to get rid of head lice, men, women and children shaved their heads, and priests and other people from high society removed hair all over their bodies.\nBut in addition to temporary treatments such as haircuts, the Egyptians also used prototypes of repellents.\nFor example, they sprayed a solution of soda and salt in their homes to get rid of fleas.\n3.\nCircumcision\nCircumcision in Ancient Egypt. / Photo: listverse.com\nAlthough anthropologists disagree on the origin of circumcision of the foreskin, they believe that the ritual was practiced in Egypt as early as 4000 BC.\nMass circumcision ceremonies were held among young men under the age of 15 and were intended both for the rite of puberty and for the sake of purity.\nSome anthropologists claim that the procedure originated as a sign of desecration or slavery.\nIn fact, captive warriors in ancient Egypt used to be castrated, but this was often fatal.\nTherefore, the slaves began to simply cut off the foreskin.\n4.\nDeodorant\nSpices - deodorant in Egyptian. / Photo: listverse.com\nEgyptians are often credited with inventing the first deodorant.\nThey tried to get rid of the unpleasant smell of sweat with various spices such as citrus and cinnamon.\nBy mixing numerous fragrances, including flowering evergreen carob shrubs, they made natural deodorizing granules that were worn under their arms.\nIn addition, to get rid of the unpleasant smell, they shaved their hair under their arms.\n5.\nAncient recipes\nHygiene in Ancient Egypt: ancient recipes. / photo: caprizulka.ru\nTwo thousand years before Hesi-Re, the world \u2019 s first dentist, the Egyptians, as well as the Babylonians, used their own version of a toothbrush, which was made from twigs with soaked ends.\nThese primitive toothbrushes are found in tombs next to the mummified remains of their owners, which date back to 3500 BC.\nWhat \u2019 s even more surprising is that, 1,500 years before that, the Egyptians used toothpaste to brush their teeth.\nIn the National Library in Vienna, Austria, there is a collection of papyrus documents, in which you can find the world's oldest known recipe for toothpaste consisting of dried iris flower, salt, pepper and mint.\n6.\nAccessories\nHygiene in Ancient Egypt: accessories. / photo: listverse.com\nThe attention of the Egyptians to their appearance is evident from the contents of their graves.\nEven in the ancient kingdom with their owner buried a variety of cosmetic accessories.\nFor example, there were decorative studs and ridges made of ivory and silver, bronze tweezers to shape the eyebrows and gold razors.\nPolished copper mirrors with intricate graceful handles were also found everywhere, which were placed under the heads of the deceased or in front of their face.\n7.\nPreventive medicine\nHygiene in ancient Egypt: preventive medicine. / photo: bookpalace.com\nPreventive medicine was as important to the Egyptians as any other measure they took to preserve their health and prevent the spread of disease.\nIn this regard, they focused mainly on their diet.\nFor example, the Egyptians included in the diet of their workers onions, garlic and radishes, which are extremely rich in allistatin, allicin and raphanin - natural powerful antibiotics.\n8.\nEye makeup\nHygiene in Ancient Egypt: eye makeup. / photo: listverse.com\nCharming eye makeup, which became the epitome of ancient Egyptian glamour, actually served not only for vanity.\nWhen analyzing 52 samples of ancient cosmetics, scientists found that most of the lead-based substances used in Egyptian cosmetics increased the level of nitric oxide in human skin cells by 240%.\nImportantly, nitric oxide boosts the immune system to help fight disease.\nThis was of particular importance in tropical swampy areas such as the Nile, where eye infections were rampant.\n9.\nMedical knowledge\nHygiene in Ancient Egypt: medical knowledge. / photo: listverse.com\nIn the \"Ebers papyrus\" dating back to 1500 BC, the Egyptians described soap-like materials that were made with alkaline salts, as well as vegetable and animal fats.\nThis substance was used not only for washing, but also for the treatment of skin diseases.\nIn fact, the Ebers papyrus includes as many as 877 recipes, as well as the earliest documented description of tumors.\n10.\nFemale doctors\nHygiene in Ancient Egypt: female doctors. / photo: listverse.com\nAt a time when women were very limited in terms of freedom of choice, Egyptians differed from other societies in that educated women had the right to work in any field of their choice.\nWomen doctors most often engaged in obstetrics.\nAnd they used different things.\nFor example, the earliest known pregnancy test existed in the Egyptians, and it needed barley and spelt (wheat).\nWomen had to urinate on these grains for several days and if neither barley nor spelt began to germinate, it meant that the woman was not pregnant.\nInterestingly, modern scientists have confirmed that urine in non-pregnant women inhibits the growth of grains.\nsource\nIf you liked this post, please share it with your friends:\nAnd don't forget:\nSubscribe to my Instagram\nLink to the original source\nPicture of the day\ntop","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0013.json.gz:106250","uncompressed_offset":36164407,"url":"vopros-ik.mirtesen.ru/blog/43192492044/10-porazitelnyih-faktov-o-gigiene-v-Drevnem-Egipte","warc_date":"2022-05-07T19:52:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:27682f1d-0698-47e1-89a2-7ddb74fe2db0>","warc_url":"https://vopros-ik.mirtesen.ru/blog/43192492044/10-porazitelnyih-faktov-o-gigiene-v-Drevnem-Egipte"},"created":"2022-05-07T19:54:41.000Z","lang":"eng"},"44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199_660616524":{"id":"44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199_660616524","text":"Museum organizes events for visitors to see pet cats\nJuly 29, 2024 07: 15\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nVisitors lined up at the entrance of the Shanghai Museum with their pet cats.\nThe Shanghai Museum recently held the \"Top of the Pyramids: Ancient Egyptian Civilization Exhibition\", in which the People's Square Museum opened on Saturday (27th), the \"Museum Curious Night\" held on Saturdays, a series of nine shows.\nAt the first event, about 200 spectators and cute pet cats gathered at the venue to watch the exhibition.\nBefore the launch, many visitors with pet cats were waiting in line at the entrance of the Shanghai Museum, and about 200 cats were dressed up to attend, attracting many passers-by to stop and take photos.\nAmong them, the hairless cat held by Ms. Huo attracted the attention of many passersby.\nShe said that in order to prepare for the exhibition, she specially took the cat downstairs for a walk two days before the event began to help the cat adapt to the multi-person environment.\nVisitors can take photos with their pets in the Cat Temple area in the exhibition hall, and can also experience items such as \"Giant Cat Sculpture Photo\" and \"Cat Claw Interactive Message\".\nIn ancient Egyptian civilization, the mythical goddess of the cat's head, Bastard, was a symbol of conservation and spirituality, which matched the love of cats today.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0019.json.gz:21574","uncompressed_offset":660616524,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/cnnews/20240729/bkn-20240729071533028-0729_00952_001.html","warc_date":"2024-07-28T22:49:31.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/cnnews/20240729/bkn-20240729071533028-0729_00952_001.html"},"created":"2024-07-28T23:56:27.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1104","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1104","narrative_id":"1104"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"The ancient Egyptians had a profound reverence for cats, which is evident in their mythology, art, and daily life."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"This reverence was largely due to the cat's ability to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, a valuable commodity at the time."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The Egyptians also associated cats with the goddess Bast, who symbolized well-being, joy, love, and fertility."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"In addition to their practical uses, cats were also considered sacred animals, often depicted with divine qualities and associated with the gods."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The Egyptians believed that their gods could take different forms, including that of a cat, which further solidified the cat's importance in their culture."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The goddess Bast, for example, was often depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat's head, emphasizing the cat's spiritual significance."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The Egyptians' love and respect for cats were so great that they would often mummify and bury their deceased pets, providing them with a complex and honorable burial process."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"This practice was an integral part of their religious practice, highlighting the special status of cats in the eyes of the Egyptians."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"Archaeological studies have uncovered evidence of the ancient Egyptians' reverence for cats, including the burial of crocodiles and other animals at the necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"One of the most notable examples of this reverence is the mummification of a pet cat, which was a common practice among the ancient Egyptians."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The Egyptians' spiritual connection to cats was not limited to their role in mythology and art, but also extended to their daily lives, where cats were often kept as pets and cherished as members of the family."},{"citations":{},"text":"When a family cat died, the Egyptians would often shave their eyebrows as a sign of mourning, demonstrating the depth of their emotional connection to these animals."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The significance of cats in ancient Egyptian culture is also evident in their association with the sun and their ability to see in the dark, earning them the nickname \"sunny eye\"."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"This unique property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology, further solidifying their position in the culture."},{"citations":{"44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199_660616524":1.0},"text":"The ancient Egyptians' reverence for cats has also been noted in other cultures, including their modern-day descendants, who continue to celebrate the importance of cats in their lives."},{"citations":{"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":1.0},"text":"In fact, International Cat Day is celebrated on August 8, highlighting the importance of caring for and respecting our feline friends."},{"citations":{"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":1.0},"text":"The role of cats in human history is not limited to ancient Egypt, as they have played a significant role in various cultures and historical moments, from medieval Europe to modern-day societies."},{"citations":{"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":1.0},"text":"In medieval Europe, for example, cats were considered guardians of homes and farms due to their ability to keep rodent populations in check."},{"citations":{"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":1.0},"text":"Despite their importance, cats have also faced challenges and hardships throughout history, including persecution during the Middle Ages."},{"citations":{"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":1.0},"text":"However, their significance in human culture has endured, and they continue to be celebrated and cherished as beloved companions."},{"citations":{"1fc775dc-2141-4589-9133-510fabf35ecb_454309968":1.0},"text":"The Egyptians' spiritual connection to cats is also evident in their narrative heritage, where animals are often used to convey moral and philosophical messages."},{"citations":{"1fc775dc-2141-4589-9133-510fabf35ecb_454309968":1.0},"text":"The story of the cat who wears twins, for example, is a dominant belief in Upper Egypt, highlighting the importance of animals in the region's folklore."},{"citations":{"1fc775dc-2141-4589-9133-510fabf35ecb_454309968":1.0},"text":"The use of animals in storytelling is a common theme in Egyptian culture, where they are often used to convey complex ideas and emotions."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the ancient Egyptians' reverence for cats was deeply rooted in their mythology, art, and daily life, and their spiritual connection to these animals continues to be celebrated and studied today."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The significance of cats in ancient Egyptian culture is a testament to the importance of animals in human society, and their enduring legacy continues to inspire and fascinate us."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"The ancient Egyptians had a profound reverence for ca