968","text":"Mohammed Abdul Samea (Sharjah)\nThe 21st Sharjah International Narrator Forum concluded at Expo Centre Sharjah, while the events continue at the headquarters of the Sharjah Heritage Institute, where the Eastern Region activities were launched yesterday, on 25 and 26 September in Khorfakkan City in the Khorfakkan Literary Council, Al Dhaid City in the University of Sharjah Al Dhaid Branch, Kalba in the University of Sharjah - Kalba Branch, and Dibba Al Husn Sports Club. Sessions, activities, workshops and programs will be completed by default until 30 September on the social media of the Sharjah Heritage Institute.\nThe popular imagination.\nResearchers at the Sharjah International Narrator Festival yesterday read the image of the animal in Arab heritage narratives and children \u2019 s tales, and how this relates to the popular imagination and social belief, interested in investing this as a rich element of our Arab culture in different eras.\nThe seminar, which was part of a specialized focus of the 21st edition of the festival, was attended by Dr. Ahmed Bahey El Din Assassi, who talked about the animal image in ancient Egypt and the ancient Egyptians' interest in eternal life. He discussed the significance of animal symbols in the ancient Egyptian language and their connection with the prevailing doctrine that adopted animal sanctification, especially in the writing of this image on the walls of temples. in the context of numerous and varied comparisons.\nAwareness Messages\nFor her part, Dr. Wafa Mizghani spoke about the image of animals in children \u2019 s stories in Tunisia, stressing the role of these stories in bringing happiness to children who find them a way to vent and express feelings and joy, as well as awareness messages and knowledge of the positives and negatives through telling stories on the animal \u2019 s tongues. Onamir, Maezza Mazouna, and the Hanash Boy, \u201d and other stories.\nIn her paper, the Egyptian expert Dr. Nahla Imam talked about the Upper Egypt region, looking at the belief of the cat who wears twins, as a dominant belief related to some beliefs of African countries, and said that the human nature is looking for a means of optimism and pessimism, so the animal found an important heritage element for his psychological projections.\nShe explained that the belief indicates that one of the twins wears his soul cat, and goes out to the village for many purposes, including searching for food, adventure and love of knowledge, pointing to the existence of this belief in Nubia and its extension to neighboring countries, such as Sudan.\nExpressive values\nDr. Abdulrahman Alghanmi addressed the narrative heritage text \u201cHayy Ibn Yazqan \u201d by Ibn Tufayl, as one of the animal stories in the Arab heritage and the Islamic West in Morocco and Andalusia, stressing the specificity of this model and its importance in this field.\nFinally, Dr. Khairuddin Shatra spoke about \u201cMiniatures in Islamic Civilization: The Animal as a Model \u201d, as an artistic phenomenon in which Muslims have excelled, as one of the traditional Islamic arts, also pointing to the existence of this art in some Asian countries.\nShtura explained the features of the miniature of understanding the written text and carrying the exact expressive values, which helped to spread, because of the expressive image along with the writing, and said that this artistic model relied on the animal in the construction of its worlds, affecting many world literature, and therefore can only be understood in its heritage and cultural framework.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0027.json.gz:56507","uncompressed_offset":454309968,"url":"www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%AB%D9%82%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%A9/4223658/-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%88%D9%8A--%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A3--%D9%82%D8%B5%D8%B5-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%86--%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A","warc_date":"2021-09-26T01:23:24.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:1fc775dc-2141-4589-9133-510fabf35ecb>","warc_url":"https://www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%AB%D9%82%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%A9/4223658/-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%88%D9%8A--%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A3--%D9%82%D8%B5%D8%B5-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%86--%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AB-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A"},"created":"2021-09-26T02:26:56.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":{"id":"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389","text":"The mummy of a pet: why and why did the ancient Egyptians do this?\n1: 43\nThe Egyptians showed special respect for their pets, their love was so great that they wanted these animals to have eternal life.\nAfter death, pets were mummified and went through a complex burial process.\nIn ancient Egyptian worldview, four-legged and feathered creatures were considered sacred, divine and influencing their destinies.\nThey occupied an honorable place in the pantheon, and the gods were often depicted with animal heads.\nMummification was an integral part of this religious practice, emphasizing the special status of these creatures in the eyes of the Egyptians.\nThe Egyptians mummified various animals, believing that their gods could take different forms.\nFor example, the goddess Bast, the daughter of Ra, was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat \u2019 s head.\nThis goddess symbolized well-being, joy, love and fertility.\nThe Egyptians especially revered cats for their ability to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, then considered valuable as gold.\nCats have also earned the nickname \u201csunny eye \u201d due to their ability to see in the dark.\nThis property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology.\nArchaeological studies conducted at the ancient Egyptian necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa have uncovered the burial of crocodiles, one of which has been preserved in the form of a practically whole mummy, providing a unique look at the ancient rites and veneration of animals in this culture.\nAuthor Petr Deryabin\nPetr Deryabin \u2013 journalist, correspondent of Pravda.Ru news service","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:108288","uncompressed_offset":297891389,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/","warc_date":"2023-12-21T15:51:28.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/"},"created":"2023-12-21T16:02:19.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025":{"id":"1d0e4045-aa67-43dd-b7b5-1783d200d0e4_526858025","text":"Home \u00bb Celebrating our fellow felines\n\nCelebrating our fellow felines\n\nby admin\n\nEvery August 8, animal lovers around the world come together to celebrate International Cat Day, a day dedicated to honoring and recognizing the presence and special role that cats have in our lives, this holiday has become an opportunity to highlight the importance of caring for and respecting our feline friends, as well as to raise awareness of the need to protect and preserve their well-being.\n\nThe role of the Cat in the History of Culture\n\nCats have played a significant role in various cultures and historical moments. From ancient Egypt, where they were considered symbols of divinity and associated with the goddess Bastet, to medieval Europe, where they were considered guardians of homes and farms due to their ability to keep rodent populations in check, cats have been around. present in human life in different ways.\n\nIn the Middle Ages, however, cats also faced hard times when they were linked with superstition and witchcraft, leading to persecution and slaughter. Fortunately, over time, the relationship between humans and cats has evolved towards a more harmonious and beneficial coexistence for both parties.\n\nEducation and care of cats\n\nPhoto: Pet City\n\nTraining a cat requires patience, understanding and knowledge. Here are some key tips to ensure your cat thrives happy and healthy.\n\nProvide a suitable environment, make sure your home is safe and comfortable for your cat. Provide places for him to rest and hide, as well as toys and environmental enrichment to stimulate his mind.\n\nFood and hydration, offers a balanced diet appropriate to the needs of your cat. It often provides fresh, clean water.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The Democratic Party of Korea, taking to the streets, \"condemns the marine discharge of contaminated water from Fukushima\" [\ub274\uc2dc\uc2a4Pic] :: Sympathy Press Newsis News Agency ::\n\nLitter box, keep a clean and accessible litter box so your cat can eliminate. Clean the box regularly to avoid health problems and bad smells.\n\nHealth problems and bad odors. Socialization and Play Interact and play with your cat daily to keep him physically and mentally active. Play with toys and interaction with other animals can be beneficial\n\nVeterinary Care Schedule regular visits to the vet to make sure your cat is up to date on vaccinations and health checks. This is essential to prevent and detect any medical problem in time.\n\nHygiene, brush your cat\u2019s coat to keep it clean and reduce the formation of hairballs. Also, take care of their oral health by brushing their teeth or providing dental treats.\n\nRespect and love, each cat has its own personality and needs. He respects his space and his quiet times, and show him love and affection according to his preferences.\n\nfun facts about cats\n\nCourtesy Week The sense of smell, although we don\u2019t talk so much about their sense of smell as about their vision and hearing, cats have a highly developed sense of smell. They use their nose to explore and recognize the world around them. They are amazing, they are excellent jumpers and can jump up to six times their length in a single jump. This is partly due to the unique structure of their hind legs, which gives them great power and flexibility. Mysterious purr, cats are believed to purr not only when they are happy, but also when they are sick or injured. Purring could have healing properties and help in the regeneration of bones and tissues. Cats in space, the first cat to travel to space was named Felicette, also known as \u2018Felix\u2019. She was launched by the French Space Agency in 1963 and returned safely. Tail Communication Cats use their tails to communicate. A pricked tail usually indicates confidence and happiness, while a wagging tail could mean the cat is excited or agitated. Born hunters, domestic cats retain their hunting instincts. They can hunt insects, mice and other small animals, which is also a form of exercise and mental stimulation. Exceptional night vision, cats have cells in their eyes called rods, which allow them to see in low light conditions. Their night vision is up to six times better than that of humans.\n\nYou may also like\n\nThis website uses cookies to improve your experience. We'll assume you're ok with this, but you can opt-out if you wish. Accept Read More\n\nPrivacy & Cookies Policy","url":"https://www.breakinglatest.news/news/celebrating-our-fellow-felines/"},"44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199_660616524":{"id":"44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199_660616524","text":"Museum organizes events for visitors to see pet cats\nJuly 29, 2024 07: 15\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nVisitors lined up at the entrance of the Shanghai Museum with their pet cats.\nThe Shanghai Museum recently held the \"Top of the Pyramids: Ancient Egyptian Civilization Exhibition\", in which the People's Square Museum opened on Saturday (27th), the \"Museum Curious Night\" held on Saturdays, a series of nine shows.\nAt the first event, about 200 spectators and cute pet cats gathered at the venue to watch the exhibition.\nBefore the launch, many visitors with pet cats were waiting in line at the entrance of the Shanghai Museum, and about 200 cats were dressed up to attend, attracting many passers-by to stop and take photos.\nAmong them, the hairless cat held by Ms. Huo attracted the attention of many passersby.\nShe said that in order to prepare for the exhibition, she specially took the cat downstairs for a walk two days before the event began to help the cat adapt to the multi-person environment.\nVisitors can take photos with their pets in the Cat Temple area in the exhibition hall, and can also experience items such as \"Giant Cat Sculpture Photo\" and \"Cat Claw Interactive Message\".\nIn ancient Egyptian civilization, the mythical goddess of the cat's head, Bastard, was a symbol of conservation and spirituality, which matched the love of cats today.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0019.json.gz:21574","uncompressed_offset":660616524,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/cnnews/20240729/bkn-20240729071533028-0729_00952_001.html","warc_date":"2024-07-28T22:49:31.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:44d5ff3b-7397-4f8c-8b9d-aa2b54c43199>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/cnnews/20240729/bkn-20240729071533028-0729_00952_001.html"},"created":"2024-07-28T23:56:27.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
