set of benefits that can enhance overall health and well-being, and their popularity is expected to continue to grow in the coming years."}],"references":["abcc75c1-8606-43d7-9727-a5f0ef54e1bb_42404643","f2191b5d-250b-4a7e-b4fb-3047f83a6829_974086854","7bc87769-b800-4b3c-8d37-274568fbd581_918907066","7c9126d4-1629-4a1a-aa4d-03a9c622b034_296262592"],"documents":{"7bc87769-b800-4b3c-8d37-274568fbd581_918907066":{"id":"7bc87769-b800-4b3c-8d37-274568fbd581_918907066","text":"Thorpe Bay in Essex is the home of yoga with a twist. Pawsz and Tails Yoga combines zen with something probably a little less calm: puppies and kittens everywhere. The Southend based yoga classes have combined all of your favourite things so you can leave feeling warm and fuzzy.\n\nAt \u00a330 for an hour session, you can combine a half an hour class with a full hour of silliness with an army of fluff. Pawz and Tails writes on their website: \u201cIf you love animals and would like to cuddle and play with them for an hour incorporating a half hour beginner yoga class then book your class now\u201d. The popular classes are booked up far in advance, with only a handful of classes left in the upcoming months.\n\nThey add: \u201cWe provide a calm and safe atmosphere for our furry companions. Our puppies are free to roam around during the hour to play, sleep and enjoy the attention they receive from humans. Our classes are there to create playtime and socialisation before they go to their forever home.\n\nREAD MORE: RSPCA rescue Spaniel puppy 'dumped in a box with his dying brother' on Essex roadside\n\nREAD MORE:Pebbles the instantly recognisable 'campus cat' at the University of Essex who now has his own statue\n\n\u201cWe have the highest safety standards and you can enjoy our classes knowing that we only work with reputable breeders who have the highest standards of care, we also donate to rescue charities each month.\n\nClasses are for beginners aged 14 and over and aim to create a stress-free environment. A fully qualified yoga teacher will work with you through mainly floor postures, so you\u2019re on a level with the puppies and kittens. Cuddles are optional.\n\nTime spent with a fluffy companion has been proven to have a massive impact on mental health, with 37% of people saying that their pets help them with their lives, according to a Blue Cross study. Just being around animals can have a positive impact on our mental health.\n\nAt Pawz and Tails, their classes \u201cprovide a haven of pure uplifting bliss, interacting with baby animals is extremely heart warming and you will leave us with a big smile on your face. It's also a fun time for our furry companions, who love to play and be cuddled\u201d.\n\nThe animals brought in for the yoga classes are brought from responsible breeders who are looking to socialise the little ones, and Pawz and Tails donate to rescue charities every month.\n\nGet more news from EssexLive straight to your inbox for FREE","url":"https://www.essexlive.news/whats-on/whats-on-news/essex-yoga-venue-puppies-kittens-9328087"},"7c9126d4-1629-4a1a-aa4d-03a9c622b034_296262592":{"id":"7c9126d4-1629-4a1a-aa4d-03a9c622b034_296262592","text":"6 myths about yoga: dispel and start practicing\n28 September 2021, 16: 47\nRead news in ukrainian\nSource:\nEveryday Health\nYoga is not only about physical exertion, but also about relieving stress and peace.\nRegular classes will help to get in shape, improve mood and give a lot of energy.\nYoga Alliance says that yoga is suitable for many and is a universal occupation.\nIt will help relieve pain, give strength and flexibility, relieve stress, improve breathing, the cardiovascular system, help lose weight and promote better circulation.\nIf you still doubted about this way of recovery and rest, we will dispel them in our material.\nWhat danger lies in wait for children in the sandbox\n6 myths about yoga\nI'm not flexible.\nOften, professional yogis on social networks demonstrate the incredible flexibility of their body in various exercises.\nThis raises doubts about whether it is suitable for those who do not consider themselves flexible at all and have never heard of stretching.\nIn fact, yoga begins with light exercises that everyone is able to repeat.\nOver time, they can become more difficult, and you will develop.\nIn addition, exercises can be replaced if some can not be repeated.\nYou don \u2019 t have to be flexible to practice yoga / Photo Unsplash\nMy back hurts.\nPain should not interfere with you both at work and during yoga classes.\nThat is why there are many different practices for almost every medical condition.\nIf you are worried about some disease, consult your doctor before signing up for classes, and do not forget to warn the coach so that he can choose individual exercises for you.\nFor example, if you have glaucoma (a disease that damages the optic nerves of the eyes), you need to avoid lowering your head below the heart, which means that you will have to change certain poses.\n\u2013 explains Samantha Parker, a physiologist and certified yoga instructor.\nIt may be against my religious beliefs.\nYou can focus only on exercises / Photo Unsplash\nYoga is often associated with Hinduism and Buddhism, but it does not require certain religious beliefs and can be practiced by everyone.\nIt only propagates the idea of peace and purpose, which some people identify with spirituality.\nIf this is not very close to you, you can find appropriate classes where instructors focus exclusively on physical aspects.\nYoga for women\nAccording to the 2016 Yoga in America study, 72% of participants were women and 28% were men.\nHowever, this trend is changing every year.\nYoga is a universal practice that helps everyone to improve joint mobility, range of motion and overall physical fitness.\nIn addition, it contributes to good posture, control of muscles and tendons.\nYoga is suitable for women and men / Photo Unsplash\nYoga is just a stretch.\nYoga is often about the emphasis on flexibility, because it involves a lot of stretch marks.\nHowever, along with mobility, you build muscle and stamina.\nThe study, published in the journal Research Complementary and Alternative Medicine, described that a 12-week yoga program improved not only flexibility, but also cardiovascular, muscle strength, and endurance in adults.\nWhy you can not lose weight: nutritionists called 5 common mistakes\nI don 't have time\nEven short classes will improve well-being / Photo Unsplash\nYou have time, you just spend it doing other things,\nThis is Samantha Parker.\nYoga does not require a specific time to practice.\nYou can choose the duration and load on your own.\nLong classes will bring more benefits, but even short practices will help relieve excessive tension and give a good mood.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0028.json.gz:27055","uncompressed_offset":296262592,"url":"zdorovo.24tv.ua/ru/6-mifov-o-joge-razveivaem-nachinaem-zanimatsja_n1751067/amp","warc_date":"2021-09-28T19:15:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7c9126d4-1629-4a1a-aa4d-03a9c622b034>","warc_url":"https://zdorovo.24tv.ua/ru/6-mifov-o-joge-razveivaem-nachinaem-zanimatsja_n1751067/amp"},"created":"2021-09-28T19:32:38.000Z","lang":"eng"},"abcc75c1-8606-43d7-9727-a5f0ef54e1bb_42404643":{"id":"abcc75c1-8606-43d7-9727-a5f0ef54e1bb_42404643","text":"Tuesday, Aug 09, 2022\nOutlook for Brands\n\nThe Inspiring Tale Of An Emerging Yoga Practitioner And Fitness Enthusiast Manish\n\nManish apart from being a fitness freak is also a Yoga Practitioner who aims to connect more and more people with the ancient Indian practice of Yoga to help them lead a healthy life.\n\nThe world, with the outbreak of the Covid-19 Pandemic, has realised the importance of being fit and leading a healthy lifestyle. The last two years have been a tough phase for people across the globe as they were confined to their homes due to lockdown and other restrictions in place. With Gyms and fitness centers shut, people had no options other than Yoga to keep themselves in shape. Yoga, an ancient Indian tradition that is now practiced across the globe, is not just good for a healthy mind and body but also beneficial for a robust economy. Unlike the previous time, Yoga is emerging as a new career option among the youth and people have started taking the ancient practice seriously. According to a report, the Yoga Industry was valued at $87,926 million in 2017 and is projected to reach a whopping $15,811 million by 2025, growing at a CAGR of 11.7 percent from 2018 to 2025. This has resulted in youth taking up the profession of Yoga Practitioner as their career choice. One such notable person who is a fitness enthusiast and an emerging Yoga Practitioner is Manish.\n\nManish apart from being a fitness freak is also a Yoga Practitioner who aims to connect more and more people with the ancient Indian practice of Yoga to help them lead a healthy life. Manish, since his childhood days, was very much into fitness as he used to admire bodybuilders and models. Taking his passion seriously, he started working towards the goal of attaining a healthy & fit body and he enrolled himself into Gym in 2013. Following a strict diet, sweating rigorously in Gyms for hours, and meditating helped him achieve the body that he desired. Having done his Bachelors in Management in 2016 from the prestigious Lovely Professional University (LPU), he is pursuing his Masters in Yoga from Uttarakhand Sanskrit University, following his passion with utmost sincerity.\u00a0\n\nThe young fitness freak entered the realm of professional fitness in 2017 and has done a lot of extensive fitness studies. It is often said that \u201cHard Work never goes in vain\u201d and the same was in the case of Manish. He was honoured with the prestigious title of \u2018Perfect Body\u2019 for the Year 2020-21 at the biggest male pageant of India - Rubaru Mr. India, culminated in Goa on April 8, 2021. Since then, he never had to look back and is slowly becoming an emerging name in the realm of fitness. Manish, with his sheer determination, hard work, and passion has carved a niche around himself and is currently working as a freelancer and Yoga Practitioner. As of now, Manish has successfully mentored numerous young students and has made numerous people connect with the ancient practice of Yoga.\n\nTalking more about his journey and the importance of Yoga, Manish stated, \u201cI always had a passion for fitness since my young days, I sincerely believe that a healthy mind is incomplete with a healthy body and catering to the same, I decided to pursue my career in the realm of Fitness and Yoga. Unlike the general perception, a fit body is not just about hitting the Gym and sweating for hours but it is also about getting proper sleep, following a balanced diet, meditating and practicing Yoga. With the United Nations (UN) officially recognizing June 21 as International Yoga Day, it is indeed a great victory for India where the practice of Yoga originated. I am glad that more and more people have started to realise the importance of Yoga and it is indeed a positive sign that youth today are pursuing their career as a Yoga Practitioner.\u201d\n\nWith an aim to open a multidisciplinary fitness and Yoga brand, Manish is working toward making the world a healthier and happier place. Through his franchise that he envisions opening up both in India and abroad, he not only aims to connect more people with Yoga but to also provide a credible platform for Yoga Practitioners to showcase their skills and make a name for themselves.\u00a0\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement","url":"https://www.outlookindia.com/outlook-spotlight/the-inspiring-tale-of-an-emerging-yoga-practitioner-and-fitness-enthusiast-manish-news-215214"},"f2191b5d-250b-4a7e-b4fb-3047f83a6829_974086854":{"id":"f2191b5d-250b-4a7e-b4fb-3047f83a6829_974086854","text":"Create\n\nThe Benefits of Yoga and Meditation for Mind-Body Wellness\n\nYoga and meditation have emerged as powerful practices that promote mind-body wellness, helping individuals find inner peace, reduce stress, and improve physical health.\n\nIn this article, we will explore the numerous benefits of yoga and meditation and how they contribute to achieving a harmonious and healthy mind-body connection. By incorporating these practices into our daily lives, we can enhance our well-being and experience a greater sense of calm and vitality.\n\nThe Benefits of Yoga and Meditation for Mind-Body Wellness\n\n1. Cultivating Mindfulness and Presence\n\nYoga and meditation encourage the cultivation of mindfulness and presence, allowing individuals to be fully engaged in the present moment. By focusing on the breath, sensations, and thoughts without judgment, practitioners develop a heightened sense of awareness and learn to embrace the present moment, rather than dwelling on the past or worrying about the future. This practice of mindfulness brings a sense of clarity, peace, and contentment.\n\n2. Stress Reduction and Emotional Well-being\n\nBoth yoga and meditation are powerful tools for stress reduction and promoting emotional well-being. Engaging in yoga postures, known as asanas, helps release physical tension stored in the body and activates the relaxation response. Combined with deep breathing and meditation techniques, yoga helps calm the nervous system and reduces stress hormones, leading to a sense of calm and relaxation. Regular practice can also enhance emotional resilience and improve overall mental health.\n\n3. Improved Physical Flexibility and Strength\n\nYoga incorporates a wide range of physical poses that promote flexibility, strength, and balance. The practice involves stretching and elongating the muscles, improving joint mobility, and increasing overall flexibility. As individuals progress in their practice, they gradually build strength, particularly in the core muscles, contributing to better posture and overall physical stability.\n\n4. Enhancing Mind-Body Connection\n\nYoga & meditation emphasize the connection between the mind and the body. Through conscious movement, individuals learn to listen to their bodies, respect their limits, and cultivate a deeper understanding of their physical sensations and abilities. This increased awareness allows practitioners to make informed choices that support their overall well-being and prevents overexertion or injury.\n\n5. Boosting Energy and Vitality\n\nContrary to popular belief, yoga, and meditation can invigorate the body and boost energy levels. Through gentle movements, deep breathing, and focused attention, yoga and meditation help release tension, clear energy blockages, and activate the body's natural energy centers. As a result, individuals often experience increased vitality, improved sleep patterns, and a greater sense of overall well-being.\n\n6. Improved Cognitive Function and Mental Clarity\n\nRegular yoga & meditation practices have been linked to improved cognitive function and mental clarity. The combination of physical movement, breath awareness, and mindfulness helps quiet the mind, improve concentration, and enhance mental focus. As a result, individuals often experience increased productivity, creativity, and a greater ability to handle challenges and make clear decisions.\n\n7. Promoting Overall Health and Well-being\n\nYoga and meditation have a positive impact on overall physical health. The practices help regulate blood pressure, strengthen the immune system, improve digestion, and support healthy organ function. Additionally, the stress-reducing effects of these practices can have a beneficial impact on heart health, reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.\n\n\nThe benefits of yoga and meditation extend beyond physical fitness and relaxation. These practices offer a holistic approach to mind-body wellness, promoting mindfulness, reducing stress, enhancing emotional well-being, improving physical flexibility and strength, boosting energy levels, and fostering a greater sense of overall well-being.\n\nBy incorporating yoga & meditation into our daily routines, we can nurture our mind-body connection and experience the transformative effects of these ancient practices. Embrace the journey of self-discovery and embark on a path of enhanced well-being with yoga and meditation.\n\nEdited by Nihal","url":"https://www.sportskeeda.com/health-and-fitness/the-benefits-yoga-meditation-mind-body-wellness"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1107","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1107","narrative_id":"1107"},"responses":[{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles, a collection of ancient Greek sculptures, have been at the center of a long-standing dispute between Greece and the UK, with Greece seeking their return to the country of origin."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The sculptures were removed from the Parthenon in Athens by Lord Elgin in the early 19th century, sparking a bitter and long-running dispute with the UK, with Greece claiming they were stolen."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The British Museum, where the sculptures are currently housed, is prohibited from permanently returning them to Greece due to a 1963 Act of Parliament."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"However, the museum's chair, George Osborne, has proposed a loan deal that would allow the sculptures to return to Athens in exchange for Greek treasures being displayed in London."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has been pushing for the return of the sculptures, offering to loan Greek treasures to the British Museum in an attempt to broker a deal."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"Mitsotakis has stated that the sculptures belong in the Acropolis Museum in Athens and has expressed willingness to discuss the issue with the UK government."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"A potential resolution to the dispute may involve a temporary loan of the sculptures to Greece, with Labour leader Sir Keir Starmer reportedly open to such a deal."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"The return of the Elgin Marbles to Greece would be a significant step in resolving the controversy, with Mitsotakis stating that it would be a \"fantastic statement\" by the UK."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The dispute over the Elgin Marbles has been ongoing for over 200 years, with Greece repeatedly requesting their return, and a resolution is yet to be reached."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles, a collection of ancient Greek sculptures, have been at the center of a long-standing dispute between Greece and the UK, with Greece seeking their return to the country of origin."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The sculptures were removed from the Parthenon in Athens by Lord Elgin in the early 19th century, sparking a bitter and long-running dispute with the UK, with Greece claiming they were stolen."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The British Museum, where the sculptures are currently housed, is prohibited from permanently returning them to Greece due to a 1963 Act of Parliament."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"However, the museum's chair, George Osborne, has proposed a loan deal that would allow the sculptures to return to Athens in exchange for Greek treasures being displayed in London."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has been pushing for the return of the sculptures, offering to loan Greek treasures to the British Museum in an attempt to broker a deal."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"Mitsotakis has stated that the sculptures belong in the Acropolis Museum in Athens and has expressed willingness to discuss the issue with the UK government."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"A potential resolution to the dispute may involve a temporary loan of the sculptures to Greece, with Labour leader Sir Keir Starmer reportedly open to such a deal."},{"citations":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":1.0},"text":"The return of the Elgin Marbles to Greece would be a significant step in resolving the controversy, with Mitsotakis stating that it would be a \"fantastic statement\" by the UK."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The dispute over the Elgin Marbles has been ongoing for over 200 years, with Greece repeatedly requesting their return, and a resolution is yet to be reached."}],"references":["92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535","b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911","692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005"],"documents":{"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911":{"id":"b6746fc6-bfc0-4d50-b37c-f497296fac8d_113494911","text":"Skip to main content Skip to navigation\n\nGreek prime minister tries to broker deal for return of Parthenon marbles\n\nKyriakos Mitsotakis offers to loan Greek treasures to British Museum if \u2018stolen\u2019 sculptures are returned to Acropolis\n\nThe Greek prime minister has demanded that the 2,500-year-old Parthenon marbles, which he accuses Britain of stealing, be returned to Greece, and even offered to loan some of his country\u2019s treasures to the British Museum in an attempt to broker a deal.\n\nKyriakos Mitsotakis told the Daily Telegraph that the sculptures, also known as the Elgin marbles, belong in the Acropolis Museum in Athens.\n\nHowever, Boris Johnson has previously ruled out returning them on the grounds that they were acquired legally.\n\nMitsotakis said: \u201cOur position is very clear. The marbles were stolen in the 19th century; they belong in the Acropolis Museum and we need to discuss this issue in earnest.\n\n\u201cI am sure that if there was a willingness on the part of the government to move we could find an arrangement with the British Museum in terms of us sending abroad cultural treasures on loan, which have never left the country.\u201d\n\nThe marbles were removed from the Acropolis more than 200 years ago by Lord Elgin in circumstances that have spurred one of the world\u2019s most famous cultural rows and have long been the subject of dispute.\n\nMitsotakis said he would raise the issue with Johnson when the two meet next week for talks that could shape future relations between the two countries.\n\n\u201cRefusing to discuss the topic seems to me, given the context of everything that has been happening in terms of the return of cultural treasures, to be rather an anachronistic approach,\u201d he added.\n\n\u201cIt would be a fantastic statement by what Boris calls Global Britain if they were to move on this and look at it through a completely different lens.\u201d\n\nBut Johnson dismissed the appeal for their return to Greece earlier this year, telling the Greek newspaper Ta Nea: \u201cI understand the strong feelings of the Greek people \u2013 and indeed prime minister Mitsotakis \u2013 on the issue.\n\n\u201cBut the UK government has a firm, longstanding position on the sculptures, which is that they were legally acquired by Lord Elgin under the appropriate laws of the time and have been legally owned by the British Museum\u2019s trustees since their acquisition.\u201d\n\nGreece has long called for the reunification of the sculptures, displayed in museums across Europe but mostly in London, and says it is integral to understanding the artworks in the context of the Acropolis.","url":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2021/nov/13/greek-prime-minister-tries-to-broker-deal-for-return-of-parthenon-marbles"},"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":{"id":"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005","text":"LONDON (Reuters) - The historic Greek treasure of Elgin Marbles is nearing its return to its country of origin, 200 years after it was moved and ended up in the British Museum.\nThe Parthenon marble, seen as a symbol of freedom in Greece, was controversially moved out of the country by a British diplomat in a move that ignited a debate that lasted more than two centuries.\nGreece has made repeated requests for the sculptures to be returned after they were controversially removed from one of the world \u2019 s most historic landmarks.\nPrime Minister Rishi Sonak had been scheduled to meet his Greek counterpart Kyriakos Mitsotakis on Tuesday, but Downing Street canceled the arrangement and sent Deputy Prime Minister Oliver Duden instead.\nThe head of the British Museum, former Conservative Chancellor George Osborne, is pushing for a temporary loan to be returned to Greece, and is believed to have drawn up a deal.\nBut both Sonak and Labour leader Sir Keir Starmer say they will not support a change to the British Museum law that currently bars their return.\nThe museum said it was continuing \"constructive discussions\" about their possible return.\nGin Marble\nThe Algin marble is 17 sculptures that are 2,500 years old.\nHis pieces were part of a frieze that adorned the ancient Parthenon temple at the Acropolis in Athens, Greece.\nThe marbles make up about half of the 160-meter-long frieze of the Parthenon Temple, which is considered one of the greatest cultural monuments in the world.\nThese sculptures are seen as symbols of freedom in Greece, where they are known as Parthenon marble.\nBritish diplomat Lord Elgin removed the sculptures from the majestic Parthenon temple in the early 19th century.\nAt that time, he was ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, which ruled Greece.\nBeginning in 1801, Lord Elgin is said to have supervised the removal of the marble and shipped it to the UK in 170 boxes.\nHe is said to have claimed to have obtained permission from the Ottoman Empire to move the marble, but despite massive documentation from that period, nothing was found to support his actions.\nIn the United Kingdom, Lord Elgin received support and criticism, and sold it to the United Kingdom government in 1816 before the marble was transferred to the custody of the British Museum.\nThe beginning and evolution of the dispute\nThe controversy between Greece and Britain can be traced back to when the marble first arrived in Britain due to criticism of its removal.\nIn 1832, Greece gained independence from the Ottoman Empire before it began trying to recover sculptures and other works of art taken from the country.\nIn the early 1980s, the actress and then Greek Minister of Culture, Melina Mercury, reignited the campaign when she made it her mission to secure the return of marble sculptures.\nIn 1983, she met with the director of the British Museum, Dr. David Wilson, in London to demand the return of the sculptures.\nShe continued to press the museum and the British government until her death in 1994.\nDespite other requests and high-level media coverage, no agreement was reached in the years that followed.\nA new campaign\nIn 2009, Greece stepped up its marble recovery campaign after opening a new museum at the foot of the Acropolis Hill, hoping one day to house it.\nIn 2014, human rights lawyer Amal Clooney called on Britain to start talks with Greece over the return of the Elgin marble.\nThe lawyer, who is the wife of Hollywood star George Clooney, said: \"This is an injustice that has been going on for a long time, in a world full of intractable conflicts.\"\nIn 2015, Greece ruled out any legal action against the UK over Elgin Marbles.\nIn May 2022, the so-called Fagan fragment \u2014 a piece showing the foot of the ancient Greek goddess Artemis seated \u2014 was permanently returned to Athens from a museum in Italy.\nIt was originally part of the eastern frieze of the temple dating back to the 5th century BC.\nThe British reaction\nIn 2022, there were calls to make it easier for UK museums to consider returning cultural objects, but the government rejected them.\nFormer Conservative culture minister Lord Vaizi also headed a new body aimed at returning Elgin marble to Greece.\nThe refusal came after then-Prime Minister Boris Johnson told the Greek prime minister during talks at Downing Street in 2021 that the sculpture issue was \"a matter for the curators of the British Museum\".\nThen, at the beginning of December, George Osborne, the head of the British Museum, reportedly held secret talks with the Greek prime minister about the possibility of returning the marble sculptures.\nNegotiations between former Treasury Secretary Osborne and Kiriakos Mitsotakis have been taking place in London since November 2021, according to the Greek daily Ta Nea.\nThe Greek prime minister has on numerous occasions called for the relocation of the sculptures, and even offered to lend other treasures to the British Museum in return.\nA spokesman for Project Parthenon, a campaign advocating the return of marble sculptures, hailed the talks as a \u201cpositive sign \u201d that a\u201c win-win solution \u201d to the centuries-old debate could be reached.\nPossible deal?\nIn December last year, Downing Street said there were no plans to change the law that prohibits the museum from disposing of objects in its collection except in very limited circumstances.\nA spokesman for the prime minister said: \u201cThe Parthenon sculptures are legally owned by trustees and are practically independent of the government. \u201d\nLast month, the British Museum issued a statement saying it would not dismantle its collection \u201cbecause it tells a unique story of our common humanity, \u201d but added that it wanted to forge a new\u201c Parthenon partnership \u201d with Greece.\nThe talks in Westminster were used by former culture minister Lord Vaizi to press again for the return of the sculptures.\nHe said that the frieze in Athens \"resembles a film that was cut in half and half of it was moved against the will of its owners to another country.\"\nAfter cancelling the bilateral meeting between Sonak and Mitsotakis on Tuesday, the Greek leader said he was \"disappointed\".\nMr Sonak said the UK \u201chas no plans to change our approach \u201d but\u201c did not ask him [Mr Mitsotakis] what short-term or new ideas have been put forward \u201d.\nStarmer and Mitsotakis Meet\nOpposition Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer met Mitsotakis on Monday.\nA source close to Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer told the Financial Times he was unlikely to change the law if he won the next election.\n\"We are committed to the current law, but if a mutually acceptable loan deal can be agreed between the British Museum and the Greek government, we will not stand in the way.\"\nIs the agreement possible?\nThe head of the National Museum, George Osborne, is understood to have drawn up a deal with Athens, according to the Daily Telegraph.\nCurrent legislation bars the museum from legally granting treasures, but Osborne is said to be seeking to repatriate the antiquities as part of a long-term \"cultural exchange.\"\nBut this loan deal is not expected to permanently end the long-running dispute.\nThe article was prepared from the site of (Sky News) British channel:\nhttps: / / news.sky.com / story / elgin-marbles-what-are-they-and-how-did-they-end-up-in-the-british-museum-12779617","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0034.json.gz:11001","uncompressed_offset":430177005,"url":"elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html","warc_date":"2023-11-28T18:49:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b>","warc_url":"https://elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html"},"created":"2023-11-28T19:10:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":{"id":"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535","text":"Greek premier to meet Starmer and Sunak in renewed push to return Elgin marbles\n\nKyriakos Mitsotakis due to meet Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer in London next week\n\nMatt Mathers\nSaturday 25 November 2023 23:43\nComments\nElgin Marbles: British Museum lends statue\n\nGreek prime minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis is set to raise the issue of the Parthenon sculptures with the UK next week.\n\nHe is reportedly due to hold talks with Labour leader Keir Starmer on Monday and prime minister Rishi Sunak on Tuesday and will raise the subject with both.\n\nThe Financial Times reported that Mr Starmer was open to a potential loan deal that would see parts of the ancient sculptures returned. Labour declined to comment.\n\nThe 2,500-year-old sculptures, also known as the Eglin Marbles, were taken from Athens to Britain by agents of Thomas Bruce, the 7th Earl of Eglin, in the early 19th century and never returned. Greece says they were stolen, sparking a bitter and long-running dispute with the UK.\n\nHoused in their own dedicated room, the sculptures of Olympian gods and goddesses, centaurs and warriors are among the greatest at the British Museum.\n\nA 1963 Act of Parliament stops the British Museum from permanently handing them back.\n\nGeorge Osborne, the museum\u2019s chair and the former Conservative Party MP and chancellor, has backed a loan deal.\n\n\u201cI hope we\u2019ll find a way to partner with Greece so that a portion of the Marbles spend part of their time in Athens\u2009.\u2009.\u2009.\u2009and we see more of their treasures in return,\u201d he wrote in The Spectator last week. Mr Osborne conceded that \u201cwe may well not succeed\u201d but that it was \u201csurely worth the effort\u201d.\n\nThe proposed deal, which Mr Osborne and Mr Mitsotakis have held secret talks over, would allow the sculptures to return to Athens in exchange for Greek treasures being displayed in London.\n\nMany of the artworks in question are in storage in museum vaults and have never before been seen.\n\nMr Mitsotakis, who has said it is his \u201cpassion\u201d to get the sculptures back, is scheduled to meet both party leaders next week. He intends to raise the issue in both meetings, a person close to him told the FT.\n\nMr Sunak is said to be not opposed to the idea of a loan deal but sceptical that the sculptures would ever be returned if they were loaned to Greece, according to the paper.\n\nNo 10 has been contacted for comment.\n\nA UK government spokesperson told the FT: \u201cThe UK has cared for the Elgin Marbles for generations.\n\n\u201cOur galleries and museums are funded by taxpayers because they are a huge asset to this country. \u201c\n\nWe share their treasures with the world, and the world comes to the UK to see them. The collection of the British Museum is protected by law, and we have no plans to change it.\u201d\n\nThank you for registering\n\nPlease refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in","url":"https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/parthenon-sculptures-greek-pm-uk-b2453540.html"}}}
