"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"However, with recent developments and negotiations, there is hope for a potential resolution, which could involve a temporary loan of the sculptures to Greece."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the return of the Elgin Marbles to Greece would be a significant step towards resolving the dispute and recognizing the cultural heritage of the country."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles, a collection of ancient Greek sculptures, have been a subject of controversy for over two centuries, with their presence in the British Museum being a point of contention between Greece and the UK."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The sculptures, which are 2,500 years old, were removed from the Parthenon in Athens by Lord Elgin in the early 19th century, sparking a long-standing dispute over their ownership and return."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"Greece has made repeated requests for the sculptures to be returned, with the Greek government considering them a symbol of freedom and an important part of their cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The British Museum, where the sculptures are currently housed, has been resistant to returning them, citing a 1963 Act of Parliament that prevents the museum from permanently handing them over."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"However, there have been recent developments that suggest a potential resolution to the dispute, with the head of the British Museum, George Osborne, proposing a temporary loan of the sculptures to Greece."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"Osborne has stated that he hopes to find a way to partner with Greece, allowing the sculptures to spend part of their time in Athens, while also seeing more Greek treasures displayed in London."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The proposed deal would involve the exchange of the Elgin Marbles for other Greek artworks, many of which are currently in storage and have never been seen before."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has been a key figure in the negotiations, meeting with UK leaders, including Prime Minister Rishi Sunak and Labour leader Keir Starmer, to discuss the potential return of the sculptures."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"Mitsotakis has stated that it is his \"passion\" to get the sculptures back, and he intends to raise the issue in his meetings with UK leaders."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"While Sunak is said to be not opposed to the idea of a loan deal, he is skeptical that the sculptures would ever be returned if they were loaned to Greece."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"The UK government has stated that it has no plans to change the law that protects the British Museum's collection, which includes the Elgin Marbles."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"Despite this, there is still hope for a resolution, with Labour leader Keir Starmer reportedly open to a potential loan deal."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles are a significant cultural treasure, consisting of 17 sculptures that make up about half of the 160-meter-long frieze of the Parthenon Temple."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"They are considered one of the greatest cultural monuments in the world, and their return to Greece would be a significant victory for the country's cultural heritage."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, the controversy surrounding the Elgin Marbles is a complex and long-standing issue, with both Greece and the UK having strong claims to the sculptures."},{"citations":{"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":1.0},"text":"However, with recent developments and negotiations, there is hope for a potential resolution, which could involve a temporary loan of the sculptures to Greece."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":1.0},"text":"Ultimately, the return of the Elgin Marbles to Greece would be a significant step towards resolving the dispute and recognizing the cultural heritage of the country."}],"references":["92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535","692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005"],"documents":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":{"id":"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005","text":"LONDON (Reuters) - The historic Greek treasure of Elgin Marbles is nearing its return to its country of origin, 200 years after it was moved and ended up in the British Museum.\nThe Parthenon marble, seen as a symbol of freedom in Greece, was controversially moved out of the country by a British diplomat in a move that ignited a debate that lasted more than two centuries.\nGreece has made repeated requests for the sculptures to be returned after they were controversially removed from one of the world \u2019 s most historic landmarks.\nPrime Minister Rishi Sonak had been scheduled to meet his Greek counterpart Kyriakos Mitsotakis on Tuesday, but Downing Street canceled the arrangement and sent Deputy Prime Minister Oliver Duden instead.\nThe head of the British Museum, former Conservative Chancellor George Osborne, is pushing for a temporary loan to be returned to Greece, and is believed to have drawn up a deal.\nBut both Sonak and Labour leader Sir Keir Starmer say they will not support a change to the British Museum law that currently bars their return.\nThe museum said it was continuing \"constructive discussions\" about their possible return.\nGin Marble\nThe Algin marble is 17 sculptures that are 2,500 years old.\nHis pieces were part of a frieze that adorned the ancient Parthenon temple at the Acropolis in Athens, Greece.\nThe marbles make up about half of the 160-meter-long frieze of the Parthenon Temple, which is considered one of the greatest cultural monuments in the world.\nThese sculptures are seen as symbols of freedom in Greece, where they are known as Parthenon marble.\nBritish diplomat Lord Elgin removed the sculptures from the majestic Parthenon temple in the early 19th century.\nAt that time, he was ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, which ruled Greece.\nBeginning in 1801, Lord Elgin is said to have supervised the removal of the marble and shipped it to the UK in 170 boxes.\nHe is said to have claimed to have obtained permission from the Ottoman Empire to move the marble, but despite massive documentation from that period, nothing was found to support his actions.\nIn the United Kingdom, Lord Elgin received support and criticism, and sold it to the United Kingdom government in 1816 before the marble was transferred to the custody of the British Museum.\nThe beginning and evolution of the dispute\nThe controversy between Greece and Britain can be traced back to when the marble first arrived in Britain due to criticism of its removal.\nIn 1832, Greece gained independence from the Ottoman Empire before it began trying to recover sculptures and other works of art taken from the country.\nIn the early 1980s, the actress and then Greek Minister of Culture, Melina Mercury, reignited the campaign when she made it her mission to secure the return of marble sculptures.\nIn 1983, she met with the director of the British Museum, Dr. David Wilson, in London to demand the return of the sculptures.\nShe continued to press the museum and the British government until her death in 1994.\nDespite other requests and high-level media coverage, no agreement was reached in the years that followed.\nA new campaign\nIn 2009, Greece stepped up its marble recovery campaign after opening a new museum at the foot of the Acropolis Hill, hoping one day to house it.\nIn 2014, human rights lawyer Amal Clooney called on Britain to start talks with Greece over the return of the Elgin marble.\nThe lawyer, who is the wife of Hollywood star George Clooney, said: \"This is an injustice that has been going on for a long time, in a world full of intractable conflicts.\"\nIn 2015, Greece ruled out any legal action against the UK over Elgin Marbles.\nIn May 2022, the so-called Fagan fragment \u2014 a piece showing the foot of the ancient Greek goddess Artemis seated \u2014 was permanently returned to Athens from a museum in Italy.\nIt was originally part of the eastern frieze of the temple dating back to the 5th century BC.\nThe British reaction\nIn 2022, there were calls to make it easier for UK museums to consider returning cultural objects, but the government rejected them.\nFormer Conservative culture minister Lord Vaizi also headed a new body aimed at returning Elgin marble to Greece.\nThe refusal came after then-Prime Minister Boris Johnson told the Greek prime minister during talks at Downing Street in 2021 that the sculpture issue was \"a matter for the curators of the British Museum\".\nThen, at the beginning of December, George Osborne, the head of the British Museum, reportedly held secret talks with the Greek prime minister about the possibility of returning the marble sculptures.\nNegotiations between former Treasury Secretary Osborne and Kiriakos Mitsotakis have been taking place in London since November 2021, according to the Greek daily Ta Nea.\nThe Greek prime minister has on numerous occasions called for the relocation of the sculptures, and even offered to lend other treasures to the British Museum in return.\nA spokesman for Project Parthenon, a campaign advocating the return of marble sculptures, hailed the talks as a \u201cpositive sign \u201d that a\u201c win-win solution \u201d to the centuries-old debate could be reached.\nPossible deal?\nIn December last year, Downing Street said there were no plans to change the law that prohibits the museum from disposing of objects in its collection except in very limited circumstances.\nA spokesman for the prime minister said: \u201cThe Parthenon sculptures are legally owned by trustees and are practically independent of the government. \u201d\nLast month, the British Museum issued a statement saying it would not dismantle its collection \u201cbecause it tells a unique story of our common humanity, \u201d but added that it wanted to forge a new\u201c Parthenon partnership \u201d with Greece.\nThe talks in Westminster were used by former culture minister Lord Vaizi to press again for the return of the sculptures.\nHe said that the frieze in Athens \"resembles a film that was cut in half and half of it was moved against the will of its owners to another country.\"\nAfter cancelling the bilateral meeting between Sonak and Mitsotakis on Tuesday, the Greek leader said he was \"disappointed\".\nMr Sonak said the UK \u201chas no plans to change our approach \u201d but\u201c did not ask him [Mr Mitsotakis] what short-term or new ideas have been put forward \u201d.\nStarmer and Mitsotakis Meet\nOpposition Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer met Mitsotakis on Monday.\nA source close to Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer told the Financial Times he was unlikely to change the law if he won the next election.\n\"We are committed to the current law, but if a mutually acceptable loan deal can be agreed between the British Museum and the Greek government, we will not stand in the way.\"\nIs the agreement possible?\nThe head of the National Museum, George Osborne, is understood to have drawn up a deal with Athens, according to the Daily Telegraph.\nCurrent legislation bars the museum from legally granting treasures, but Osborne is said to be seeking to repatriate the antiquities as part of a long-term \"cultural exchange.\"\nBut this loan deal is not expected to permanently end the long-running dispute.\nThe article was prepared from the site of (Sky News) British channel:\nhttps: / / news.sky.com / story / elgin-marbles-what-are-they-and-how-did-they-end-up-in-the-british-museum-12779617","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0034.json.gz:11001","uncompressed_offset":430177005,"url":"elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html","warc_date":"2023-11-28T18:49:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b>","warc_url":"https://elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html"},"created":"2023-11-28T19:10:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535":{"id":"92673347-9486-4c3f-a1d5-089cbaf4e1a2_1039697535","text":"Greek premier to meet Starmer and Sunak in renewed push to return Elgin marbles\n\nKyriakos Mitsotakis due to meet Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer in London next week\n\nMatt Mathers\nSaturday 25 November 2023 23:43\nComments\nElgin Marbles: British Museum lends statue\n\nGreek prime minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis is set to raise the issue of the Parthenon sculptures with the UK next week.\n\nHe is reportedly due to hold talks with Labour leader Keir Starmer on Monday and prime minister Rishi Sunak on Tuesday and will raise the subject with both.\n\nThe Financial Times reported that Mr Starmer was open to a potential loan deal that would see parts of the ancient sculptures returned. Labour declined to comment.\n\nThe 2,500-year-old sculptures, also known as the Eglin Marbles, were taken from Athens to Britain by agents of Thomas Bruce, the 7th Earl of Eglin, in the early 19th century and never returned. Greece says they were stolen, sparking a bitter and long-running dispute with the UK.\n\nHoused in their own dedicated room, the sculptures of Olympian gods and goddesses, centaurs and warriors are among the greatest at the British Museum.\n\nA 1963 Act of Parliament stops the British Museum from permanently handing them back.\n\nGeorge Osborne, the museum\u2019s chair and the former Conservative Party MP and chancellor, has backed a loan deal.\n\n\u201cI hope we\u2019ll find a way to partner with Greece so that a portion of the Marbles spend part of their time in Athens\u2009.\u2009.\u2009.\u2009and we see more of their treasures in return,\u201d he wrote in The Spectator last week. Mr Osborne conceded that \u201cwe may well not succeed\u201d but that it was \u201csurely worth the effort\u201d.\n\nThe proposed deal, which Mr Osborne and Mr Mitsotakis have held secret talks over, would allow the sculptures to return to Athens in exchange for Greek treasures being displayed in London.\n\nMany of the artworks in question are in storage in museum vaults and have never before been seen.\n\nMr Mitsotakis, who has said it is his \u201cpassion\u201d to get the sculptures back, is scheduled to meet both party leaders next week. He intends to raise the issue in both meetings, a person close to him told the FT.\n\nMr Sunak is said to be not opposed to the idea of a loan deal but sceptical that the sculptures would ever be returned if they were loaned to Greece, according to the paper.\n\nNo 10 has been contacted for comment.\n\nA UK government spokesperson told the FT: \u201cThe UK has cared for the Elgin Marbles for generations.\n\n\u201cOur galleries and museums are funded by taxpayers because they are a huge asset to this country. \u201c\n\nWe share their treasures with the world, and the world comes to the UK to see them. The collection of the British Museum is protected by law, and we have no plans to change it.\u201d\n\nThank you for registering\n\nPlease refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in","url":"https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/parthenon-sculptures-greek-pm-uk-b2453540.html"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1109","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1109","narrative_id":"1109"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The popularity of corgis can be attributed to the historical bond between the royal family and the breed, with Queen Elizabeth II playing a central role in making them beloved worldwide."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The Queen's love for corgis began in 1933 when her parents welcomed the family's first corgi, Dookie, and later, her father gifted her a corgi named Susan for her 18th birthday."},{"citations":{"0f582f8d-3aa3-47f1-9bbb-4cfcd595c3de_891736516":1.0},"text":"This marked the beginning of the royal line of corgis, with all subsequent royal corgis bred by the monarch descending from Susan, the original."},{"citations":{"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899":1.0},"text":"The Queen's affection for corgis was not only due to their \"energy and untamed spirit\" but also because of their intelligence and ability to herd animals."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"The breed's popularity declined in 2014, with the Kennel Club listing them as 'vulnerable', but the Queen's love for them helped boost their popularity, making them one of the UK's most popular breeds today."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"In fact, the number of Pembroke Welsh Corgis registered with the Kennel Club hit a 30-year peak after the Queen's Platinum Jubilee and death."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The royal connection has also influenced corgis' rise in media and culture, with events like the Tour de Corgi parade, which includes a \"Queen Elizabeth and her corgis\" costume competition, being held in their honor."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"Overall, the unique popularity of corgis can be attributed to the Queen's long-standing association with the breed, which has made them a symbol of British royalty."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The popularity of corgis can be attributed to the historical bond between the royal family and the breed, with Queen Elizabeth II playing a central role in making them beloved worldwide."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The Queen's love for corgis began in 1933 when her parents welcomed the family's first corgi, Dookie, and later, her father gifted her a corgi named Susan for her 18th birthday."},{"citations":{"0f582f8d-3aa3-47f1-9bbb-4cfcd595c3de_891736516":1.0},"text":"This marked the beginning of the royal line of corgis, with all subsequent royal corgis bred by the monarch descending from Susan, the original."},{"citations":{"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899":1.0},"text":"The Queen's affection for corgis was not only due to their \"energy and untamed spirit\" but also because of their intelligence and ability to herd animals."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"The breed's popularity declined in 2014, with the Kennel Club listing them as 'vulnerable', but the Queen's love for them helped boost their popularity, making them one of the UK's most popular breeds today."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"In fact, the number of Pembroke Welsh Corgis registered with the Kennel Club hit a 30-year peak after the Queen's Platinum Jubilee and death."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The royal connection has also influenced corgis' rise in media and culture, with events like the Tour de Corgi parade, which includes a \"Queen Elizabeth and her corgis\" costume competition, being held in their honor."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"Overall, the unique popularity of corgis can be attributed to the Queen's long-standing association with the breed, which has made them a symbol of British royalty."}],"references":["7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899","23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552","0f582f8d-3aa3-47f1-9bbb-4cfcd595c3de_891736516","4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987"],"documents":{"0f582f8d-3aa3-47f1-9bbb-4cfcd595c3de_891736516":{"id":"0f582f8d-3aa3-47f1-9bbb-4cfcd595c3de_891736516","text":"Queen Elizabeth II is known to have had over 30 different dogs during her reign as the head of the monarchy until her passing last week, Thursday September 8th 2022.\n\nThe Queen who has been succeeded by her son, the now His Royal Highness King Charles III, was a big animal lover, but had a definite soft spot for dogs, and in particular, the breed Pembroke Welsh Corgi.\n\nOn the day she passed, Queen Elizabeth II had four dogs, two Pembroke Welsh Corgis, one Dorgi \u2014 a cross between a Dachshund and a Corgi \u2014 and one Cocker Spaniel.\n\nRead more: Prince Harry and Meghan Markle set to fly children Archie and Lilibet to the UK for Queen Elizabeth's funeral\n\nIt has been confirmed that her two remaining Corgis, named Muick and Sandy, will now be looked after by her son, Prince Andrew The Duke of York.\n\nHe will look after the dogs alongside his ex-wife Sarah Ferguson, The Duchess of York. Despite divorcing in 1997, they remain cohabiting.\n\nThe animals will live alongside The Duke and Duchess at their Royal Lodge in Windsor.\n\nThe change of ownership was confirmed by a spokesperson for the Duke of York.\n\nBoth dogs were gifted to the late monarch by the prince, and so will be returned to his ownership.\n\nDuring lockdown, Prince Andrew gave Queen Elizabeth two dogs, Muick and Fergus. Sadly, Fergus died last May, and he was replaced with Sandy.\n\nSarah Ferguson, The Duchess of York, posted an emotional statement following the loss of her former mother-in-law.\n\n\"I am heartbroken by the passing of Her Majesty the Queen. She leaves behind an extraordinary legacy: the most fantastic example of duty and service and steadfastness, and a constant steadying presence as our head of state for more than 70 years,\" she penned.\n\n\"To me, she was the most incredible mother-in-law and friend. I will always be grateful to her for the generosity she showed me in remaining close to me even after my divorce. I will miss her more than words can express.\"\n\nQueen Elizabeth II was renowned for her love of dogs, and other animals including horses.\n\nShe began her love of Pembroke Welsh Corgis back in 1933, when she was first given a little corgi named Susan as a gift for her 18th birthday.\n\nAll of the subsequent royal corgis bred by the monarch descended from Susan, the original.\n\nIt is not known or publicised who will care for Candy and Lissy, the previously mentioned Dorgi and Cocker Spaniel.\n\nGet the latest RSVP headlines straight to your inbox for free by signing up to our newsletter\n\nRead more:","url":"https://www.rsvplive.ie/news/celebs/what-happens-queen-elizabeth-iis-27971357"},"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899":{"id":"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899","text":"Skip to main content\nABC Rural\n\nCorgis bred for herding livestock long before Queen Elizabeth II made them famous\n\nBy Sophie Johnson\nPosted\u00a0\n\nWhile corgis are synonymous with the late Queen Elizabeth II, it might be a surprise to know the tiny breed is still used as a working dog\u00a0in Australia.\n\nThe Queen had 30 corgis as pets over her lifetime, giving the breed its international recognition.\n\nBut the dog has been used for centuries to herd livestock.\n\nJean Milnes herds south of Adelaide with her female corgi, Tirion.\n\n\"[Corgis] have been herding since the Middle Ages at least, there is documentary evidence of them herding back in about 800AD,\" she said.\n\n\"I just got into it because I thought this would be fun to do to see if she could remember what her ancestors used to do.\"\n\nExercising instincts\n\nThere are few corgi herders in Australia now, but Ms Milne is hoping the popularity will boom after the death of the Queen, returning the breed\u00a0to its farming roots.\n\n\"I still have the conversation with people who think corgis are wonderful, associate them with being the Queen's dog, and don't realise that they actually have a job to do,\" Ms Milnes said.\n\n\"There is ...\u00a0going to be an influx of people wanting corgis for the next year or so, and it would be nice if they did something more than just go to the dog park.\"\n\nHer corgi trains for herding competitions.\n\n\"We should be doing things that \u2026 dogs enjoy as well,\" she said.\n\n\"They need to be given the opportunity to achieve things.\n\n\"I think it is very important in any breed to maintain what they were intended to do.\"\n\nBig brain, little legs\n\nNational Welsh Corgi Council secretary Sadie Podger said the dogs were very intelligent, which was needed when herding animals.\n\n\"Years ago \u2026 the farmers found that these dogs are actually quite smart and adapt to their conditions that they're in and found that they were the better of all the cattle type dogs that they had,\" she said.\n\nMs Podger said corgis were known as herd heelers because they could\u00a0nip the rear legs of livestock to guide and direct the animal.\n\n\"When they herd they can roll from one side \u2026 of the cattle to the other side with that, and then sort of directing the cattle to where they want it, because cattle can be quite stubborn.\"\n\n\"They're low to the ground so they can drop their head a little bit, and basically the hoof goes over the top of their head where a taller dog could get hit in the head.\"\n\nLoading YouTube content\nPosted\u00a0","url":"https://www.abc.net.au/news/rural/2022-09-22/corgis-bred-herding-livestock-before-queen-elizabeth-made-famous/101461686"},"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":{"id":"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552","text":"King Charles Spaniel numbers are declining and the breed is on the Kennel Club's 'vulnerable list' - amid Corgi boom following Queen Elizabeth's death\n\n  \u2022 Corgis have seen boom in popularity after Platinum Jubilee and death of Queen\u00a0\n  \u2022 Number of Pembroke Welsh Corgis registered with Kennel Club hit 30-year peak\n  \u2022 But popularity of King Charles Spaniels is continuing to decline, hitting a low\n  \u2022 Lovers of the breed are hoping sharing name with new King will boost the dogs\n\nInterest in Corgis has boomed following the Platinum Jubilee and the death of Queen Elizabeth, according to the Kennel Club.\n\nNumbers of Pembroke Welsh Corgis registered with the organisation have reached a 30-year high, the Times\u00a0reports.\n\nConversely, King Charles Spaniels are continuing to see a decline in their popularity, with lovers of the breed reportedly hoping that sharing a moniker with the new monarch may give the dogs a boost (though the new king prefers\u00a0Jack Russells).\n\nThe breed, which is on the Kennel Club's vulnerable list, hit a low in 2020, with just 56 registrations. This increased to 91 in 2021, but numbers so far this year are so low, it is likely to drop beneath 2020.\n\nThe number of Corgis registered with the Kennel Club has reached a 30-year high, with interest growing following the death of the Queen (pictured here in 1980 with three of the dogs)\n\nCavalier King Charles Spaniels (as pictured) are doing well in terms of popularity, although their close relative the King Charles Spaniel (not pictured) is seeing a decline\n\nHowever, it notes that Cavalier King Charles Spaniels, the original breed from which King Charles diverged in the middle of the century, is doing well, with 3,772 registrations last year.\u00a0\n\nThe original\u00a0Cavalier King Charles Spaniel dog breed was developed from toy spaniels. Popular as women's pets, they were also beloved of\u00a0King Charles II, who was said to be so fond of his spaniels, he could not be parted from them.\n\nAlthough Corgis were on the Kennel Club's vulnerable list in 2014, they are now one ofthe UK's most popular breeds, and the Queen is credited with boosting their popularity (pictured: Queen Elizabeth with one of her beloved corgis, Candy)\n\nThe Pembroke Welsh Corgi has become known as a symbol of British royalty thanks to its long-standing association with the Queen\n\nLovers of the ailing King Charles Spaniel may look to the influence the Queen had in turning around the fortune of corgis in recent decades.\n\nThe breed was\u00a0listed as 'vulnerable' in 2014, and the Kennel Club credits Her Majesty's love of the dogs as the major factor in making them one of the UK's most popular breeds today.\n\nCorgis, which have four short legs, a long snout and two huge pointed ears, are famous for being a symbol of British royalty.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nHISTORY OF THE CORGI BREED\u00a0\n\nThe word 'Corgi' is Welsh for 'Dwarf Dog', and there are two types; the Pembroke, which is the Queen's breed, and the Cardigan Corgi, a descendent Teckel family of dogs, which also produced the Dachshund\n\nPembroke Welsh Corgis originated in Pembrokeshire, Wales from the Spitz family of dogs which are characterised by long, thick fur and pointed ears and muzzle\n\nCorgis are a cattle herding breed that can be traced back\u00a0as far as 1107 AD, thought to have been brought to Wales by\u00a0 Flemish weavers\u00a0\n\nThey are the type of herding dog referred to as 'heelers', meaning that they would nip at the heels of cattle to keep them moving\u00a0\n\nThe combination of their low height off the ground and the innate agility of Welsh Corgis would allow them to avoid the hooves of the larger animals\n\nThey were officially recognised as a native British breed by The Kennel Club in 1928, but Cardigans and Pembrokes weren't seen as separate breeds until 1934\n\nAdvertisement\n\nThe Queen owned more than 30 of the sandy, short-legged dogs throughout her reign.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nShe was gifted her first corgi, called Susan, for her 18th birthday from her late father King George VI. Ten generations of her corgis then descended from Susan.\u00a0\n\nHer dogs were given the Royal treatment having their own rooms with elevated wicker baskets and meals of beef, chick, rabbit, liver, cabbage and rice being prepared by a chef each evening.\u00a0\n\nSometimes the Queen herself made the dog's meals. But her late husband was said to have 'loathed' the dogs' yapping.\u00a0\n\nShe left behind two dogs - Sandy and Muick - who are now cared for by Prince Andrew and the Duchess of York at their Royal Lodge home.\n\nMuick, pronounced Mick, joined the royal family at the start of 2021 along with a so-called 'dorgi', a cross between a corgi and a dachshund, called Fergus.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nFergus, who had been named after the Monarch's uncle who was killed during battle in the First World War, died after just five months.\n\nHe was later replaced with a new corgi called Sandy, as a 95th birthday present from Prince Andrew and his daughters, Princesses Beatrice and Eugenie.\u00a0\n\nMeanwhile Muick was named after Loch Muick on the Balmoral Estate.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nPalace sources speaking to the Daily Mail previously revealed the beloved corgis were\u00a0'with [the Queen] in the room' at her deathbed when she died on September 8 at Balmoral.\n\nThey then\u00a0touched people's hearts when they made a poignant appearance at Her Majesty's funeral on September 19.\n\nAs the late monarch's coffin made its way from London to its final resting place in Windsor, Muick and Sandy waited for the processional to pass, to see the Queen for one last time.\u00a0\n\nThe dogs were seen waiting in the quadrangle with two aides before the late monarch was laid to rest in St George's Chapel.\u00a0\n\nAdvertisement\n\nKing Charles Spaniel numbers declining amid Corgi boom following Queen Elizabeth's death\n\nThe comments below have been moderated in advance.\n\nThe views expressed in the contents above are those of our users and do not necessarily reflect the views of MailOnline.","url":"https://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-11323485/King-Charles-Spaniel-numbers-declining-amid-Corgi-boom-following-Queen-Elizabeths-death.html?ns_mchannel=rss&ito=1490&ns_campaign=1490"},"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":{"id":"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987","text":"Sunday, Sep 11, 2022\n\nAnnual \u2018Tour de Corgi\u2019 event to include new \u2018Queen Elizabeth\u2019 costume category to honour the monarch\n\n\u201cWe all have a very strong affection for her as a fellow corgi lover,\" Tour de Corgi founder Tracy Stewart was quoted as saying\n\nQueen Elizabeth II is seen walking in the private grounds of Windsor Castle, in England, on steps at the rear of the East Terrace and East Garden with four of her dogs: clockwise from top left Willow (corgi), Vulcan (dorgie), Candy (dorgie) and Holly (AP/PTI)\n\nAs a tribute to the late UK monarch Queen Elizabeth II, who passed away at the age of 96 at her Balmoral estate in Scotland on September 8, after reigning for 70 long years, the Tour de Corgi parade \u2014 an annual event that celebrates the dog breed corgi \u2014 will include a new element this year that is likely to make fans of the British royal family and corgi lovers happy.\n\nBuy Now | Our best subscription plan now has a special price\n\nIt is no secret that the queen was extremely fond of dogs, especially corgis, from a very early age, and that she had been breeding them until 2018, when she finally realised that she may have to leave some of them behind after her death.\n\nAccording to Country Living, the queen had four dogs at the time of her death: two Pembroke Welsh Corgis, a Dorgi (Corgi-Dachshund mix), and a Cocker Spaniel named Lissy, who joined the family only this year, in January 2022.\n\n\u00a0\n\nView this post on Instagram\n\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by The Royal Family (@theroyalfamily)\n\nIn her lifetime, she reportedly bred 14 generations of corgis, and even famously declared: \u201cMy corgis are family.\u201d\n\nAccording to an Independent report, Queen Elizabeth\u2018s love for her four-legged friends was well-documented during this year\u2019s platinum jubilee celebrations in the UK, when the sky above Buckingham Palace was lit up with images of the dog breed.\n\nThe publication mentioned that the Tour de Corgi parade this year \u2014 which has been taking place in Fort Collins, Colorado since 2014 \u2014 will include a \u201cQueen Elizabeth and her corgis\u201d costume competition, in \u201cmemorium and to honour her\u201d, quoting the event\u2019s organisers who shared this with a local newspaper \u2018The Coloradoan\u2018.\n\nThis is a May 12, 1973 file photo of Queen Elizabeth II sitting with her corgis, at Virginia Water to watch competitors, including Prince Philip in the Marathon of the European Driving Championship, part of the Royal Windsor Horse Show.\n\nTour de Corgi founder Tracy Stewart was quoted as saying, \u201cWe all have a very strong affection for her as a fellow corgi lover. I think it is just, you know, our dogs are such a big part of our hearts that it creates a very heartfelt connection.\u201d\n\nAdvertisement\n\nThe aforementioned event will take place on October 1, 2022, and will conclude with a corgi parade through the town.\n\n\u00a0\n\nView this post on Instagram\n\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by @bronskiandfriends\n\nAccording to a Reader\u2019s Digest report, the queen was fond of corgis because of their \u201cenergy and untamed spirit\u201d, and the fact that her parents welcomed the family\u2019s first corgi, Dookie, in 1933. Eleven years later, in 1944, the queen\u2019s father gifted her a corgi named Susan for her 18th birthday. The pupper even accompanied her on her honeymoon, and gave birth to a pair of puppies in 1949, which reportedly marked the beginning of the royal line of corgis.\n\n\ud83d\udce3 For more lifestyle news, follow us on Instagram | Twitter | Facebook and don\u2019t miss out on the latest updates!\n\nFirst published on: 11-09-2022 at 07:10:45 pm\nNext Story\n\nBombay High Court says judicial system answerable to accused, fair and speedy trial expected\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement","url":"https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/life-style/annual-tour-de-corgi-event-queen-elizabeth-costume-category-honour-monarch-8143690/"}}}
