0264552":1.0},"text":"The breed's popularity has been further boosted by the queen's Platinum Jubilee and her subsequent passing, with the number of Pembroke Welsh Corgis registered with the Kennel Club reaching a 30-year high."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"Conversely, the popularity of King Charles Spaniels, another breed favored by the royal family, has been declining, with the breed being listed as 'vulnerable' in 2014."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"However, lovers of the breed are hoping that sharing a name with the new King will boost the dogs' popularity."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The Tour de Corgi parade, which has been taking place in Fort Collins, Colorado since 2014, has also contributed to the breed's popularity, with a \"Queen Elizabeth and her corgis\" costume competition being held in her honor."},{"citations":{"4a6f8b30-e1d2-4503-a54c-4842176faffd_760865987":1.0},"text":"The event's founder, Tracy Stewart, has expressed her affection for the queen as a fellow corgi lover, stating that the connection between dog owners and their pets creates a \"very heartfelt connection\"."},{"citations":{"23cd6320-dc30-49bb-b11d-4e573e59f6db_380264552":1.0},"text":"Corgis are known for their unique characteristics, including their intelligence, energy, and short stature, with four short legs, a long snout, and two huge pointed ears."},{"citations":{"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899":1.0},"text":"Their intelligence is particularly notable, with National Welsh Corgi Council secretary Sadie Podger stating that they are \"very smart\" and adapt well to their conditions."},{"citations":{"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6df-d62fc9c7e481_363892899":1.0},"text":"In fact, corgis were originally bred for herding animals, and their intelligence and energy make them well-suited for this task."},{"citations":{"7b7063fa-c3ab-47ba-a6d