ts has been met with criticism, with some seeing it as an act of madness at a time when Europe's energy supply remains precarious."},{"citations":{"2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04_1033813326":1.0},"text":"About 60% of the country's residents have called the government's decision to abandon nuclear power wrong, citing concerns over further increases in electricity prices."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals by 2035 may be hindered by the boycott of Russian oil and gas, making it a complicated situation for Germany."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"Overall, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a complex issue, with both supporters and critics presenting valid arguments, and the country's energy market will likely face significant challenges in the short term."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a significant step towards becoming carbon neutral, with the country aiming to be carbon neutral by 2045."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs."},{"citations":{"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":1.0},"text":"Nuclear energy accounts for about 10 percent of Germany's electricity production, and the shutdown has sparked criticism as Germany will have to dramatically ramp up renewable energy."},{"citations":{"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":1.0},"text":"The shutdown of the last three nuclear plants in Germany was due to be completed by the end of 2022, with the environment ministry stating that the country is drawing a line under a highly problematic technology."},{"citations":{"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has had a significant impact on Germany's energy supply, with the country being forced to look for alternatives to Russian gas."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"In response to the war, there have been calls to delay the shutdown of nuclear reactors, with 67 percent of Germans supporting a five-year extension of the country's nuclear plants."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"However, the German Green Party has only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The closure of the nuclear power plants has been met with criticism, with some seeing it as an act of madness at a time when Europe's energy supply remains precarious."},{"citations":{"2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04_1033813326":1.0},"text":"About 60% of the country's residents have called the government's decision to abandon nuclear power wrong, citing concerns over further increases in electricity prices."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals by 2035 may be hindered by the boycott of Russian oil and gas, making it a complicated situation for Germany."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"Overall, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a complex issue, with both supporters and critics presenting valid arguments, and the country's energy market will likely face significant challenges in the short term."}],"references":["0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207","2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04_1033813326","533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295","e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519"],"documents":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":{"id":"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEXPRESS: Germany \u2019 s exit from atomic energy sector affects Europe \u2019 s largest economy\nGermany \u2019 s closure of the country \u2019 s last three nuclear reactors and its eventual exit from the atomic energy sector raises concerns about the impact of the decision on the European Union \u2019 s largest economy.\nGermany \u2019 s action could deal a blow to the technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nBerlin is implementing its plan to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035.\nEarlier this week, Germany shut down its last three nuclear power plants as part of Berlin's plan to limit power generation to renewables by 2035, ending a six-decade programme that has sparked one of Europe's most powerful protest movements.\nOther industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France and Britain, rely on nuclear power to replace the fossil fuels that are warming the planet, and Germany \u2019 s decision to stop using both has been met with some skepticism, as well as unsuccessful last-minute calls to halt the shutdown, the report said.\nNuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, realizing that the action taken by Europe \u2019 s largest economy could deal a blow to technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nThe German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs, even as steps are taken to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, and Germany aims to be carbon neutral by 2045.\nBut officials like German Environment Minister Stevie Lemke say the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth, citing data showing that the share of atomic energy in global electricity production is shrinking.\nThe construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns.\nLimki noted that the construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns, and said the money spent on maintaining old reactors or building new ones would be better spent on installing cheap renewables.\nExperts such as Claudia Kemfert of the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin say the 5% share of German electricity currently coming from its three remaining reactors can be easily replaced without risking power outages.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:26416","uncompressed_offset":493378519,"url":"www.dostor.org/4369517","warc_date":"2023-04-17T07:53:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4369517"},"created":"2023-04-17T08:28:34.000Z","lang":"eng"},"2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04_1033813326":{"id":"2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04_1033813326","text":"Chernobyl and the war: how the events in Ukraine prompted Germany to abandon nuclear energy\nGreenpeace activist at a protest against nuclear power in Berlin, Germany.\nPhoto by REUTERS / Nadja Wohlleben\nThe end of the atomic age.\nThis weekend, Germany, as promised, shut down its last nuclear power plants.\nOn Sunday night, the Germans decommissioned three stations: Izar 2 in Bavaria, Necarwesteim-2 in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg and Emsland in Lower Saxony.\nNuclear power plants, which have recently produced about 5% of the country \u2019 s electricity, have been shut down as part of the so-called \u201cenergy transition. \u201d\nIts goal is to completely switch to green energy by 2035, that is, to produce electricity from renewable sources.\nRead also:\nThe decision to finally abandon the peaceful atom was given to the German authorities not easy.\nA week ago, in political Berlin, there were calls to postpone the closure of the reactors for at least a few months, so as not to jeopardize the security of energy supply in the country.\nMoreover, the temporary continuation of the work of the nuclear power plant of Chancellor Olaf Scholz was requested by both the opposition Christian Democrats and the liberals included in the ruling coalition.\nMost Germans did not support the closure of the nuclear power plant.\nAccording to sociologists, about 60% of the country \u2019 s residents called the government \u2019 s decision to abandon the peaceful atom wrong.\nThe reason is obvious: people are afraid of further increases in electricity prices, which have literally exploded.\nFarewell to the atom: the Ukrainian factor\nIn fact, the decision to close all German nuclear power plants was made in 2011 by the government of Angela Merkel after the accident at the Japanese nuclear power plant Fukushima.\nBut the discussion about the abandonment of nuclear power began much earlier \u2014 in 1986, after the disaster at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.\nThe accident sparked widespread protests against the use of the peaceful atom, and after Chernobyl, the now ruling Social Democratic Party announced that it would support the closure of all German nuclear power plants and enshrined this position in its political program.\nEvents in Ukraine also affected the timing of the closure of the nuclear power plant.\nGermany planned to shut down all its nuclear power plants by the end of 2022.\nHowever, after a full-scale Russian attack on Ukraine, the operation of the reactors was decided to extend for several more months.\nGermany, which took the course of abandoning all Russian energy resources, was afraid of problems with energy supply.\nBavarian exception: will one of the richest lands in Germany be allowed to restart nuclear power plants\nIn the final rejection of the peaceful atom, it seems, not all German politicians believe.\nAt least regional.\nThe prime minister of Bavaria - one of the richest German states - Markus Seder has already said that he will ask the federal government to reconsider its decision.\nAnd this is a few hours after the closing of the last nuclear power plant!\nSeder wants the Bavarians to make an exception \u2013 allowed them to continue to operate the nuclear power plant \u201cIzar-2 \u201d, located on the territory of the earth.\nLike, now, in times of energy crisis, to abandon nuclear energy is not only risky, but also stupid.\nThat can be done a little later.\n\"Bavaria demands that the federal government take responsibility for the continued operation of nuclear power.\nUntil the crisis is over and the country has switched to renewable energy, we must use all forms of energy before the end of the decade.\nAnyone who, like the ruling coalition, hopes that the next winter will be as mild as the previous one, acts extremely naive and careless for an industrial country like Germany, \u201d said Seder.\nAnd he promised that in the case of a positive decision from Berlin, Bavaria is ready to take responsibility for the operation of the nuclear power plant.\nThe Bavarian prime minister thought about other lands.\nIt requires the government to develop and submit a plan for the reactivation of disconnected nuclear power plants.\nIf necessary, nuclear power plants will be able to resume their work quickly.\nOfficial Berlin has already responded to the calls of the Bavarian Prime Minister \u2013 the Minister for Environmental Protection advised Zeder not to engage in political populism.\nNon-peaceful atom: Germany wants sanctions against Russian nuclear energy\nOn the day of the closure of their own nuclear power plants, the Germans also mentioned the nuclear energy of the aggressor country of Russia.\nVice-Chancellor and Minister of Economy of Germany Robert Gabeck proposed to impose sanctions against the nuclear industry of the Russian Federation.\nAt the EU level.\nFor example, to include penalties in the next, already eleventh, sanctions package, the development and coordination of which the Europeans will begin in the near future.\n\u201cWe have seen that Russia purposefully uses dependence in the energy sector for pressure.\nTherefore, the federal government called on the European Commission to impose sanctions on the civilian nuclear sector.\nNuclear technology is an extremely sensitive area, and Russia can no longer be perceived as a reliable partner here, \u201d Gabek said.\nWhat sanctions are we talking about \u2013 the politician did not specify.\nHowever, in early April, after a visit to Ukraine, he proposed to impose sanctions against states that buy uranium from Russia for their nuclear power plants.\nNot immediately, but after the transition.\n\u201cIt is important to start and not be afraid of decisive actions in this area, \u201d Gabek explained.\nThe EU \u2019 s dependence on Russia \u2019 s nuclear sector is really serious.\nAbout 20% of the uranium for their nuclear power plants EU countries receive from Russia.\nBulgaria, Slovakia, Hungary and the Czech Republic are completely dependent on these supplies, that is, 100%.\nOn the sale of uranium in the European Union, Russia earns 450 million euros a year.\nTopical on the topic\nChildren Hub is a safe way to adapt Ukrainian children and migrants in the EU\nOver a thousand children from 3 to 15 years old are given free employment in Warsaw\nHelp develop CHILDREN HUB","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:119360","uncompressed_offset":1033813326,"url":"world.novyny.live/ru/chornobil-ta-viina-iak-podiyi-v-ukrayini-sponukali-nimechchinu-vidmovitisia-vid-atomnoyi-energetiki-88405.html","warc_date":"2023-04-17T14:07:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2e61d3a9-0355-4af8-b64e-1d3c99a65f04>","warc_url":"https://world.novyny.live/ru/chornobil-ta-viina-iak-podiyi-v-ukrayini-sponukali-nimechchinu-vidmovitisia-vid-atomnoyi-energetiki-88405.html"},"created":"2023-04-17T14:47:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":{"id":"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","text":"Since the beginning of the Russian-Ukrainian war on February 24, the US sanctions on Russia have become wider and stronger.\nEuropean countries have responded differently to near-\u201c unlimited \u201d economic and financial sanctions.\nHowever, there are dissenting expressions of resistance to Russian oil and gas, Germany and the former Soviet Union \u2019 s Middle Eastern and European countries.\nIn August 2021, the United Nations Committee on Climate Change released a report by 234 scientists, revealing that the inescapable and increasingly serious climate crisis is a common historical undertaking that humanity must face together.\nThis is an important warning to EU authorities who proposed the \u201cEuropean Green Agreement \u201d in 2019, which aims to reduce carbon emissions by 55% by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, based on 1990 carbon emissions.\nAs a result, the European Commission proposed on December 31 last year and hoped to list nuclear power as a so-called \"green energy\".\nHowever, EU member states are clearly aligned on the ultimate goal of carbon neutrality based on their respective energy mix and sources of supply, but they are quite divided on how to achieve it within the EU \u2019 s planned timeline.\nAs this proposal creates a conflict between nuclear France and anti-nuclear Germany, the European Union \u2019 s rotating presidency (January to June this year), French President Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s assertion that \u201cnuclear energy = green energy \u201d has exacerbated the differences between the two countries.\nFor the German government, \"nuclear energy is not a clean green energy, let alone renewable energy\", this view directly collides with President Macron's \"to reduce carbon emissions, but also reduce natural gas imports, we must take the road to nuclear energy\".\n\"Carbon emission reduction\" and \"carbon neutrality\", two different paths of thinking, originally just the EU \"storm in the teapot\", after the outbreak of the war between Russia and Ukraine, US President Joe Biden publicly asked European allies to boycott Russian imports of oil and gas, the EU's energy policy has become an important issue for economic development after the epidemic.\nAfter the Russian-Ukrainian war, the United States hopes that the world will jointly sanction Russia's oil and gas exports. This call, in addition to the United Kingdom's decision to no longer import Russian oil and gas by the end of this year, the European Union and NATO's European countries \"excluding energy sanctions\" show three meanings: First, the war may affect the safety of nuclear power plants.\nSecond, the different energy supplies and ratios of various countries directly affect the ability to cooperate with the United States to sanction Russia.\nThird, the nuclear abolition of Germany and nuclear France, after the Russian-Ukrainian war, will make the European Union's energy policy, into a new stage.\nFirst of all, there are many nuclear power plants in Europe; before the war, no one thought that the incident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in 1986 could happen again.\n4 nuclear power plants with 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of all electricity in Ukraine.\nWhether the escalation of war affects the safety of nuclear power plants is of great concern to European countries.\nThe situation is different in Switzerland and Belgium; five nuclear power plants have been decommissioned in Switzerland after the 2017 nuclear referendum, and one has been decommissioned in 2019.\nHowever, in Belgium, where half of its electricity comes from nuclear power, the government of Belgium decided on March 18 to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035 after the Russo-Ukrainian War.\nSecond, 30% of Europe \u2019 s crude oil and 40% of its natural gas come from Russia, and it will be difficult for renewable energy to replace it in a short period of one year, or even three or five years.\nIn Germany, for example, 35% of oil and 40% of natural gas come from Russia. Even if it comes from the United States (Texas) on the other side of the Atlantic, it also involves the construction of LNG (liquefied natural gas) receiving stations and the arrival of ships, and even a large number of super tankers above 320,000 tons, it is bound to not be the current Rotterdam (Netherlands), Hamburg (Germany), Anteppt (Belgium, etc. All major ports in Europe can handle the load.\nAnd thousands of miles away from the oil tankers and LNG fleet, itself requires a large amount of fuel costs, the arrival of the transmission line of the laying, also can not be completed overnight.\nAfter the completion of the price of oil and gas, the cost of fuel transportation must be added, and for Germany, which is the first high electricity price in Europe, the burden of the people and the operation of enterprises will be seriously affected.\nFinally, Germany, which insists on eliminating nuclear weapons this year and hopes to achieve 100% green power by 2035, is a complicated situation.\nAfter the Russo-Ukrainian War, Germany stopped reviewing Nord Stream II, which had already been built.\nHowever, there is no political feasibility without Russia \u2019 s \u201cEastern Gas Delivery \u201d, as the Green Party has a joint government with the deputy prime minister and foreign minister, forced to re-use the policy option of coal burning.\nCompared with the energy policy of France with nuclear energy as the main body, for Germany with a GDP of 3.8 trillion US dollars, even natural gas is only a part of the energy transformation, the pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals, in the year of total nuclear abolition, if it also boycotts Russian oil and gas, it will be unbearable for the economy.\nThe delay of the Russian-Ukrainian war, on the one hand, some countries began to think about the safety of nuclear power plants at the same time, on the other hand, due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas, will hinder the achievement of the EU's energy transformation policy goals.\nAnd for Germany, which pursues \"100% renewable energy (green power)\" in 2035 and is Europe's largest economy, it is a short-term solution and may not be able to do so in the medium term, and the achievement of long-term goals still has a long way to go.\n# Nuclear # Energy # Natural Gas # Russo-Ukrainian War # EU","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:28866","uncompressed_offset":867928485,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113","warc_date":"2022-03-23T20:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113"},"created":"2022-03-23T21:39:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295":{"id":"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295","text":"Germany \u2019 s last three nuclear power plants may be delayed\nIn light of the potential energy crisis in Europe in the winter, officials revealed that Germany intends to delay the decommissioning of the last three nuclear plants in the country, although it will only temporarily prolong the life of the plants, but it marks the first time that Germany has deviated from the energy policy introduced in the millennium and has so far been enshrined by almost all parties.\nThe Wall Street Journal (WSJ) quoted senior officials as saying that German Chancellor Olaf Scholz has not yet formally adopted the proposal to delay the discharge, and if it is decided to do so, there are technical and legal issues, including passing through parliament.\nThe cabinet is currently discussing some details, and while it will have to wait for the results of the energy demand assessment in the coming weeks to come to a conclusion, officials have revealed that everything is almost a foregone conclusion.\nThe last three nuclear plants in Germany were due to be decommissioned on December 31, and the government reportedly believes that a temporary delay would require two conditions: Germany is likely to suffer from a natural gas shortage and there are no safety concerns about keeping nuclear reactors in operation.\nThe shift in German policy underscores the shock of Russia \u2019 s invasion of Ukraine to European political circles, especially Germany, which has been closely tied to Russia \u2019 s economy and has long relied on Russian gas supplies.\nAfter the Russian invasion of Ukraine, he began to increase military spending, send weapons to Ukraine, break years of pacifism, supply arms to conflict zones, the latest energy policy shift, and involve the almost sacred issue of \u201cnuclear abolition \u201d in German politics.\nThe German economy ministry, which dominates energy policy, declined to comment on the report, saying only that it all depends on the outcome of an assessment of Germany \u2019 s energy needs.\nThe remaining three nuclear power plants account for about 6% of Germany's electricity generation, and if they continue to supply power, they will not have to use natural gas or coal-fired power to fill the gap, allowing some areas to continue to have natural gas.\nIn some parts of Germany, huge coal-fired power plants have resumed operations in response to a potential power outage from a Russian supply cut in June, disrupting Germany \u2019 s progress so far in reducing carbon and fighting air pollution.\nThe German government has drawn up two executive orders on how to reduce natural gas and energy consumption over the next two years.\nEnergy authorities estimate that Germany will need to reduce its use of natural gas by 20% in order to avoid a shortage of natural gas this winter and next.\nIt is unclear when the German authorities may extend the discharge period, with some officials offering a few months, but the ruling Liberal Democrats believe it should be extended to 2024.\nExtended reading\nRelated Posts","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0024.json.gz:20015","uncompressed_offset":407851295,"url":"news.cnyes.com/news/id/4936584","warc_date":"2022-08-17T01:37:25.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b>","warc_url":"https://news.cnyes.com/news/id/4936584"},"created":"2022-08-17T02:12:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":{"id":"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207","text":"Three nuclear-fired power plants will be taken off the grid in Germany on Friday as part of the country's plan to end atomic power.\n\n\"The nuclear phaseout makes our country safer and helps to avoid radioactive waste,\" said Federal Environment and Nuclear Safety Minister Steffi Lemke.\n\n\"It is now essential to ... advance the search for a final repository for high-level radioactive waste as well as permanent solutions for low- and medium-level radioactive waste,\" the environment ministry said.\n\nFormer German Chancellor Angela Merkel speeded up the phaseout following the 2011 Fukushima accident in Japan.\n\nFriday's shutdown affects power plants in Brokdorf in Schleswig-Holstein, Grohnde in Lower Saxony and Gundremmingen C in Bavaria.\n\nGermany's remaining three nuclear plants \u2014 Emsland in Lower Saxony, Isar 2 in Bavaria and Neckarwestheim 2 in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg \u2014 will be closed by the end of 2022 \"at the latest,\" the environment ministry said.\n\n\"Since 2011, Germany has been drawing a line under a highly problematic technology in an orderly, reliable process,\" Lemke said.\n\nNuclear accounts for about 10 percent of Germany's electricity production. The shutdown has sparked criticism as Germany will have to dramatically ramp up renewable energy and has also increased its reliance on highly polluting coal-fired power.\n\n\"Security of supply in Germany continues to be guaranteed,\" said Robert Habeck, federal climate and economy minister. He added that reliable and \"sustainably generated electricity\" is a \"central requirement for aligning our economy and industry toward climate neutrality.\"\n\nThat stance puts Berlin at loggerheads with France, where nuclear is the largest element of its energy mix (and also helps supply Germany).\n\nEU Internal Market Commissioner Thierry Breton said in September that existing nuclear plants, which provide low-carbon electricity essential to the green transition, can be kept running \"for two, five, 10 years,\" adding: \"Why deprive ourselves of this production capacity?\"\n\nFrance is planning to scale down the share of nuclear in its electricity mix from 75 percent to 50 percent by 2035, but President Emmanuel Macron said in November that France \"will restart the construction of nuclear reactors\" while \"continuing to develop renewable energies.\"\n\nMacron also said France will invest \u20ac1 billion into research and development, notably into small modular reactors.\n\nBelgium recently decided to shut down all its nuclear power plants by 2025, but plans to invest \u20ac100 million in new generation nuclear reactors and research.\n\nMore from ... Louise Guillot","url":"https://www.politico.eu/article/germany-powers-down-3-nuclear-plants/?aid=app_feed"},"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":{"id":"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","text":"\u201cThere is no excuse for the rich West to be oblivious to the global debt crisis. \u201d \u2013 The Guardian\nWe start with an opinion piece by Larry Elliott, the Guardian \u2019 s economic editor, entitled \u201cThe wealthy West has little excuse for finally waking up to the global debt crisis. \u201d\n\u201cAfter a decade or more of their obsession with their own problems, countries in the wealthy West have begun to pay attention to the threat of a looming debt crisis in the poorer parts of the world, \u201d he says at a meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank in Washington this week.\nThe good news is that debt has risen to the highest level on the policy agenda and is seen as a problem that needs to be regulated, IMF Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said about the need for distressed countries to help: \u201cHelp them deal with the debt burden, which has made the shocks of past years more difficult; and help ensure that the IMF can continue to support them in the years to come. \u201d\nThe bad news, according to Elliott, is that Georgieva \u2019 s appeal has not yet been heeded, as rich countries are still primarily interested in their own problems.\nThe geopolitical rivalry between the United States and China is also not helping.\nCreditor countries may wake up to the idea that there is a debt problem but it is far from a solution.\nTalk is not like work. \u201d\nAchim Steiner, director of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), said: \u201cThere are more than 50 countries on his radar that can default very quickly. \u201d\nSteiner believes that the UN has no chance of meeting its ambitious 2030 development goals, unless there is urgent action.\nThe volume of lending by the private sector has made attempts to restructure or write off debt more complex than in the past.\nAt the time of the HIPC initiative, creditors tended to be either individual governments or multilateral organizations such as the World Bank.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cBut since the global financial crisis, many countries, especially middle-income countries, have borrowed heavily in financial markets, taking advantage of very low interest rates to finance domestic projects. \u201d\nAfter the setback of the COVID-19 epidemic, low- and middle-income countries have since been hit by two other undesirable shocks: the war in Ukraine, which led to higher food and fuel prices, and the sharp increase in central bank interest rates in large Western economies.\nThe result is that debt servicing has become much more expensive, with many countries now frozen out of financial markets altogether.\nSteiner said: \"The issue is not financial but political.\nThe United States has mobilized $400 billion to secure Silicon Valley Bank deposits.\nThis is more than the developing world has received in three years.\nIt took the Swiss government less than 48 hours to find 100 billion Swiss francs to secure the rescue of one of its banks.\n\u201cThe lesson of the recent banking crises is clear.\nRich countries can act fast enough when they want to, \u201d the writer concludes.\nFears of Macron \u2019 s politics\nWe turn to another Financial Times opinion piece by Alain Beatty, a trade writer, entitled \u201cThe Risks of Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s Strategic Insistence. \u201d\nMacron \u2019 s focus on keeping a distance from both Washington and Beijing in pursuit of the EU \u2019 s vague \u201cstrategic autonomy \u201d is not an innovation among European policymakers, but geopolitical Europe enthusiasts need to recognize that the lack of unity and trust within the EU, rather than the sinister manipulation by Washington and Beijing, is the main obstacle.\n\u201cWe \u2019 ve already seen this happen in trade policy, which is one area where the EU has long had the ability to act collectively.\nIn the same way that there is nothing stopping European governments from increasing military spending and playing a greater geopolitical role, the bloc can certainly increase its ability to use trade to project its strategic influence.\nBut while France has been keen to create new tools for intervening in trade and investment, other member states recognize that the views and interests of Paris are not necessarily those of the bloc as a whole.\n\u201cIn recent years, the European Commission has carefully designed a range of trade instruments to confirm the bloc \u2019 s geo-economic weight.\nThe most politically salient is the anti-coercion tool ECI, which will allow the EU to use a wide range of trade and investment measures to retaliate against the bullying of trading partners.\nFrance has strongly supported all this activity, and has also called for the creation of new EU central funds to pursue industrial policy.\n\u201cBut the Commission will struggle to use this set of tools if there is opposition from other member states that are mindful of their export interests or distrust in using trade tools to manage a centralized strategic policy.\nA few days before Macron \u2019 s trip, the Commission succumbed to pressure from some EU governments, including Germany, and gave member states a major role in determining the use of ECI.\nBerlin instinctively avoids confrontation that could damage German exports and investments abroad.\nThere have also been more principled objections from liberal member states including Sweden and the Czech Republic, sceptical of attempts to politicize trade policy and the likelihood that it will be overly influenced by certain governments.\nMacron inadvertently contributed to these concerns, especially as he unnerved some other EU governments two years ago with a clear orientation toward a major investment deal with China, \u201cleaving a legacy of caution. \u201d\n\u201cAttempting to push a union with divergent views to adopt a single approach to a specific global issue is unlikely to produce long-term results. \u201d\nGerman split on energy policy\nWe remain with an article by Laura Bettel, the Financial Times correspondent in Berlin, entitled \u201cGermany is being torn apart by energy policy with the closure of nuclear plants. \u201d\nBethel said Germany \u2019 s last remaining nuclear power plants were shut down on Saturday, \u201cmarking a watershed moment in a country that has long had deep doubts about atomic energy. \u201d\nAnti-nuclear activists hailed the shutdown of three reactors as a victory after a temporary delay following the start of the Russian-Ukrainian war that forced Berlin to look for alternatives to Russian gas.\nCritics see the shutdown as an act of madness at a time when Europe \u2019 s energy supply remains precarious and the world is struggling to stop using fossil fuels.\nAfter decades of anti-nuclear protests, the decisive moment came in 2011 when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants until 2036, bringing the phase-out date to 2022.\nThe anti-nuclear movement in former West Germany dates back to the 1970s, when a popular campaign succeeded in stopping the construction of a nuclear power plant in the southwestern village of Weil.\nThe nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 fuelled that movement.\nBut German public opinion shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War: an August 2022 poll from Der Spiegel found that 67 percent of Germans supported a five-year extension of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants.\n41% supported the construction of new plants.\nIn a similar poll three decades ago, only 3% said yes.\nBut the German Green Party, now part of the three-way coalition government led by Olaf Schulz, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis.\n\u201cThe way in which Germany has chosen to phase out nuclear power, and step back from fossil fuels as a bridging gap even as renewables increase dramatically, has been highly controversial. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:8737","uncompressed_offset":317213251,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036","warc_date":"2023-04-14T03:30:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036"},"created":"2023-04-14T03:57:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1114","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1114","narrative_id":"1114"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to move away from nuclear energy is a significant development in the country's energy market, driven by its desire to become carbon neutral by 2045."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged that the shutdown of nuclear power plants will lead to a reliance on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs in the short term."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"However, the government is taking steps to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, with a goal of achieving 100% renewable energy by 2035."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has had a significant impact on Germany's energy supply, with the country being forced to review its energy strategy from the bottom up."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"Germany imports more than 50% of its natural gas, and the war has led to a shortage of natural gas, causing concerns about the country's energy security."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has also led to an increase in energy prices, with the cost of fuel transportation adding to the burden on the people and the operation of enterprises."},{"citations":{"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295":1.0},"text":"The German economy ministry has declined to comment on the possibility of delaying the shutdown of nuclear power plants, but officials have revealed that a temporary delay would require two conditions: a natural gas shortage and no safety concerns about keeping nuclear reactors in operation."},{"citations":{"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692":1.0},"text":"The Netherlands, which plans to stop importing Russian natural gas this year, has fallen into an unprecedented energy crisis due to Germany's intention to completely shut down the nuclear power plant, and has begged Berlin to extend the operation of the nuclear power unit."},{"citations":{"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692":1.0},"text":"A survey by financial bloggers has found that 59% of Europeans are unwilling to pay the price for the Russian-Ukrainian war, and some people are dissatisfied with the government's sacrifice of their own interests and blindly following US policy."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government's decision to shut down nuclear power plants has been met with skepticism from other countries, with nuclear energy advocates around the world criticizing the move."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The situation is different in other European countries, such as France, which relies heavily on nuclear energy, and Belgium, which has decided to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The European Union's energy policy is entering a new stage, with the Russian-Ukrainian war forcing countries to re-evaluate their energy strategies."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a complex issue, driven by its desire to become carbon neutral, but also influenced by the Russian-Ukrainian war and its impact on the country's energy supply."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"The loss of nuclear energy as a component of the national energy grid is significant, and the country is struggling to cope with the shortage of natural gas and the increase in energy prices."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"While some sectors of the German population may be pushing to bring nuclear reactors back online, the government's commitment to achieving 100% renewable energy by 2035 remains a key priority."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"Overall, the situation in Germany highlights the challenges of transitioning to a low-carbon economy, and the need for a balanced and diversified energy mix to ensure energy security and mitigate the impacts of external factors such as the Russian-Ukrainian war."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to move away from nuclear energy is a significant development in the country's energy market, driven by its desire to become carbon neutral by 2045."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged that the shutdown of nuclear power plants will lead to a reliance on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs in the short term."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"However, the government is taking steps to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, with a goal of achieving 100% renewable energy by 2035."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has had a significant impact on Germany's energy supply, with the country being forced to review its energy strategy from the bottom up."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"Germany imports more than 50% of its natural gas, and the war has led to a shortage of natural gas, causing concerns about the country's energy security."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has also led to an increase in energy prices, with the cost of fuel transportation adding to the burden on the people and the operation of enterprises."},{"citations":{"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295":1.0},"text":"The German economy ministry has declined to comment on the possibility of delaying the shutdown of nuclear power plants, but officials have revealed that a temporary delay would require two conditions: a natural gas shortage and no safety concerns about keeping nuclear reactors in operation."},{"citations":{"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692":1.0},"text":"The Netherlands, which plans to stop importing Russian natural gas this year, has fallen into an unprecedented energy crisis due to Germany's intention to completely shut down the nuclear power plant, and has begged Berlin to extend the operation of the nuclear power unit."},{"citations":{"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692":1.0},"text":"A survey by financial bloggers has found that 59% of Europeans are unwilling to pay the price for the Russian-Ukrainian war, and some people are dissatisfied with the government's sacrifice of their own interests and blindly following US policy."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government's decision to shut down nuclear power plants has been met with skepticism from other countries, with nuclear energy advocates around the world criticizing the move."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The situation is different in other European countries, such as France, which relies heavily on nuclear energy, and Belgium, which has decided to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The European Union's energy policy is entering a new stage, with the Russian-Ukrainian war forcing countries to re-evaluate their energy strategies."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a complex issue, driven by its desire to become carbon neutral, but also influenced by the Russian-Ukrainian war and its impact on the country's energy supply."},{"citations":{"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":1.0},"text":"The loss of nuclear energy as a component of the national energy grid is significant, and the country is struggling to cope with the shortage of natural gas and the increase in energy prices."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"While some sectors of the German population may be pushing to bring nuclear reactors back online, the government's commitment to achieving 100% renewable energy by 2035 remains a key priority."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"Overall, the situation in Germany highlights the challenges of transitioning to a low-carbon economy, and the need for a balanced and diversified energy mix to ensure energy security and mitigate the impacts of external factors such as the Russian-Ukrainian war."}],"references":["17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692","e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295","c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341"],"documents":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":{"id":"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","text":"Since the beginning of the Russian-Ukrainian war on February 24, the US sanctions on Russia have become wider and stronger.\nEuropean countries have responded differently to near-\u201c unlimited \u201d economic and financial sanctions.\nHowever, there are dissenting expressions of resistance to Russian oil and gas, Germany and the former Soviet Union \u2019 s Middle Eastern and European countries.\nIn August 2021, the United Nations Committee on Climate Change released a report by 234 scientists, revealing that the inescapable and increasingly serious climate crisis is a common historical undertaking that humanity must face together.\nThis is an important warning to EU authorities who proposed the \u201cEuropean Green Agreement \u201d in 2019, which aims to reduce carbon emissions by 55% by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, based on 1990 carbon emissions.\nAs a result, the European Commission proposed on December 31 last year and hoped to list nuclear power as a so-called \"green energy\".\nHowever, EU member states are clearly aligned on the ultimate goal of carbon neutrality based on their respective energy mix and sources of supply, but they are quite divided on how to achieve it within the EU \u2019 s planned timeline.\nAs this proposal creates a conflict between nuclear France and anti-nuclear Germany, the European Union \u2019 s rotating presidency (January to June this year), French President Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s assertion that \u201cnuclear energy = green energy \u201d has exacerbated the differences between the two countries.\nFor the German government, \"nuclear energy is not a clean green energy, let alone renewable energy\", this view directly collides with President Macron's \"to reduce carbon emissions, but also reduce natural gas imports, we must take the road to nuclear energy\".\n\"Carbon emission reduction\" and \"carbon neutrality\", two different paths of thinking, originally just the EU \"storm in the teapot\", after the outbreak of the war between Russia and Ukraine, US President Joe Biden publicly asked European allies to boycott Russian imports of oil and gas, the EU's energy policy has become an important issue for economic development after the epidemic.\nAfter the Russian-Ukrainian war, the United States hopes that the world will jointly sanction Russia's oil and gas exports. This call, in addition to the United Kingdom's decision to no longer import Russian oil and gas by the end of this year, the European Union and NATO's European countries \"excluding energy sanctions\" show three meanings: First, the war may affect the safety of nuclear power plants.\nSecond, the different energy supplies and ratios of various countries directly affect the ability to cooperate with the United States to sanction Russia.\nThird, the nuclear abolition of Germany and nuclear France, after the Russian-Ukrainian war, will make the European Union's energy policy, into a new stage.\nFirst of all, there are many nuclear power plants in Europe; before the war, no one thought that the incident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in 1986 could happen again.\n4 nuclear power plants with 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of all electricity in Ukraine.\nWhether the escalation of war affects the safety of nuclear power plants is of great concern to European countries.\nThe situation is different in Switzerland and Belgium; five nuclear power plants have been decommissioned in Switzerland after the 2017 nuclear referendum, and one has been decommissioned in 2019.\nHowever, in Belgium, where half of its electricity comes from nuclear power, the government of Belgium decided on March 18 to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035 after the Russo-Ukrainian War.\nSecond, 30% of Europe \u2019 s crude oil and 40% of its natural gas come from Russia, and it will be difficult for renewable energy to replace it in a short period of one year, or even three or five years.\nIn Germany, for example, 35% of oil and 40% of natural gas come from Russia. Even if it comes from the United States (Texas) on the other side of the Atlantic, it also involves the construction of LNG (liquefied natural gas) receiving stations and the arrival of ships, and even a large number of super tankers above 320,000 tons, it is bound to not be the current Rotterdam (Netherlands), Hamburg (Germany), Anteppt (Belgium, etc. All major ports in Europe can handle the load.\nAnd thousands of miles away from the oil tankers and LNG fleet, itself requires a large amount of fuel costs, the arrival of the transmission line of the laying, also can not be completed overnight.\nAfter the completion of the price of oil and gas, the cost of fuel transportation must be added, and for Germany, which is the first high electricity price in Europe, the burden of the people and the operation of enterprises will be seriously affected.\nFinally, Germany, which insists on eliminating nuclear weapons this year and hopes to achieve 100% green power by 2035, is a complicated situation.\nAfter the Russo-Ukrainian War, Germany stopped reviewing Nord Stream II, which had already been built.\nHowever, there is no political feasibility without Russia \u2019 s \u201cEastern Gas Delivery \u201d, as the Green Party has a joint government with the deputy prime minister and foreign minister, forced to re-use the policy option of coal burning.\nCompared with the energy policy of France with nuclear energy as the main body, for Germany with a GDP of 3.8 trillion US dollars, even natural gas is only a part of the energy transformation, the pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals, in the year of total nuclear abolition, if it also boycotts Russian oil and gas, it will be unbearable for the economy.\nThe delay of the Russian-Ukrainian war, on the one hand, some countries began to think about the safety of nuclear power plants at the same time, on the other hand, due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas, will hinder the achievement of the EU's energy transformation policy goals.\nAnd for Germany, which pursues \"100% renewable energy (green power)\" in 2035 and is Europe's largest economy, it is a short-term solution and may not be able to do so in the medium term, and the achievement of long-term goals still has a long way to go.\n# Nuclear # Energy # Natural Gas # Russo-Ukrainian War # EU","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:28866","uncompressed_offset":867928485,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113","warc_date":"2022-03-23T20:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113"},"created":"2022-03-23T21:39:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692":{"id":"17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8_737313692","text":"World Vision: Europe 's lack of energy, no operation, aid to Ukraine may become empty talk\nJuly 15, 2022 00: 04\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nAfter the Russian army claimed to occupy the Luhansk Oblast in Ukraine, the attack slowed down, and the Kiev government began a public debate.\nUkrainian Defense Minister Leonid Leznikov said that President Zelensky has ordered the assembly of millions of troops equipped with Western weapons, which will soon recover the southern territory from Russia, and called on the West to continue to \"water\" aid.\nOn the other hand, Europe continues to emerge as the negative impact of the full range of sanctions imposed by the United States on Russia continues to emerge, and many are mired in the energy crisis, and inflation has caused everything to become expensive, causing the resentment of the European people to rise to a boiling point.\nAs energy prices continue to be high, Russia will temporarily suspend the supply of natural gas to Germany for 10 days on the Nord Stream 1 pipeline.\nPreviously, Canada refused to return the Nord Stream 1 gas turbine sent by the Siemens subsidiary to Russia on the grounds of sanctions, which caused the latter to sharply reduce natural gas supply.\nGermany is worried that if Nord Stream 1 continues to close after the annual review, it will paralyze domestic heavy industry and insufficient natural gas reserves to meet winter demand.\nDespite Zelensky's objections, the Germans continued to head hard to retrieve parts of the Nord Stream pipeline from Canada.\nEuropean countries obviously did not expect that the Russian-Ukrainian war would cause such a big problem for energy supply.\nUnder the severe shortage of natural gas supply, Germany relies on natural gas production industry can only struggle to survive, and some are even more lifeless.\nThe Netherlands, which plans to stop importing Russian natural gas this year, in addition to the road blockage demonstrations caused by domestic farmers due to the emission reduction plan, and recently fell into an unprecedented energy crisis due to Germany's intention to completely shut down the nuclear power plant, can only beg Berlin to extend the operation of the nuclear power unit.\nAfter the Russian invasion of Ukraine, most of the European people supported the government's punitive measures against Russia.\nBut the theory is very full, the reality is very bones, with the protracted war, coupled with soaring prices and soaring inflation, Europeans are gradually disgusted with the Russian-Ukrainian war, and some people are dissatisfied with the government's sacrifice of their own interests and blindly follow US policy.\nAccording to a survey by financial bloggers, 59% of Europeans say they are unwilling to pay the price for defending democracy in Ukraine.\nIn Hamburg, Germany, the local government housed Ukrainian refugees in luxury apartments in the city center, at a cost of \u20ac3,600 per month per apartment, paid by the government.\nSome reporters teased that this building, more than 100 meters high, is becoming the grave of the German taxpayer.\nThe Scottish government has suspended the intake of Ugandan refugees for three months due to a lack of suitable housing.\nFrom the country and even the people, Europe is gradually tired of the Russian-Ukrainian war, and the Kiev government may only hope that the United States will do more and better in the future.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0021.json.gz:8563","uncompressed_offset":737313692,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20220715/bkn-20220715000436283-0715_00832_001.html","warc_date":"2022-07-15T02:28:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:17202c24-5191-43b8-a90e-f4826f8bede8>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20220715/bkn-20220715000436283-0715_00832_001.html"},"created":"2022-07-15T03:27:50.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295":{"id":"d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b_407851295","text":"Germany \u2019 s last three nuclear power plants may be delayed\nIn light of the potential energy crisis in Europe in the winter, officials revealed that Germany intends to delay the decommissioning of the last three nuclear plants in the country, although it will only temporarily prolong the life of the plants, but it marks the first time that Germany has deviated from the energy policy introduced in the millennium and has so far been enshrined by almost all parties.\nThe Wall Street Journal (WSJ) quoted senior officials as saying that German Chancellor Olaf Scholz has not yet formally adopted the proposal to delay the discharge, and if it is decided to do so, there are technical and legal issues, including passing through parliament.\nThe cabinet is currently discussing some details, and while it will have to wait for the results of the energy demand assessment in the coming weeks to come to a conclusion, officials have revealed that everything is almost a foregone conclusion.\nThe last three nuclear plants in Germany were due to be decommissioned on December 31, and the government reportedly believes that a temporary delay would require two conditions: Germany is likely to suffer from a natural gas shortage and there are no safety concerns about keeping nuclear reactors in operation.\nThe shift in German policy underscores the shock of Russia \u2019 s invasion of Ukraine to European political circles, especially Germany, which has been closely tied to Russia \u2019 s economy and has long relied on Russian gas supplies.\nAfter the Russian invasion of Ukraine, he began to increase military spending, send weapons to Ukraine, break years of pacifism, supply arms to conflict zones, the latest energy policy shift, and involve the almost sacred issue of \u201cnuclear abolition \u201d in German politics.\nThe German economy ministry, which dominates energy policy, declined to comment on the report, saying only that it all depends on the outcome of an assessment of Germany \u2019 s energy needs.\nThe remaining three nuclear power plants account for about 6% of Germany's electricity generation, and if they continue to supply power, they will not have to use natural gas or coal-fired power to fill the gap, allowing some areas to continue to have natural gas.\nIn some parts of Germany, huge coal-fired power plants have resumed operations in response to a potential power outage from a Russian supply cut in June, disrupting Germany \u2019 s progress so far in reducing carbon and fighting air pollution.\nThe German government has drawn up two executive orders on how to reduce natural gas and energy consumption over the next two years.\nEnergy authorities estimate that Germany will need to reduce its use of natural gas by 20% in order to avoid a shortage of natural gas this winter and next.\nIt is unclear when the German authorities may extend the discharge period, with some officials offering a few months, but the ruling Liberal Democrats believe it should be extended to 2024.\nExtended reading\nRelated Posts","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0024.json.gz:20015","uncompressed_offset":407851295,"url":"news.cnyes.com/news/id/4936584","warc_date":"2022-08-17T01:37:25.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d6326b30-5d72-4c6e-8a2c-7bcc09d1089b>","warc_url":"https://news.cnyes.com/news/id/4936584"},"created":"2022-08-17T02:12:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":{"id":"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEXPRESS: Germany \u2019 s exit from atomic energy sector affects Europe \u2019 s largest economy\nGermany \u2019 s closure of the country \u2019 s last three nuclear reactors and its eventual exit from the atomic energy sector raises concerns about the impact of the decision on the European Union \u2019 s largest economy.\nGermany \u2019 s action could deal a blow to the technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nBerlin is implementing its plan to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035.\nEarlier this week, Germany shut down its last three nuclear power plants as part of Berlin's plan to limit power generation to renewables by 2035, ending a six-decade programme that has sparked one of Europe's most powerful protest movements.\nOther industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France and Britain, rely on nuclear power to replace the fossil fuels that are warming the planet, and Germany \u2019 s decision to stop using both has been met with some skepticism, as well as unsuccessful last-minute calls to halt the shutdown, the report said.\nNuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, realizing that the action taken by Europe \u2019 s largest economy could deal a blow to technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nThe German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs, even as steps are taken to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, and Germany aims to be carbon neutral by 2045.\nBut officials like German Environment Minister Stevie Lemke say the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth, citing data showing that the share of atomic energy in global electricity production is shrinking.\nThe construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns.\nLimki noted that the construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns, and said the money spent on maintaining old reactors or building new ones would be better spent on installing cheap renewables.\nExperts such as Claudia Kemfert of the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin say the 5% share of German electricity currently coming from its three remaining reactors can be easily replaced without risking power outages.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:26416","uncompressed_offset":493378519,"url":"www.dostor.org/4369517","warc_date":"2023-04-17T07:53:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4369517"},"created":"2023-04-17T08:28:34.000Z","lang":"eng"},"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341":{"id":"c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593_1065655341","text":"Geopolitics / Ukraine\nThe Ukraine War Affects Germany \u2019 s Energy Strategy\nRussia \u2019 s war on Ukraine forced Germany to overhaul its energy strategy.\nBerlin has urgently started the construction of two previously abandoned LNG terminals.\nThis is the subject of a field interview published by our RFI correspondent in the French \"Chronique Reportage International\" column on Thursday, March 3rd.\nAdvertisement\nIn an interview published on Thursday, March 03, 2022 in Chronique Reportage International, correspondent Julien M\u00e9chaussie reported from Berlin that Germany, which imports more than 50% of its natural gas and relies on Russian supplies, is now forced to review its energy strategy from the bottom up.\nIn the face of the inevitable price increase, the people are very worried.\nThe original title of this RFI column in French was: [Guerre en Ukraine: les cons\u00e9quences sur l'appropriationnement en gaz russe pour l'Allemagne].\nThe war in Ukraine: consequences of Russian gas supplies for Germany.\nBelow is a brief summary for information.\nThe German people are upset -\nIn a live interview from Berlin published Thursday in Chronique Reportage International, RFI \u2019 s French-language network, a passer-by said in German on his way to work that the outbreak of the war in Ukraine had caused a decades-old energy policy to collapse in a matter of days.\nRising energy prices are not good for anyone.\nThis is not good for the job market, which automatically leads to price increases for all products.\nPeople will be afraid of huge inflation, and the impact on the economy is tragic.\nHere, the RFI French correspondent pointed out that the fear of the passer-by interviewed represents many German people.\nIn Germany, which has a long history of importing Russian gas, Prime Minister Olaf Scholz announced the suspension of the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project.\nThe pipeline linking northern Germany to Russia via the Baltic Sea was completed in September 2021.\nThe project has now come to a halt. Nord Stream 2 declared bankruptcy this week and more than 100 of its collaborators lost their jobs.\nThere were signs before the war -\nA well-known professor of environmental and resource economics called Germany naive.\nHe said that at the beginning of this winter, the wind has turned around.\nBefore the war, Russian gas exports to Germany had dropped to their lowest level in months.\nDespite the record price, it is now good to see that this is clearly part of the overall strategy of the Russian side.\nGerman Deputy Prime Minister and Federal Minister for Economy and Climate Robert Habeck plans to increase coal imports.\nThe German Federation of Small and Medium Enterprises has called for an extension of the deadline for coal abandonment, which was decided at the end of last year.\nGermany, now seeking to diversify its energy supply, will turn to countries like the United States and Qatar.\nBut the problem is that these countries are now exporting liquefied natural gas, and Germany has no corresponding terminal to be docked.\nExperts interviewed pointed out that Germany is in urgent need of new liquefied natural gas terminals.\nHowever, it takes three to four years to build a terminal.\nOf course people can do it as quickly as possible, but this new strategy is not a very short-term solution.\nWe need to rely on existing infrastructure.\nOnce the new terminal is put into use, the sky should clear up.\nGermany launches old project -\nAbandoned two years ago due to a lack of political support, two projects to build LNG terminals in the North Sea have now been urgently launched at a cost of around \u20ac1 billion.\n... and...\nEmail News Headlines In Your Daily News Letter\nDownload the Guangdong-France app to track international current events","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0006.json.gz:27103","uncompressed_offset":1065655341,"url":"www.rfi.fr/cn/%E6%AC%A7%E6%B4%B2/20220303-%E4%B9%8C%E5%85%8B%E5%85%B0%E6%88%98%E4%BA%8B%E5%BD%B1%E5%93%8D%E5%BE%B7%E5%9B%BD%E8%83%BD%E6%BA%90%E6%88%98%E7%95%A5","warc_date":"2022-03-03T23:36:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:c0a43ab9-dd1e-4616-a597-abbe1818e593>","warc_url":"https://www.rfi.fr/cn/%E6%AC%A7%E6%B4%B2/20220303-%E4%B9%8C%E5%85%8B%E5%85%B0%E6%88%98%E4%BA%8B%E5%BD%B1%E5%93%8D%E5%BE%B7%E5%9B%BD%E8%83%BD%E6%BA%90%E6%88%98%E7%95%A5"},"created":"2022-03-04T00:36:42.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1115","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1115","narrative_id":"1115"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a significant move towards becoming carbon neutral, with the goal of achieving this by 2045."},{"citations":{"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628":1.0},"text":"The country has been phasing out nuclear power since 2011, after the Fukushima disaster in Japan, and has now completely abandoned nuclear power, with the last three power units being shut down."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"This move has sparked criticism, as Germany will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs in the short term."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged this, but believes that the benefits of shutting down nuclear power outweigh the costs, with Environment Minister Stevie Lemke citing data to support this decision."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has had an impact on Germany's energy supply, with the country increasing its reliance on coal and gas due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"This has led to concerns about the feasibility of Germany's energy transformation policy goals, particularly its aim to achieve 100% renewable energy by 2035."},{"citations":{"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":1.0},"text":"Despite this, the German government remains committed to its goal of becoming carbon neutral, with Federal Climate and Economy Minister Robert Habeck stating that reliable and sustainably generated electricity is a central requirement for aligning the economy and industry towards climate neutrality."},{"citations":{"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628":1.0},"text":"Some sectors of the German population are pushing to bring nuclear reactors back online, with two-thirds of Germans not supporting the government's decision to replace nuclear power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, the German government remains opposed to this, with Lemke stating that the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a significant move towards becoming carbon neutral, with the goal of achieving this by 2045."},{"citations":{"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628":1.0},"text":"The country has been phasing out nuclear power since 2011, after the Fukushima disaster in Japan, and has now completely abandoned nuclear power, with the last three power units being shut down."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"This move has sparked criticism, as Germany will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs in the short term."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged this, but believes that the benefits of shutting down nuclear power outweigh the costs, with Environment Minister Stevie Lemke citing data to support this decision."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has had an impact on Germany's energy supply, with the country increasing its reliance on coal and gas due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"This has led to concerns about the feasibility of Germany's energy transformation policy goals, particularly its aim to achieve 100% renewable energy by 2035."},{"citations":{"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":1.0},"text":"Despite this, the German government remains committed to its goal of becoming carbon neutral, with Federal Climate and Economy Minister Robert Habeck stating that reliable and sustainably generated electricity is a central requirement for aligning the economy and industry towards climate neutrality."},{"citations":{"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628":1.0},"text":"Some sectors of the German population are pushing to bring nuclear reactors back online, with two-thirds of Germans not supporting the government's decision to replace nuclear power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, the German government remains opposed to this, with Lemke stating that the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth."}],"references":["c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628","4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207"],"documents":{"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":{"id":"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207","text":"Three nuclear-fired power plants will be taken off the grid in Germany on Friday as part of the country's plan to end atomic power.\n\n\"The nuclear phaseout makes our country safer and helps to avoid radioactive waste,\" said Federal Environment and Nuclear Safety Minister Steffi Lemke.\n\n\"It is now essential to ... advance the search for a final repository for high-level radioactive waste as well as permanent solutions for low- and medium-level radioactive waste,\" the environment ministry said.\n\nFormer German Chancellor Angela Merkel speeded up the phaseout following the 2011 Fukushima accident in Japan.\n\nFriday's shutdown affects power plants in Brokdorf in Schleswig-Holstein, Grohnde in Lower Saxony and Gundremmingen C in Bavaria.\n\nGermany's remaining three nuclear plants \u2014 Emsland in Lower Saxony, Isar 2 in Bavaria and Neckarwestheim 2 in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg \u2014 will be closed by the end of 2022 \"at the latest,\" the environment ministry said.\n\n\"Since 2011, Germany has been drawing a line under a highly problematic technology in an orderly, reliable process,\" Lemke said.\n\nNuclear accounts for about 10 percent of Germany's electricity production. The shutdown has sparked criticism as Germany will have to dramatically ramp up renewable energy and has also increased its reliance on highly polluting coal-fired power.\n\n\"Security of supply in Germany continues to be guaranteed,\" said Robert Habeck, federal climate and economy minister. He added that reliable and \"sustainably generated electricity\" is a \"central requirement for aligning our economy and industry toward climate neutrality.\"\n\nThat stance puts Berlin at loggerheads with France, where nuclear is the largest element of its energy mix (and also helps supply Germany).\n\nEU Internal Market Commissioner Thierry Breton said in September that existing nuclear plants, which provide low-carbon electricity essential to the green transition, can be kept running \"for two, five, 10 years,\" adding: \"Why deprive ourselves of this production capacity?\"\n\nFrance is planning to scale down the share of nuclear in its electricity mix from 75 percent to 50 percent by 2035, but President Emmanuel Macron said in November that France \"will restart the construction of nuclear reactors\" while \"continuing to develop renewable energies.\"\n\nMacron also said France will invest \u20ac1 billion into research and development, notably into small modular reactors.\n\nBelgium recently decided to shut down all its nuclear power plants by 2025, but plans to invest \u20ac100 million in new generation nuclear reactors and research.\n\nMore from ... Louise Guillot","url":"https://www.politico.eu/article/germany-powers-down-3-nuclear-plants/?aid=app_feed"},"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":{"id":"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","text":"Since the beginning of the Russian-Ukrainian war on February 24, the US sanctions on Russia have become wider and stronger.\nEuropean countries have responded differently to near-\u201c unlimited \u201d economic and financial sanctions.\nHowever, there are dissenting expressions of resistance to Russian oil and gas, Germany and the former Soviet Union \u2019 s Middle Eastern and European countries.\nIn August 2021, the United Nations Committee on Climate Change released a report by 234 scientists, revealing that the inescapable and increasingly serious climate crisis is a common historical undertaking that humanity must face together.\nThis is an important warning to EU authorities who proposed the \u201cEuropean Green Agreement \u201d in 2019, which aims to reduce carbon emissions by 55% by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, based on 1990 carbon emissions.\nAs a result, the European Commission proposed on December 31 last year and hoped to list nuclear power as a so-called \"green energy\".\nHowever, EU member states are clearly aligned on the ultimate goal of carbon neutrality based on their respective energy mix and sources of supply, but they are quite divided on how to achieve it within the EU \u2019 s planned timeline.\nAs this proposal creates a conflict between nuclear France and anti-nuclear Germany, the European Union \u2019 s rotating presidency (January to June this year), French President Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s assertion that \u201cnuclear energy = green energy \u201d has exacerbated the differences between the two countries.\nFor the German government, \"nuclear energy is not a clean green energy, let alone renewable energy\", this view directly collides with President Macron's \"to reduce carbon emissions, but also reduce natural gas imports, we must take the road to nuclear energy\".\n\"Carbon emission reduction\" and \"carbon neutrality\", two different paths of thinking, originally just the EU \"storm in the teapot\", after the outbreak of the war between Russia and Ukraine, US President Joe Biden publicly asked European allies to boycott Russian imports of oil and gas, the EU's energy policy has become an important issue for economic development after the epidemic.\nAfter the Russian-Ukrainian war, the United States hopes that the world will jointly sanction Russia's oil and gas exports. This call, in addition to the United Kingdom's decision to no longer import Russian oil and gas by the end of this year, the European Union and NATO's European countries \"excluding energy sanctions\" show three meanings: First, the war may affect the safety of nuclear power plants.\nSecond, the different energy supplies and ratios of various countries directly affect the ability to cooperate with the United States to sanction Russia.\nThird, the nuclear abolition of Germany and nuclear France, after the Russian-Ukrainian war, will make the European Union's energy policy, into a new stage.\nFirst of all, there are many nuclear power plants in Europe; before the war, no one thought that the incident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in 1986 could happen again.\n4 nuclear power plants with 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of all electricity in Ukraine.\nWhether the escalation of war affects the safety of nuclear power plants is of great concern to European countries.\nThe situation is different in Switzerland and Belgium; five nuclear power plants have been decommissioned in Switzerland after the 2017 nuclear referendum, and one has been decommissioned in 2019.\nHowever, in Belgium, where half of its electricity comes from nuclear power, the government of Belgium decided on March 18 to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035 after the Russo-Ukrainian War.\nSecond, 30% of Europe \u2019 s crude oil and 40% of its natural gas come from Russia, and it will be difficult for renewable energy to replace it in a short period of one year, or even three or five years.\nIn Germany, for example, 35% of oil and 40% of natural gas come from Russia. Even if it comes from the United States (Texas) on the other side of the Atlantic, it also involves the construction of LNG (liquefied natural gas) receiving stations and the arrival of ships, and even a large number of super tankers above 320,000 tons, it is bound to not be the current Rotterdam (Netherlands), Hamburg (Germany), Anteppt (Belgium, etc. All major ports in Europe can handle the load.\nAnd thousands of miles away from the oil tankers and LNG fleet, itself requires a large amount of fuel costs, the arrival of the transmission line of the laying, also can not be completed overnight.\nAfter the completion of the price of oil and gas, the cost of fuel transportation must be added, and for Germany, which is the first high electricity price in Europe, the burden of the people and the operation of enterprises will be seriously affected.\nFinally, Germany, which insists on eliminating nuclear weapons this year and hopes to achieve 100% green power by 2035, is a complicated situation.\nAfter the Russo-Ukrainian War, Germany stopped reviewing Nord Stream II, which had already been built.\nHowever, there is no political feasibility without Russia \u2019 s \u201cEastern Gas Delivery \u201d, as the Green Party has a joint government with the deputy prime minister and foreign minister, forced to re-use the policy option of coal burning.\nCompared with the energy policy of France with nuclear energy as the main body, for Germany with a GDP of 3.8 trillion US dollars, even natural gas is only a part of the energy transformation, the pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals, in the year of total nuclear abolition, if it also boycotts Russian oil and gas, it will be unbearable for the economy.\nThe delay of the Russian-Ukrainian war, on the one hand, some countries began to think about the safety of nuclear power plants at the same time, on the other hand, due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas, will hinder the achievement of the EU's energy transformation policy goals.\nAnd for Germany, which pursues \"100% renewable energy (green power)\" in 2035 and is Europe's largest economy, it is a short-term solution and may not be able to do so in the medium term, and the achievement of long-term goals still has a long way to go.\n# Nuclear # Energy # Natural Gas # Russo-Ukrainian War # EU","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:28866","uncompressed_offset":867928485,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113","warc_date":"2022-03-23T20:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113"},"created":"2022-03-23T21:39:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628":{"id":"c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679_1033223628","text":"The people are not particularly happy with the government \u2019 s choice.\nrecommendations\nGermany has completely abandoned nuclear power, turning off the last three power units located at the Emsland nuclear power plant (Lower Saxony), Necarwesteim-2 (Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg), Isar-2 (Bavaria).\nNow the country has only to get rid of nuclear waste.\nadvertising\nThe decision to phase out nuclear power came from then-Chancellor Angela Merkel after the disaster of 2011, when the accident at the Fukushima-1 nuclear power plant in Japan, which killed at least 15.9 thousand people.\nInitially, it was planned to stop nuclear reactors on December 31, 2022, but due to rising energy prices, the German government delayed this until mid-April 2023.\nThe nuance is that in the near future, Germany will have to rely on coal and gas, which have a negative impact on the environment.\nOf the advantages, only that you need to compensate a little - 6% of electricity generation, which was just those nuclear reactors.\nrecommendations\nAccording to YouGov, two-thirds of Germans do not support the government \u2019 s decision to replace the cheap \u201cpeaceful atom \u201d.\nFor the post accrued remuneration\nThis material is written by a visitor to the site, and a reward is accrued for it.\n2\nPopular news","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:107184","uncompressed_offset":1033223628,"url":"overclockers.ru/blog/Nacvark/show/91016/germaniya-polnostju-otkazalas-ot-yadernoj-energetiki","warc_date":"2023-04-17T03:25:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:c992d399-8222-49f0-95d9-20850571b679>","warc_url":"https://overclockers.ru/blog/Nacvark/show/91016/germaniya-polnostju-otkazalas-ot-yadernoj-energetiki"},"created":"2023-04-17T05:06:07.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":{"id":"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEXPRESS: Germany \u2019 s exit from atomic energy sector affects Europe \u2019 s largest economy\nGermany \u2019 s closure of the country \u2019 s last three nuclear reactors and its eventual exit from the atomic energy sector raises concerns about the impact of the decision on the European Union \u2019 s largest economy.\nGermany \u2019 s action could deal a blow to the technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nBerlin is implementing its plan to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035.\nEarlier this week, Germany shut down its last three nuclear power plants as part of Berlin's plan to limit power generation to renewables by 2035, ending a six-decade programme that has sparked one of Europe's most powerful protest movements.\nOther industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France and Britain, rely on nuclear power to replace the fossil fuels that are warming the planet, and Germany \u2019 s decision to stop using both has been met with some skepticism, as well as unsuccessful last-minute calls to halt the shutdown, the report said.\nNuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, realizing that the action taken by Europe \u2019 s largest economy could deal a blow to technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nThe German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs, even as steps are taken to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, and Germany aims to be carbon neutral by 2045.\nBut officials like German Environment Minister Stevie Lemke say the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth, citing data showing that the share of atomic energy in global electricity production is shrinking.\nThe construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns.\nLimki noted that the construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns, and said the money spent on maintaining old reactors or building new ones would be better spent on installing cheap renewables.\nExperts such as Claudia Kemfert of the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin say the 5% share of German electricity currently coming from its three remaining reactors can be easily replaced without risking power outages.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:26416","uncompressed_offset":493378519,"url":"www.dostor.org/4369517","warc_date":"2023-04-17T07:53:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4369517"},"created":"2023-04-17T08:28:34.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"dog","topic_id":"1116","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1116","narrative_id":"1116"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a significant move towards becoming carbon neutral, with the goal of being carbon neutral by 2045."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The country aims to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035, with a focus on increasing electricity production from solar and wind power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, this decision has been met with skepticism from other industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France, and Britain, which rely on nuclear power to replace fossil fuels."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Nuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, arguing that it could deal a blow to a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"This is a concern for the country's carbon neutrality goals, as well as its energy security, particularly in light of the Russian-Ukrainian war."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The war has led to a shift in Germany's energy policy, with the country looking for alternatives to Russian gas."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"In fact, the shutdown of Germany's last three nuclear power plants was hailed as a victory by some, but criticized by others as an act of madness at a time when Europe's energy supply remains precarious."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The decision to shut down the nuclear power plants was made in 2011, when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country's nuclear plants until 2036."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"This decision was influenced by decades of anti-nuclear protests in Germany, which date back to the 1970s."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 also fueled the anti-nuclear movement in Germany."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"However, public opinion in Germany shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War, with 67% of Germans supporting a five-year extension of the country's nuclear plants, and 41% supporting the construction of new plants."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"Despite this shift in public opinion, the German Green Party, which is part of the coalition government, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The German government's decision to shut down the nuclear power plants has been highly controversial, with some arguing that it will hinder the country's ability to meet its energy needs and achieve its carbon neutrality goals."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The country's energy market is coping with the loss of nuclear energy by increasing its reliance on renewable energy sources, such as solar and wind power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, this transition is not without its challenges, particularly in light of the Russian-Ukrainian war, which has led to a shortage of natural gas and other energy supplies."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has also led to a increase in energy prices, which is affecting the German economy and the livelihoods of its citizens."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"In fact, Germany's pursuit of 100% renewable energy by 2035 may not be achievable in the short term, particularly if the country is unable to access sufficient energy supplies."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The country's energy policy is also being influenced by the European Union's energy transformation policy goals, which aim to reduce the bloc's reliance on fossil fuels and increase its use of renewable energy sources."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has also raised concerns about the safety of nuclear power plants in Europe, particularly in Ukraine, where there are 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of the country's electricity."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has led to a shift in the European Union's energy policy, with some countries, such as France and Britain, maintaining their reliance on nuclear energy, while others, such as Germany, are moving away from it."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Overall, Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a complex issue, with both positive and negative consequences for the country's energy market and its ability to achieve its carbon neutrality goals."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"While the decision has been criticized by some, it is also seen as a necessary step towards reducing the country's reliance on fossil fuels and increasing its use of renewable energy sources."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"However, the country's energy policy must be carefully managed to ensure that the transition to renewable energy is smooth and does not lead to energy shortages or price increases."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government must also consider the impact of the Russian-Ukrainian war on the country's energy supply and take steps to mitigate any negative consequences."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a significant step towards becoming carbon neutral, but it is a complex issue that requires careful management and consideration of the potential consequences."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a significant move towards becoming carbon neutral, with the goal of being carbon neutral by 2045."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The country aims to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035, with a focus on increasing electricity production from solar and wind power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, this decision has been met with skepticism from other industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France, and Britain, which rely on nuclear power to replace fossil fuels."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Nuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, arguing that it could deal a blow to a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"This is a concern for the country's carbon neutrality goals, as well as its energy security, particularly in light of the Russian-Ukrainian war."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The war has led to a shift in Germany's energy policy, with the country looking for alternatives to Russian gas."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"In fact, the shutdown of Germany's last three nuclear power plants was hailed as a victory by some, but criticized by others as an act of madness at a time when Europe's energy supply remains precarious."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The decision to shut down the nuclear power plants was made in 2011, when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country's nuclear plants until 2036."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"This decision was influenced by decades of anti-nuclear protests in Germany, which date back to the 1970s."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 also fueled the anti-nuclear movement in Germany."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"However, public opinion in Germany shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War, with 67% of Germans supporting a five-year extension of the country's nuclear plants, and 41% supporting the construction of new plants."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"Despite this shift in public opinion, the German Green Party, which is part of the coalition government, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis."},{"citations":{"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":1.0},"text":"The German government's decision to shut down the nuclear power plants has been highly controversial, with some arguing that it will hinder the country's ability to meet its energy needs and achieve its carbon neutrality goals."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The country's energy market is coping with the loss of nuclear energy by increasing its reliance on renewable energy sources, such as solar and wind power."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"However, this transition is not without its challenges, particularly in light of the Russian-Ukrainian war, which has led to a shortage of natural gas and other energy supplies."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has also led to a increase in energy prices, which is affecting the German economy and the livelihoods of its citizens."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"In fact, Germany's pursuit of 100% renewable energy by 2035 may not be achievable in the short term, particularly if the country is unable to access sufficient energy supplies."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The country's energy policy is also being influenced by the European Union's energy transformation policy goals, which aim to reduce the bloc's reliance on fossil fuels and increase its use of renewable energy sources."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The Russian-Ukrainian war has also raised concerns about the safety of nuclear power plants in Europe, particularly in Ukraine, where there are 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of the country's electricity."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"The war has led to a shift in the European Union's energy policy, with some countries, such as France and Britain, maintaining their reliance on nuclear energy, while others, such as Germany, are moving away from it."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"Overall, Germany's decision to shut down its nuclear power plants is a complex issue, with both positive and negative consequences for the country's energy market and its ability to achieve its carbon neutrality goals."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"While the decision has been criticized by some, it is also seen as a necessary step towards reducing the country's reliance on fossil fuels and increasing its use of renewable energy sources."},{"citations":{"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":1.0},"text":"However, the country's energy policy must be carefully managed to ensure that the transition to renewable energy is smooth and does not lead to energy shortages or price increases."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"The German government must also consider the impact of the Russian-Ukrainian war on the country's energy supply and take steps to mitigate any negative consequences."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Germany's move away from nuclear energy is a significant step towards becoming carbon neutral, but it is a complex issue that requires careful management and consideration of the potential consequences."}],"references":["533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485"],"documents":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":{"id":"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEXPRESS: Germany \u2019 s exit from atomic energy sector affects Europe \u2019 s largest economy\nGermany \u2019 s closure of the country \u2019 s last three nuclear reactors and its eventual exit from the atomic energy sector raises concerns about the impact of the decision on the European Union \u2019 s largest economy.\nGermany \u2019 s action could deal a blow to the technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nBerlin is implementing its plan to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035.\nEarlier this week, Germany shut down its last three nuclear power plants as part of Berlin's plan to limit power generation to renewables by 2035, ending a six-decade programme that has sparked one of Europe's most powerful protest movements.\nOther industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France and Britain, rely on nuclear power to replace the fossil fuels that are warming the planet, and Germany \u2019 s decision to stop using both has been met with some skepticism, as well as unsuccessful last-minute calls to halt the shutdown, the report said.\nNuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, realizing that the action taken by Europe \u2019 s largest economy could deal a blow to technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nThe German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs, even as steps are taken to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, and Germany aims to be carbon neutral by 2045.\nBut officials like German Environment Minister Stevie Lemke say the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth, citing data showing that the share of atomic energy in global electricity production is shrinking.\nThe construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns.\nLimki noted that the construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns, and said the money spent on maintaining old reactors or building new ones would be better spent on installing cheap renewables.\nExperts such as Claudia Kemfert of the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin say the 5% share of German electricity currently coming from its three remaining reactors can be easily replaced without risking power outages.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:26416","uncompressed_offset":493378519,"url":"www.dostor.org/4369517","warc_date":"2023-04-17T07:53:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4369517"},"created":"2023-04-17T08:28:34.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485":{"id":"e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d_867928485","text":"Since the beginning of the Russian-Ukrainian war on February 24, the US sanctions on Russia have become wider and stronger.\nEuropean countries have responded differently to near-\u201c unlimited \u201d economic and financial sanctions.\nHowever, there are dissenting expressions of resistance to Russian oil and gas, Germany and the former Soviet Union \u2019 s Middle Eastern and European countries.\nIn August 2021, the United Nations Committee on Climate Change released a report by 234 scientists, revealing that the inescapable and increasingly serious climate crisis is a common historical undertaking that humanity must face together.\nThis is an important warning to EU authorities who proposed the \u201cEuropean Green Agreement \u201d in 2019, which aims to reduce carbon emissions by 55% by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, based on 1990 carbon emissions.\nAs a result, the European Commission proposed on December 31 last year and hoped to list nuclear power as a so-called \"green energy\".\nHowever, EU member states are clearly aligned on the ultimate goal of carbon neutrality based on their respective energy mix and sources of supply, but they are quite divided on how to achieve it within the EU \u2019 s planned timeline.\nAs this proposal creates a conflict between nuclear France and anti-nuclear Germany, the European Union \u2019 s rotating presidency (January to June this year), French President Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s assertion that \u201cnuclear energy = green energy \u201d has exacerbated the differences between the two countries.\nFor the German government, \"nuclear energy is not a clean green energy, let alone renewable energy\", this view directly collides with President Macron's \"to reduce carbon emissions, but also reduce natural gas imports, we must take the road to nuclear energy\".\n\"Carbon emission reduction\" and \"carbon neutrality\", two different paths of thinking, originally just the EU \"storm in the teapot\", after the outbreak of the war between Russia and Ukraine, US President Joe Biden publicly asked European allies to boycott Russian imports of oil and gas, the EU's energy policy has become an important issue for economic development after the epidemic.\nAfter the Russian-Ukrainian war, the United States hopes that the world will jointly sanction Russia's oil and gas exports. This call, in addition to the United Kingdom's decision to no longer import Russian oil and gas by the end of this year, the European Union and NATO's European countries \"excluding energy sanctions\" show three meanings: First, the war may affect the safety of nuclear power plants.\nSecond, the different energy supplies and ratios of various countries directly affect the ability to cooperate with the United States to sanction Russia.\nThird, the nuclear abolition of Germany and nuclear France, after the Russian-Ukrainian war, will make the European Union's energy policy, into a new stage.\nFirst of all, there are many nuclear power plants in Europe; before the war, no one thought that the incident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in 1986 could happen again.\n4 nuclear power plants with 15 nuclear reactors supplying half of all electricity in Ukraine.\nWhether the escalation of war affects the safety of nuclear power plants is of great concern to European countries.\nThe situation is different in Switzerland and Belgium; five nuclear power plants have been decommissioned in Switzerland after the 2017 nuclear referendum, and one has been decommissioned in 2019.\nHowever, in Belgium, where half of its electricity comes from nuclear power, the government of Belgium decided on March 18 to retain some of its power generation units and extend them until 2035 after the Russo-Ukrainian War.\nSecond, 30% of Europe \u2019 s crude oil and 40% of its natural gas come from Russia, and it will be difficult for renewable energy to replace it in a short period of one year, or even three or five years.\nIn Germany, for example, 35% of oil and 40% of natural gas come from Russia. Even if it comes from the United States (Texas) on the other side of the Atlantic, it also involves the construction of LNG (liquefied natural gas) receiving stations and the arrival of ships, and even a large number of super tankers above 320,000 tons, it is bound to not be the current Rotterdam (Netherlands), Hamburg (Germany), Anteppt (Belgium, etc. All major ports in Europe can handle the load.\nAnd thousands of miles away from the oil tankers and LNG fleet, itself requires a large amount of fuel costs, the arrival of the transmission line of the laying, also can not be completed overnight.\nAfter the completion of the price of oil and gas, the cost of fuel transportation must be added, and for Germany, which is the first high electricity price in Europe, the burden of the people and the operation of enterprises will be seriously affected.\nFinally, Germany, which insists on eliminating nuclear weapons this year and hopes to achieve 100% green power by 2035, is a complicated situation.\nAfter the Russo-Ukrainian War, Germany stopped reviewing Nord Stream II, which had already been built.\nHowever, there is no political feasibility without Russia \u2019 s \u201cEastern Gas Delivery \u201d, as the Green Party has a joint government with the deputy prime minister and foreign minister, forced to re-use the policy option of coal burning.\nCompared with the energy policy of France with nuclear energy as the main body, for Germany with a GDP of 3.8 trillion US dollars, even natural gas is only a part of the energy transformation, the pursuit of 100% renewable energy policy goals, in the year of total nuclear abolition, if it also boycotts Russian oil and gas, it will be unbearable for the economy.\nThe delay of the Russian-Ukrainian war, on the one hand, some countries began to think about the safety of nuclear power plants at the same time, on the other hand, due to the boycott of Russian oil and gas, will hinder the achievement of the EU's energy transformation policy goals.\nAnd for Germany, which pursues \"100% renewable energy (green power)\" in 2035 and is Europe's largest economy, it is a short-term solution and may not be able to do so in the medium term, and the achievement of long-term goals still has a long way to go.\n# Nuclear # Energy # Natural Gas # Russo-Ukrainian War # EU","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:28866","uncompressed_offset":867928485,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113","warc_date":"2022-03-23T20:49:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e2f38329-3d60-4c8f-aeb4-9f4374525b5d>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/opinion/20220324000102-262113"},"created":"2022-03-23T21:39:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":{"id":"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","text":"\u201cThere is no excuse for the rich West to be oblivious to the global debt crisis. \u201d \u2013 The Guardian\nWe start with an opinion piece by Larry Elliott, the Guardian \u2019 s economic editor, entitled \u201cThe wealthy West has little excuse for finally waking up to the global debt crisis. \u201d\n\u201cAfter a decade or more of their obsession with their own problems, countries in the wealthy West have begun to pay attention to the threat of a looming debt crisis in the poorer parts of the world, \u201d he says at a meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank in Washington this week.\nThe good news is that debt has risen to the highest level on the policy agenda and is seen as a problem that needs to be regulated, IMF Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said about the need for distressed countries to help: \u201cHelp them deal with the debt burden, which has made the shocks of past years more difficult; and help ensure that the IMF can continue to support them in the years to come. \u201d\nThe bad news, according to Elliott, is that Georgieva \u2019 s appeal has not yet been heeded, as rich countries are still primarily interested in their own problems.\nThe geopolitical rivalry between the United States and China is also not helping.\nCreditor countries may wake up to the idea that there is a debt problem but it is far from a solution.\nTalk is not like work. \u201d\nAchim Steiner, director of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), said: \u201cThere are more than 50 countries on his radar that can default very quickly. \u201d\nSteiner believes that the UN has no chance of meeting its ambitious 2030 development goals, unless there is urgent action.\nThe volume of lending by the private sector has made attempts to restructure or write off debt more complex than in the past.\nAt the time of the HIPC initiative, creditors tended to be either individual governments or multilateral organizations such as the World Bank.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cBut since the global financial crisis, many countries, especially middle-income countries, have borrowed heavily in financial markets, taking advantage of very low interest rates to finance domestic projects. \u201d\nAfter the setback of the COVID-19 epidemic, low- and middle-income countries have since been hit by two other undesirable shocks: the war in Ukraine, which led to higher food and fuel prices, and the sharp increase in central bank interest rates in large Western economies.\nThe result is that debt servicing has become much more expensive, with many countries now frozen out of financial markets altogether.\nSteiner said: \"The issue is not financial but political.\nThe United States has mobilized $400 billion to secure Silicon Valley Bank deposits.\nThis is more than the developing world has received in three years.\nIt took the Swiss government less than 48 hours to find 100 billion Swiss francs to secure the rescue of one of its banks.\n\u201cThe lesson of the recent banking crises is clear.\nRich countries can act fast enough when they want to, \u201d the writer concludes.\nFears of Macron \u2019 s politics\nWe turn to another Financial Times opinion piece by Alain Beatty, a trade writer, entitled \u201cThe Risks of Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s Strategic Insistence. \u201d\nMacron \u2019 s focus on keeping a distance from both Washington and Beijing in pursuit of the EU \u2019 s vague \u201cstrategic autonomy \u201d is not an innovation among European policymakers, but geopolitical Europe enthusiasts need to recognize that the lack of unity and trust within the EU, rather than the sinister manipulation by Washington and Beijing, is the main obstacle.\n\u201cWe \u2019 ve already seen this happen in trade policy, which is one area where the EU has long had the ability to act collectively.\nIn the same way that there is nothing stopping European governments from increasing military spending and playing a greater geopolitical role, the bloc can certainly increase its ability to use trade to project its strategic influence.\nBut while France has been keen to create new tools for intervening in trade and investment, other member states recognize that the views and interests of Paris are not necessarily those of the bloc as a whole.\n\u201cIn recent years, the European Commission has carefully designed a range of trade instruments to confirm the bloc \u2019 s geo-economic weight.\nThe most politically salient is the anti-coercion tool ECI, which will allow the EU to use a wide range of trade and investment measures to retaliate against the bullying of trading partners.\nFrance has strongly supported all this activity, and has also called for the creation of new EU central funds to pursue industrial policy.\n\u201cBut the Commission will struggle to use this set of tools if there is opposition from other member states that are mindful of their export interests or distrust in using trade tools to manage a centralized strategic policy.\nA few days before Macron \u2019 s trip, the Commission succumbed to pressure from some EU governments, including Germany, and gave member states a major role in determining the use of ECI.\nBerlin instinctively avoids confrontation that could damage German exports and investments abroad.\nThere have also been more principled objections from liberal member states including Sweden and the Czech Republic, sceptical of attempts to politicize trade policy and the likelihood that it will be overly influenced by certain governments.\nMacron inadvertently contributed to these concerns, especially as he unnerved some other EU governments two years ago with a clear orientation toward a major investment deal with China, \u201cleaving a legacy of caution. \u201d\n\u201cAttempting to push a union with divergent views to adopt a single approach to a specific global issue is unlikely to produce long-term results. \u201d\nGerman split on energy policy\nWe remain with an article by Laura Bettel, the Financial Times correspondent in Berlin, entitled \u201cGermany is being torn apart by energy policy with the closure of nuclear plants. \u201d\nBethel said Germany \u2019 s last remaining nuclear power plants were shut down on Saturday, \u201cmarking a watershed moment in a country that has long had deep doubts about atomic energy. \u201d\nAnti-nuclear activists hailed the shutdown of three reactors as a victory after a temporary delay following the start of the Russian-Ukrainian war that forced Berlin to look for alternatives to Russian gas.\nCritics see the shutdown as an act of madness at a time when Europe \u2019 s energy supply remains precarious and the world is struggling to stop using fossil fuels.\nAfter decades of anti-nuclear protests, the decisive moment came in 2011 when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants until 2036, bringing the phase-out date to 2022.\nThe anti-nuclear movement in former West Germany dates back to the 1970s, when a popular campaign succeeded in stopping the construction of a nuclear power plant in the southwestern village of Weil.\nThe nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 fuelled that movement.\nBut German public opinion shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War: an August 2022 poll from Der Spiegel found that 67 percent of Germans supported a five-year extension of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants.\n41% supported the construction of new plants.\nIn a similar poll three decades ago, only 3% said yes.\nBut the German Green Party, now part of the three-way coalition government led by Olaf Schulz, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis.\n\u201cThe way in which Germany has chosen to phase out nuclear power, and step back from fossil fuels as a bridging gap even as renewables increase dramatically, has been highly controversial. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:8737","uncompressed_offset":317213251,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036","warc_date":"2023-04-14T03:30:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036"},"created":"2023-04-14T03:57:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
